<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET LETT GO; NOW'S TIME FOR REBUILDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ As is his custom, Leon Lett was here one
day, gone the next.
</P>
<P>
   One minute Tuesday night he was a rolling avalanche, tormenting
the New Orleans Saints' backfield. In the next breath, he was a
limping bystander, watching from the sidelines again.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cowboys, it should have been a reminder fraught with
omens. No Lett, no defensive anchor. No Leon, no chance.
</P>
<P>
   And though new coach Chan Gailey chose to put a positive spin on
the news of Lett's sprained knee _ ``It's an opportunity for
somebody else. It's an opportunity for us to rally, an opportunity
to see how we can handle adversity in another situation'' _ the
fact is that all the opportunity in the world means nothing unless
you have the wherewithal to answer the knock.
</P>
<P>
   I think they don't. I think they're an NFL playoff also-ran.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Cowboys can't march, at least moderately
impressively, to the NFC Championship Game, what's the point?
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for Leon's knee to mend, the prudent alternative
would be to attempt to trade him. Avoid the seemingly annual
substance-abuse suspension. Swap him for both the cow and the bag
of beans.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-year pro's trade value will never be higher. You could
argue that next to the starting quarterback, Lett, 29, might have
the highest sheer trade value on the squad.
</P>
<P>
   Oh? You say that would wreck the defense, and probably the
entire 1998 season?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it could. And that's exactly my point.
</P>
<P>
   Two lackluster full-dress scrimmages and two tellingly
unimpressive exhibition contests have drained me of all vestiges of
optimism. The new offense still pings instead of purrs. Emmitt
Smith ran like an old memory Tuesday, but be still, thy hearts _ it
was against yon feeble Saints.
</P>
<P>
   And there are better pass rushes on sale days at Mervyn's.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it is mid-August. In games that truly matter, the
Cowboys remain undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   But shouldn't a team with deep-playoff aspirations be showing
something _ something besides controversial headlines _ even by
now?
</P>
<P>
   If Lett misses any string of regular-season games, either by
knee or indiscretion, the starting front four likely becomes Kavika
Pittman, Antonio Anderson, Chad Hennings and rookie Greg Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Depth, once a franchise hallmark, has been chipped away by age
and free-agent defections.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cowboys were rolling over and quitting for Barry
Switzer last autumn _ not an altogether unpopular move, of course _
they also were squandering a year of their ``window of
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   You know the window. From it, the swaggering young Cowboys once
thought they could see four, six, even nine or 10 Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're a year older, with a 6-10 blotch on their resumes.
From the window of opportunity, on a clear day, the Cowboys can
barely see beyond Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Lett? Better think about it. And why not trade Michael
Irvin and Deion Sanders, if someone would dare bite the bait?
</P>
<P>
   I am preaching to the mortician, of course. Owner Jones would
never flush the season in August. Pepsi and Nike, to name two,
would be horrified.
</P>
<P>
   But if this team pales on paper against the likes of Green Bay
and San Francisco, what's the point?
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, former coach Tom Landry and general manager Tex
Schramm harvested success by having the boldness and foresight to
replace veterans one year early. Replace them one year late, and
you wind up like the Cowboys that Owner Jones inherited.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, let me suggest, has already learned this. A major purge
of old faces has already begun _ Bill Bates, Tony Tolbert, Mark
Tuinei, et al.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones, the eternal wildcatter, seems to think that by
drafting Flozell Adams and bringing in veteran hands such as Chris
Warren, Ernie Mills and George Teague, he can prop open the golden
window one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Salary cap constraints would complicate any mass fire sale.
Lett's contract, however, would not be a burdensome one to unload.
It calls for $2.25 million in 1998 and would cost $3.1 million
against the salary cap this season, but only $850,000 the next.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for a Pro Bowl lineman like Lett, the Cowboys could
launch their renovation effort with, say, two high draft picks _
picks that could eventually exchange for the next Leon Lett.
</P>
<P>
   It's what a team with Super Bowl dreams needs to do.
</P>
<P>
   If a window looks like it's closing, in other words, it opens
another one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
