<HEADLINE>
BOEING ANNOUNCES CONSOLIDATION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST and JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Moving agressively on several fronts to return the
company to more profitable times and restore its tarnished image on
Wall Street, Boeing on Thursday announced sweeping consolidations
of its defense and space facilities in Kent, Wash., and elsewhere,
and said it will begin producing new 737s on a Southern California
assembly line in October.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was not specific on how many more jobs will be cut,
Boeing said it will further trim its work force in 2000. This would
be on top of previously announced plans to eliminate as many as
28,000 jobs companywide by the end of next year. Current employment
totals about 238,000 in 27 states.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's Information, Space &AMP; Defense Systems plans to cut its
workforce companywide by up to 10,000 over the next 5 years. Some
but not all of those jobs are included in the 28,000 figure.
</P>
<P>
   And Boeing reiterated that it will reduce commercial airplane
employment in the Seattle area by about 12,000. Those jobs are
included in the 28,000 figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were not easy decisions to make because they affect the
people of Boeing,'' Chairman Phil Condit told employees in an
internal bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some instances we will be closing facilities. In other
cases, we will be moving work from one site to another. And jobs
will be reduced in the process. However, these were essential
decisions to make. They will allow us to reduce our costs, operate
more efficiently and better meet the needs of our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that Boeing will start a new 737 final assembly
line for its business jets in Long Beach had been the subject of
much media attention in recent months. But industry analysts said
the real message yesterday is that through a series of cost-cutting
moves and consolidation of facilities, the company hopes to boost
profits.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Boeing will close more than 18 million square feet of
office, warehouse and manufacturing space by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly due to production problems on its commercial airplane
lines in Renton and in Everett, north of Seattle, Boeing posted its
first annual loss in 50 years in 1997. Its stock has been battered
on Wall Street and the company has been forced to deny recent
rumors that Condit will be ousted along with Ron Woodard, president
of the Commercial Airplane Group.
</P>
<P>
   A 737 assembly line in California would be a first since World
War II for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Boeing's largest union, which earlier had threatened
legal action to block the California assembly line, said they
reached a ``landmark'' agreement with the company after a series of
unprecedented talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this agreement gives our members the job security
they demand and they need,'' said Bill Johnson, president of the
Machinists local that represents 39,000 Boeing workers. ``We do not
believe the battle should be between the union and the company. The
battleground should between Boeing and Airbus.''
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with the introduction of the 737 work, the
commercial airplane operation in California is being renamed the
Long Beach division. It has been known as the Douglas Products
Division.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Boeing promised the union it will produce
no more than five next-generation 737s a month at Long Beach at
least until after the current contract expires Sept. 1, 1999.
Boeing also promised that no union-represented employees in the
Puget Sound area, Spokane, Wichita, Kansas, or Portland will be
laid off for the duration of the current labor contract as a result
of the Long Beach line and pledged to keep production of 737 wings
and other components in the Puget Sound area, and to continue
building fuselage sections in Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   Both Johnson and Boeing executives said their successful talks
have paved the way for smoother labor negotiations next year. In
1995, talks broke down and the Machinists went on strike for 69
days. ``I see this (success) carrying into the negotiations,''
Johnson said. ``I would like to see this as a way of doing
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Calhoun, Boeing vice president of employee and union
relations, agreed, saying: ``I would hope that the formal round in
the fall of next year is a non-event, and that's what we're
striving to have happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Mitchell, an executive vice president of Boeing's
commercial airplane group, said assembly at the Long Beach plant
will begin in October and will be used initially to produce Boeing
Business Jets, a corporate version of the 737-700.
</P>
<P>
   He said about 600 workers in California will be needed for the
new line. The production rate will increase gradually to three
airplanes per month by the second quarter of 1999 with the addition
of selected next-generation 737s for airline customers.
</P>
<P>
   Later next year, the new line could begin producing convertible
freighters known as 737-700Cs. He said the move would give the
company the capability to move beyond the currently planned peak
737 production rate of 27 a month if market conditions demand.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the plans for Long Beach, much of Boeing's
defense and space consolidation will occur in southern California,
which has become home to the company's growing space business.
</P>
<P>
   Kent will see several changes, though it will continue as
headquarters for the defense and space group that is now called
Information, Space &AMP; Defense Systems. But the headquarters of
Boeing's information and communications systems unit in Kent will
move to Anaheim, Calif. Fewer than 100 people are affected.
</P>
<P>
   And Boeing's work on the Teledesic ``Internet in the Sky''
satellite project will shift to Seal Beach, Calif. Boeing's role
was greatly diminished recently when Motorola took over as prime
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   As the Post-Intelligencer first reported Monday, Boeing tabbed
St. Louis as the location for all future fighter aircraft
production. This includes the Joint Strike Fighter should Boeing
win the heated competition over Lockheed Martin in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing hinted in its announcement that its present work on the
F-22 stealth fighter, which it makes in partnership with Lockheed
Martin, could eventually move out of the Seattle area. About 1,400
workers now build the wings and aft fuselage of the next-generation
stealth fighter at facilities near Boeing Field. Sources said that
work would be moved, probably to St. Louis, only if Boeing
determined it would make good business sense to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation plans are a result of the many facilities and
programs Boeing acquired last year from McDonnell Douglas and its
purchase in late 1996 of the space business of Rockwell
International in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mulally, president of Boeing's Information, Space &AMP; defense
Systsems, said in an internal message to employees that the moves
and consolidations will save about $1.6 billion over the next 5
years.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Boeing announced it would cut about 2,000 jobs from
its Information, Space &AMP; Defense Systsems. Those would be included
in the 5,000 to 10,000 jobs that Boeing plans to eliminate in its
space and defense business over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California will experience the brunt of the defense and
space consolidations.
</P>
<P>
   All Boeing operations now in Downey will be moved to other areas
in Southern California, including Huntington Beach and Anaheim.
Most of the facilities in Downey now occupied by Boeing are owned
by NASA, which had wanted Boeing out so the buildings could sold as
part of its own cost-savings consolidations.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing laboratory facilities across the country will be reduced
from about 600 to 450, Mulally said.
</P>
<P>
   The company will close laboratories in Downey, Long Beach,
Palmdale and Canoga Park, and some other Southern California
operations will be moved to new locations in the region. Boeing did
not say how many jobs might be affected by those moves.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's news was greeted by cheers in Long Beach. The new
production line will preserve about 600 jobs otherwise targeted for
elimination as Boeing ends production of the MD-80, MD-90 and MD-11
planes now built at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, California Gov. Pete Wilson said the decision by
Boeing to build 737 planes in Long Beach could eventually result in
more than the 600 jobs now projected. He noted that Boeing has
backorders for about 1,000 next generation 737s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased that the good folks at Boeing have chosen Long
Beach to build the next generation 737s,'' he said. ``This will
mean an immediate 600 new jobs for the Southland, and even more
jobs as Boeing builds 1,000 of these aircfart ... Boeing didn't
chose us so they could take their lunch breaks at the beach. They
were impressed by out skilled workforce and the ability of the
state and the city to work together to produce a winning offer.''
</P>
<P>
   California's trade and commerce department has been working
closely with Boeing on a multimillion economic incentive package,
but people familiar with the talks said nothing has been signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``California stands ready to do everything possible for Boeing
on an incentive package,'' said department spokesman Jesus
Arredondo. ``We have been working with them on and off, and now
with the 737 announcement we will re-engage 100 percent and see
what we can come up with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
