<HEADLINE>
SONY VIDEO CAMERA CAN SEE THROUGH CLOTHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- X-ray vision may no longer be limited to
Superman.
</P>
<P>
   The Sony Corp. said Thursday that under certain conditions,
users of its Nightshot-equipped Handycam video cameras can peep
through thin, light-colored clothing and even bathing suits.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation has caused a rush of calls to Los Angeles-area
stores that sell the cameras, which cost from $600 to $1,800. But
they won't be available forever, because Sony has modified all of
its new cameras so they cannot be used by video peepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It recently came to Sony's attention that this Nightshot
feature has an unintended capability to see through clothing under
certain conditions,'' said Hiro Takahashi, a Sony Corp. spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still keeping the Nightshot function so it works in
darkness, but it has been modified so that it cannot be activated
in daylight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony said it was as surprised as anyone. It designed the
infrared feature to capture such innocent moments as sleeping
babies or nocturnal animals. But with an inexpensive gelatin
filter, a Nightshot-equipped camera can see through some clothing,
Takahashi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires certain conditions,'' he said. ``So an image taken
in daylight or a similar type of brightness -- and depending on the
thickness or color of the clothing -- under these conditions you
can see through clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Handycam's unintended use came to light first in an article
in Takarajima, a popular Japanese men's magazine. From there the
word spread -- quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be video voyeurs were quick to call up electronic stores
throughout the L.A. area in hopes of finding one of the 400,000
Handycams that Sony shipped to North America.
</P>
<P>
   And store employees were also quick to try it out for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Samy's Camera in Hollywood received 20 calls Thursday from
people wanting ``the camera that sees through people's clothing,''
said Doug Kim, a video-sales employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning, I was inundated with calls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But then Kim tried every possible filter to see what he could
see -- and it didn't work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to see through people's clothes,'' he added.
``It's just some science-fiction fantasy. I don't know who's saying
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim said he believes that even if it were possible, the picture
would lack true definition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, it's just impossible,'' he said. ``All you would
see would just be blobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the dozens of people who called Fry's Electronics
in suburban Woodland Hills to ask about the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants that camera,'' said one employee who declined
to be named.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
