<HEADLINE>
BOEING TO LAY OFF 2,300 CONTRACT WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN WEST  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ About 2,300 Boeing contract workers in the Puget Sound
area will lose their jobs in the next few weeks as part of the
company's phase-out of its temporary engineering work force in the
commercial aircraft division, the Seattle Post-Intelligencer has
learned.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing already has notified some of the workers and more
termination notices were expected to go out as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Some exceptions could be made for contract workers who are
crucial to production of Boeing commercial aircraft. Boeing
officials are in the process of evaluating the company's contract
labor force to determine how many jobs would remain.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing spokeswoman Susan Davis confirmed Thursday that a
majority of the 2,300 positions _ nearly all of which are in
engineering _ will be phased out in the next few weeks. She said no
specific timetable has yet been set, although some contract workers
already have been let go.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Peterson, who designs interiors for Boeing widebody
passenger jets in Everett, north of Seattle, said he and dozens of
other contract employees were warned they could lose their jobs
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody feels like they have one foot off the diving
board,'' said Peterson, who just bought a home in Bremerton. ``It's
not a very productive work environment right now. They are letting
experience just walk out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   After a series of management meetings Thursday, Peterson said
his boss still did not know whether the contract workers in his
area would have jobs Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just told us to prepare for the worst,'' said Peterson, who
has worked for Boeing on and off since 1992. ``It's a sad situation
for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   He said lower-level managers are being put in the awkward
position of having to break the news to their employees, but not
given any specific information.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to be left holding the bag when there's nobody
left to build airplanes,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   The contract employees are among the first of the 12,000
positions Boeing had previously announced it would cut from its
commercial aircraft division beginning this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing this to avoid laying off permanent Boeing
employees,'' Davis said. ``The reason we bring these people in is
to keep the permanent work force more stable.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract labor force phase-out, which is not part of the
companywide consolidation announced Thursday, comes just two days
after Boeing Commercial Airplane Group President Ron Woodard
ordered a hiring freeze in the commercial division. He also ordered
managers to limit travel expenditures and to curtail spending on
``non-essential'' items.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard's cost-cutting program is in response to Boeing Chairman
Phil Condit's goal of obtaining a 7 percent net return on sales by
2000 _ a goal the company has so far never been able to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Companywide, Boeing has about 9,800 contract employees, 3,000 of
whom work for the commercial division's engineering unit. For now,
the only concerted effort to reduce Boeing's temporary labor force
is in its Commercial Airplane Group, which has 118,000 employees
and is based in Renton.
</P>
<P>
   While the contract employees work for Boeing, they are not
considered permanent Boeing employees and do not receive full
company benefits. Instead, they are employed by individual contract
labor firms who offer their own set of benefits and perks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there would be some reductions but we didn't
anticipate it would be to this extent,'' said Steve Dworkin,
president of Bellevue-based CTS International, a recruiting company
specializing in placing high-tech personnel for aerospace and
telecommunications. ``When Boeing goes through a period of
cost-cutting, it affects us as well.''
</P>
<P>
   He said about 1,000 of the contract employees his firm has
placed with Boeing could be affected by the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Boeing Commercial Airplane Group managers
began studying the need to phase out its contract labor force as
part of overall cost-cutting measures, but until now, no major job
reductions have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike union members, Boeing is not required to give contract
workers advance warning that their jobs will be eliminated,
although the company has given workers early notice in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know they can be let go at any time,'' said Kim Cartland,
account executive with Butler Service Group in Redmond, one of the
10 consulting companies Boeing uses to find engineering and
technical contract workers.
</P>
<P>
   She said about 300 to 400 of the contract workers her firm has
placed with Boeing could be affected by the job cuts. Many of those
workers are highly skilled engineers who were hired during Boeing's
worldwide recruiting drive 2{ years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident we will be able to place them in other
positions throughout the Puget Sound,'' Cartland said.
</P>
<P>
   Dworkin with CTS agreed, saying there is a strong marketplace
for top-notch engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are highly sought-after technical aerospace engineers
and designers who are experts in their fields,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
