r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-ARMY-AZR &LR;      08-14 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ARMY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAYWORTH AND KOLBE LEARN LEADERSHIP STRATEGIES AT PENTAGON
EXPENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers have long traded rhetorical fire, and now
they've gone a step further: military training.
</P>
<P>
   A new Pentagon report details how Army centers around the
country improperly picked up the tab to train GOP House members,
including two Arizonans, in war and leadership strategies after
Republicans took over Congress in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona representatives, J.D. Hayworth and Jim Kolbe, and 18
of Kolbe's staff members, traveled to Army bases in 1995 and 1996,
respectively, for sessions on such topics as strategic thinking and
crisis management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were interested in learning how the Army trains individuals
to be more effective leaders,'' said Ron Foreman, Kolbe's press
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave the staff some insight into how a war fighter thinks,
how a war fighter seeks to neutralize the `enemy.' Don't forget
that at the time this training took place, we had only recently had
to deal with the Mount Graham protesters coming into the office and
chaining themselves to furniture and being disruptive.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators were protesting a Kolbe-backed telescope
project on Mount Graham.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the training took root when Newt Gingrich _ a
self-styled ``military brat'' whose stepfather was a career Army
officer _ sent his chief of staff and other aides to the Army
Training and Doctrine Command at Fort Monroe, Va., for a briefing
on organizational design.
</P>
<P>
   Other training sessions followed, but the Pentagon Office of
Inspector General now says the Army made a mistake by picking up
the bill instead of having the lawmakers pay their own way. The
report didn't question the value of the training itself.
</P>
<P>
   Though there is no evidence that Republicans were hatching
strategy to use against Democrats, an Army official expressed
concerns about the seminars in a December 1995 memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal feelings are that we keep a wary eye on this
process; we could wind up being loved too much, and to our
embarrassment,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The $15,000 expenditure for the sessions included training for
Hayworth, Kolbe, 18 members of Kolbe's staff, Gingrich and a small
group of other GOP aides and lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe and his staff accepted an Army invitation to be sent to
Fort McNair in Virginia in March 1996. The one-day training cost
$1,022, including meals.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon isn't asking for any of the $15,000 back. Foreman
noted that, from a fiscal standpoint, it doesn't matter who pays
because ``we're really talking about taxpayer dollars coming out of
one account to reimburse taxpayer dollars for another account.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate breakdown on how much Hayworth's training
cost. He attended a two-day session at Virginia's Fort Monroe in
November 1995 along with a dozen other members and staff.
</P>
<P>
   An itinerary for Hayworth's trip includes the notation,
```Depart for Fort Monroe via U.S. Army helicopter.'' It says that
the members and staff began training on a Thursday evening, stayed
overnight at a hotel and continued the sessions the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth ``thought it was all very valuable,'' said Joseph Eule,
his chief of staff. ``This is the kind of training that military
officers get who work in high stress jobs like we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Eule said Hayworth, like the other members who attended, assumed
the Army had checked out the propriety of footing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with Congressman Hayworth,'' Eule said.
``This was organized by the Army and by the speaker's office
(Gingrich), and if there are outstanding issues regarding billing,
we're confident that the Army and the speaker will work them out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Kolbe has taken the White House to task for
using taxpayer dollars to fund political events such as coffees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that context, if the Army determined these (training
sessions) were reimbursable expenses . . . then we'd certainly
support that,'' Foreman said. ``No one should be left with the
impression that we're trying to get away with something here.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kolbe nor Hayworth were available for comment, their
aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report emphasized that, despite some
initial concerns, there was no evidence the Army personnel
addressed partisan issues in their briefings. It said instructors
wore their uniforms to emphasize that their training was on Army
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The seminars covered such things as information management,
strategic thinking and the art of battle decision-making. Gingrich,
R-Ga., has made three personal visits to Fort Monroe in 1993, 1995
and 1997 for briefings on such subjects as lessons learned in
Somalia, war fighting concepts and the Army's future.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich spokesman Andrew Weinstein said the report ``concludes
that this was a minor internal Defense Department billing issue.''
He said it was proper for the military to help lawmakers learn how
to better carry out their official duties. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
