<HEADLINE>
`EL DUQUE' BLANKS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dear Texas Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Yankees' /No. 5'' starter.
</P>
<P>
   (Gulp.)
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, who recorded a
career-high 13 strikeout during 8 1/3 innings, surrendered only two
hits as New York defeated the Rangers, 2-0, last night at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That does not bode well for the Rangers should the two emerge as
opponents in the American League's best-of-five, divisional playoff
series, which would occur if the postseason began this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers retained their half-game advantage in the AL West
with a little help from the second-place Anaheim Angels, who lost
to the Blue Jays, 4-3, last night in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's masterpiece overshadowed the performance of Rangers
right-hander Rick Helling, who surrendered only three singles and
issued three walks during his third complete-game effort this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scratched a run during the first inning with a
two-out, run-scoring single from first baseman Tino Martinez and
scored the game's only other run on a third-inning sacrifice fly
off the bat of shortstop Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers wasted what manager Johnny Oates described as
Helling's ``best outing'' this season. But perhaps no inning proved
more costly than the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore collected the first of the Rangers'
season-low two hits with a one-out double that glanced high off the
center-field wall. Hernandez (8-3) then demonstrated his savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez _ who entered the game allowing left-handed hitters a
.315 batting average _ pitched left fielder Rusty Greer cautiously
and issued a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez _ who entered the game allowing right-handed hitters a
.144 batting average _ went aggressively after right fielder Juan
Gonzalez with a steady diet of sliders off the plate. Hernandez
retired the right-handed batter on strikes for the inning's second
out before loading the bases with a two-out walk to first baseman
Will Clark, another of the Rangers' left-handed hitters.
</P>
<P>
   That brought catcher Ivan Rodriguez to the plate with two outs,
and Hernandez took an approach similar to the one Gonzalez
witnessed. Hernandez retired Rodriguez on strikes as well, and the
Rangers managed only three runners the remainder of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth inning was a telltale sign of what type of pitcher
he is,'' Oates said of Hernandez. ``It looked like he knew who he
wanted to pitch against. He knew he wanted to go after Juan and
Pudge, and he wasn't going to mess around with Rusty and Will.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who missed the previous three games with muscle spasms
in the left side of his neck, went 0-for-3 with three strikeouts
and a ninth-inning walk against Hernandez. The Rangers'
right-handed batters went 1-for-14 with two walks and 10 strikeouts
against ``El Duque.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough on right-handed hitters,'' said third baseman Todd
Zeile, who collected the Rangers' second and final base hit with a
seventh-inning double. ``He throws strikes with three different
pitches from all different angles. Anybody who can do that is going
to be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of their rotation best explains why the Yankees will
enter tonight's game 59 games over .500 and on a pace to establish
a major-league record with 121 victories this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great rotation,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it might not include Hernandez once the playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   That likely pleases the Rangers, but what does that say about
the remainder of the Yankees' rotation?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice problem to have,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
