<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACURA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT REACHES QUARTERFINALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scorching, hot, en fuego... pick a word to describe Lindsay
Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked second in the world, Davenport has won the last two Corel
WTA tournaments, at Stanford and La Costa, and is looking for her
third straight win in the Acura Classic at Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport sizzled again on Thursday night. She advanced to the
quarterfinals with ease when she beat Julie Halard-Decugis 6-0,
6-4, in 49 minutes and win her ninth consecutive match.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Manhattan Beach tournament in 1996, Davenport
is trying to reclaim Los Angeles bragging rights because Monica
Seles dethroned her in last year's final. Next, in the
quarterfinals, Davenport faces eighth-seeded Natasha Zvereva
tonight at 7. Zvereva, who also lives in Newport Beach, is
Davenport's usual doubles partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's the battle of Newport Beach,'' Davenport
said. ``It will be important when we go back to our club.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning at Manhattan Beach is important to Davenport, but it
does not compare to winning a Grand Slam event. With the rest of
the tour, she is keying up for the U.S. Open later this month.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that the rigors of the tour are taking a toll on
the 6-2, 175-pound Davenport. She has opted not to play doubles
this week to grab some rest and will skip a tournament between the
Acura Classic and U.S. Open. She was lucky to not have played since
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really happy to have the Thursday start,'' Davenport
said. ``I was pretty sore all over, and the days off helped. I was
able to relax at home. I saw a few friends, didn't do anything
strenuous.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest paid off in the match against Halard-Decugis, ranked
34th. Davenport took the first set in 16 minutes. In the second
set, Halard-Decugis staged a brief comeback, tying it at 4 after
trailing 4-1. But Davenport took the final two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you're playing really well, a few more errors
start to creep in,'' Davenport said. ``That's what happened then.
She really started to run well and get a lot of balls, and before I
knew it, it was 4-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, 22, lives in Newport Beach and was born in Palos
Verdes. Her hometown ties add incentive to win in Manhattan Beach,
but that is not her main tennis goal. That goal, winning a Grand
Slam event, cannot be achieved on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that the ranking doesn't matter that much,''
Davenport said. ``If I had to choose between being No.1 or winning
a Grand Slam tournament, I'd chose to win the Grand Slam. I'm sure
I'd be happy and excited if I became No.1. But that still is a long
way away.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though she has been inching toward top-ranked Hingis,
Davenport is not quite breathing down her neck. Davenport first
became No.2 on November 17 and was 2,741 points behind Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport has made huge strides and now stands 497 points behind
Hingis. But that still is a world away. For example, when Davenport
won the Toshiba Classic at La Costa last week and Hingis lost in
the semifinals, she gained just 90 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 500 points, but that seems like a far way away,''
Davenport said. ``But in the past few months, I think my level has
really risen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
