<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ CHALLENGES RANGERS AND WINS, 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez lived his whole life according to
the whims of the state before defecting from Cuba. Now he is in the
United States, wearing New York Yankee pinstripes, living the way
he wants, pitching the way he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez worked against conventional baseball wisdom Thursday
night, as he struck out 13 batters in eight and a third innings and
beat the Texas Rangers, 2-0, before 53,835 fans at Yankee Stadium,
many of them cheering and standing as Hernandez struck out another
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   In beating the Rangers, who lead the American League West,
Hernandez (8-3) allowed two hits before yielding to Mariano Rivera
with one out in the ninth inning. By then he had pitched a
two-hitter and shut down the team ranked second in the league in
batting average and runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   By striking out 13, Hernandez set a single-game record for a
Yankee rookie, surpassing the mark of 12 by Stan Bahnsen against
Boston in 1968. Only David Cone, with 14 against Florida on June 7,
has collected more strikeouts in a Yankee game this season.
</P>
<P>
   The performance prompted a curtain call for Hernandez by the
crowd, which roared in appreciation after he departed in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Just another day at the records office for the Yankees, who are
running away from the rest of the American League East, the rest of
the American League and almost all previous standards of success.
</P>
<P>
   They have won eight straight games, their third winning streak
of eight games or more this season, and have 88 victories and 29
losses. They need to win 29 of their remaining 45 games to set a
major-league record for victories in one season.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez works out according to his own program; Manager Joe
Torre figures that Hernandez's training regimen is so much more
strenuous, with so much more running, that he may as well let the
right-hander do what he wants. Hernandez wears his baseball pants
higher than almost any other player, he bends the bill of his cap
unlike anyone else and he certainly pitches the way he wants.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out five batters in the first three innings without
allowing a hit, establishing early that he had a good fastball and
that right-handed batters would have difficulty tracking his
sidearm slider.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the fourth and the Yankees ahead by two runs,
Mark McLemore ripped the Rangers' first hit, tomahawking a high
fastball off the top of the wall in right-center field for a
double. Rusty Greer, a left-handed hitter, was coming up, and as
Juan Gonzalez, with a major-league-leading 119 RBIs, loomed in the
on-deck circle, biceps bulging, it figured that Hernandez would
pitch aggressively to Greer.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, Hernandez defied that logic. He worked around
Greer, walking him on four straight pitches, the sort of approach
that makes a manager grind his teeth. Hernandez, no doubt, had seen
Gonzalez swing weakly at sliders in his first at-bat, and he wanted
to test him again.
</P>
<P>
   Three sidearm sliders. Three swings. A strikeout. A roar.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark stepped up, and Hernandez once again demonstrated his
preference to work around a left-handed batter. He walked Clark to
fill the bases, bringing up Ivan Rodriguez, who entered the game
with a .326 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez got ahead of Rodriguez with two fastballs, then threw
a slider. The fans stood and screamed for another strikeout, and
got it, when Rodriguez flailed pathetically at another sidearm
slider.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck out the side again in the fifth, giving him 10
strikeouts in five innings, then struck out Gonzalez for the third
time in the sixth. When Mike Simms struck out in the seventh,
Hernandez had 12 strikeouts. His previous high had been nine,
against Montreal on June 3 and against the New York Mets on June
28.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Yankees have led at some point in every game since that Mets
game, 42 in all, and as they have done during this homestand, they
jumped out ahead early last night.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the first, Derek Jeter reached on a throwing
error by the Texas shortstop Royce Clayton, and Paul O'Neill
walked. Jeter seemed to sabotage the rally by getting thrown out
trying to steal third base.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams singled, however, with O'Neill stopping at
second, and Tino Martinez smacked a single to left, O'Neill
scampering home with the Yankees' first run.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Scott Brosius, who has been using a heavier
bat in the last month, led off with a single. Swinging a 34-ounce
bat, Brosius had four homers in the five games preceding last
night's and he had five RBIs on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Batting against Texas starter Rick Helling in the third inning,
Brosius pulled a single through the left side, then took second on
a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees then put their fundamental skills to work. Chuck
Knoblauch pushed a grounder to the right side, giving himself up to
advance Brosius to third, and Jeter lined out to deep right field,
allowing Brosius to tag up and score.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2-0, all the runs Hernandez would need.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles may fade out of the playoff race and look
to trade veteran players before the Sept. 1 deadline for playoff
rosters, but the Yankees have destroyed any chance of the Orioles'
swapping either second baseman Roberto Alomar or first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro. According to an American League executive, the
Yankees placed waiver claims on both players, forcing the Orioles
to withdraw both names from the waiver wire. By rule, neither can
be traded for the rest of the season. ... Designated hitter Chili
Davis has four days left in his rehabilitation assignment at Class
AAA Columbus, and assuming he doesn't reinjure his right ankle, the
Yankees intend to activate him on Monday, for a game in Kansas
City. Outfielder Shane Spencer is expected to go back to the
minors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
