<HEADLINE>
`YOU BE THE JUDGE': THOUGHT-PROVOKING, IF CHEESY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tune in to ``You Be the Judge'' to hear Jerry Orbach say,
``Coming up next, arguments why you should have a gun in your
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, good. One reason might be for just such an occasion. To blow
your Sony through the wall and into your next-door neighbor's
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you believe in speaking reasonably to your Sony and
trying to persuade it to hurl itself through the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Sunday's special on NBC, hosted by the ``Law and Order''
star, tries to stink up the tube but has merit in spite of itself.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to take three divisive public issues, separately
present strident pro and con arguments for each, and let viewers
figure out where they stand.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't issues like, should we watch ``Home Improvement''
or ``Frasier.'' Sunday's trio: Should police engage in high-speed
pursuits? Have sexual harassment lawsuits gone too far? Should
Americans keep guns in their homes for self-defense?
</P>
<P>
   You (big sound effect) be the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Be the Judge'' does its best to conceal its value under
all the cheesy production values of an ``Unsolved Mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   That means turbocharged re-enactments and raw emotion. The pro
and con pieces, about seven minutes each, are like extended
political hit commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But ``You Be the Judge,'' with its battling tape clips, does
effectively provoke thought about things that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the best reasons for cops to barrel after a traffic
violator at dangerous speeds, or not. The best reasons to keep a
gun, or not.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual harassment installment is less focused. One clip
makes the case that laws are vague, the other that sexual
harassment exists. When you can agree with both clips, the argument
hasn't been properly framed.
</P>
<P>
   For NBC, the unintentional irony is that a low-rent
entertainment special will probably give viewers more insight and
useful information than the news division's ``Dateline NBC,'' which
follows it on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Stone Phillips, or Jerry Orbach? You (sound of rapping gavel) be
the judge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ Other sluggers have broken his major records, but HBO's ``Babe
Ruth,'' on Sunday, shows how the Bambino remains baseball's
greatest figure, 50 years after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Rick Bernstein's hourlong documentary is repetitive and
hyperbolic. But it does capture Ruth as a force of nature, and a
well-timed metaphor for America's own growing clout and broad
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   He was jolly and vulgar, and had a huge appetite for everything
from chow to sex. He wasn't the brightest bulb. When he heard that
someone had a case of amnesia, he wondered if a bottle might be
saved for him.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth was also exciting, and generous, and so physically gifted
that he took the national pastime on his back and transformed it
forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a joy to be around,'' says one of Ruth's biographers.
``He lifted things up. He was alive.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Also this weekend: On HBO's ``Hot Cup of Talk'' (Friday),
comic Kathy Griffin of ``Suddenly Susan'' is delicious dissing
Celine Dion and Mariah Carey, but perhaps too crude for most tastes
when she converts her own anatomy into a comedy riff ... ``Titanic
Live'' (Sunday on the Discovery Channel) will be just that _ a live
telecast exploring the liner's wreck site in the North Atlantic ...
And the Fox Family Channel, formerly just the Family Channel,
presents ``Men in White,'' a movie spoof of ``Men in Black,'' on
Sunday. They're a mite slow on the uptake, and didn't send out a
preview tape.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
