<HEADLINE>
STREET SMARTS/MARK VEVERKA  
 RUMORS OF VANSTAR BREAKUP HAVE SILICON VALLEY HEADS SPINNING 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - STREET SMARTS   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
A breakup of Vanstar appears to be in the cards.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the bottom continues to drop out of the Atlanta-based
computer services company, the probability of a corporate
restructuring that would unlock shareholder value is running very
high, say sources familiar with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley is abuzz with leaks about Vanstar's plans to spin off
its more valuable computer services and consulting business as a
separate company. The $2.8 billion behemoth has a huge presence in
the Bay Area, employing about 1,000 workers at offices and
warehouses in Pleasanton, Concord, Alameda and Livermore. Vanstar's
companywide payroll is just short of 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Word is that line-managers on up have been taking part in
strategy powwows to prepare for a divestiture, sources say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plans (for a breakup) are in the works,'' says a vendor
source who has been apprised of the changes. ``I think its pretty
imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that one of Vanstar's three business segments,
the selling of personal computers, is punishing the company's stock
valuation. Unit sales for that segment are up, but gross profit
margins are down.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company's other two businesses _ computer
services and consulting _ each are growing rapidly and enjoy fat
profit margins in the 30 to 40 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the likely scenario is for Vanstar to spin off its
consulting and services shops as a separate company so that it
might fetch a much higher stock price than the valuation of the
three companies combined.
</P>
<P>
   It can't get much worse. Right now, Vanstar stock is in the
tank. It closed yesterday at $7.56 a share, a 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
   The share price has been slammed because the company warned last
week that financial results for its first quarter ended July 31
would be worse than anticipated. Vanstar says it expects revenues
of about $645 million, some $35 million to $55 million lower than
previous estimates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company expects an operating loss of as much as
25 cents a share for the quarter, which is way off the Street's
adjusted consensus estimate of 2 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the warning, though, one financial analyst pegged the
breakup value of Vanstar at $20 a share. But now, Vincent Turzo of
Jefferies in San Francisco is backing off that valuation until the
company officially posts its July quarter numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Above and beyond lousy earnings, a key problem is that investors
consider Vanstar a personal computer distributor, using a
price-earnings multiple of about 13 times earnings. Consulting and
services companies often see multiples as high as 30 times
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Vanstar officials are sticking to the party
line. They acknowledge that the company has been working closely
with CS First Boston's technology group, led by uberbanker Frank
Quattrone, to ``evaluate the full range of options'' for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   In a previously released statement, Vanstar said its choices
include ``realignment or separation of the company's business
units, the merger or sale of the company, or the disposition of
certain assets.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the playbook called for option one (a spin-off),
investor relations director Christine Mohrmann would say only that
the company ``does not comment on speculation or rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Vanstar's directors are prepared to vote on a
restructuring is unclear. The full board is next scheduled to meet
at the company's annual shareholder meeting in Atlanta on September
9.
</P>
<P>
   Mohrr would not ``speculate'' on whether a breakup vote would be
on the board's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the company's proxy statement for the shareholder
confab is expected to be filed today or Monday with the Securities
and Exchange Commission. And it is not expected to include any
official business for shareholders regarding a restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pressure is on Vanstar chief executive William
Tauscher and his board to do something to boost shareholder value.
Applying the most heat is Leon Cooperman, manager of the $4.5
billion Omega hedge fund in New York, which has owned as much as
4.9 percent of Vanstar.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperman called for a divestiture during a conference call with
management in late spring. Now, he's just sitting by his phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just waiting to see what the company has to say,''
Cooperman says.
</P>
<P>
   The money manager adds that Vanstar management has told him that
its bankers also are ``shopping the company around to strategic
buyers,'' which means that a buyout is not totally out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, it sounds as though management has been listening to
Cooperman's pleas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by &LR;   &LR; e-mail
at  &LR; lf  &LR; mveverka &LR; sfgate.com.  &LR; li &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
