<SLUG> BC-CITYSEARCH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITYSEARCH PULLS IPO, WILL BUY TICKETMASTER  
 BY JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - CITYSEARCH   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
CitySearch abruptly yanked its initial public offering yesterday
and instead announced a merger with USA Networks' Ticketmaster unit
worth a reported $260 million.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The combined company, to be called Ticketmaster
Online-CitySearch, plans to file an IPO later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision,'' said Charles Conn, Ticketmaster
Online-CitySearch chief executive. Conn previously was the CEO of
CitySearch. ``Investors were jazzed about the CitySearch offering,
but something better came along. We anticipate a more successful
IPO with the new company.''
</P>
<P>
   CitySearch had every intention of going public, he said, until
USA Networks began 11th-hour merger talks two weeks ago. The
companies inked a deal last year for CitySearch to offer
Ticketmaster access on its community Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of yesterday's merger, USA Networks agreed to
increase its stake in Pasadena-based CitySearch to 62.5 percent
from 13 percent. Conn said the deal would allow the firm to offer
``integrated ticketing'' on its online arts and entertainment guide
of 18 cities, including San Francisco, Los Angeles and Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster Online, launched almost two years ago, has
increased monthly sales to $10 million from $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers said CitySearch officials pulled the
company's IPO out of fear that it would pale in comparison with
another online community, GeoCities, which more than doubled its
initial offering price of $17, to $37.31, on Tuesday. The stock
closed at $38.50 yesterday, placing its market cap at a staggering
$1.18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Monica-based GeoCities, which generates online traffic by
letting users create free Web sites, pegged its initial price range
at $12 to $14 in a Securities and Exchange Commission filing.
</P>
<P>
   CitySearch, by comparison, had not changed its pricing range of
$11 to $13 since an IPO filing in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough IPO market even for Internet companies,'' said
portfolio manager Kathleen Smith of Renaissance Capital Corp.'s IPO
Fund in Greenwich, Conn. ``It's important to get out there first
and establish your brand name.''
</P>
<P>
   Jittery investors also were concerned whether CitySearch could
knock heads with America Online, Microsoft, Yahoo and others.
</P>
<P>
   CitySearch lost $8.5 million for the quarter ended June 30,
compared with an $8.9 million shortfall a year ago. The company
registered sales of $3.7 million, up from $1 million last year. All
told, the 3-year-old company has lost $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Conn insisted that the merger strengthens CitySearch's
offerings and primes it for a bigger IPO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are desperate for good stories,'' Conn said. ``The
fact that GeoCities went strongly created a greater buzz for us
among investors.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
