<HEADLINE>
RIFLE CHAMP DISQUALIFIED, ACCUSED OF CHEATING ON SCORES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP PERRY, Ohio _ A young Arizona woman, hailed last year as a
national shooting champion, has been accused of cheating at the
nation's most prestigious shooting tournament here.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Abbott, 18, was disqualified Wednesday from the
National Rifle Association's high-power rifle championships after a
rules committee determined she had falsified a score card.
</P>
<P>
   A California youth also admitted to falsifying a score card.
Both left Camp Perry on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, preliminary results Thursday indicated that Nancy
Tompkins-Gallagher of Prescott won the match's highest overall
award, the national high-power rifle championship. Her daughter,
Michelle Gallagher, 17, won a 600-yard rife match; Jake Quamme, 13,
of Goodyear, won a standing shooting match.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, whose family lives in Queen Creek, astonished the
shooting world here last year when at age 17 she won the civilian
service rifle championship. But many in the Valley were also
questioning that remarkable victory Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know many shooters are wondering about that win last year,
but as far as I'm concerned right now, it's a dead issue,'' said
match director Jim Hill, himself a past Camp Perry champion.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott could not be reached for comment Thursday. However, her
father, Terry Abbott, 45, said: ``She does not deny anything. She
put herself under tremendous pressure to do well. That pressure
overcame her good judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made a mistake. She regrets that very much.''
</P>
<P>
   The prestigious four-day event at an Ohio National Guard base on
Lake Erie establishes the NRA national champion in various
categories of high-power rifle shooting. Shooters regard the annual
contest as the ultimate challenge; many prepare for it all year.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said that on Tuesday, five competitors who were shooting
``with or near'' Abbott filed a protest with officials when they
saw scores posted with higher values for Abbott than they had
witnessed her shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her scorekeeper also said the signature on the scorecard was
not his, and the scores were not the same as he had recorded,''
Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the scoring committee determined that Abbott
apparently substituted another score card for the original one,
``and falsified the scores she received.'' He said he never before
had known of a suspected cheating incident at Camp Perry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got two at one time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   High-power rifle competitors shoot from 200, 300 and 600 yards,
with rifles equipped with open sites _ no telescopic sights are
allowed. Competitors shoot from standing, sitting and prone
positions.
</P>
<P>
   While one person is shooting, another competitor keeps score
beside the shooter; a third stands down range behind a protective
berm and raises and lowers the target and marks the spot where the
bullets hit.
</P>
<P>
   It was a scorer working with a competitor near Abbott who first
noted problems with her score. Quinn Moore, 45, of Albertville,
Ala., lost the championship to Abbott last year by one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did she come here and not think we'd be watching her?'' Moore
asked Thursday. ``I watched her shoot a 196, but when it was posted
it became a 199. After we saw that we really started watching her,
and she did it again.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
