<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3456 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-BONILLA-L     08-14 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BONILLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MOVE BONILLA TO BENCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bobby Bonilla, batting only .190 since returning
from the disabled list nine days ago, has been benched by the
Dodgers in favor of a left-field platoon of Matt Luke and Trenidad
Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, acquired from the Florida Marlins in the May 15 Mike
Piazza trade, came to the Dodgers to provide left-handed power and
leadership. But with the Dodgers struggling and Bonilla healing
from offseason surgery to his left wrist and left Achilles tendon,
the club ran out of patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He simply isn't in shape to play left field,'' Dodgers manager
Glenn Hoffman said. ``We're not saying he is responsible for the
team's trouble. He's pretty banged up and can't do the job. It was
a mutual decision.''
</P>
<P>
   And an expensive one. Bonilla, 35, has two years remaining on
his contract at $5.9 million per season. The club made the decision
after interim general manager Tom Lasorda met with manager Glenn
Hoffman at 3 p.m. Hoffman then broke the news to Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm OK with it, I'm not angry,'' Bonilla said. ``If they want
to blame this season on me they can. I haven't played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla homered last Sunday in a 2-1 loss to Pittsburgh. It was
his first home run since the first night he joined the club, a span
of 39 games and 136 at-bats. With the Dodgers, he is batting only
.200, and .202 from the all-important left side.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his defense that was most alarming. Bonilla had
difficulty getting to balls and became a target of booing fans at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the least of my problems,'' Bonilla said. ``I've
heard a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda has been particularly frustrated with Bonilla's lack of
production. Before the July 31 non-waiver trade deadline, Lasorda
unsuccessfully tried to trade Bonilla to the St. Louis Cardinals
for outfielder Ron Gant.
</P>
<P>
   During the Dodgers' recent East Coast trip, Lasorda became upset
when Bonilla said the club should let him go home to rehabilitate
his injuries rather than wait for him to regain his 1997 form. He
drove in 96 runs for the World Series-champion Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they put me in left field, they knew I still had injuries
that would hurt my effectiveness,'' Bonilla said. ``(The injuries)
are getting better, but the doctors said both would take a year to
get back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Bonilla will pinch hit and occasionally play third in
place of rookie Adrian Beltre. But even Hoffman said there does not
appear to be many at-bats in Bonilla's immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might want to give Beltre a day off against a certain
pitcher, but he's going to pretty much be in there,'' Hoffman said
of his rookie third baseman, who hit a two-run homer in the fourth
inning Thursday. ``We'll see what develops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
