<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISSBANKS-NAZIS-1STL     08-14 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSBANKS-NAZIS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SANCTIONS AGAINST SWISS ENDED IN WAKE OF SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for inserts and to recast lede.)  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Pa.)  (lh) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after the $1.25 billion settlement between Holocaust
survivors and Swiss commercial banks accused of profiting from the
Nazi era, officials in several states said that they would drop
threatened sanctions against Swiss financial interests, and a major
Swiss insurer facing a lawsuit from victims of the Holocaust agreed
to honor their outstanding life and property claims.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in New York, California, Pennsylvania and a number of
other cities and states had threatened to begin imposing sanctions
on Sept. 1, saying they were necessary to press the Swiss because
two years of negotiations had not led to a settlement. The State
Department had opposed the proposed penalties _ like barring
short-term deposits of city and state funds in Swiss banks _ saying
such pressure was hardening attitudes in Switzerland and souring
relations between Switzerland and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with the agreement'' with the banks, which was
announced Wednesday, said New York City Comptroller Alan Hevesi,
who heads a national committee of financial officers who have been
monitoring the negotiations. He said they ``have unanimously agreed
that we will cancel all planned sanctions.'' Hevesi spoke at a news
conference with New York state Comptroller Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
   In California, state Treasurer Matt Fong, who had imposed some
sanctions on Swiss banks a year ago, announced that he was lifting
all investment sanctions effective immediately. Pennsylvania
Treasurer Barbara Hafer said she was also canceling proposed
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Zurich Insurance Co. agreed to work with an
international commission to help process and settle unpaid claims
to Holocaust victims and their heirs, Reuters reported. Along with
15 other European insurers _ including two Swiss companies _ the
company is facing a class-action lawsuit in the U.S. District Court
in Manhattan by Holocaust survivors and their families who say the
companies withheld or concealed the value or proceeds of policies
sold before 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish organizations and Holocaust survivors generally welcomed
the bank settlement as at least partial closure on a painful
chapter. ``It is a fair settlement,'' said Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean
of the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles. ``I'm happy this is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewish organizations took pains to stress that the settlement
was neither punishment for the banks nor a reward for survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a question of a settlement; it is not a question of
money,'' said Benjamin Meed, president of the American Gathering of
Holocaust Survivors and a survivor of the Warsaw Ghetto. ``This is
a question of morality.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo Rechter, 70, who endured the Holocaust as a child and lost
his father to it, said that most Holocaust survivors would receive
little money. ``I think the Swiss could have done much better,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the plaintiffs said the amount roughly
corresponded to the amount of Jews' assets that were seized by the
Nazis and processed through Swiss banks. Joel Sweet, one of the
lawyers, said the settlement could establish an important global
precedent. ``When commercial actors profit illicitly from political
or human-rights abuses, they will be forced to pay,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under the settlement, the major Swiss commercial banks, Credit
Suisse and Union Bank of Switzerland, agreed to guarantee payments
of $1.25 billion, plus any interest accrued before the payments are
made. As a result of mergers and acquisitions, the two banks now
represent 85 percent of Switzerland's commercial bank activity in
1945, lawyers for the plaintiffs said.
</P>
<P>
   In return, a class-action lawsuit against the commercial banks
in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn and a suit in the Northern
District in California will be dropped, as will a major suit
against the Government-owned Swiss National Bank in U.S. District
Court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although Credit Suisse recently purchased another of the Swiss
insurers named in the lawsuit, the settlement with the banks
specifically did not eliminate the suit against the insurance
companies, officials said Thursday, which may have prompted Zurich
Insurance Co.'s decision to cooperate in resolving the claims
against it.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Swiss government nor the National Bank took part in
the negotiations, although evidence indicates the national bank
processed most of the gold looted from Jews by the Nazis, and
neither is expected to contribute to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi praised Judge Edward Korman, who several weeks ago began
personally overseeing the talks, for ``putting parties in a room
and apparently not letting them out until there was an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials familiar with the negotiations said as recently as
Monday that the two sides were still far apart. Negotiations had
broken down in June after the Swiss offered $600 million, a figure
the plaintiffs quickly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   But the sanctions deadline was looming and pressure from elected
officials and other public figures increasing and finally, on
Wednesday afternoon, a settlement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   The money will go, first, to those able to document claims to
dormant accounts in Swiss banks, which often denied survivors or
their relatives access to funds deposited before the war if they
lacked proper documentation. Paul Volcker, the former chairman of
the Federal Reserve, is leading a commission that is attempting to
match some 8,000 claims against the dormant accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Ratner, an attorney for the plaintiffs, said the amount
paid out for dormant accounts would prove to be a ``small
percentage'' of the total, since so much evidence on specific
claims has been lost or destroyed over the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the money will be distributed to Holocaust survivors
through a mechanism yet to be determined. That money is considered
a form of ``rough justice,'' or restitution to those who cannot
prove their claims to lost assets, as well as for the profits Swiss
banks made from looted gold and art and from loans to the Nazis
that were used for the construction of slave-labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 law firms working on the case can apply to Korman for
fees, to be paid from the settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   After the judge gives preliminary approval to the settlement
amount, which could happen as early as next week, the Swiss banks
have 30 days to make the first payment of $250 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
