<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3471 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-14 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros sweep four-game series
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Larry Dierker is as cerebral as anyone when it comes to
understanding the nuances of baseball and why certain things happen
the way they do.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he can't figure out how his team keeps finding a
different way to write a winning script night after night. The
theme for Thursday's game was revenge, and Ricky Gutierrez played
the starring role, driving in three runs in a 6-2 victory over the
Milwaukee Brewers in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros completed a four-game sweep of the Brewers _ their
first since taking four games from Montreal in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind early, the Astros did what they seem to do
at will: come back. Thursday's victory marked the 36th time the
Astros have come from behind to win a game this season. They
increased their winning streak to seven games and have won 14 of
their past 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect us to streak right on through the end of the
season,'' Dierker said. ``But it sure is more fun this way. I know
I've said it before, but we just keep finding a way to get it done,
and it seems to be a different guy every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Gutierrez was the hero after Brewers manager Phil
Garner all but dared him to get a hit. Garner ordered starting
pitcher Steve Woodard to intentionally walk Craig Biggio twice,
choosing to pitch to Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every hitter who is put into that situation is going to take
it as a challenge,'' said Dierker, who seldom calls for intentional
walks. ``It's a gamble. If you put a guy on base, the risk you take
is that he might score, and a lot of other guys might score.''
</P>
<P>
   The first spin of the roulette wheel favored Garner, but the
move backfired when Garner tried it again in the fourth.
Gutierrez's first triple of the season was the game-winning hit.
Normally, Gutierrez is low-key on the field, but he didn't hide his
feelings as after he slid safely into third.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of emotions for me right there,'' Gutierrez
said. ``It's always satisfying when they walk someone to get to you
and then you get the big hit. After he (Garner) did it the first
time, I knew he would do it again. That was very satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio is a perennial All-Star and a dangerous hitter, but it's
not often an opposing team intentionally walks the leadoff hitter
twice in the same game. Biggio had been the recipient of only three
intentional walks before Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biggio's been the guy for them,'' Brewers third baseman Jeff
Cirillo said. ``Garner said we weren't going to let him beat us. He
(Gutierrez) failed the first time, but the second time he got the
big hit. It's a tough call with their lineup. It's pick your poison
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's winning potion would not have been complete without a
dose of Jose Lima, who pitched five-hit ball for eight innings.
Billy Wagner worked the ninth in a non-save situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took advantage of seven walks and got the most out of
their seven hits. They took a 1-0 lead in the first when Gutierrez
singled and scored on a base hit by Moises Alou.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers tied it in the second when Jeromy Burnitz belted a
leadoff double off the center-field wall and scored on John Jaha's
RBI single. Lima retired the first two batters he faced in the
third but allowed the following three to reach, including Cirillo,
who singled home the Brewers' second run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard retired the Astros in order in the third but encountered
trouble in the fourth. Dave Clark and Sean Berry drew back-to-back
walks before Woodard recorded two quick outs. With first open,
Biggio was put on, but then Gutierrez ripped a three-run triple
into the right-center-field gap to give the Astros a 4-2 lead,
which they never surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   The three RBIs matched a career high for Gutierrez and gave him
a career-high 36 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Incaviglia's pinch-hit double off the left-field wall
scored two runs in the eighth. The hit came in Incaviglia's first
plate appearance since the Astros called him up from the minors
this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3472 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAGHDAD-BENETTON-BIZM     08-14 1202
