<HEADER>
A3477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVIS-AD-COLUMN-475&AMP;A     08-14 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-AD-COLUMN-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVIS TRIES A DIFFERENT KIND OF AD CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its quest to remain hip with America's youth, Levi Strauss &AMP;
Co. is introducing a campaign infused with an unconventional,
streetwise attitude for its Silver Tab line of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using typical models to showcase the clothing, the
Silver Tab campaign features colorful, illustrated images of
teen-agers hanging out, displaying their individuality and
self-expression by, of course, wearing Silver Tab clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy was to take fashion ads from the catwalk to the
sidewalk and to be part of street culture,'' said Lorraine Ketch,
managing partner and account planning director at TBWA Chiat/Day in
San Francisco, Levi Strauss' agency. In doing so, Ms. Ketch said,
the illustrative art is ``the only style we felt that would allow
us to become part of the scene'' to attract the younger audience.
</P>
<P>
   To reach its target consumers, 15- to 25-year-olds, TBWA
Chiat/Day sent out employees to build a network of contacts
familiar with the urban scene, including club-hoppers, stylists,
photographers and disk jockeys. The agency kept a scrapbook of
Polaroid pictures of different people and looks and separated them
into seven ``tribes'' that are defined by the music they like,
including the repetitive synthetic music known as electronica;
hip-hop and rap, and retro soul, music from the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to speak to the tribes in their language, have some
fun and make Silver Tab part of the scene without being overt or
contrived,'' Ms. Ketch said. ``You've seen it a million times,
fashion advertising dominated by perfect models with serious, aloof
attitudes and empty messages that are not inspirational images to
these groups. In fact, they have nothing whatsoever in common with
the people wearing them on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ketch added: ``This audience hates marketing that's in your
face. It eyeballs it a mile away, chews it up and spits it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The print and outdoor campaign for the brand, with billings
estimated at $10 million, is the fourth for Levi Strauss from TBWA
Chiat/Day, part of the TBWA Chiat/Day International unit of Omnicom
Group. The new campaign is not the first time Levi Strauss has used
illustrative art rather than photographs. In 1991 and 1992,
illustrations were the centerpiece of its Levi's Jeans for Women
campaign, which was created by its previous longtime agency, Foote,
Cone &AMP; Belding in San Francisco, part of True North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The Silver Tab advertisements, which were designed by Graham
Rounthwaite, a graphic illustrator in London, blend ethnicities and
blur racial definitions with muted skin tones and exotic hair
colors, including aqua blue, lilac and orange.
</P>
<P>
   Kendra Kallan, senior advertising manager for Silver Tab in San
Francisco, said the campaign ``uses style to bring kids together on
their turf,'' adding, ``It's a virtual melting pot of cultures and
races linked by similar interests and diversity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One ad, which is meant to appeal to the hip-hop and rap culture,
features the the statement ``It's bangin' son,'' which translates
into ``cool'' for baby boomers. Teen-agers are featured clad in
Silver Tab clothing including baggy pants, hip huggers and tiny
tops, with accessories as varied as chunky gold jewelry, nose
rings, beepers, knapsacks, baseball caps and tattoos. A second ad,
meant to appeal to the retro soul tribe, carries the statement
``Outtamyhead.'' Translation: ``Everything is great.'' It features
a woman wearing platform shoes and flared bell-bottom jeans, who
looks as if she just stepped out of ``Soul Train.'' All the ads
carry the Silver Tab logo.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hogan, director for consumer marketing at Levi Strauss,
said: ``People are able to project themselves into these settings
and relate to these characters more than they can relate to a
supermodel. It's a unique and different approach in a category that
has a lot of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss is being squeezed from all sides. The company has
been losing market share as fickle young consumers abandon the
brand in favor of higher-priced designer brands sold by Calvin
Klein, Diesel, Tommy Hilfiger USA, Polo Ralph Lauren and Versace,
and lower-priced brands like Canyon River Blues sold by Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co. and Arizona sold by the J.C. Penney Co.. And small,
fashion-focused companies like JNCO, Fubu and Kik Wear have proved
more adept at introducing the styles now favored by teen-agers,
like baggy, wide-legged jeans.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign comes during the annual push in the jeans market as
marketers gear up for the back-to-school shopping season. Several
Levi Strauss competitors recently introduced new campaigns,
including Diesel and the Kmart Corp., which is promoting its Route
66 private-label jeans.
</P>
<P>
   The Levi Strauss campaign, which will run through the end of the
year, will begin next month on billboards, buildings, buses and bus
shelters and in subway stations in 10 cities including Atlanta,
Boston, Chicago, Los Angeles, New York and San Francisco.
Advertisements will also appear in music magazines like Rolling
Stone, Spin and Vibe, alternative magazines like Blaze, Bikini,
Interview and Paper, and fashion magazines like Elle, Jane,
Seventeen and Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kallan said that the Levi Strauss brand ``is thriving on the
unexpected in its advertising this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Silver Tab urban art campaign, we continue to
communicate with our consumers in a way that's real and relevant to
their life style,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan said the campaign ``hopefully says to kids that we're
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We really understand them,'' he said, ``but we are not trying
too hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
