<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. DEFEATS K.C.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a long, long time in coming, but Carlos Hermosillo -- the
Mexican goalscorer whose juices appeared to have dried up --
finally found the net Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   And, as so many surrounding the Los Angeles Galaxy had
predicted, it led to an onslaught of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo, goalless in his first 10 Major League Soccer
matches, scored a pair -- and nearly netted a third -- as the
Galaxy claimed its postseason berth and broke the league's seasonal
scoring record with a 3-0 romp over the Kansas City Wizards before
10,291 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a magic stone -- a good-luck gift presented Wednesday
by the Galaxians, L.A.'s supporters' group -- Hermosillo scored off
scrambles in the Wizards' box in the 76th and 78th minutes, giving
L.A. (19-6, 55 points) 71 goals this season, one better than D.C.'s
record total set last year.
</P>
<P>
   After his first, Hermosillo saluted the Galaxians, then put his
right forefinger to his lips, an effort to shush his critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even in my dreams have I gone so long without a goal,'' he
said afterward, garbed in a Galaxian T-shirt. ``These two ease the
tension. When you have a lot of opportunities through the season, I
started to doubt myself at times. But I was able to come through.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobi Jones also had a goal, his 13th of the season, and a Robin
Fraser-led L.A. defense limited the Wizards (10-13, 26) to four
shots, just one of them on goal.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to give the Galaxy a playoff spot that had never
been in doubt, complete their season sweep of Kansas City, give
Kevin Hartman (who had to make only one save) his fourth shutout
and third against the Wizards, and boost L.A.'s winning streak to
three games after dropping four of the previous five.
</P>
<P>
   With the other piece of news L.A. received -- that Ecuadoran
midfielder Wellington Sanchez, sold July 24 to Mexico's Morelia,
would remain with the Galaxy through the end of the MLS campaign --
it made for a mighty fine Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano wasn't overly pleased with
his squad's effort, unhappy with how his forwards dealt with the
Wizards' man-to-man marking in the back. That, along with the
Galaxy defense's performance, led to a battle contested primarily
in midfield and lacking excitement until Hermosillo took charge
late.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one shot on target in the first half, Jones'
goal, off the best piece of work all night. All credit goes to
Martin Machon, who sent with the outside of his left foot a 50-yard
pass from deep in L.A. territory, finding space behind the Kansas
City back line. Jones turned on the afterburners, leaving three
Wizards' defenders in his dust, and picked up the ball at the edge
of the box. He touched it once, then fired to goalkeeper Mike
Ammann's left, inside the right post.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. had several chances in the second half -- the best a Welton
header cleared off the goal line in the 51st minute -- but nothing
fell until Welton beat Scott Uderitz on the left wing, then sent a
roller to Hermosillo at the near post.
</P>
<P>
   The big Mexican tried to turn to his left, then cut back the
other way, swiping the ball past Ammann.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a minute later, he got his second, blasting
home a rebound after Sean Bowers cleared a Welton shot off the
line.
</P>
<P>
   The goals may have been more important than the win, especially
if it sends Hermosillo -- who scored a record 275 goals in Mexican
League play and another 36 for Mexico's national team -- on a tear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's happy to get that off his mind,'' said Zambrano.
``Anytime a scorer goes that long without scoring, it's very tough
on him. For him to get those two goals, that should ease a lot on
his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hermosillo: ``This is a new start of the season for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, 24, didn't see any action Thursday, but his return to
the the Galaxy -- after what General Manager Danny Villanueva
called a ``financial glitch'' -- provides the team advanced
midfield depth heading into the final stretch of the regular season
and playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The money problem apparently surfaced in Morelia, although
Villanueva said he wasn't sure about the details. Sanchez, who
hadn't left for Mexico, won't join the club until the MLS season is
over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
