<HEADLINE>
MOON CAUSES NO WAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ Warren Moon's first practice after ending his
25-day holdout was more pomp than circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of more than 2,000 fans lined the fences around the
practice fields at the Seahawks' training camp Thursday, and most
were there to see the return of the team's starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Moon, however, won't reclaim that position until Monday _ after
Jon Kitna has started Saturday night's preseason game against the
San Francisco 49ers in Vancouver, B.C., and the team has returned
to its regular training facility in Kirkland.
</P>
<P>
   What the fans saw in the final practice at Cheney was Moon
taking just four snaps with the No. 3 offense. He handed off twice
to Michael Black, a rookie free agent from Washington State, and
completed two short passes to a couple of rookie free-agent
receivers _ Brian Finneran and Chris Jackson, another ex-Cougar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy. I didn't have to do too much,'' said Moon, who
will not play against the 49ers. ``I only got a few reps in each of
the periods, but it was good to get under the center again and at
least take a snap, make a read and throw a pass and complete it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon's return went more smoothly than might have been
anticipated _ for him; for Kitna, who has played well in Moon's
absence; and for their teammates, who have gained confidence in
Kitna because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation for anybody,'' Moon said. ``But I think
(Kitna) knew the situation before it happened, and I'm sure he knew
it was going to be resolved at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jon just wanted to take advantage of the work he was
getting, and the work he was getting really paid off for him,''
Moon said. ``He's doing a really good job right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon could be compensated handsomely if he can lead the Seahawks
to their first playoff berth since 1988. As part of the incentives
attached to the two-year, $4.97 million contract he agreed to
Wednesday and is expected to sign Friday, Moon will receive $75,000
for each game he starts during the regular season, another $150,000
if the Seahawks win 10 games and $250,000 if they make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If it all happens, Moon will pocket an extra $1.6 million if he
is still on the roster in March.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kitna, he figured Moon would return sooner or later and
said he actually is relieved it finally happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as Warren ran out on that field (Wednesday), it was
like a burden being lifted off my shoulders,'' the third-year
quarterback from Central Washington University said. ``Because now
I didn't have to answer the question anymore. I just like things to
be clear-cut. I don't like things to be cloudy. I want to know my
role.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get him wrong, Kitna wants to be the starter. But he also
realizes his time is coming, while Moon's time is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see him out there. It will be exciting for him,''
Kitna said. ``With the team we have this year, that's how they put
it together, with the idea Warren would be in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurt feelings? Hardly. Kitna was more concerned Thursday because
it was his fourth wedding anniversary and his wife, Jennifer, was
in Bothell while he was in Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great opportunity for me to show what I could do. It
was something I didn't expect,'' Kitna said of being No. 1 for a
couple of weeks. ``It's good for me. It's good for the
organization. It makes us a stronger team.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, this remains Moon's team. He was welcomed back by being
called out at the end of pre-practice stretching to lead the
traditional jumping jacks to a chorus of hoots from the other
players. He then stayed after practice for more than an hour to
sign autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren is the leader of our offense,'' coach Dennis Erickson
said. ``He held out, now he's back and our players are excited
about having him back. It's not that he has to apologize or worry
about being accepted. He was accepted as soon as he walked onto the
field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
