<HEADLINE>
NBA PLAYERS WITHDRAW CHARGE OF UNFAIR LABOR PRACTICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Faced with the failure of their litigation
initiative, National Basketball Association players withdrew their
unfair labor practice charge Thursday and prepared to fight the
league's lockout on the arbitration front.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the players union said they decided to drop their
effort through the National Labor Relations Board because they were
not going to get action quickly enough, but it was apparent that
the board's New York office had concluded there was no merit, at
least not now, in the union's charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a decision that we were not going to get anything to
happen soon enough to suit ourselves,'' Jeffrey Kessler, one of the
union lawyers, said, explaining the union's decision. ``The NLRB
was always considered a long shot, and we concluded it wasn't worth
the effort or our resources to pursue it.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Granik, the league's deputy commissioner and chief
negotiator, noted that when the union announced that it had filed
an unfair labor practice charge last month, it did not indicate
that the action was not important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's now confirmed that we have a perfectly lawful
lockout,'' Granik said, adding: ``We're not jumping up and down
because this doesn't get a deal. We'll only get a deal when we sit
down and negotiate some more.''
</P>
<P>
   In filing the charge, the union contended that the lockout was
illegal because the players were not working and had nothing to be
locked out from. Furthermore, the union said, by placing a freeze
on the signing of free agents, the league was unilaterally changing
working conditions when the two sides had not bargained to impasse.
</P>
<P>
   The union wanted the board to seek an injunction in federal
court that would serve to end the lockout, just as a
board-generated injunction sent the baseball players back to work
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances in the two disputes, however, were different. The
board acted on behalf of the baseball players because it felt the
owners had made unilateral changes in the method of negotiating
individual contracts, centralizing signings in the Player Relations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA case, the owners are not changing anything
unilaterally but rather suspending the period in which free agents
can be signed. So the board was not prepared to seek an injunction
or even issue a complaint against the league. Union lawyers
presumably learned of that position and decided to withdraw the
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't affect the players' determination,'' Kessler said.
``Now we're focused on the Feerick arbitration about player
contracts. Our position hasn't changed at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler referred to John D. Feerick, the arbitrator, and the
hearing he has scheduled for Aug. 24 on the union's grievance
contending that players with guaranteed contracts should have to be
paid regardless of the lockout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
