<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT MARLINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers had one last chance to redeem
themselves against the worst team in the National League before
taking on the best.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of their series opener against the mighty Atlanta
Braves, the Dodgers finally defeated the lowly Florida Marlins 5-4
in front of 34,804 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After back-to-back demoralizing losses, the struggling Dodgers
finally looked like a team worthy of your playoff consideration.
Granted it was against the Marlins, who have not swept a season
series all year. But at this point the Dodgers aren't good enough
to be picky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, it's a win,'' said weary Dodgers manager Glenn
Hoffman. ``It wasn't easy, but with what's been happening and what
is coming up, it was something we really needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which moved the Dodgers within five games of idle
Chicago for the wild-card spot, came after the news that struggling
left-fielder Bobby Bonilla will be benched until further notice.
Not only was Bonilla missing, but so were the boos that have been
following him around the entire homestand.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, fans had a chance to cheer. Rookie third baseman
Adrian Beltre blew the game open with a fourth-inning, two-run
homer. Starter Brian Bohanon (6-7), the only Dodgers starter not to
struggle recently, allowed just two runs in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bohanon pitched well,'' Marlins' manager Jim Leyland said.
``He's the perfect example of a lefty who moves the ball around and
changes speeds. He kept us off balance all night. He had a great
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre also helped Bohanon by starting two double plays after
the Marlins got runners on to open the second and eighth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon then gave way to closer Jeff Shaw, who allowed two hits
in the ninth but held on to record his 35th save and 12th as a
Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good all night and could have pitched the ninth,'' said
Bohanon, who had allowed just five earned runs in his last five
starts. ``But Jeff hadn't pitched in four days and he needed to get
some work.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Dodgers, the only downside came in the fifth when Raul
Mondesi fouled a pitch off his left shin and was forced to leave a
half inning later. Mondesi, who went 0 for 3 and is 3 for 19 on the
homestand, was taken to Centinela Hospital Medical Center in
Inglewood for precautionary X-rays. They were negative and he is
listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   The news on Gary Sheffield was much better. After suffering his
first slump since joining the Dodgers in mid-May, Sheffield snapped
an 0-for-18 slide with an eighth-inning single and then recorded
his 18th stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   The stolen base might have been as important as the single. The
Dodgers played passively during the previous eight games when they
went 2-6 against sub-.500 opponents. In the first inning, Eric
Young opened with a single and No.2 hitter Mark Grudzielanek
immediately tried to move him over with a hit-and run play.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work, but the Dodgers kept the pressure on when Young
stole his 35th base of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike first two games of the series, the Dodgers were the
aggressors from the outset. They scored three runs in the second
off Marlins' rookie right-hander Brian Meadows (9-9).
</P>
<P>
   The first sign the inning would be a little different was the
infield single to short by slow-footed Eric Karros. After a base
hit by Matt Luke put runners at first and second, Karros scored on
a sharp single to left by Charles Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With Beltre at the plate, Luke scored on a wild pitch. Beltre
then walked and moved to second on a sacrifice by Bohanon. Young,
who had four hits and two two-out RBI Wednesday night, did it
again, singling to left to score Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, who only has shown glimpses of his projected talent,
will not be affected much by the benching of Bonilla. Beltre might
be occasionally be replaced by Bonilla at third, but the job is
still his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking for a good pitch,'' Beltre said of his home
run. ``It was a changeup and I went after it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
