<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES MIGHT PLAY YOUNG RUNNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A funny thing happened this week when freshmen
reported for early football drills at the University of Washington.
The Huskies introduced five rookie running backs and _ get this _
hinted some of them might play this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until Don James hears about this. He's off in South Bend,
Ind., getting inducted into the College Football Hall of Fame this
weekend. The ex-Husky coach's career was built partly on the idea
that once you signed kids to letters of intent, usually you had no
reason to know their names until they were sometime past the legal
drinking age.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never even talked about it,'' UW coach Jim Lambright said
with a laugh. ``It was, `You guys are going to be redshirted, let's
get on to the guys who are going to play.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the last vestige of James' days as UW coach was the Pac-10
probation that rocked the program in 1993. Five years later, as a
result of two recruiting classes trimmed to 15 scholarships
allowed, Lambright's program still chafes from the manacles:
Fourth-year juniors and fifth-year seniors from the 1994 and '95
recruiting classes number only 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in such a huge need for running backs,'' Lambright said.
``This is exactly what we need, a big line of running backs.''
</P>
<P>
   If junior Maurice Shaw returns healthy from spring back surgery,
he is the likely incumbent to the Napoleon Kaufman-Corey
Dillon-Rashaan Shehee succession of recent years. Junior Jason
Harris hasn't shown he can stay healthy, and redshirt freshman
Jabari Johnson is unproven as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ergo, the welcome mat for five guys, all of whom are 18. The
thinking entering camp is that the two with the best chance of
pushing for significant playing time are Willie Hurst and Jelani
Harrison. But Thursday, Lambright was singing the praises of
6-foot-1, 200-pound Braxton Cleman.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst and Harrison are from south-central Los Angeles. Cleman is
from the harsh streets of Oroville, where he played Class B-11
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about an athlete from a small school, and you wonder
how he's going to fit in,'' Lambright said. ``Boy, he's really
smooth. He's really doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurst is 5-10 and 200 pounds and was described earlier this year
by UW recruiting coordinator Dick Baird as ``a linebacker's
nightmare.'' One Pac-10 coach questioned whether Hurst has the
speed to get to the perimeter consistently, but he conceded Hurst
is a serious inside runner.
</P>
<P>
   Speed is unquestioned with Harrison, a sprinter who says he ran
the 100 meters in 10.4 in track this year after posting a 10.53 as
a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison broke a lot of hearts in Pullman last winter, including
Washington State coach Mike Price's, when he pulled out of a
commitment to the Cougars to sign with Washington. Price, who
already had snagged JC catch Kevin Brown, had hoped he could 1-2
the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I committed to them in January before I took my trip here,''
Harrison said. ``The environment ... there's really nothing out
there. I think I could maintain here better than out there. I'm
from the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurst picked Washington over Arizona and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches stayed true to me,'' Hurst said. ``The Oregon
coaches, they tried to, like, hide people they were recruiting.
Arizona, they tried to paint me this perfect picture of their
place, and it was totally different once I took my trip. They told
me the team acted a certain way, and when I got there, they were
actually totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison hopes to run track here once he establishes his
football, but Hurst likely won't swing to his second sport. Hurst
was the starting point guard on a Dominguez High basketball team
that spent last season in the nation's top 25, led by USC's touted
football recruit, 6-4 Jason Thomas, and 6-8 Kentucky basketball
signee Tayshaun Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, Hurst and Clemans are joined by two other candidates:
5-11, 195-pound Matthias Wilson of Ferndale, who broke the state
high school season rushing record with 2,648 yards; and 5-10,
185-pound Andrae Perry of Fontana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   All of them are bucking some significant history. There isn't a
lot of tradition of Husky tailbacks bursting out as true freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman, the UW career rushing leader, had 307 yards for the
1991 national champions, playing behind Beno Bryant and Jay Barry.
Greg Lewis, No. 3 on the career list, was fifth among Husky rushers
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Jacque Robinson was MVP of the 1982 Rose Bowl with 142 yards,
but he didn't start the game, or any other in his freshman year.
Joe Steele, No. 2 behind Kaufman on the Husky career list, had 421
yards in 1976, third on a 5-6 team.
</P>
<P>
   Among Kaufman, Lewis, Robinson and Steele, there were but three
starts as freshmen, all due to injury. Without knowing any of this,
Harrison and Hurst are properly deferential.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to come in and compete,'' Hurst says. ``The
opportunity is there. We can't just say right off the bat we're
going to start. That'd be a bald-faced lie. Once the vets come in,
we'll go from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 0128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
