<HEADLINE>
SURPRISE: MARINER STAFF ERA APPROACHING RESPECTABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Mariner pitching coach Stan Williams laughed Thursday
when recalling his first meeting with the M's pitching staff. He
had told them they could finish the season with a composite earned
run average under four runs a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must have thought I was an alien,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners were the laughingstock among major league pitching
staffs, especially the bullpen, which regularly blew leads and cost
former pitching coach Nardi Contreras his job. But since May 1, the
staff ERA is 4.48, slightly above average in the offensive-minded
American League.
</P>
<P>
   The slow and meticulous climb to respectability has reached the
point where bad performances, like those Tuesday night and
Wednesday afternoon in Toronto, are considered a glitch instead of
a trend. Seventh-inning collapses in both games led to back-to-back
losses.
</P>
<P>
   As the M's continue their nine-game road trip Friday night at
Comiskey Park against the Chicago White Sox, the team ERA is 4.76 _
nearly two runs a game lower than when Williams took over April 13.
It's the eighth-lowest in the 14-team AL.
</P>
<P>
   ``ERA-wise, we are where we thought this staff would be when the
season started,'' manager Lou Piniella said Thursday. ``We didn't
think we would be in the top three, but figured we would be
respectable.''
</P>
<P>
   While a sub-4.00 ERA might appear unreachable with only 43 games
left, Williams believes it can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been improvement,'' he said, ``but there still is
room for improvement. Everyone has brought their ERAs down a couple
of notches and can go even lower. I'm still planning to get under
4.00.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons for the ERA decline. The biggest
factor, Piniella and Williams say, is better control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been throwing more strikes, cutting down on our
walks,'' Piniella said. ``(Williams) has done a good job of getting
the pitchers to believe in themselves and trust their ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariner pitchers issued 111 walks in 2381/3 innings during
April, when they had an AL-worst 5.59 ERA, and have improved every
month since _ 93 walks in 2451/3 innings in May (4.92 ERA); 74 in
2411/3 innings in June (4.92 ERA); 72 in 231 innings in July (3.86
ERA) and 30 in 88 innings in August (3.99 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has climbed from 14th in walks allowed to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate walks,'' Williams said. ``I had a lot of them early in
my career, and I knew that if I could improve my control, so could
they.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is more laid back than Contreras, and the approach has
been a key factor in the turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it helps to have a goofy pitching coach,'' Williams
said. ``I like to have fun and am a little off-the-wall for a
purpose. The more relaxed I can get these guys, the better job
they're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto debacles notwithstanding, there has been noticeable
improvement in Seattle's overall pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big mystery,'' said reliever Mike Timlin, who leads
the staff with a 2.87 ERA and has settled into the closer role.
``Stan has gotten everyone to relax, go at the hitters and throw
strikes. It's pretty simple, really. As the old `KISS' theory goes,
keep it simple, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Throw strikes and let the hitters put the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   It took some pitchers longer than others to catch on:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Heathcliff Slocumb was among the most undependable
pitchers on the staff. But in his past 20 appearances, the
right-handed setup reliever has a 2.16 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Until a giving up a two-run double and grand slam against
Toronto on Wednesday, left-handed reliever Greg McCarthy provided
the type of specialty relief Tony Fossas didn't, holding
left-handed hitters to a .053 (1-for-19) batting average.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Long reliever Bob Wells, a right-hander, has been solid
while limiting right-handers to a .168 (17-for-101) average.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Timlin has eight saves in nine save opportunities since
the All-Star Game and a 2.05 ERA in his past 45 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Bobby Ayala is still extremely inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, there has been an attitude change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a more relaxed atmosphere and not as much
negativity,'' Slocumb said. ``We might say negative publicity
doesn't bother us, but it does. Every time somebody said something
about us, it was something bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The negative vibes rippling through the Mariner clubhouse have
subsided, replaced by confidence and competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every manager wants to see the pitchers competing to get the
ball, and the best way to get the ball is to get people out,''
Piniella said. ``The best situation is having pitchers competing
for roles and that's what we have now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all starts with confidence and you hope it continues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 0128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
