<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUZZ BUILDING FOR LONGACRES MILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Wash. _ The defending champion of the Northwest's
biggest horse race is a temperamental fellow. Kid Katabatic has
been known to pitch a fit, kick and bite according to his
high-strung desire.
</P>
<P>
   So it is best to admire the talented thoroughbred from a few
feet away at his barn stall at Emerald Down.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the stall, the dark-eyed Kid just flicks his strong neck
and gives a sideways glance at the stranger admiring him. It's like
a warning, as if the Kid is daring you to go ahead and treat him
like some ordinary barnyard animal.
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics) ``I'm the Longacres winner,'' (end italics) the
5-year-old Kid Katabatic seems to sneer. (begin italics) ``That's
who you're looking at.'' (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   The big dude, about 16 hands high, has made his unspoken, equine
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always looking to get into something,'' said Shauna Van
Ootsdam, one of Kid Katabatic's owners and his loyal trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is to get him to the race in one piece. He's funny
that way. He sees other horses moving through the barn and he gets
tense and freezes up. It's just his way of saying he wants to be
working, too. But he has matured so much,'' Van Ootsdam said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Kid Katabatic won the 62nd running of the Grade III
Longacres Mile _ the state's most historic horse race and also its
biggest.
</P>
<P>
   The Kid took on the favored shipper from California _ Hesabull,
who went off at 1-6 odds. Kid Katabatic won by two full lengths,
setting a course record.
</P>
<P>
   Now Van Ootsdam would like her prize to do it again. On Aug. 23,
the Kid will get his chance to defend his title.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a great accomplishment for Kid Katabatic _ a horse
who possesses all the natural killer instinct of a winner.
</P>
<P>
   It also would be a great story for Emerald Downs, which would
most appreciate a local equine hero to help promote the excitement
and colorful atmosphere of a day at the races. With a guaranteed
purse of $200,000, the Longacres Mile is the only graded stakes
race run in the state, which means it is the single-most important
foothold Washington has into the national racing scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the premiere race in the state,'' said trainer Terri
Forster, whose colt, You've Got Action, is another Mile favorite.
``Certainly, if you figure there are 1,200 to 1,500 horses being
trained here and the field is somewhere between six and 12 horses
and yours is one of them, then you're one of the elite horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Elite for Washington is not necessarily elite by national
standards.
</P>
<P>
   While New York is running its history-rich and purses-fat meet
at Saratoga this August, and as the Southern California circuit
keeps up its daily dose of high-stakes racing, Emerald Downs is
diligently trying to restore thoroughbred racing to the health and
well-being it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear the Auburn track still feels the effects of
Longacres' closure and the four years of dark days that followed.
The thoroughbred ranks were depleted during that time. Breeders got
out of the business. The number and quality of Washington horses
dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   But in its third season now, Emerald Downs is seeing a comeback.
The track's betting handle has increased ever since the state voted
to allow simulcasting. And with increased handles, purses have
increased as much as 47 percent this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more money that goes to the horses, the better the horses
you attract,'' Forster said, explaining the simple cycle on which
the entire industry depends.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why there is a certain buzz around the barns at Emerald
Downs this week. Elite horses like Kid Katabatic and You've Got
Action are being prepared for the big day _ Mile day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They build the race up quite a bit,'' Forster said,
anticipating the news about which horses will be shipped up from
California for the Longacres Mile.
</P>
<P>
   Mud Route, said to be one of the top horses in country right
now, is on the list of potential entries. Also, acclaimed trainer
Bob Baffert might ship Anet, a seven-time winner whose earnings
over the past two seasons exceed $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it tougher to win when the stakes horses from
California come up, especially since we like to see the Northwest
horses do well,'' Forster said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is the only graded stakes race (here), and in order
to keep its status, you need to have those better horses shipped
in. It's the way to improve the racing,'' Forster said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a wild-eyed horse named Kid Katabatic is making
things interesting in his barn, kicking and causing a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   And two barns over, You've Got Action seems to be enjoying his
daily walks, workouts, ice packs and the special liniments rubbed
into his delicate legs. The gentle but all-business-on-the-track
horse can be found standing in a bed of soft straw, getting the
royal treatment and waiting for the big day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really like any athlete,'' Forster said. ``They are
very well pampered.''
</P>
<P>
   And very well worth the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
