<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TWINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX HAVE LAST WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They hit plenty. Ran a little, too.
</P>
<P>
   But pitching? Not even an honorable mention.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox banged out their 70th win of the season Thursday
night, an 8-7 endurance test against the Twins at Fenway Park, with
the help of 16 hits, a couple of defensive gems, and even _ brace
yourself down there on the beach on Block Island _ a couple of
timely stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   For a team in pursuit of a wild-card bid, it doesn't get much
wilder than Thursday night at the Fens, where the clubs combined
for 28 hits, 11 pitchers, and 10 extra-base hits, including Nomar
Garciaparra's game-winning double in the seventh inning that
brought Mo Vaughn lumbering around with the 15th and final run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll blow some teams out,'' said Sox catcher Scott Hatteberg,
who contributed three hits to the assault and flashed the signals
for no fewer than a half-dozen hurlers. ``And we'll be in some
tight games, too. Winning the tight ones like this is key during
the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Thursday night's game appeared to be a Sox blowout in
the making. A three-run fourth inning, spiced by Garciaparra's
line-drive homer into the screen and a Darren Bragg squeeze bunt
that brought in Mike Stanley soon after a stolen base, put the Sox
in command, 4-0. A little more than an hour had passed in what
would become a 3-hour 26-minute crawl before a crowd of 32,801.
</P>
<P>
   The truth was, the game had just begun. The Twins halved the
lead in the fifth after starter Pedro Martinez opened the inning by
fanning Todd Walker and getting Terry Steinbach on a fly to right.
Back-to-back singles by David Ortiz and Pat Meares, followed by an
Otis Nixon walk, set the stage for Brent Gates to lash a two-run
single to center. Sox, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struggled into the seventh and finally staggered to the
showers, his final line bloated: 6 1/3 innings, 10 hits, 6 runs,
all earned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel in a groove,'' said Martinez after logging his
first no-decision since May 14. ``I didn't feel I had it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg felt Martinez was only slightly off his game, missing
marginally with some good pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``But sometimes it's not there,'' said Hatteberg. ``It's never a
velocity thing with Pedro. His velocity is always there. And he's
such a finesse pitcher, he can get by without his best stuff. But
sometimes ... sometimes it's just not as easy as riding a bike.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox reasserted themselves in their half of the fifth, adding
three runs on four hits _ including doubles by John Valentin and
Vaughn and singles by Garciaparra and Stanley. Just before
Stanley's shot to left, Garciaparra moved to second on the Sox'
second stolen base of the evening (call Tommy Harper and give him
the news). When Garciaparra crossed the plate, the Sox were in
front by five runs, 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   But the Twins kept bashing, too. They trimmed the lead by a pair
in the sixth when Ortiz delivered a two-run double, then tied it in
the seventh when they chased Martinez. A Gates double followed by a
Paul Molitor single sent Martinez to the showers. After Greg
Swindell gave up an infield single, Dennis Eckersley was rocked for
a Marty Cordova two-run double. It was tied, 7-7, and the Eck
eventually picked up the win despite getting torched. That's
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn and Garciaparra, a combined 6 for 9 on the night with
three doubles, a homer, and four RBIs, rattled Travis Miller for
the winning run in the seventh. Vaughn launched a leadoff double to
center, and Garciaparra matched it, drilling a shot high off the
Wall in left-center. It was the star shortstop's 95th RBI of the
year, leaving him only three shy of his 1997 total.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gordon made it stand up with a perfect ninth for his 33d
save.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't think so, with (Brad) Radke and Martinez
pitching,'' said Sox manager Jimy Williams, alluding to how wide
open the night became despite the presence of the two aces. ``But
that's the nature of the sport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
