<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL PALM, 47, INNOVATOR IN METHOD OF REINSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Colo., Pa., Conn.)  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael D. Palm, a former English teacher who made a fortune in
reinsurance _ the business of sharing the risk of insurance
companies _ and then contributed millions to benefit the arts, gay
rights and AIDS treatment, died Aug. 7 at his home in Telluride,
Colo. He was 47 and also had homes in New York City and St. Croix
in the Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was heart failure caused by complications
from AIDS, according to his sister, Melissa Jamula of Reading, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Steven Gluckstern, a former colleague at an
English-language school in Tehran, Iran, Palm founded Center Re, a
Bermuda reinsurance company, in 1988. Centre Re specialized in a
then relatively little-used kind of coverage that specifically
limited the losses the reinsurer could suffer and rewarded
customers with rebates on premiums for keeping claims down.
</P>
<P>
   The approach, known as finite risk and now often used as a tool
in both reinsurance and primary insurance, lowered the cost of
protection for customers and eliminated the rare, but very real,
possibility of a reinsurance company's being wiped out by an
avalanche of claims.
</P>
<P>
   While the method Palm helped popularize can be profitable, it is
not a factor in most reinsurance, partly because calculating limits
of coverage and rebate levels is difficult and because an
overweening goal of many primary insurers is virtually unlimited
protection against huge losses. Also, many reinsurers prefer the
higher premiums that come their way in exchange for fuller
protection.
</P>
<P>
   One of the initial backers of Centre Re, now called Centre
Solutions, was the Zurich Insurance Group. The Zurich group bought
the entire company in 1993 and kept the founders as the chief
executives. Palm retired as vice chairman at the turn of the year,
saying he wanted to devote himself to philanthropy and more reading
and thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Palm, whose father was a policeman and later a city councilman
in Reading, graduated from Yale University and earned a master's
degree from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   After working together in Tehran, Palm and Gluckstern initially
followed different paths in finance. But they were reunited when
Gluckstern was hired by Warren Buffett to run a reinsurance unit of
Berkshire Hathaway and Gluckstern invited Palm to join him. Buffet
did not share their enthusiasm for finite risk, so the two friends
struck out on their own. Their creation now has assets of more than
$9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Palm set up the Michael Palm Foundation in New York in 1995 with
an endowment of $10 million. The next year, the foundation gave
$2.5 million to the Gay Men's Health Crisis, the nation's largest
provider of AIDS services, to help build a $12 million headquarters
in New York. The foundation also pledged $1 million each to the Gay
and Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation and the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest gay political organization. It
pledged $1 million to Yale the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Palm, who kept two pianos _ a Baldwin and an antique Steinway _
in his penthouse apartment overlooking Lincoln Center and loved to
romp through classical pieces and popular songs from the 1930s and
1940s, also contributed to the Metropolitan Opera and Carnegie Hall
as well as the opera in Telluride.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his sister, Palm is survived by his mother, Irma,
of Reading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
