<HEADLINE>
MINIMALIST RITCHIE IS THE MOST
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM KEOWN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
For those of you who like your symbolism delivered with the
delicacy and precision of a sledgehammer, we present the issue of
Jon Ritchie's wardrobe.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Metaphorically freeing himself of worldly concerns, Ritchie
arrived at his first NFL training camp with only the clothes on his
back _ a T-shirt, khaki carpenter's pants and a pair of leather
sandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I normally try to keep my mind free for other things,''
Ritchie says.
</P>
<P>
   His planned asceticism turned into a biblical dilemma after
roughly two weeks, however. Word percolated through Napa's seamy
underside that Ritchie's clothes would be rendered unwearable by
some of the Raiders' veterans if they didn't see a change.
</P>
<P>
   One man's asceticism, apparently, is another man's lack of
hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rumors abounded,'' Ritchie says. ``Some of the veterans were
going to take action, and that first outfit is very dear to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie splurged on another pair of carpenter's pants (olive
this time) and another T-shirt. Monastic, sure, but with just
enough options to keep them guessing.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie's mind, we are to assume, remains mostly uncorrupted by
the exponential increase in material possessions. There might have
been a minor adjustment, because he says you have to think fast in
order to play fast, and too many choices can slow the process. You
start picking through the closet in the morning and before long
you're standing paralyzed in the buffet line, unable to choose
between white and whole wheat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unique to me _ there's a lot I have to learn,'' he
says. ``I have to pick up the offense and work on technique. I want
to immerse myself in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rookie, your role is to keep your mouth shut. You do what
the coaches tell you, you listen and keep yourself open-minded. You
need to be willing to give of yourself and not start things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie is the Raiders' starting fullback, a statement that
means more than it did a year ago. Before, being the Raiders'
starting fullback was a lot like being in charge of setting up Al
Davis' media interviews: There might be a job there, but the
workload is pretty light.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie delivers every line with the same deadpan, heavy-lidded
demeanor. He plays guitar and saxophone, writes his own music and
lyrics, assiduously avoids combing his hair. He's cool because he
is trying so hard to be the antithesis of cool.
</P>
<P>
   He listens to bands like Creed and Days of the New. He has
always been in awe of Hendrix and Morrison. He has a scraggly Gen-X
beard and his hair sticks up and out in every direction, almost
magically. This hair, much shorter than his days at Stanford, kicks
gravity's sorry butt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some cowlick problems,'' he says, his tone taking on
the staged seriousness of a mock psychiatric evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie was in a band once; he played with The Briefs during his
two years at Michigan. Now he writes songs in his spare time (one
rule: no odes to football, ever).
</P>
<P>
   His most recent composition begins:
</P>
<P>
   (ital) You're so enticing as you smile &QC; 
and muddy me &QC; 
piercing my dark, dirty despair &QC; 
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders _ muddied like few before them _ care only that
Ritchie weighs 250 pounds and moves them fast enough to stay in
front of Napoleon Kaufman. The evolution in the Raiders' offense
makes the fullback a viable pass-catching option; when they opted
against re-upping the Joe Bugel offense _ a system established just
weeks after men began walking upright _ the Raiders sent out a call
for a productive fullback.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone who remembers Tom Rathman swinging out to the right
with half a field in front of him will know what Ritchie is hoping
to see.
</P>
<P>
   Later in his most recent composition, Ritchie sings:
</P>
<P>
   (ital)
</P>
<P>
   I'm stuck in my fantasy &QC; 
I'm lost in my fantasy &QC; 
in gleeful hope and hopeful glee &QC; 
But what's destiny besides a prayer &QC; 
for what can never be? &QC; 
(unital)
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie's bohemianism may make him an unlikely football player,
but his lineage is straight from a B movie. He grew up in a central
Pennsylvania town where every kid's dream was to play football for
Cumberland Valley High School. As Ritchie describes it, ``If, for
genetic reasons, you couldn't play football, then you were forced
to play another sport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Jon's a little different,'' says Raiders running backs
coach Skip Peete. ``But his work ethic is great. He comes from a
part of the country where you're taught to grab your lunch pail and
go to work all day till the work's all done. That's the way he
approaches his job.''
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, Ritchie wouldn't be all that different. There
are thousands just like him walking the streets of the Bay Area,
ducking in and out of used-record shops and coffee houses, coming
to terms with their dark dirty despair.
</P>
<P>
   But in football, which is not the real world, Ritchie is quite a
bit different. That's why he keeps his mouth shut, his mind clear
and his options few. For now, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
