<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NELSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: WITH EYE ON OCTOBER, NELSON WATCH STARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Open the door to the Yankee clubhouse and watch the
premier team in baseball preparing for another game in routine
fashion. Orlando Hernandez is stretching by his locker on the left
side, Paul O'Neill is trying on batting gloves at the far end of
the room and Tino Martinez is swinging new bats in the right
corner. The scene is businesslike and blase.
</P>
<P>
   But take one step to the right after entering and there is a
scene that is unsettling to a team pursuing destiny and greatness.
That is where Jeff Nelson is sitting, hoping that the bulging disk
in his lower back does not plague him when he stands up or bends
over and especially when he throws off a mound Friday for the first
time in almost two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just get up every day and hope the stiffness I feel goes
away,'' Nelson said Thursday. ``I don't think about the possibility
of missing any more of this. It's been tough missing the last two
months. Even if I did come back and feel something, I would try to
hide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is so desperate to return to the Yankees and be an
important part of this magical year that he admitted he might not
disclose the truth about his back injury, which could have been
tough talk or silly talk. If Nelson really intends to be deceitful,
that would be a thornier problem for the Yankees and a poor career
decision by the 31-year-old reliever.
</P>
<P>
   When Nelson was asked about concealing information from the
Yankees, he said: ``Probably, especially if it's going good now. If
I don't feel anything, I'm not going to say anything. If I feel
something and I'm helping, I'm not going to say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It is nearly impossible to find fault with a team that is on
pace to set a major-league record for regular-season victories, a
marvelous team that had Manager Johnny Oates of Texas admitting it
was natural for the Rangers to feel intimidated Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the Yankees peek ahead to the postseason and analyze
how they can be most impenetrable, Nelson must be an influential
part of the equation. The bulging disk was causing pain to shoot
down Nelson's legs, which is why the Yankees have proceeded
cautiously with his rehabilitation and have targeted his return for
Sept. 1, and why they are seriously considering obtaining another
right-hander, like San Diego's Brian Boehringer or Jim Bruske.
</P>
<P>
   Another right-hander would provide insurance, but neither
Boehringer, a former Yankee, nor Bruske, who is pitching at Class
AAA Las Vegas, is Nelson. Although Nelson has a 5-3 record with an
ordinary 4.54 earned run average and has permitted a .291 average
to right-handed batters this season, his sidearm motion and wicked
slider helped him limit right-handers to a .168 mark last season
and to .245 when the Yankees won the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to October. If Joe Torre needs a reliever to retire
Juan Gonzalez or Nomar Garciaparra or Manny Ramirez in the eighth
inning, he had better be able to call on Nelson. Ramiro Mendoza is
valuable and Hernandez might be effective in the setup role, but
Torre needs Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go into postseason play, you have to win right now,''
Torre said. ``There's no such thing as tomorrow. You might find
yourself making changes quicker than in the season. The more
choices you have, the better-armed you are.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cone, David Wells, Andy Pettitte, Hideki Irabu and
Hernandez have given the Yankees such consistency in the rotation
that Nelson joked, ``They're doing so good, they don't miss
anyone.'' But the games seem a lot shorter in October, and the
bullpen is usually busier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything changes once September hits,'' said Nelson, who
will travel to Tampa, Fla., on Sunday and should pitch in
minor-league games within 10 days. ``Our starters have been
outstanding, but things change in the playoffs. It's a different
situation because you're not going to leave your starters in there
as long.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Nelson think he will make it back and be effective?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can come back,'' he said. ``You always have some kind
of twitch, and you always have a sense it's going to come back.
That's the biggest fear. I do feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said: ``If you put yourself in a playoff atmosphere and
you've got a right-handed hitter coming up, there's not anyone in
the world you'd rather have face him than Nellie. He's nasty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
