<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-DAYONE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS OPENS WITH COURSE-RECORD 66 FOR PGA LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Tiger Mountain sits 10 miles south of Sahalee
Country Club, but Thursday there was another Tiger towering above
the trees.
</P>
<P>
   The guy with all the shots and fans, Tiger Woods, found himself
a few floors above the rest of the neighborhood, emerging as the
first-round leader of the 80th PGA Championship. He carded a
4-under-par 66, good for a two-stroke advantage over eight players
and a course record.
</P>
<P>
   His Stripeness never pulled his driver out of the bag. But for
4{ hours, he was everything his legions of admirers have come to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   Overpowering. Magical. Unwavering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a more mature Tiger than you saw last year at this
time,'' said Woods, pursuing his second major and eighth PGA Tour
victory. ``I've got more shots.''
</P>
<P>
   While Woods, the 1997 Masters champion, had his way with the
6,906-yard layout, Sahalee stood up well in its first test against
the tour. Just 20 of the 150 players broke par, including Mark
O'Meara, bidding for a record-tying third major victory this
season.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, one of 11 players who shot 69, bogeyed two of his first
three holes. But the 41-year-old rebounded nicely, making no more
mistakes _ just like he did on his way to victories this year in
the Masters and British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept myself in the ballgame,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sahalee wasn't the Olympic Club, the San Francisco course that
humbled the best during the U.S. Open in June. But it wasn't
Interbay Family Center, either.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the game's biggest names simply crumbled in the face of
100-foot trees and 4-inch rough. Five players shot 80 or higher,
including 1991 PGA champion and former British Open winner John
Daly. Reigning U.S. Open champ Lee Janzen, Open runner-up Payne
Stewart and tour money leader David Duval each fired 76 and entered
the clubhouse 6 over par.
</P>
<P>
   The normally steady Duval mangled the par-4 10th hole. He dumped
shots in a lake and a bunker, and then three-putted for
triple-bogey 7. Two holes later, he found another bunker, hit a
tree and chipped one out after landing a foot from a chain-link
fence, finishing with a double-bogey 6 on the 12th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Duval warned against using the driver on the Redmond
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get away with it for awhile,'' he said, ``but it's
gonna get you in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' club of choice was his putter. Turning in a seven-birdie,
three-bogey round, he dropped six putts from 15 feet or more.
Actually, the club wasn't his; it was O'Meara's backup, borrowed
for several weeks from his good friend.
</P>
<P>
   Woods thought about using his driver just once, on the par-4
seventh hole. The temptation wasn't great enough. He settled on a
2-iron on the 421-yard hole _ and carded a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big donut today,'' Woods said of his driver use.
</P>
<P>
   Golf's prodigy was sluggish at the start, bogeying the first
hole. His tee shot found the rough; his approach missed the green.
</P>
<P>
   Two shots into the second hole, a 507-yard par-5, Woods got
everything going. He was 220 yards from the green when he leaned
into a 3-wood and sent his ball sizzling toward a lake bordering
the right side of the green. He groaned. But it carried over the
water by two feet and rolled 10 feet from the cup. He birdied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole round was probably made on No. 2,'' Woods
said. ``Snuck out with one there.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' card showed a bogey on the sixth hole. Witnesses,
however, saw Woods do something otherworldly there. On the 480-yard
par 4, he put his tee shot into a fairway bunker. He muscled his
next shot 230 yards, over trees and onto a green that wouldn't hold
it, the ball finding a back bunker. But the sheer magic of that
2-iron had eyes hanging out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has an incredible ability to recover,'' playing partner
Nick Price said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely flushed it,'' Woods said, noting that he hit the
shot perfectly. ``It was just one of those things where I hit too
good a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He birdied three of four par-3s, draining a 35-footer on the
last one, the 215-yard 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Even without his driver, Woods was a monster off the tee. On the
18th, he hit a 3-wood shot 305 yards to the middle of the fairway,
with the crowd roar lasting longer than the air time. Price and
Jeff Sluman were more than 50 yards back on their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my length is definitely a huge advantage on this golf
course because I'm able to hit 2-irons and 3-woods where guys are
sometimes having to hit drivers,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   His 66 was one better than Sahalee's course record, set 14 years
ago by Jack Nicklaus in a charity exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected him to play well,'' O'Meara said. ``This is a good
course for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Two shots back were Billy Andrade, Paul Azinger, Glen Day, Bob
Estes, Bill Glasson, Scott Gump, Frank Lickliter and Shigeki
Maruyama. Not exactly a threatening group. Collectively, they have
one major victory among them, Azinger's PGA Championship in 1993,
and he hasn't won since, with health setbacks getting in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade and Day each birdied their first four holes, but
couldn't maintain the perfect pace. Andrade, the last alternate
added to the field, fell back with a double bogey on the sixth
hole.
</P>
<P>
   Day, still looking for his first tour victory, was 5-under
through 14 holes _ the only golfer to go that low _ but he
double-bogeyed the 15th and bogeyed the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves Woods, pining for a second major, in a choice
position. Still, Woods has never won a tournament after leading
following the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to give myself a chance,'' he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At least he has 149 guys looking up at him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
