<SLUG> BC-GOLF-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALY GOES LONG, THRILLS FANS ... AND ENDS WITH 80 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ So different was John Daly's game Thursday from
anyone else at Sahalee _ hey, from anyone else's on the planet _
that he nearly rendered it unscoreable.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's drives were so far ahead of playing partners Al Geiberger
and Wayne Grady that the volunteer scorekeeper assigned to the
threesome nearly lost track of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell if he's hitting again,'' said a worried Linda
Strum, straining to see around the dogleg for Daly while standing a
hundred yards back with the drives of his partners. ``This is kind
of hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard on everybody, including Daly. He shot 80.
</P>
<P>
   The 1991 PGA champion blew himself out of the 1998 championship.
Fulfilling his promise of the day before when he vowed to play his
motto, ``grip it and rip it,'' Daly attacked the course with his
driver.
</P>
<P>
   At least six tee shots went beyond 300 yards, including the
386-yard No. 4, in which he swallowed 322 yards with his first
swing. But as far as catching up with this course, he may as well
have tried to run down a rabbit with a dump truck.
</P>
<P>
   The worst came at 18. The expectation was that Daly would be
stripping bark from the trees with his drives.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he found himself virtually beneath the bumper of
KING-TV's satellite truck, which was parked on a hilltop near
buildings a good 25 yards from the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Had KING's Danger Jim Forman only known, he could have leaped
from the truck for a quote from the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The placement was actually a drop for Daly, whose tee shot
snap-hooked into a hillside forest so deep that the ball was found
next to a dead elf. Daly took a penalty stroke just to get a lie
visible to the fairway, then scuffed one into the rough. His next
shot gained him maybe a hundred yards.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he missed a 10-foot putt on the final green for a
quadruple-bogey seven, the mercurial Daly was expected to launch
his putter through the sliding glass doors of a course-side home.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he calmly signed his card, calmly walked past waiting
reporters, and calmly drifted into the warm night, leaving others
to explain his day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started to lose it toward the end,'' Geiberger said. ``He
was going for it on just about every hole. Eventually it grabs you
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Urged on at nearly every drivable hole by legions of
thrill-seekers waiting to be taken to the frontier of golf, Daly
cranked the club so far, and whipped it through so fast, it seemed
possible to detect a slight vapor trail.
</P>
<P>
   At 60 with 22 years on the PGA Tour, Geiberger figures he had
seen just about everything in golf. Thursday was a new experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were cheering like crazy and they have no clue,'' the
1966 PGA winner said. ``They're just waiting for the big shot. It
would be very hard (for him) because of their expectations. It's a
lot to live up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is Daly himself who has created the standard, because he
loves to indulge himself and the crowds with his prodigiousness off
the tee. Of course, as perhaps sports' best-known recovering
alcoholic, indulgence has always been an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays a reckless game, just lets it go,'' Geiberger said.
``Crowds love it. I felt like a peashooter out there. I felt like I
was in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Geiberger was smiling when he said it, because he shot an 81.
Grady grinned through his recollections, too, because his 76 meant
``the way I'm playing, I can't get upset at anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it does get a little over the top out there sometimes. If
I was playing well, I might have gotten a bit distracted.''
</P>
<P>
   Grady, an Australian who won the 1990 PGA, the year before
Daly's first win in a major, also knows that the public affection
for Daly goes beyond his howitzer work in the tee box.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have a feel for what he's gone through over the
last couple of years,'' he said. ``I imagine that's a lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Daly's sobriety, now in its 17th month, is obviously a far
greater achievement than anything he can produce on a golf course.
But perhaps it is Daly's former reputation as a party hound that
helps bring out the wolf howls in a sport that accepts no betrayal
of civility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unfortunate thing about some fans is they scream just to
listen to themselves scream,'' Grady said. ``As soon as the club
head hits the ball, it's like, `Did you hear me scream?'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When the screams die away, Daly usually finds himself on the
green, where his putter has for months been dead in his hands. That
held true Thursday, when he was unable to compensate for his
wayward driving with a single birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had big hitters in the past who've won on narrow
courses, but that's because they go to the 2-iron all day,''
Geiberger said. ``John doesn't want to play that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly is an ice cream truck coming down a neighborhood street,
bells tinkling. Kids flock and giggle, but what is delivered lately
is sweetness, not substance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
