<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-COUPLES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMECOMING TURNS FRUSTRATING FOR COUPLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ It was a rough day that just seemed to get
rougher after an all-too-brief but heartfelt send-off for the
hometown favorite Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best part of Fred Couples' opening round 4-over-par
74 at the PGA Championship was walking off the first tee and
hearing hundreds of fans encouraging him to ``Rip it up Freddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples is used to hearing encouraging words, but they made him
feel all the more discouraged because of his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're walking along and people are screaming, `Have a
good round,' or `Go get 'em,' that's pretty normal,'' Couples said.
``Just because I come from here ... it's on the first hole, it's on
the second hole, all the way to the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was pretty much making them subdued the way I was
playing. There wasn't a whole lot to scream and yell about.''
</P>
<P>
   When Couples started straying, it was the 4- to 6-inch rough
that penalized him time and again. He likened it to the rough at
the U.S. Open at San Francisco's Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a demanding course from the fairways, and when you're in
the rough, you can't really get it to the greens,'' he said. ``The
rough is all gnarly and matted down.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples started out looking like he would navigate the tight
course without too much trouble, with a par on the 406-yard par-4
first hole. He followed that by sinking a 12-foot putt on No. 2 for
a birdie. But then his 3-wood started to draw to the left and he
began missing fairways, hitting into the tangled tall grass.
</P>
<P>
   He blew a chip shot from the fringe at No. 7 and made bogey,
lipped a sand shot from one fairway bunker into another on No. 8
and made bogey, and then ended the round with a disastrous double
bogey at 18 after hitting a perfect 3-wood 233 yards in the middle
of the fairway off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   After the round, Couples admitted he kept having different swing
thoughts all day and that none of them seemed to take root in his
brain. He felt like he was scrambling and struggling just to make
pars when they came and he had only three birdie chances all day,
converting the one on No. 2 and on the 215-yard par-3 17th.
</P>
<P>
   He also wasn't spurred on by the group he was playing with.
Spaniard Jose-Maria Olazabal shot a 5-over 75 and Englishman Lee
Westwood limped like Couples with a 74.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes players can feed off each other if they starting
hitting good shots, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole group was pretty mediocre and we just got in each
other's way,'' Couples said. ``I couldn't get any help from them
and I certainly didn't give them any. I was just trying to make
pars.''
</P>
<P>
   But Couples had no excuses, saying his oft-strained back was not
a problem and that he didn't even mind playing in the hot afternoon
sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back on the last two tournaments I've had (a tie
for 53rd at the U.S. Open and a tie for 66th at the British Open),
I've done nothing to turn that around, and that's disappointing,''
Couples said. ``But it's a hard course.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst feeling, he said, was finishing No. 18 with a double
bogey after his birdie at No. 17. He hit his second shot at 18, a
4-iron, into the handicapped-access area in the left grandstand.
After taking a drop, he then chipped 30 feet below the hole and
three-putted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would have made par there, then 72 would have been a
decent score for the way I played,'' Couples said. ``But 74 for the
way I played, I can always say that's about what I deserved. ... It
was a sour finish to a pretty mediocre round.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was unhappy with his play, Couples did say he
``had fun'' playing in a major tournament in front of fans who grew
up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a few good pars, but it was pretty mediocre stuff,''
Couples said. ``It's very difficult when you are not doing anything
very well and people are on you're side. That's just a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help you hit a 3-wood down the fairway or a 7-iron
on the green, but it's still nice to know that they are yelling for
you. ... Coming from Seattle, that's nice. Now all I have to do is
go out there and play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples no longer even thinks about winning, going into Friday's
round, in which he has a 7:43 a.m. tee time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to really play some good golf just to get back into
position to be close to the lead. I think I'm quite a ways from
there,'' he said. ``I'd like to play a good round (Friday) and then
Saturday and Sunday so I can look like I know what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples may have had trouble with his swing thoughts Thursday,
but he's trying not to think the unconscionable: that he might not
even be around to play the final two rounds in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an old cliche that tomorrow is another day. But if I
don't play better, I'll have my work cut out for me just to make
the cut,'' Couples said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
