<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-COLUMN-TIGER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TIGER PLAYS, IT'S A SPECTACLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELLIS E. CONKLIN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A warm wash of applause splashed down on Tiger Woods on Thursday
as he stepped to the first tee at 8:19 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Woods made no eye contact with the crowd, and unlike Nick Price,
who is a big-league hat-tipper, Tiger tipped his white cap ever so
slightly. There was no wild cheering. No one screamed out his name.
No Tiger pandemonium erupted as it does at his increasingly rare
autograph sessions. Just respect, admiration, appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger is the main attraction at Sahalee. He is the reason
Michael Landers of North Seattle rousted his two little boys at
dawn in order to get to the course on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger is the guy you want to see. What he does out there is
beyond amazing,'' Landers said.
</P>
<P>
   With a 2-iron, Woods' first shot crackled down the fairway but
found the right rough. Groans echoed through the woods. Then he
hacked into more ankle-deep rough near the green. The crowd,
pressed against the ropes and straining to see, was silent.
</P>
<P>
   Head forward, Woods marched briskly down the fairway. ``He's
quite a fast walker,'' one woman observed.
</P>
<P>
   Woods two-putted the first hole and ended with a bogey. More
groans.
</P>
<P>
   All along the way, thousands of spectators positioned themselves
just for the chance to see him walk by. Many followed him for the
entire 18 holes. This is life in Tiger Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so awfully cute,'' said Sally Weiner, a 29-year-old
cocktail waitress in Everett. ``My son has his whole room done up
with Tiger posters.''
</P>
<P>
   All day, a sporadic chorus of ``Go get 'em Tiger,'' and ``Nail
it, baby,'' serenaded Woods as he blasted his way through Sahalee's
tight fairways.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods cracked a drive down the fairway on No. 2, a man
cried out, ``He is a god, isn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   As Woods set up to putt on the No. 3 green, his flamboyant
Deadhead-loving caddie, named Fluff, smoked a Marlboro. Fluff, with
his white walrus mustache, also gets a lot of attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of a scruffy guy, isn't he?'' a woman muttered to
her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Woods owned the crowd _ and, as it later turned out, the course
as well _ after draining a 10-foot putt on the third for a birdie.
From then on, the crowd yelled ``Get in! Get in!'' on every putt.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, people began to shout his name as Woods passed them
by, the conquering hero moving from to shot, always shadowed by a
platoon of reporters and a couple of security guards.
</P>
<P>
   Does he notice the attention? Does he hear his fans bellowing
``awesome,'' and ``amazing,'' and `wow'' at every drive? Did he see
7-year-old Cole Adams telling him, ``Good shot, Tiger,'' on the
17th hole?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's young and he's good _ and he's animated. That's what I
like about him,'' said Don Ball, who lives in Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger is indeed animated on the course. He'll pump his fists in
a moment of jubilation, and angrily throw a tee away the next as he
did on the sixth hole when his drive took a detour into a right
sand trap.
</P>
<P>
   By the 15th hole, it seemed as though all of Sahalee was
following Woods. This would have been the hole at which to see the
master at work. His first shot sliced right and lay wedged deep
into the rough.
</P>
<P>
   But then Woods pulled out a 9-iron and to launch a screaming
75-yard line drive that landed within six feet of the cup.
</P>
<P>
   As Marilyn Monroe once said to Joe DiMaggio, ``Joe, you have
never heard such cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome touch,'' one fan cried out.
</P>
<P>
   At the 18th hole, thousands in the steamy hot grandstands roared
their approval as Woods made his way to green.
</P>
<P>
   And at last, Tiger Woods tipped his cap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
