<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-WILLIAMS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDMOND NATIVE FINDS PGA DREAM OVERWHELMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Normally on the first tee, you see nervous fidgeting from
anxious players. Thursday, with Byron Nelson and the Wanamaker
Trophy behind him, Scott Williams showed that the emotion of the
situation had finally tracked him down, producing tears.
</P>
<P>
   The eyes welled up when his name was announced: ``From the great
state of Washington, Redmond's own, Scott Williams!''
</P>
<P>
   Before then, even in his practice rounds with Fred Couples, the
local club pro from Glendale had just been enjoying himself,
oblivious to the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   When it hit him, it was a solid blow. He was the kid who grew up
in Bellevue at Tam O'Shanter, a housing development with a
nine-hole golf course on the west side of Lake Sammamish. He went
to Interlake High School just up Northeast 24th Street.
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's biggest tournaments was being played on a
course that is just three miles from his house in Summer Ridge on
the Sammamish Plateau. His wife and two sons were there, along with
his sister and brother and so many other family members and friends
they could have lined the 11th hole, the longest fairway at
Sahalee. Like one of the fans, Williams got Nelson's autograph and
stood there unprepared for what happened next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sense or feel a lot of it (pressure),'' Williams
said. ``But 15 minutes before my tee time, it was really something.
All of a sudden, they call my name and, God, I was nervous. I told
my caddie: `I don't know how I'm going to get this one in the
air.'''
</P>
<P>
   When he did, when the ball found the fairway, Williams threw up
his arms in relief.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the day, he battled Sahalee and lost, shooting an
8-over-par 78, but none of the scars were evident. He beat John
Daly by two shots and is two behind Lee Janzen and David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters encouraged him, and Williams acknowledged them.
It was an unusual sight. Tournament players typically are zoned in
on their jobs, focused on flagsticks more than fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (club pros) are in a different mindset than tour players,''
he said. ``For us, it's Christmas. I can still grind it out and say
howdy to people.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, in fact, helped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have scored a lot worse if it had just been me out
there,'' Williams said. ``The fan support was frightening. The
atmosphere, the people ... I rode that. I played off it.''
</P>
<P>
   During one nine-hole stretch from the sixth through the 14th,
Williams was even-par, but the rhythm disappeared on the final four
holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Scotty, did you go to the right again? I'm going to spank
you,'' said his mom, Barbara Williams, as she watched her son's
drive sail behind two cedar trees at the 18th. ``My heart aches
when he's struggling. I know how good he is. I'm like his son
(Ryan) who thinks he is the best golfer in the world ... I wish I
could magnetize the ball to make it go to the center of the
fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Williams slumped into a chair and took a swig of his
Dr Pepper before getting up to answer questions. He was still
wearing his Lexus hat and Lexus shirt. This wasn't a national deal
like Mark O'Meara has with Toyota. He was sponsored by Lexus of
Bellevue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go out and just have fun,'' he said about Friday. ``I've
always got to dream and think I can shoot 64.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't and fails to make the cut, Williams understands
the consolation of all this _ the experience of having the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had that much fun shooting 78,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
