<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-FANS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE YOUNG, DIVERSE AND FANS OF TIGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TERESA TALERICO  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Marcy Sjodin doesn't even play golf, much less
watch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been driving (at a golf range) once in my life,''
admitted the 26-year-old Seattle woman.
</P>
<P>
   But a free ticket to the PGA? She'll take it _ and make the
pilgrimage there just to see the young, the attractive, the
charismatic and talented golf superstar Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   That includes fighting snail's pace traffic on state Route 520,
parking at the far end of a dusty field at Marymoor Park and riding
a shuttle (er, yellow school bus) to the Sahalee course in Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   Sjodin was one of thousands of people who showed up this week to
watch Woods practice for the 80th PGA Championship tournament.
Camera in hand, she trailed him, hoping to get a good photograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's exciting,'' she said, craning her neck to see the
22-year-old golf prodigy. ``It's not that much fun to watch on TV.
But here it's different. You're outside on a nice day.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger. His name was on virtually everyone's lips. Flocks of fans
snapped pictures of him, watched in reverential silence as he swung
and tried, mostly unsuccessfully, to engage him in conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice one, Tiger!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger, can my son have your autograph?''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, they agreed, has helped spark interest in the sport among
a whole new generation that cuts across ethnic lines.
</P>
<P>
   Bon Regala, his brother Jon and friend Rich Aquino also showed
up to watch Woods, who is of mixed descent. They say they play at
least once a week. Young, stylish Filipino-Americans, the trio
represents the new breed of golfers. Aquino wears a small gold
earring.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are playing at a younger age, especially since Tiger
came along,'' said Bon Regala, 24. ``There are more minorities
playing. The stereotype of the upper-class golfer has begun to
decline.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the National Golf Foundation nor the National Minority
Golf Foundation has done a comprehensive study of minorities in
golf.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of African-American golfers has increased a bit,
the National Golf Foundation says. In 1986, they made up 1.8
percent of all golfers. Last year, they made up 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Women now make up 22 percent of all golfers. Female golfers went
from 4.5 million in 1986 to 5.7 million today _ a 26 percent
increase, according to NGF figures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Generation X-ers polled recently by the Zandl Group,
a New York City firm that studies young adult market trends,
proclaimed golf the sport that's getting ``cooler'' than any
others, including mountain biking and even snowboarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, there were more young people as beginners than
there had been in previous years,'' said Judy Thompson, NGF
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the sport _ once the domain of wealthy older males _
has become more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Using his backpack as a pillow, 58-year-old Bill Crane stretched
out under some trees at Sahalee. He and his son, Dan, 26, play golf
together every chance they get.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go to a Mariners game, by the time you get good seats and
parking, you could play probably two rounds of golf at an
outstanding course for the same price,'' said Crane, of Gig Harbor.
``And I think the young generation is a little more into doing
active things and not just spectator sports.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sahalee's picturesque, tree-lined 15th hole, PGA volunteer
Patty Seaton watched the parade of people following Woods. A
longtime golfer, she too has noticed new faces on the links.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're younger,'' she said. ``More women. Lots of young
people. Probably because of Tiger. I've been standing here on this
hole for three hours. Some of the best players in the world have
been practicing, and nobody came through to watch _ except when
Tiger played.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
