<P>
   Here are the top stories from The New York Times News Service
report for PMs Friday, Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, (212) 556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. ET. To get
story repeats before this hour, call (212) 621-1595 for reruns on
AP DataFeatures or (214) 980-8305 or 8306 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   ART ADV: Graphics and photos have been sent, as indicated below,
to NYT graphic and photo subscribers. Clients needing
retransmissions or information, or non-subscribers seeking to
arrange individual purchases, should call (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY (Washington) _ President Clinton has
had extensive discussions with his inner circle about a strategy of
acknowledging to a grand jury on Monday that he had intimate sexual
encounters with Monica Lewinsky in the White House, senior advisers
have said.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-SUIT (Washington) _ A federal appeals court, in a
nationwide class action, expanded the rights of Medicare patients,
ruling that they are entitled to immediate hearings and other
protections if they are denied care by an HMO. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY (Washington) _ In the government's first
Internet-privacy enforcement action, the FTC says a popular site on
the World Wide Web run by GeoCities lied about how it would use the
personal information it collected from more than 2 millions
subscribers, both adults and children. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN-LAND-TRUSTS (Clark, Colo.) _ Here and across the
mountain west, tourism and the second-home industry have spurred a
land rush that is carving up the ranch land that composes
heart-stopping Western vistas, threatening the very landscape that
draws so many people to the Rockies. The pressures are so powerful
that they are forging alliances of two longtime adversaries:
cattlemen and environmentalists. By James Brooke. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FONG (San Francisco) _ Less than three months ago, Matt
Fong was little known outside California, where he is state
treasurer. Now, Republican heavyweights like Newt Gingrich and
Trent Lott regard him as a new best friend. By Michael Janofsky.
(With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK-CONCERT (Bethel, N.Y.) _ A more sedate Woodstock tries
to lure yuppies, not hippies. By Andrew C. Revkin. (With map and
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   WEST-POINT-NOVEL (West Point, N.Y.) _ Lucian Truscott IV's new
novel, ``Full Dress Gray,'' like his 1978 mystery, ``Dress Gray,''
is a steamy potboiler set at the United States Military Academy in
West Point. Surprisingly, the academy has eagerly embraced the
book. ``I thought I would never be welcome up there again,'' says
Truscott, who graduated from the academy in 1969. ``Now they're in
the process of milling a whole new red carpet to run out for me.''
By Frank Bruni. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBING (Nairobi, Kenya) _ The FBI agent in charge of
solving the bombing of the U.S. Embassy here says that the bureau
has found fragments of the truck that carried the explosives and is
piecing together a picture of what happened in the seconds before
the bomb went off. By Tim Weiner and Raymond Bonner. (With
graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-MEMORIAL (Andrews Air Force Base, Md.) _ To the strains
of ``Nearer My God to Thee,'' the remains of 10 Americans killed by
the terrorist bomb in Kenya are borne home and received at a solemn
ceremony by President Clinton. By Katharine Q. Seelye. (With
photos.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Stock and bond prices plunged Thursday,
jarring Russian hopes that the government could avert a depletion
of its finances and a meltdown of the banking system. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELS (Kinshasa, Congo) _ Rebels hostile to President
Laurent Kabila apparently knocked out all electrical power to the
capital and tightened their hold on a strategic region outside this
city. By Howard W. French. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CROQUET (Dalian, China) _ Croquet, or ``gate ball'' as
they call it here, is the game of the moment in China. Among the
elderly, anyhow. In cities throughout northern China, retired and
not-completely-retired people are spending much of their summer
days playing it, and they compete with a ferocity that seems almost
primal. By Seth Faison. (With map and photo.)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ In a serious setback for
Western governments hoping to end the war in Kosovo through
negotiations, the ethnic Albanian leader, Ibrahim Rugova, Thursday
named a team to negotiate peace with the Serbs that does not have
the ingredient that diplomats consider essential to success:
representatives of all ethnic Albanian political forces. By Mike
O'Connor. (With map)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BORDER-DEATHS (Los Angeles) _ In an oven-hot patch of
California desert just north of the Mexico border, the bodies of
seven people were found Thursday, apparently the victims of the
heat and their dreams for a better life. By Don Terry. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   CENDANT-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Cendant says it has completed an
internal probe of its accounting fraud and that it has restated its
earnings for the past three years. It lowers its 1997 earnings by
28 cents a share and cuts 14 cents from 1995 profit and 18 cents
from 1996 profit. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI-BOTTLERS (Kinston, N.C.) _ Pepsico's independent bottlers
have been fighting an uphill battle against Coca-Cola Consolidated,
the second-largest Coke bottler in the United States, which can
afford big marketing campaigns and price wars in the fight over
shelf space and vending machines. Now, 12 years after Coke moved to
a centralized ``anchor bottling'' model, Pepsico is considering a
spinoff of its company-owned bottling operations, which might then
acquire independent bottlers _ which are already consolidating. By
Constance L. Hays. (With graphic and photos.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CORRUPTION (Undated) _ Earlier this year, it seemed that a
sweeping corruption investigation might send a good number of
Japan's mighty philosopher kings _ the bureaucrats who largely run
the country _ to prison. But these days, despite a Cabinet change,
nearly the only government employee who has gone anywhere is
Katsuhiko Kumazaki, the prosecutor who led a much-heralded
investigation into scandals involving expensive free entertainment
paid for by businessmen who wanted the bureaucrats' favor. By
Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The growing possibility of a
devaluation of the Russian ruble swept the world's markets
Thursday. Although the Russians insist there will not be a
devaluation, the threat has already led to a major selloff in
emerging markets and proved a drag on Wall Street and other major
stock markets. By Jonathan Fuerbringer. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ A growing sense of crisis in the Russian
economy helped push U.S. markets lower Thursday. The Dow Jones
industrial average closed at 8,459.50, its lowest point of the day,
down 93.46 points, or 1.1 percent. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-ETHNIC-ENTERTAINMENT (New York) _ If all New Yorkers share
one experience, it's the sensation of suddenly feeling like a
tourist without leaving the city. Take an alternate route, turn an
unfamiliar corner, peek into an open doorway, and suddenly you
could be in Tokyo or Timbuktu, with strangers chatting in an
unknown language while intriguing scents waft from a kitchen. By
Jon Pareles. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `s' category)
</P>
<P>
   NOTRE-DAME (South Bend, Ind.) _ Notre Dame halo loses some glow
after recent revelations. By Joe Drape. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-NELSON (New York) _ With eye on October, Nelson watch
starts. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   TRIATHLON-TRIALS (Undated) _ Three times the pain! Three times
the gain? By Joe Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BERKOW-COLUMN (New York) _ Cherished, and lost memories. By
Ira Berkow
</P>
<P>
   OPINION _ COMMENTARY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `k' category)
</P>
<P>
   BAKER-COLUMN _ Lament for a lost season. By Russell Baker.
</P>
