A3611 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOXER-ECONOMY-SFCHRON     08-14 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXER-ECONOMY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SILICON VALLEY SPEECH, BOXER PATS SELF ON BACK OVER ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN WILDERMUTH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNNYVALE, Calif. _ California's economy has been humming along,
and Democratic Sen. Barbara Boxer showed Thursday that she is
anxious to take her share of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past five years, the United States has enjoyed a
renaissance of peace, prosperity and creativity unmatched in this
century,'' Boxer told a friendly crowd of Silicon Valley business
people Thursday. ``Emerging from the recession of the early 1990s,
we have marched from success to success.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of the keys to that success, the senator suggested, is
the risk she and other Democrats took in supporting President
Clinton's 1993 budget, which passed by a single vote over the angry
opposition of Republicans. That vote was the first step toward this
year's first balanced budget in three decades, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to tell you the vote I cast was a popular one at the
time,'' Boxer said. ``It wasn't. A lot of people lost their
(Senate) seats over that 1993 vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators called the budget ``a one-way ticket to a
recession,'' and ``a prescription . . . to put people out of
work,'' but those predictions were wrong, Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We passed the president's first budget, invested in America,
made tough choices, and now our country has the strongest, most
vibrant economy of any in the world today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the luncheon talk at Amdahl's ``Good Government'' forum
in Sunnyvale was considered a nonpolitical event, there's no such
thing for Boxer, who is locked in a furious re-election struggle
with Republican State Treasurer Matt Fong. Her view of the 1993
budget is a direct challenge to Fong, who has slammed that budget
as ``the biggest tax increase in U.S. history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most respected economists say if not for that budget vote, the
economy would be growing even faster than it is today,'' said Steve
Schmidt, a spokesman for Fong. ``And it's preposterous to say
(Boxer) had any involvement in a positive way with a balanced
budget.''
</P>
<P>
   But the glowing economic news of the past few years is likely to
be one of Boxer's main weapons in her re-election bid, and she came
armed with statistics that show just how good the times have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area has added more than 100,000 jobs in the past
year, 15 percent of the national increase in employment,'' the
senator said. ``It now has the nation's highest per capita income .
. . and the Silicon Valley now leads the nation in exports,
surpassing Detroit and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought that not too many years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   While private businesses have played the main role in the
economic turnaround, the government, led by Democrats like herself
and President Clinton, helped lay the foundation for the recovery,
Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We invested in education, infrastructure, scientific research
. . . sending a critical signal to investors and manufacturers that
the national government wanted to be a partner in this economic
recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   When talking about what has to be done to keep the economy
growing, Boxer touched on issues dear to Silicon Valley businesses,
including tougher intellectual property rights, open access to
encryption technology, updated export controls and permanent tax
credits for research.
</P>
<P>
   She also chided Fong and other Republicans, concerned about what
they see as the dangerous transfer of possible military technology
to countries like China, for supporting an effort to give the State
Department, rather than the Commerce Department, the final say on
exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would go back to the bad old days when companies here
tried to export simple things and couldn't get an answer from the
State Department,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Good times are not times for businesses, or the government, to
rest, the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be apathetic about where we are headed, we can't just
sit back and coast,'' Boxer said. ``We have to go forward with an
optimistic plan for the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
