<HEADER>
A3613 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEPATITIS-DRUG-SFCHRO     08-14 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEPATITIS-DRUG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM SURROUNDS MAKER OF DRUG FOR HEPATITIS C 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An anti-viral drug with a long history of
controversy in the fight against AIDS has reappeared as a treatment
for hepatitis C _ and immediately become the focus of new
complaints over the marketing practices of drugmaker
Schering-Plough Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and regulators have accused the New Jersey-based company
of inflating the benefits and minimizing the side effects of a
newly approved hepatitis C treatment called Rebetron.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment consists of two drugs _ the anti-viral ribavirin
and Schering's Intron A, the company's proprietary brand of alpha
interferon _ taken in combination.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco patient-advocacy group turned up the heat
Thursday, condemning Schering for ``monopolistic and arrogant''
business practices by ``bundling'' the two drugs in a single
package, which sells for as much as $1,440 a month depending on
dosage, roughly double the price of alternative treatments using
only interferon.
</P>
<P>
   Ribavirin was touted in the early '80s by ICN Pharmaceuticals
Inc., a Costa Mesa, Calif.-based drugmaker, as a possible treatment
for AIDS. But the drug failed to live up to the company's
aggressive promotion, eventually prompting lawsuits by stockholders
and the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The company, headed by former Yugoslavian leader Milan Panic,
eventually settled the lawsuits and sold Schering exclusive U.S.
rights to ribavirin for $16.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schering won U.S. Food and Drug Administration approval for the
dual-drug therapy on June 3. Within two weeks of the product's
launch, FDA officials issued a formal warning to Schering about its
promotional tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The agency accused Schering of avoiding mention of such side
effects as life-threatening anemia and ``severe psychiatric adverse
events,'' including several suicides, in patients with no prior
history of psychiatric illness.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the agency's complaints concerned statements that the
company made at a medical meeting in New Orleans even before the
drug was approved. In addition, the FDA said, Schering's news
release heralding the new treatment's debut ``fails to adequately
convey the serious risks associated with the use of Rebetron.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Consalvo, a Schering spokesman, said the complaints were
about ``one-time'' events, declining further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The news release, in its original form, is still being
distributed through the company's Web site. An FDA spokesman said
Thursday that the matter ``has not been resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some doctors also have been raising complaints about
Schering's marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The expense and lack of access to ribavirin separately make it
virtually impossible for doctors to use the ribavirin in
combination with other interferons, such as Infergen, marketed by
Southern California-based Amgen Inc., or Roferon-A, sold by a unit
of Swiss drug giant Roche Holding AG.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing strategy ``impedes our progress for research in
this field,'' said Dr. Joanne Imperial, a liver-disease specialist
at Stanford Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Heidi Jolson, director of the FDA's division of anti-viral
drugs, said the company could sell the two ingredients separately
if it chose to do so, although this would require separate
approvals for new labels on each product.
</P>
<P>
   But Schering's Consalvo said the company has no plans to change
its marketing approach.
</P>
<P>
   The ``bundling'' strategy simply prevents competitors from
reaping the benefits of Schering's research, Consalvo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
