<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISLAM-WEDDING-$ADV15-     08-14 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAM-WEDDING-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUP WEDDINGS IN WEST BANK PROMOTES ISLAM, FUELS HAMAS
 &HT;    With photo to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server by The Palm Beach Post.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Aug. 15 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox Newspapers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABLUS, West Bank _ On the soccer stadium stage, behind the
multi-colored disco lights and with fireworks streaking above, this
is their moment of glory.
</P>
<P>
   They were 35 Islamic grooms, holding above their heads
red-covered Korans and green flags of Islam. They looked out at a
crowd of about 15,000 people, men on the field in front and women,
including their brides, on the bleachers in back.
</P>
<P>
   This recent rally was the second annual Islamic wedding in
Nablus. This large city in Israel's West Bank is one of several
that has come under Palestinian control after Israel began
withdrawing from land it captured in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding itself is a showcase for Islamic values and, nearly
as important, provides an affordable marriage for couples. Weddings
here usually require the groom to spend thousands of dollars on
gifts and parties -- a test of suitability that is hard to meet in
today's West Bank recession.
</P>
<P>
   But, the event is also informally called the ``Hamas wedding,''
for the group that helped pay the $10,000 to hold it and, according
to some observers, reaps the biggest benefit from generating
interest in fundamentalist Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Hamas, a group known for its opposition to the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process and the terrorist bombings
committed by its military wing, has built a local reputation as a
guardian of Islamic purity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, Hamas is not just the military wing,'' said
Jordan-based Hamas spokesman Ibrihim Ghosheh, who said similar
weddings have been held in Amman. ``These Muslims are the raw
material for Hamas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghosheh vowed that Hamas' military wing is still seeking to
commit attacks against Israelis, but has been stymied by its rival,
Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   In support and institutions, Hamas is still far behind the
Arafat's Fatah movement, the largest Palestinian party.
</P>
<P>
   But support for the group wedding, kindergartens, health
clinics, universities and even a soccer team, have helped Hamas
gain a reputation for good works compared to the corruption often
cited in Arafat's secular party.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, most of the grooms do not wear the beards of
religious Muslims. They include businessmen and students who rode
to the stadium from a mosque nearby on horses -- the horseman being
a mythical Islamic archetype.
</P>
<P>
   The event illustrates the sometimes unclear crossover between
fundamentalist Islam and Hamas.
</P>
<P>
   They note that the bill was paid by several local charities and
the crowd is composed of all kinds of Palestinians -- religious,
secular, old and young.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a Hamas wedding. Hamas is part of the Palestinian
people and these are Palestinians,'' said Sheikh Hamed Betawi, the
organizer who is a fiery anti-Israel sermonizer and Hamas
supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Israeli Jews running the sound system at the event,
Betawi said it shows that Palestinians oppose Israel's policies,
not its people.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding is supposed to be an example for secular
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Betawi said Palestinian weddings are getting too western. Men
and women mix, dance and drink alcohol. None of that will go on in
their weddings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the west has prospered economically,'' Betawi said.
``But their behavior in the west has disconnected them from their
ties to God.''
</P>
<P>
   These 35 couples had their legal marriages conducted before the
rally, part of a lengthy, multi-step process that culminates with a
small ceremony weeks later when the groom takes the bride to spend
their first night together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have girlfriends,'' explained groom Iqab Jamil, a
25-year-old television repairman, adding that good Muslims do not
date casually, but select a woman and arrange a marriage through
their families.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is not a Hamas supporter, but simply a ``a Muslim
without any organization.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Another groom, Wael Hashash, is a 28-year-old student and
teacher of Islamic studies who spent time in Israeli jails for
Hamas activity. He said he approves of Hamas's terror attacks
because the Israeli army has killed Arab civilians.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the group wedding because it was affordable and showed
that fundamental Islam can be fun. His sister helped him choose his
wife, another religion student at his university.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is to show people the other side of Islam,'' he adds, on
stage amid the balloons and a troupe of Arabic vocalists.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting a week later at a small wedding celebration near his
house -- held in two separate houses for men and women -- he
explains the courtship of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   They barely spoke until their families approved of their
engagement 17 months ago. Hashash would not accept a woman who
would speak to suitors before they were engaged.
</P>
<P>
   The group wedding and other social projects are part of Islam,
he said, and Hamas is showing Palestinians that it stands for ``the
right Islamic concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
