r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-JASON-PATRIC-ART     08-14 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JASON-PATRIC-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASON PATRIC PUTS HIMSELF IN A NAUGHTY NEW ROLE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 With color slides and black and white photos of Jason Patric in
``Your Friends and Neighbors.'' 
 (EDS.: Nastassja Kinski is cq) 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features  
 &HT;    He ran off to Ireland with Julia Roberts to comfort her just a
couple of days after she dumped fiancee Kiefer Sutherland on the
eve of their wedding. He has squired beautiful women like Robin
Wright (Sean Penn's wife) and Isabelle Adjani, and his current
girlfriend is Maybelline supermodel Christy Turlington.
 &HT;    So it would seem ideal that Jason Patric should play a womanizer
in his controversial new movie ``Your Friends and Neighbors''
(opening Aug. 19 in New York and Los Angeles and elsewhere on Aug.
28 and Sept. 4).
 &HT;    In the movie Jason's character Cary is a superbly buffed sexual
athlete who sees himself as a love machine, bedding women as a pure
athletic endeavour or in revenge for injustices he feels women have
done him.
 &HT;    He's a nasty, narcissistic meanie _ and it's a role that Patric,
who also produced the film, carefully picked for himself. Dressed
in black from shirt to shoes, the handsome actor sits in a hotel
suite in Beverly Hills and makes no apologies for stepping into
such a nasty role.
 &HT;    ``I've played dark and edgy characters before, but never this
dark or edgy. The scary thing about this guy and the thing that
drew me to him is that he has an explanation or justification for
everything he does. And he seems to have no remorse ... I think
that's chilling because as awful as it may be sometimes, it's
fascinating to watch.''
 &HT;    Patric sees the movie, a morality tale about three guys and the
women in their lives, as wickedly funny because he says he and
others have been there. ``The situations are all ones that we think
of, or that we've been involved in. You're laughing, which is a
reflexive response, but you're also forced to breathe in the brutal
reality of what you're watching.''
 &HT;    The ensemble piece is from writer-director Neil LaBute and the
dysfunctional characters are played by Amy Brenneman, Ben Stiller,
Nastassja Kinski, Catherine Keener and Aaron Eckhart. Eckhart last
appeared in LaBute's controversial film ``In the Company of Men,''
about two nasty businessmen who _ on a bet _ seduce a beautiful
deaf secretary.
 &HT;    In ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' the men swap the woman, and
one woman swaps her man for another woman. But Cary is the most
diabolical of the lot. And as for Patric's ``we've all been there''
line, how many people do you know who practice their sexual
dialogue into a tape recorder while pumping iron?
 &HT;    Yet Patric says he didn't have such a hard time stepping into
the skin of the despicable Cary. ``You have to find those dark
places in yourself,'' he says. ``I've been in relationships where
I've wanted to strangle the other person for some reason. I've
wanted to shoot people for cutting me off on the freeway ... Actors
are fortunate because playing dark characters allows us to free
those hidden emotions.''
 &HT;    Until fairly recently Patric says he avoided starring in
mainstream movies because he wanted to make films that meant
something to him personally.
 &HT;    The grandson of the late comedian Jackie Gleason, and son of
playwright-actor Jason Miller, Patric has worked mostly in
uncommercial films like ``Geronimo: An American Legend'' (1993),
``Rush'' (1991), ``After Dark My Sweet'' (1990) and ``Sleepers''
(1996).
 &HT;    Two years ago he decided to try for a wider audience and agreed
to step into the sequel to ``Speed'' _ ``Speed 2: Cruise Control''
_ opposite Sandra Bullock, when Keanu Reeves turned it down. The
picture was overpriced and a resounding box office flop.
 &HT;    It didn't do much for his reputation but he doesn't regret
taking the big paycheck.
 &HT;    ``I had been offered many 'Speed 2's' in my life and I turned
them all down,'' he says. ``Then at this point in my career I
realised a I needed a mainstream movie to give me the clout to get
the movies I really wanted to be in. That meant I had to be visible
in the global marketplace. And there was no question that film made
me visible _ maybe all for the wrong reasons. But it worked. I was
able to get the $7 million I needed to make 'Your Friends and
Neighbors.'''
 &HT;    Patric is one of those actors who is as handsome off-screen as
movie stars are supposed to be and so seldom are. It's not
something he particularly wants to talk about, however.
 &HT;    It makes him ``uncomfortable,'' he says, when actors are defined
by their looks. ``I'd rather not talk about it or consider it. But
the truth is beautiful people have an advantage in this world
because we want to like them. A beautiful girl can get away with
murder in a relationship based solely on her looks,'' says the man
who has dated his share of gorgeous ladies and should know what
he's talking about.
 &HT;    ``We have certain expectations based on the way a person looks
and when we discover that's not who they are under the surface we
become disappointed and angry.''
 &HT;    While still not considered an A-list box office draw like Tom
Cruise, Brad Pitt or Leonardo DiCaprio, Patric feels being in
charge of his own life and work provides greater satisfaction.
 &HT;    Through his recently formed Fleece Productions he has two
projects in the works _ neither of them blockbuster material. The
first is ``The Gipp,'' which could team him with director Francis
Ford Coppola in a story about Notre Dame football great George
Gipp. There's also ``1066,'' an historical film about the Battle of
Hastings, the decisive victory in the Norman conquest of England.
 &HT;    Patric believes he did his best work in the early '90s, and he
fervently hopes those best days aren't behind him. ``I was given
such great material. Now at 32 I like the idea that I was really a
brazen actor in my early 20s. I only wish I'd done more films. Now
I have to really search for the material.''
 &HT;    --------
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
