<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLU-VACCINE15-COX     08-14 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-VACCINE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spray flu vaccine could be on market by 1999
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Fifteen thousand children in Temple_ almost a
third of the Central Texas city's population _ are being recruited
for the largest study ever of a promising flu vaccine that is
misted up the nose rather than injected with a needle.
</P>
<P>
   Texas researchers leading the $3 million study by the National
Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, which begins Monday,
are seeking Temple children age 18 months through 18 years for each
winter influenza season through 2001. The viral disease usually
strikes from November through March, but the vaccine must be given
early to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed FluMist by Aviron, the California biopharmaceutical
company that makes it, the vaccine showed 93 percent effectiveness
against the flu in a previous, smaller study.
</P>
<P>
   It may even help protect Temple adults from the annual virus,
said study leader Dr. W. Paul Glezen, an epidemiologist at the
Influenza Research Center of Baylor College of Medicine in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the nasal-spray flu vaccine is effective in our study
participants,'' Glezen said, ``they will be less likely to spread
influenza to their parents, which means fewer adults should be
exposed to flu viruses.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Coffee of Temple, which has a population of about 47,000
people, said she has enrolled her daughter Tristan in the study
because of day care and its inevitable infections. Tristan, 20
months old, goes to day care this fall for the first time, where
she will mingle with many other children and their associated
microbes. Most children get influenza two or three times by age5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I can do to protect her against infections will help
her and me,'' said Coffee, a pharmacist at Scott and White Hospital
and Clinic in Temple, where the study will be conducted by
researchers from Scott and White, Baylor and the Texas Department
of Health in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee isn't just concerned about the flu, but also about the
painful ear infections it often inspires. They afflict about 80
percent of children at least once by age 3 and, for about half of
them, three or more times.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous study of the spray in 1,600 children, age 1
through 6, in Houston and at eight other sites around the country,
it was shown to be 98 percent effective against associated ear
infections.
</P>
<P>
   Viral infections such as flu often are the stimulus for ear
infections, swelling the eustachian tubes of the ears and trapping
fluid near the middle ear.
</P>
<P>
   Bacteria in the fluid multiply, causing further swelling and
pain, which can take several doses of antibiotics and a week or
more to cure.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Temple study is planned to last three years, it
could end sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Aviron, which submitted the vaccine in June for approval by the
Food and Drug Administration, hopes to have FluMist approved for
sale in time for the 1999 flu season.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pedro Piedra, a pediatrician at Baylor College of Medicine
who co-authored a report on the previous study in the May 14 issue
of The New England Journal of Medicine, said the spray should be
more appealing to children and their parents because it is not a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many children who fear the pain of a shot might be more
inclined to get vaccinated this way,'' said Piedra, a
co-investigator in the Temple study.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers plan to monitor the spray's effectiveness by
keeping track of the number of flu-related visits to Temple health
clinics.
</P>
<P>
   They'll compare those visits to flu-related clinic visits in
Austin, where the spray vaccine will not be available.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping children and their parents beat
influenza, scientists have another reason for hoping the Temple
study finds further evidence for the spray's effectiveness at
preventing ear infections.
</P>
<P>
   They'd like it to help slow down the development of bacteria
that are resistent to antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Bacterial resistance to front-line antibiotics is increasing
around the world, primarily in hospitals, raising fears that the
infectious bugs once so easily conquered may not be in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Because ear infections can be hard to treat, more anti biotics
than usual may be used, enhancing the rates at which some bacteria
develop resistance to the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
