<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Can't recycle those jokes any more
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I'm a little upset at Mike Barnicle, the Boston
Globe's tough-guy columnist who got suspended for two months for
stealing jokes from George Carlin.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't he have ripped off somebody a little less prominent,
like, say, Judy Tenuta? No wonder he got busted. Borrowing from
Carlin would be like stealing material from Moses and expecting to
get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, this sets a horrible precedent. If Barnicle can get
himself sent home without pay for lifting jokes, the same thing
could happen to the rest of us columnists.
</P>
<P>
   The guy owes me an apology. Originally, I had intended to pass
off some of this material from David Letterman's top 10 list of
things the Pope has done to make himself look cool.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite one was No. 6 _ ``changed his name to Notorious
P.O.P.E.''
</P>
<P>
   I was going to lift that and share it with you. But thanks to
Barnicle, I can't. I hope he's happy.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of Barnicle, according to Time he said he got the
jokes that sounded like Carlin's from a bartender friend.
</P>
<P>
   I think I know this bartender. After a couple of drinks, he
tells everybody he's the hippie-dippy weatherman.
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 2 column that got Barnicle in trouble included
one-liners that sounded similar to some of Carlin's stuff from his
1997 best-selling book, ``Brain Droppings.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Carlin's joke was, ``Someday I wanna see the Pope
come out on that balcony and give the football scores.'' On the
other hand, Barnicle wrote, ``Someday I'd love to see the Pope
appear on his balcony and give the baseball scores.''
</P>
<P>
   So why the big stink? Barnicle rewrote this joke to make it
timely for baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me. Why did the chicken cross the road? He was
trying to hide from the publisher for lifting material and putting
it in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   What really irritates me about Barnicle, though, is that I doubt
he's using his real name.
</P>
<P>
   That's a little too convenient, being a columnist from Boston
named Barnicle. If some guy writing for a Boston newspaper told me
his name was Samuel T. Scrod, I wouldn't believe that one, either.
</P>
<P>
   But back to my original premise. As I stated earlier, until I
got sidetracked by a chronic case of smarty-pantsitis, I'm a bit
miffed because now I can't lift jokes off the Internet without
figuring out where they came from, thanks to Mr. Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   For example, this guy was walking past the laughing academy when
he heard the people inside the fence chanting, ``Thirteen.
Thirteen. Thirteen.''
</P>
<P>
   Curious to find out what it meant, the guy looked through a
small knothole in the fence, when someone poked him square in the
eye.
</P>
<P>
   After which the happy chant went up, ``Fourteen. Fourteen.
Fourteen.''
</P>
<P>
   A friend sent me an e-mail with that joke. And I had hoped to
tell it to you. But I can't since I have no clue who wrote it. But
don't blame me. Blame Mike Barnicle. Then again, maybe I stole it
from him. After he got it from the bartender.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes a humor column for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
