<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: That could happen to my kid
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Four teens killed in a fiery wreck, racing on a
country road. Hump-hopping, they call it.
</P>
<P>
   These tragedies never feel like just another headline. They hit
us hard. All that promise, lost in an instant. I used to think,
``That could have happened to me or my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Now I think, ``That could happen to my kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing I hate most about being a parent is the 24-hour-a-day
fear that something could happen. That you could hear the news
three sets of parents heard early Tuesday morning. That you could
change 6,000 diapers, fix 8,000 macaroni-and-cheese dinners,
deliver 10,000 look-both-ways lectures, and still your child could
be taken away from you in a single moment. No matter how vigilant
you are, your child could steal the car keys, sneak away in the
middle of the night and test that exhilarating sense of immortality
against a treacherous dip in the road, never imagining he might
lose.
</P>
<P>
   My youth was hardly wild and reckless, but my mother still
worried, still lectured about my going to a rock concert or driving
too late at night. I chafed. She countered, ``I've invested 18
years in you.''
</P>
<P>
   I responded with all proper dignity and indignation: ``I am not
an investment.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course children are an investment, of the most precious
and irreplaceable kind.
</P>
<P>
   Once you become a parent, whatever was your worst fear becomes
your second-worst fear. Rape, murder, fire, plane crash, lightning
striking: you would a thousand times rather it happen to you than
to one of your children.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if there's this little man on duty, inside your head. He
never sleeps, never takes a coffee break. You can keep him locked
up in the attic, but you can never banish him.
</P>
<P>
   Pick up Thursday's paper, and he's in the front room, banging on
the pots and pans. Three-year-old girl dies in Springfield blaze.
Sister, 13, accused in accidental shooting of brother. Service held
in Utah for five girls who accidentally lock themselves in car
trunk.
</P>
<P>
   You want to scream. You never want to read the paper, or turn on
the TV news, again. And you feel guilty: Is this pain for the
victims and their families, or how vulnerable you feel?
</P>
<P>
   You lock the little man in the attic again, keep your fears in
check, or you'll drive yourself _ and your kids _ crazy. You
constantly strive for the right balance between prudence and
paranoia, caution and confinement. If your kids are to grow into
true adulthood, you must balance your fear with the need to let
them take some risks, make some mistakes. You must give them more
and more freedom.
</P>
<P>
   When we talk about the decision to have another child, our
questions are pragmatic: Can we afford it? Do we have the time and
energy? Secretly I worry about emotional risk, about whether my
heart can bear the weight of one more little person I couldn't live
without. How can I bring a child into the world if I can't promise
he will make it safely to adulthood?
</P>
<P>
   Children have never come with any such guarantee. Parenthood is
a brave and foolish venture, where you play the odds every day, and
there's no such thing as risk-free investing.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices rise and fall; one day you gain, the next day you
lose. Children are an investment of the soul. What you lose can
never be regained.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty is a columnist for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
