<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GMC's Savana a full-sized alternative to minivans
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When auto experts talk about ``alternative'' vehicles,
they are usually referring to those powered by natural gas or
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   But you might also consider a nontraditional vehicle as an
alternative. When most families consider the purchase of a van,
their only consideration may be a minivan. The perception is it is
driver- and parking-lot-friendly. Few buyers would ever consider a
full-size van, but they may be missing a great opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   GMC totally redesigned its full-size van for the '98 model year.
The Savana went back to being a full-frame vehicle, and from a
driving standpoint, it shows perhaps the greatest improvement of
any GM product this year.
</P>
<P>
   The previous full-size GM van could be quite a handful. It
tended to sail its way down the highway, often requiring intense
concentration on the part of the driver just to keep it in its
proper lane.
</P>
<P>
   Another shortcoming of this vehicle was the placement of the
engine and driver in relation to the front wheels. The driver sat
up over the front wheels, and legroom was cramped. The engine
compartment protruded into the passenger cabin.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it was not a package that was very user-friendly for
anything other than commercial applications.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the new Savana.
</P>
<P>
   The driver now sits on a flat floor, and the engine has been
moved out of the interior compartment, providing a large, flat
pass-through to rear seats and storage areas. Seating can
accommodate everything from a full-size family to the soccer team.
When equipped with two rear seats (a third is optional), there is
still ample storage inside the van for six bicycles, a host of
camping gear or a vacation's worth of luggage.
</P>
<P>
   This space provides more than just convenience. It keeps your
belongings out of the weather and does so securely.
</P>
<P>
   Many times I see minivans traveling with either rooftop carriers
or overloaded bicycle racks. Rooftop carriers pose two problems:
They tend to make vehicles top-heavy because most folks put too
much in them, and they cause incredible drag, eating up fuel
mileage. It might be more cost-effective to ship your luggage ahead
than to pay the additional fuel costs. Bicycle racks run the risk
of people walking into them and being injured, or your bicycling
finding its way to a new home while you're in a rest stop or
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The Savana eliminates all these problems, and does it in a
vehicle that drives as comfortably as any minivan while providing
the safety benefits of a full-frame vehicle. Fuel mileage is not
far from that of minivans, and the biggest surprise may be that a
dressed-out Savana can be less expensive than a comparably dressed
minivan.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is an automotive writer with The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
