<HEADER>
A3943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWORKING-WARNER15-     08-14 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWORKING-WARNER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodworkers fair in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For woodworkers with boundless energy and an
overwhelming interest in equipment, the International Woodworking
Machinery and Furniture Supply Fair is almost upon us. It opens
Thursday in Atlanta at the Georgia World Congress Center and runs
through Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Every woodworker ought to go to this thing at least once, even
if it does cost $20 to get in.
</P>
<P>
   It used to offer very little for the home or small shop
woodworker, but that's no longer the case. Now there's something
for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it makes the little woodworker's show that comes
around once a year look like a one-dog and one-pony show.
</P>
<P>
   It's also interesting to see the vast machines intended for
furniture factories. Interesting, but not inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   This is an enormous show, and it has become too physically
exhausting for me to deal with unless there is an extremely
compelling reason, such as seeing old friends.
</P>
<P>
   It's generally divided into two rooms, or caverns, one for
machinery and the other for things that make little or no noise.
</P>
<P>
   The noise level is so high in the machinery section that
conversation is virtually impossible. If I were going again, I'd
wear ear plugs. I can't imagine how the vendors who spend four days
in that place can stand it.
</P>
<P>
   Every booth where stuff can be purchased and carried out by
hand, or by hand truck, has its show specials. Be careful of these
_ they aren't always special at all.
</P>
<P>
   For people who've been there and done that, Highland Hardware is
bringing Roy Underhill, star of the PBS show ``The Woodwright's
Shop,'' to town the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The store, of course, will have its usual major booth at the
show, but back on Highland Avenue, Underhill will be demonstrating
his Colonial tools and techniques all day Thursday, Friday and
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 23 he'll be in the Tage Frid seminar room conducting a
workshop for paying observers.
</P>
<P>
   Store owner Chris Bagby promises that Underhill will ``fell a
tree before your eyes, and proceed to hew it, rive it, shave it and
shape it in authentic Colonial style.'' Seeing a tree felled in the
seminar room ought to be worth the price of admission.
</P>
<P>
   So next weekend you can pay your money and take your choice: go
to the fair and wreck yourself, or sit in the seminar room in
comfort and watch Underhill get all the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Call the store at 404-872-4466 for more information, and take a
look at the fall seminar lineup on the Internet at
www.highland-hardware.com. I'll try to bring you more information
on the other seminars next week.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes about woodoworking for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com. We want to hear
from you but are unable to acknowledge every message.
</P>
