<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ In the outermost ring of the
Pentagon, plans are being drawn for a retaliatory strike against
the terrorist bombers who blew up the American embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania. One option under official review would sub-contract
this anti-terrorist task to interested and competent parties in
Jerusalem. (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ This thing could go badly awry yet, I suppose,
but for now it appears the families of those two little girls
switched at birth in Virginia are going to work the matter out
sensibly and in mutual caring. While they do, the rest of us,
following the story at a distance, might usefully pause for a
moment and think about what we mean by family. (Teepen, Cox News
Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ There is no greater sacrifice a person can
make for his country than giving his or her life for it. And that's
what Air Force 1st Lt. Michael J. Blassie did over Vietnam in 1972.
But, was what he did worthy of the Medal of Honor, the highest
award this country can bestow on a military hero? (Kleinberg, Cox
News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ PARIS _ Just in time for my arrival, 1 million
cheering Frenchmen, women too, had turned the Champs Elysees into a
sea of Gaullic humanity, garlic too.This is the first in a series
of reports from Europe. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ ``So, ahem, is this a subpoena for us, Mr.
Starr?'' ``Oh, no, sirs. It's a script for a TV pilot. I've come to
you to ask for the $40 million I need to get it on the air as a
network series.'' (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ I'm a little upset at Mike
Barnicle, the Boston Globe's tough guy columnist who got suspended
for two months for stealing jokes from George Carlin. Couldn't he
have ripped off somebody a little less prominent, like, say, Judy
