<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN15-COX     08-14 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Roughing it in style
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNGRY HORSE, Mont. _ Our friends Alex and Judy Moye, who reside
on the affluent Northside of Fayetteville, Ga., are world
travelers. Having dinner with them at their home about a year ago,
I remarked that I had just finished reading Stephen Ambrose's book
about the Lewis and Clark exploration of the Northwest commissioned
by President Thomas Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   I added a brief editorial comment suggesting it would be an
interesting adventure to retrace their route from St. Louis to the
Pacific Ocean. I forgot to add that I never venture north of Harp's
Crossing or south of Woolsey on my own volition.
</P>
<P>
   Late one afternoon last month I came in from the garden to
discover my wife in a state of ecstasy. ``Guess what?'' she
announced. ``Alex and Judy have invited us to go with them on a
trip retracing the Lewis and Clark expedition!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very nice of them,'' I replied, ``but that would take a
good part of the summer and we can't afford to be gone when the
figs are ripening and all the stuff I planted in the garden is
coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a better reason to be gone,'' she answered.
``Just give me two good reasons why we shouldn't go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of one,'' I replied. ``We can't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we need to go,'' she countered. ``Besides getting
to ride practically free in their motor home, Alex has a Golden
Eagle Senior Citizen pass that will get us into national parks
without having to pay. You better accept their offer. At your age
you probably won't get another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know you were so concerned about my age,'' I said.
``Is that the reason you've quit buying green bananas?''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, we reached a compromise. We decided to make the trip
and let the garden go to pot. Alex and Judy invited us back to
their Northside Fayetteville home to finalize plans. I was alarmed
when I got a look at the motor home parked on the south half of the
Moye homestead. It is only slightly smaller than an L-1011 jumbo
jet. Being a former Eastern Airlines captain, Alex likes
navigational challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex,'' I asked. ``Do you think it's legal to have all that on
the road?'' He assured me it was, which didn't keep me from
checking with the Department of Transportation in Washington. After
listening to my description of the Moye rig, the person answering
the phone in Washington said it would be legal as long as we didn't
drive in small states like Vermont and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Because of upcoming end-of-summer sales at Neiman Marcus and
Saks, we decided to limit our trip to two weeks. We flew to Rapid
City, S.D., where the Moyes met us in the towed vehicle and
transported us into the Badlands. The Badlands are a collection of
eroding hills holding the earth together while sustaining a few
leftover buffalo and a handful of Indians.
</P>
<P>
   When we stopped for refreshment a weathered old gentleman, a
Northern Baptist, explained how the Badlands came to be. He said
God was working on Saturday afternoon putting the place in order
when he remembered he'd made a bad oversight. Being able to see
into the future, he knew about the coming automobile age. Realizing
he had forgotten to make a back-seat driver, he dropped what he was
doing and rushed back to the Garden of Eden, where he swiped a rib
from Adam and made Eve. Being worn out from a hard week's work, he
never got around to finishing his job in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   I pass the story on for what it's worth. Some of the old-timers
out here are bad to tell lies when the audience is a tenderfoot
from back East.
</P>
<P>
   We dropped in on the Wall Drug Store in Wall, S.D. The Wall Drug
Store was about to go under in the 1930s when Mrs. Wall got the
bright idea of advertising free ice water for thirsty travelers.
Now it's bigger than Gatlinburg, Tenn., and offers all sorts of
gadgets and gimmicks Ron and Pam Pendergraft might consider for
their drugstore in Fayetteville in case the Viagra market drops
off. We visited Little Big Horn, where the Indians wiped out Lt.
Col. Custer and his U.S. cavalry troop, an event that, as Lewis
Grizzard frequently pointed out, was not universally mourned in the
states of the old Confederacy. We drove 350 miles in the towed
vehicle to see Old Faithful belch in Yellowstone Park and 75 miles
to get fingernails repaired in the only nail salon in the Northwest
Territory, located between Hungry Horse and Whitefish.
</P>
<P>
   Although I worry about all the figs and tomatoes going to waste
back home, I think the trip has so far been successful, with one
exception. The female members of the party haven't located a
shopping mall to match Lenox Square and Phipps. But then Lewis and
Clark didn't find everything they were looking for either.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
