<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The making of 'Starrfeld'
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``So, ahem, is this a subpoena for us, Mr. Starr?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, sirs. It's a script for a TV pilot. I've come to you
to ask for the $40 million I need to get it on the air as a network
series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty million. Who do you think we are? Congress? You could
build a dozen elementary schools with that. You could make giant
scientific advances for our industry, like cloning George
Clooney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, Mr. Starr. This had better be good. For that money, we
should have the next 'Perry Mason' in our hands. So, how did you
arrive at the premise for this show?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we set out to make it about an investigation into
fraudulent land deals. Then we tried to make it about intrigue
involving shredded documents and even a homicide, and, yada yada
yada, we came up with this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's about sex, and lies and cheating among people in
business attire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, like 'Ally McBeal.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not exactly. It's about the all-points pursuit of one man
accused...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of espionage, hiring hitmen?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Accused of sneaking around on his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So, it's 'The Fugitive' without a murder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be up to his wife. But we don't need a homicide to
make this must-see TV. This is the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not clear. You expect to get something long-running
out of this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet. We do by examining every piddling detail of his life
_ what he's read, what he eats, what gifts he gives. One by one, we
meet all the women in his past or those believed to be his lady
friends. It we stay focused on his trail of piddle, we can be into
our fourth season without any loss of viewership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the 'Seinfeld' formula. A show about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And where is the show set?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we started out in Little Rock...''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see. A Southern theme, like 'Designing Women,' only with
corn-cob pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we moved it to D.C. Far more appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And in Washington there's far more dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More dirt. And a lot more effluent. And even though there are
big issues that affect millions of people's lives, like Medicare,
Social Security, the national debt, education and more, there's no
doubt what matters most to the viewing public.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Effluent, of course. So in this case we're going to focus on
dirty little secrets. And if we can find even one, we'll hold our
noses and focus on that with an electron microscope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really think people would make the private life of one
person such a fixation?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd stake my job on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have something, here. With 'Jerry Springer,' with
'Jenny Jones', and various mutations, viewers have shown a
remarkable desire to delve into matters once pondered only by sewer
vermin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right. For a profound medium, television has explored
new frontiers in nauseam.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right. It's shown us the moon landing. It's also shown
us wife-swapping Siamese twins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, all right, Mr. Starr. So we have a show. It had better
be good for the money you'll have spent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it'll be good. As for those people who are saying it's
about nothing, or 'it's about sex,' well, sex isn't nothing. In
terms of the marketplace, I'm sure you'd agree. It's everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not sure you could take one person's personal life
and build an entire production around it and not have a dead body
somewhere in the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we had one in there for a while. For another $40
million, maybe we could dredge a few canals.''
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald. E-mail:
JYoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
