<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-KAHN15-COX     08-14 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-KAHN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Writer Kahn shares much in common with `Rabbi's Wife'
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Sharon Kahn started writing fiction again,
it was with a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was in her 70s when she tried to do some writing,''
Kahn said quietly. ``She'd always wanted to write a book. And she
didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most afternoons Kahn sits on the red-and-white-figured couch in
her Austin living room with her cat, Alpie, and writes for four or
five hours on a laptop computer. Mornings, she spends doing water
aerobics, running errands and playing with her grandchildren. She
just turned 64.
</P>
<P>
   What separates her from other Austin grandmothers typing novels
in their living rooms is that Simon &AMP; Schuster just published her
book. It's been named a Book of the Month Club Alternate Selection,
and she'll go on an East Coast/West Coast book tour in the fall.
Last week she saw her book on display in an Austin bookstore for
the first time: ``Fax Me a Bagel: A Ruby the Rabbi's Wife Mystery''
by Sharon Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the literary novel she started out to write, the
historical one about how her family fought the Klan in Birmingham,
Ala. That was her mother's story, and it stalled out. But this one,
this mystery, was fun and easy to write because it's almost her own
story. For 31 years, Kahn was a rabbi's wife. She never was a
sleuth like Ruby _ never had her nerve _ but they have other things
in common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruby's independent, as I was,'' Kahn says. ``It was an
interesting way of life, but it took a sense of humor to get
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   She's wearing a simple black dress, and you can't help but think
of Ruby in the book, ``dressed in my tried-and-true basic black.''
That's in the second chapter, where Ruby is on her way to a funeral
for the murder victim, a member of the congregation who dropped
dead before her eyes in a bagel shop.
</P>
<P>
   As the title hints, ``Fax Me a Bagel'' is funny, often
irreverent. It's the first in a series featuring 46-year-old,
red-haired Ruby Rothman, a rabbi's widow in Eternal, Texas, south
of Austin. Her adventures continue in ``Never Nosh a Matzo Ball,''
due out next year. ``She's going to stay the same age at first,''
Kahn says. ``Later, she's going to age very slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruby first appears in ``Fax Me a Bagel'' wearing torn cutoffs
and a ``Born to Bake'' T-shirt her son gave her as a joke. She's
hoping not to run into anybody from the congregation, so, of
course, she meets the most annoying woman in it, ``dressed in a
white silk suit untouched by human hands.'' (Her bland sister is
the one who dies.)
</P>
<P>
   What makes Kahn's book fun to read are the characters and Ruby's
offhand comments about life in the congregation. Walking through
the temple she thinks: ``I'm late. The Kaufman clock with the
gilded Hebrew numbers is just chiming eight. ... I hang my jacket
in the Goldberg cloakroom, just off the Blumberg social hall.
Jewish fund-raising is not nameless.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been 10 years since Kahn was a rabbi's wife. They divorced.
The rabbi is in Tucson, Ariz.; she moved here five years ago to be
near her children who were studying at the University of Texas. She
doesn't talk about the divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came of age in the '50s, and when I graduated from Vassar
nobody expected to do much besides marriage,'' she said. I married
at 23 and thought that was old. In Birmingham, it was. After
college I was married and had three kids and had the profession of
being a rabbi's wife. I really didn't come up for air until I was
about 40 years old and decided to go to law school.''
</P>
<P>
   Law school?
</P>
<P>
   Kahn explains matter-of-factly that she graduated from the
University of Arizona Law School and practiced for 17 years, much
of that time as a labor management arbitrator, traveling all over
the West. If it was hard doing that, she doesn't make too much of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm taking a vacation now from the more serious job of
labor arbitration, where you were able to get people's jobs back,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of her children, both social workers, live in Austin. On
visits to them in years past she learned about the Austin Writers'
League and joined; she later joined Sisters in Crime. The day she
moved here she attended a seminar at the league that led her to a
critique group, the same one that nurtured mystery writer and UT
sorority housemother Nancy Bell. Kahn won the league's Teddy Award
for children's fiction for ``Kacy and the Space Shuttle Secret,''
published by Eakin Press in 1996. Last year she and Ruthe
Winegarten co-authored ``Brave Black Women,'' published by UT
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn continues to work on literary fiction, as she first did
decades ago at Vassar. She says she still may write her mother's
book, or some form of it. The taste for mysteries came from her
father, who owned a men's wear store in Birmingham next door to the
police station. ``We listened to 'Gang Busters' together on the
radio, and when I was 8 he gave me a mystery game which included
glossy photos of crime scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ours was Sharon Kahn's first interview, she said, and she did
turn over a pitcher of iced tea as it began. But other than that,
she seems pretty calm about what looks like an exciting year ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (anything that happens with the Ruby mysteries) is a
bonus at this age. I had a successful career. I raised my kids.
Anything I do now is . . . well, I feel like the pressure's off,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Or maybe it's just starting up again. ``Ruby's
independent, as I was. It was an interesting way of life, but it
took a sense of humor to get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Morris is a staff writer for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
