<HEADER>
A3952 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVE-MATTHEWS15-COX     08-14 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVE-MATTHEWS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guy-next-door rocker is floating some of the season's hottest
air time
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If '90s rock heroes had to play the parts of
``Sesame Street'' characters, Billy Corgan's baldness and bleakness
would make him the Count, Courtney Love's yellowy makeover and
annoying cackle would fit Big Bird, and Kurt Cobain and Eddie
Vedder could pass for Oscar the Grouch. All that would be left for
Dave Matthews, then, is Ernie.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely rock star if ever there was one, Matthews has
nonetheless stumbled dumbfounded into the ranks of '90s pop-culture
sensations. His record-sales figures have topped 11 million and
counting. MTV and radio stations across the country have played the
garbanzo beans out of his singles _ even the recent, hook-less
``Don't Drink the Water,'' which the 31-year-old singer agrees
isn't hit material.
</P>
<P>
   Concert-industry watchers, meanwhile, have declared the summer
of '98 his, as shows by the Dave Matthews Band are selling out with
Deadheadian regularity. And the desperately hip Spin magazine went
so far (or low, perhaps, from its readers' views) as to use the
words ``king of rock'' next to one of the most dopey, baffling
cover photos of recent memory: More startling than Matthews' queer
pose was the hairy belly-roll hanging out from his undersized
Banana Republic sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Raised a Quaker and bred on David Letterman-style,
self-deprecating humor, Matthews is the first to cut such hype down
to size.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard enough time reading or seeing things in the
media about me,'' he said recently, calling from a tour stop in
Hartford, Conn. ``But if and when I ever refer to something like
(the Spin article), it's with tongue firmly planted in cheek. How
else can I react, but by being a goof?''
</P>
<P>
   A goof. An everyman. A guy next door. A common dude with the Tom
Hanks sort of haircut and overbite to prove it. All are fitting
descriptions of this Charlottesville, Va.-based superstar, who has
dated the same hometown girl for five years and is among the
majority still a little perplexed by the so-called electronic music
revolution that every other major rocker is getting into.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I listen to on the radio? `Car Talk,' ''
Matthews said, referring to the National Public Radio show led by
two mechanic brothers. ``I mean, I tell people I'm really an NPR
junkie, and they think, `Oh, Garrison Keillor?' No, Click and
Clack. My nose isn't up in the wind, man.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Matthews isn't a cultured guy. Having grown up in
South Africa and since traveled the world, he eats up foreign life
and customs. You should have heard his excitement over touring
Latin America for the first time this fall.
</P>
<P>
   And while Matthews' radio preferences may edge on motorhead, his
musical tastes are hardly Motrhead. The one thing Matthews takes
seriously _ so much so, you can hear a change in the tone of his
raspy, leathery voice whenever the subject comes up _ is music.
Especially Dave Matthews Band music, which its namesake is far
quicker to defend than critical jabs at his own person.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that really gets me,'' he said, in that tone, ``is
when critics write that we're too average, or too much a throwback.
I mean, I guess they think we're too much like all those other
(expletive) bands with a violin and saxophone as two of the main
instruments. I understand where the criticism comes from _ from the
fact that we like to jam in concert, but that is no reflection of a
lack of creativity in the band. All the jams in the world can't
make this band average.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with Matthews' decisively quirky lyrics and throaty,
choppy vocal delivery, and the band's blink-less mix of jazz, twang
and rock influences, the DMB certainly deserves an objective look.
The band's newest album, ``Before These Crowded Streets,'' is the
hardest to categorize of all six, with a lawn-sprinkler sort of
approach to musical styles and a delivery that allows everyone from
Bela Fleck to the Kronos Quartet to Alanis Morissette to help with
the watering. This, from the band that already had non-fans
scratching their heads over songs like ``Ants Marching,'' ``What
Would You Say,'' ``Too Much'' and the sweet 1996 hit that made
Matthews something of a sex symbol, ``Crash Into Me.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more to the band's nonconformity than just music,
though, and certainly more to it than what violinist Boyd Tinsley
and saxophonist LeRoi Moore play on their instruments. Moore,
Tinsley and drummer Carter Beauford make up the group's black
majority, to Matthews and bassist Stefan Lessard's white minority.
An overboiled melting pot, you might call it. It's another
characteristic that makes the Dave Matthews Band all the more
unlikely of a pop-music sensation. Let's face it, such
multi-culturalism is often looked upon as dim-witted tokenism by
skeptical white and black audiences alike. Having spent his teen
years in an anti-apartheid South African household after moving
from upstate New York at age 13, Matthews said of the racial makeup
of the band: ``It's what I know. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not like he went out looking specifically for a few African
Americans when forming the Dave Matthews Band in 1991. He wasn't
even specifically seeking a violin or sax player.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be bandleader was tending bar at a now-legendary
Charlottesville hangout (Miller's) when he passed along a homemade
tape to Tinsley and Moore, local jazz and funk veterans. They
agreed to play on some demos. That studio work drew the attention
of Beauford and Lessard. Within a year, the DMB was a sensation
around the University of Virginia and ready to conquer other
college towns, with a style of music that even campus crowds
couldn't pin down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say our style fell into place immediately,''
Matthews said. ``But it was immediately obvious we should be able
to work out something pretty amazing together.''
</P>
<P>
   After six albums, seven years and a blur of success, Matthews
said he still finds the band that amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a cliche, but we're like a family, right down to
our daily rituals,'' he said. ``When we're on tour, we all kind of
go off and do our own thing during the day, but each night, we have
our dinner time. We all come together on stage, and it's like we're
at the same table, eating the same meal.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his own, shall we say, ``kingly'' status, Matthews said,
``I was a high-school screw-up. I was such a screw-up, I know
there's people who knew me then that now can't believe I haven't
blown this yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Riemenschneider is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
