<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie spies say `The Avengers' stinks
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tragically miscast Uma Thurman flounders. Sean Connery's
performance has made test audiences wince and cringe. Derisive
catcalls have been flung at the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Avengers,'' it would seem, is in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The first red flag spoke volumes: No press screenings for the
anticipated thriller, which is based on the '60s cult TV series of
the same name. When a studio, in this case Warner Bros., declines
to show their product to the press for opening day reviews, it
historically means they've got a stinker on their hands. (``We're
very proud of the movie,'' the studio has replied.)
</P>
<P>
   Then came the ouch-inducing clincher: Nine out of 10 writers on
Harry Knowles' bird-dogging Web site, aint-it-cool-news.com,
savaged ``The Avengers.'' For months, Knowles' emissaries have been
filing dismal reports based on the movie's few test screenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warners didn't do very many test screenings for this movie,''
says the Austin, Texas-based Knowles. ``They realized early on they
had a major bomb. They're trying to disguise a really bad movie. I
know people at the Phoenix, Ariz., test did not like the movie at
all. You could hear people laugh at the questions on the survey
cards afterwards. A couple of people said they felt embarrassed for
Sean Connery, that it was painful to watch him.''
</P>
<P>
   A reviewer who saw the film in England wrote on Knowles' Web
site, ``Uma just DIDN'T GET IT! ... Connery pretty much faxed in
his performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowles, who hasn't seen ``The Avengers'' yet, read the film's
script last summer. ``I could tell the Emma Peel character was
written wrong,'' he says. ``In the TV show, it was never about if
you could trust her, but here they try to create pseudo-tension
with a possible fake Emma Peel. It's so ill-conceived.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie reportedly cost $50 million to $60 million (not
including $30 million to $40 million to market it) and is bathed in
garish vestiges of '60s style. Knowles thinks the quirky aesthetic
might be losing some viewers. ``It's very visual. It's really
inspired by a lot of pop art. That stuff is going to be very iffy
for a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'll see,'' he says. ``I don't tend to trust opinions
about really quirky movies like this. It's like test screening a
Coen brothers movie in the Midwest, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
