</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOKENWORD-REVIEWS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Spoken Word: Audiobook Reviews
 &HT;    By Joe Stafford
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ History tends to gloss over peaceful events,
focusing on the drama of conflict and the revelations of people at
their worst. No bit of recent history brings this home more
forcefully than ``The Rape of Nanking'' by Iris Chang (Blackstone
Audiobooks, 9 nine hours), in which the author argues that Japan's
refusal to accept its culpability as aggressor in World War II
makes this one of the war's great unclosed chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Unabridged in an irony-tinged reading by Anna Fields, the
audiobook transports the listener to a real-life hell where, for
about six weeks starting in December 1939, the Japanese army
murdered, raped, tortured and mutilated 300,000 civilians and
unarmed soldiers. This narrative of half-forgotten holocaust, which
Chang terms the worst single-event wartime atrocity in history, is
not for the weak of stomach, but one feels an obligation to the
victims to bear witness.
</P>
<P>
   Of Chinese descent, Chang does herself credit by refusing to
insinuate that the massacre or the war reveal a flaw in Japan's
national character. Instead, she passionately argues that Japan can
only hope to atone for wartime crimes by owning up to its
culpability and rebuking those extremists who seek to whitewash
events or paint wartime Japan as victim rather than aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   Chang's call is bolstered by more recent events: The release in
May of the Japanese movie ``Pride,'' in which Hideki Tojo, the
Japanese prime minister who gave the green light for the attack on
Pearl Harbor, is painted as a would-be savior. In the movie, which
met with approval or apathy in Japan, but with outrage in China and
North Korea, Tojo denies that the atrocity ever occurred _ a belief
now popular among Japanese right-wing nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most chilling moment in Chang's narrative is not a
scene of rape or torture, though there are many. The most
frightening moment occurs in modern times, as an anecdote from a
Japanese elementary school teacher. Because textbooks in Japan tend
to gloss over such events, his students are unaware their country
ever fought a war with the United States. And they want to know who
won.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: This important book, though incomplete as a
history, should be read, in audio or hard copy, by anyone wishing
to claim a familiarity with the lingering consequences of World War
II. Recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Other recent histories on audio worthy of note:
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest to us here in what was once 'Lyndon's
Town,' ``Taking Charge'' by Michael R. Beschloss (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
abridged, six hours) uses recordings of private conversations from
1962-'64 to create an interesting, mostly unbiased portrait of
Lyndon Johnson while exploiting one of audio's strengths: We hear
Johnson as he cajoles, rambles, jokes and charms, unveiling
dimensions that can be appreciated only when heard first-hand.
Though the tapings are often of poor quality and reveal nothing
genuinely new or startling, they do show the complexity of this
controversial and fascinating man.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want more where ``Saving Private Ryan'' came from
should listen to ``Citizen Soldiers,'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio,
abridged, 5 five hours, narrated by Cotter Smith) the latest book
on audio from historian Stephen E. Ambrose. The book follows the
U.S. Army from D-Day through V-E Day, drawing a detailed portrait
of those who met the war at grunt level. Like Ambrose's other
recent histories on audio (''D-Day'' and ``Undaunted Courage''
among them), ``Citizen Soldiers'' is full of fascinating details,
from the agonies of trench foot to instructions on how to capture
an occupied house. One word of warning: Ambrose's reading voice is
grating and distracting. Look for titles, like this one, narrated
by a professional reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``A History of the English People'' by Paul Johnson (Blackstone
Audiobooks, 21 hours, unabridged, read by Nadia May) is a
provocative and insightful look at 2,000 years of English history.
Anglophiles will savor this study of how an island backwater
developed into one of the world's great empires. Its length and
depth makes this a worthy study for those wanting real scholarship
from their audio listening time. Available as a rental from
Blackstone, which specializes in great books.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Stafford is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
