<SLUG> BC-TEST-DRIVE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BMW roadster, M3 models bring prestigious series to a milestone
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The German/American automaker BMW reaches a milestone
this month when the 100,000th of its ``brand within a brand''
M-Series vehicles comes off the assembly line at its Greer, S.C.,
plant. The car, a two-seat roadster, will be pulled aside, given
some commemorative trim and shipped to Jacksonville to be raffled
off this fall by the BMW Car Club.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing amazing about the number of M-Series cars built
in South Carolina and Germany. The high-performance cars given the
performance perks by BMW's racing-oriented Motorsports division are
coveted by car buffs with deep pockets and by those who only dream
of owning one. What is astonishing is that BMW is allowing the
landmark M car to be built outside the fatherland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky to win the lottery of production,'' said Scott
Doniger, the New Jersey-based M brand manager. ``It happens to be
one of the roadsters (based on the Z3) targeted for the United
States market. It will be given some special trim and make some
appearances, including at the Petit LeMans race at Road Atlanta on
Oct. 10, before being raffled off in October by the 45,000-member
BMW Car Club.''
</P>
<P>
   No big deal is scheduled at the plant, although recognition will
be given the employees who complete the roadster, which would carry
a sticker of $43,340 if it joined its siblings in showrooms.
Instead, it will go into a special niche in the history of the M
cars, which debuted in 1978 when the mid-engined M1 sports car, a
277-horsepower rocket priced at about $60,000, was spun off from
the M1 race car.
</P>
<P>
   That 160-mph M1 has been followed by various M6, M5 and M3
machines, with some of the M6s from the 1980s now considered
collector cars. The offerings this model year include the Z3-based
M roadster, the M3 sedan ($40,840), the M3 coupe ($40,840) and the
M3 convertible ($47,040). All are powered by an ultra-responsive
3.2-liter six-cylinder engine, which makes 240 hp at 6,000 rpm and
has a broad torque range that peaks at 236 feet-pounds at 3,800
rpm.
</P>
<P>
   All also are image cars, both for BMW and their owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``BMWs are performance cars, and the M cars are the epitome of
our performance,'' brand manager Doniger says. ``People who buy
them include racing enthusiasts and people who take driving
programs. They're 70-75 percent male, very well educated and
modest, but with pretty high incomes. These are active people who
are very involved with cars. They don't sit around watching
television.''
</P>
<P>
   These are cars that beg to be driven, causing drivers to look
for errands to run and the long way home. The roadster, a logical
extension of the Z3, and the M3 cars, despite some having four
doors, clearly qualify as sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is overly large, nor will they take on much cargo. The
interiors and layouts are functional, but not particularly
luxurious or striking. Power tops and leather seating are standard
on both, and Harmon Kardon stereos with enough power to negate the
noise inherent with top-down driving are available.
</P>
<P>
   Safety considerations include the usual front air bags, with the
M3 cars adding side bags (optional on the roadster). The drop-tops
have roll-over protection systems, and all have seat belts that
give occupants a real belted-in feeling. Crisp steering, near 50-50
front-rear weight distribution, strong disc brakes and beefed-up
suspensions make both the roadster and the M3s remarkably
maneuverable.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the roadster's size _ or lack of it _ means it's not a
car that inspires comfort and security going wheel-to-wheel with
large cars and trucks on expressways and interstates. The
3,100-pound roadster is 158.5 inches long and 68.5 inches wide,
making it about an inch wider than the M3s, which are 174.5 inches
nose to tail.
</P>
<P>
   Get them out of the mainstream, however, and the roadster and
all three M3 machines really come into their own. BMW credits both
with 0-to-60 mph times of five-plus seconds, so acceleration is not
a problem. Clutches and shifters have solid, no-nonsense feels, and
a five-speed automatic transmission ($1,200) is available on the M3
sedan and convertible for those who don't care for the five-speed
manual that's standard on both cars.
</P>
<P>
   With its top up, the roadster has almost as much headroom (37.6
inches) as the M3s, and both have 41-plus inches of legroom. Both
have the usual wretched visibility of most convertibles and the
plastic covering of the instrumentation can generate glare that
makes it difficult to read the gauges and speedometers. The
leather-and-plastic interiors hold heat, and neither the roadster
nor the M3 air conditioner had enough strength to cope immediately
with this summer's 90-degree weather.
</P>
<P>
   Major controls are easily reached and operated. The
stalk-mounted levers are conveniently placed for finger-flicking
operation even by drivers who routinely keep both hands on the
steering wheel, which both cars encourage because of the erect
posture mandated by the seating and their fun-to-drive natures.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a drive in the roadster or the 3-Series variants,
fun is what will stand out. BMW can talk about image, and some
owners may be lured by the status that comes with
limited-production cars, but the M roadster and the M3 convertible,
coupe and sedan are best appreciated by drivers who relish feeling
connected to the machine and the road under them.
</P>
<P>
   Chart: BMW's M cars
</P>
<P>
   _ Roadster ($43,340)
</P>
<P>
   _ Coupe/sedan ($40,840)
</P>
<P>
   _ Convertible ($47,040)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front and side air bags (side air bags
$385 on roadster), roll-over protection systems, power anti-lock
disc brakes, traction control (not available on roadster)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrains: 3.2-liter six-cylinder engines (240 horsepower),
five-speed manual transmissions
</P>
<P>
   Major features: leather seating, air conditioning, power tops,
power windows and locks, stereos with cassette players and 10
speakers
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 20 mpg premium unleaded city; 27 mpg highway.
</P>
<P>
   Russ DeVault reviews cars for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
