u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC15-COX     08-14 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Octane choice a vital decision for all
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Adhering to the manufacturer's specification for fuel
octane is not a condition limited to the owners of ``high
performance'' vehicles. It is just as important for the rest of us
to heed the octane requirements of the cars we drive.
</P>
<P>
   So what do we do when our owners manuals have long ago
disappeared? How do we determine which gas to stick in our tank at
the pump?
</P>
<P>
   Finding the best gas for the vehicle you drive is often a
condition of trial and error and compromise. This could involve
trying different brands of gasoline or different octanes of those
brands. The objective is to get the best performance and mileage
from your vehicle without wasting money on octane you don't need or
use, keeping in mind that ``marbles rattling in the can'' sound
(engine ping) is what you don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the manufacturer's specifications, other conditions
affect fuel the octane requirement for your vehicle:
</P>
<P>
   _ Driving habits, both how you drive and where you drive.
</P>
<P>
   Driver type 1: You spend most of your time in stop-and-go
traffic and taking short trips. Your accelerator pedal is rarely
depressed past mid- to three-quarter throttle and sees the floor
only in an emergency, the expressway on-ramp or when you're really
mad. Expressway trips are mostly mid-throttle.
</P>
<P>
   These driving conditions call for regular, 87 octane fuel with
an occasional (maybe once every fourth fill) tank of 89 octane
mid-grade. The only reason I mention the mid-grade is because it
usually contains more detergent additive than regular fuel and will
help minimize engine deposits. A gasoline with a higher RON number
(the R in R+M/2 on the pump) would be ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Driver type 2: Same driving conditions as above, except you're
more aggressive with the throttle, tempering the rapid acceleration
with the brake pedal. You prefer the left lane of the expressway.
I'd shop around the 89 octane market for starters. (The higher the
M number in R+M/2 on the pump.) If it pings, you need to pay the
big bucks for premium.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vehicle condition, age and maintenance (or lack of).
</P>
<P>
   Older, basic transportation vehicles that receive minimal
maintenance may actually require a higher octane fuel. Neglected
cooling systems, carbon buildup in the combustion chamber, and
marginal or nonfunctioning emission control systems can cause an
engine to run hotter. Although premium fuel helps eliminate the
pinging caused by any of these conditions, it is merely covering
the source of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Older vehicles that are well maintained may also ping on lower
octane fuel. Carbon deposits accumulate in the combustion chamber
over a period of time and miles. Emission control systems, which
quite frankly have no maintenance intervals, quit working
correctly. Both of these conditions are repairable without taking
out a bank loan. The reimbursements are the ability to use lower
octane fuel once again.
</P>
<P>
   Always buy high-quality fuel from a major distributor. Cheap gas
leads to problems too numerous to list.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter writes about automotive issues for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
