<HEADLINE>
A HOLLYWOOD OUTSIDER DABBLES IN THE EMMY SPHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ The Emmy Award nominees this year are
the usual batch of glittering names. David Duchovny. Helen Hunt.
Jack Lemmon. Tom Hanks. Thomas Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   You heard right, Thomas Lewis. The racing crowd aside in this
historic town, Saratoga Springs and the campus of Skidmore College
is about as far removed as you are going to get from Hollywood, but
this professor is becoming a regular in Emmy circles.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 56, a member of the Skidmore faculty, is an Emmy nominee
in the Historical Programming category for his program ``Divided
Highways: The Interstates and the Transformation of American
Life.'' The PBS documentary, based on a Lewis book, has already won
the prestigious Peabody Award for Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   For a show about pavement.
</P>
<P>
   The key to Lewis' success is finding the significant in the
everyday. His 1992 Emmy-nominated PBS effort, ``Empire of the Air:
The Men Who Made Radio,'' also based on one of his books, looked at
the origins of what today is a common household appliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you find in these films is a definition of who we are as
an American people, what makes us different,'' Lewis said. ``All of
these projects that I work on have to deal with the face of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   His latest effort deals with what is underfoot, our nation's
highways. We navigate our roads, occasionally cursing their
potholes and traffic, but generally don't stop to contemplate their
significance. How can you make highways interesting?
</P>
<P>
   ``Divided Highways'' ``turns the seemingly mundane development
of interstate highways into a transcendent statement about the role
of the car and the highway in our national consciousness,'' the
Peabody judges determined.
</P>
<P>
   The idea took form a few years back, as Lewis was traveling the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to get the idea after getting a traffic ticket in
Montana, which is a hard thing to do,'' he explained. ``I began
slowing down and thinking about the highways and how they
transformed America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interstates have created this enormous economic engine
which changed the world,'' Lewis said. ``What I didn't realize
right away was the phenomenal social impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The Emmys for daytime, news/documentary and sports programs will
be presented Wednesday, Sept. 9, in New York City. The Primetime
Emmys will be held and televised Sunday, Sept. 13, in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is already working on his next project, a four-part
history of Washington. He plans to look not just at the tourism of
the city, but the environs of a municipality created to serve as a
cradle of government.
</P>
<P>
   So why hasn't Lewis traded in his snow shovel for the sun of
Southern California?
</P>
<P>
   ``My first love is teaching,'' the English professor said. ``I
like teaching very much at Skidmore, because Skidmore gives me the
latitude to do what I want to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a Hollywood kind of guy, a West Coast person. I like
it here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1211EDT &QL; 
