<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PARADISE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBEN'S FILM IS FAR FROM PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's also a Serious Movie because Anne Heche, playing a Serious
Lawyer, is in need of a Serious Comb. Her level of disheveledness
rises as the plot evolves, as though a heavily moussed blond shag
were all that separated us from Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was directed by Joseph Ruben (``Sleeping with the
Enemy,'' ``The Good Son''), who has a way with darkly crafted
moments. The dialogue by screenwriters Wesley Strick (``The
Saint'') and Bruce Robinson (``Fat Man and Little Boy'') is
literate in fits and starts, offering oblique commentary on an
extraordinary human struggle. And Joaquin Phoenix delivers a
crushing turn as the balmy inmate; his performance, full of agony
and grit, is the best reason to sit through this misdirected,
spasmodically compelling study of morality and errant justice.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame, because ``Return to Paradise'' could have been
better. It should have been better. And it might have been were it
a mite less self-important, were it peopled with consistent
characters, and were the drama not disrupted by an absolutely
asinine romance. The film is based on a terrific premise: That
Phoenix's character (Lewis) will hang in eight days unless two
friends agree to serve time in the same prison. All three had spent
five hash-smoking, rum-swilling weeks in Malaysia, but only Lewis
got busted. He never told his buddies; he didn't want to drag them
into it.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after two solid years of squatting on a dirt floor, he
faces execution. Enter the buddies: Tony (David Conrad, of ABC's
erstwhile ``Relativity''), a sincere young construction worker, and
Sheriff (Vince Vaughn, ``Swingers'' and ``The Lost World: Jurassic
Park''), a natty limo driver whose disposition veers from sardonic
to cynical. He's not the kind of guy who'd volunteer for residency
in a Penang prison.
</P>
<P>
   Tony and Sheriff hear the bad news from Beth (Heche), Lewis'
American lawyer, who gives it to them straight: If both friends
agree to serve three years, Lewis will live. If one friend agrees
to serve six years, Lewis will live. If neither agrees, he'll die.
</P>
<P>
   It's a smart set-up, for it places a suffocating moral burden on
Tony and Sheriff. Tony has a fiancee would she wait three years for
him? Six years? How could he live with himself if Lewis died?
Sheriff is resolutely self-centered about the whole business,
shrugging off Beth's appeals with cold dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're appealing to a morality I don't have,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The hemming and hawing goes on and on, but none of it develops
into honest conflict; characters perform ethical backflips and
abrupt 180-degree turns for no particularly forceful reason. First
no one's going. Then both are going. Then only one is going. Then
Sheriff starts sleeping with Beth, but Tony doesn't know about it,
and Beth has a secret, and there's this obnoxious reporter who
ruins everything (Jada Pinkett Smith), and everyone gets mad at
each other, and no one makes any sense at all.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is hardly to blame Heche labors admirably in a vague
role, and Conrad wins a big gold star for restraint. Vaughn's
snippy charm carries him through the first half of the film, but
the sticky romantic subplot transforms him into a lop-eared rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   Moral waffling is a fine subject for a film (see ``The Horse
Whisperer''), but moral waffling based on blindly erratic behavior
is a dribbling waste of celluloid.
</P>
<P>
   The only rational character in the entire film is, ultimately,
Phoenix's. He has three remarkable scenes: One a taped appeal to
his friends, one during a prison visit, and one at the film's
climax. The visit sequence is a bit of hard poetry, a raw soliloquy
on emptiness and prayer delivered with trembling urgency.
</P>
<P>
   If you see ``Return to Paradise,'' see it for that. See it for
Phoenix, one of the most viscerally gifted young actors in film.
But shut your eyes to the rest of the movie, a rambling spin on
``Midnight Express'' with a permanently furrowed brow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
