<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-PRESIDENCY-ADV17     08-14 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-PRESIDENCY-ADV17 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROBES AND LAWSUITS AGAINST CLINTON MAY HAVE PERMANENTLY ALTERED
THE PRESIDENCY
 &HT;    Advance for release Monday, August 17.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr's investigation of President
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky and Paula Corbin Jones'
sexual harassment lawsuit against the chief executive have
established legal precedents that may have permanently altered the
office of the presidency, diminishing what was once widely regarded
as ''imperial.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have moved from the imperial presidency to the imperiled
presidency,'' said Darrell West, a presidential scholar at Brown
University.
</P>
<P>
   While much of Washington has been waiting breathlessly for weeks
for Clinton's testimony Monday in the Starr investigation,
historians and scholars have spent months trying to determine the
long-term consequences to the White House of the Starr probe and
the Jones lawsuit, despite its dismissal earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Many wonder whether the presidents who follow Clinton into the
White House will be more vulnerable to legal assaults by political
enemies and unrestrained prosecutors, their power and prestige
thereby diminished, their political agendas curtailed or even
derailed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Defending against lawsuits may become a permanent state of
affairs for presidents,'' said Lane Crothers, a professor at
Illinois State University. ''And that means a lot of political
capital spent on things unrelated to a president's programs.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Supreme Court on down, judges involved in the Starr and
Jones cases have established a new set of precedents that have cost
Clinton dearly and, say the scholars, will make future presidents
easier targets for civil and criminal lawsuits, regardless of their
motive.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new legal restraints will check presidents of low
character, but will burden presidents of high character,'' said
John Pitney, a professor of government at Claremont McKenna College
in California. ''A future Lincoln or Eisenhower will have to live
by rules designed to rein in a Nixon or a Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Future presidents will come to office knowing that their most
senior legal advisers may be forced to testify against them, that
Secret Service agents charged with preserving their lives may not
protect their privacy, and that they themselves may be compelled to
testify, even in times of international crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Historian Arthur Schlesinger Jr., who authored ''The Imperial
Presidency'' a quarter century ago, wrote in The New York Times
earlier this month that Starr's investigation of Clinton's sex life
had produced a ''harried and enfeebled'' presidency, also
succeeding in ''eliminating protections of presidential privacy
heretofore unchallenged.''
</P>
<P>
   But Donald Robinson, a White House expert at Smith College,
cautioned against ''buying into the Schlesinger line.'' ''Be
careful of writing an obituary for the imperial presidency,''
Robinson added. ''It is far from dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlesinger originally used the term ''imperial presidency'' to
call attention to the fact that the power of modern presidents
enabled them to commit troops abroad and to conduct foreign policy
without consulting, much less cooperating with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''And that still persists,'' said Robinson, noting that Clinton
extended the commitment of U.S. troops to Bosnia last spring _
after the Lewinsky scandal broke _ with hardly a whimper from
Congress. ''If anything, the president's troubles with Ken Starr
have increased his ability to make national security policy
secretly, on his own,'' Robinson added.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, the damage done to the presidency is the work of
Clinton himself. ''Most presidents leave their mark on the
office,'' said Pitney. ''Bill Clinton will leave a stain.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Starr's lengthy investigation, initially of a shady
Arkansas land deal that happened 15 years ago, has led to court
rulings that there is no attorney-client privilege between a
president and White House lawyers in a criminal case and that
Secret Services agents may be compelled to tell a grand jury what
they have witnessed as a result of their required proximity to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're forcing presidents into a cocoon,'' said Joel Goldstein,
a constitutional scholar at Saint Louis University. ''Future
presidents may not be willing to discuss private matters with
anyone except their spouses.'' Husbands and wives cannot be
compelled to testify against their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   And last spring, amid heightened tensions with Saddam Hussein
over United Nations inspections of Iraqi weapon sites, Jones'
lawsuit produced a Supreme Court ruling that a civil suit against a
sitting president does not have to wait until the president has
left office.
</P>
<P>
   ''What this all means, of course, is that the country is forced
by the media and Kenneth Starr to focus attention on the politics
of scandal rather than the substantive domestic and foreign policy
issues that deserve the country's attention,'' said Craig
Rimmerman, a professor at Hobart and William Smith Colleges in New
York and author of numerous books on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
