<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOT-WOODSTOCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE WOODSTOCK SITE, A `GARDEN' GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREG HAYMES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, N.Y. _ For 17 years, Danny Socolof has been creating
special events, but nothing had really prepared him for his current
job _ executive producer of ``A Day in the Garden,'' the three-day
rock festival that's being held this weekend at Max Yasgur's farm
in Bethel, the site of the original Woodstock fest back in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School of
Business, Socolof began his career as a concert promoter for Little
Feat, Count Basie, Genesis, Jethro Tull and other acts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he founded the Marketing Entertainment Group of America
(MEGA), which produced events for such clients as MTV, Pepsi Cola
and Nintendo. The company celebrated its 10th anniversary by
creating the six-acre Surreal Field at the Woodstock '94 festival
in Saugerties.
</P>
<P>
   But now Socolof, 42, is focusing all of his attention on ``A Day
in Garden,'' but the main behind-the-scenes man took a few minutes
out to chat about this weekend's big shows:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's been going on at the festival site?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, we are underneath some extraordinary pressures here.
Basically, we're building a venue. We are bringing an extraordinary
venue to life after 29 years of it being a mostly dormant pasture,
and it's an enormous amount of work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you mean by ``building a venue''?
</P>
<P>
   A: What I mean is that we are hosting three days of shows here
with the same stage that Garth Brooks used in Central Park last
year. We're erecting over a quarter million square feet of tenting
for the food and craft vendors. And then there's the infrastructure
_ roadways, backstage facilities for artists, parking lots for the
convenience of our patrons.
</P>
<P>
   So we're not actually ``building a venue'' in the conventional
sense. In fact, we're building a venue in quite the unconventional
sense. We're taking a farm that hasn't been used in almost 30 years
and making it a viable, workable, safe and beautiful environment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are ticket sales going? Are they selling as well as
expected?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I don't know what anybody expected. No one's done
anything here in 29 years, so I think it's safe to say that this is
a learning experience for everybody that's involved. But let me say
that we are doing very well ...
</P>
<P>
   The point of this whole thing was to balance art and commerce.
And I think that if we had to lean one way, we definitely have
chosen to lean toward art.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you envision building a permanent stage on the site in the
future?
</P>
<P>
   A: The idea here is to rededicate the site, and get it into
shape so that it can have a long and healthy future to host a
variety of music, including classical, jazz, blues, country and, of
course, rock 'n' roll, too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the mood of the people working on the site?
</P>
<P>
   A: Everybody's got a really good spirit about it. It's very
exciting to be doing this because there's a certain buzz, a certain
magic, on this site. All you have to do to feel it, is to walk onto
the land. It's a very magical place, and everybody working here
feels it. We hope that _ with some good weather _ we're going to
have a really extraordinary weekend of performances.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The event will go on rain or shine, right?
</P>
<P>
   A: Of course, this is a world-class stage with a covered roof
for the artists. And we'll have over a quarter of a million square
feet of tenting that was never here before.
</P>
<P>
   The show will go on rain or shine, but we're crossing our
fingers that it goes on under beautiful blue skies and white
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How big a security force will you have? A: I can't divulge
details of that because it wouldn't be a secure plan if I divulged
it.
</P>
<P>
   We're hoping that people are really cool this year, and don't
try to sneak in. This is a tremendous, tremendous site, and when
you have people like Pete Townshend and Joni Mitchell and Don
Henley and everybody else that's coming, you have an opportunity in
this region to host extraordinary artists.
</P>
<P>
   And part of that depends on having a covenant with the audience,
where the audience respects the site and respects what we're trying
to do. And so the first part of our message is for everybody to be
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, the tickets are priced right.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has new technology and the Internet affected the event?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're Web-casting all of ``A Day in the Garden.'' The entire
event _ all three days of performance in real time _ is being
broadcast over the Internet via Infoseek (http://www.infoseek.com).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Obviously, you were at the Woodstock '94 festival, but did
you go to Woodstock in 1969?
</P>
<P>
   A: For Woodstock '94, my company produced the Surreal Field, so,
oh yeah, I was there.
</P>
<P>
   At Woodstock '69, I was 13 years old, and I tried to go, but I
had a six-foot-four dad who blocked every route out of the house,
so I didn't make it to that one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you plan to do on Monday morning when you wake up and
it's all over?
</P>
<P>
   A: If I wake up, you mean? If I wake up Monday morning, I'm
going to try to go back to sleep. (Laughter.) Actually, I love my
work. I love what I'm doing, and I'm a dedicated pro, so I'll
probably wake up Monday morning and help clean up and break down
the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But then I am headed off to a very remote, faraway place with no
phones, no faxes and no beepers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Any closing thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have a message that we're sending to everybody, and it's
very simple _ welcome back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
