<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DRIVER IS SOFTWARE THAT CONNECTS PROGRAMS TO COMPUTER HARDWARE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: It's definition time for this computer ``dummy.'' I have seen
you mention ``drivers'' in various columns and stories, but I
really don't understand what a driver is. It didn't matter until
last week, when I got my first computer (yes, I was reading your
column before I had one!) and suddenly I realize I need to keep my
drivers updated, as you and others say. But, um, what are they?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can think of a driver as a kind of translator.
</P>
<P>
   In an operating system such as Windows 95/98/NT, in which a
friendly face is presented to shield the user from the complexity
of the operating system's ``guts,'' software is not allowed to talk
directly to the various hardware components.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a game running in Windows 95 doesn't send its audio
directly to the sound card. Instead, it must go through a layer of
software that, in turn, talks to the hardware. These are known as
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers keep order, both in the operation of your PC and in the
world of software development. First, they help to prevent
conflicts when two programs try to access the same piece of
hardware _ though particularly in Windows 95/98, they aren't always
successful. Those who remember hassling with sound settings in DOS
games know what I'm talking about.
</P>
<P>
   They also provide a uniform way for the creators of software
programs to communicate with various hardware devices. This way,
each program doesn't need its own set of translators to talk to the
hardware. Developers can rely on the fact that the hardware drivers
they need to use will be in place, and program accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   In the bad old days of DOS, developers had to write drivers for
each program they created. For example, the popular WordPerfect 5.1
_ the last great DOS word processor _ came with several disks of
printer drivers. Now, WordPerfect 8 for Windows 95/98/NT can rely
on the printer driver installed in the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to be able to have my screen saver launch at my
control in Windows 98. It used to do this, when I had Windows 95. I
could put my mouse cursor in a corner and it would start the screen
saver. Since installing Windows 98, this feature doesn't work
anymore. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ability to have so-called ``hot corners'' for your screen
saver is a function of the Windows 95 Plus! pack, an add-on for
Windows 95. The hot corners actually are controlled by a component
called the System Agent, which is used to auto-start programs at
specific times. You can tell when the System Agent is running
because you have an icon in the taskbar tray that looks like a
window with a clock and calendar in front of it.
</P>
<P>
   With Windows 98, Microsoft has changed the System Agent into the
Task Scheduler, and several features were apparently left out,
including hot corners. They are not present in the Windows 98 Plus!
pack, either.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is an alternative. Screen savers in Windows are
files with a .SCR extension, and they are stored in the Windows
folder. Find the saver you want to use and drag it from the Windows
folder onto your desktop, or create a shortcut to the file on your
desktop. Then, when you want to launch the saver, just click on the
file.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you settle a bet? A friend of mine says the original
floppy disks were 5 1/4 inches. But my dad said he remembers floppy
disks that were bigger than that.
</P>
<P>
   A: Score one for Dad. The first floppy disks were 8 inches
across and held less than 200 kilobytes of data: They barely fit in
a briefcase, much less a shirt pocket.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
