<HEADLINE>
MOM AND DAD'S ADVENTURE IN COMPUTING ENDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About a month ago, I decided to put a made-for-novices personal
computer to the ultimate test: my parents. Although they're not
completely computer illiterate _ having suffered through a pokey,
hand-me-down, 486 system _ they're close to it.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have to ask how to turn the thing on, but they're
hard-pressed to find the America Online download folder in Windows
95.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent column, I chronicled their experience unpacking and
setting up a new Compaq Presario 2254, a low-end system that sells
for $899, and a 14-inch MV400 multimedia monitor with a $179 price
tag (www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/98/07/10/compute.html).
That process went smoothly enough, with only a couple of glitches.
However, those problems would have required separate calls to
technical support, had I not been present.
</P>
<P>
   After it was obvious the computer was functioning as it should,
I drove off into the sunset, leaving them to explore. I checked
back with them on a weekly basis to see how it was going.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `WE NEED TWO COMPUTERS'
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Overall, they loved this computer. Despite the fact that it's a
low-priced machine, it's hardly low-performing. With its
266-megahertz Advanced Micro Devices K6 chip, 32 megabytes of
memory, four-gigabyte hard drive, 32X CD-ROM drive and 56K modem,
it galloped with the applications they use regularly.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was the speed that they appreciated the most.
They've been living with a 486 system that runs at 66 megahertz and
has only 20 megabytes of memory. This is a seriously slow machine.
Sometimes you can literally boil a cup of water in a microwave in
the time it takes the opening page at Yahoo! _ my father's favorite
stop on the Infobahn _ to finish loading on AOL.
</P>
<P>
   After using the Presario 2254 for a few days, he sent me this
message: ``This is the way it's supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   I keep him on the ``buddy list'' of AOL Instant Messenger _ a
chat program that alerts you when friends sign on to AOL or fire up
their own copy of the Messenger program _ and I watched his time
spent online increase. Suddenly, using the Web went from being
painful to pleasant, and Dad developed a serious Internet jones.
</P>
<P>
   My mother uses the computer to do artwork and play card games,
which she loves. My father's time online apparently caused some
tension in the household.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need two computers,'' my mother said through clenched
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The speed also helped with a low-budget scanner my parents had
bought to digitize old family photos and send recent pictures to
friends and relatives via e-mail. Using the scanner on the 486 was
an exercise in agony, but became nearly effortless on the Presario.
</P>
<P>
   My mother complained that the cards jumped off the screen so
fast when she won at Solitaire that she couldn't savor her victory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GOOD POINTS, BAD POINTS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In general, they both found the computer easy to use. They
mentioned Compaq's extensive online help files as being a big plus
_ they were understandable and actually helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Although they didn't venture too far from their regular PC
usage, they did experiment a bit with new things. For example, my
father became a fan of MotoRacer, a motorcycle game that's bundled
with the 2254. He's not been interested in racing games before _
and couldn't play this one on his older machine, anyway _ but now
he's talking about getting a joystick.
</P>
<P>
   However, it wasn't all digital peaches and cream. There were
some things about this computer they didn't particularly like.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was the keyboard. They both found it stiff and
unresponsive. My father even went so far as to grab a micrometer
from his workbench and measure the size and depth of the keys and
compare them to the old keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   (This highlights a crucial factor to consider when trying out a
computer. If you are buying a system in a store, spend time typing
on the keyboard. The keyboard is one of the primary ways humans
interact with computers, so you should find one that's
comfortable.)
</P>
<P>
   The Presario keyboard also includes a set of four buttons that,
when pushed, launch a browser showing pre-chosen Web sites. My
parents played with this feature and found it interesting, but they
resented the fact that the main Internet button directed you to a
Compaq-branded GTE Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already use AOL. Why can't it just set up so it uses what
we already have?'' my father asked.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, they tried signing up for the 50 free hours of
Internet access. Both were put off by the amount of personal
information the sign-up process required, and when they tried to
connect to the server to send in their application, the screen just
sat there. They eventually gave up.
</P>
<P>
   After a month, their grand experiment was over. This was only a
loaner, and I arrived to box up the Presario and take it. They both
looked on wistfully as I loaded it back in my car.
</P>
<P>
   They're back to living with the older machine. Maybe they'll buy
a new system now that they've had a taste of modern computing
power. Or, maybe they'll do what many other users of older PCs do,
and keep using it as long as it meets their needs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a comment or question about computing? Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
