<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL INVOLVEMENT NEEDED TO CLEAN UP RACIALLY-TINGED MESS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The bizarre story of Jermaine Henderson, Sean
McKenna and William Bonanni has taken an intriguing twist. In one
of the most controversial criminal cases in the memory of this
town, the prosecutors either:
</P>
<P>
   A. Screwed up by the numbers, or
</P>
<P>
   B. Were victimized by bad decisions by a judge, or
</P>
<P>
   C. Took a dive that Greg Louganis would envy.
</P>
<P>
   At best, both the Albany County district attorney's office and
Special Prosecutor John Dorfman come off like abject mental
deficients. The mayor is beside himself. A good portion of this
city's black community seems furious. And everybody involved in
this debacle is pointing fingers at everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   A little background here:
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine Henderson, who is black, is the former College of St.
Rose basketball star who either did or did not sucker punch an
off-duty cop in a bar last October. Sean McKenna and William
Bonanni are the two off-duty white cops who busted Henderson,
handcuffed him and then either did or did not beat the spit out of
him some time later in a police garage.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, we'll probably never know for sure who did
what to whom. That's because Albany County Court Judge Larry Rosen
threw out criminal charges against the cops on Wednesday, just as
he'd thrown out the charges against Henderson the previous week. He
ruled that the prosecutors had badly bobbled both cases.
</P>
<P>
   So none of these guys seems likely to end up on a witness stand,
sworn to tell the truth under penalty of perjury _ assuming, that
is, that perjury is still a crime in this country. That seems an
open question these days. Sure, there'll be a civil lawsuit, but
those things generally get settled without courtroom testimony.
It's also possible that the feds will go after the cops for
supposedly violating Henderson's civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, too, that an appeal by the prosecutors will
overturn Rosen's decision and a jury might actually get to hear
this case.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, it seems that a good many black folks in this
town strongly suspect that the D.A.'s office, which works with the
cops all the time, just tanked on this baby rather than prosecute
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   As Albany County Legislator Lucy McKnight said: ``I hope the
federal government steps in ... That's what the public needs to
have. We need to have a trial and to have all this aired.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was this:
</P>
<P>
   In separate grand juries, one hearing the sucker punch
accusation against Henderson and the other hearing the street
justice charge against the cops, both the D.A.'s office
investigating Henderson and the special prosecutor investigating
the cops let all three guys testify without first getting them to
sign waivers of immunity from prosecution for what they told the
grand juries.
</P>
<P>
   Like, duh.
</P>
<P>
   Without a waiver, Rosen ruled last week, Henderson couldn't be
prosecuted for whatever he fessed up to. And, Rosen ruled
Wednesday, when the Albany County D.A.'s office asked the cops what
had happened in the bar without a waiver, they were essentially
asking about the cops' alleged motive to allegedly whomp Henderson
upside the head in the garage later _ allegedly.
</P>
<P>
   Dorfman, livid, is appealing the cops' decision. District
Attorney Sol Greenberg needs to appeal the decision on Henderson.
Both prosecutors should be begging frantically for the feds to step
in immediately. To do anything else would only fan the flames of
suspicion felt by Lucy McKnight and the minority folks she
represents about this incredible turn of events in this ugly,
sloppy case.
</P>
<P>
   Just the truth. That's all Lucy McKnight wants.
</P>
<P>
   And to get this horrible stink out of the air.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
