<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAW-DEANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW DEANS' TENURE GROWS PRECARIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ When Boston College law students decide whose
courses to take this year, their choices will include three
professors who not only enjoy national reputations but whose last
jobs were as the deans of respected law schools.
</P>
<P>
   This trio of heavyweights shares another distinction, and it's
the reason they are now teaching at BC rather than leading at their
respective schools. They were all forced from their posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call this my own special program for deposed deans,'' Aviam
Soifer, a Boston College Law School professor, said last week. He
arranged the visiting professorships for his two ousted colleagues
even as he joined their ranks, resigning last fall as dean under
pressure from his own institution's president.
</P>
<P>
   The academics' situations are hardly unique. In the last year,
at least seven law school deans nationwide have been ousted from
their jobs _ a much higher number in such a short period than
anyone in the legal community can remember.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, exactly one-quarter of the nation's 180 law
schools reported dean vacancies this year, according to the
American Bar Association. Figures compiled by the ABA and the
Association of American Law Schools indicate that on average, deans
today remain in their position for less than four years _ down from
five to six years a decade ago, and from 10 to 15 years just a
generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this lessening of continuity hurts legal education in
the long run is unclear. But nearly all those involved agree the
trend, barely noticed outside the legal world, reveals fundamental
changes in how the leadership of law schools _ and, in some ways,
of universities in general _ has evolved to become more difficult
and stressful.
</P>
<P>
   ``A job that in the past had been one that was always
challenging and that most people could control ... has become much
more intense and rigorous,'' said David Hall, who resigned recently
as dean of Northeastern's law school to become the university's
provost. ``That has to make various individuals rethink what
they're going to do with their careers.''
</P>
<P>
   As universities operate more _ and more overtly _ like
bottom-line enterprises, the demands on deans have grown. They
include stunning amounts of time for fund-raising; increased
competition for high-caliber professors and students, leading some
deans to take extraordinary steps such as traveling the country to
personally recruit individual college seniors; and diminished power
for many deans, who are treated by their presidents as middle
managers rather than as autonomous leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The universities are hustling for money,'' said Fr. Robert
Drinan, who served as law school dean at Boston College for 14
years and now teaches at Georgetown University in Washington. ``So
things have become very competitive, and deans don't stay so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   The school-as-business phenomenon throws new balls into deans'
juggling acts while giving more weight to others.
</P>
<P>
   Those include trying to achieve a balance between theoretical or
academic teaching, which most professors consider vital, and
practical training _ showing students how to be attorneys _ which
law firms increasingly press law schools to do. And, even as they
strive to please their presidents and boards of trustees above, the
deans also try to maintain peace below in their faculties, which
have conflicting priorities and often include media stars, strong
personalities, serious scholars, and others with considerable egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of different constituencies and a lot more
ways in which those constituencies need to be paid attention to
than there were 10 or 15 years ago,'' said BC law professor Soifer.
He was among many current and former deans interviewed who
emphasized that despite the new challenges, they enjoyed the work.
</P>
<P>
   Deans' burdens also include longtime nuisances that are growing
in magnitude, such as wealthy people hinting at huge grants or even
bribes if their children gain acceptance to a particular school.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Barbara Aldave _ who will be teaching at
Northeastern in the fall and then Boston College in the spring,
after being pushed out as dean of St. Mary's University Law School
in San Antonio _ said she has been offered as much as $1 million,
for her own use, to ``expedite'' a student's acceptance. And Colin
Diver, who served briefly as law school dean at Boston University
and now holds that post at the University of Pennsylvania, said he
has rejected two separate $250,000 incentives.
</P>
<P>
   James Rogers, interim dean at BC Law, said that many professors
who take a dean's job become frustrated once they realize how
little time they have for academic work. ``In general, to be a
successful law school dean ... you need to be a distinguished
scholar,'' Rogers said. ``But the job allows you very little time
for those activities that led you to the job in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Soliciting contributions, in particular, has become so integral
to most senior administrators' responsibilities that it increases
the stress and workload of jobs that are already difficult.
Moreover, fund-raising success has come to rival academic and
management skills as a key measure of performance.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to raise money has grown even though law schools,
unlike most divisions of a university, take in enough tuition to
pay their own expenses. But cash-strapped presidents increasingly
are asking for a share of any extra tuition money or other
surpluses to fill other institutional needs.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case this year with the dean of Georgetown Law
Center, Judith Areen, who was so successful in obtaining
contributions that the school's president wanted to channel some to
his deficit-ridden medical school. When Areen refused, she was
booted, but a public-relations campaign by the popular dean's
supporters and financial backers led to a rapid reversal of that
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Shane, who will teach at Boston College this spring with
Aldave and Soifer, wasn't as lucky. Three weeks after being named
one of the nation's 40 ``Young Leaders'' by the American
Association of Higher Education in January, he was prodded to
resign as dean of the University of Pittsburgh School of Law
because of another fund-sharing dispute. He, like all of those
interviewed, declined to discuss specifics of his situation.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Clark, the dean at Harvard Law School for a decade, said
fund-raising now fills about one-third of his time. ``It just
didn't used to exist as part of the job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark added that a boom in law-school growth during the 1970s
and 1980s led to another little-understood addition to most deans'
duties: overseeing more clerical workers and other staff members
who deal with expanded student bodies and bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be the CEO of a large administrative staff ...
while being an intellectual, a political leader and a
fund-raiser,'' said Clark.
</P>
<P>
   One factor cited by dean after dean as a reason their jobs have
gotten tougher is the law-school ranking published annually since
1990 by US News &AMP; World Report. They said the ratings have
heightened competition among all the institutions, escalating their
efforts to recruit students and prestigious professors, which adds
to their expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, 164 law school deans signed a letter to
93,000 applicants asking them to disregard the US News issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're engaged in an arms race for students and faculty, and in
order to pay for it, we have to raise ever larger amounts of
money,'' said Diver, who cited Harvard Law's recent success in
luring Lani Guinier from the University of Pennsylvania. ``And
those US News rankings just exacerbate the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As for finding a successor for Soifer at BC, sources familiar
with the situation said the search process has taken longer than
expected because two candidates who had expressed strong interest
fell through.
</P>
<P>
   One reportedly was Russell Osgood, dean of the Cornell
University Law School, who was wooed away from BC Law to become
president of tiny Grinnell University in Iowa _ with a pay package
sweetened by billionaire Warren Buffett, a trustee of the school.
The other candidate, who was described only as ``a minority with
terrific credentials,'' was said to have been unable to arrange the
logistics of leaving his current post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
