<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4100 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GOVERNESS-REVIEW     08-14 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GOVERNESS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF-CENTER `GOVERNESS' OFFERS GUILTY PLEASURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEFF MILLAR 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is much to admire about ``The Governess,'' a
handsome-to-the-eye and thematically engrossing British film set in
the 1840s. A young Sephardic Jewish woman whose family suffers
reduced circumstances must take a position as governess on an
island off the coast of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Were you to triangulate writer-director Sandra Goldbacher, you
would find her blip moving among the coordinates of Bronte, Peter
Greenaway and Harlequin.
</P>
<P>
   It is pleasurable in there, sometimes guiltily pleasurable, and
sometimes the guilt is sorely pressured. The dialogue often dices
with howlers.
</P>
<P>
   Rosina Da Silva (Minnie Driver) lives within a loving family, as
intensely insular as the Sephardic Jewish community itself.
Antisemitism is intense, not that the Sephardic are that interested
in assimilation; the Da Silvas believe themselves superior in every
way to gentiles and want little of their company.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosina's beloved father is murdered. To support the family,
Rosina assumes the name of Mary Blackchurch and takes the position
as governess to the Cavendishes of the Isle of Skye.
</P>
<P>
   Her charge is the early-adolescent Clementina (Florence Hoath).
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cavendish (Harriet Walker), who longs to live in London,
asks Rosina/Mary if ``it is possible to die of boredom and
disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cavendish (Tom Wilkinson) is an archetypal 19th-century
English gentleman scientist who spends almost all his waking
moments collecting specimens or in his workroom with the camera
obscura. ``Arcane and futile,'' he calls his work.
</P>
<P>
   Goldbacher gives Mr. Cavendish the intellectual life of
gentleman scientist William Henry Fox Talbot, the inventor of the
calotype. Talbot was in a race with Louis Daguerre to discover how
to permanently fix a photographic image to a medium _ Daguerre as a
positive to a metal plate, Talbot as a negative to paper.
</P>
<P>
   Rosina is a passionate, artistic, curious and intelligent woman
gender-trapped in a time and place where there is little socially
acceptable outlet for any of those qualities. She would have been
an actress, had not the profession been so utterly disreputable.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cavendish asks her to help catalog his collections, which
leads to her working with him on the calotype experimentation. This
leads to her prodding him into using photography for artistic
expression, not just for getting an image on paper to see if it can
be ``fixated,'' as Goldbacher puts it, borrowing the induction for
the word's auxiliary usage of ``to preoccupy obsessively.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have made it possible to capture the essence of people,''
says Rosina passionately, ``to fix memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldbacher suggests that it is the confluence of Rosina's
intellectual excitement and sexual curiosity that results in her
falling in love with her employer, and to her taking bold measures
to prompt love's reciprocation.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a period piece; Goldbacher's perspective is entirely
contemporary, and we suspect there is to be gender perfidy ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Cavendish is unprepared to commit to Rosina to the extent
she has immersed herself in him. ``This is madness!'' he cries,
thinking of his family. And then, thinking more of himself, ``You
consume me! I do not want the feelings that I have! You take the
strength I need for my work!'' Goldbacher's dialogue tends to
sprout exclamation points.
</P>
<P>
   When Rosina suggests that when the work on the calotype is
published she share in the credit, Mr. Cavendish smiles besottedly.
But what will he say when the editor of the scientific journal
arrives for the demonstration?
</P>
<P>
   (Among other things that, in truth, the discovery of the
fixative agent _ saltwater _ was an accident. It was Rosina who had
the accident _ she spilled the saltwater on a negative _ but it was
just an accident. She didn't exactly sit down with a Periodic Table
and a quill and work out that sodium chloride should do the trick.
Goldbacher later has Mr. Cavendish metaphorically smite his
forehead and cry out that he should have realized that sodium
chloride would do the trick. Had one of the Cavendish hounds
knocked over the bowl of saltwater, would Mr. Cavendish have been
obliged to share the publication credit with the pooch?)
</P>
<P>
   The film is impeccably acted, in that impeccable British way.
Although it's entirely Driver's film, one becomes conscious of the
valiant Wilkinson, whom Goldbacher has given the highest-risk
dialogue (``I could drown in your hair. It's like . . .
treacle.''). Wilkinson played the homophobe in ``Wilde'' and the
reticent laid-off steel mill foreman in ``The Full Monty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Governess,'' rated R, is consistently off-center, which is
enough to recommend it. But the screenplay feels a bit long in the
hothouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
