</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RETURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PARADISE' LOST DESPITE FINE CAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
RETURN TO PARADISE 
Directed by: Joseph Ruben 
Screenplay by: Wesley Strick, Bruce Robinson 
Starring: Vince Vaughn, Anne Heche, Joaquin Phoenix, David Conrad,
Vera Farmiga, Nick Sandow, Jada Pinkett Smith 
Running time: 109 minutes 
Rated: R (language, drug content, some sexuality and a scene of
violence) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to be a ``Midnight Express'' for the '90s, ``Return to
Paradise'' is a misfire instead. It at least has more ambition than
most films. Also to its credit, it isn't predictable. But it never
catches us up in its issues or what it means to persuade us are its
passions. Taken from a French film, ``Force Majeure,'' it begins
with a scene that fills you with dread because you know that the
three young Americans on the loose in Malaysia are courting
disaster when they grow heedless about local customs as they bomb
around Penang, drinking, whoring, and buying drugs cheap.
</P>
<P>
   They seem to have escaped without harming themselves when we see
Vince Vaughn's more experienced leader say goodbye to David
Conrad's shy young architect and Joaquin Phoenix's Greenpeace
activist, on his way to save orangutans. Then, two years later, the
ax falls. Vaughn, a cynical limo driver, and Conrad, now an
up-and-coming architect, get word that the young naturalist never
made it out of Malaysia. When a rented bike that Vaughn discarded
brought the irate bicycle shop owner to their rented house,
accompanied by police, they found a brick of discarded hashish
there. Phoenix's gentle idealist was arrested, tried as a drug
dealer, and condemned to die.
</P>
<P>
   The only way he can be saved, his lawyer informs the two men she
tracked down in New York, is for them to go back and share the
blame, changing the sentence from death for one to prison terms for
all three. They're informed by their convicted companion's lawyer _
Anne Heche _ that they have eight days to act before the sentence
is carried out. So the clock starts ticking on their guilt.
Complicating the crisis-of-conscience drama is the career agenda of
an ambitious reporter played in career-stretching fashion by Jada
Pinkett Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Heche's lawyer fears that if Pinkett's journalist trumpets the
story around the world things will go worse for her client. She
cites precedent _ the Malaysian caning incident, when an American
youth was caned despite protests because Malaysian police were
angry at being pressured from outside. So Heche tries to get the
reporter to cool it while working on the limo driver and architect.
It might have worked if the film had stuck to its original
imperatives and not veered off into a totally unconvincing
escalation of passions between the lawyer and one of the
codefendants.
</P>
<P>
   The film almost blasts past its dramaturgical shortcomings once
the scene shifts to Malaysia. Justice takes a surprising turn that
makes the jailed member of the trio seem more sympathetic, more of
a victim as he sits in his hellhole of a cell awaiting his fate.
Vaughn, Heche, and Phoenix throw themselves at their assignments.
But that's the problem. They just seem like actors carrying out
assignments, with the script throwing even greater odds against
them than the harsh Malaysian government does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
