<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FIRST-LOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT LOOKING `FIRST LOVE' FAILS TO ENGAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
FIRST LOVE, LAST RITES 
Directed by: Jesse Peretz 
Written by: David Ryan (based a Ian McEwan short story.) 
Starring: Natasha Gregson Wagner, Giovanni Ribisi, Robert John
Burke, Jeannetta Arnette, Donal Logue, Eli Marienthal 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Unrated 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The steamy Louisiana bayou atmosphere runs so thick and heavy in
``First Love, Last Rites,'' it almost masks the fact that there's
very little going on here. Jesse Peretz's languorous first feature
sets its sights on the well-worn topic of first love, and all the
unexpected bumps that a virgin heart encounters along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Gregson Wagner and Giovanni Ribisi certainly make a
photogenic young couple, and Peretz spends plenty of time capturing
the erotic blush of this new love. With a mattress propped on a
table, the two engage in all kinds of slow, passionate, dreamy
lovemaking.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, those seem to be the best of times for the couple.
Wagner's Sissel and Ribisi's Joey are a bit of a mismatch. Sissel
is moody and Southern, and Joey is an easygoing kid from Brooklyn.
They spend much of their time in a one-room house on stilts, trying
to tolerate visits from Sissel's relentlessly obnoxious little
brother Adrian (Eli Marienthal) and Joey's eel-trapping
get-rich-quick scheme with Sissel's father, Henry (Robert John
Burke).
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the rat, and its insistent scratching within the
walls of the house. That rodent _ and he's a big sucker who could
give Boston's best a run for their money _ pops up in several dream
sequences. It is a clumsy symbol for all the gnawing doubts and
uncertainties in a relationship that is never as stable in upright
positions as it is when Sissel and Joey are getting horizontal.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on a 1975 short story by Ian McEwan, and
perhaps this just worked better on the written page. The film,
though beautifully filmed, is as often stagnant as Louisiana swamp.
There's no dramatic momentum, and the film repeatedly sags when it
should soar.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner and especially Ribisi are intriguing young actors.
(Ribisi's talents are put to greater use as an Army medic in
``Saving Private Ryan''). With his sleepy eyes and sad smile,
Ribisi nails the confusion of a young man who believes he's in
love, but doesn't know what love is.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner is appropriately mercurial, loving and needy one moment,
then distant and sour the next. Her Sissel is not yet quite a
woman, but she already understands the spells she can cast on a man
with just one look. Wagner is an actress to watch, and yes, she
inherited the limpid beauty of her late mother, Natalie Wood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
