<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY COS. BUYS ANOTHER ASSET FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is this the way to build a money management empire?
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Financial Cos. of Boston struck its latest deal in a
summer shopping spree yesterday by acquiring Societe Generale Asset
Management Corp., which invests $5 billion, and its star money
manager Jean-Marie Eveillard. Price tag: up to $216 million.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Liberty Financial has spent $147.5 million to
purchase Crabbe Huson Group, which manages about $5.3 billion, and
bought Progress Investment Management Co., overseeing $2.5 billion,
for an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   These firms will be added to the group of money managers Liberty
has already collected, including Colonial Group, Stein Roe &AMP;
Farnham, and Newport Pacific Management Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The stable of firms, which manage a combined $54 billion, make
up about half of Liberty's business. The rest is generated by the
company's big annuity operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really built out a very full and, we think, a robust
product line,'' said Liberty Financial's chief executive, Ken
Leibler.
</P>
<P>
   Robust could be a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Financial filled a long-standing gap in its money
manager lineup by acquiring SoGen, a diversified international
investor, and Eveillard, one of the few marquee names in the field.
</P>
<P>
   But Liberty Financial also will buy a company that has struggled
in recent times, a recurring theme in its acquisitions this year.
The firms pursued by Liberty Financial may be part of a smart
long-term plan, but they have a habit of limping to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Eveillard's SoGen International, a mutual fund that contains
most of the firm's assets under management, has lost 1.5 percent
over the last year and ranks in the last quarter of the global fund
field for 1-, 3- and 5-year performances, according to Lipper
Analytical Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Performance has taken a toll on SoGen's business recently. The
New York-based company managed net sales of $70 million last year
but has seen shareholder redemptions outpace new sales by $650
million through the first half of 1998, according to Financial
Research Corp., a Boston-based firm.
</P>
<P>
   SoGen recorded net sales of more than $1 billion in the better
days of 1996. The company is the US mutual funds unit of Societe
Generale SA, one of France's largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   Leibler describes the problems as a short-term setback for a
proven and popular manager. Some outsiders agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean-Marie Eveillards come around every few years and they
were able to nail this one,'' said Burton Greenwald, an industry
consultant based in Philadelphia. ``When the tide changes, it will
pay off big-time for Liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   An even stronger investment tide was working against Crabbe
Huson when it struck a deal with Liberty Financial in June. The
firm, once a hot shop with a value-oriented investment style _
picking stocks it believes are underpriced and will appreciate over
time _ has been crushed in the otherwise strong stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Its Crabbe Huson Special fund has lost 36.1 percent in the last
year, ranking it dead last among 291 mid-capitalization funds
tracked by Lipper. The Crabbe Huson Small Cap fund has lost 24.8
percent in the same period, worse than all but two of 540 funds in
its category, according to Lipper.
</P>
<P>
   Customers pulled about $140 million out of Crabbe Huson's mutual
funds in the first half of this year, following net redemptions of
about $130 million last year, according to Financial Research Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Leibler said the bulk of Crabbe Huson's business, managing about
$4 billion for institutional clients, has actually been growing. He
said the firm's performance has suffered only because its
investment style fell out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think value will have its day, as it always has had
historically,'' Leibler said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Financial had been in the hunt for yet another
well-known mutual fund firm with slumping short-term results in the
spring. The company was widely reported, in this column and
elsewhere, to be leading the chase for the $6.1 billion Kaufmann
fund. Eventually, all the companies pursuing the fund lost
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Financial has experience waiting for investment trends
to turn around. Colonial, a Boston-based bond shop, was its first
big purchase, in 1994, and fixed-income investments have been out
of favor ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial sales exceeded redemptions by $178 million in the
second quarter this year. But it was the first quarter since early
1991 in which customers gave the company more money than they
pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   Newport Pacific Management, a well-known name among Asian-stock
mutual fund firms, was on a roll when it was acquired by Liberty
Financial. But the Asian stock collapse of the last year has put
the brakes on new business.
</P>
<P>
   Another big Liberty Financial unit, growth-stock manager Stein
Roe, attracted net sales last year. But sales have roughly equaled
redemptions in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice if you can buy something that's doing
phenomenally well at that second,'' said Leibler. ``But we are more
long-term investors. We are putting together investment
capabilities'' to carry the company through all types of investment
cycles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
