<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENOWNED CHILDREN'S AUTHOR INSPIRES RESPECT FOR ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARLA BENNETT  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. _ More than a thousand people recently gathered in
Oxford and Cambridge, England, to celebrate C.S. Lewis. This
brilliant author and scholar _ famous for his children's books,
including the ``Chronicles of Narnia,'' his religious writings,
including ``Mere Christianity,'' and countless books and articles
about ethics _ richly deserves the praise.
</P>
<P>
   Though he died 35 years ago, every one of his books remains in
print. A few years ago, Sir Anthony Hopkins portrayed Lewis in the
acclaimed film ``Shadowlands.''
</P>
<P>
   But I wonder how many of those gathered in England know he was
an advocate for animal rights.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Problem of Pain,'' Lewis renounces experiments on
animals. ``Vivisection,'' he writes, ``can only be defended by
showing it to be right that one species should suffer in order that
another species be happier .... If we cut up beasts simply because
they cannot prevent us, and because we are backing our own side in
the struggle for existence, it is only logical to cut up imbeciles,
criminals, enemies or capitalists for the same reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years since Lewis' death, the experimentation industry
has become a mega-conglomerate that uses up and kills more than 60
million animals a year to get billions of dollars in government and
private grants.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't agree with Lewis' view of vivisection, don't
be fooled into thinking that all research on animals is meant to
save human lives. It seems that experimenters dream up new
``research'' in order to pay their mortgages. They have rotated
kittens' eyeballs, then made them jump from a high platform onto a
plank in a pan of water (University of Oregon); sewn rabbits'
eyelids closed, chained them in stocks, shocked them and given them
LSD (University of Maryland); shocked squirrel monkeys in
fear-conditioning chambers (Stanford University); shocked rats'
feet until the animals reached a pathetic state of ``learned
helplessness,'' and scalded their tails with hot water (University
of North Carolina); harnessed cats fitted with ``cranial implants''
to treadmills and subjected them to tail and paw shocks, producing
loud cries and ``excessive struggling''; and on and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   C.S. Lewis warned in the ``The Screwtape Letters'' that
worldliness can gradually corrupt a person's soul. I think he would
say that experimenters have become corrupt to their very essence.
But what would he say about those who accept this wholesale torture
by remaining silent on the issue?
</P>
<P>
   I think Lewis would be pleased if the scholars who traveled to
Oxford and Cambridge to honor his work chose to pay attention to
his view of animals and experimentation. I think he would be
pleased if we all did. It would go a long way toward renewing the
soul of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Carla Bennett is senior writer for People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals, 501 Front St., Norfolk, Va. 23510.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
