<HEADLINE>
WHAT PRICE MAUGHAM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's how Howard Gotlieb, the always amusing director of Boston
University's Special Collections library, explains his heterodox
collecting tastes: ``Yale got the 18th century, Harvard got the
19th century. That left me the 20th century.'' So Gotlieb has been
gobbling up the ephemera of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Through Gotlieb _ who does not like the nickname I once assigned
him, ``The Vacuum Cleaner'' _ BU has acquired a ragtag collection
of stuff: a Carl Hiaasen manuscript, Fred Astaire's dancing shoes,
and works from Hank Ketcham, creator of Dennis the Menace. As I
write, Gotlieb is assembling a trove of ``documents'' from Shirley
MacLaine. (To be fair, the university also has huge archives from
Martin Luther King and Albert Einstein.) Just recently, Gotlieb
came away with something of genuine literary merit: one of the
largest collections of Somerset Maugham letters and manuscripts
ever sold.
</P>
<P>
   Gotlieb is boasting that he got quite a deal, and he did. Don't
ask me why, but among collectors of first editions and literary
artifacts, Maugham is ``out.'' James Joyce, Graham Greene, Agatha
Christie, and the like still command high prices. But at Sotheby's
huge Maugham sale, several prize items found no buyers, including a
draft manuscript of his autobiography and a letter in which the
homosexual Maugham accuses his wife of ``terrorizing'' him.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding surreptitiously by phone from his office in Boston,
Gotlieb bought five major lots containing hundreds of Maugham
letters and documents for under $200,000. Says Sotheby's Vice
President Marsha Malinowski, ``He got some very good buys for BU.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for a Maugham exhibit in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whatever happened to ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newton's own Melanie Thistle? Readers with medium-term memories
will recall that the 28-year-old Thistle was sacked from her job at
Waltham's National Managed Health Care Congress when she asked for
a day off to raise money for the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute by
running in the Boston Marathon. (A Dana-Farber doctor had treated
Thistle's mother.)
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, things turned out fine for Thistle. After I
wrote about her plight, she was deluged with media calls. I gave
her one free piece of public relations advice: Return the call from
the Associated Press, which services every news outlet in the
country. She did, and moments later I saw her on the ``Today'' show
with Matt Lauer.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the exposure, Thistle says she raised an additional
$5,000 for Dana-Farber. She also received over 100 offers for job
interviews and now has a job with a company that promotes
health-care programs. What about the guy who fired her? NMHCC
executive Steve Toman didn't return my call.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Can Jaguars swim? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of mall developer Steve Weiner's most alluring new
investments _ the gorgeous remodeling of 27 Commonwealth Ave.,
which was once a dormitory for nurses at Mass. General _ is under
water. Well, the garage took on several feet of water during the
June floods, ``impacting'' (my word, not theirs) some luxury cars
parked there. Everyone assures me that new pumps have been
installed, which should forestall any future water damage under the
building. The nurses are long gone, and 27 Comm has been broken up
into four multimillion-dollar condos, one of them Weiner's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Kay two, ascending
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Christian Science Monitor editor Kay Fanning has holed up
in Anchorage to work on a memoir of her years in journalism. It
could be quite a tale, rivaling or even outstripping the recently
published autobiography of journalism's Other Katharine, Ms. Graham
of Washington Post renown.
</P>
<P>
   Once the wife of jillionaire Marshall Field Jr., Fanning hied
off to Alaska in 1965, bought the Anchorage Daily News, and married
Chicago newspaper editor Larry Fanning. After her husband's death
in 1971, Fanning ran the Anchorage paper and won a Pulitzer Prize.
A convert to Christian Science, she left Alaska in 1983 to become
editor of the Monitor for five tumultuous years. Fanning may have
some scores to settle with former Christian Science bigwigs, but I
doubt she will use her memoir to that end. That's not what Science
is about, and that's not what Kay Fanning is about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
