<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-VINEYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINEYARD STILL OFFERS SOME HAVENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VINEYARD HAVEN, Mass. _ ``Is that the Black Dog?'' the girl asks
her mother as they wait near the ferry dock where an old Labrador
retriever is cooling off with a harbor swim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is,'' says the mother as the rotund old canine,
wearing a red kerchief, slowly emerges from the water and shakes
off unapologetically. ``That's the Black Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Here we are in the heart of darkness. The belly of the beast.
And, paying $20 for a T-shirt with a black lab on the front. The
bite here is definitely worse than the bark.
</P>
<P>
   This is the other end of Martha's Vineyard, the plainer side.
The story here is about how a quaint, dry (alcohol-free) village
with one restaurant, some oil tanks, and an authentic wooden
boatworks produced the hippest logo at this or any summer resort.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the T-shirt and logo make Vineyard Haven a hipper
place than upper-crust Edgartown, which plays these days like a
maritime mansion theme park with no parking.
</P>
<P>
   And hey, wasn't that Margaret Thatcher and Nancy Reagan lunching
aboard Malcolm Forbes's old yacht the other day not far from where
Shenandoah and Alabama _ Vineyard Haven's resident schooners _ are
moored?
</P>
<P>
   As logos go, you have to look to Vermont, to Ben &AMP; Jerry's
dappled cows, to find the Black Dog's equal, and aside from Maine's
rather generic boiled lobster (usually shown on a place mat with a
bed of fries), there's nothing even close anywhere in New England
to the Black Dog.
</P>
<P>
   Which is nothing to brag about, except in the Chamber of
Commerce sense. For it was not that many years ago that Martha's
Vineyard rang in the ears of outdoors folks as something close to
paradise. It was a laid-back but quite civilized island with a
serene feel and a modest offer of the best fishing, swimming,
biking, boating, beaching in all of New England. (No, not golf. You
would not come to the Vineyard for the golf any more than you would
the food, says an island newspaper friend.)
</P>
<P>
   But now all of New York and much of Washington have discovered
the island and pounce on it heavily each August, with the real
ooomph coming next week with the Clinton entourage. Which is why
some restaurants (sorry, ristorantes) on the island charge $7 each
for an a la carte salad and baked potato to go with your $27
entree.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for Martha's Vineyard outdoor purists who watch with
dismay the traffic jams that mimic Callahan Tunnel mayhem, there
are essences of the old Vineyard to be found in hidden pockets.
</P>
<P>
   As a general guideline, you will be happier, freer, and find
access to almost everything without a car on the Vineyard. Take or
rent bikes instead; a small boat is ideal.
</P>
<P>
   BEACHERS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Forget South Beach with its crowds, undertow, and vicious
riptides. There are alternatives, though some get a little tricky
because so many of the island's beaches are closed to the public.
Here are a few of the best swimming and sunbathing beaches on the
island, which are best accessed by bikers or hikers.
</P>
<P>
   _Find the westerly back road route (get a map) from Vineyard
Haven to Tashmoo Lake. The tide flows through a pair of jetties,
and on the near side is a white sand beach overlooking Vineyard
Sound with clean, lovely swimming. Or, just before reaching Tashmoo
along the packed dirt road from town, take the right fork to
another spot on the same shore, Wilfred Pond.
</P>
<P>
   _On the other side of Vineyard Haven Harbor, ride Beach Road
heading toward Oak Bluffs. About a quarter of a mile past the
Lagoon Pond drawbridge, take a left down the public way to the
beach. Clean swimming and fine beaching in a fairly secluded spot.
</P>
<P>
   _In Oak Bluffs, ride down East Chop Drive past the boat club and
onto the sand. Plunk down on the beach near the jetty to the north
side of the Oak Bluffs Harbor channel. This is clean, fast-moving
water, and the beach is soft (few rocks), and sandy white.
</P>
<P>
   _East Beach in Edgartown. This beach is secluded and often empty
because it takes some effort to get there. This long sweep of beach
in the Wasque Point Reservation can give you privacy on a white
sand beach and clean, fast-moving Nantucket Sound water that seems
impossible on the crowded Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   HIKERS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Even though the ugliest element on the Vineyard is the auto
traffic, once you're a few yards off the beaten track on any of the
several nature trails, the world really does fade away. The effort
to preserve the island's wilderness has been serious and effective.
Start with a conservation map of the Vineyard and try the following
walks:
</P>
<P>
   _Chappaquiddick, the southeast barrier island on the Vineyard,
is easy to reach by ferry and has 700 acres of refuge land that
draws all manner of shore birds and inland residents such as wild
turkey. Wasque Reservation and Cape Pogue Wildlife Refuge will keep
you busy all day, with a nearby beach to finish with a swim.
</P>
<P>
   _West Chop Woods, off Franklin Street in Vineyard Haven, has 80
acres.
</P>
<P>
   _Menemsha Hills Reservation, off North Road in Chilmark,
features 200 acres of varied upland terrain, including the beach on
the southwest shore.
</P>
<P>
   _Long Point Wildlife Refuge, on Waldron Bottom Road in West
Tisbury, is a tract with more than 600 wilderness acres.
</P>
<P>
   In all cases, use the maps available at the ferry dock and most
of the above outdoor alternatives _ and many more _ will give you a
good sense of the Vineyard before it became the hippest take in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   And again, do everyone a favor, including yourself, and leave
the car home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
