<SLUG> BC-NY-TUNNEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATERING THE APPLE: TUNNEL IS FOR THE AGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Deep beneath the Earth's surface _ 60 stories deep _
the workers in Shaft Number 19-B drill through some of the hardest
bedrock that anyone has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Around the clock, in three shifts of eight hours, they are
building New York's City Water Tunnel Number 3, a $6 billion,
60-mile-long bit of urban infrastructure that officials say ranks
as the largest construction project in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The first segment of the tunnel, which spans 13 miles, was
turned on to great fanfare Thursday, gushing forth water at a
pressure of 350 pounds per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   When finished, about 20 years from now, the tunnel will not only
be the longest in the world, but will complete one of the world's
most massive engineering marvels _ yet, being entirely underground,
perhaps also the least-noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often ask New Yorkers if they know where their water comes
from,'' said Joel A. Miele, commissioner of the Department of
Environmental Protection, which runs the tunnel and all the city's
water projects. ``No more than 6 to 8 percent have the slightest
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The water for all three tunnels _ Tunnels Number 1 and 2 were
built in 1917 and 1936, respectively _ comes from as far as 125
miles away, north of the city, coaxed out of the Croton, Delaware
and Catskill Reservoirs along the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   Wending through an elaborate system of aqueducts, tunnels, and
smaller reservoirs, the water streams into Yonkers, down through
the Bronx, then off through various other tunnels and pipes into
Manhattan, Queens, Brooklyn, and Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Tunnels Number 1 and 2 carry, together, 1.5 billion gallons of
water a day _ 95 percent of it without any pumps, flowing along by
simple force of gravity.
</P>
<P>
   New York City consumes nearly every drop of this water. This led
officials to start planning a third tunnel as far back as the
mid-1950s. Not until 1970 did construction begin _ and not until
2020 is it expected to end.
</P>
<P>
   Shaft 19-B, plunging 672 feet below a far-flung industrial site
in a decrepit area along the Brooklyn-Queens border, leads into a
stretch of Tunnel Number 3's Second Stage, which is not due to come
on line for seven years or so.
</P>
<P>
   A few reporters were allowed down in the shaft Wednesday
afternoon between shifts. The narrow elevator takes two minutes to
hit bottom. (The ride back up is three minutes.) Then you step out
into a vast cavern dug out from the rock.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing remotely claustrophobic about the space, a
cylinder 23 feet in diameter. A constant flow of air is pumped
through a huge tube on the ceiling. Smaller pipes on the walls
carry water. Railroad tracks have been laid on the floor, to bring
the workers to the outer reaches of their drilling, now three miles
away from the shaft. Conveyor belts stretch overhead, carrying the
busted-up rocks back up to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Tunnel Number 3 has taken the lives of 23 workers in its 28
years of construction, but all but one of the deaths were caused by
accidents typical of industrial projects _ falls, electrocutions,
collapsing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   No one fears a cave-in of the tunnel itself. The rock that
surrounds it was formed 450 million years ago, long before life
began on this planet. It's as solid as anything. But just in case,
eight-foot-long bolts have been hammered into the arc of the
cylinder, the tunnel's ceiling, for extra stability.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the life-support gear and the constant clanking of
the pump and the chugging of the motor, the scene feels like
another planet. The ground is muddy like clay. The walls are
craggly, made of a rock that nobody has ever seen before.
</P>
<P>
   The rough sections of the tunnel were created the old-fashioned
way _ by sandhogs, as the workers called themselves, wielding
dynamite and hand drills.
</P>
<P>
   Then you approach a newer area _ built in just the past two
years _ when the workers were given the Tunnel-Boring Machine, a
110-foot-long, worm-like device, spinning 50 huge cutters on a
rotating head, that digs into the rock with 3.5 million pounds of
thrust, capable of pushing forward at a rate of 15 feet per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The cylinders that the machine have dug out are smooth and
symmetrical. One finished section, which has been lined with
concrete, glistens in the arc lights. The project's resident
engineer, Ami Mukherjee, seemed jaded by the effect. ``That's what
concrete looks like when it's wet,'' he said nonchalantly. But,
seen for the first time, it seems surreally spectacular, like a
high-tech aircraft-hangar that somehow wound up on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Shaft 19-B is twice as deep as any part of the city's first two
water tunnels, but even it stops short of Tunnel Number 3's deepest
point _ an area under Roosevelt Island, just east of Manhattan,
that goes 780 feet underground.
</P>
<P>
   That segment of the tunnel is part of the 13-mile stretch that
opened Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, according to Commissioner Miele, Tunnel Number 3,
First Phase, has been flowing with water for three weeks now. ``You
can't expect us to have opening ceremonies without making sure it's
all right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in New York City these days, no official event happens until
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani declares it so. The mayor made the
pronouncement Thursday at a grand ceremony near the Central Park
reservoir, with fireworks, music and, earlier in the day, a
memorial service for those who died while building the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Like cracking a champagne bottle to commemorate the launching of
a ship, Giuliani turned on a spigot that activated an 80-foot-high
fountain _ and, thus was Water Tunnel Number 3 deemed officially
open.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Park fountain was first turned on in 1917, with the
opening of Tunnel Number 1, but was immediately turned off and
forgotten about. City officials rediscovered it just six months
ago, hooked its pipes up to Tunnel Number 3, and decided to turn it
on again for symbolic effect.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani liked the idea so much, he decided to keep the fountain
gushing all the time, as a publicly visible monument to the maze of
metal and mud carved through the prehistoric rock down under.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
