<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTONS-SWORD-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOSTON PUBLIC GARDEN, THE THIEF IS MIGHTIER THAN THE SWORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ General George Washington cuts an imposing figure as he
sits astride his prancing warhorse in the Public Garden. Proud,
patriotic, determined to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, the father of our country can't hold on to his
sword.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Charlestown sculptor Thomas Ball completed the bronze
statue in 1869, Washington's sword has been ``liberated'' many
times by pranksters and petty vandals.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the thefts have become so routine that the latest
sword, installed last month, is made of plastic and expected to be
only a temporary adornment.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long it will stay this time is a matter of speculation,''
said Henry Lee, president of the Friends of the Public Garden, with
a slight laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was perhaps a rite of passage for fraternities or some such
groups to climb up and take the sword. I think it's probably been
removed many dozens of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington has faced other assaults at his post near Arlington
Street and Commonwealth Avenue. Whitewash was used to deface the
statue about a half-dozen years ago, and flourescent paint has been
used periodically to highlight the horse's undercarriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't a public monument and very valuable, it might be
very funny,'' said Fran Beatty, senior landscape architect for the
city's historic parks.
</P>
<P>
   But as embarrassing as the flourescent touch-up is, holding on
to the sword is a bigger problem for Washington, who undoubtedly
had no such trouble when he assumed command of the Continental Army
in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's plight is shared by the nearby likeness of Civil
War hero Robert Gould Shaw, commander of the gallant 54th
Massachusetts Regiment, the Union's first black infantry unit. &UR;  &LR; 
Shaw's sword, part of Augustus Saint-Gaudens' masterpiece memorial
on Boston Common, has been as popular as Washington's as a prize
for pilferers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told people at the Washington statue and the Shaw
memorial that they better look fast, because the sword might not be
there next time,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the original bronze sword held across Washington's
body has had a succession of inferior reincarnations of wood and
plastic. At one time, Lee said, a Boston Art Commission official
kept several replacement swords, waiting for their call to arms,
stacked behind his desk.
</P>
<P>
   City park officials are skittish about describing how the swords
are attached to the sculptures. But it is clear that welding them
in place is not the preferred option. If the choices are no sword
or a nub of a sword, the former seems preferable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way bronze is cast, the sword had to be a separate item
and inserted to make it look realistic,'' Beatty said. Since the
thefts began, she said, the city has faced this difficult question:
``Do you fasten it so hard so it can't be taken off, and does that
set yourself up for someone who is very determined?''
</P>
<P>
   The patrons of the Public Garden know about determination. In
December 1988, a thief used an acetylene torch to separate a bronze
duckling from his mother and siblings at the other end of the park.
</P>
<P>
   The theft caused an uproar among Bostonians who had become
enamored of the sculpted tribute to Robert McCloskey's children's
book ``Make Way for Ducklings.'' To the rescue came bartenders
Eddie Doyle of the Bull and Finch Pub and Tommy Leonard of the
Eliot Lounge, who launched a button campaign that raised $5,000 and
replaced the Nancy Schon statue only four months later.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of misguided persistence occurred in the Fens'
Rose Garden, where someone lopped off the hands from a carrara
marble statue. A new, graceful pair of hands have been attached to
``Desconsol,'' said Mildred Farrell, director of the city-funded
Boston Art Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Such vandalism is difficult to stop, officials said. Park
rangers do not patrol 24 hours a day, and police have more
important duties than keeping an all-night eye on Washington and
his sculpted brethren.
</P>
<P>
   And, truth be told, Bostonians behave quite well toward their
statuary. ``Generally, the monuments are much respected by the
public and there is surprisingly little vandalism,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   The same attitude applies to the Public Garden as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '70s, things were very bad. Several small statues were
stolen; vandalism was rife,'' Lee said. ``But we have had better
work by the Parks Department, the Friends of the Public Garden
deserve some credit, and the public deserves a good deal of credit,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few places in our country, or any country, that are
open 24 hours a day, unprotected, and greatly used. I think the
public in Boston is remarkably caring about their Garden.''
</P>
<P>
   And remarkably affectionate toward certain pieces of public art:
the Red Auerbach statue in Quincy Market, for example, and the
Boston Massacre monument on the Common.
</P>
<P>
   Both objects tend to be touched so often that their surfaces
have been rubbed shiny. On the Common, the outstretched hand of one
massacre victim is considered lucky by many passersby.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee, whose group also helps preserve the Common's monuments,
is not concerned about such wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's love, not vandalism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if it's possible to love a sword _ but not too much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
