<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-STELLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STELLA' MOVES TO AN EASY GROOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
HOW STELLA GOT HER GROOVE BACK 
Directed by: Kevin Rodney Sullivan 
Screenplay by: Terry McMillan &AMP; Ron Bass (based on McMillan's
novel) 
Starring: Angela Bassett, Whoopi Goldberg, Taye Diggs, Regina King,
Suzzanne Douglas, Michael J. Pagan 
Running time: 116 minutes 
Rated: R (language and some sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glossy romantic fantasy doesn't get any glossier than ``How
Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' Terry McMillan's slick and seductive
if not quite soulful semi-autobiographical follow-up to ``Waiting
to Exhale.'' Like her first novel-to-film, this one is dedicated to
the proposition that upmarket black visibility has been
ridiculously lacking in films from the Hollywood assembly line. If
the first film showed Hollywood what it had been missing by letting
Angela Bassett floor it with a couple of equally high-powered
girlfriends, this one reminds us that she can carry a film herself,
with a little help from the Jamaica Tourist Board, a hunky but
sensitive newcomer with a dazzling smile, and a string of sassy
one-liners from Whoopi Goldberg in a sidekick role.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some movie queens, Bassett projects warmth and dignity as
well as beauty. She has an enticing way of smiling a slow-release
smile inspired by some secret that is being kept private _ except
from us in the audience. The film does ask us to make a few
longer-than-usual leaps. The first is that Bassett's high-powered
single mom and workaholic San Francisco financial district diva
would stop hawking bonds long enough to let one Jamaica tourism TV
commercial send her flying off to the Hop-py Island when she's
freed up by her son's annual two-weeker with his dad. She'd like a
little adventure, and the fact that she's accompanied by her
extremely frank girlfriend allows her to be perceived as the demure
one.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of comic misadventures involving two would-be
wild and crazy guys, Bassett's Stella finds she's being flirted
with at breakfast by a polite but definitely hunky young local.
She's appalled to find how young _ he's 20, she's 40. But with the
distinct possibility of a sexual reawakening in the air, she lets
herself be implored by the well-spoken young man. Nothing bursts
the bubble of this feel-good fantasy. It's the visual equivalent of
an easy-listening station. The young man is not only well-bred, but
intelligent, sensitive, and in some ways more mature than his
years. More to the point, we believe in the chemistry that begins
to emerge between Bassett and Taye Diggs's passionate but poised
romancer.
</P>
<P>
   We can believe in the gravitational pull between the two
characters _ and with a long-overdue difference. In a summer
hitherto largely devoted to older men getting much younger women,
this film reverses the pattern, frankly and amusingly turning
Diggs's playful yet essentially serious Winston Shakespeare into
the sex object here. It's a strategy that peaks in a shower scene
when Stella watches the unwitting Winston soaping up and finds she
can't resist opening the glass door and keeping him company. For
Diggs, this film debut represents a quantum leap forward from his
role as the landlord in the lugubrious musical ``Rent.'' His
gravity and his smile insure that we'll be seeing more of him.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, Winston just stands around with his face hanging
out while Stella undergoes the roller-coaster rides. She's called
to New York for a crisis, then finds, once home in Marin County,
that her company's sale to a larger one has suddenly left her
jobless. But while the script makes a pass at drama, there's never
any real conflict. It's all a bit too smooth and trouble-free, even
for a spun-sugar fantasy. There's the merest suggestion of sisterly
rivalry with Regina King's ambulance-driving, mouthy sibling,
Suzzanne Douglas's sister is worried that Stella's questionable
impulsiveness in pursuing a romance with a younger man will impede
her own progress in the upper middle class. Too bad, because the
three are funny when they go at one another.
</P>
<P>
   Things go conveniently smoothly with Stella's son, played with a
helpful down-to-earth quality by Michael J. Pagan. But the very
real complications of a matchup between Stella and Winston are
never really approached on a more than superficial level. Bassett
is the big reason ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' stays sweet
and warm and nothing but likable, and Diggs makes a highly engaging
debut.
</P>
<P>
   You're always aware that Stella and Winston seem to be reading
their lines from a travel brochure rather than real life. Kevin
Rodney Sullivan, making his own debut behind the camera, seems to
have settled for packaging the film rather than actually directing
it. You couldn't ask for prettier escapism, and Hollywood has never
prized reality. Still, ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' does seem
to spend a lot of its time waiting to inhale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
