<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-DO-RAGS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEADY DAYS FOR AN OLD SOCK-DRAWER STAPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's about as basic and black as you can get, and right
now, it's wrapped like a gauze skin around Sandler Lacoste's
low-cut, caramel-colored head.
</P>
<P>
   This is not _ he repeats, not _ your grandmother's do-rag.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always wore it for the waves,'' said Lacoste, a
Lexington High School freshman who plopped onto a park bench and
considered how a single piece of nylon cloth has evolved from a
hidden headpiece to an essential urban uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like me, I cut this from a stocking, to keep my waves in
check. But now, these other kids are wearin' them just to wear
them. 'Cause they wanna be with their boys. They wanna be hard. ...
Who knows why they do it?''
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Lacoste knows where do-rags have been, and he knows where
they're going.
</P>
<P>
   He's not happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   They always served a function _ to cover rollers at night, keep
curls in place, and enhance the natural wave buried in thick black
locks. But the do-rag, that cut-up piece of worn stocking that came
from the deep recesses of a forgotten sock drawer, has become a
fashion statement on the street corners of many neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the headgear has spawned sleeker, skullcap models of
itself, in brand names like Nike and Tommy Hilfiger. They come with
strings in the back and without. They come in different colors,
naturally, to match with different outfits.
</P>
<P>
   It's gotten to the point where youths like Lacoste and his
friends are being forced to revert to the old style before it
became a new style _ stealing hose from a sister's drawer and
smoothing it over their heads _ just to maintain their dignity
against the slaves to street fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people started wearing it outside for function, and
everyone else started following it just to do it,'' said Jonathan
Rogers, 14, whose do-rag stretched from his head like a ratty
Christmas stocking. ``Then they started making them in blue, red,
white, you name it. It's all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   For David Kong, owner of Mattapan Discount Hair &AMP; Beauty,
granny's old rag has turned into a $200-a-week moneymaker. In a
beauty shop where almost all women shoppers wade through huge bins
of hair accessories and endless aisles of shampoo, men dominate the
do-rag business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every guy who comes in here buys at least one or two
packs of them,'' said Kong. ``Older guys, younger guys. It's just
the style. That's what happens when one famous person starts
wearing it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Phillip remembers when it was just a woman thing. He also
remembers when men started wearing it at night, or just before they
were getting ready to go out. But he has no idea why something so
functional at its core has turned into fashion on a brand-name
scale. All he knows is, it works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only good reason to wear something like that tied around
your head in public is to keep your hair neat,'' said Phillip, 23.
``I need it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
