<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFINITI G20 A MUCH IMPROVED LOW-END LUXURY MODEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, August 16, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Japanese automakers took aim at the American luxury-car
market, they followed the dictum of an American general who had
advised ``Hit 'em where they ain't'' as sound strategy. And where
the Americans were absent in the luxury car battle was in the
fields of quality control and customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern was repeated by Honda (Acura), Toyota (Lexus) and
Nissan (Infiniti). Don't just make a luxury Honda/Toyota/Nissan;
create a whole new luxury division, open separate showrooms and
dedicate the sales and service forces to customer satisfaction.
And, by the way, sell at a ridiculously low price while offering
ridiculously extravagant service so as to capture market share _
the Japanese understand market share.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers had to commit to new showrooms, lots of money and
training programs. But, dealers make a living on a complex
assortment of business _ used-car sales, service and repair,
aftermarket stuff _ not just new-car sales. In fact, for many, the
cutthroat competition for new-car business can thin gross profit
margins to a losing proposition. What to do?
</P>
<P>
   The answer for all three, it seems, was to become ``full-line''
divisions offering not just the top-drawer luxury boats _ the
Legend, Lexus and Q45 models _ but adding entry-level and
mid-priced luxury cars, sporty luxury cars ... you see the
oxymorons here? Entry-level luxury? Just what is that?
</P>
<P>
   A very real problem with this approach is that the low rungs
added to the luxury ladder tend to compete with the upper rungs of
the mother division _ Infiniti's G20, for example, is up against
Nissan's Maxima. It's cannibalism, creating another model line to
devour sales of the original line. The early G20 was pretty much a
well-dressed Sentra, something akin to what Cadillac Cimmarron was
to Chevy Cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the pitfalls, the Japanese made it work. Nissan has its
problems, but Nissan/Infiniti is still a major presence in the
American market. And the G20 is still around, too _ which brings us
to the point of all this.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not certain that the G20 is the answer to anybody's luxury
fantasies, but it is a vastly improved automobile over its earlier
incarnations, stylish, well-appointed, comfortable with a real back
seat. The performance is a wee bit anemic _ it is sadly eclipsed in
that department by its Nissan cousin, Maxima, which falls in the
same price range.
</P>
<P>
   The G20 for 1999 comes with a 140-horsepower, 16-valve,
2.0-liter I-4 engine coupled with a 5-speed, manual gearbox, and a
cloth interior for $20,995 nicely equipped. A fancier touring
model, the G20t, is $22,495 with manual shift _ all prices plus
$495 delivery. A four-speed automatic adds $800 to either model; a
leather package that includes a moonroof is $1,700 on the base,
$1,200 more on the G20t. Alone the moonroof is a $950 extra; heated
seats at $420 complete the option list.
</P>
<P>
   The new G20 may be ``entry level,'' but as an Infiniti it is no
bottom feeder. It at least looks like an Infiniti on the outside,
with a grille that proclaims its claim on the family name and nice
lines. You might even say it's elegant for a small car.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, there is no doubt about heritage, no mistake about the
luxury intent. The tested G20t was finished in leather, trimmed
with expensive veneer, abounding in small bits of elegance. But
what really made it for me was the rear _ it has room for adults
and underway does not induce mal de mer. That alone is a
significant improvement over the original effort.
</P>
<P>
   That original G20 of memory was a tight fit _ small door to
squeeze through, no kneeroom, not a lot of headroom, either. And
the suspension was tough, with the ride characteristic of a
buckboard or a Morgan _ stiff _ and a ``busy-ness'' that induced
nausea.
</P>
<P>
   So I made it a point to ride in the back of the new G20t that
Nissan insisted was ``much improved,'' albeit with a solid axle and
multilink rear suspension rather than the independent arrangement
used on other Nissan models. Maybe old stuff rides better than new
technology sometimes. For once, a car company was right to say
``much improved.'' The new G20 is a pleasant vehicle on a bad road
even after a big lunch, and there is decent legroom even with the
front seats pushed all the way rearward on the track.
</P>
<P>
   But much improved doesn't mean it's leapfrogged the competition
_ or even caught up. The G20t optioned approaches the other guys'
entry level models in appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, gauges are clear, controls fairly well laid out _
although the radio does not have the knobs this columnist favors,
at least the buttons and bars were reasonably big. And it is a Bose
system with CD player and tape deck. Window switches and mirror
controls were handy.
</P>
<P>
   A small covered bin conceals removable cupholders; small glove
box, door bins, and seat pockets offer some interior storage. The
car comes with a fair-sized trunk, but the opening is a bit small
if you're contemplating bulky stuff. In addition to front air bags,
the G20 also comes with side air bags for a bit more protection and
4-wheel antilock brakes. So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   The tested car came with a smooth, five-speed, manual transaxle,
but the engine is disappointingly tame, even with the stick.
Acceleration is OK, but don't bother trying to pass in fifth gear.
Think twice before attempting it in fourth. No, shift down to third
as you squeeze the pedal to the floor and demand everything it can
give _ which will be enough but not really impressive. The G20t
comes with a spoiler, an accouterment of performance, usually _ in
this case it might be considered false advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The handling is more than competent. This is no sports car, but
it corners well, grips the curves, proved nimble in traffic and
steady in evasive maneuvers. Fuel mileage was pretty good; the G20t
delivered 25.67 miles per gallon in varied driving over 675 miles
charted.
</P>
<P>
   Infiniti blathers on in the ads about European heritage, and one
supposes some people will buy into that, and a lot of them will
never know the difference. This is not a premier luxury/performance
sedan. The G20t is a taste of luxury, not the whole meal. It offers
an Infiniti badge at Nissan prices, comfort, room, style, good
handling and ride, and a bit more than adequate performance _
budget luxury.
</P>
<P>
   I give the G20t a thumbs up ... mostly. Understand that in the
G20 line Infiniti is promising a bit more than it really delivers _
and if you insist on getting that Euro-pizazz you thought was
promised, they'll offer you an I30.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
