<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-AIRBUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AIR BUD' SEQUEL SHY OF A GOLDEN ACHIEVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
AIR BUD: GOLDEN RECEIVER 
Directed by: Richard Martin 
Screenplay by: Paul Tamasy and Aaron Mendelsohn 
Starring: Kevin Zegers, Gregory Harrison, Cynthia Stevenson, Nora
Dunn, Perry Anzilotti, and Robert Costanzo 
Running time: 91 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Beethoven''/``Bad News Bears'' formula that helped concoct
last year's successful family film ``Air Bud'' is tinkered with
only slightly in ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver,'' the second in what
the producers promise will be a series of
sport-playing-dog-saves-the-day movies.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy is now a two-sport player, adding football to his
basketball skills. The golden retriever still has a knack for
helping fatherless Josh (Kevin Zegers) find his way through junior
high school life and he's again pursued by evil-doers, two Russian
circus animal wranglers who replace the first movie's sleazy clown.
This time around, Buddy adds a touch of matchmaking to his athletic
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   When Josh takes Buddy to the vet for a checkup, Patrick Sullivan
(Gregory Harrison) makes instant friends with the needle-shy dog
and it's clear that their shared love of yogurt will lead to
romance between Sullivan and Josh's widowed mom Jackie (Cynthia
Stevenson). And almost as fast as you can say 101 Dalmatians, Buddy
pulls a rollerblading Jackie down the boat dock where Patrick is
tending his boat and into his arms.
</P>
<P>
   As the romance grows, Josh grows anguished about his loyalty to
his late father and his mother's new happiness. He decides it's
best to be away from the house more often, and so he goes out for
the football team. Just as in the first movie, Josh is practicing
when he discovers Buddy has a talent: this time instead of shooting
baskets, it's playing wide receiver. Josh becomes the hapless
team's backup quarterback, only to get called into the first game
when the starter goes down for the season with a shoulder injury.
After a disastrous first play, Josh goes back to pass again, fires
deep and, of course, Buddy appears to catch the ball and run to the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   With Buddy now the team's offensive and defensive star (just
like the pros, his tackles low and goes for the ball), the
Fernfield Junior High team is on its way to the Washington state
finals. But there are hurdles for both the team and the blooming
romance between Jackie and Patrick. Josh, suspicious of Patrick,
finds photos of him with other women. Then, just before the big
game, the Russian circus duo finally capture Buddy to star in their
show.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian duo is homage to Boris and Natasha from the Rocky
and Bullwinkle cartoons, with Nora Dunn's Natalya sounding like
Natasha on helium. Natalya and Popov (Perry Anzilotti), other than
providing plot advancement, are there just for John Hughes' ``Home
Alone''-like physical comedy, and really don't provide the same
tension that the first movie's clown created.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver'' suffers a bit when compared to the
first ``Air Bud.'' While Zegers is wholesomely appealing as Josh
and Harrison is fine as the love interest/emerging father figure,
this story lacks an engaging character like the Bill
Russell-lookalike electrician/coach from the first movie. But
despite its more predictable storyline, ``Air Bud: Golden
Receiver'' will appeal to those looking for that too-rare family
movie. At one advance screening, kids 5 and up seemed more able to
sit through it than those younger. For those with younger kids,
consider waiting for what we'd propose as the third installment,
when Buddy learns baseball: ``Air Bud: Golden Reliever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
