<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-KORN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KORN FEEDS THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have witnessed the Clinton campaign, the Dole campaign, and
the Dukakis campaign. Now comes the Korn campaign _ a populist rock
'n' roll assault led by the ear-splitting, heavy-metal 'n' rap band
Korn, which aims to bypass normal media outlets and create a direct
pipeline to its fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Korn campaign is going to be insane,'' says Korn singer
Jonathan Davis. ``We got a private jet and we'll do a spoof on
campaigning and stuff. And we'll have press conferences and take
questions from fans. We're just bringing our music to the kids.
We'll hang out with them and find out their concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Korn _ the screamingly intense, no-holds-barred California band
that sings about dysfunctional families and general societal
outcasts _ has a new album, ``Follow the Leader,'' which is another
part of the campaign. It's a totally in-your-face, often
outstanding, follow-up to their multiplatinum, Grammy-nominated,
and viciously ironic ``Life Is Peachy'' disc.
</P>
<P>
   Korn's men-of-the-people marketing scheme includes a series of
in-store appearances around the nation. These events are a prelude
to the band's ``Family Values'' tour, which includes fellow misfits
Limp Bizkit, Ice Cube, and Orgy (the first band on Korn's new
record label, Elementree). (Rob Zombie was also on the bill, but
dropped out after a dispute between the managers of the two groups.
``Our band has nothing against Rob, but his manager was being a
(jerk). He was trying to have creative control of our tour,'' says
Davis.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the tour:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a revolving stage and do songs with Limp Bizkit and
Ice Cube,'' says Davis, whose group used these acts on album tracks
that assault your ears with out-on-the-fringe irreverence. One new
track is ``All in the Family,'' a rapping battle royale between
Davis and Fred Durst of Limp Bizkit. Durst gets in his shots
(``halitosis is the only thing you're rocking steady,'' he says to
Davis), but Davis nails him in return. ``You look like one of those
dancers in the Hanson video,'' Davis raps. And this is just the
printable stuff. There are many other exchanges that, shall we say,
hit below the belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just me and him ragging on each other,'' says Davis,
laughing. ``Some kids think that Korn and Limp Bizkit hate each
other. But hey, why we would be in the same room talking to each
other if we hated each other? We have total respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, the song was for B Real of Cypress Hill,'' adds
Davis. ``But his record label wouldn't let him do it. I'm glad,
because this came out way better.''
</P>
<P>
   Outlaw rapper Ice Cube was brought in for ``Children of the
Korn,'' a new tune that may be the heaviest song that Korn has ever
recorded _ and that's saying something, given the band's reputation
for sledgehammer riffs mixed with techno sound effects and
over-the-top shrieks and death-rattle moans from Davis. Cube's
contribution is also blistering. He angrily raps that ``we're not
taking no more guff,'' followed by some four-letter words that
would stop Tipper Gore in her tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice Cube came in and listened to the song, then wrote his
lyrics. He's so professional that it's insane. He did his thing in
two takes,'' says Davis. ``And he was totally into it. He started
screaming and really going off. He said, `I want some of this
(stuff) on my record.' He was so happy. And that guy is like an
idol to us, from the days he was with N.W.A. He's the one hip-hop
artist we all like. We tend to like different kinds of hip-hop, but
we all have Ice Cube's albums.'' (Korn returned the favor by
backing up Ice Cube on the song ``Should I Stay or Should I Go''
for the upcoming Clash tribute album, and by playing on three songs
for Ice Cube's next solo disc.)
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Follow the Leader'' is Korn's third album _ and a
pivotal one, in Davis's eyes. ``The third album is really
crucial,'' he says. ``We're over the sophomore jinx. But I think
that the third album is more important than the second one. If it's
good, you're set for the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   It's good, make no mistake about that, but it's not for the
squeamish. There's one song, ``Pretty,'' about a 12-month-old girl
raped and killed by her father. It's a true story, based on Davis's
former experience as a coroner in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an image that has haunted me ever since I saw it,'' says
Davis. ``There are a lot of memories that haunt me from that place,
but this one more than anything. And I always wanted to write a
song about it. I tried back on the first Korn album, but it didn't
work out. I just couldn't put it into words.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and his band mates _ Fieldy on bass, James ``Munky''
Shaffer on guitar, Brian ``Head'' Welch on guitar, and the simply
named David on drums _ aren't totally obsessed with the dark side
of life, however. Another new song, ``Seed,'' talks about Davis's
2-year-old son, Nathan, and yearns for the innocence of that age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take him to Disneyland and see his face light up. I want to
have that feeling again of being a kid,'' he says. ``I want to be
innocent again. I don't want to be a stressed-out (adult).''
</P>
<P>
   Davis lavishes attention on Nathan and even plays Korn's music
for him, which might horrify some parents. ``My little baby listens
to the stuff every day. He screams and has fun. It's awesome,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Davis endured a rough childhood with a stepmother he blasted on
earlier Korn albums. ``We don't even say her name anymore,'' he
notes today, adding that his father has since remarried. ``The No.1
thing that screwed me up in life was her. But everything is cool in
my family now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Korn has succeeded despite meager help from MTV, which is often
reluctant to play a ``heavy rock band,'' says Davis. But that may
change with the band's new single, ``Got the Life,'' a fast-paced
guitar tune that has been lighting up modern-rock radio stations
and may force MTV's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``MTV is now begging us for a video,'' Davis says. ``So we're
doing a video. What the heck, all it can do is help us. It can't
hurt us. We'll give it to them and see what happens. We'll see if
they finally give us some love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
