<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTIVE-REUNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ EXECUTIVE SUITE HAS A DIGITAL LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the old days at Digital Equipment Corp., executives who fell
out of favor with the computer maker's legendary founder, Kenneth
Olsen, were banished to a small, nondescript office insiders dubbed
``the penalty box.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Olsen hadn't fired them _ they were typically assigned
to ``special projects'' _ most understood their careers at Digital
were over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sat there until you got bored and quit,'' observed &UR;  &LR; Terry
Shannon of Ashland, an independent consultant and longtime Digital
watcher who writes a newsletter about the company. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A few of those who were banished stuck it out at Digital _
outlasting Olsen, who was forced out in 1992 _ while
others &UR;  &LR; eventually ended up at Compaq Computer Corp., the
fast-growing, Houston-based PC company that acquired Digital two
months ago. &UR;  &LR; Now a handful of these refugees &UR;  &LR; find themselves
sharing Compaq's executive suite with other Digital alumni who were
picked for Compaq's top management after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Call them survivors. Whether it's because of the merger or the
vagaries of corporate politics, there's a sizable Digital alumni
club running Compaq, the world's No. 2 computer maker. Their common
bond is that they all made the move &UR;  &LR; from a fallen computer giant
to a &UR;  &LR; rising technology star. Their climb at Compaq underscores the
fact that in the fast-changing world of technology, perhaps more
than in any other industry, reincarnation is always possible. &UR;  &LR;   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``You can sin from time to time and still come out a winner,
as long as you have the proper attributes,'' said Shannon. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Half of the 12 executives that Compaq chief executive Eckhard
Pfeiffer named to his senior management team after the merger are
Digital veterans _ a fact that Pfeiffer insists will help smooth
the transition as the companies are melded into one.
</P>
<P>
   Three of his new deputies _ John Rando, William Strecker and
Thomas Siekman _ are longtime Digital managers who took the direct
route to Compaq, joining when the deal was completed. (They were
the only members of the senior team of Robert B. Palmer, Olsen's
successor, &UR;  &LR;  who were retained by Compaq.)
</P>
<P>
   Three others _ John Rose, Enrico Pesatori and Earl Mason _ left
Digital in the 1990s after clashing with Olsen or Palmer &UR;  &LR; over the
company's direction. But their career paths, full of twists and
turns, also brought them to Compaq's top ranks, where, ironically,
they now have a bigger say in what was once the Digital empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it Rose's revenge,'' quipped one longtime Digital
employee.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who left Digital in 1992 after clashing with Olsen over
Digital's PC strategy, is now a senior vice president at Compaq in
charge of the enterprise computing group, which includes much of
the former Digital operations.
</P>
<P>
   Pesatori, 57, an Italian-born industry veteran who joined
Digital in 1993 and ran the company's computer systems division,
also has found career redemption at Compaq. Many people viewed him
as Digital's &UR;  &LR; second-in-command and the likely candidate to succeed
Palmer. But in July 1996, Pesatori quit abruptly amid signs that he
was being blamed for the company's flagging personal computer
sales.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't unemployed for long. Four months later, he became
president of Tandem Computers Inc., ending up at Compaq after the
Houston-based PC company bought Tandem in 1997. Pesatori is now
Compaq's senior vice president of marketing, responsible for the
company's marketing, branding, and advertising strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime manager Strecker, a talented engineer who was
instrumental in the development of some of Digital's most
influential computer systems, nonetheless spent his share of time
in Olsen's penalty box, according to many current and former
Digital employees. Olsen reportedly blamed Strecker for misreading
several important market trends, which caused Digital, for
instance, to stick too long with its proprietary VMS operating
system instead of shifting to the more broadly accepted Unix
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Strecker was skewered in a 1997 article in Upside
magazine, which claimed that he and Palmer were ``the ultimate
architects of Digital's failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Strecker, widely regarded as a technological genius, is
clearly a survivor, too. He's now Compaq's chief technical officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's got more lives than a cat and more endurance than
the Energizer bunny,'' said Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   The reunion of these former Digital comrades inside Compaq's
executive suite has rekindled memories of the glory days, when
Digital was the king of the minicomputer era and operated from a
converted woolen mill in Maynard.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Rose and I bunked in the same tent together at Ken
Olsen's campground up in northern Maine,'' recalled Rando, head of
Compaq's services division. Olsen frequently brought Digital
managers up to his rustic campground on the Canadian border for
in-depth strategy sessions known as ``woods meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles from the nearest highway, managers had no choice but to
bond with their fellow Digital executives in those primitive
surroundings, Rando said.
</P>
<P>
   The closeness that developed during those team-building
exercises at Digital, he said, has resulted in a level of
familiarity and trust within Compaq's new management team that is
rare in the wake of a merger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Our working relationships are well-established,'' Rando
said. ``We know how each other thinks. That kind of mentorship and
supportive interactions of the management team are hard to come by.
They're real assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, power struggles among rival executives can often doom a
merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``These mergers are usually disasters,'' said Edgar Schein,
professor emeritus at the MIT Sloan School of Management. ``If this
one is not a disaster, that might be the reason.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone thinks the preponderance of former Digital
executives within Compaq's top ranks is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It troubles me that so many Digital managers are in a position
of authority at Compaq,'' said writer Geoffrey James, who penned
the 1997 Upside article and is also author of a new book called
``Success Secrets from Silicon Valley'' (Times Books, May 1998).
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest danger that Compaq has is it will take on
Digital's culture, instead of the other way around,'' James said in
an interview, alluding to Digital's historically consensus-driven,
slow-moving, bureaucratic culture. ``If that happens,'' said James,
``the company will go right down the toilet, just like Digital did.
... On the other hand, if Compaq energizes what's left of Digital,
then something good could come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Digital executives now running Compaq admit there are
differences in the ways the companies have been run, but said the
cultural differences are overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you graphed it, Digital would probably have had more ideas
and initiatives bubble up from the bottom, while Compaq would have
more of a top-down direction,'' said Siekman, who was Digital's
chief counsel before the merger and now holds the same position at
Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Because Digital under Olsen emphasized the concept of ``buy-in''
or consensus-building, it often took a long time for decisions to
be made, said Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Compaq, there's an orientation to finding the data, getting
the data visible, and making decisions very quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rose, Siekman and the others agreed that the culture that
existed at Digital in the 1970s and '80s was much different in the
1990s, after competition increased and Digital endured a painful
series of restructurings and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken had unique ideas about how a company should be managed,''
Strecker said. ``I think the environment under Bob Palmer was not
the same. There was a bit more top-down orientation under Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Rando insists that neither company's past culture matters, nor
does the culture that existed at Tandem before it was acquired by
Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to build a new culture,'' he said. ``You don't
bring three companies together and believe that any one is going to
dominate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
