u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMEDY-RIVERS-BOS &LR;      08-14 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMEDY-RIVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN WE TALK _ ON RADIO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can we talk?
</P>
<P>
   It's mid-afternoon and the plumber has just arrived at Joan
Rivers's apartment in Manhattan. It seems that her toilet is
undergoing a renovation and she's not taking it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a rotten day,'' she says. ``How can it be a good
day when the plumber shows up? Just say Rivers is a bitch. I'd like
to say I'm having a PMS day but that would make me too young.''
Then she laughs.
</P>
<P>
   While some know Rivers as the ``E!'' correspondent who covered
this year's Oscars, or as the host of a syndicated radio show,
others remember her as the queen of comedy _ a feminist trailblazer
in a field long dominated by men. She started in the late '50s,
before there were comedy clubs. In 1965, the Barnard College Phi
Beta Kappa graduate got a shot on ``The Tonight Show'' with Johnny
Carson and became a huge hit. She became a substitute host for the
vacationing Carson and, as the '60s ended, she was headlining in
Las Vegas _ the hottest female comic in America.
</P>
<P>
   Through the '70s and into the '80s, Rivers continued her upward
spiral, substituting for Carson for one week every month. In 1986,
she made a career move that, at the time, seemed perfect. She
agreed to host her own late night talk show on the burgeoning Fox
network with her husband, Edgar Rosenberg, producing. It was a
horrible error. Carson trounced her in the ratings, and some say he
used his considerable clout to keep guests from appearing on her
show. Rivers's show bombed. And, a year later, Rosenberg committed
suicide. Rivers was devastated.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time she couldn't really talk about it. But she
pulled herself together and, in 1989, she re-energized her career
with an Emmy-winning daytime talk show that ran for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't miss that show,'' says Rivers, 65, as her Yorkshire
Terrier, Spike, barks in the background. ``TV talk changed too
much. I'm just not interested in some cousin who sleeps with his
brother's wife or people with mall haircuts who live in trailer
parks. Get a life. Get busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivers has returned to talk but this time, she's on the radio
with a two-hour call-in talk show.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to say exactly what you want to say,'' she says. ``And
you don't have to get dressed up. And I can shave my legs while I
work _ with a weedwhacker.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there's a loud flush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the only toilet in New York that everyone will hear
every time I use it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers says she enjoys teaming up with Don Rickles for these
weekend summer stock-type engagements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family and crew all pile into the van with the barking
dogs and everything else,'' she says. ``And we stop at
McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   Do the workers ask for your autograph?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yea, I sign about 37 from the manager on down and they don't
give me as much as a French fry,'' she says. ``And they won't let
the dog in the restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Joan and Melissa Rivers starred in ``Tears and
Laughter: The Joan and Melissa Rivers Story'' a TV movie that
focused on, among other things, Rosenberg's suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The male critics all hated that movie and the female critics
loved it,'' she says. ``The first day we shot Edgar's funeral it
took a long time to set up the shot. We were in a car and Melissa
said to me, `if Daddy were producing this movie, we'd be done by
now.'''
</P>
<P>
   The dog's barking in the background. And Joan Rivers, whose
career spans five decades, is waiting for the plumber to finish.
Sometimes even she gets tired of talking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1321EDT &QL; 
