<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4156 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SLOW-BOS &LR;      08-14 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SLOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SLOW MOTION' VIEW OF A LIFE UNTETHERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SLOW MOTION 
A True Story 
By Dani Shapiro 
Random House, 245 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Slow Motion'' is a candid memoir of a misspent life
resurrected from the ruins of a devastating tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   At 23, Dani Shapiro was drifting toward oblivion. Once a
promising student of music and literature at Sarah Lawrence
College, she dropped out of school to pursue acting, but that was
little more than a half-hearted attempt at respectability. Her true
career was being the mistress of Lenny Klein, a powerful New York
lawyer who also happened to be the stepfather of her best friend.
Klein made Shapiro a kept woman, and while she hated his swaggering
ways, she loved the money and power which kept her in fancy
apartments, well-stocked limousines, and five-star European hotels.
</P>
<P>
   She changed her surname from Shapiro to York to conceal her
ethnic and religious heritage. To drown out the white noise of her
life, Shapiro packed her nose with cocaine, and drank vodka
splashed over ice, chased with wine. It had become a life
untethered and unrecognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Then she receives a telephone call which, Shapiro recalls,
``divides my life into before and after.'' She was three days into
her stay at a ritzy Southern California health spa, no doubt paid
for by her sugar daddy Klein, when her aunt informs her that her
parents have been critically injured in a car accident. Her mother
sustained more than 80 broken bones, and her father would be left
with the mentality of a confused child.
</P>
<P>
   A blizzard back east prevented Shapiro's immediate return to her
New Jersey hometown, but Klein manages to get her on the first
available flight. Once she boards, she anesthetizes herself with
alcohol, but it is not enough to numb her greatest fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been old enough to comtemplate loss, I have
imagined losing my father. Whenever we have been together and said
goodbye I have wondered if that goodbye would be the last,''
Shapiro writes. ``Though he is a bear of a man, an imposing figure
really, I have seen him as physically fragile, vulnerable,
picturing a fatal heart attack, an embolism, a stroke _ my father
falling like an old heavy tree to the pavement on Wall Street where
he works, or while walking to temple on a Shabbos morning.''
</P>
<P>
   For Shapiro, returning home means not only dealing with the
current crisis, but with the life she abandoned. For her first 17
years, she was raised in an Orthodox Jewish home where her father
wore a yarmulke, the Sabbath was observed, and her family adhered
to religious dietary laws. Even among other Jewish families in
Hillside, N.J., her family stood apart, separate from others who
``sent their daughters for nose jobs and their sons to golf camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping back into her parents' home churns up a plethora of
painful memories from the lonely years of an only child who always
felt somewhat estranged from her parents. There, she also finds the
girl who became the woman who only saw value and currency in her
blond good looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have used myself as a physical instrument, slicing my way
through the world with nothing but youth, long legs, and long blond
hair,'' Shapiro writes. ``At times I think I have chosen the easy
way, but every once in a while I realize that this may be the
hardest way of all.''
</P>
<P>
   From the ashes of her family's hardship, Shapiro begins to
restore and reshape herself. Dealing with her parents' daily
medical crises, she finds the structure and rhythm her life has
long lacked. Whereas once it revolved around Klein and job
auditions, she finds she at last has ``a purpose, a reason to wake
up in the morning. I am needed.''
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished novelist _ her last book, ``Picturing the
Wreck,'' also dealt with a family tragedy _ Shapiro uses the tools
of fiction to tell her story. Unfortunately, that technique robs
the book of some of its emotional power. And since the story is
told in the present tense, it loses the weary wisdom of
retrospection.
</P>
<P>
   But Shapiro does not sugarcoat her life; she writes with an
eviscerating, raw honesty about the wrong turns and mistakes she
made. She is equally harsh with her family, capturing the
jealousies and pettiness they refuse to put aside in a time of
calamity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slow Motion'' has an upbeat ending, but it is an arduous trip
to that conclusion. Along the way, Shapiro will battle her
addictions, and confront the full horror of her relationship with
Klein. One of her parents will die, and she will deal with
long-simmering tensions with the one who remains. Yet Shapiro
emerges sadder but wiser, the one true survivor of that horrific
accident on a snowy night in New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4160 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV16     08-14 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS NO TIME TO BE TOO HEAVILY INVESTED IN STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 16, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 64 years old and my wife and I are retired. We own our
home, have no debts, and have fixed expenses of $16,000 a year.
Income from Social Security and a pension is $36,000 a year. I have
a total of $306,000 in IRA accounts of which $256,000 is in stock
mutual funds and $50,000 in a zero-coupon bond maturing in the year
2000. In addition, my wife has various investments totaling
$100,000 in mutual funds, savings bonds, and bank savings. Since I
have no plans to withdraw any of the investments before the
mandatory age of 72, when should I plan to reinvest into a more
conservative portfolio, and what should the portfolio consist of?
</P>
<P>
   D.E., Bristol, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, there's no time like the present. Even though you can
afford to take a long-term view of the market, it seems to me that
holding more than 84 percent of your portfolio in stock funds at
this point is far too aggressive. I find no fault with your fund
choices _ the largest holding is $58,000 in the excellent Legg
Mason Value Trust, followed by holdings of $25,000 in Fidelity
Growth and Income, and $24,000 in Vanguard Index 500. But I
calculate that more than 75 percent of the fund portfolio is
dominated by large-cap stocks _ the very market segment that has
dominated the strong market gains of recent years and which is now
stumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you decide to stick with such a stock-dominated
portfolio, I suggest you seek more diversification. For example,
you have $18,000 each in Vanguard Growth and Income and Vanguard
Windsor II, both of which have large-cap, value-oriented
portfolios. My suggestion would be to swap one of these positions
for something such as Vanguard Small-Cap Index. You might also look
for a good mid-cap fund (such as Homestead Value or Mutual Beacon)
and a good health-care fund, (such as the sector offerings of both
Fidelity and Vanguard).
</P>
<P>
   But more important than diversifying within the various sectors
of the stock market is diversifying beyond stocks. I suggest that
about 25 percent of the current stock fund portfolio be moved to
the fixed-income side, building a bond portfolio consisting of
about 50 percent in a GNMA fund, and 25 percent each in a
short-term bond and a high-yield (or junk) bond fund. You might
also further cut your reliance on stock funds by moving some of the
large-cap holdings into a balanced fund such as Fidelity Puritan or
Vanguard Balanced Index.
</P>
<P>
   One final thing: you're a little optimistic about when you'll
need to begin taking mandatory distributions from your IRA accounts
_ the rules require that the first distribution come by April 1 of
the year following the year when you reach age 70 1/2, so even if
your birthday falls in the second half of the year, your first
distribution would precede your 72nd birthday by a few months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be 67 years old next January, and I am beginning to
taper off working as a temporary employee. I have already started
drawing Social Security, but have to return most of it because of
my earnings. My monthly benefit from Social Security is now $1,287.
From the following portfolio, where should I begin drawing funds to
bring my monthly income up to $3,000? I have $193,800 in IRAs,
$69,700 in common stocks, $29,500 in money markets and CDs, and a
variable insurance policy with a $12,700 cash value.
</P>
<P>
   R.P., San Marcos, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In the best of all possible worlds, what you would be looking
for is at least a 6.72 percent return from the total portfolio,
which would allow you to make the monthly withdrawals of $1,713
with no loss of principal. If you judge by the stock markets of the
past few years, that would seem like falling off a log. But I have
long been trying to persuade people that the last few years have
been atypical for Wall Street, and that when you have a sequence of
unusually strong years there, it's most likely that what will
follow is a sequence of so-so, weak, or horrible years. So to me a
6.72 percent portfolio average seems to me a bit more dubious, at
least in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   A good deal of the IRA portfolio is well chosen for income _
Cohen and Steers Realty fund, Equity Residential Property Trust (a
NYSE REIT), Janus Flexible Income fund, and Lindner Dividend fund
all sport solid yields. Dodge and Cox Balanced, at 3.1 percent,
also has a respectable yield for the current market. But the
dividends are minimal for Hotchkiss and Wiley International,
Neuberger and Berman Guardian, and Vanguard Index 500, the last of
which is your largest single holding.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to reduce your positions in those final
three funds from the current total of $77,600 to about $40,000,
diverting the proceeds to a pure fixed-income fund such as Janus
Flexible Income or Vanguard GNMA. I would tentatively suggest
similar moves within the common stock portfolio, which is dominated
by telephone issues, providing that there would be no horrible tax
consequences. Finally, you include a $9,000 money market account
with a credit union and a $7,000 money market account that is
associated with a brokerage account. Check on the yields from these
accounts _ my strong hunch is that you could probably get better
money market yields from a money market mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Where should you draw the money once you have tapered off from
working? If you expect to have some earned income during 1999, it
would make sense to draw from the taxable accounts, calculating
that in subsequent years your taxable income will be lower, and
thus you will be better off waiting to withdraw from the IRA until
you have little or no earned income. Thus I would begin by taking
income from the stock dividends, the yields realized if you convert
some of the common stock to fixed-income holdings, and finally from
the money markets and CDs. Once your earned income has trickled
down to an insignificant level, you might then begin withdrawing
the actual yields from the IRA accounts, and then taking whatever
else you need from whatever holding seems weakest or most
tax-efficient to sell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We would like to start our 14-year-old grandson in investing
his money _ birthday gifts and Christmas gifts and so forth. Should
he do a CD or some mutual funds? What is the best place for his
small amount of savings? We have investments with Fidelity. What
type of investment might our 19-year-old daughter make?
</P>
<P>
   P.H., Lynn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The answer to the question depends on another question _ when
are your grandson and granddaughter likely to use the money? If
he's likely to go on to a secondary education in about three years,
there's no question that CDs would be far better than most mutual
funds; even funds at the more cautious end of the spectrum, bond
funds and the like, can be quite volatile over a three-year time
frame, even though their longer-term records seem quite stable.
</P>
<P>
   But let's presume that both your grandson and granddaughter
won't be using the money right away, perhaps letting it grow until
they are in their late 20s and are thinking about making their
first home purchase. In that case a mutual fund would be a good
choice. With such a time frame, I'd suggest an investment such as
Fidelity's Puritan fund, which holds about 63 percent of its assets
in stocks and the rest in bonds and other fixed-income securities.
It's been one of Fidelity's stronger funds in recent years
(relative to its objective) and has a good record of weathering
sour markets fairly well.
</P>
<P>
   The only potential bug is the Puritan requires a minimum initial
investment of $2,500, even for a uniform gift to minor's account.
They do allow a $1,000 minimum for custodial accounts in Fidelity
Asset Manager, which is roughly similar, but which hasn't done as
well historically as Puritan. There are a number of no-load
balanced funds with lower minimum investments _ AARP Balanced Stock
and Bond, and Pacific Horizon Asset Allocation at $500, and Pax
World and Strong Asset Allocation at $250. But of the funds I have
listed, all but Fidelity Puritan are given average ratings by
Morningstar Mutual Funds. Puritan is rated above-average. So a
solid strategy, if the minimum deposit is an issue, might be to
begin with CDs and then move into a mutual fund once the account
reaches the required level.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
