<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: In recognition of Senior Month in September _ which
includes National Grandparents Day on the 13th _ The New York Times
Syndicate presents five stories of special interest to seniors.
</P>
<P>
   _ WEB SITES FOR SENIORS
</P>
<P>
   _ DIAL 911 OR GO BACK TO SLEEP?
</P>
<P>
   _ HOW HUMANS CAN UPGRADE MEMORY
</P>
<P>
   _ HELPING THE ELDERLY GET ORDERLY
</P>
<P>
   _ NEW SOLUTIONS FOR ELDER HOUSING
 &UR; (HOW TO ORDER? SEE BELOW) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEB SITES FOR SENIORS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,500 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ANN ORR
</P>
<P>
   Once seniors overcome any anxiety they might have about
computers, they find a host of intriguing Web sites to suit their
needs and interests. Ann Orr, a software reviewer for Children's
Software Revue, highlights some of the best sites that are geared
to or likely to appeal to seniors. (slugged:
BC-WEB-SITES-FOR-SENIORS-(SENIOR-MONTH)-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code l)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIAL 911 OR GO BACK TO SLEEP? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 1400 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHLEEN JONAH LENANE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From McCall's magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's late at night and you suddenly feel chest pains. Do you
call an ambulance or figure that it can wait until the morning?
Lenane offers tips on how to determine whether various ailments _
skipped heartbeat, chest pain, cramps, night sweats, dizziness _
are likely to be serious enough for a 3 a.m. run to the emergency
room. (slugged: BC-LATE-NIGHT-HEALTH-WORRIES-(SENIOR-MONTH)-NYTSF,
priority code r, category code l)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW HUMANS CAN UPGRADE MEMORY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By EVE GLICKSMAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As people age, they tend to suffer memory loss. Glicksman
discusses the three types of memory _ long-term, intermediate and
short-term _ and how each is affected by the aging process. She
also offers strategies on how to keep one's memory sharp. ``Much
like muscles that grow flabby if not exercised, your memory
requires daily toning,'' she writes. (slugged:
BC-MEMORY-LOSS-(SENIOR-MONTH)-NYTSF, priority code r, category code
l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HELPING THE ELDERLY GET ORDERLY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By FLORENCE FELDMAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Organization is important in everyone's life, but for the
elderly it can be the key to how well they can function
independently _ and for how long,'' writes Feldman, a professional
organizing consultant. Discussing how she assisted her own mother,
she gives practical advice on reorganizing kitchens, shelves,
personal papers, shopping lists and jewelry boxes to make life
easier for the elderly. (slugged:
BC-ORGANIZING-FOR-ELDERLY-PARENTS-(SENIOR-MONTH)-NYTSF, priority
code r, category code l) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW SOLUTIONS FOR ELDER HOUSING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JERE DANIEL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From Family Circle magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Millions of senior citizens and their offspring wrestle with the
difficult and often heartrending problem of where the elderly
should live when they can no longer cope alone at home. These days
nursing homes or moving in with the children are not the only
options. Daniel looks at some of the alternatives he and his wife
explored for his aging mother-in-law, including cooperative living,
home sharing, assisted living and continuing care. (slugged:
BC-NEW-HOUSING-OPTIONS-(SENIOR-MONTH)-NYTSF, priority code r,
category code l) &QL;
</P>
