<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BABE: A LARGE SLICE OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's intriguing to consider just how the modern media would
cover George Herman Ruth. No self-respecting journalist in this day
and age of self-promotion would let the off-field antics of the
Babe go unexposed.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other recent reports, Sunday night's HBO Sports
documentary on Ruth presents a balanced account of a complicated
man. Born and raised near the seedy Baltimore waterfront, Ruth was
the son of a saloonkeeper who ultimately sent him to St. Mary's
Reform School to live. The Babe was a troublesome child and
struggled throughout his life with philosophical issues such as
right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife was 16 _ he was 19 _ and the child they adoped
was believed to have been the product of Ruth's affair with a maid.
Either way, he abandoned child and wife quickly, not exactly ready
to deal with commitment when there was so much fun to be had.
</P>
<P>
   And that he did, from the booze and chorus girls to the home
runs and World Series championships. He was at once celebrity and
father figure, admonishing his friends to attend Mass every Sunday
while at the same time refusing to see a priest because he had been
having a wild time with several women simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Foley has one of the best lines in the hour-long special.
He was a peanut vendor at Fenway Park and recalled the Babe helping
bag peanuts and leaving the kids $10 or $20.
</P>
<P>
   Foley also recalls the Babe cursing at kids who used foul
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would tell them to do what their mother and father told
them to do,'' Foley said. ``And if he heard a kid swearing, he
would yell, `Goddammit, stop that goddamn swearing.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is a classic Babe story and suggests what would be considered
hypocrisy these days. But at the time, it was considered colorful,
complicated, and, well, purely Babe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had a serious thought in his head,'' said one
commentator. ``But you would have liked him. He wasn't a bad
fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO presents a moving tribute to commemorate the Babe on the
50th anniversary of his death at age 53. The insult of receiving a
contract for $1 from the Yankees at the end of his career and his
battle with terminal cancer were dark developments. But otherwise,
Ruth was full of life and joy, an innocent in paradise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to ask Babe what he thought of Einstein, he would
ask you, `What's he hittin'?''' said another commentator.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different time then. In the 1920s, baseball became the
national pastime because Ruth's slugging heroics and the sheer
force of his personality restored the game to prominence after the
1919 White Sox gambling scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people knew about Babe Ruth than knew about the president
in this country,'' Pete Hamill told HBO. ``And a lot more cared.''
</P>
<P>
   As Yankee great Tommy Henrich said, ``Babe Ruth is the only guy
that ever lived up to his reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth befriended everyone, including journalists who covered him.
</P>
<P>
   And he made great copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babe Ruth was a larger-than-life character,'' HBO Sports
executive producer Ross Greenburg said. ``His accomplishments and
impact were profound, perhaps to a degree that people born after he
retired cannot fully comprehend. Why is a man who passed away 50
years ago still the best-known figure in baseball?''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason was his prodigious talent. He averaged more
than 50 homers for six years. He retired with a .342 average, a
.690 slugging percentage, and a then-record 714 home runs. And that
was after he made the transition from pitching, at which he had
been one of the premier lefthanders in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a living man who became a mythic god,'' said journalist
Bill Gleason, ``and nothing can change that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A major trade
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia-based Entercom announced Thursday that it has
agreed to swap two radio stations in Tampa for CBS's five stations
in Boston, including WEEI. The value of the exchange is estimated
at $160 million. The other Boston stations involved are WRKO, WWTM,
WAAF-FM, and WEGQ-FM.
</P>
</TEXT>
