A4179 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-     08-14 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DEEP IN DEFENSIVE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ You quickly learn that this group is
intriguing when one of its interplanetary members says, ``I've
never been to Mexico, but I have been abducted before. Yep. I've
been hit by lightning and I've been abducted.''
</P>
<P>
   You ask this very large man, who will be making his first trip
to Mexico next week, exactly when and where he was hit by
lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my house,'' he says. ``I was knocked off the couch. I swear
to God. Remember those big thunderstorms we were having in May? I'm
not lying. I swear. A big flashlight came in the window. Huge
thunderstorm. I was hit.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs. You begin to wonder if this is what the Patriots had
in mind when they talked about their defensive line being a very
diverse group. So, you ask Chad Eaton, who's competing for a
starting defensive tackle job, when was he whisked away by aliens
or Trekkies or a group of sci-fi experimentalists?
</P>
<P>
   ``That was in 1984,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   You ask where he went.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's settled. If you wanted to put together a wide-ranging
poll on NFL opinions, the Patriots defensive linemen would be
perfect. They have very young people, those teetering between youth
and veteran status, and a few old guys, although ``Hank is going to
kill me for saying ``old guys,' '' defensive line coach Ray
Hamilton says of Henry Thomas. They have speed rushers and bull
rushers. Those who have been hyped and those who have been
overlooked. Those who have had their hair bleached blond and those
who are on the verge of having dreadlocks. And, yes, those who have
been abducted.
</P>
<P>
   Move those varied personalities onto the field and you have a
team strength. You also have a potential problem. Understand that
quality linemen are in the same category as major league pitchers.
Teams never feel they have enough of them. But the Patriots have
enough (last year they kept eight linemen). So many that the ones
who don't make the team won't have a problem finding a new job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an entire group that is real deep. I wouldn't want
BG's job this year,'' Ferric Collons says of Bobby Grier, the
team's top personnel man. ``They can't keep everybody. That's just
a fact of the game. I wouldn't want to be the man having to make
those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. There's Eaton, Collons, and Thomas. Willie McGinest,
Mark Wheeler, and Brandon Mitchell. Chris Sullivan, Greg Spires,
and Devin Wyman. Mike Jones, Leonta Rheams, and Artie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much fluff among that group. Hamilton said earlier
this week that the idea is to play all the linemen who are on the
team's active roster come Sept. 7 when the season opens. There will
be no backups just for the sake of having backups. We have heard
stories about the Patriots' running back problems, leading some to
joke Wednesday that visiting commentator and retired Raider/Chief
Marcus Allen was the best back in town. Defensive line, though, is
a team strength. Late summer days can become tiresome when there is
no zip in the training camp air. The linemen have made things
interesting for themselves by creating several competitions.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most prominent is the quirky Eaton vs. Wheeler, a
seven-year veteran. Both want the lead nose tackle position.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm afraid of is: I don't want to walk out there with the
second-string line anymore,'' Eaton says. ``I'm not part of that
anymore. I don't want to be a backup role player. I want to be a
guy Pete Carroll can count on. Where he can say, `It's first and
goal; put him in there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler sees Eaton coming. He's a veteran, so he knows this is
not the same Eaton who was once so unwanted that he went to his
neighborhood Kinko's and faxed a job request to an Arena Football
League team in San Jose. Or the Eaton who claims he sat in his
apartment for a week, waiting on phone calls. When the calls
weren't business-related, he would cut them short because ``I
couldn't afford call-waiting.'' Or the Eaton Bill Parcells used to
psych up on the practice squad, telling him to ravenously chase
down the first-team offense.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like that anymore. Eaton came into camp saying he
wanted to do what Wheeler does because ``Mark's a great defensive
tackle.'' Wheeler doesn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, having all these guys around definitely makes the game
go by quicker,'' he says. ``It keeps everybody fresh. That's what
you need when you're trying to get to the Super Bowl. We need depth
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton says he likes the intelligence of his linemen. He often
sits with them and shows them what to look for in films of
offensive linemen. Who is more vulnerable to speed rushes? Who
looks weak when pressured to the right? Who has the best footwork?
Now Hamilton doesn't have to worry about being a sole group leader
because Thomas and McGinest are good filmgoers, too.
</P>
<P>
   But soon enough, some of the film students will have to leave.
Collons is right. The Patriots can't keep them all. There was a
good line in place last season. Now the team has added Spires, a
rookie from Florida State who didn't get a lot of college acclaim
because he played alongside Andre Wadsworth, the third pick in the
1998 draft. ``People say he's too small,'' Hamilton says of the
6-foot-1-inch, 260-pound Spires. ``They said the same thing about
Hugh Douglas (now with the Eagles), and he was defensive rookie of
the year. I like those small guys.''
</P>
<P>
   And big guys. And soon-to-be-dreadlocked guys (Collons). And
guys who have seen all this before (Jones).
</P>
<P>
   ``You get used to the competition,'' says Jones, one of the men
who could get caught in the lineman shuffle. ``So it becomes: Go
for what you know.''
</P>
<P>
   He is asked how he is doing compared with everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess all right,'' he says. ``The staff knows what I can do.
If they like it, fine. If not ... Know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. If they don't like it, maybe another team going waiver-wire
shopping will.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd hope so,'' Jones says.
</P>
<P>
   No one is to that point yet. There are still three practice
games to play, the next one against the Cowboys in Mexico City
Monday. Spires was the star of the previous two exhibitions. On
Monday, it could be Mitchell, Sullivan, or Jones. Or Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the 300-pound lineman who is fascinated by interior
designing, are there any updates on the '84 abduction?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask me at the start of the season,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we're asking too late, but is this Eaton well?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as crazy as he wants everybody to think,'' Collons
says. ``Chad's a new dad. He's mellowed out. He used to be a little
off the hook. But let me tell you something: If I was going to war,
I'd want him on my side.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than a month, Collons will be preparing for real games.
Eaton will be on his side. So will five or six other linemen.
Patriots fans should take comfort in knowing all of those linemen
will be good players. They should also be glad they don't have the
responsibility of Grier, who will most certainly have to release a
quality big guy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
