<HEADER>
A4182 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-OFFENSE-     08-14 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-OFFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAMPESE: OFFENSE NOT IN DRIVER'S SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Ernie Zampese hasn't been around Boston long,
but he's been here long enough to understand the best way to
describe the struggling nature of his team's offense to New
England's worried football fans. So Thursday he talked about being
lost in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to speed everything up, and it's like all of a
sudden, you're driving a car in Kansas City,'' the Patriots' new
offensive coordinator explained. ``You don't know where you're
going, so you're not moving too fast. You're hesitating. Then you
come back to Boston and you know just where the off ramp is. You
know what lane to be in and when you have to move over to the right
and where to get off.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, you're going full speed again, which after two
exhibition games, New England's offense is not. That the Patriots
have struggled thus far to execute Zampese's timing-based passing
game, with its short three-step and five-step drops and quick
decision-making, has been obvious but not unexpected. The
development of timing, by its very nature, takes time, and there is
no one who understands that better than Zampese.
</P>
<P>
   He knows quarterback Drew Bledsoe must grow accustomed to making
his drops quicker and letting the ball fly sooner, without benefit
of seeing his receivers breaking into the open, which is an act of
faith not easy to make at first.
</P>
<P>
   He knows those receivers must get used to reading defenses
quickly and coming to the same conclusions about them as Bledsoe.
They must then get to specific spots at the same time the ball
does. That is always the aim, of course, but it's not always as
simple as you might think until everyone understands exactly what
Zampese's system is asking of them.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Zampese has been around pro football for three decades, so
he understands what this all means. Unfortunately, not everyone
watching his offense operate lately shares either his eye or his
patience, which has caused the pressure to mount only weeks into
that offense's birthing process in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all getting a little frustrated,'' Zampese said. ``Like
everybody, you want it to happen. It will. We just need more reps.
We've put a lot in and we're trying to speed everything up. The
drops. The decision-making. As Drew does these things more and
more, the latter gets speeded up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we took a whole practice and just worked on one play 60
times in a row, a guy will start to feel pretty comfortable with
that play. But you can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Bledsoe and his receivers reach that comfort level with a
lot of plays, things will very likely continue as they have. Thus
far, Bledsoe has completed only 41.7 percent of his throws (10 of
24) and is averaging barely 4 yards a completion (4.04). He has no
touchdowns, two interceptions, and has not looked good.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has his offense, which has not scored a first-half
touchdown and is averaging only 230.5 yards of total production a
game. Obviously, there is only one way to describe that. Not good.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bledsoe knows internally that he is getting closer. He knows
he and his receivers were closer last week to success than they
were the week before. Most of all, he knows there are still three
exhibition games and nearly a month of practices left before the
season opener in Denver, which at this level of football is a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   He knows, in other words, that he will get many more
repetitions, many more opportunities to read, react, and, most of
all, throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quarterback is all about reps and being able to adjust,''
Bledsoe said. ``At whatever level _ high school, college, or the
pros _ the reads are the same and the pictures you get are the
same, but you have to have a chance to see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe has not yet had that chance often enough in game
conditions, and it may show again Monday night in Mexico City,
where the Patriots will play the Dallas Cowboys. Zampese
understands that because he knows his system is initially fighting
a quarterback's natural instinct, which is to hold the ball until
his receiver is running free. Understanding it, however, is not the
same as accepting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do this a few times,'' Zampese said. ``Drew is
taking a five-step drop, and on the fifth step, we want him to
throw it. So he goes and does it and the receiver's not out there.
Next time, he's thinking, `I better wait.' It's just a little
different for him still, and that makes you hesitate. That's what
we got.''
</P>
<P>
   What the struggling Patriot offense has is hesitation, because
things are new and different and all the signs aren't quite clear
yet to the driver or his passengers. So they are moving slower, one
foot on the accelerator and the other tapping the brakes, just like
you'd do trying to find that off ramp in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But the point to remember, as Ernie Zampese knows, is that if
you can drive, eventually you'll find that off ramp and head for
home. And when you do, you'll be flying again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
