<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACCORDIONS-HNS &LR;      08-14 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCORDIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCORDION PLAYERS SEEK A SPOT IN THE RECORD BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EVE MITCHELL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MENLO PARK, Calif. _ Some might call it the ultimate squeeze
play: Hundreds of avid accordion players are expected to gather
here next month in an attempt to earn a spot in the Guinness Book
of World Records.
</P>
<P>
   Jamis MacNiven, a restaurateur in Woodside, Calif., hopes to set
the record for the most accordion players gathered at one time to
play ``Lady of Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   The musicians won't be out to break any records because no one
else has tried. So no matter how many players show up, they will be
accordion pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no record (to break) so we will be setting the
record,'' MacNiven said.
</P>
<P>
   MacNiven is optimistic that he'll meet his goal of at least 500
accordion players for the morning gathering Sept. 20 that will
feature the official instrument of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many accordion players out there,'' he said.
``It's really amazing. They get so little respect that a lot of
them are thrilled to be in the largest accordion band ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the Accordion Invasion, the parade of musicians will kick
off the second annual Sand Hill Challenge, a modern soap box derby
that takes place in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   The race attracts entries from Silicon Valley venture
capitalists and high-tech companies. Proceeds go to local youth
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Why the accordion? ``The accordion marches well and it sounds
great and it doesn't need amplification and it's also nostalgia,''
MacNiven said. ``It's an instrument a lot of kids in crew cuts were
brought up with it and then it disappeared from view. Well, it's
back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Marian Kelly, president of the San Francisco-based Bay Area
Accordion Club, said it has never been a neutral instrument.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a certain period when the accordion kind of fell
from grace,'' with the rise of rock and roll, she said. ``I think
(young people) just kind of found the accordion as square. Now,
we're in a much more accepting mode.''
</P>
<P>
   The club, which has a membership of 325, was formed in 1990, the
same year that the pleated-player became San Francisco's official
instrument.
</P>
<P>
   There can never be too many accordion players, said the man who
spearheaded the city's official instrument drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have too many people playing at a single event
because of the fabulous music that's played on the accordion,''
said Tom Torriglia of All Things Accordion of San Francisco. ``If
you're the greatest accordion player in the world, if you're just a
beginner, if you just want to learn that morning, that's fine with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The accordionists will be preceded in the parade by a contingent
of bagpipe players, because MacNiven explained, the bagpipes always
come before accordions in a marching band.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
