 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, Aug. 15,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, Aug.
15, 1998. We will update this budget at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISLAM-WEDDING_ NABLUS, West Bank _ Standing before a soccer
stadium packed with about 15,000 people, 35 men stand in black
suits holding red Korans and the green Islamic flag. They are young
Palestinian grooms, expressing what for many is a new attachment to
Islam in a public wedding celebration that glorifies the religion
and, indirectly, Hamas. One Hamas spokesman calls the young
believers the ``raw material'' for his movement. For the second
year, Islamic groups in this large West Bank city are reviving
their faith with a strong dose of politics and by helping young
couples navigate the complexities of Islamic courtship. These
weddings keep men and women guests separated, offer no alcohol or
hedonistic music and they're catching on. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL-FOREIGN _ MOSCOW _ It's time once again to take
the pulse of the foreign media on President Clinton's alleged
sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
Are the newspapers, magazines and television in Moscow, Mexico
City, London and Jerusalem as insatiable about this tawdry mess as
the U.S. media? We shall see. (Holmes w/foreign staff).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 3 p.m. EDT Friday.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   PROBE-COSTS _ WASHINGTON _ Critics of independent counsel
Kenneth Starr say he has spent in excess of $40 million
investigating President Clinton. Starr's defenders say one of the
chief reasons for the expense is White House stall tactics,
including several costly court appeals. Regardless, Starr's
expenses are only part of the real cost, since dozens of government
lawyers have been pulled into the case on the White House side. And
that doesn't include the fees that witnesses have paid to
attorneys, estimated by one recent survey at $23 million. (Malone,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REPORTERS _ WASHINGTON _ They slogged through Whitewater
despite a public that often preferred to hear less rather than more
about presidential scandal. They weathered the backlash of the
Clinton White House and sometimes faced resistance from fellow
reporters and their own publications. Now the handful of
journalists who have followed a trail of Clinton controversies for
six years are seeing their work lead to the first-ever appearance
by a president before a criminal grand jury. The persistence of
fewer than a dozen reporters has been largely responsible for
keeping the issue of Clinton's conduct before the country. ``The
heroes are the ones that have kept it alive,'' says Britt Hume, who
anchors an evening report on Washington for Fox Cable News. ``These
people have done tremendously well on this story, and it hasn't
been easy.'' Among them: Susan Schmidt of The Washington Post,
Newsweek's Mike Isikoff, Steve Labaton of The New York Times, Pete
Yost of the AP, as well as Jackie Judd and Chris Vlasto of ABC.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved spot earlier this week and is being repeated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   US-ADULTERY _ WASHINGTON - Despite President Clinton's high
approval ratings in the face of allegations of marital infidelity,
a huge majority of Americans still believe adultery is wrong,
according to polling data. And adultery among the average American
couple is far less common than the flurry of recent allegations
against Clinton and other public figures would suggest, say
sociologists, marriage counselors and clergy. But in cases of
divorce, adultery plays a much larger role. (Shepard, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved spot earlier this week and is being repeated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
