<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON-STARR &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Developments on White House
strategy for Clinton's Monday testimony before the Kenneth Starr
grand jury. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REACT (Washington) _ Political reaction to President
Clinton considering an admission that he had sexual contacts with
Monica Lewinsky. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NH-VOICES (Dover, N.H.) _ In 1992 Bill Clinton, his New
Hampshire primary campaign wounded by allegations of extra-marital
affairs and questions about his draft record, defied speculation
that he would have to drop out and instead, at the Elks hall here,
vowed to stick it out until ``the last dog dies.'' Voters rewarded
his perseverance with a second-place showing in this
first-in-the-nation primary, just enough to keep his candidacy
alive. Today, in that same Elks hall, with Clinton facing possibly
the most perilous moment of his presidency when he testifies before
a grand jury on Monday, club members and buyers at an antiques
auction voiced yet another chorus of defiant indifference to the
allegations against him. Pausing for emphasis, Bob Carroll, an
auctioneer, said, ``Leave. The poor man. Alone.'' By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS (Undated) _ Rural towns in Maine that
don't have high schools pay tuition for their children to attend
private schools. But a federal judge has upheld the state's law
excluding parochial schools from the voucher system.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The political briefings column. By
B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly Religion Column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Africa Bombings &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KENYA-BOMBING (Nairobi) _ A look a the psychological and
economic impact the bombing at the U.S. Embassy has had on Kenya.
By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KENYA-MOSQUE (Nairobi) _ Against a backdrop of suspicion after
the bombing, the scene at mosques here on the Muslim holy day. By
Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ Developments in Washington in the
wake of the terrorist attacks in Kenya and Tanzania. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other international &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ Developments on U.S. regarding Iraq and
arms inspections. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELLION (Kinshasa) _ Developments in the rebellion
against President Kabila's government: conflicting reports that the
president has fled the capital. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ The post-meltdown scene in Moscow banks,
markets. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOON-FOSSETT (Undated) _ After narrowly avoiding being drawn
into a high-pressure system over the Indian Ocean that would sent
him in a useless loop, Steve Fossett nearly doubled his speed in
his attempt to circle the globe in a balloon. He is expected to
break the distance record for a balloon sometime today. By Malcolm
W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ Hong Kong's government buys stocks
and futures to fend off an escalating attack on the territory's
currency and safeguard the economy. Stocks stage their biggest
rally in six months, with the Hang Seng Index jumping 8.3 percent.
The rally capped a week in which the index swung more than 700
points, or 11 percent. Few investors think that the volatility is
over. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CIENA-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Ciena's shares tumble as much as 19
percent after the maker of phone equipment, its sale to Tellabs
pending, says it expects third quarter profit far below what
analysts were predicting. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was up 6 points at 1:45 p.m. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments: The long bond
was up 13/32 at midday. By Robert Hurtado.
</P>
