<SLUG> BC-ORNAMENTAL-JOCKEYS-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWN JOCKEYS, BACK IN STYLE, HAVE IMPORTANT HISTORIC MEANING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 16)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Jockeys aren't just at the racetrack. Replicas of
uniformed jockeys can also be found on residential lawns, where
they are most commonly featured holding a decorative or working
lantern to light the way, or a ring, which could be used to tether
a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Cast-iron and concrete jockeys have been a common sight in just
about any area that has a racetrack and on thoroughbred farms,
where they are often painted in the colors that the stable races
under.
</P>
<P>
   Black-faced lawn jockeys were used beginning in the 1800s. They
fell out of favor in the 1960s with the civil rights movement, when
many owners began to paint the exposed faces and hands of their
lawn jockeys white.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn jockeys have remained a constant staple in horse catalogs,
antiques shops and most lawn-sculpture centers. Concrete law
jockeys also can be found.
</P>
<P>
   The Impressions of Saratoga Springs catalog listed weatherproof,
cast-aluminum lawn jockeys with customized colors, measuring 43
inches tall with a 13-inch base, selling for $650.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage cast-iron lawn jockeys with original black face are
valued at approximately $1,000 to $1,500, according to Terry Kovel
of Kovel's Antiques Buyer Guide.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond being decorative, lawn jockeys with (original) black
faces were originally used as house markers on the Underground
Railroad prior to the Civil War. This was a secret network of
blacks and whites who helped black slaves flee to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Those who chose to aid the slaves would tie a green ribbon to
one of the arms of the black jockey, to signify it was safe to
enter a house, and not to stop if the ribbon was red. In lieu of
ribbons, some households placed an American flag in the hand of the
jockey as an indication that it was safe to enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every county in New York state was involved with the
Underground Railroad,'' Charles Blockson, curator of the
Afro-American Collection at Temple University in Philadelphia and
published authority on the Underground Railroad, said in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn jockeys were also known as ``Jockos.'' This folklore tale
dates back to a young boy named Jocko, who held George Washington's
horse on shore at the crossing of the Delaware and froze to death
in the process. Because of the boy's dedication, Washington had a
statue made of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, the little boy's image changed to a groomsman
in the Old South and eventually evolving into that of a jockey. The
statue became a national figure after World War II,'' Blockson
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said not all black-faced jockeys should be seen as demeaning,
contrary to views held by some.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not a stereotypical image of a black _ where the
`Jocko' is dressed as a black-faced minstrel, with big white eyes
or other negative images _ the statue stands as a positive reminder
of the Underground Railroad and the good deeds of helping to
abolish slavery,'' Blockson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep a 5-foot-tall, 400-pound cast-iron black groomsman with
a lantern in hand from the 1800s at the entrance to the lobby of
Sullivan Hall on campus, where our collection is housed. People who
see it for the first time often don't know how to respond. That is
until they read the caption at the bottom: `Lawn Jockey, original
statue with light, which served as a symbol of safety on the
Underground Railroad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lawn ornaments, including lawn jockeys, are experiencing a
popular resurgence that have made them targets for theft, so be
sure they are bolted down or imbedded in cement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
