<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4329 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-BILLBOARDS-HNS     08-14 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BILLBOARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MEXICO CITY, OUTDOOR ADVERTISING IS A SIGN OF THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 16)  
 (EDs: Photos available on Wieck database)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Not all of the curves around the Mexican capital's
major traffic arteries are in the roadway.
</P>
<P>
   A satiny brunette gazes down on frazzled commuters on the
Periferico Norte freeway, pumps a bicep, and touts the only article
of clothing she wears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weaker sex? Me?'' the model asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``100 percent Wonderbra'' the billboard assures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the transition road to the Viaducto Miguel Aleman,
a coquettish cheerleader type sporting a full-coverage Loveable
brassiere that a grandmother could probably wear to church
advocates ``Don't hide, discover your beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   And all over the city, leggy beauties wearing micro-minis ending
just south of the intersection of the models' hip and thigh hype
various brands of panty hose.
</P>
<P>
   It is a capitalist axiom that sex sells, and outdoor advertisers
here have caught on with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``The billboards are popping up like mushrooms everywhere you
look in the city, blocking people's view of trees, mountains,
volcanoes, churches and monuments,'' said Homero Aridjis, a poet,
social critic and ecologist, and president of the prestigious
Committee of 100 environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a pollution of brassieres and underwear, alcohol and
tobacco, junk food and luxury cars,'' Aridjis complained. ``Mexico
City is fast becoming more a Calcutta of the mind than the valley
painted and lyricized by generations of artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Ponce Nava wants to do something about that.
</P>
<P>
   Ponce is the director of environmental projects under Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas Solorzano, elected mayor of Mexico City last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a great anger amongst the public about all of
this,'' Ponce said in a recent interview. ``It is mostly the
business types who support this explosion. I don't think there are
very many people who say that the billboards actually relieve the
monotony of sitting in traffic on the periferico.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 of the billboards are illegal, Ponce said. She
intends to remove them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working on a two-pronged project,'' she explained.
``First, we want the illegal signs taken down. Then, we are working
on a new regulatory code that will give us back control over our
open spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the city has ordered more than 150 billboards removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That leaves us only 5,850 to go,'' Ponce said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, at least one sign recently removed _ it had a
pole planted squarely in the middle of a city sidewalk _ announced
an exhibit in a municipal cultural museum.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt billboards are a growth industry in Mexico
City.
</P>
<P>
   They crowd sidewalks and streets everywhere, looming over
roadways, parks and plazas, invading landscaped boulevard dividers.
</P>
<P>
   Ponce said she could document instances where advertisers have
cut down three or four trees to improve the billboard's exposure.
The battle is perhaps most vicious for the prime space along the
city's freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down onto a freeway from a pedestrian overpass, one
might easily forget there is a city surrounding the
bumper-to-bumper traffic, so closely spaced are the wall-to-wall
billboards.
</P>
<P>
   The damage is not all visual, Aridjis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming use of the female body to sell spawns a
tremendous sexism among the people and a degradation of
sexuality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One downtown sign suggested that for chest congestion, a
particular brand of pills could provide relief. Accompanying the
text was a waist-up shot of a busty young model wearing a bikini
top.
</P>
<P>
   Too, it is considered hip among advertisers to meld English into
the Spanish text of most of the signs, creating a kind of Spanglish
that Aridjis called ``language pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   Stringent city regulations on billboards have been on the books
for at least a decade. But past administrations have done little to
enforce them.
</P>
<P>
   Aridjis questions whether some of the mammoth signs are
structurally sound.
</P>
<P>
   One day in May, strong winds blew down 15 billboards, the Mexico
City daily newspaper Reforma reported. No one was injured, but
homes and cars were damaged. Only one of the billboards was
licensed, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Responsible advertisers are just as concerned as Ponce and
Aridjis, said Leticia Rodriguez Moctezuma, executive secretary of
the Mexican Association of Outdoor Advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said her organization represents more than 80 percent
of all of Mexico's billboard operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the sign industry was out of control until a year
ago,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new administration is trying to establish control, and
that is good,'' she said. ``It guarantees citizens a better city
and advertisers a secure investment on their properties.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Regulations adopted in past administrations were too strict and
enforcement too lax, so no one bothered to comply, Rodriguez said.
And in those cases where a city official actually did complain,
under-the-table payments usually smoothed things over, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said the 6,000 signs that Ponce complained about are
``not illegal, but unregulated.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution is not to take down the signs, because that would
cost jobs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In all Mexico, about 60,000 people depend directly or indirectly
on the outdoor advertising industry; 48,000 of them live in Mexico
City alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in the industry want regulations that we can live with. I
think we can work with the new administration to find a way to
settle things,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   That remains to be seen, as Ponce said that her vision of Mexico
City is more like that of European cities, where billboard
regulations are far more restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a cynical limit of sorts was reached with the recent
message pasted to a billboard on a sweeping curve in the city's
Circuito Interior freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murphy's Law,'' the sign read. ``Just as you turn to read this
sign, the car in front of you will brake.''
</P>
<P>
   It was paid for by an auto insurance company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
