<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4334 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADETTRIAL-INTERVIEW-     08-14 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADETTRIAL-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID GRAHAM SAYS HE TOOK BLAME FOR FORMER GIRLFRIEND DIANE ZAMORA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT THARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ David Graham, a convicted murderer, expects
many to think him a liar.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that the detailed account he wrote describing his
involvement in the brutal murder of 16-year-old Adrianne Jones
sealed his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I signed the confession that was pretty much my
future,'' said Graham, 20. ``I didn't think it at the time, but
when I look back, I realize that it's going to be hard for anyone
to believe me. What can I do?''
</P>
<P>
   During a wide-ranging interview this week in the basement of
Tarrant County Jail, Graham was subdued as he talked about the
Jones case. The case attracted national attention because of its
titillating combination of two U.S. military academy students mixed
up in love, sex, revenge and murder. Even Graham says the case was
like a soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said that his confession _ which describes Jones' slaying
as well as the manic teen-age romance with his former fiancee,
Diane Zamora, a former Naval Academy student _ was written because
he had agreed to take the blame with Zamora for the slaying. That
confession, along with extensive publicity about the case, probably
swayed jurors the most, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In saying that I pulled the trigger, I was protecting her from
a large amount of the blame,'' Graham, a former Air Force Academy
student, said in his first print interview. ``More just to be with
her in it, to stand with her.''
</P>
<P>
   At his trial last month, Graham abandoned that ground.
</P>
<P>
   He disavowed the confession, which stated that he killed Jones,
and he denied that he was present when Jones was beaten and shot
along a rural road in Grand Prairie, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   When asked where he was on that cold, predawn morning of Dec. 4,
1995, Graham smiled, turned to his attorney and asked, ``Can I tell
him?''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Rob Swofford said that disclosing the
information must wait because it is vital to winning a new trial.
Investigators are searching for witnesses to support Graham's
contention that he was elsewhere when Jones was killed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said that if Graham has an alibi, it would have
surfaced during his trial.
</P>
<P>
   While investigators pursue his story and lawyers prepare for the
appeal, Graham, dressed in a tan county jail jumpsuit and plastic
sandals, awaits transfer to a prison where he will probably spend
the next 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   These days, he said, he writes to friends, many of whom ask for
photos of him. He reads the newspaper daily and monitors TV news
programs about the case. He has a single cell, but for six hours a
day, he can use a larger room with a TV and a shower. He also talks
on the phone, runs in place and does push-ups, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once in prison, Graham said, he plans to stay out of trouble
because he's ``not the kind of guy who gets in fights.'' He hopes
to take college courses in science and math and possibly teach
other inmates.
</P>
<P>
   He is reading the Bible, he said, and Herman Melville's ``Billy
Budd,'' a short story often assigned in literature classes about a
naive young man unable to defend himself against a wrongful
accusation. He started reading it during his trial in New
Braunfels, and he said he identifies with the main character on
some levels. But he said he is not as simple as Billy Budd.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's different, because he's so naive and innocent. He doesn't
understand the ways of the world,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's understanding of the world also may be a bit askew,
based on his recanted confession and his view of his relationship
with Zamora, 20.
</P>
<P>
   Zamora became consumed with an erroneous idea that Graham and
Jones were romantically involved, Graham said. Only after he
learned of Jones' slaying did Graham agree to take part in a
cover-up to protect Zamora, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Graham and Zamora were originally arrested, police said the
couple told them they killed Jones because she had sex with Graham,
and Zamora wanted revenge. Since then, Graham has denied having a
sexual relationship with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In separate trials that resulted in capital murder convictions,
prosecutors argued that Zamora and Graham acted together, plotting
and carrying out Jones' death as a way to salvage their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his love for Zamora, Graham said, he never seriously
considered calling police during the nine months that the slaying
went unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   He described attending a school memorial service for Jones
immediately after her death as ``hard'' but said being with Zamora
was more important than the Jones family's anguish.
</P>
<P>
   That same obsession, Graham said, allowed him to see a childhood
friend, Bryan McMillen, falsely arrested for the slaying and spend
more than two weeks behind bars. Graham said he had known McMillen
off and on since the two were in kindergarten in Mansfield, Texas,
yet he never thought to tell police that McMillen wasn't guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dedicated to protecting Diane,'' he said. ``I wouldn't
have thought twice about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he still thinks about Zamora but adds emphatically
that he is no longer in love with her.
</P>
<P>
   Although Zamora described him during her trial as domineering,
violent and the mastermind behind Jones' death, Graham said he
thinks Zamora could still have feelings for him. He said he has
learned that she wore her engagement ring to prison but that it was
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   After Zamora's conviction, Graham wrote her a letter saying he
was ``sorry her life turned out this way.'' Each received an
automatic life sentence and must spend at least 40 years in prison
before becoming eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diane and I were people you'd expect to have great futures.
It's so out of the ordinary,'' he said. ``Plus Adrianne was like
Diane and I, she was popular and athletic and smart. So three
people, all three of our lives were destroyed. Plus the love
triangle and the sex appeal, it's kind of like a soap opera.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
