<HEADER>
A4338 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-14 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMANDER IN CHIEF VS. FIRST MOURNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton did what he does best: He gushed empathy and
compassion in the aftermath of tragedy. Then he took a half-hearted
stab at a job he doesn't do very well at all: being commander in
chief.
</P>
<P>
   No president has played the role of ``first mourner'' with more
conviction and fervor than Clinton, and he was in peak form
yesterday when the bodies of 10 of the 12 Americans killed in the
U.S. embassy bombings in Africa arrived at Andrews Air Force Base
near Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton delivered a moving eulogy to the slain Americans and
watched at least part of the ceremony with tears streaming down his
cheeks. If the voters wanted someone who cries at funerals as their
top elected official, they certainly picked the right guy.
</P>
<P>
   We live in an era when it is considered mandatory for
politicians _ and everybody else, for that matter _ to wear their
hearts on their sleeves. Those who won't cry in public are
dismissed as lacking in compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may or may not be sincere when he indulges his penchant
for public displays of emotion, but many Americans clearly accept
such displays as evidence of his eagerness to feel their pain. In
two successful campaigns for president, Clinton probably garnered
more votes by shedding tears than most candidates rack up with
promises of world peace and full employment.
</P>
<P>
   He was at it again at Andrews as he voiced the nation's
appreciation for the bombing victims and concern for their loved
ones. He praised the ``adventurous spirit'' and ``generous soul''
of each victim. He comforted the survivors by reminding them that
no one can take away their cherished memories of those who died.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is acting when he does this sort of thing, then he's
one heck of an actor. But whether or not his words and tears are
heartfelt, they are effective. They provide solace and support, not
just for those directly involved, but for the nation as a community
that has suffered a tragic loss.
</P>
<P>
   The current national sorrow, of course, is the result of
criminal acts of murder and destruction. The ever-present specter
of international terrorism has once again led to the heartbreaking
sight of flag-draped coffins carrying the bodies of murdered
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such violent provocation, the American people
require more from their president than tears and sympathetic words.
</P>
<P>
   And so the president shifted gears and addressed the nation as
commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what it takes, we must find those responsible for
these evil acts and see that justice is done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed that America ``will not retreat from the world and
all its promise, nor shrink from our responsibility to stand
against terror and with the friends of freedom everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The words sounded great. But what would lead anyone _ including
terrorists who so brazenly target American citizens _ to believe
that Clinton's words had any meaning?
</P>
<P>
   What act of terrorism against the United States has Clinton
avenged with swift and effective military action? When has Clinton
made some outlaw nation pay a price for harboring and sponsoring
terrorists?
</P>
<P>
   When has Clinton followed through on any threat to ``stand
against terror''?
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about a president who can't even bring himself to
punish Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein for thwarting United
Nations-mandated weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam is as easy and juicy a target as any president could
want. If Clinton doesn't have the stomach to strike at Iraq, why
would he expect us to look upon his denunciations of terrorism as
anything but empty rhetoric?
</P>
<P>
   The world's terrorists must have laughed themselves silly as
they watched the tear-stained president of the United States
pretending to put them on notice.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's most ardent detractors are so busy being indignant
about his private behavior that they have apparently overlooked the
real ``high crime and misdemeanor'' of his presidency: his shameful
capitulation to America's enemies.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
