<HEADLINE>
`AIR BUD' GAINS LITTLE YARDAGE WITH SEQUEL 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDY SUMMA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dog couldn't play football in real life, of course.
</P>
<P>
   People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals would protest the
animal's endangerment, parents would scream for rabies shots, kids
would get fleas and the dog would make a mess on the field.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't reality: It's a world where monkeys commandeer
ice cream trucks, parrots chant ``Show me the money!'' and dogs win
football games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver,'' the sequel to last year's
basketball-playing dog story, works only if you suspend your
disbelief, lower expectations and are in the third grade. ``Golden
Receiver'' has heart, but it's story is slight. Kids will marvel at
Buddy's football tricks, but they may be bored with the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The film picks up a year after the first (and more engaging)
``Air Bud'' ended. Buddy is a year older, and a year wiser. So is
his 13-year-old chum/owner, Josh Framm (Kevin Zegers again), who
spends his days playing basketball, hanging out with Buddy and
keeping his widowed mom from dating.
</P>
<P>
   Josh isn't a bad kid, just one who loves his deceased dad. But
when his mom (Cynthia Stevenson) falls for the town's veterinarian
(Gregory Harrison), Josh joins the junior high football team to
avoid seeing them together. The football team is terrible,
finishing last for several seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Josh's best friend is on the team, and the coach is a good guy,
so Josh laces up as the team's backup quarterback. Josh has a great
arm, just no confidence. Naturally, the team's all-star quarterback
gets hurt, and Josh has to step in. It's a good thing his dog knows
how to run a deep post pattern! Buddy runs onto the field, scores a
touchdown, and a sequel is born.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few clever sight gags, but the prevailing comic
theme is Buddy acting human. He opens doors, wears football jerseys
and celebrates touchdowns with paw-dropping dances. But that wears
thin, and eye pokes become the joke de jour. Giving Buddy human
characteristics is necessary to the story, but so is humor.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, at this point, director Richard Martin has
established a decent (if not abused) setup: Josh can't accept his
mom's new beau, and sports success might bring them together. Plus,
Buddy is a football dynamo.
</P>
<P>
   So why did Martin add Russian circus wranglers? Meant to be
comic foils (think ``Rocky and Bullwinkle's'' Natasha and Boris),
Natalya and Popov are instead terribly written sketches. Buddy
could have written better-developed characters.
</P>
<P>
   Natalya (Nora Dunn) is Cruella De Vil with a new accent. She
wants Buddy to be the main attraction in a traveling animal
carnival. So she and Popov buy an ice cream truck and try to kidnap
the wily golden retriever. Along the way, they trip over rocks,
fall in lakes and get hit in the head. The film doesn't really need
them and, consequently, ``Golden Receiver'' fumbles when Natalya
and Popov are forced into the storyline.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back at the real movie, Buddy and Josh have become
football heroes, and Josh has even started to warm to his mom's
boyfriend. Josh and Buddy have led their hapless team to the state
championship, but Air Bud is kidnapped the night before the title
game.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a little help from a vat of fish guts (don't ask),
Josh has to win the big game and save his canine friend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
