<HEADLINE>
FOR TEAM MANAGER, NO MORE DAMN YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Damn Yankees. That's what they were to Joe Torre when
he was young and growing up in Brooklyn and incapable of knowing
any better.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees loomed over the baseball landscape _ as
impersonal as U.S. Steel, as pervasive as General Motors, as
ominous as the Communist threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the Yankees teams in the '50s,'' Torre said. ``It
got boring to me. That was probably why I was never a Yankees fan.
I always said, `You're not a Yankees fan. You're a Yankee rooter.'
Because they were going to win every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre was sitting in the Yankees dugout of Yankee Stadium on
Thursday, wearing the Yankees pinstripes, the embodiment of what he
used to hate. After decade upon decade of looking up in envy,
longing to get to the World Series just once, Torre has managed to
accumulate an embarrassment of riches at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees win almost every day. To keep it interesting, they
win almost every fathomable way.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are on schedule to win more games than any team this
century. Torre spent so many years playing, and then managing,
teams that ranged from miserable to middling, who'd have known he'd
have any idea what to do with prosperity?
</P>
<P>
   Even Torre didn't consider his managerial record a source of
particular pride when he arrived after the 1995 season. For the
record, it was 894-1,003. That's 109 games below .500.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday night, he was two games above .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't important to me,'' Torre said. ``What was
more important was being offered this job, and having a chance to
be accountable on a team that legitimately has a chance to win it.
A year like this has been magical. It's something that will always
be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' ability to get in a position to win, day after day,
would amaze Torre, if not for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you send a (quality) pitcher out there every day, why
not?'' Torre said. ``Why shouldn't we win today? That's what it
comes down to. We have a legitimate starter going out on the mound
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Torre sent Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez to the
mound to face the second-highest scoring team in the major leagues.
Hernandez merely two-hit the Rangers for 8 1/3 innings, striking
out a Yankees rookie-record 13.
</P>
<P>
   And at the moment, Hernandez is the Yankees' No. 5 starter _ the
likely oddman out of the rotation once the playoffs start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitchers _ it just seems like they have this competition
going with each other,'' Torre said. ```Go out and pitch a good
one, and if I don't, I'm letting people down.' It just seems that
each guy takes a challenge every fifth day to give us a chance to
win. That's all we want.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the time hitters get finished sifting through the arms and
legs and angles, they're hard-pressed to find the ball. Hernandez
is particularly hazardous to the mental health of right-handed
batters, who entered the game with a .144 average against him. He
retired the first 10 batters he faced, striking out five of them.
</P>
<P>
   The only threat Hernandez faced was in the fourth inning. A
one-out double byswitch-hitter Mark McLemore and a walk by
left-handed Rusty Greer brought up cleanup hitter Juan Gonzalez.
Hernandez fed Gonzalez a slider off the outside part of the plate.
Strike one. Hernandez fed Gonzalez another slider. Strike two.
Hernandez fed Gonzalez another slider. Strike three.
</P>
<P>
   Another lefty, Will Clark, walked to bring up Pudge Rodriguez
with the bases loaded. Rodriguez is a right-handed hitter, which is
to say he, too, struck out on a slider off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth inning was a definite sign of what type of pitcher
he is,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``It looked like he
knew who he wanted to pitch against. He knew he was going to go
after Juan and Pudge, and he wasn't got to mess around with Rusty
and Will.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez left in the ninth after a one-out walk by Gonzalez,
who had struck out the previous three at-bats. He left to a
standing ovation from the crowd of 53,835.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great support,'' Hernandez said. ``But to be honest with
you, I don't always listen to it. I always try to focus on what is
at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   For somebody who came over from Cuba on a raft in December, that
seems like a reasonable enough approach. It was the 11th time in 13
starts that Hernandez has worked at least six innings. Take away a
3 1/3-inning, 10-run bombing at Anaheim, and he has a 1.93 earned
run average.
</P>
<P>
   And he still might not be able to work his way past David Cone,
David Wells, Andy Pettitte and Hideki Irabu into the Yankees'
playoff rotation. The postseason is what it's about for these
Yankees. It's a different age, a different environment, from when
the Damn Yankees considered the World Series their birthright. The
Yankees made it to the World Series eight times in the 1950s,
missing in 1954 and 1959. Those were the days when a team went
straight from winning the pennant to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a team must make it through two rounds of playoffs just to
get to the World Series. Torre already is fretting about the perils
that await in a best-of- five, first-round playoff series. A
best-of-seven format throughout the playoffs would make for more
justice, unless frostbite became a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three series of seven (games) would be tough,'' Torre said.
``Unless they do it like the Super Bowl. Make the first two series
seven games, and the last one one game. How would that go?
Aaagghh!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
