<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4391 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWIMMER-HNS &LR;      08-14 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIMMER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SOVIET SWIMMER PROSPERS UNDER THE STARS AND STRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLOVIS, Calif. _ The path to one American record started in a
Soviet Army pool. Lenny Krayzelburg started swimming there as a
little boy. At 10 years old, he was training at least five hours a
day, about as much as he does now as a 22-year-old world champion
with an endorsement deal.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates were his classmates. At the club, school and
swimming went together. Everything was carefully arranged to
cultivate athletic talent. But Krayzelburg never became a
state-sponsored star. Instead, he moved to the United States and
did things the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his teens, he barely practiced five hours a week,
much less a day. His family, starting over in a new country, had
little money. Krayzelburg had to work 30 hours a week at a
recreation center in West Hollywood. He took buses to the pool,
because his parents kept long hours in their new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Even this week, while their son competes in the national
championships, his father is driving six hours round-trip, from Los
Angeles to Clovis, on the days that he swims.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, he saw Lenny win the 200, breaking his own
American record. Then he got into the car and drove home. As soon
as the championships end, the family will take a big trip together.
The Krayzelburgs are going back to their hometown, Odessa, in the
former Soviet republic of Ukraine. This will be their first trip
back since Christmas Day 1988, when they came to the United States
to find better opportunities for their children _ Lenny and his
sister, Marsha, now 20.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny remembers coming here and being overwhelmed by American
culture. ``The haircuts, the earrings, the tattoos,'' he said.
``They wear anything they want. In Russia, it is more conservative.
It's fascinating, but I don't know if I liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was thrown by visits to the supermarket, rows and rows of
foods, dozens of types of cereal in one aisle, meats in another. He
didn't speak any English when he arrived. Help came from neighbors
in West Hollywood, a hub of Russian immigrants. (The family
considers itself more Russian than Ukrainian.)
</P>
<P>
   In turn, when Lenny had learned English, he tutored some young
Russian girls in an after-school program at the recreation center.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of countries in the world, America is the Promised
Land, but it's not as easy when you get here as you think when it's
overseas,'' Krayzelburg said.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the family still speaks Russian, and a satellite dish
brings Russian television into their townhouse in Studio City. His
mother, Yelena, has a job as a pharmaceutical technician, and Oleg
is a cook at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   They are prospering compared with the early years, when they
lived in a two-bedroom apartment smaller than the one they had in
Odessa. This winter, they were able to travel with Lenny to
Australia for the world championships, watch him climb onto a medal
stand and receive two golds while ``The Star-Spangled Banner''
played.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg became a U.S. citizen in 1995. His swimming career
had started to flourish. He went to Santa Monica City College for 2
1/2 years, and his coach there contacted Mark Schubert, the
University of Southern California coach, and asked him to take a
look at this promising young backstroker. Schubert started training
him in the summers, alongside 1996 Olympic gold medalist Brad
Bridgewater, and eventually, Krayzelburg got a scholarship to USC.
</P>
<P>
   Schubert has turned out national and Olympic champions at a
prolific rate. But he has never met one quite like Lenny
Krayzelburg. After Wednesday's races, he and Krayzelburg left the
pool together and stopped at a Boston Market for something to eat.
Lenny insisted on paying for the coach's dinner, as a token of
thanks. Schubert was touched and surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a swimmer buy me dinner at nationals,''
Schubert said. ``It's not something I expect at all, but when it
happens, you really appreciate it. It's very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a month ago, Krayzelburg signed his first professional
contract. He has to complete another semester of college for his
degree in finance and information systems, but his athletic
eligibility expired in the spring. Speedo gave him a contract, and
he asked for an unusual clause. If he makes it to the 2000
Olympics, his sponsor will pay for his family to fly to Sydney for
the Games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg has noticed that most Americans aren't as
family-oriented as Russians. He doesn't quite understand why, but
he knows that being here doesn't prevent him from being anything he
wants, even a conservative young man with a nondescript haircut, a
soft Russian accent and a strong attachment to his parents.
</P>
<P>
   He appreciates the fact that no one ever taunted him when his
English was in its infancy, and that he ended up with a college
scholarship and a lucrative contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you work hard here,'' he said, ``the sky's the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   He had to work harder than most. If he had stayed in Odessa, who
can say what would have happened to his swimming career? Most of
the great athletic programs have been dismantled since the Soviet
system collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Popov, the great Russian sprinter, moved to Australia
to train.
</P>
<P>
   But even in this country, Krayzelburg thrived on his own for a
long time. In that sense, he is a classic American immigrant, and
indeed, the sky is his limit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
