<HEADER>
A4395 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-STELLA-REVIEW-HN     08-14 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STELLA-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING INTO THE MOVIE `GROOVE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEFF MILLAR 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' is based on the novel by
Terry McMillan, who wrote ``Waiting to Exhale.'' But it's inferior
to the film taken from her earlier book.
</P>
<P>
   That one felt richer, this one feels thinner, perhaps because
``Exhale'' was more of an overview of contemporary African-American
women's issues, and there were simply more things set on our plate
to chew on.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair to its makers, richness of text isn't ``Stella's''
objective. It's a romance; any choice confronting filmmakers
between realism and glossy . . . well, the choice is never hard to
make.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what's best about the film is what feels the most
reality-based. And what's weakest is the gloss.
</P>
<P>
   Stella (Angela Bassett) is a hard-driving San Francisco
securities broker who has forgotten how to have fun. Upon shipping
her 11-year-old son off for a couple of weeks to visit her
ex-husband, she makes an impulse trip to Jamaica, taking along her
lifelong friend, Delilah (Whoopi Goldberg).
</P>
<P>
   The morning after her arrival, at breakfast, Stella sees at the
next table an attractive young Jamaican named Winston. The part was
cast with Taye Diggs, so impossibly handsome that he wrenched from
a theater full of adult women the noises usually confined to a
Hanson concert.
</P>
<P>
   Winston is young _ not that Stella is old. She's 40. Winston is
25, she guesses hopefully. Five years off. Winston is 20. That's 50
percent of Stella's age. That's HALF.
</P>
<P>
   The film enters a protracted loop of diminishing returns in
which their dialogue boils down to this:
</P>
<P>
   Stella: But our age difference.
</P>
<P>
   Winston: What difference does it make? I love you.
</P>
<P>
   Stella: But our age difference.
</P>
<P>
   Winston: What difference does it make? I love you.
</P>
<P>
   Stella: But our age difference.
</P>
<P>
   Winston: What difference does it make? Marry me.
</P>
<P>
   Before you rush to this as antidote for the recent spate of
geezers-get-the-girls movies, it has neither look or feel of the
Nicholson-gets-Hunt, Ford-gets-Heche, Beatty-gets-Berry movies. And
it's not the kind of role Meryl Streep has been recently demanding
on behalf of her actresses-of-a-certain-age peers.
</P>
<P>
   There is no gender-reversed, flab-vs.-firm dichotomy _ Bassett
turns 40 Sunday, but is buffer than Diggs. She occupies a Jerry
Rice 49ers jersey as well as Rice does. You really wonder what
she's talking about when Stella brings up the age difference. She
looks as good as he does.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan, who says she based the Stella-Winston relationship on
one of her own, doesn't make much of a case for the happy ending.
We get it, of course _ did you ever think we wouldn't? _ but we
don't get much sense of why we're getting it.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few filmmakers have shrugged shoulders over the
decades and said, ``Ah, l'amour'' as explanation for an unlikely
clinch at fade. It's just that explanations that feel based in the
real world, upon describable and ubiquitous experience, are more
satisfying. McMillan and screenplay collaborator Ron Bass have the
characters describe critical and explanatory scenes, but it would
be better to have the audience experience those events onscreen as
they happen.
</P>
<P>
   Director Kevin Rodney Sullivan brings his narrative to full stop
several times for embedded music videos considered crucial to the
film's marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The film's best moments come in the scenes between Bassett and
Goldberg. The filmmakers and Goldberg give meaning to a character
right out of the movie stockroom: Delilah is the standard
best-friend Listening Character, there to be an earlobe to the
interior dialogue in McMillan's book, to be Stella's coach and
cheerleader in the groove-retrieval process.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue between them is warm and funny, and the actors'
playing of it evokes the immense value in the women's familiarity.
You might wish the film had been less about this age-difference
thing and more about these best girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
