<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4423 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIMITZ-MOCKBATTLE-TEX     08-14 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIMITZ-MOCKBATTLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOCK BATTLE WILL RE-CREATE ATTACK ON JAPANESE BUNKER IN PACIFIC
CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDERICKSBURG, Texas _ On Saturday, out behind the dollar store
and a couple of blocks from the antique shops in this Hill Country
town, a Japanese bunker will be destroyed by small arms fire and a
big burst from a flamethrower.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be a real battle, but Marvin Schroeder, the living
history coordinator for the Adm. Nimitz Museum and Historical
Center, promises that visitors will get to see an authentic World
War II assault, and they'll smell it as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we can do that the movies can't,'' he said.
``We're already getting comments about the new Steven Spielberg
movie, ``Saving Private Ryan'' _ how realistic it is _ but at our
re-enactments you can feel the ground shake when the trucks come
in, and you can smell the diesel, the spent brass and the powder.
You can feel the heat of the flamethrower.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder and 35 members of his World War II re-enactment group
spread out across the state when the Spielberg movie opened last
month. They sent men dressed in World War II uniforms to theaters
in San Antonio, Austin and Houston. A group in the Dallas-Fort
Worth area did the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are kind of an anomaly,'' he said. ``Most groups do Indian
wars, the Civil War; not many people do anything from the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, 15 to 20 re-enactors will gather at the 2-acre
History Walk near the Fredricksburg museum northwest of San Antonio
for ``Island Assault: 1944.'' It will be the fourth, and final,
demonstration of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made that 2 acres into a battlefield,'' Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully placed among towering bamboo plants are such equipment
as a Sherman tank, a howitzer, an amphibious landing vehicle, an
intricate line of trenches, foxholes and bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. torpedo plane and the wreckage of a Japanese dive bomber
are in one large hangar at the beginning of the walk; in another
rest naval exhibits such as the combat information center from the
destroyer USS Frankford.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the History Walk, is a ``Fat Man'' atom bomb
casing.
</P>
<P>
   It shows that World War II brought us into the nuclear age,
Schroeder says.
</P>
<P>
   At 49, Schroeder has limited military experience. He spent a
year and a half in the Army, but when military doctors discovered
he had a steel pin in his wrist, they booted him out.
</P>
<P>
   Two brothers and his father were Marines. His family history,
plus the Nimitz Museum's emphasis on World War II's Pacific
battles, fed Schroeder's interest in the island-hopping campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is a Texas Parks &AMP; Wildlife historical site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I created the living history side of the museum in 1986-87 as
a volunteer,'' he said. ``We began special event programming in
1990 when I got a job here. It took until 1994 to come up with a
base plan on how to teach World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he engineered a Marine landing on Galveston Island;
in 1995 he put together a ``Welcome Home Parade'' for veterans of
the war in the Pacific. ``That's something they never got after the
war,'' he said. More than 65 World War II vehicles were used in the
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder insists that he and his re-enactors are not trying to
romanticize war. With children, he explained, they don't even talk
about war. They emphasize the equipment, the training, the living
and working together that takes place in a military unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers don't have time to teach this kind of history,'' he
said. ``Schools might have two days to teach World War II history.
The kids might come away learning a little about the atomic bomb,
the battleship Missouri, Normandy and some guy named Patton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we can take up the slack for those teachers,'' he said.
``We just want to make people appreciate our heritage. You know
what they say about history _ we are doomed to repeat it, if we
forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
