<HEADLINE>
EXERCISING MORE THAN YOUR MIND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's not the same as lifting weights or a swim at the
pool, but working in an office does burn calories. At the high end,
running an animated meeting in front of your boss burns off 188
calories an hour, according to Fitness magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, sitting through a boring office meeting lobs off
88.5 calories an hour. That may sound like a lot (go ahead and eat
that piece of chocolate cake!), but it's nothing like real
exercise: An hour's worth of swimming the breast stroke burns off
576 calories, an hour of running (assuming you're running a
nine-minute mile) expends 684 calories and baton twirling (this is
Texas, after all) uses up 486 calories per hour. But if your boss
frowns on baton twirling while you're on the phone, try these other
``low impact'' exercises while you're on the clock:
</P>
<P>
   _ Typing on the computer: 96 calories an hour.
</P>
<P>
   _ Writing a proposal by hand: 102 calories an hour.
</P>
<P>
   _ Photocopying and stapling or filing papers (both while
standing): 147.5 calories an hour.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cleaning up your desk and surrounding area: 177 calories an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
