<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHIVES-RELOCATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURED ARCHIVES COULD GO TO AN OUT-OF-STATE LOCATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURIE MAYK 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a musty World War II-era building on the
south side of Fort Worth, the legend of John Newton Means sits amid
tales of cowboys, presidents and astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   Means must have kept lawmen hopping around the Indian Territory
of present-day Oklahoma, according to information on the shelves of
the National Archives-Southwest Region facility. Records from the
1880s show three murder charges and several larceny indictments
against the rancher, who died in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that Means was ever convicted, but the
documents researched by his descendants indicate that he may well
have been the outlaw folks said he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the stories, but I didn't know whether to believe
them,'' said Means' grandson, J.B. Means of Ardmore, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 30 years, the National Archives center on West
Felix Street has been home to the Means family lore and other
federal treasures of Texas, Arkansas, Louisiana, New Mexico and
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   But the documents may be moved out of state soon, depending on
whether the National Archives and Records Administration
consolidates collections and moves them to newer facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the country's 13 regional sites are running out of room
and are struggling to prevent pollutants from damaging records.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, the city has an interest in buying at least some
of the land around Felix Street from the federal government.
Negotiations have been ongoing for about 2 1/2 years, Assistant
City Manager Mike Groomer said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say they like the location of the property and
believe that area businesses could generate jobs and help with
redevelopment. A land swap is also possible, Groomer said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's negotiations with the General Services
Administration, the agency working as the federal real estate
broker, will not affect the agency's decision about what to do with
the Southwest records. The agency is about a year away from a
decision, but officials have assured genealogists that census and
other crucial research records will stay in Fort Worth, even if the
stacks of original documents do not. But many remain concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Among the records housed in Fort Worth are:
</P>
<P>
   A document dated May 7, 1934, indicting Bonnie Parker, Clyde C.
Barrow and four others in the theft of four Browning automatic
rifles and 13 .45-caliber Colt automatic pistols from the Texas
National Guard Armory in Ranger, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   An official refusal by President Monroe to pardon 15 pirates
sentenced to death in the case of the United States vs. John
Defargues. Secretary of State John Quincy Adams also signed the
document.
</P>
<P>
   Several presidential pardons, complete with signature and seal,
piled on a shelf a few aisles away from the Apollo 11 flight plan.
President Harrison's 1890 pardon of convicted murderer George
Tobler and President Grant's 1875 act to reduce Oscar Snow's
sentence from death to life lie together in plastic film.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person could pick almost any topic that the federal
government got involved in in this region, and we'll have something
you can start to do research on,'' Southwest Region Director Kent
Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   RECORDS DATE TO 1806
</P>
<P>
   With 67,000 cubic feet of permanent records from about 90
federal agencies, the Fort Worth center is among the largest of the
13 regional archive holdings.
</P>
<P>
   About 70,000 to 80,000 cubic feet of records await transfer into
the permanent collection after a 25-year waiting period. Those
records should be in the temperature-controlled chamber even before
NARA takes official possession, Carter said, but there isn't enough
room.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest documents at the Fort Worth site are federal records
from New Orleans dated 1806. The newest papers of the permanent
collection are NASA flight plans.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the site's 1,600 visitors each month are genealogists.
Many argue that consolidating the Southwest records with those from
another part of the country would be an inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   After Congress decides how many new or renovated facilities it
will fund, the politics of choosing the sites _ if the order is for
fewer than the current 13 _ will heat up, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the Fort Worth location emphasize the convenience
of Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, reasonable rent for the facility and
access to historians at local universities.
</P>
<P>
   The shortcoming of the Fort Worth facility and many of its
regional sister sites is the lack of a filtration system to keep
out pollution and harmful gases.
</P>
<P>
   When the Fort Worth facility was built, pollution wasn't the
problem it is today, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Original records are kept in acid-free folders and boxes, and
some documents and photos are kept in polyester film sleeves for
extra protection.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, original documents should be stored at 50 percent
relative humidity, at 65-70 degrees and away from sunlight,
ultraviolet rays or polluted air, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   The building is equipped with smoke detectors and sprinklers
designed to dampen, but not soak, the document holdings.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEDY ARTIFACTS IN STORAGE
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, NARA's motto of ``ready access to essential
evidence'' does not apply to the disassembled Parkland Memorial
Hospital emergency room, where President Kennedy died on Nov. 22,
1963.
</P>
<P>
   Permission from the Assassination Records Review Board is
required _ and rarely granted _ to see the boxed-up floor and
ceiling tiles, cabinet, gurney and assorted medical instruments
from the Dallas hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy Library did not want the materials, and the Sixth
Floor Museum in Dallas can't have them because it is not federally
owned, Carter said. They remain locked in a temperature-controlled
vault in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we threw it away, the conspiracy people would say, `See,
there was something in the trauma room that proves' '' a conspiracy
theory, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   The information for which J.B. Means and his wife, Dolores, were
looking, however, was quite accessible. After narrowing their
search with information on the NARA Web site, they enlisted the
help of their sister-in-law, a genealogist in Fort Worth, to pore
over folders of yellowing court records filed under ``Means,
John.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the records on John Newton Means is a letter from James
Abel to a deputy U.S. marshal involved in a case in which Means was
accused of stealing cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Abel's connection is unknown, but the letter, dated June 1,
1889, reads: ``John Means has a bad reputation. ... He has been
stealing for some time and if you can do anything to get him to
justice you will do this country a favor.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
