<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING A MERGER WORK IN YOUR FAVOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ So, what do you do when your company announces it's
getting purchased by its competitor? Or maybe your company is the
big fish swallowing the guppy. How do you survive with your job
intact?
</P>
<P>
   You know the new company will need only one accounting
department and one human resources department and you hope like
crazy that your good performance will be so widely known that the
acquiring company retains your services, but don't bet on it. Many
employees sit on their hands when people they don't even know are
deciding whether they're on the ``stay'' or ``go'' list.
</P>
<P>
   It's a challenge many more employees are facing today. It's M&AMP;A
fever lately: 10 of the nation's biggest mergers and acquisitions
have occurred since November, according to Challenger, Gray &AMP;
Christmas, the outplacement firm in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, British Petroleum announced it was acquiring
Chicago-based Amoco Corp. and would shed 6,000 jobs, which has
employees of both firms nervous about their job security.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as you hear the news about a merger or acquisition, you
need to shore up relationships with people you know in both
companies, said John Challenger, executive vice president of the
outplacement firm. It's a lame duck period, when the folks at the
top are sorting out who will be the new leaders, and typically
people hire the folks they know. So try to get to know the
perceived players.
</P>
<P>
   You need people to stick up for you during those meetings when
employees' fates are decided, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the top bosses are identified, put a marketing campaign
into place, Challenger said. You've got to let the top dogs know
what you've done. Prepare a resume or list of accomplishments so
when you meet with the new leaders you can present yourself well.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the time to take a holiday, especially if you're
with the firm getting swallowed, he warned. Defer your vacation and
point out to your boss that you want to be on board in case you and
your data are needed.
</P>
<P>
   It's critical to keep a positive attitude about the acquisition,
said Greg Nakanishi, managing partner of GN Resources in Kingwood.
It's bad form for employees to grump around, complaining about the
deal and its effect on employees.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, when Nakanishi was executive director of human
resources for Tenneco, he had the job of interviewing employees who
worked for companies that Tenneco had acquired. The Tenneco team
would ask officials from the companies it was buying to identify
its stars. Often, the ``stars'' then proceeded to trash the buyout
and complain that the buyer and seller had done a lousy job of
explaining the arrangement to employees.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the acquiring company says: ``Hey, we can't have this
guy on our management team,'' Nakanishi said.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors were the ones who talked up the buyout, looked on
the positive side and help meld the two cultures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That fearful, resentful attitude is a typical reaction to
change, he said. People worry about what effect the buyout will
have on them personally _ will they lose their job, how will they
provide for their family, will they still command respect in the
new organization?
</P>
<P>
   Typically, people focus on what they will lose, Nakanishi said.
That kind of attitude isn't exactly productivity-enhancing at a
time when their performance is being closely scrutinized by a new
boss.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Osmon was a lucky merger survivor. She was in charge of
media relations for Memorial Healthcare System when the hospital
system announced it was merging with Hermann Hospital System of
Houston in November.
</P>
<P>
   The new vice president of corporate communication, who had come
from Hermann, was named almost immediately after the merger was
announced and Osmon got a chance to meet with him when the two
departments came together to design a new logo and image. She also
met with the new boss to explain how Memorial had run its media
relations office.
</P>
<P>
   Osmon said she didn't have much time to jockey for position
because the two communication departments were so busy and was
pleasantly surprised soon after the merger was announced when she
was tapped as the assistant director of corporate communications
for the newly combined Memorial Hermann Healthcare System.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone stayed on board, she said, although some job duties
changed. Osmon became a communication generalist for the new
system, a switch from her previous specialist role. She says she
enjoys her new, broader range of responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
