<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ALL THE POTENTIAL K'S OUT THERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He hadn't watched one of the Sunday-morning talking heads shows
for weeks, having grown weary to his toenails of their fixation on
the Bill-Monica-Ken affair.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of the terrible events that had unfolded in Kenya
and Tanzania within the preceding 48 hours, the average,
semi-informed news junkie felt certain that the astute ladies and
gentlemen whose views he once took seriously might ponder and
pontificate about that horrible event.
</P>
<P>
   And to his delight, he was right. Although the terrorist attacks
on the American embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam _ with their
resulting deaths, grievous injuries and destruction _ sickened and
infuriated him, in a perverse way he welcomed the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   He (call him K for short) needed the rush of such superficial
repartee about something substantial.
</P>
<P>
   But quicker than you could say, ``Linda Tripp is just an average
person,'' the moderator found a way to segue all the way from Kenya
to the FBI laboratory where Monica Lewinsky's blue dress was taken
to be tested for traces of presidential semen.
</P>
<P>
   K swiftly switched channels and landed right in the middle of a
parallel discussion in the same universe of discourse.
</P>
<P>
   He really resented the network talk shows' insistence on
force-feeding him and other average news junkies a steady diet of
interminable rumination and speculation on whether the president
violated the sixth commandment in the White House with the
erstwhile intern and what ought to happen to him if he did.
</P>
<P>
   Quite frankly, it didn't matter to K whether the two consenting
adults carried out illicit sexual trysts, or even whether one or
both of them lied about it. It was, in his view, a trivial matter
that should never have been allowed to consume so much public
attention and money.
</P>
<P>
   K conceded, however, that if the tawdry affair forced Bill
Clinton out of office, it was the president's fault. It had been
within Clinton's power to end the whole boring business before the
oh-so-average Tripp provided Kenneth Starr with another direction
in which to slant his failed multimillion-dollar Whitewater witch
hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The republic, K concluded, would endure regardless of what
Clinton with his peccadillos and Starr with his McCarthyesque
antics did to the credibility of the office of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he was as worried by all this as he was bored with
it. And it was not the fate of the president that concerned him. He
worried about those average Americans with whom Tripp so
inappropriately attempted to compare herself.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigation, he felt, made a mockery of due process.
The special prosecutor, in effect, targeted an individual and used
all the resources made available to him by the citizens and
taxpayers of the United States to find something with which to
prosecute or persecute him.
</P>
<P>
   It all reminded him of Franz Kafka's bizarre and terrifying
novel, ``The Trial,'' in which a man named K is put through
juridical and bureaucratic hell without ever being told what
offense he is supposed to have committed.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it is the president of the United States who is
being put through the Kafkaesque ordeal. But the president has had
ample resources with which to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   What, K speculated, if Clinton were an average American with
limited resources? And what about all of the average Americans who
have been dragged into the investigation and forced to hire
expensive legal counsel just to participate as witnesses?
</P>
<P>
   But beyond this specific case, he believed, Starr's
investigation set a perilous precedent that invited imitation by
prosecutors at all levels of jurisdiction. In fact, he knew people
who had been subjected to similar treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Such thoughts reinforced the news junkie's determination to
avoid the talking head shows for the duration of the White House
sex scandal. K was not just bored with the unseemly subject; it
also scared him breathless.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
