<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISHES-COLLECTING-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME IS WHERE THE DISHES ARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 16)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's all my grandmother's fault, really. If she
hadn't bequeathed me the colorful plates on which she'd served
roast chicken and garlic potatoes every Sunday for years, I would
never have started. Her haul of Harlequin _ those pointy-handled
cousins of Fiesta ware that once sold for a pittance at Woolworth's
but now command top dollar at collectibles shows _ set me on the
path to collecting-heaven and storage-hell. Thanks to her china,
dishes have become my obsession.
</P>
<P>
   The box of yellow-and-white-flowered Cavalier ironstone that
matches my kitchen perfectly found its way home from a Brooklyn
sidewalk sale, where it cost $12. The 18-piece set of McCoy
Suburbia with its so-wrong-it's-right 1964 color scheme came from a
New Jersey antiques mall. The '50s squared-off gray plates with big
pink hibiscus flowers on them _ Bali Hai by Continental Kilns _ are
the spoils of an Atlanta weekend.
</P>
<P>
   My Tropical and Tahiti dinnerware _ sister patterns in pale
chartreuse decorated with dark green palms _ has been gathered from
flea markets, dish-ware shows and resale shops. Last week, I added
a service for four of this fabulous frond-ware from an Upper West
Side collector, who agreed to sell his overstock after years of
hounding from me.
</P>
<P>
   That's just my vintage inventory.
</P>
<P>
   My new dishes _ those that have not been ``previously
experienced'' _ are an assortment of '80s period items and '90s
eccentricities, stored in every drawer and cabinet in my Manhattan
apartment. I've got collage-patterned dessert dishes by the fashion
designer Gene Meyer, which look like his mod ties and speak of
mid-'90s retro fever. Just the other day, a set of white, Japanese,
crackle-finish dishes from Williams-Sonoma cried out to me from the
sale table, ``How gorgeous would we look with your Tahiti?''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they're very now and very Zen _ pre-millennial
table-top calm.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I use any of them much. My dish collecting has little
to do with their actual employ. I haven't had a dinner party in
more than two years, and I eat most of my at-home meals out of the
containers in which they arrive.
</P>
<P>
   What has me hooked on dishes is the idea that someday I will
lead the wonderful life that will give me reason to use them. My
plethora of plates lets me fantasize about festivity, prosperity
and real estate. At nearly 36, I have everything I need to set up
house, except the house.
</P>
<P>
   My dishes let me dream of chic suppers on an exquisite urban
terrace overlooking something other than the black-tar roof next
door. In the weekend beach house I don't have, my virtual table
will be set with finery collected over years of travel. In these
porcelain-fueled flights of fancy, friends enjoy themselves,
celebrating their good fortune and our charmed lives together.
</P>
<P>
   When I bought a set of English bone china covered in spiraling
gold-leaf tendrils at the Barneys New York warehouse sale a year
ago, I imagined they'd be perfect if I had Tim Burton over for
Christmas dinner. I don't know him, but I am confident he'd love
these chic but slightly creepy dishes covered with my delicious but
highly caloric cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Although we joke about our obsession, those of us who collect
dishes take our penchant for place settings seriously. There is a
bit of madness behind the desire to collect a service for 40 of
Lu-Ray Pastels when you live in a New York apartment _ as one
couple I know has done _ but there is also something else.
Collecting an object so closely associated with family and
tradition is a way to establish a sense of security, a feeling of
sanctuary in an often hostile world.
</P>
<P>
   As John Pirman, an illustrator and a collector of vintage
Russell Wright and new Jonathan Adler ceramics, says, having the
right dishes ``makes me feel that my home is complete, like a big
family lives here, even though I'm single.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting a proper table lets many of us live down our unglamorous
pasts, too. Like so many suburban children in the '70s, I grew up
eating off Corelle, the ``living ware'' from Corning. Ringed in
blue cornflowers _ or worse, designs in harvest gold or avocado _
they were the leisure suits of dishes and lasted forever. You
couldn't break them if you tried, and I tried. There is some talk
that these hideous examples of technology over taste will be
collectible someday. Not by me. The settings I choose to collect
would make my grandmother _ and Martha Stewart _ proud.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, until I get that dream house, who has the room to store
any more?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
