<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     08-14 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYS AND GIRLS MAKE MISTAKES; ONLY GIRLS PAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, no matter how hard you try, no matter how many things
you get right, life can be like a spelling bee. Make one mistake,
and you're disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened recently to 17-year-olds Somer Chipman and
Chasity Glass. They took all the right classes, made the right
grades to get into the National Honor Society. Then they got
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Big mistake!
</P>
<P>
   Pregnant girls, even those with 3.9 and 3.7 grade-point
averages, aren't allowed membership in the National Honor Society.
Not at Grant County High School in Williamstown, Ky. No, girls
there who engage in premarital sex are not to be held up as role
models, no matter how much book smarts they have.
</P>
<P>
   Boys either, according to the admissions committee that
eliminated Somer and Chasity. But of course, boys can't get
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the problem with the rule book. And that as the
American Civil Liberties Union has concluded, makes the girls'
rejection, among other things, an act of sex discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's making a girl wear a scarlet P and bear the burden for
something that is a joint activity,'' ACLU attorney Sara L.
Mandelbaum told ``The New York Times.'' ``No boy is being left out
of the society for having engaged in premarital sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when you think those awful days of dragging pregnant girls
before the altar to ask for forgiveness are long gone, you discover
things haven't changed, and a lawsuit is in order.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, a spelling bee might have yielded better
results for Somer and Chasity. At least in a spelling bee, you can
ask questions about the derivation of the word stumping you and get
a straight answer.
</P>
<P>
   The young mothers were never officially told why they were the
only ones denied entry to the National Honor Society. When they
demanded an answer, they were told that they had not met the
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Ruberg, lawyer for the Grant County School Board of
Education, said that, given the fact that character is among the
criteria, the admissions committee did not feel that students who
had engaged in premarital sex should be held up for others to
emulate.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder if the admissions committee took some poll to
determine whether the other students were sexually active. And if
they didn't, how can they in good conscience eliminate Somer and
Chasity? After all, they have to know that not every sexually
active teen becomes pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Somer and Chasity admit they were wrong to have engaged in
premarital sex, but they consider abortion far worse. Who can argue
with that? And who can argue that teen-age mothers who not only
remain in school, but excel, lack character?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't give up my daughter for the world,'' Chasity was
quoted as saying. ``But I want to tell others how expensive it is,
how much work it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Let me hasten to say that teen-age pregnancy worries me as much
as the next person. And for all the obvious reasons, I wish every
teen could abstain from having sex until marriage. But when they
don't, none of us has the right to ostracize them, to tell them
they don't meet the criteria for being a role model, without
careful consideration of our own lives.
</P>
<P>
   When we do, life's missteps take on a whole other meaning for us
and our children. Rather than a spelling bee, where one error can
disqualify you, we get to live life like, well, baseball. No matter
who wins or loses, you get to try again next season.
</P>
<P>
   Somer and Chasity should be so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Send e-mail to gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
