<HEADER>
A4482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNTAN-LOTIONS-ART-$A     08-14 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNTAN-LOTIONS-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTTLED TANS GOOD ENOUGH TO FOOL A DERMATOLOGIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 16) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID COLMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say what you will about a deep dark tan, but for many it is this
season's vice of choice. With the consumption of luxuries _ and the
flaunting of a luxuriously pampered look _ at full throttle,
well-bronzed skin has a certain devil-may-care appeal, despite the
health risks.
</P>
<P>
   But if you must have the suntanned look, why not turn to the
large array of self-tanning creams, which allow the user to appear
heedlessly self-indulgent, without any actual damage?
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, men have been more reluctant to tangle with
self-tanning products than women have. That may be one factor in
why malignant melanoma, a skin cancer, is the most common form of
cancer diagnosed among white men between 35 and 39, according to
The New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Tellingly, it's often wives who first notice the signs and
insist that their husbands see a doctor, said Dr. Karyn Grossman, a
dermatologist who practices in Los Angeles and New York. Men may
resist self-tanning creams and lotions because, as Dr. Grossman put
it, ``guys think it's a girl thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellas _ get over it.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have resisted self-tanning potions in the belief
that the products leave an artificial orange cast to the skin, are
hard to apply and can stain clothing. But self-tanners have come a
long way since 1970s products like QT. Prestigious companies like
Chanel, Clarins, Lancome and Orlane entered the business a few
years ago, with much improved products.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the tan you can get without stepping outside is good
enough to fool a dermatologist. Products come in different shades
for different complexions. There are also lower-cost alternatives
from Neutrogena, Kiss My Face, Bain de Soleil and even that '70s
stalwart Sea &AMP; Ski.
</P>
<P>
   An array of creams, gels, mousses and sprays now make
application easier. Putting them on requires knowing two tricks.
First, use a lot _ after all, you wouldn't skimp on house paint.
Second, fill the sink with water and repeatedly wet your hands
while applying the stuff. No tell-tale streaks that way, because
the water dilutes the product and lets it go on more evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Self-tanners work by using a dye that provides no protection
from sunburn. But several products, like those from Chanel and
Clarins, also include a sun-blocking formula with an SPF of 6 or 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot to be said for having a tan,'' said Jean
Godfrey-June, the beauty director of Elle magazine and an avid
self-tanner. ``You look better, you look thinner, you look happier,
more rested and so on. If people tell me I look tired, I just put
on some self-tanner, and I'm just back from vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest problem with self-tanner today, she added, is
actually how well it works, since people are often horrified to
discover that a tan is fake, as they used to be when hair turned
out to be dyed. ``People somehow think that a self-tan is somehow
more vain than going out and getting a real tan,'' Ms. Godfrey-June
said. ``But I would be far more embarrassed about ending up burnt
to a leathery crisp in 30 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
