<HEADLINE>
HBO'S `BABE RUTH' FAILS TO SEPARATE THE MAN FROM THE MYTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My favorite Babe Ruth anecdote is the one about the 600-foot
home-run blast that lands in the exact spot where the rotund Ruth
pointed moments before that wayward pitch _ the upper deck of the
center-field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   To argue this fact/myth with a Ruth connoisseur is often
pointless, possibly even life-threatening, and HBO's ``Babe Ruth''
(7 p.m. CDT Sunday) doesn't clear up the matter.
</P>
<P>
   It does, at the very least, offer grainy slo-mo footage of Ruth
gesturing in some way to left field. But it looks as though he's
telling some overzealous patron to sit down and shut up, which
might actually be closer to the truth because Ruth was also known
for possessing a healthy supply of crude arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Author Jean Shepherd, one of many talking heads spewing Ruthisms
during the hour, asks, ``What's the fuss?'' _ that the Babe's
point-and-hit is ``a harmless little myth'' and, besides, ``a lot
of people believe in Santa Claus.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone ought to tell Shepherd that Santa Claus really IS a
myth.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Babe Ruth, whose baseball statistics really are
astonishing, has been a victim of his own legend, a man whose
contributions will always be debated and questioned and
exaggerated, like Satchel Paige and those Negro Leaguers whose
extraordinary exploits grow with every retold account. (The story
of a player being able to catch his own fly ball hit to deep center
field is one.) Reality, it seems, evaporates as the myth becomes
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Like drunken barflies making up stories as they go, the
sportswriters, authors and others who offer up Ruthisms here are a
lively bunch. ``Babe Ruth,'' then, ought to be viewed as an
entertaining tribute, not a fully annotated study, if it is to be
digested without disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of ``He was a living man who became a mythic god
and nothing can change that,'' and ``To me the Babe is still alive;
he is truly like Shakespeare _ he'll never die,'' and ``The truth
is that Ruth is bigger than the myth.'' Faces zip on and off the
screen, usually gray-haired fellas in fedoras leaning next to
typewriters, some fighting back tears when spinning their favorite,
personal Ruth tale.
</P>
<P>
   One sportswriter put this worship reportage in perspective by
claiming that the publicity-loving Ruth had a jovial nature when
meeting with the press and could make each media scribe feel
special. ``It was like writing about a friend,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This relationship played so well with newspaper beat writers and
radio reporters that they would never reveal a discouraging word
about the Babe, even though he was quite the boozer and womanizer.
His uncultured ways were ``cute,'' although reporters appeared to
be less forgiving of other players.
</P>
<P>
   In actuality, Ruth was a complex mix of crudeness and inner
turmoil, a personality formed without discipline. Growing up in
Baltimore, Ruth was such a little terror that his father, a saloon
keeper, shipped him off to reform school at age 8. This is about as
psychologically deep as ``Babe Ruth'' gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babe Ruth'' does make mention of Ruth's inability to manage
family, though. He was married at age 19 to a 16-year-old, but he
tired of that union when his career with the Boston Red Sox took
off.
</P>
<P>
   He abandoned his family (they adopted a daughter) due to ``the
temptations of fame and fortune. He devoured food, sex and fun,''
says the narrator, ``living up to his reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth used to have his female ``visitations'' in the morning
before ballgames. Another myth involved a woman who supposedly made
her way to the dugout with a gun, firing shots at the Babe but
missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babe Ruth,'' produced by Ross Greenburg and Rick Bernstein,
doesn't attempt to separate Ruth's artistry from his celebrity,
even though it is central to his place in baseball. This often
throws the documentary out of balance, but does not make it devoid
of merit.
</P>
<P>
   By far the best things about ``Babe Ruth'' are the still photos
and motion-camera footage, covering ground from Ruth's days as a
star pitcher in Boston to his glory days in New York, to his public
funeral procession. Many of his towering homers are shown, and the
most moving footage shows how baseball, like any business, has its
share of coldheartedness. As Ruth's skills diminished, the Yankees
pushed him out the door. He'd return at age 40, lured by
``promises'' of being a manager, only to be used as a gate
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth is shown as a spokesman for Ford and other products,
playing mock ``games'' like a used-up prizefighter.
</P>
<P>
   A frail Ruth died of cancer in 1948, and it's not until you see
these photos, showing a humbled, dejected Ruth, that you can
separate man from sport. -
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere this week:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Smart Guy'' was more effective on the same topic in a
half-hour episode, but the two-hour ``Every Mother's Worst Fear''
(8 p.m. CDT Wednesday on USA) has its moments in dramatizing the
creepy side of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Ladd and her real-life daughter, Jordan, are mother and
daughter here, Connie and Martha Hoagland. Martha falls into ``a
real cool'' chat room only to be tricked into traveling to another
city, where she faces a psychopath. Things only get worse from
there.
</P>
<P>
   After the FBI become convinced that Martha is a runaway and not
a kidnapping victim, they bail, leaving Connie to track down her
daughter on her own, ending with a climactic, dragged-out tussle.
</P>
<P>
   Predictable and often corny, ``Every Mother's Worst Fear''
blames divorced parents and working moms for Martha's Internet
obsession, spending far too much time explaining what it's trying
to say: Kids, be careful. As one terrified mother says after seeing
``date'' chats where teens simulate having sex, ``I never knew
there were chats like this!'' ...
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
