<P>
   CLINTON-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Developments on White House
strategy for Clinton's Monday testimony before the Kenneth Starr
grand jury. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-FDA (Richmond, Va.) _ A federal appeals court said the
Food and Drug Administration has no authority to regulate tobacco
and threw out restrictions on the sale of cigarettes to minors. By
Barry Meier. (Summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NH-VOICES (Dover, N.H.) _ In 1992 Bill Clinton, his New
Hampshire primary campaign wounded by allegations of extra-marital
affairs and questions about his draft record, defied speculation
that he would have to drop out and instead, at the Elks hall here,
vowed to stick it out until ``the last dog dies.'' Today, in that
same Elks hall, club members and buyers at an antiques auction
voiced yet another chorus of defiant indifference to the
allegations against him. Pausing for emphasis, Bob Carroll, an
auctioneer, said, ``Leave. The poor man. Alone.'' By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ After days of speculative attacks on
its currency, Hong Kong's government confirmed that it had launched
a counter-strike by intervening in the stock and futures markets.
By Mark Landler.
</P>
