<HEADLINE>
BANK MERGER MEANS JACKPOT FOR SOME PARTING EXECUTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One of the severance packages doled out in the
fallout over the proposed merger of BankAmerica Corp. and
NationsBank Corp. merger could cover the $10 monthly checking
charge for 2.3 million account holders for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ... Or pay the $25 annual fee for 920,000 credit card customers.
</P>
<P>
   ... Or pay the yearly salaries of about 80 tellers.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you slice it, a $23 million severance package is a
lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   According to human resource and compensation experts, packages
in excess of $10 million and $20 million are becoming the
going-away rate for a top executive these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the numbers, they may seem staggering, but
they are not inconsistent with the industry,'' said Gregory Green,
a Santa Fe, N.M.-based vice president for the outplacement firm
Challenger, Gray and Christmas. ``Everyone in this business at this
level creates golden parachutes for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Although regulators still must approve the $57.9 billion merger
of San Francisco-based Bank of America and the Charlotte,
N.C.-based NationsBank, the deal has already cost several top Bank
of America executives their jobs. Four of the bank's top seven
executives are packing up. But they will hardly be walking away
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   H. Eugene Lockhart, 48, who left his position as chief executive
with MasterCard International to join the bank just 11 months
before the merger, will receive a severance package worth about $23
million. Lockhart's position for the combined bank, which covered
global retail banking, will be filled by a NationsBank executive.
</P>
<P>
   Martin A. Stein, vice chairman and director of technology and
operations, also is being displaced by a NationsBank executive.
Stein, 58, who has been with the bank eight years, will receive
three times his $1.95 million salary plus about $3.7 million in
restricted stock options for a total of $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also leaving are Bank of America's highest ranking woman,
47-year-old Kathleen J. Burke, head of human resources, and Jack L.
Meyers, 55, head of risk management. The bank did not disclose the
amount of their severance deals, but they are worth three years of
salary and bonuses plus options and stock.
</P>
<P>
   While Bank of America chief executive David Coulter, who will be
the No. 2 man at the united bank, said he is not planning to leave,
his employment contract would give him more than $30 million in
compensation if he leaves after the merger. He is expected to
replace NationsBank chief executive Hugh McColl Jr., 65, when
McColl retires.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America officials said that they didn't know how many
bank employees would be leaving, but that they would have a clearer
idea when the merger is finalized, probably at the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are doing is looking at all of the functions and
choosing the best of the best for the new company,'' said Bank of
America spokesman Dennis Wyss.
</P>
<P>
   The top six positions at the combined bank are split evenly
between the San Francisco and Charlotte banks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles King of William M. Mercer Inc. in San Francisco, a human
resources and management consulting firm, said he did not expect
major layoffs among rank-and-file employees because the territories
of the two companies did not overlap. He said mid-level managers,
however, might be hit harder.
</P>
<P>
   As for the large-scale payouts, King said it was part of doing
business following a merger. ``There's only a tiny, tiny minority
of people who have the background, the track record and maneuvering
ability to put together that kind of deal,'' he said. ``They've
spent a lifetime earning the right to get this big payoff.''
</P>
<P>
   King said the parachutes were not shocking, considering the
combined company would have nearly $570 billion in assets. The
severance packages ``are not trivial, but very near trivial
considering the magnitude of the deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America is known for its generous executive compensation
agreements, said Frank Glassner, managing director of Compensation
Resource Group, a national executives compensation and benefits
consulting firm based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Glassner said shareholders would revolt if they thought the
severance packages were too high, or high enough to jeopardize the
cost-saving benefits of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   And cases like that of Lockhart, who was with Bank of America
for less than a year, just underscore why it is important for
executives to negotiate strong employment agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, one does not expect the company they have just
joined and given up solid employment opportunities for to get
bought within a year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not all compensation experts thought the arrangements were
typical for top-level managers. Beverlee Rydel of Michigan-based TR
Human Resource Services, which specializes in negotiating severance
packages, said high-ranking executives rarely get more than $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shocking number,'' Rydel said in reaction to the Bank
of America figures. ``But severances are based on risks, and you
have to look at all the risks based on terminating someone at that
level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
