<HEADLINE>
THAT CURIOUS ROLLS-ROYCE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The automobile business gets curiouser and curiouser _ and the
curious cup this week goes to the new owners of Rolls-Royce ...
whoever they are.
</P>
<P>
   That venerable British company known for its exquisite
automobiles has been sold as only the British could do it _ not
just to the highest bidder but, apparently, to all the bidders.
Volkswagen gets the factory in Crewe and the Bentley rights; BMW,
the original buyer _ or so we thought _ gets ownership of the
Rolls-Royce trademark, which it will lend to VW until 2003(?), and
the stockholders of Vickers PLC get a pile of money _ except that
some of it will have to be invested in the new BMW company building
the Royce ... is this beginning to sound like a daytime soap?
</P>
<P>
   It started as a fairy tale. Once upon a time, a poor but honest
engineer, Henry Royce, disappointed with his French automobile that
kept breaking down, built a fine English car that ran so smoothly,
one could balance a penny on its bonnet whilst the engine were
running _ Henry left school at 10 to go to work, before the grammar
lessons ``took.'' That was 1904.
</P>
<P>
   Royce's great success was noticed by Charles Rolls, a wealthy
aristocrat in the business of selling those unreliable foreign
cars, and he immediately did what the rich do when they see a poor
bloke with a good thing _ he horned in. In 1906, the Rolls-Royce
company was launched (notice whose name went on the sign first).
</P>
<P>
   In 1910, Rolls achieved the dubious distinction of becoming the
first Englishman to be killed in an airplane crash.
</P>
<P>
   By 1914, the company was well established and began building
aircraft engines, which also proved successful. During World War I,
Lawrence of Arabia originated desert tank warfare with a fleet of
nine armored Rolls-Royce cars, thus establishing a long tradition
of Rolls-Royce sales in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In 1931, Rolls-Royce acquired Bentley and two years later Royce
died. In World War II, Rolls built the famed Merlin engine that
powered the Supermarine Spitfire, Hawker Hurricane, and the North
American P-51. Postwar, Rolls became a power in aviation. And went
broke doing it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, in dire financial straits, the motor car and diesel
divisions survived as a public company, Rolls-Royce Motors; in
1980, that company merged with what is now Vickers PLC. In 1998,
the car company, once again in dire financial straits, was put on
the block by Vickers.
</P>
<P>
   BMW, the company that built the Luftwaffe engines that the
Spitfires were shooting at in the air war, was apparently the
successful bidder. A deal was announced. Volkswagen, builder of
Hitler's ``people's car'' and wings for Messerschmitt fighters,
slipped a higher bid under the back door, so to speak, and it was
announced that ``in the interest of Vickers stockholders'' _ more
dough _ Volkswagen would get the company.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where the story really gets weirdly complicated. Rolls
had decided that its engines could no longer pass muster in the
face of increasingly stringent pollution requirements, couldn't
afford to develop a new motor, and so had contracted for BMW
engines. When VW got Rolls, BMW said it would cancel the engine
contract. Suddenly, VW had a factory to produce engineless cars.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the deal had never included the Rolls-Royce trademark _
Rolls-Royce Motor Co. leased its name from the mother corporation,
a holdover from previous restructuring. So, BMW bid $66 million and
bought the label _ it would build a new facility in Britain to put
a car under it. It was looking like the deal from hell. Orders for
Rolls-Royce cars plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, a good fairy has come to the rescue, disguised as a
golf bag _ the whole mess was reportedly ironed out on a golf
course. As the deal now stands, BMW gives its blessing to VW to use
the trademark and build the cars at Crewe until Dec. 31, 2002,
presumably when its new factory will be ready. BMW will continue to
build engines for the VW Royce. In 2003, BMW begins building
Rolls-Royce models in a new facility in England, and VW is limited
to Bentleys. According to Automotive News, VW at that time will
begin supplying Royce car bodies to the new BMW company.
</P>
<P>
   What's really weird is that these two archrivals will enter into
a joint marketing arrangement selling both cars through the
existing dealer networks. If you thought Chrysler-Daimler was
strange, this is really cuckoo.
</P>
<P>
   I guess the next question is: Will the Germans learn to like tea
and warm beer? And will they all live happily ever after?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A recent column on driver ed prompted some mail and news of a
new driver ed opportunity. Sandy Stevens, driving trainer for
police academies and operator of an advanced driving school for
many years, has teamed up with an insurance company, Vermont Fire,
to offer real training to the novice driver.
</P>
<P>
   The program stems from the insurance company's unusual approach
to insuring young drivers: Don't gouge them for stiff premiums
until after an accident but offer them training to avoid mishaps.
Cost of the training session is $100, thanks to subsidies from the
insurance firm; similar courses go for $400-$500.
</P>
<P>
   For information, write to Sandy Stevens, PO Box 1122, Merrimack,
NH 03054.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Stevens offers a videotape study course in driving
technique for $39.95 plus $4 shipping _ same address. No, you can't
learn to drive watching a tape, but it will sort out the good
information from the myths and start you thinking correctly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
