<HEADLINE>
MISSING OUT ON ARKANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- The first lady says that many of her husband's
critics are biased against Bill Clinton's native soil. ``I think a
lot of this is prejudice against our state,'' she told the Arkansas
Democrat-Gazette. ``They wouldn't do this if we were from some
other state.''
</P>
<P>
   This spirited attack on the ``prejudice against our state''
comes at a peculiar time from Mrs. Clinton, who grew up in a
Chicago suburb and did not reside in Arkansas until after she
attended Wellesley College and Yale Law School. Just when they
could use the lift of home cookin' and the bracing air of the
Ozarks, the Clintons will soon decamp for Martha's Vineyard, a
crowded, expensive island off the coast of Massachusetts
geographically and culturally remote from Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who say that Arkansas lacks diversity and
culture. To that, many loyal Razorbacks reply ``Bull Shoals!'' That
is the name of a 100,000-acre state park, a paradise for boating,
fishing, and picnics. For cultural diversity, there's a nice view
of the Boston Mountains. And how can Nantucket Sound compete with
Lake Ouachita?
</P>
<P>
   Martha's Vineyard features gourmet ice cream, but by skipping an
Arkansas August, the first family will miss the annual Watermelon
Fest in the president's hometown of Hope, not to mention the Great
Arkansas Pig-Out in Morrilton and Mosquito Awareness Weekend in
Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always been a restless sort. From Hope, he went to
Hot Springs, Georgetown University, Yale Law School, and Oxford
University. His striving makes him seem more Oxford than Ozark.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he owes no particular obligation to the Arkansas tourist
business. No one can begrudge him his vacation choice. It's not an
election year, and his former image-shaper, Dick Morris, can't urge
all-American camping in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Any president's vacation gives a clue as to his retirement
plans. In this respect, Massachusetts loses to California. This
president comes here as often as other people go to the post
office. He was in San Francisco last week, and when he comes again,
the board of elections will be ready to register him to vote.
Recreational fund-raising is to him what flyfishing was to Herbert
Hoover and Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Among recent presidents, most have returned home. George Bush is
in Texas, while summering in Maine. Ronald Reagan is in California,
and Jimmy Carter is in Georgia. But Gerald Ford does not live in
Michigan, which he served in Congress for 24 years. He divides his
time between California and Colorado. Calvin Coolidge, now enjoying
an overdue reappraisal, loved his native New England, but also
liked summer in the Black Hills of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma for the Arkansas tourist business can be solved by
advertising. ``The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn'' relates the
troubles of a traveling show, of which Mark Twain's character says:
``So the duke said these Arkansaw lunkheads couldn't come up to
Shakespeare; what they wanted was low comedy _ and maybe something
rather worse than low comedy, he reckoned.'' The duke then ``made
up some handbills for his show, with one line in capital letters:
`LADIES AND CHILDREN NOT ADMITTED.' `There,' says he, `if that line
don't fetch them, I don't know Arkansaw!'''
</P>
<P>
   According to the AAA guide, ``Mountain, delta, and prairie meet
in Arkansas. The blend makes the state a vacationland where
fashionable resorts are complemented by traditional backwood
lifestyles and a wide variety of recreational opportunities.
Renowned natural springs, sparkling lakes and streams, monuments of
frontier history, more than 2 million acres of National Forest
lands, six National Parks, and the only diamond mine in the country
that is open to the public give Arkansas diverse appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional backwood lifestyles and a wide variety of
recreational opportunities?'' Well, if that line don't fetch them
tourists, I don't know Arkansaw.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
