<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METHODIST CHURCH'S BAN OF SAME-SEX CEREMONIES CHEERED, JEERED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conservatives gained important ground in one of America's
historic denominations this week when the United Methodist Church's
``supreme court'' affirmed as binding a ban on ministers performing
same-sex covenants for homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The blunt effect of the ruling is that Methodist ministers who
conduct same-sex ceremonies can be defrocked.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the ruling elated Methodist conservatives. Liberals
were distressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day for United Methodism,'' said Mark Bowman of
Chicago, director of a nationwide Reconciling Churches program for
some 150 congregations that reach out to gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lesbian and gay persons continue to be second-class members of
United Methodist churches ...,'' Bowman said. ``They can sit in the
pew and give their money, but their loving relationships cannot be
recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   But United Methodist bishops who backed the ruling said it does
not mean that gays and lesbians are not welcome in the 9.5-million
member denomination. It simply proclaims the validity of a church
statement adopted by the General Conference, the church's highest
legislative body, the bishops said. Delegates adopted the ban in
1996 during a convention in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Debates have gone on since then as to whether the same-sex union
ban is advisory or mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute increased this year when the Rev. Jimmy Creech was
narrowly acquitted in a church trial in Nebraska after he conducted
a same-sex ceremony last year for a lesbian couple.
</P>
<P>
   Creech, then pastor of the First United Methodist Church of
Omaha, argued that the ban was advisory, because it appeared in the
Social Principles section of the Book of Discipline, the Methodist
book of rules. Social Principles, Creech said, traditionally have
been interpreted as advisory.
</P>
<P>
   But the nine-member United Methodist Judicial Council _ after a
two-day meeting in the Metroplex _ disagreed. They ruled that the
edict declaring ministers ``shall not'' conduct same-sex unions is
clearly a ban and has the force of law.
</P>
<P>
   Another advocate for gay rights, Kathryn Johnson of Washington,
D.C., president of the Methodist Federation for Social Action, said
her church is moving backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time in history when gay and lesbian persons are gaining
... greater acceptance in society, it is tragic that the United
Methodist Church would be a place where they cannot experience full
acceptance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Methodists were buoyed by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' said the Rev. Dean Posey of Bedford, Texas.
``This issue has been debated a long time, and this ruling makes it
unquestionably clear what the position of the church is.''
</P>
<P>
   Posey said he hopes the decision means that the church of John
Wesley is moving back to its conservative roots and that it will
lead to strengthening the church's current stand against ordaining
gays.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight is not over, said James Heidinger, executive
director of Good News, a United Methodist conservative coalition
based in Wilmore, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the many United Methodists who disagree
with the ruling will challenge it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that about 240 pastors signed a statement this year
saying they would conduct same-sex ceremonies if asked,'' Heidinger
said. ``I'm going to guess that someone will push a test case.''
</P>
<P>
   But those pastors will have to think twice before carrying out
their promise. If they defy the church edict, they could be without
a job.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
