<HEADER>
A4534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MUMMIES-2TAKES-AR     08-14 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MUMMIES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANCIENT EGYPT MOVES INTO NEW QUARTERS AT THE MFA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Egyptian and Ancient Near Eastern collections in
the Museum of Fine Arts used to be housed in quarters that
suggested ``The Mummy's Curse.'' They were either banished to
basement storage that was dark and dank or consigned to galleries
that weren't much better. Not very respectful treatment for a
collection that dates back to 1872, just two years after the
museum's founding, and ranks among the world's best.
</P>
<P>
   All that changes as of Saturday, Aug. 15, with the opening of
the museum's lavishly renovated galleries for this material. The
oldest objects in the MFA's collections now reside in the most
modern quarters in the whole museum complex.
</P>
<P>
   The galleries cost a bundle. The MFA acknowledges that, but
won't say exactly how much, only that a members' campaign raised
$1.2 million toward the overhaul. A particularly populist
fund-raiser _ more than 9,000 individual gifts, ranging from $5 to
$30,000 _ it reflects the popularity of these collections.
Everybody loves the mummies.
</P>
<P>
   The galleries were designed to prolong the life of objects
celebrating death _ objects from Egypt, a society obsessed with the
hereafter, and from the Ancient Near East, parts of which were
equally obsessed with mass murder. Or, as MFA curator Rita Freed
cheerfully puts it, ``Ancient Near Eastern art was about killing as
many people as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 700 newly ensconced objects have never been on
public view before, and others have been hidden away for their own
protection. The MFA's mummies first enjoyed the luxury of climate
control during their appearance in the 1988 Gund Gallery show
``Mummies and Magic.'' They got spoiled. They couldn't stand the
strain of returning to MFA galleries where ``climate control''
meant electric fans and open windows, so they went to an area of
storage where (itals)real(unitals) climate control existed. Only
now are some of them surfacing again.
</P>
<P>
   One enormous 6th-century BC sarcophagus _ a black basalt monster
belonging to a general named Kheper-Re _ is not only surfacing, but
standing at attention. Meant to spend eternity in a prone position,
the sacophagus is now bolt upright. Authenticity has been
sacrificed for drama: The looming, dimly lit anthropomorphic
sculpture looks ready to cast a spell on you.
</P>
<P>
   At least the 2-ton sarcophagus won't fall on you _ not even in
an earthquake. Arthur Beale, the MFA's director of objects
conservation and scientific research, explains that extensive
earthquake precautions make the new galleries the place to be when
the Big One hits Boston. And it just might, warns Beale, adding
that there was a major quake here in the 18th century, and that the
museum's location on filled land makes it particularly vulnerable.
So, to rev up for the renovation, Beale headed to California to
study seismic retrofitting, and came back to oversee the building
of steel ``cocoons'' around each case in the new galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Another earthquake precaution: The stones in that ornately
carved 5-ton tomb wall are no longer resting on one another,
although they look as if they are. Each is now separately
suspended. In the event of an earthquake, they'll bounce, not
break.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber optic lighting, used more extensively here than anywhere
else in the museum, cuts the excess heat that can turn exhibit
cases into greenhouses, eliminates emissions that might endanger
fragile objects, and can be changed without opening exhibit cases
and disturbing their delicate environments. Silica gels in the
bases of the new cases control the humidity around artworks that
used to live in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the most advanced microclimates we've used in the
museum,'' says Beale. ``We've set a benchmark for all future
installations here.'' That benchmark has made walking out of the
new spaces and into the adjacent classical or Nubian galleries like
walking out of the First World and into the Third, where air
conditioning is but a dream, and August is sauna season.
</P>
<P>
   Beale's contributions to the new galleries are elaborate,
expensive, state-of-the-art _ and invisible. All that fiber optic
plastic and glass spaghetti, all those silica gels, are hidden
away, in the interest of creating an atmosphere akin to the tomb
scene in ``Aida'' for the Egyptian gallery, and a Cecil B. De
Mille-ish version of ancient Babylon in the one devoted to the
Ancient Near East.
</P>
<P>
   In these new spaces the MFA has signed on to the recent
museological trend toward galleries-as-stage-sets, especially in
the Ancient Near Eastern gallery, with its approximation of the
archways and ziggurat-shaped crenellations from the Great Ishtar
Gate in Babylon. The designers _ the architectural firm
Jung/Brannen Associates Inc., who worked with the MFA's in-house
team _ must have had fun coming up with details to help define the
Ancient Near East for Americans who are vague even on where it was.
Hence their cleverest stroke _ a map of the area made of colored
stones, embedded in the floor as if it were an ancient mosaic. A
single map can't show 6,000 years' worth of shifting borders, of
course, so this map doesn't have any _ just strategically placed
names of cities, countries, and bodies of water. Some, like
``Babylon'' and ``Ninevah,'' have a magical ring; occasionally,
there's a modern intrusion, as with ``Iran.'' The floor map also
saves valuable wall space, and is child-friendly: Freed expects to
see school groups sitting on the carpet beside it.
</P>
<P>
   Another curator might have installed an image with a come-hither
look at the entrance of a new gallery, to lure visitors in. Not
Freed. ``This is our banner,'' she says proudly, pointing to a
9th-century BC Assyrian stone relief of a demigod she pronounces
``a brute.'' This thug's role was to protect King Assurnasirpal II
from harm, by scaring off evil spirits. While he looks as if he's
been spending his days at Gold's Gym, the shallow carving that
defines his bulky contours is crisp, even dainty. Reliefs of
demigods once lined the halls of Assyrian palaces; in the 19th
century, though, Christian missionaries brought them back by the
cartload to Europe and America, not just for their aesthetic merit,
but for their Biblical associations as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4538 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MUMMIES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     08-14 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MUMMIES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... associations as well.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On one wall of the new gallery is a Babylonian lion, one of many
excavated by Germans who didn't have enough room to show them all,
so they sold off parts, including the one the MFA bought in the
1930s. It's made of bricks glazed in gold and turquoise, colors
that still sparkle in spots. The lion's mouth is wide open.
``Egyptian lions have closed mouths,'' Freed observes. ``But this
one is ready to chew.'' There's more chewing in a stone relief from
Persepolis, in which a lion chomps on the flank of a bull. However
gory the subject, the style is lyrical and rhythmic, and the lion
has a cuddly, overgrown pussycat look.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the aid of the map and the well-written wall texts,
most visitors will find the ``where's'' and ``when's'' of this
gallery confusing. (Freed suggests you start by remembering you're
looking at 6,000 years of history in an area 6,000 miles in
circumference.) But the objects themselves are so enchanting
they'll spur you on to learn more. They're arranged in
chronological rather than geographical order, starting with the
object that is possibly the oldest in the entire museum _ a stone
vessel in the shape of a sweet little bunny, which may date from as
early as 6400 BC. Sharing the same case is neolithic pottery from
southwest Turkey, painted with jazzy zigzag patterns that Art Deco
would borrow thousands of years later.
</P>
<P>
   Gold funerary jewelry from northwest coastal Turkey suggests you
can take it with you. The sleek designs _ spirals, twining rope,
animal heads _ may make you want to take these exquisite bracelets
and rings home with you instead. The MFA gift shop, big on selling
replicas, should take note.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most charming of all the objects here is a board game
dating from 2000-1500 BC. It involves pegs and holes, and although
it was popular from Egypt to Iran, contemporary archeologists can
only make educated guesses about its rules _ and about the
consequences for the loser.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room is a tiny amulet, just an inch or so high, which
would have been worn by a pregnant woman to ward off Lamashtu, a
particularly nasty demon in the habit of killing newborns. She's
shown here cackling with glee and carrying off the bribes the
mother-to-be has given her to go away: a comb and safety pin,
trinkets whose modesty suggests Lamashtu should up the ante.
</P>
<P>
   A corridor is lined with cases containing Ancient Near Eastern
coins, helmets, and jewelry including a single earring that was set
with 460 separate specks of semiprecious stones. There's also an
incense burner in the form of a dromedary, from the enigmatic
Nabataean civilization _ which Americans know from the Nabataean
capital, Petra, the red-rock city used as a setting for ``Raiders
of the Lost Ark.''
</P>
<P>
   That corridor leads to the new gallery for Egyptian funerary
arts, where you first encounter a mummification how-to, a case
filled with implements for procedures including pulling out the
brain through a corpse's nose. Turquoise faience canopic jars were
for storing the deceased's organs, although they look like
contemporary kitchen canisters where you'd keep flour and sugar.
There's a mummy tag, used ``so your grandmother didn't get mixed up
with someone else's,'' Freed explains, adding that there's no
record in ancient Egypt of the equivalent of the baby-switching you
hear about in American hospitals. (For those who can't get enough
of mummification, Robert Brier, the first person in 2,000 years to
mummify a cadaver in authentic Egyptian style, speaks at the MFA on
Oct. 29.)
</P>
<P>
   The new gallery's stars are, not surprisingly, the mummies,
along with their gorgeously painted coffins and their fleets of
shawabtis, the little fellows who did the dirty work for you in the
afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the MFA's Egyptian treasures came to the museum
early in this century, as a result of joint MFA-Harvard excavations
sanctioned by the Egyptian government, this new installation
includes recent loans, gifts, and purchases. Leveraged buyout king
Thomas Lee, cited recently by ARTnews as one of the world's top 200
collectors, has loaned a serenely beautiful mummy mask with
geometric patterns painted on a buttercup-yellow ground, the color
alone hinting at happiness in the Great Beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Freed was particularly pleased with a recent gift from the
Shackford family of Wellesley, who called Freed and said they
didn't want the responsibility of taking care of their papyrus
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' says Freed, ``I went out to Wellesley for tea and came
back with a fragment from the `Book of the Dead.''' It's a
particularly lovely fragment, with attenuated figures acting out
the Weighing of the Heart, the crucial test to see if you'd been
good enough in this life to qualify for bliss in the next. If you
flunked, you were fed to the crocodile-headed monster Ammit.
</P>
<P>
   For the Egyptians, death was just the beginning. For the MFA,
the Egyptian gallery is just the beginning of the long process of
bringing the old part of the museum into the 21st century. For
Egyptomaniacs, the new gallery is a warm-up for the first major
international loan show on Egypt that the MFA has mounted since
1982. ``Pharaohs of the Sun,'' opening in November 1999, celebrates
the 17-year reign of Akhenaten, who was not only history's first
monotheist, but also husband of Nefertiti _ Egypt's second most
famous glamour girl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
