<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-RUBLE-CHAOS-NY     08-14 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RUBLE-CHAOS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA NEEDS LEADERSHIP, NOT IMF BAILOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Just weeks ago, after many rounds of hard bargaining, the IMF
finally authorized a $22.6 billion loan package for Russia.
Meanwhile, the Russian markets have continued to plunge and the
fear that Russia would devalue the ruble is as strong as ever.
Despite initial optimism from the IMF, investors are apparently
still full of doubt, asking hard questions about progress before
they put their money into Russia.
 &HT;    Amid all this, the ordinary men and women on the street are
living day to day, trying to feed their children, often going for
weeks and months unpaid, despite holding, perhaps, two or three
jobs and exhausting themselves with work.
 &HT;    What is the problem here? Is Russia, as the president states,
really under control?
 &HT;    Other questions are being asked too both in Russia and the West:
Has the IMF done the right thing? Will the new IMF bailout affect
the Russian situation in a positive way? How can IMF money
influence the course of events in Russia?
 &HT;    At home and abroad, I am asked whether aid to Russia is
necessary and, if so, what kind of aid. Legitimate questions, all
of them.
 &HT;    It seems that the new monetary package is an endorsement of the
program of anti-crisis measures proposed by the government of Prime
Minister Kirienko. When presenting the plan to Parliament, the
prime minister said that the Cabinet was in effect charting a new
economic policy aimed above all at reviving production.
 &HT;    But it is already clear that the new economic policy is no more
than a mirage. The measures that the government has been able to
push through the Duma and the recent presidential decrees merely
introduce tougher fiscal policies in accordance with IMF
requirements.
 &HT;    Whatever modest steps were initially planned to stimulate
production _ the real economy _ have now been dropped from the
government's program. The tax burden is set to increase, most of it
falling on the beleaguered people. Hence, the too-small amounts of
real income and effective demand can be expected to shrink. With
tax pressures on business continuing to increase, economic growth
will not resume.
 &HT;    In today's global society, a total collapse of the Russian
economy would send tremors throughout the world. The old Cold War
thinking _ ``let them suffer, we will win'' _ has no place in this
world where boundaries are slim and we are one people.
 &HT;    If Russia and its partners are facing a dead end, this has
strong implications for the West, for Asia and for the rest of the
world.
 &HT;    What I believe is that the root causes of the crisis _ despite
Western bailouts _ lie in Russia. They lie in the flawed economic
policies pursued for seven years now with the West's support. These
policies have had a bad effect on Russia. They have discredited
democracy and magnified corruption, lawlessness and arbitrary rule.
They have allowed organized crime to penetrate ever deeper into the
bodies of government.
 &HT;    The point at issue is this: How long do we wait? Will the loans
save the day? Will they cause the inertia to be reversed?
 &HT;    In Russia, most analysts feel that the IMF package, based on the
pledges of the president and the Kirienko government, just like the
previous bailout in spring 1997, is bound to fail because it lacks
popular support. If so _ and the conclusion rings true _ what
should we expect? Moscow is awash with scenarios trying to predict
further developments.
 &HT;    If the president and his entourage continue to insist on a
flawed and unworkable economic program, it could ignite mass
protest. Currently, 90 percent of those polled think that a social
upheaval could erupt in Russia in the near future. It is quite
ominous and the events could go out of control. This is an
unacceptable scenario.
 &HT;    But there is a different course of action, which offers a
realistic alternative to chaos. I suggest that if the breathing
space allowed by the IMF loan _ we were told that it would allow us
a respite _ does exist, then it should be used as time to chart a
more or less orderly way out of the most dramatic phase of the
current crisis.
 &HT;    It is up to us to implement the reforms that best suit our own
circumstances. Our reforms are entirely our responsibility. We do
need support from other nations. I am, however, against handouts.
We need equal and mutually beneficial cooperation.
 &HT;    I believe we should have early presidential and parliamentary
elections, held simultaneously, this fall or early spring, to open
the way to a type of federal government that would have credibility
among a majority of the Russian people and thus be strong enough to
implement a program for ending Russia's crisis.
 &HT;    The president should call for these elections, and they should
be coupled with a referendum on certain sections of the
Constitution, in order to reallocate the powers of government
between the president, the cabinet and parliament. Russia's 1993
Constitution, which vested the president with unlimited powers, has
turned out to be both unworkable and dangerous.
 &HT;    It is a source of political instability, engendering
irresponsible behavior and confrontation between the branches of
government.
 &HT;    I also propose submitting to the referendum a constitutional
amendment creating a post of life-long senator for former
presidents after they leave office. Such an initiative would help
to ease this very dramatic moment, avoiding a dangerous division in
Russian society and assuring a democratic transition from one team
to another.
 &HT;    The time has come for the president to prove that Russia's
interests and stability and, above all, the interests of its people
are indeed his highest priority.
 &HT;     c.1998 LaStampa  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston. He also writes a
monthly commentary column for La Stampa, a newspaper in Turin,
Italy.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
