<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-FOREI     08-14 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-FOREIGN-0815-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONICA VS. BILL: THE WHOLE WORLD IS WATCHING, LIKE IT OR NOT
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A film critic for a Russian newspaper recently told his
readers to skip ``Primary Colors,'' the vaguely fictional
book-turned-movie about the Clinton White House, which has reached
cinemas here.
</P>
<P>
   Why spend your hard-earned rubles to see John Travolta as Bill
Clinton, he concluded, when the real thing on your television
screens is much more outlandish and entertaining?
</P>
<P>
   When the subject is Clinton's alleged sexual affair with Monica
Lewinsky, the whole world is watching, whether it wants to or not.
From the pages of Pravda to talk radio in Tel Aviv, months of
coverage has nestled the scandal into the global public
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Around the world, it is alternatively portrayed as a sensational
soap opera, a political tragedy or an American farce. It is the
story everyone loves to loathe, but like it or not gets more of,
particularly as Clinton prepares to deliver his grand jury
testimony on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Like Americans, the rest of the globe appears ambivalent about
the ultimate significance of the allegations and the potential
peril to Clinton should they prove true.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that our readers are more interested in the
political aspects,'' said Roberto Cespedes, chief of foreign
correspondents at Reforma, a Mexico City newspaper, ``rather than
knowing whether a dress has semen on it.''
</P>
<P>
   But rest assured that angle, too, has been reported around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Israel's largest newspaper, Yediot Aharanot,
published a five-page spread on the scandal in its weekend
magazine. The coverage was headlined ``Monica Sex,'' a word-play on
a popular Israeli rock band that coincidentally took that same name
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The section, which even included detailed profiles of Lewinsky's
parents, stated, ``All the world is poised, waiting to hear whether
President Clinton will admit to having had sexual relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nowhere outside the United States has the tale been
splashed on news pages as abundantly as in Britain, with its
boisterous tabloids and competitive mainstream dailies. They have
joyfully and sometimes luridly reported every turn in the story,
very often on Page One.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton Goes Down,'' screamed one recent headline in The
Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged affair also has been frequent fodder for TV
commentators, who even have dwelled -- as perhaps only the very
proper British could -- on apropos women's fashion for a grand jury
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   One BBC analyst spent a considerable amount of air time on a
chat show expressing alarm that Lewinsky would carry a white purse
to her date with the grand jury. The commentator recanted later
when she learned that the handbag was actually a tasteful cream
color.
</P>
<P>
   For Russians, it is a somewhat amusing and bewildering saga,
regarded with interest but not fascination. Like many other
countries whose past political scandals have included murder and
brutality, they don't quite understand what all the fuss is about
over mere sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our own important problems and mainly people think
that this is the private business of Bill Clinton,'' said Yuri
Levada, director of the Russian Center for Public Opinion and
Market Research.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, male chauvinism is alive and well and sexual
harassment in the legal sense does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   The daily newspaper Izvestia carried an extensive article this
week defending Clinton against what it described as a gold-digging
horde of harlots, including Lewinsky, Paula Jones and others,
simply out to profit from their claimed sexual encounters -- or
near misses -- with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders range far and wide.
</P>
<P>
   The dean of Communist dictators, Cuba's Fidel Castro, said
recently that he sympathized with Clinton's situation, and that he
blamed Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., one of Castro's most-vocal
critics, for fomenting the charges against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, where the politics of the Jewish-Arab divide
colors every issue, the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal reportedly is
affecting the peace process, too.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Maariv reported Friday that Clinton has instructed
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to put public pressure on
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to give up land to the
Palestinians. But, Albright, according to the paper, is waiting for
the Lewinsky headlines to die down.
</P>
<P>
   For the French, who tend to be profoundly blase toward the idea
of an older man fooling around with a younger woman, the
Clinton-Lewinsky story has been treated as a grand farce.
</P>
<P>
   Le Monde commented wryly that even a full confession by Clinton
would amount only to a lie of ``Pinocchian proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   But in France as elsewhere, the serious fallout from the episode
also has been reported. The Lewinsky case is often portrayed as
Clinton's greatest personal crisis and speculation about his fall
has run rampant.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the world's media seem to appreciate what's at stake for
the American president if he is accused of perjury -- rather than
just having sex.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there was the 1,000-word story this week in
the Scottish Daily Record, by a fashion writer reviewing Lewinsky's
wardrobe in her many public appearances to date. The story was
headlined: ``Looking Good: It Doesn't Cost Much To Catch The Roving
Eye Of The Most Powerful Man In The Western World.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Washington has displaced Hollywood as the world
capital of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The French daily Le Figaro expressed cynical frustration with
the whole episode. ``Wake up Washington and Jefferson,'' the
newspaper wrote. ``They've gone crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Contributing to this report were Cox Newspapers' foreign
correspondents Bert Roughton, Jr., in London; Larry Kaplow in
Jerusalem; Susan Ferriss in Mexico City; and Shelley Emling in
Miami.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
