<HEADER>
A4592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHER-AUDITIONS-$ADV16     08-14 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHER-AUDITIONS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GYPSIES, TRAMPS AND CHER-WANNABES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 16)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 5 a.m. Friday, Rhonda Roenfeldt, 23, woke up in
Queens, put on a glittery tube top in metallic blue and a tube
skirt patterned with Indian goddesses and fitted a long black wig
over her red hair. She said she applied more makeup than usual,
using several coats of jet-black mascara, then gathered her head
shot and some sheet music and made her way to Manhattan to the open
casting call for ``And the Beat Goes On: The Sonny and Cher
Story,'' a made-for-television movie that will air on ABC in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the bewigged Cher hopefuls, who stood in line
outside the Anne G. Wilder Theater on West 42nd Street, Ms.
Roenfeldt, who tends bar on Second Avenue in Manhattan, seemed
terrifyingly confident, projecting the defensive happiness and
high-beam smile of a fledgling actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday, I will be a very highly paid movie actress,'' she
said, her bold words somehow not meshing with a shy smile. In the
four-hour wait from her arrival in line to her audition, she had
befriended Maggie Gallagher, 29, a teacher from Manhattan, and
Sharon Allitt, a paralegal from Beachwood, N.J., and they both
nodded soberly in agreement. In homage to the Cher of the 1970s,
all three women wore midriff-baring tops, but in a distinct nod to
the '90s, all three exposed belly buttons were pierced.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roenfeldt, the mother of a 2-year-old daughter, didn't
remember ever seeing Sonny and Cher when they were on television.
Ms. Gallagher wanted to sing ``If I Could Turn Back Time,'' and Ms.
Allitt was going for the big kahuna, ``Gypsies, Tramps and
Thieves.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the legions of rumpled nonprofessionals, the long hours
and the guaranteed tears of heartbroken amateurs, the open casting
call has worked for Larry Thompson, the project's producer.
Thompson _ who was a lawyer for both Sonny and Cher until their
divorce, after which he represented Sonny only _ also produced
``Lucy and Desi: Before the Laughter'' for CBS in 1991, and found
his actor and actress in a similar open call. Several hundred
people turned out for his recent auditions in Chicago, Los Angeles
and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're making a movie about icons, people who are the
audience know what those icons look like,'' Thompson said. ``So if
you cast a star or a celebrity in the role of Sonny or Cher, it's
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the Beat Goes On'' is based on Sonny Bono's autobiography,
which was a fleeting best seller in 1991, and will depict the
couple's life together, from the moment they first met _ when
Salvatore Bono was a driver for a meat-packing company _ to the
period after their divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would drive his truck down Hollywood Boulevard, stop at the
speciality record companies, rip off his bloody apron and start
pitching his songs with blood still on his shoes,'' said Maura
Dunbar, an ABC vice president, who oversees miniseries and special
projects.
</P>
<P>
   When Sonny was 28, he met 16-year-old Cherilyn Sarkisian
LaPierre, an aspiring singer so shy she was unable to sing by
herself. Together, they hit the charts, dropped off the charts and
had a baby. She bared her belly button, he wore fur vests and they
became symbols of the smiley-face '70s. They spawned four variety
shows: ``The Sonny and Cher Show'' was the first. After their
divorce, there was ``The Sonny Show,'' ``The Cher Show'' and then
``The Sonny and Cher Comedy Hour'' _ which Thompson calls ``The
Sonny and Cher Divorce Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Bono metamorphosed from campy crooner to restaurateur to Palm
Springs, Calif., Mayor to U.S. congressman, and died last January
in a skiing accident. His wife, Representative Mary Bono, is
cooperating with the film. Cher, who transformed herself from
pre-disco chanteuse to Oscar-winning actress to hawker of hair
products, is not.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Thompson finds his Cher or Sonny among the
hundreds of people who auditioned for him, he succeeded in
generating a shudder of publicity for his made-for-television
movie. More than a half-dozen camera crews stuck their microphones
into the pancaked faces of the Cher wannabes. Stories went out
about the woman who drove nine hours from Missouri to get to the
Chicago auditions, and the middle-aged couple who perform a Sonny
and Cher act in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entertainment Tonight,'' the nightly television magazine show,
followed actress Elizabeth York for two days before her Manhattan
audition, recording her every step.
</P>
<P>
   But the aspiring Sonnys and Chers displayed a consistent lack of
cynicism about the publicity stunt. ``Look, even if this thing is
already pre-cast, we don't care,'' Selena Cantor, a professional
singer, said. ``This is the way Broadway works. You get some
buzz.'' For her audition, she sang ``I Got You, Babe'' with Stephen
Morfesis, a reiki masseur she had met on line. (``It was a
four-hour romance,'' he said.) Despite Morfesis' toothy Bono-esque
smile and Ms. Cantor's resemblance to Cher, Thompson said the
dreaded words _ ``thank you'' _ before they finished.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. York, the actress tailed by the ET crew, said she felt
awkward about all the cameras _ but hey, that's show biz. ``I feel
like I'm being used, that it's just a manufactured event, sure, but
it's kind of what most actors do all the time anyway,'' she said.
``This role could have been cast months ago, and I'd still be here
today. I'm getting out there, do you know what I mean? And at least
I got a great outfit out of it,'' she added, pulling at her
lizard-print nylon pants suit, circa 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The auditions rolled. Thompson sat inside the darkened theater
listening to a relentless stream of women sing the first few lines
of ``I Got You, Babe.'' After vamping confidently in line for
hours, many of the women became inexplicably shy when they hit the
stage, their voices whittled down to a whisper. Suddenly, they were
standing in a dark room looking at bright lights and steely eyed
producers, no longer discussing itchy wigs outside in the safe
sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Auditioner No. 19, Dina Nicki Rassias, stood on stage in her
striped tank dress, her arms goose-pimpled from the
air-conditioning, and spoke about why she wanted the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, I would watch Cher, and here I was this
little Greek-Romanian girl and she was this little Armenian girl,
and I thought, I can be beautiful, too, without being one of these
huge blond all-American beauties,'' she said, and started to sing.
Thompson said, ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   At her audition, Ms. Gallagher, the teacher, belted out ``If I
Could Turn Back Time'' with exaggerated gutsiness, moving her lips
in distinctive Cher style. Thompson cut her off with a swift but
warm ``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the hallway, reunited with her temporary friends
again, Ms. Gallagher looked upset. Her lower lip trembled. She said
she wanted to get a drink. ``If only I hadn't cracked on that
note,'' she said, her face drawn. ``Maybe I would have had a
chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
