<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR
AUGUST 14, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- QUAKE. If the earthquake that startled San
Francisco residents this week had been of a far greater magnitude,
destroying homes instead of just knocking bottles off shelves, some
lawmakers would have wanted the federal government to foot the
bill. But instead of doling out the usual amount of disaster aid,
lawmakers say the federal government should establish a fund to
bolster state organizations like the California Earthquake
Authority, which back insurance policies that cover damage caused
by natural disasters. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- VACATION. Since January, the U.S. House has been in
session 65 days and when they get back from their August recess,
they plan on wrapping up business by the middle of October, having
worked just 89 days. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND -- CAMPAIGNS. Democrat Ralph Neas ranks 20th out of the
top 50 House challengers for total contributions to his campaign in
his race against Republican incumbent Connie Morella. (Possible for
Wed.) Brown.
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS -- VINEYARD. President Clinton will visit Martha's
Vineyard next week and local leaders want him to know there is more
to the island than a destination place for the rich and famous.
(Working-Will be filed early next week). Preston
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- GUNS. Pennsylvania has more residents walking
the streets with concealed handguns than any other state in the
nation, according to a study by Handgun Control, Inc. There are
currently 575,000 residents licensed to carry a concealed gun in
Pennsylvania -- that's three-and-a-half times as many concealed
guns as in Texas. Kane
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN ISLANDS -- ISLAND. Attention divers! Are you looking for
uncrowded, unspoiled coral reefs with a rainbow of vibrant colors
and alive with a diversity of plant and animal life? A team of
scientists from the Center for Marine Conservation has found such a
place in the middle of the Caribbean, between Haiti and Jamaica.
But there's a catch. Williams
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- KLUG. When Congress returns from its summer recess,
Rep. Scott Klug will no longer have a House committee seat. He
resigned from the Commerce Committee just before leaving
Washington, insisting that he needed to spend his remaining time
concentrating on a privatization report that Speaker Newt Gingrich
asked him to complete. Marlin
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
