<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Pass-along plants a green reminder of happy kinships
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a good day for digging, soon enough after a rain, not
terribly hot or sticky. Flossie Dodge and I set off, down the stone
steps toward the stream running through her wooded landscape in
northwest Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the water, we came to what I had come for: several
clumps of Oconee bells, the evergreen herb with roundish, leathery
leaves that look like galax.
</P>
<P>
   On this day in late July, Flossie and her husband, David, were
preparing for their move to Madison. Her sharing was the kind of
thing you do when you're leaving a garden _ along with taking a few
cuttings, potting up a prized plant here and there and saying a lot
of goodbyes.
</P>
<P>
   As a frequent and longtime recipient of pass-along plants, I
always appreciate the connections with the givers. This gift was
especially meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Oconee bells, first discovered in Oconee County, S.C., in 1788
and now considered rare and endangered, grow around the Blue Ridge
Mountains and in the highlands of Georgia and the Carolinas.
Flossie's plants came from her mother, Honto Hall, who rescued
Oconee bells from an abandoned home site 12 years ago and started
growing it in Highlands, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In its natural habitat, Oconee bells is found along streams,
usually under shrubs. ``I don't think it'll survive in Madison,''
said Flossie, explaining that the woods around her new home ``are
not real old.''
</P>
<P>
   And, she and I agreed, it must survive.
</P>
<P>
   Alzheimer's disease now has Flossie's mother, so the once
knowledgeable and spirited gardener cannot keep this plant going.
For some years now, its survival has depended on Flossie. Now me.
Passing it on to keep it going ``is what she'd like,'' Flossie
said.
</P>
<P>
   And so we dig. The shallow-rooted plants, with runners forming
new clumps, come out easily, along with richly decayed leaves,
fragrant, like ancient woods. ``This is what it likes,'' Flossie
tells me.
</P>
<P>
   As we put the plants in plastic bags, we talk of mothers and
Alzheimer's. (It got Lyn's mother some six years ago, erasing her
memory of her wonderful gardening talents.)
</P>
<P>
   Of her 77-year-old mother, Flossie said: ``She was an artist _ a
watercolorist. She was an amateur floral designer. And she raised
four girls.'' I talked about how Lyn's mother, Hazel McConnell, 84,
once traveled the world, living in East Pakistan for several years.
How she followed her own advice to family and friends: ``Have all
the fun you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, since Alzheimer's got her, all that is moot. For her, but
not for those who knew her then, those who see her life being
sucked away, unable to do anything but watch. And wait.
</P>
<P>
   Such conversation contrasted starkly with the life-affirming act
of passing on these joyous little plants. But, of course, they were
linked.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, I had two bags of Oconee bells. I put some in a damp,
shady spot in my back garden, some under a rhododendron out front.
And I took some to McCaysville, planting one clump on the bank of
Fightingtown Creek and two on the edge of woods on the other side
of the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   I will have to wait until spring to see the small white flowers
rise on stalks and look like tilting bells.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in their new homes, the plants decide whether to
survive. I water and watch and wait, knowing they must.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
