<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-BOAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's a summer tradition on Lake Rabun _ Sunday worship for the
boat people, sky above, waves below.
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKEMONT, Ga. _ At 8:50 every Sunday morning between Memorial
Day and Labor Day the boats come into sight _ pontoon craft,
runabouts and ski boats _ skimming across the glimmering water like
bugs.
</P>
<P>
   They converge near a barge where a minister, a keyboardist and a
young choir robed with life jackets are ready to conduct a worship
service.
</P>
<P>
   Up a hill in a boathouse their landlubber counterparts sit on
backless benches overlooking the mica-like water where the deep
green images of the trees on the bank are doubled in their
reflection.
</P>
<P>
   The lapping waves of the boat wakes play a prelude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning, Lake Rabun,'' says the Rev. Kirk Bozeman at 9
a.m. ``It's time for boat church!''
</P>
<P>
   Officially called Lake Rabun Leisure Ministries, boat church is
a 27-year tradition of Clayton's First United Methodist Church,
which holds its early service at the lake during the summer. On a
recent Sunday, 152 people came in about 45 boats; an additional 53
walked or drove to the boathouse.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is a gathering diverse in both denomination and species,
since at least one boat usually includes a pet or two.
</P>
<P>
   On this Sunday in midsummer, Bozeman preaches from a passage of
Ecclesiastes brought into popular culture during the 1960s by the
Byrds: ``To everything there is a season and a time for every
purpose under heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Bozeman speaks of life and death, chronology and eternity. But
here in this cathedral created by nature and the Georgia Power Co.,
which impounded the lake in 1915, the verses seem to apply
literally to budding springs of promise, steamy summers of fun and
relaxation, rich autumns of return to routine, and cold-winded
winters of contemplation.
</P>
<P>
   Boat church ``allows you to experience the beauty of this part
of God's creation as well as have a church service,'' said Cissy
Bruce Jackson, 33. At home in Birmingham she's an Episcopalian, but
here at her family's house on the lake, she's a boat-churcher.
``You don't have to get all dressed up and leave the lake to get
some religion.''
</P>
<P>
   The worship service makes a statement to people who are not
regular churchgoers, said Mary Jane Dennison, 25. She is attending
with her husband, Brian, 25, a University of Georgia law student
for whom boat church is a lifelong tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says to people God isn't just there in a big building for
people in suits,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
