<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-VACATION-COX     08-14 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-VACATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Respite &AMP; Religion
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the lull of summer, as metro Atlanta churches cut back on
worship services, combine Sunday school classes and have a hiatus
in weeknight programs, houses of worship in popular getaway spots
are making room for pews full of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the city's top ministers are away from their
pulpits on vacation or sabbatical, in much different settings other
clergy are preaching to crowds _ many of them (both clergy and
congregation) in shorts and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Some retreats _ such as the Episcopal Church's Kanuga near
Hendersonville, N.C. _ are geared especially for people seeking
respite and religion. But even in decidedly secular settings from
the mountains to the seashore, congregations have developed special
ministries for vacationers.
</P>
<P>
   First Baptist Church in Helen, Ga., a little more than a decade
old, was founded to be ``a ministry to a tourist town, to the
tourists who come through Helen as well as the people who work in
the tourist industry,'' said the Rev. Kyle Woodfin, 35, its pastor.
``That has helped shape the personality of the church and the
outreach of the church.''
</P>
<P>
   With only 150 members, the church frequently has 180 to 190
people in worship. ``It's not uncommon for us to have 30 to 40
percent of the congregation on big weekends be tourists,'' he said.
``Our church realizes that's a part of who we are and welcomes
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The church operates Georgia Mountain Resort Ministries, which
uses about 400 volunteers a year, including many church youth
groups, to work in the area. The ministry operates as many as six
simultaneous day camps for children in different locations where
tourists stay and play, and an Alzheimer's club for family members
to leave patients for a few hours in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Several days a week, groups of college students walk along the
Chattahoochee River and the Appalachian Trail to clean up after
tubers and campers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do this as a community service,'' Woodfin said, ``but it
also gives us an opportunity to interact with campers and hikers.
We share Gatorade, Snickers bars, whatever we happen to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the church are mostly retired people or people who
have moved into the area to work, Woodfin said. For those who work
in Helen's shops and hotels, Sunday is one of the busiest days of
the week, so the church has an early morning service geared to
them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing a church on the tourist industry ``does take a
different mind-set,'' said Woodfin, who came to Helen from
Clarkesville five years ago. ``We realize a lot of people on
vacation don't bring coats and ties and dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Arnold Belzer, 54, of Congregation Mickve Israel in
Savannah, Ga., said he likes the fact that visitors often show up
in shorts. It helps him recognize them as guests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Belzer's Reform synagogue is not only in a tourist town, it is a
tourist attraction in its own right. Its congregation was founded
in 1733, only five months after James Edward Oglethorpe brought a
load of colonists to Georgia, and its Gothic building is a regular
stop on tours of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The number of visitors has doubled in the past five years, the
rabbi said, since the book and film ``Midnight in the Garden of
Good and Evil'' and the PBS television show ``This Old House''
featured Savannah prominently.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, docents at the synagogue give tours to visitors
and answer questions. A museum features the country's oldest Torah,
brought over by the 42 Jews who accompanied Oglethorpe and already
old at the time, and a collection of letters from 14 U.S.
presidents, including Washington, Jefferson and Madison. A gift
shop offers Judaica and souvenirs, including a mezuzah in the shape
of the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   During services on Friday evenings and Saturdays, the rabbi asks
all members to greet strangers with a ``Shalom, y'all.'' After
Saturday worship services, the congregation invites all guests to
share lunch _ even those who have not attended services but have
come only to see the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is such a thing as a free lunch,'' the rabbi quips.
</P>
<P>
   At times, especially in spring, visitors, many of them non-Jews,
outnumber the members at the 350-family synagogue, Belzer said. ``I
don't want visitors to know that,'' he said, ``but it's a wonderful
problem to have.''
</P>
<P>
   The hottest months are a slow time on St. Simons Island, said
the Rev. Germain Belen, a Franciscan priest who serves St. William
Catholic Church. ``Most of our people leave during the summer,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in winter, the 10:30 a.m. Sunday Mass at the 650-seat church
is standing room only.
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors who come to the island every winter have been part
of the church for years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out over the congregation, Belen said he can always tell
who is going to the golf course afterward because of the way they
dress.
</P>
<P>
   The most enjoyable aspect of a tourist-heavy church is ``meeting
new people,''he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the special needs of a tourist-heavy ministry, the
country's largest Protestant denomination has set up a special
department to establish ministries and advise churches. The Rev.
Jeff Wagner heads resort ministries for the Southern Baptist
Convention's Atlanta-based North American Mission Board.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, 38, first became involved in resort ministry as a
student at Golden Gate Baptist Theological Seminary outside San
Francisco. He was asked to start a new ministry in the Russian
River area of Northern California. He began with puppets and games
for children in campgrounds along the beach areas of the river and
built on those efforts. From the new Redwood Resort Ministry, he
moved to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I learned was that resort areas are often neglected by
traditional churches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A challenge of such ministries is dealing with the workers in
the tourism industry, Wagner said. ``People go there thinking
they're going to have the same experience they had on vacation.
They realize it's hard work, long hours, low pay and high rent. The
payoff is the beauty of the area, and the slow times when they can
recuperate. Those who live and work in those settings tend to
balance that.''
</P>
<P>
   Worship in resort areas should draw from its setting, said
Wagner, such as an oceanside reference to Jesus calming the waters
for his disciples. ``You use those kinds of illustrations so that
when people go home, part of their memory is not only did they
recreate, but they re-created themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   To be an effective minister to tourists, Wagner said, a minister
``has to learn how to be a tourist. You have to remember why people
come there in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
