<HEADER>
A4607 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TABLETOP-DESIGN-COX     08-14 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TABLETOP-DESIGN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Give a designer a blank canvas, a good cause, and creativity
sizzles
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a designer invites you to dinner, you can usually count on
the table being a dazzler _ elegant china, sparkling stemware,
exotic flowers.
</P>
<P>
   And when 50 of them agree to host the same party, you can bet
the heat will be on to push those tables over the top. A little
friendly competition suddenly makes a place setting good enough for
Martha Stewart about as flashy as a fast-food takeout tray.
</P>
<P>
   Such will be the case Aug. 27, when the Atlanta chapter of
DIFFA, Design Industries Foundation Fighting AIDS, hosts
``Collection Rouge II: Dining by Design.'' The fund-raising dinner
combines nine three-dimensional tabletop creations by nationally
renowned designers and 41 done by local talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some tables are outrageous, others are hilarious and some,
just sleek and sophisticated,'' said David Sheppard, national
director of the 15-chapter, New York-based DIFFA.
</P>
<P>
   The outrageous: Fashion designer Anne Klein shows what ``Dining
With the Devil With the Red Dress On'' can be like. Radiant
8-foot-tall, flame-shaped chairs, made from plastic glass, sizzle
around a table with an 11-foot mannequin, ``Miss Mephistopheles,''
rising out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The hilarious: Atlanta interior designer Carole Weaks gives new
meaning to a live centerpiece by putting a masculine Carmen Miranda
in the middle of the table, entertaining guests by passing out
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The sleek and sophisticated: Home and fashion guru Calvin Klein
stretches a 9-foot-long centerpiece to the max with 36 fat candles
_ nothing else _ for an intimate, minimalist look.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta designers _ who come from the interiors, fashion,
floral and hair industries _ are pulling out all the stops, from
tented tables to gushing waterfalls, said Kevin Knaus, a local
DIFFA board member. ``They're really going much more over the top
than they did in New York,'' where the tour began, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because many participants already have seen the
traveling designs, which have appeared in Elle Decor magazine, the
event's national media sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Each Atlanta-area designer is given a plain 72-inch round table
with three stipulations: The design must accommodate 10 guests,
reflect the red theme and include stemware for serving champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The bubbly's important, because the event is sponsored by
Champagne Mumm. The company first joined forces with DIFFA in 1995
to stage a traveling, red-themed fashion extravaganza that also
teamed up with local talent in major cities, including Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like Atlanta remembered it from the first time and
that this would be a really great way to build on that by
participating,'' said John Dyer, chairman of DIFFA's Atlanta
chapter.
</P>
<P>
   The dining tour, with stops in eight cities, supports local AIDS
care organizations through company sponsorships of tables, priced
from $2,500 to $25,000. So far, Dining by Design has raised more
than $550,000 in three cities, and Atlanta's event is nearly sold
out. ``It's gone gangbusters,'' event chairwoman Sara Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers believe the big selling point is that, unlike formal
seated dinners, Dining by Design is an interactive event, where
guests are encouraged to move from table to table and check out the
designs.
</P>
<P>
   And innovation is everything these days when competing for
charity dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has this false impression the fight against AIDS is
over, which makes it tough for organizations,'' said Sheppard, a
former Atlanta interior designer. ``DIFFA is different, in that we
have this loyal support from the design communities in our chapter
cities. And people know that when these designers get involved,
they're going to experience something really special.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
