</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-BOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traveler's work focuses on divine experiences
 &HT;    FREELANCE STORY. TO BE USED BY COX PAPERS ONLY. NOT TO BE USED
BY NY TIMES WIRE.
 &HT;    By Laurie Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone who travels around America asking people if they've seen
God lately could very well attract the attention of local law
enforcement. But when writer/photographer Steve Wall took just such
a trip, he stumbled upon several people who not only didn't think
he was nuts, but who shared fascinating stories about their
experience of the divine. ``Dancing With God'' (St. Martin's Press,
240 pages) is the record of Wall's adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Wall, who has had a long career as a photojournalist for
``National Geographic'', ``Time'' and other magazines, says his
grandmother is responsible for his strong desire to explore
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really started with my grandmother telling me stories when
I was four or five years old,'' Wall recalls ``She's always pointed
me toward the divine.'' Wall remembers being haunted by his
grandmother's account of the night she believed an angel visited
her.
</P>
<P>
   Wall's work with Native American spiritual elders, which led to
his best-selling books ``Wisdomkeepers'' and ``Wisdom's
Daughters,'' fueled the fire of his interest. When his son
suggested that he seek out spiritual elders who weren't Native
American, Wall was ready to continue his life's quest. ``So I
started this journey of just getting in my truck and following my
own intuition,'' he said. He admits to being changed by what he
found.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Wall met Little Willis who survives on the streets
of Atlanta while devoting all his time to activities like finding
coats for friends. These friends seem convinced Little Willis is
doing God's work.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Justice of Toccoa, who was pulled from a river still alive
after some two hours underwater, told Wall he felt God's presence
with him and knew he wouldn't die. Gwen Scott, former anchor at CNN
Headline New, now living in Albuquerque, described having a vision
of the Virgin Mary which kept her from committing suicide. Germaine
Curley of Picayune, Miss., spoke about often hearing a voice which
diverts her from danger.
</P>
<P>
   Wall notes that people in crisis may be more open to the
spiritual plane. ``I am convinced that the divine is real in all of
our lives whether we recognize it or not. A lot of times when
you're sitting on top of the mountain in your bliss you don't pay
attention. When you get into a crisis situation you are much more
open to other possibilities. He also noticed real kindness in each
person he met. '''Each and every one of them did have this love,''
he said, ``and there was a gentleness about each one.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall is quick to admit how much he learned from these people and
how he was changed by them. ``There are some things that happened
to me that I recognize have changed me at this point, he said.
``But I don't know what effect the others had on me for tomorrow or
next week, because I may not realize what that person's lesson was
for me until down the road sometime.'' William McFarland, a Vietnam
vet who suffers from severe flashbacks and horrific memories, had a
profound effect. While driving through Texas together, Wall and
McFarland saw a woman riding on a donkey whom McFarland identified
as the Virgin Mary. ``There was a love about him and a caring, Wall
says. ``I offered to share my hotel room. He wouldn't do it because
he was afraid he'd have a dream and hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall says he was also very moved by the artist Fernando Mercado.
``Some of these people have had events in their lives that are so
dramatic. And his was more of coming to an understanding of things
for himself. And yet, he said he saw God everyday.'' Mercado told
Wall that the crucial things are ``love, respect and pay(ing)
attention!''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Wall's experiences were encouraging. While dressed as
a street person he attended services at a large Atlanta church. ``I
wanted to find out how people reacted to those who were down and
out,'' he said. ``I've always thought of the church as possibly the
one place where you could really find comfort, you could actually
find help there because that's actually what they talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   The reception he received was far from warm. First, several men
in the church asked Wall to move to a pew of homeless men in the
front where the other visitors were sitting. Then the minister
directed his sermon about rising from the gutter at Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some of the people in a very different light,'' Wall
remembers. ``There were expressions of condemnation . . . It was
like I was an island . . . an island of garbage. and they wanted to
keep away from me. ``
</P>
<P>
   But most of Wall's experiences brought him hope, and he returned
feeling that the divine is present in day to day life. ``If we just
look out our windows and we see the creation, then we know that the
creation is a part of us,'' he said. ``We're a part of it . . . If
that's so, then the Creator is in you. and you can't separate
yourself from the Creator.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
