<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Presbyterians build house in Mexico
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the seventh consecutive year, St. Luke's Presbyterian Church
of Dunwoody, Georgia sent a group to Mexico to build a house in
Piedras Negras, a border town across from Eagle Pass, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The 36 church members, ages 12 to 60, spent a week last month
hand-constructing a simple three-room house in temperatures that
reached 110 to 120 degrees each day. Everything was done by hand,
even mixing the concrete. ``These people live in a massive expanse
of tar-paper shacks under conditions we won't put animals in,''
says Dunwoody lawyer C. G. ``Sonny'' Jester, who headed the St.
Luke's Mexican mission. ``For them, these new houses are palaces.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Luke's has scheduled next year's Mexican housebuilding trip
for July 3-10. The project is a partnership with the Birmingham
organization ``Constructores para Christo'' (Builders for
Christ).www.jobseekers.org
</P>
<P>
   Mitchem named to post
</P>
<P>
   Nichelle A. Mitchem has been appointed executive director of
metro Atlanta's Partnership Against Domestic Violence, effective
Aug. 3. A native of Colorado Springs, Colo., Mitchem, 36, has more
than 10 years experience with organizations combating domestic
violence, most recently as executive director for the New Jersey
Women &AMP; AIDS Network. Her advocacy of battered women began in law
school at the University of Wisconsin, where she interned in a
legal assistance program for female prisoners. Mitchem replaces
Barbara Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   JobSeekers expands
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, JobSeekers has helped hundreds of unemployed Atlanta
white collar men through its extensive job networking services and
emotional and spiritual support. Now the Atlanta-based nonprofit
Christian organization is rapidly expanding its mission. It has
just opened a branch in Peachtree City, with additional branches to
follow over the next two months in Phoenix, Ariz.; Chattanooga,
Tenn.; Modesto, Calif.; and Fort Lauderdale, Fla. Last year,
JobSeekers opened its first out-of-state branches, in Knoxville,
Tenn., and Tucson, Ariz. To learn more about the organization, call
co-founder Denny Brown at 770-551-9263 or log into the web site at
www.jobseekers.org
</P>
<P>
   _Derrick Henry
</P>
