<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MAY BAN JET SKIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco officials are considering banning
the use of Jet Skis and other personal watercraft from within 1,200
feet of shoreline, a move that supporters hope will trigger a wave
of other jurisdictions to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so important for the quality of life _ for the noise,
for safety, for the environment,'' said Supervisor Gavin Newsom,
chief sponsor of the legislation. ``In many respects, we are
setting a tone and creating a model for other counties.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law, the first of its kind by a county in the San
Francisco Bay area, would forbid personal watercraft along much of
the waterfront, including Alcatraz, Treasure and Yerba Buena
islands and the east side of Angel Island.
</P>
<P>
   Personal watercraft are manufactured under such names as Jet
Skis, Sea Doos and Waverunners.
</P>
<P>
   The only launch site allowed in the city would be Pier 52 in
China Basin. The personal watercraft also could come to shore at
Gas House Cove near Aquatic Park for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Violators would be subject to a $50 fine for the first
infraction, $100 for the second and $250 for the third violation
and subsequent ones in a year's period. In addition, the law would
allow San Francisco residents to sue the personal watercraft
operators.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal won the unanimous support of the Board of
Supervisors' Health, Family and Environment Committee. The full
board is expected to approve it. The earliest the personal
watercraft would be outlawed near San Francisco shores would be
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Mahan, who sells personal watercraft in Daly City, said
the proposed law was insane. ``I can understand restricting some
areas,'' she said, ``but something like this is too restrictive.
It's unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade associations also oppose the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members are very concerned any time a political
jurisdiction attempts to take away people's abilities to use public
waterways,'' said Mark Denny, public affairs director of the Santa
Ana-based International Jet Sports Boating Association. He said
other boats, ``even tankers carrying nuclear waste,'' seem to have
fewer restrictions than personal watercraft.
</P>
<P>
   Among those supporting the proposed ban are kayakers, swimmers,
surfers, fishermen and environmentalists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
