<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4663 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FAMILY-AZR &LR;      08-14 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FAMILY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DYSFUNCTIONAL FAMILY CHANNEL   
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Let's play word-association. I write a word, and you
list all of the related words that quickly come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   First word: Family.
</P>
<P>
   Second word: Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Third word: Attitude.
</P>
<P>
   In all but the most dysfunctional lives, ``family'' should
conjure such concepts as ``love'' and ``respect'' and ``comfort''
and ``wholesome'' and ``caring'' and maybe ``bathroom-sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox,'' as in Rupert Murdoch's Fox entertainment empire, should
spark associations with words like ``Married'' and ``with'' and
``Children.'' Or ``When'' and ``Animals'' and ``Attack'' and
``IV.''
</P>
<P>
   You could swap ``attitude'' _ as in ``That dude's got an
attitude, man!'' _ with ``rude'' or ``obnoxious'' or ``unkind,'' or
maybe ``penitentiary-bound doom magnet.'' Use it in a sentence and
you're also likely to use a phrase like ``loud-mouth mall punk.''
Picture ``attitude'' and you see a head-wagging Springerette just
before she lunges for a handful of someone else's hair.
</P>
<P>
   All three words _ Fox, family and attitude _ are associated by
way of the makeover that's been done by Murdoch on what used to be
The Family Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The new Fox Family Channel has ditched all but one element of
the old Family Channel's programming _ which relied heavily on
comfortable, wholesome reruns like ``Bonanza,'' ``Diagnosis
Murder'' and ``The'' ``Big Valley'' _ in favor of a new lineup with
``attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   About half of all the new shows are original. In prime time on
weeknights, there will be original video-clip shows (a Fox
favorite), game shows and a sketch comedy built around the ancient
Mr. Bill character from ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   There will also be movies, including original movies starring
the likes of Tom Arnold (and an unauthorized Michael Jordan biopic
is also in the works). Preschoolers are the targets in the morning
and midday, older kids and younger teens appear to be the targets
in the afternoons. Families, all watching together, are targeted at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Families with attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most TV is not safe for family viewing, and that is why
families need the Fox Family Channel,'' said Rich Cronin, president
and CEO of the new net, who met recently with TV critics in
Pasadena, Calif. ``The current Family Channel has a strong
following, but kids and teens are not sitting down with their
parents to watch shows like ``Diagnosis Murder'' or ``Hawaii
Five-0.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are fine shows, don't get me wrong, but we have the
opportunity with Fox Family Channel to expand on the current
audience by creating a network that the whole family will watch
together, a network that entertains contemporary families with a
Fox attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you may be wondering: How do you define contemporary
families, and what exactly is Fox attitude?
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to have every single family in America watching
Fox Family Channel, but we've got to focus. Our focus is on
families that are a little younger, more suburban or urban, more
plugged in to pop culture. What we call contemporary families who
appreciate a network with attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``And how do we define Fox attitude? We think it's a funny,
quirky, surprising, savvy attitude that is combined with our
mandate to always be safe for family viewing.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Super spin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox'' and ``safe'' and ``family'' _ does anybody else notice
that burning smell, or hear the faint howling of souls suffering
eternal damnation?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Fox may be chasing a ghost. The multiple-TV household
and expertly programmed niche networks have seemingly splintered
the nuclear viewing family. The soon-to-launch Pax Net is aiming
for the same apparition.
</P>
<P>
   That the big networks have abandoned families probably shouldn't
be interpreted as an evil plot. It's a business trend. Families
haven't stopped watching TV together because there's nothing
wholesome to watch (though family advocates would disagree), but
rather because the kids have viewing choices they like better
playing on the little set in the back room.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, those choices _ Fox Family Channel competitors such as
Nickelodeon, the Disney Channel and the Cartoon Network _ all have
a bit of sassy ``attitude.'' Adults are not universally respected
in some of the programming on those networks, and musical promos
and soundtracks often share gangsta rap's rhythmic vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference here is Fox, which has proven over time _
despite ``Ally McBeal,'' despite ``The Simpsons,'' despite ``The
X-Files'' _ that it can't be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Given its otherwise craven business plan (see any sweeps ratings
month, clogged with lower-order-appeal reality programs), Fox's
aesthetic successes (see above list) have to be judged as
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and family. Fox and family. It's just such a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing on the Fox network's prime-time schedule that
I would feel comfortable sitting down and watching with my
family,'' said Mark Honig, executive director of the Parents
Television Council, an advocacy group whose World Wide Web site
(www.parentstv.org) carries family-friendly TV recommendations
while hounding the networks for ruining America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the mildest of their shows _ ``The Simpsons'' and
``King of the'' ``Hill'' _ there are aspects of those programs
you'd just get ambushed by.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Fox Family Channel's premiere programs, airing
Sunday, is a Spice Girls concert. Next Sunday, the feature film is
``Home Alone'' ``II'' (edited down, as will all of the Fox Family
Channel's library of feature films, to the equivalent of a ``G''
movie rating.) Even one of the new network's brightest programming
decisions _ to rerun the fabulous ``Pee-wee's Playhouse'' series,
which has been mothballed since its creator, Paul Reubens, was
busted in 1991 for indecent exposure in a Florida porno theater _
will strike some potential viewers as inappropriate. &QL; 
 &QL; 
`700 Club' stays  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows what Pee-wee's lineup mate, Family Channel founder
Pat Robertson, thinks about it.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the $1.9 billion transaction between Murdoch and
Robertson, the televangelist and political power broker gets to
keep his fire 'n' brimstone ministry on the network. After a brief
launch period without it, Fox Family will air 90 minutes of ``The
700 Club'' every weekday morning.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you're checking your TV listings, holy mayhem raining
down on gay-loving Orlando comes right after ``Mork &AMP; Mindy'' and
just before ``The All New Captain Kangaroo.''
</P>
<P>
   More ``700 Club'' follows the evening movie.
</P>
<P>
   Audience flow _ it's a key consideration for most TV programmers
_ will be one of the first challenges for the Fox Family Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to have Pat Robertson and his ``700 Club'' on the
air,'' said Haim Saban, of Saban Entertainment (distributor of the
``Mighty'' ``Morphin Power Ranger''s) and Murdoch's partner in the
Fox Family Channel. ``We don't think it's conflicting with anything
that we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``The 700 Club'' airs, ``all the kids that are above
preschool are gone to school,'' said Saban, who also met with the
critics. ``Families watch the ``700 Club.'' Mothers watch ``The 700
Club.''''
</P>
<P>
   Programs that follow ``The 700 Club'' ``will be appointment
television for preschoolers,'' he said. ``Preschoolers and their
moms will know that is when preschool programming on the Fox Family
Channel starts. There will be a flow.'' &QL; 
{Dave Walker is the television writer for the Arizona Republic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
