<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GITTA-SERENY-PROFILE-     08-14 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GITTA-SERENY-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GITTA SERENY: CLOSE ENOUGH TO EVIL TO LOOK BEYOND IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In three decades of studying guilt, responsibility and
the nature of evil through the twin obsessions of her professional
life, Nazis and child criminals, Gitta Sereny has regularly been
accused of growing too close to her subjects, of becoming not only
a confessor but an apologist.
</P>
<P>
   When she wrote ``Into That Darkness'' (Random House, 1983) a
rigorous examination of the unspeakable crimes of Franz Stangl, the
fearsome commandant of the Treblinka death camp and one of Nazism's
cruelest practitioners, a critic demanded to know how she could
have, as she described in the book, made soup for the ailing Stangl
on the last day she spent with him.
</P>
<P>
   (``I had to ask myself whether there was something morally wrong
with what I had done,'' Ms. Sereny says now. ``But it was a
pragmatic thing: I needed him for another day.'')
</P>
<P>
   And when she published ``Albert Speer: His Battle With Truth''
(Knopf, 1995), the result of a 16-year project that delved deep
into the conscience of Speer, Hitler's brilliant, urbane architect
and one of his closest confidants, Ms. Sereny daringly revealed in
her very first sentence that she ``grew to like'' her subject.
</P>
<P>
   But the great accomplishment of the book served to quell all but
the most carping criticism: Ms. Sereny, through her relentless
questioning and amassing of evidence, finally forced Speer to admit
what he had been concealing even from himself: that he had known
and tacitly consented to Hitler's ``final solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in her journalistic career, however, prepared the
formidable Ms. Sereny, now 76, for the uproar that greeted her in
Britain last spring, when she published her most recent book,
``Cries Unheard.'' The book is about Mary Bell, who became one of
Britain's most notorious criminals in 1968 when, barely 11, she
murdered two little boys and then appeared, at least to a horrified
nation that followed the news of her case, to have no remorse.
</P>
<P>
   With her customary habit of becoming immersed in her subject,
Ms. Sereny spoke to Mary Bell over a period of months, sometimes
for as long as 10 hours a day, in an effort to understand what
drove her to commit her crimes. But this time, Ms. Sereny's
involvement in her subject went even further, and she grew to like
Ms. Bell and to believe that she had truly redeemed herself.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction here was swift and condemnatory, particularly when it
emerged that Ms. Sereny paid Ms. Bell for her cooperation. The
public reacted with a surge of fury and moral outrage to Ms.
Sereny's conclusion that Ms. Bell had not been morally responsible
for her crimes because of her age and because she herself had
suffered abuse as a young girl. The British tabloids referred to
Ms. Bell's ``blood money'' and ``depraved story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gitta Sereny is confused when it comes to issues of
moral blame,'' Andrew O'Hagen, the author of ``The Missing,'' an
account of violence and murder in Britain, told The Guardian in
April, criticizing the way she ``found it easy to enter into
complicity with Mary Bell in her more self-redeeming aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Sereny's other work, ``Cries Unheard'' wrestles with the
idea of guilt, evil and the possibility of redemption in a
civilized society. It also speaks to the fraught, sometimes
mutually exploitative relationship between subject and biographer,
a relationship whose implications Ms. Sereny said she fully
understood from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in her cool, book-filled London apartment recently, Ms.
Sereny was still resolute in her conviction that she was right to
write the book, and right to research it the way she had.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they don't understand is that if you do what I do, you
have to develop a relationship,'' said Ms. Sereny, a small woman
with close-cropped graying hair, large eyes and an intense manner.
``There is no other way. Your relationship is always at a distance,
of course. But it's not possible to spend weeks or months with
someone and not develop a relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cries Unheard'' which is to be published in the United States
next spring by Metropolitan Books, an imprint of Henry Holt,
examines the murders in excruciating detail and is not, Ms. Sereny
stressed, intended to justify what Mary Bell did. But the book
dwells at length on Ms. Bell's time in prison, at the mercy of a
system that Ms. Sereny says is woefully inadequate for child
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   It also provides a wrenching chronicle of her childhood: she was
abandoned by her father and unloved by her mother, a prostitute who
tried to murder Mary on a number of occasions and who forced her to
perform sex acts with her customers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GITTA-SERENY-PROFILE-     08-14 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GITTA-SERENY-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LONDON: her customers.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through her work with Ms. Bell, who is now living somewhere in
the north of England under a new name with her 14-year-old
daughter, Ms. Sereny became more convinced that there was no such
thing as an evil child. That notion, she says, puts her in conflict
with what seems to be the conventional wisdom in Britain, where
Mary Bell and the two young boys who killed 3-year-old Jamie Bulger
in another notorious case in Britain several years ago are seen as
the embodiment of wickedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind their reaction is the idea of the Devil, the idea of
evil,'' she said of her critics. ``There is this belief that the
evil person is evil, period. There's no rehabilitation, no
redemption. This is a Christian nation, but the Christianity stops
short of redemption.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sereny's examination of these issues is particularly
pertinent now, as the United States grapples with a rash of
horrific murders by children. In the most recent case, two boys,
ages 7 and 8, have been accused of sexually assaulting and killing
an 11-year-old girl in Chicago, raising calls for them to be tried
as adults.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sereny emphatically disagrees. ``I think 14 is a fair age to
make a child morally responsible, because there's been a moral
growth,'' she said. ``Children at 10, 9 and 8 are not morally
grown. Why should they be, any more than intellectually or
physically?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bell's daughter, a straight-A student who seems untouched by
the chain of hatred and violence that so affected Ms. Bell, is
living proof that redemption is possible, she said. ``Mary Bell has
broken the cycle by her own character, her own strength,'' Ms.
Sereny said. ``Instead of being demonized, she should be celebrated
for what she has accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after a career spent facing down the perpetrators of evil,
Ms. Sereny does not believe that people are evil, except perhaps in
exceptional cases like those of Hitler or Fred and Rosemary West,
the notorious British child killers who tortured and sexually
assaulted their victims. But those sorts of people are rare indeed,
she said, and they hold no interest for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a great believer in people's capacity to change, to find
themselves, to understand if they have done something terribly
bad,'' Ms. Sereny said. That, she explained, is partly why she had
sympathy for Speer, who was consumed by guilt and who tried so hard
to redeem himself by relentlessly examining his own soul. ``I grew
to like him when I realized he really wanted to find out the truth
for himself,'' she said. ``That is very likable, when the truth is
so terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sereny's own search for the truth has lasted nearly all her
life. She was born in Vienna, read ``Mein Kampf'' as a teen-ager
and, though not Jewish, began to recognize the horrors of Nazism as
she saw Jews beginning to disappear from her neighborhood. She was
in Paris, studying at the Sorbonne, when France fell to the Nazis,
and she left school and began working as a nurse at a camp for
abandoned children. When her anti-Nazi work made it impossible for
her to remain, she left Europe, returning after the war as a United
Nations child welfare officer, working with children who had been
in concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are made by the circumstances of their lives, and what
I am involved in comes out of the war,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sereny began to work as a journalist, and gained a
reputation as a dogged investigator who would not stop until she
wrestled her subject into submission. Some 20 years later, living
in London with her husband, Don Honeyman, a photographer, she was
sent by The Daily Telegraph magazine to cover the war-crimes trials
of former Nazis in Duesseldorf, Hamburg and several other German
cities. On and off for six months, Ms. Sereny sat and listened as
witness after witness described the indescribable. And as the
stories began to come alive, the truth became in a way more
elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them _ the accused and the witnesses _ had two things
in common,'' she said. ``None of them wanted to be there, and they
had all seen or done things no human being should ever see or do.
The blocking of these experiences and these feelings, and the guilt
at what they had felt or seen or done, was so strong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you didn't get was themselves,'' she added. ``You got
their descriptions of what happened, but you didn't get themselves,
because it was unfaceable. None of them could speak out about what
they had felt and what it had done to them inside themselves. I
kept thinking, `Why isn't anyone asking these questions?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sereny decided that she would ask the questions, looking at
individual guilt as a way to examine society's collective
culpability. That is why she obsessively studied every available
document and spoke to every available acquaintance and colleague
about Speer, building up to the point where she confronted him with
the biggest paradox of his life: that although he was in Hitler's
inner circle during the worst excesses of the Third Reich, he
professed to know nothing about the systematic extermination of the
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why, after covering the trial of Mary Bell in 1968
(she wrote an earlier book about it, called ``The Case of Mary
Bell''), Ms. Sereny waited nearly 30 years for the chance to meet
Ms. Bell face to face, and to question her until she was satisfied
with the explanations. ``In all these things, what I want to find
out is what that makes them capable of doing what they do, or
incapable of doing what they didn't do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring again to World War II, she said: ``Like all of my
generation across the Western world, whether Jews or Christians, we
have been deeply affected by what the Germans did. It was the worst
kind of inhumanity, such an enormous wrong, and we were all in my
generation part of it. Because of it, humanity lost something. We
lost a moral part of ourselves, and somehow we must regain this
part. Maybe my way of regaining it is by doing what I'm doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
