<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4682 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-DEFENSE-ART-$A     08-14 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DEFENSE-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOU BEEN LOOKING FOR SHELTER IN ALL THE WRONG PLACES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of defensive investing strategies is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16)  
 (af)  
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind the yen, the ruble, the dress.
</P>
<P>
   They've all been mentioned as contributors to the latest bouts
of queasiness in the long-running bull market, but sorting out the
causes can take investors only so far.
</P>
<P>
   For many people with savings tied up in stocks, it may be time
to make defensive maneuvers to protect gains and help minimize the
risk of losses.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive investing once was considered relatively simple: Move
money out of stocks and into bonds, precious metals, certificates
of deposit and cash until the storm blows over. Now the concept is
more complicated _ and the alternatives aren't so obvious.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, many experts are not keen on automatically
parking large chunks of money in bonds because interest rates
generated by almost all fixed-income investments are abysmally low.
</P>
<P>
   Gold, another historical haven, continues to languish near its
lows for the year, with little sign of change. Even some types of
stocks, including shares of basic foods and consumer products
companies _ often seen as refuges in previous downturns because of
their steady earnings _ have lost some allure and are viewed as
overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   To some strategists, defensive investing is more akin to highly
selective investing: carefully evaluating individual stocks and
mutual funds and deciding if they are potential bargains. The first
step, investment experts agree, is to take a reality check and
evaluate your investment gains before foraging for alternatives in
a panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients have told me they're getting killed in this market,''
said Rosilyn Overton, a certified financial planner in Flushing,
N.Y. ``But when I ask them to compare their net worth since the end
of last year, even with the pullback they're up 15 to 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also appropriate to do a second kind of reality check _
assessing whether your investment allocations still meet your
investment targets and tolerance for risk. Because of the market's
run-up the last three years, many investors may not realize just
how much of their money is in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   At the Dreyfus Corp., Timothy M. Ghriskey, head of value
equities, offered this test: ``If this little correction makes you
nervous, you're probably overexposed.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't necessarily mean it's time to move all money out of
stocks. Like many other market professionals, Ghriskey believes it
is premature to say a bear market has arrived or that corporate
earnings are about to evaporate. As one sign of that, he pointed to
how well the stocks of smaller financial service companies
performed during the market jolts last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Tuesday, financial stocks were the worst-performing sector
of the S&AMP;P, but the best-performing sector of the Russell 2000
small-stock index,'' he said. ``That tells us people aren't so much
worried about a recession as they are worried about the
international economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghriskey said he saw bargains in financial services stocks,
which took a battering recently. Ghriskey said he likes companies
including Citicorp, Chubb and First Union partly because market
selloffs had obscured their underlying health.
</P>
<P>
   Chubb, for example, is in the middle of a share buyback, a sign
that the company is confident about its prospects. First Union, he
said, is increasing its reliance on stable, fee-based income that
comes from generating business as an investment adviser, not just
as a commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Rowan, a senior investment strategist at Merrill Lynch,
said she liked financial services, too, particularly insurance.
``We think it's an area that's ripe for consolidation, but it's an
industry that also has some good fundamentals and above-average
dividend yield,'' she said. ``The market doesn't seem to be
rewarding many of these companies, however.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to identify her picks but said ``the ones that look
most inexpensive to us are property and casualty companies, which
have some of the best dividend yields, as well as reasonable growth
in earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan Harrel, who helps manage the Aim Value fund, said he saw
value in financial services, including insurance, and in cable
television; three of his top 10 holdings are American International
Group, Chase Manhattan and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Another sector that may be poised for growth is real estate
investment trusts. Many of these stocks, including Vornado Realty
Trust and Crescent Real Estate Equities, had been weakening for
most of the year but now seem poised for a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rowan suggested REIT stocks as defensive purchases, though
she did not specify her choices. She likes the high dividend yields
that many REITs offer, and said a good portion of the money that
many REITs had been using to buy real estate might now be used for
stock buybacks.
</P>
<P>
   Utility stocks, another historically favored sector in market
retreats because of their consistent earnings and dividend payouts,
also look underpriced to some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The average price-to-earnings ratio of utility stocks covered by
Merrill Lynch is about half that of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index. Utilities have also shown a notable resilience in the face
of the overall market's volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Rowan said, mergers and deregulation in the utility
industry meant that many of these stocks no longer offered the
safety that once attracted investors in uncertain times. ``We've
seen a blurring of the line that separates the pure, defensive,
regulated utility,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're recommending utility stocks,'' Ms. Rowan added, ``but we
like them less because of their defensive nature and more because
we have some really competitive utilities that do have very high
dividend yields, and that are trading at a discount to the
market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
