<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A broken line of strong but brief thunderstorms will rumble
across the eastern Great Lakes region as a cold front slicing
southeast wedges under and lifts humid air moving north from the
Ohio Valley. The far western flank of the front will stall over the
northern Plains, setting the stage for clusters of strong storms
over the Dakotas and Nebraska, where a stream of humid air from the
south intersects the front.
</P>
<P>
   A compact group of showers and thunderstorms will exit the
central Appalachians early Saturday and head into New York and
western New England, gradually dissipating as it proceeds
northeastward. But it will leave sufficient low-level moisture
behind so that another round of showers and thunderstorms will
develop over upstate New York and northwest New England later
Saturday as a jet stream disturbance in Canada brushes the region.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, clusters of showers and thunderstorms, some heavy,
will erupt over the South from Texas to the Southeast Seaboard as a
trough of low pressure at 18,000 feet swings slowly east over a
tropical and unstable air mass. Flash flooding is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated, strong thunderstorms will flare up from eastern Oregon
to the northern Rockies as a cool front lifts warm surface air. The
passage of the front will mark an easing of the heat that has
gripped much of the Northwest this week. Farther south, afternoon
and evening thunderstorms will bubble up over the mountains of the
West from the Sierra Nevada of California to the central and
southern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Red Flag Warning
</P>
<P>
   A ``red flag warning'' for wildfires was issued for the
Washington Cascades Friday. It has been extremely hot over the
interior Northwest during the past several weeks. Moreover,
rainfall has been sparse, which is not unusual, given that summer
is the region's dry season. Friday, a cool front bore down on
Washington from the Gulf of Alaska, signaling an eventual easing of
the heat. The changing of the guard in air masses was forecasted to
take place with high-based thunderstorms, whose rain would
evaporate before reaching the tinder-dry ground but whose lightning
would spark fires.
</P>
