<SLUG> BC-AREA-CODES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA TO GET NEW AREA CODES AS PHONE DEMAND RISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California, which had no telephone area codes at
all in 1947, is about to get its 23rd. Ant that's not the end of
it.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 24, people now living south of the Madera County line in
the sprawling Central Valley 209 area code, including Fresno, will
find themselves in the 559 area.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, new area codes will be created within 310 in Los
Angeles County and 619 in San Diego County.
</P>
<P>
   And in San Mateo, northern Santa Clara and part of Santa Cruz
counties, where people are just getting used to 650, yet another
split is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   When 650 was born on Aug. 2, 1997, then-regional area code
administrator Douglas Hescox said that it was ``expected to
accommodate the need for new phone numbers for about 12 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The unprecedented demand for telecommunication services has
caused the life span to be much shorter and even more difficult to
project,'' said Hescox's successor, Joe Cocke of Lockheed
Martin-IMS.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin-IMS is the Washington, D.C.-based company that
won a contract in January from the Federal Communications
Commission to administer area codes nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Now, prodded by telephone service providers, Lockheed Martin-IMS
is aiming to activate a new area code within the 650 area, possibly
within two years, Cocke said.
</P>
<P>
   The new 559 area will be California's 10th new area code in as
many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relief planning,'' the process whereby a new area code is
created, is triggered when the number of unused telephone numbers
dwindles. That number varies from area to area, Cocke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to give a 24-month notice that a new area code is going
to be implemented, but that hasn't happened all the time,'' Cocke
said. ``It's a pretty complicated process and, in addition to that,
we have to wait for approval from the California PUC.''
</P>
<P>
   The Public Utilities Commission must approve all new area codes.
</P>
<P>
   California law requires that phone companies offer customers six
months of ``permissive dialing,'' during which they can use the old
area code numbers after the creation of a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the proliferation of area codes assert that the
shortage of numbers is the artificial creation of phone companies,
which are buying them up and, in effect, warehousing them. Others
say that the voracious appetite for telecommunications, including
cell phones and pagers, plus the entry of new service providers
into the market, is responsible for the shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Cocke said his company, a neutral party under contract with the
Federal Communications Commission to administer area codes,
couldn't investigate the warehousing charge, which phone companies
say is false.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of a new area code within 310 will be an
``overlay,'' that is, new phone numbers added in that area will
simply be given a different area code. Next door neighbors, even
desk mates in offices, may have phones with different area codes.
</P>
<P>
   The overlay will be a first for California.
</P>
<P>
   Creating new area codes isn't cheap, even with the lead time
ostensibly built into the process. Estimates run as high as $40
million and include the costs of reprogramming computers and home
burglar alarms, changing business cards and stationery and other
standard business items that list phone numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
