<SLUG> BC-NY-FILM-FEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK FILM FESTIVAL WILL SHOWCASE FILMS FROM 26 COUNTRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Film Festival has announced the schedule
for its 36th annual presentation at Avery Fisher Hall, which opens
on Sept. 25 with Woody Allen's ``Celebrity'' and closes on Oct. 11
with ``The Dreamlife of Angels,'' the first film by the French
director Erick Zonca. Zonca's film, whose two young stars shared
best-actress honors at the Cannes International Film Festival in
May, follows the story of a pair of impoverished French women who
forge a volatile friendship.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, organized by the Film Society of Lincoln Center,
will offer 26 films from 15 countries, with a large contingent of
American and French directors. Its centerpiece presentation, Oct. 4
and 5 at Alice Tully Hall, will be ``Black Cat, White Cat,''
directed by Emir Kusturica. The film is a black comedy about a
Gypsy settlement along the polluted banks of the Danube River.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the festival include a special presentation
of ``Strike,'' the first film made by the Soviet director Sergei
Eisenstein, on Oct. 1 at the Walter Reade Theater. The showing
commemorates the 100th anniversary of the director's birth and will
be accompanied by a live performance of a new score for the film by
the Alloy Orchestra. The Swedish director Ingmar Bergman will also
be honored with a series of special screenings of his newest film,
``The Presence of a Clown,'' on Oct. 3 and 4 at the Walter Reade.
</P>
<P>
   That theater will also be home to a retrospective of the work of
the Egyptian filmmaker Youssef Chahine, whose film ``Destiny'' was
a popular entry at last year's festival, as well as the ``Views
From the Avant-Garde'' series on Oct. 10 and 11.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Zonca's debut, this year's schedule includes the
sophomore films of two promising young American directors, Todd
Solondz and Wes Anderson. Solondz, whose ``Welcome to the
Dollhouse'' was a critical success in 1996, will present
``Happiness,'' which deals with a dysfunctional suburban community.
Anderson, who was the director of ``Bottle Rocket'' in 1996, will
show his follow-up, ``Rushmore,'' a romantic comedy starring Bill
Murray as a heartsick millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule also includes showings of Mark Levin's ``Slam,''
which won top honors at the Sundance Film Festival; ``Velvet
Goldmine,'' a film about a glam rock band directed by Todd Haynes,
which will be his first full-length feature at the festival, and
``Book of Life,'' a new short film by Hal Hartley.
</P>
<P>
   Eight films from France are scheduled, including Gaspar Noe's
``I Stand Alone,'' and new works by Alain Resnais, Eric Rohmer and
Olivier Assayas. Among the other countries represented are Iran,
Russia, Denmark, Mali, Japan, Taiwan, Austria, Germany, Portugal
and Italy, whose Taviani brothers will present their newest effort,
``You're Laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   The British director John Boorman will have two films at the
festival: his latest, ``The General,'' for which he won the
best-director prize at this year's Cannes festival, and ``Point
Blank,'' his 1967 thriller starring Lee Marvin and Angie Dickinson.
</P>
<P>
   The other retrospective screening is ``Joyless Street,'' a 1925
silent film by the German director G.W. Pabst. A restored print, by
the Munich Filmmuseum, will be accompanied by a new piano score,
played by Aljosha Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK FILM FESTIVAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The box office for the festival, which is sponsored by Grand
Marnier, will open at Lincoln Center's Alice Tully Hall on Sept.
13. Tickets range from $12 to $30. Information: (212)875-5050.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
