<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4699 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HENRY-THEATER-REVIEW-     08-14 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENRY-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HENRY V': HIS KINGDOM FOR A PARKING LOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In most productions of ``Henry V,'' you do not see a
man who isn't even a cast member walk onstage, get into his
spruce-green Honda Civic and drive away. But those are the chances
you take when you stage Shakespeare in a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The Expanded Arts theater company deserves the praise it has
received for its 3-year-old series, Free Shakespeare in the
Park(ing) Lot.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say, however, that Kenneth Branagh has anything
to worry about. The company does an admirable job under the
circumstances (the competition of planes, buses, pedestrians, an
H&AMP;H Bagels truck crossing the lot, a gray plastic bag mysteriously
levitating its way across the stage), but it doesn't completely
succeed in bringing the characters' emotions to life.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Henry V,'' however, has a rousing beginning _ Henry's
drinking buddies singing about ``a drop of good beer'' _ and a
charming ending. And if the battle scenes, played against a wall of
graffiti, have the look of the Jets and Sharks' opening scenes in
``West Side Story,'' there's a kind of circular logic to that.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly McAllister (brother of the play's director, Jerry
McAllister) is a good-looking, boyish Henry who convincingly gives
up his youthful wanton ways, virtually overnight, when he becomes
king. But he takes the St. Crispin's Day speech, every Henry's
moment of glory, and turns it into bluster. He somewhat redeems
himself, with humor, wooing Katherine (Amy Speace) in the final
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Players in relatively small parts have some nice moments,
particularly Jason Brown as the Dauphin, Lee Winston as the Duke of
Burgundy and Chris Santangelo as the Earl of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Speace makes a believable, desirable Katherine, wearing a
rich, dark gown. (Most of the other cast members perform in jeans
or downtown black, with or without robes thrown over their
contemporary clothes.) And the hanging scene, which has been
stylized within an inch of its life, works beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry V'' continues Wednesdays through Saturdays at 8 p.m. at
the corner of Broome and Ludlow streets, through Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HENRY V'
</P>
<P>
   By William Shakespeare; directed by Jerry McAllister. Presented
by Expanded Arts. At the Municipal Parking Lot, Broome and Ludlow
streets, Lower East Side, New York.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jason Brown (Dauphin and McMorris), Kelly McAllister
(Henry V), Vinnie Penna (Chorus and Pistol), Baz Snider (Falstaff,
King of France, Erpingham and Grandpre), Lee Winston (Exeter and
Burgundy), Chris Santangelo (Cambridge and Constable) and Amy
Speace (Katherine).
</P>
