<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE FOR ADULT CHILDREN  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - How to help your aging parents: &QL; 
_Recognize that we all age differently. Today's elders have
different health needs than did their parents. Gather as much
knowledge as you can about the aging process so you will know what
is normal aging and what is not. &QL; 
_Children should focus on ``being with,'' instead of ``doing for''
their parents, especially when a parent is in the generally healthy
65-to-75 age bracket.  &QL; 
_Know your family style. Some families express emotional intimacy;
others are more distant. A goal for midlife is to develop an
adult-to-adult relationship with your parents, if you don't have
one already. &QL; 
_How often you should call and write depends on the family and the
health of the parents. But when an older parent begins to show
signs of even mild impairment, it is important to contact them
frequently. &QL; 
_Parents often want to feel needed and useful. They want to be
productive members of the family, but often aren't given the
opportunity. New ways for them to be productive and helpful in the
family may need to be explored. &QL; 
_Let your parents control their own decision-making. But if you
start to see severe memory impairment or a series of poor
decisions, it's time to step in. &QL; 
_If a parent becomes ill, establish an action plan that involves
all family members, with one of the children taking the lead. &QL; 
_Helping your parents get their financial and legal affairs in
order may prevent headaches later. Having a will, a living will,
and medical and general powers of attorney are vital when parents
are unable to make decisions.  &QL; 
_Keep a list of the medications your parents take. &QL; 
_After a loss of a spouse, even the most independent of parents may
need more from their children. Spend some time with them and help
assess their changing needs.  &QL; 
_The key to long-distance care is planning ahead and communicating
regularly with your parents, other family members, your parents'
friends and neighbors, doctors, bankers, lawyers and other people
who can offer assistance. &QL; 
_Children of Aging Parents, a national nonprofit organization
dedicated to assisting adult children and their aging parents, also
has information for family members, 800-227-7294. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sources: Phoenix, Ariz., psychologist David Helgeson, Bonnie Hughes
Marcus and the booklet ``Aging Parents and Common Sense,'' a
publication of Children of Aging Parents. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
