<HEADER>
A4710 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-METZ-ART-$ADV1     08-14 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-METZ-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BEAR SEES THE RETURN OF `THE REALITY PRINCIPLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16)  
 (af)  
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Metz is relieved that the stock market has retreated
more than 10 percent from the dizzying heights of mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   If the remarkable bull run had continued, stocks would have just
had that much further to fall and would have caused greater havoc
than they are now, said Metz, one of the market's leading bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reality principle is coming back to Wall Street,''
Metz said last Wednesday at the CIBC Oppenheimer Corp.'s
headquarters in the World Financial Center in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that Asia is not a passing fancy,'' he said.
``The idea, which was the consensus going into the summer _ that
you would have a resumption of 10 percent or 12 percent earnings
gains in the second half of the year _ is disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Metz, a managing director in CIBC Oppenheimer's equity research
department, said he expected cash to outperform the main indexes
over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Such predictions are not new for Metz, 69. He has been calling
stocks overpriced for four years. But he is not a perennial bear.
He advocated aggressively buying stocks during the gulf war in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   He also advocated buying stocks in 1982, the dawn of the longest
bull market in history. ``Stocks were as cheap as mud then,'' he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Metz also wryly acknowledges his forecasting errors. ``I have
been wrong about the direction of the market,'' he said. ``But I
still think it has been overvalued.''
</P>
<P>
   A frequent pundit in print and on television, Metz has his
critics and defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph V. Battipaglia, the chief investment strategist at
Gruntal &AMP; Co. and a leading bull, criticized Metz _ with whom he
has sparred often _ as being overly pessimistic, particularly on
oil and commodity prices in the early and mid-1990s, and on the
prospects for American productivity improvements. ``Michael has
been a bit of an alarmist about certain things,'' Battipaglia said.
</P>
<P>
   But Metz also has his defenders. ``Michael Metz has been
victimized by the bull market,'' said James Grant, editor of
Grant's Interest Rate Observer. ``He's the `yes, but' guy in a
gee-whiz world. I am certain when all this is over, he will be seen
as more of a prophet than a fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Metz said he did not think the market's latest gyrations
presaged a financial Armageddon. But he painted an alarming picture
about the collapse in oil prices, which has been caused partly by
reduced demand from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If oil prices stay at $12 a barrel for the next six or nine
months, you can say goodbye to the house of Saud, to Yeltsin, to
Mexico, to Venezuela and to Indonesia,'' he said. ``If you think
oil prices are going to stay here for the next six to nine months,
my advice is to sell everything. Because you're going to be in a
period of unspeakable political instability around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Metz suggested that United States policy-makers should put
pressure on friendly oil-producers like Norway, Britain and Mexico
to cut production and bolster prices.
</P>
<P>
   Given his pessimistic views, it is not surprising that Metz
warns investors to be conservative, accrue cash, pay down debts and
selectively acquire beaten-down stocks like semiconductor companies
and undervalued second-tier stocks in the United States and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong hotel chains are selling at a huge discount to
book,'' he said. ``There probably won't be another hotel built in
Hong Kong for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He also sees bargains in some energy stocks. ``I'd look at a lot
of middle-tier exploration and development companies, and
particularly those in North America. I was thinking of things like
Pennzoil, maybe Swift Energy, Apache, Burlington Resources.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Metz said he was more convinced than ever that
the market has been in the grips of the bear since April, when the
vast population of stocks began to slide, eventually pulling bigger
stocks along with it this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have got an overcrowded, overinvested universe of market
participants against a background where the so-called fundamentals
are deteriorating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He ridiculed Wall Street analysts who expect corporate earnings
growth to continue at unprecedented levels for years. ``If you
think about it, if you extrapolate on that, you're going to have
earnings higher than revenues at some point. And that's not going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Metz was Oppenheimer's investment strategist for more than seven
years until April. ``Right at the peak,'' as he put it.
</P>
<P>
   As for talk in the market that CIBC Oppenheimer was eager to
replace Metz with a more bullish strategist, Metz said, ``It's an
interesting observation, but in any case, I was wrong'' about the
market. CIBC Oppenheimer has not yet named a new strategist to
replace Metz.
</P>
<P>
   The huge run-up in the stock market reflects a fundamental
change in the people who are investing, Metz said. Americans who
once put savings in banks now plow it into mutual funds and 401(k)
plans, lured by higher rates of return. Such a shift, he said,
``creates enormous vulnerability for the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   It has given rise to some misleading canards, too, in Metz's
view. ``People talk about the baby boomers saving more,'' he said.
``It happens not to be true. What's happened is that the American
householder has depended mostly on appreciation in the stock market
to do his savings for him.''
</P>
<P>
   So, does Metz feel vindicated now that the market finally seems
to be retreating? ``No,'' Metz said, but he recalled John Maynard
Keynes's warning about the foolishness of trying to impose ``a
rational structure on an irrational institution,'' like the stock
market. ``Every once in a while,'' Metz said, ``it's wonderful when
it seems to be more rational.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
