<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-FASHIONS-2TAKES-     08-14 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-FASHIONS-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIC LITTLE NUMBERS: THE HIPLESS ELITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday Aug. 16)  
 (bl)  
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chantal William, the owner of the G.C. William
boutique on Madison Avenue near 85th Street, looked on in amusement
the other day as Romy Schreiber breezed in, her fashion antennae
twitching. As Ms. William recalled, no sooner had her client
crossed the threshold than she made a beeline for a rack of little
black dresses, pleading to try on a sleeveless model sparkling with
beads. ``I picked it out myself, it was my style,'' Ms. Schreiber
said later.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to define that style, she fumbled for the right word,
settling on ``cool,'' an adjective she applied to other items on
her most-wanted list, which ran from twin sets and pendant chokers
to long skinny skirts, bell-bottoms and tiny kilts like one she had
just acquired by Burberrys.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schreiber also obligingly listed her favorite makes and
models _ Calvin Klein, DKNY, Kate Moss and Cindy Crawford _
chanting their names in the sing-song rhythm of a small girl
skipping rope.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schreiber is 9. At an age when many of her contemporaries
are decked out in overalls and box-pleated skirts, her own
hyper-hip fashion choices conjure up an image that's two parts Posh
Spice, one part Diana, the Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   She would recognize a kindred spirit in Kristina Obermeier, 10,
who was spied perusing the racks in Saks Fifth Avenue's girls'
department. With her blond hair pulled back in a chignon like her
idol, the Olympic figure skater Tara Lipinski, Kristina streaked
toward the DKNY rack, leaving her mother in the dust. She gazed
Frisbee-eyed at a calf-length, column-shaped jumper that could
easily pass muster at her parochial school but flirted with fashion
just the same. ``It's black and I love to wear black,'' she said,
with the authority of a budding style maven. ``It goes with
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Both girls cultivate a look poised at fashion's cutting edge.
Only a few years ago, it would have marked them as members of a hip
elite, their tastes outside the mainstream. But to hear the experts
tell it, these days fashion-forward little girls have lots of
company. America's youngest fashion consumers, age 10 and under,
represent a huge market, whose profile is rapidly shifting, said
Traci Mitchell, the executive editor of Children's Business, a
fashion trade monthly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of little girls want to look grown up and
fashion-conscious _ it's a big trend,'' Ms. Mitchell said, adding
that although parents hold the purse strings, their style-savvy
offspring are increasingly making the buying decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``tweens'' in the fashion trade, there were 9.5 million
girls between ages 5 and 9 in 1996, a figure that will grow to 9.7
million by 2000, according to the U.S. Census Bureau. No longer do
many of them want to dress in the crew-neck sweaters, cotton
pullovers and starchy frocks their mothers wore as children and
might try to steer their daughters toward.
</P>
<P>
   ``My retail clients tell me that starting at about age 7, but
sometimes as young as 3 or 4, children start making the fashion
choices and the buying decisions,'' said Diane Rattican, an
importer for high-style European children's lines like Naf Naf,
Chevignon, Kenzo Jungle and Elle. ``They come in with their
parents, their minds already made up. And if the parents make the
selection, they often end up returning it because their kids
refused to wear it.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to cater to these young customers, stores and
designers have lately flooded the market with scaled-down versions
of clothes that might have marched straight off the women's
ready-to-wear runways for this season _ looks like flared pants,
Capris, long slinky skirts, fitted shirts and ribbed sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are so educated _ they know what they want, and
they're not shy about letting you know,'' Ms. William said. ``A
9-year-old will tell you: `I'd like the same skirt as my mom. I
love the way Cindy Crawford looks in that spaghetti-strap dress.'
They see W at home on the coffee table and they use it like a
catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   They are far more likely, however, to take their style cues from
a diversity of pop culture sources: the Delia's catalog of teen-age
clothing or Seventeen magazine, pilfered from an older sister's
dressing table, and television programming targeted to teen-agers,
like MTV, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and ``Moesha,'' the sitcom
starring Brandy, a 19-year-old pop diva with a rabid preteen
following (and who is on the cover of Seventeen next month).
</P>
<P>
   Children of the VCR, tweens have also had their fashion
precociousness shaped by endless viewings of movies like
``Clueless'' and ``Spice World,'' in which Posh Spice, the soigne
member of the Spice Girls, muses dreamily, ``Should I wear my Gucci
tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls get the message that it's fine to look like miniature
adults from the media, which is more powerful now than ever,'' said
Nancy Samalin, a parent-educator and the author of ``Loving Your
Child Is Not Enough'' (Penguin-Viking, 1987), a manual of child
rearing. She argues that the trend is not good for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are bombarded with brand names and images of teen-aged
girls dressed in tight little black outfits, and they're going to
want to emulate that,'' she continued. ``It's a parent's job to
help them resist that temptation by limiting the amount of time a
child spends shopping, and being more selective about the kinds of
TV and movies she sees.''
</P>
<P>
   But many parents find nothing wrong with a child who has an
advanced sense of style. ``I'm glad my girls respond to fashion,''
said Myriam Schrieber, a jewelry designer and the mother of Romy.
``I think that's a very ladylike thing to be into. Trends aren't
something you should learn about all of a sudden when you're in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents draw a line between the trendy and the tarty.
Jennifer Blaikie, an elementary school teacher in New York whose
daughters are 8 and 6, said, ``If she had her way, my eldest would
look like Baby Spice.'' She copes by compromising. ``If my daughter
wants to wear two ponytails on top of her head, that's fine,'' she
said. ``But she's not wearing sexy little clothes when she's 8. I
don't think that's teaching the right lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Retailers like Ms. William gently nudge their young clients in
the direction of chic. Seeded like Skittles throughout her boutique
are current issues of Seventeen, In Style and People, replete with
glossy images of Cameron Diaz, Christina Ricci and Dominique Swain,
the star of ``Lolita,'' sheathed in form-fitting dresses and
thigh-slit skirts.
</P>
<P>
   At Marsha D.D. on Lexington Avenue near 88th Street, racks and
tables overflow with velvet side-slit miniskirts, tank tops and
fake-fur-collared cardigans, shown not in pastels but in fashion's
current dusky palette of eggplant, black and gray. ``This is a
children's store, but you won't see any pink,'' said Marsha Drogin
Dayan, who owns the shop and a companion boys' store next door.
``Rejecting pink is a political statement for this age group,'' she
said. ``When you get to be 7 or 8, by giving it up you show that
you're not a baby anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dayan's clients are just as likely to turn up their noses at
puffy sleeves, Peter Pan collars, and smocking and shirring,
holding out instead for such badges of cool as ankle-length skirts
from Junior Kraze ($42), hip-clutching stretch denim flares from
JNCO (about $35 to $50), little black dresses by Nicole Miller ($90
to $120) and black pants. ``A 10-year-old is on the same quest for
the perfect black pant that you are,'' said Ms. Dayan, who
cultivates in her diminutive patrons a stripped-down modernist
sensibility. ``I think of them as future Prada customers,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A similarly spare, though more pointedly luxurious esthetic
prevails at Barneys New York; its children's collection is filled
with doll-size knits by Missoni, East-meets-West down-filled
jackets by Kenzo, tent-shaped dresses by Dries van Noten and A-line
jumpers by Moschino, fattened up with the same padding and quilting
that dominated the runways last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more designers are making kids' clothes modeled on
their adult collections,'' said Phyllis Pressman, the executive
vice president and general merchandise manager of Chelsea Passage,
Barneys' housewares and children's department.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pressman, who does most of the buying for the children's
collection, said the famous-designer items sell, despite their
sometimes stratospheric prices. One of the store's biggest
children's hits of last season was an Hermes jacket for $400.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Gap, purveyor of pocket T-shirts and cargo pants to the
children's mass market, has lately traded up in the hope of
appeasing customers' appetite for high style. The company plans to
open a large Baby Gap store on Fifth Avenue at 54th Street in
October, showcasing a line of sweaters in the season's hottest
luxury fabric _ cashmere _ alongside a black velvet mock-turtle
bodysuit, like the top Sharon Stone wore at the Oscars two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these sophisticated togs are meant to catch the eye not
of the toddlers, but of their trend-following elders, who snap up
looks priced from $18 to $198 _ never mind that their offspring
will streak them with Play-Doh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents tend to see their children as extensions of
themselves,'' Ms. Mitchell of Children's Business said. ``They
don't want them to wear just anything. They don't want clothes that
are frilly or emblazoned with cute cartoon characters. Cutesiness
is not appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Betty Obermeier's daughter Kristina raced toward her
clutching a leopard-print coat at Saks last week, Mrs. Obermeier
beamed approvingly. ``She could wear that to church,'' she said.
``Why not? At least on a Sunday when she wasn't altar serving.''
She was less ecstatic, however, when her 7-year-old, Melissa,
brought over a smocked dress. ``It's too babyish,'' she chided,
sending the youngster skittering back to the racks.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years in the children's clothing business, Ms. Dayan is
still astonished when her tiniest clients mimic their mothers'
shopping habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A girl might stand for a half-hour trying on these,'' she
said, gesturing toward a basket filled with $3 silver thumb rings.
``You would think that their futures depended on picking out just
the right one. I've seen people buy diamonds in less time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
