</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-PROBE-COSTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT'S BEHIND STARR'S MULTI-MILLION DOLLAR EXPENSE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Critics of independent counsel Kenneth Starr have
made the $40-50 million spent on the probe of President Clinton
into a rallying cry.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's defenders turn the tables, asserting that White House
delay tactics, stonewalling, and costly court appeals have dragged
out the four-year probe and driven up the price tag.
</P>
<P>
   And that is just part of the money battle that has been a
backdrop in this titanic legal struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress have protested that dozens of government
lawyers at the White House and in federal departments are helping
to defend the president on the taxpayers' tab.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defenders, for their part, complain about the huge
private legal fees that the first family and their associates have
to pay in the probe that stems from the Clinton's Whitewater real
estate venture in Arkansas. As many as 100 current and former White
House officials, and up to 300 others connected with the Clintons
in Arkansas and elsewhere, have run up private legal bills in
excess of $23 million, according to a recent survey conducted by
the liberal Nation magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Although much more than money is at stake, the high cost has
touched a responsive chord in the public and has become a major
refrain among the president's defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American public is sick of this $50-million five-year sex
investigation,'' James Carville, a close Clinton friend and
self-declared commander of a ``war'' on Starr, said in a call to
cable TV's ``Rivera Live'' this past week.
</P>
<P>
   That charge ``is a great sound bite,'' said C. Boyden Gray, who
served as President George Bush's chief counsel. But Gray added in
a telephone interview that most of the money was spent long before
the investigation into allegations that Clinton had sex with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky and then attempted a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the Lewinsky investigation, which is only
seven months old, has probably cost no more than $10 million, while
the bulk of the expenses have come in earlier phases of Starr's
investigation into the Whitewater land deal, the improper storage
of FBI files in the White House, the firing of the White House
travel office staff and the death of White House deputy counsel
Vincent Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Gray also said that the White House has pushed the government's
costs much higher by fighting Starr in appeals courts on
attorney-client privilege, testimony from president's Secret
Service agents assigned to protect the president, and executive
privilege claims.
</P>
<P>
   In one ultimately unsuccessful appeal of attorney-client
privilege, the Justice Department saw a conflict-of-interest in
opposing Starr, and so the Clinton administration hired the law
firm of Mayer, Brown and Platt to argue the White House case in the
Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals in St. Louis. The firm charged a
discounted rate of $99 an hour compared with its normal top rate of
$500 an hour. Nevertheless, the bill came to about $100,000, said
firm member Andrew Frey.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the White House counsel's office has more than
doubled in size since Clinton took office and now totals at least
34 people, several of whom work daily on the Clinton defense
strategy. Justice Department attorneys and lawyers at the Treasury
Department have been brought into various aspects of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The total price tag may never be known. However, the expense has
some defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a system that needs, even at a very high cost, to
guarantee that the person in charge with enforcing the federal laws
is not himself a lawbreaker, `` George Washington University law
professor Jonathan Turley said on CNN this week. ``I mean, this is
an expensive system. Madisonian democracy is not a deal. There are
cheaper alternatives. It's just that they're not better systems.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
