<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4749 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV16-B     08-14 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUST-BUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 16, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was always something of a swashbuckler by his own account, a
teen-age refugee from Hitler's Germany who fought for America in
the Pacific, then surreptitiously shipped out to Israel for its
1948 war of independence. Afterward, he picked up a PhD in
economics from the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   But the great adventure of Ralph Anspach's life began in 1971.
That was when an after-dinner game of Monopoly and an argument
about oil prices turned him into an inventor determined to build a
better game.
</P>
<P>
   That put him on a collision with Parker Brothers, the Salem game
publishing firm that during the 1930s had turned Monopoly into the
best-selling board game ever. And the subsequent clash between the
populist professor and the determined corporation flickered in and
out of the headlines for a quarter of a century before it was
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Now Anspach, a professor of economics at San Francisco State
University, has produced a book-length account of his adventure.
And though it may not be the last word, it is by far the fullest
version yet of a battle that illuminates key elements of American
business history, from the populism of the 1880s to the great
galvanization of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everybody knows the story of Monopoly _ how it was
invented by an out-of-work heating engineer named Charles Darrow
during the dark days of the Great Depression. Darrow set the game
in Atlantic City to remind his children of happier days at the
beach resort in the days before the 1929 Crash. The story was
contained in every box.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's where matters stood when Anspach put his game of
Anti-Monopoly on the national market in 1974. Then Parker Brothers
sued, charging patent infringement, determined to put the professor
out of business. But pretty soon it turned out that the Darrow
legend concealed a far more fascinating, if less inspiring, truth.
</P>
<P>
   When sued, Anspach did what inventors usually do. He prepared to
defend his originality and countersued as well, asserting that
Parker Brothers didn't really have a perfect right to patent
protection. As the confrontation began to make the airwaves _ it
was a cute story, after all _ people began telling Anspach of how
they had played the game of Monopoly in the early years of the
century, long before Darrow claimed to have ``invented'' it.
</P>
<P>
   Then began a strange cross-country journey in the course of
which Anspach visited old-timers, interviewed them, and slowly
traced Monopoly back to its beginnings. Often he was accompanied by
Parker Brothers patent attorney, an amiable New Yorker named Oliver
Howes.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the basic version of the game we know today _
purchasable properties including utilities, a ``Go to jail'' space,
and a public park where ``free parking'' is today _ had been
invented in 1904 by a woman named Elizabeth Magie who was
interested in illustrating Henry George's single tax principles.
She called it the Landlord's Game.
</P>
<P>
   Magie's game had passed through many hands, being played in
universities and utopian communities, gradually coming to be known
as monopoly, until it took its distinctive present form _ Atlantic
City street names, including the misspelled Marvin Gardens _ in a
group of Quakers with roots in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   It was from a high school friend among the Quakers that Darrow
learned the game. Anspach actually found the couple who taught him
the rules. And the professor reconstructed in loving detail the
subsequent fraud that Darrow and his Parker Brothers sponsers
perpetrated: buying up rival patents (especially a game called
Finance,) intimidating would-be imitators, rewriting history, all
in the interest of developing what would become one of the
entertainment industry's most successful brands.
</P>
<P>
   All this is laid out in Anspach's 224-page book, ``The Billion
Dollar Monopoly Swindle.'' It is self-published, costs $18, can be
easily obtained at 650-299-0534 or www.antimonopoly.com, and is
engagingly written in detective story fashion. It really belongs in
every summer cottage that now contains a game of Monopoly (or
Anti-Monopoly) and a reader or two.
</P>
<P>
   This is Anspach's story, not Monopoly's: his early start-up
difficulties, the search for evidence, the court battles (in one
momentary reversal, his Antimonopoly games are plowed into a
Minnesota garbage dump), his continual public relations battle with
the giant corporations that own the game (at one point, Anspach
crashes the World Monopoly Tournament; at another, he ceremonially
contributes a plaque to the Atlantic City Holiday Inn that stands
on the site where the game was actually invented).
</P>
<P>
   Less clear in this account, but still stimulating, is Anspach's
analysis of patent, copyright, and trademark law. What he doesn't
fathom is the high fixed cost that was necessary to make a national
game of Monopoly, and Parker Brothers' corresponding drive to
recover its investment and make a gain. After all, what
businessperson will be willing to expensively develop a product he
cannot control? There is a world of difference between a tenured
professor off on a quest and a commercial firm desperately
struggling for solvency.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the climax of Anspach's book comes when Robert R.M.
Barton, the business genius who saw Parker Brothers through the
Great Depression, describes his patent strategy: ``We had the basic
underlying patent of the Landlord's Game...we owned the Finance
game, and we owned Charles Darrow's game...We had the whole
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Anspach's rejoinder, that only inventors are entitled to
patents, is much too flip. For Barton has assembled a monopoly on
the rights to Monopoly _ and he (and his front Charles Darrow) have
gained a great fortune, just as in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the book, when Anspach finally has won the
right to market his Antimonopoly game, a vice president of Hasbro
Inc., Parker Brothers' most recent corporate parent, says to him,
``Welcome to the world of competition, Ralph.'' What does he find?
That Pawtucket, R.I.-based Hasbro has bought up 80 percent to the
game market, that Toys R Us controls a similar portion of the
retail market, that shelf space is all, and that computers are
quickly turning board games into a novelty items. In this rough and
tumble world not even patents can make the world safe for
cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   You can't ask one guy to do everything. Anspach has blazed a
trail, amassed a great lot of evidence, written a great cautionary
tale against the trust we too often repose in public relations
hype. But his economics are disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   It will remain for others to draw the moral, to make the most
basic point _ that we tolerate, even sanction monopolies, because
they deliver the goods. They are a vital feature of the landscape,
as desirable as they are inevitable. So in the meantime, Parker
Brothers' Monopoly still has much economics to teach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
