<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-ISLAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS DISCOVER THRIVING CORAL REEFS NEAR TINY CARIBBEAN ISLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The discovery of pristine coral reefs near a
virtually unknown American island in the Caribbean is a chance for
the United States to repair a ``melancholy history'' of coral reef
preservation, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A two-week scientific expedition to the remote island revealed
coral reefs that researchers said may be the most pristine reefs in
Caribbean and U.S. waters, according to scientists from the Center
for Marine Preservation (CMC), a nonprofit marine preservation
group.
</P>
<P>
   The island, called Navassa, supports hundreds of species of
animals and plants in a dry, hot climate. The tiny, rocky two
square miles of U.S. territory, 40 miles east of Haiti, lacks fresh
water. A surrounding cliff forces visitors to either climb a ladder
from the shore or fly in on helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   CMC scientists have been interested in exploring the island for
some time, according to Roger McManus, president of the group. When
CMC asked the Interior Department to sponsor the expedition,
Babbitt said his first response was: ``I never heard of Navassa
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said the proposed expedition was ``fraught with mystery
and romance possibilities.'' He endorsed the proposal on the basis
of the scientific knowledge that would be gained, Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no escaping the fact that we must prevent the
melancholy history of degradation and misuse'' of coral reefs, he
told reporters here. Coral reefs have been mismanaged, exploited
and overused by the United States, he said, citing reef destruction
by boaters or water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   When areas such as the Florida Keys were opened to boaters in
the 1930s, there wasn't much emphasis placed on preserving the
delicate coral growths that house hundreds of marine organisms.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department is considering making the island a
refuge or special management zone, which would limit human access
to the territory. The department already requires visitors to
obtain special permission to go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural values of this place _ small, fragile, uninhabited
_ certainly speak of protecting it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Smith, a CMC scientist on the trip, said the remote
location and difficult access have made it difficult for humans to
extensively exploit the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Navassa is not in anyone's backyard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Navassa has not always been deserted. In the mid 1800s, a
Baltimore-based mining company sent 140 workers there to mine
guano. But in 1889, a rebellion killed five supervisors, and many
workers were returned to Baltimore to face murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   The company continued operations until 1898 when the
Spanish-American war forced the company to evacuate the workers.
The firm later filed for bankruptcy. The island has not been mined
since.
</P>
<P>
   Holes made by the miners make it difficult to walk on the
island. ``It takes four hours to walk a mile,'' hopping over holes,
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The scientific expedition discovered 15 species of previously
unknown plants, insects, lichens and reptiles unique to the island,
Smith said. Scientists may find up to 250 new species once the
samples are examined, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In waters around the coral reef, the marine team also found
healthy populations of organisms that are declining in other parts
of the Caribbean, such as black spiny sea urchins, which nearly
died off in the 1980s, according to Nina Young, the CMC's marine
team leader. She said nearby deep waters haven't been explored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only begun to scratch the surface,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting access to the area will be necessary to preserve the
marine environment, which the CMC scientists tout as the best
example of primitive Caribbean waters, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Lured by the natural riches of the island, people ``could come
in and destroy the fabulous nature of this reef,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh climate and lack of water have prevented people from
settling the island and, as a result, the coral reef has had
limited human contact, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said diving into the waters off the coast of the tiny island
was like ``looking into the window of an aquarium.''
</P>
<P>
   The island has been a U.S. territory since a sea captain named
Peter Duncan claimed it in 1857.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
