<SLUG> BC-LUBY-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDER OF LUBY'S CAFETERIA CHAIN DEAD AT 88 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARMINA DANINI  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Robert M. ``Bob'' Luby, founder of a cafeteria
that opened in San Antonio in 1947 and eventually evolved into a
multimillion-dollar chain serving homestyle food, has died at age
88.
</P>
<P>
   Luby died of heart complications Thursday in a Colorado Springs,
Colo., hospital, according to Luby's spokeswoman Karen Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company founded by Luby and his cousin, Charles R.
Johnston, has 231 units in 11 states. Texas has 160 Luby's
Cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   Born July 14, 1910, in Mansfield, Mo., Bob Luby and his parents
moved to San Antonio in 1927. Although he'd owned a successful
cafeteria in Dallas before the war, Bob Luby decided to open his
first post-war venture in San Antonio after returning from military
service.
</P>
<P>
   Opening a cafeteria at a downtown location was viewed as Luby's
folly. But it turned out to be the perfect spot. Opening day _ Jan.
28, 1947 _ found Luby's Cafeteria packed with customers at lunch
and at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Success was due to three things: throngs of servicemen home from
the war, downtown hotels filled with families because of the
housing shortage and theaters that drew people to see a movie and
eat dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Luby and Johnston ran the company based partly on the philosophy
of ``share the work, share the risks, share the profits,''
principles attributed to Luby's father, Harry.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, 40 percent of a cafeteria's net income goes to the
managers and the owners get the rest.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years, according to ``The Luby's Story,'' written
by Steve Barnhill and published in 1988, Luby and Johnston had
their office in the front seat of their Studebaker.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting system wasn't sophisticated, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We paid for everything in cash _ deliveries, bills _ right out
of the cash register. The outgo was recorded in a little book kept
beside the register,'' Luby said.
</P>
<P>
   Luby served as president until 1971, chairman of the board until
1982 and as director and consultant until 1993, when he was named
director emeritus. That same year, Luby was inducted into the Texas
Business Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   It was Luby's father, Harry Luby, a clothes merchant, who first
embraced a concept that was quite new in 1911 of customers
selecting their food from a counter and carrying it on trays to
their table.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Luby opened his first cafeteria, the New England Dairy
Lunch, in Springfield, Mo., in 1911. By 1927, he owned 11
cafeterias in three states. The venture proved so lucrative that he
retired at age 39.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Bob Luby worked in his father's cafeterias,
learning the business from the ground up. He also took to heart his
father's credos: Give people fresh, quality food at reasonable
prices and feed the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Luby is survived by his wife, Kathleen Lane Luby; two
daughters, Dr. Martha Luby Lahana of Colorado, and Elizabeth Rogers
and husband Wallace Rogers III of San Antonio; and two
grandchildren, Emmy Rogers and Wallace Rogers IV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
