<HEADLINE>
BOOK FOCUSES ON RAISING HEALTHY, SPIRITUAL FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Praise your children in public. Criticize them in
private.
</P>
<P>
   Don't lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Express joy that your child is your child. Keep your marriage
strong.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to your teenagers about saving sex for marriage, then give
them reasons to say no.
</P>
<P>
   Apologize. Spank your child in specific circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   And pray. Pray a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Focus on the Family's ``Complete Book of Baby &AMP; Child Care''
takes parents from preparing the nest to emptying the nest in its
887 pages and over territory not traveled by the world's
best-selling parenting resource, ``Dr. Spock's Baby and Child
Care.``
</P>
<P>
   The seventh revised edition of Benjamin Spock's book, released
in June, is light on religion, with only a brief mention of
spirituality and God.
</P>
<P>
   Focus' book integrates spirituality as an everyday part of life
for families, gives advice on instilling moral and religious
beliefs in children, and acts as a practical reference book for
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to have a book that would cross over into the
broader public . . . yet to get across the idea that it's as
reasonable for a family to pray over something as it is for them to
check it out on the Internet,'' said Dr. Paul C. Reisser, the
book's primary author and a family practitioner in Thousand Oaks,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The authors succeeded in writing a book with up-to-date medical
advice on caring for children that will appeal beyond the
conservative Christian circles that are Focus on the Family's
biggest supporters, said Elisa Morgan, the founder and president of
Mothers of Preschoolers. The Christian support group for mothers is
found in many denominations, and she is recommending the book to
the organization's 70,000 mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It covers the gamut,'' Morgan said. ``I felt it was fair and
balanced and written very comfortably on the lay level. It's just
practical wisdom and advice. We get this precious baby in our
hands, and we think `Yikes! What am I supposed to do now?' If
you've got a problem, you can look it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The 13,000-member Christian Medical &AMP; Dental Society also is
recommending the book to its members and their patients. There are
good comprehensive child-care books on the market and good books on
spirituality and children, but this is the first book to combine
the two so well, said Dr. David Stevens, the executive director of
the Tennessee-based national professional organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book has filled a void that has existed for many years,''
said Stevens, a physician with a specialty in family practice.
``There's a great hunger out there among parents for somebody who
can speak authoritatively on key issues as well as integrate that
with a clear (religious) world view.''
</P>
<P>
   The foreword was written by James Dobson, founder and president
of Focus on the Family, an evangelical Christian ministry with
radio programs, books, magazines and other ministries based in
Colorado Springs. The book itself is the work of 40 Christian
physicians, members of the Focus on the Family Physicians Resource
Council. An additional 50 physicians, covering numerous
specialties, reviewed and edited the material.
</P>
<P>
   The physicians are a volunteer group that advises the Christian
ministry on medical issues, and they worked on the book at the
request of Tyndale House Publishers Inc., which wanted a
comprehensive book on nurturing a child's mind, body and soul for
the both the churchgoing and non-churchgoing crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The book's values are Judeo-Christian, but the tone is Christian
with quotes from both the Old and New testaments. In the foreword,
Dobson's first advice on parenting is ``dedicating yourself and
your baby to the care of the only truly perfect parent _ the Lord
Jesus Christ,'' but the book is not a crusade for the soul. Rather,
it's written for single mothers, unwed teen mothers, divorced
parents, stepfamilies, grandparents raising grandchildren and
traditional families.
</P>
<P>
   The book does not gloss over heavy subjects such as suicide,
drugs and alcohol, sexual activity, homosexuality, death,
pornography, teenage pregnancy, eating disorders and divorce. They
are discussed from a biblical viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Spock advises parents to tell their teenagers to
wait until ``love is deep and long-lasting before having sexual
relations.'' Focus' book says it is ``appropriate, wise and
potentially life-saving'' to teach your children to save sex for
marriage and spends several pages on why the book advocates this.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the topic of teenage pregnancy, a parent's
reaction to other families' situations is important: ``If you give
a clear signal that the non-marital sex was wrong but respond with
compassion (and prayer) for the people involved, you make it clear
you can be approached if anyone at home has a problem. But if your
response sounds something like `Don't you ever do something as
stupid/shameful/evil as this,' you could block potentially critical
communication in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of child-care books advise against spanking a
child, as does the American Academy of Pediatrics, an organization
of 53,000 doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Parents do spank their children, Reisser said, and the Focus
book gives guidelines so spanking is not a release of a parent's
anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a problem of many parents who use it too much, too
often, too harshly,'' Reisser said.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-page chapter on discipline spends a page and a half on
spanking, and discusses at length how corporal punishment should
not be administered: not out of anger or frustration, not
frequently, not to bruise or break the skin, not with a paddle,
belt or hairbrush, not after a child is 10, not if the parent was
abused as a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``A disciplinary spanking should be administered only in
response to an episode of willful defiance characterized by a
clear, appropriate parental directive that the child understands
and is capable of following; a direct challenge from a child,
especially with a disrespectful or hostile tone; or persistent and
blatant refusal to cooperate,'' the book reads.
</P>
<P>
   A spank should be one to three quick swats on the buttocks,
enough to catch the child's attention and break through the
defiance, the book reads.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are moments of intense conflict that can develop,
usually among young children, who are simply in a flat-out
go-ahead-make-my-day defiant mode and talk isn't working and time
out isn't working,'' Reisser said. ``Reasonable conversation has
come to a conclusion, and the child is just begging to see who is
going to win this conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyndale House is calling the book the most current and complete
guide to child care from birth to teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes them through that initial stage of coming to decision
points, and often times it gives them the information they need to
handle the situation,'' Stevens said. ``I think it's going to be a
resource that is going to be utilized for generations. It will be
the first gift I give my son and my daughter when they have their
first children.''
</P>
<P>
   The Physicians Resource Council began working on the book in
1994, and Tyndale House Publishers released it in October. The
hardcover book sells for $29.95.  &QL; 
Kelly Ettenborough can be reached at kelly.ettenborough(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
