<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4785 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-GUNS-PA     08-14 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-GUNS-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  PENNA. LEADS NATION IN CONCEALED GUNS
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 14 -- Pennsylvania has more residents walking
the streets with concealed handguns than any other state in the
nation, according to a study by the nation's leading gun control
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania's ``lock-and-load'' reputation is buttressed by a
system that allows just about anyone except hardened criminals and
the mentally ill to carry a concealed weapon, gun control advocates
say.
</P>
<P>
   There are currently 575,000 residents licensed to carry a
concealed gun in Pennsylvania, according to a report by Handgun
Control, Inc., an advocacy group headed by Sarah Brady, the wife of
former White House Press Secretary James Brady.
</P>
<P>
   Only New York, with 530,000 licenses for concealed weapons,
comes close to Pennsylvania. The third highest number of licenses
came from the state of Washington, with less than 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Texas, a state with almost twice as many people and an
historic image of gun-toting cowboys, can compare to Pennsylvania.
It has just 161,433 concealed weapons permits, more than 3.5 times
fewer than in the Keystone state.
</P>
<P>
   And Handgun Control's estimates may be a bit conservative.
Pennsylvania State Police say the number of residents licensed to
carry a concealed handgun is probably closer to 600,000 -- about 8
percent of the state's adult population.
</P>
<P>
   Cambria County Sheriff Bob Kolar said most of his applications
are submitted, and approved, by mail. In 1997, he issued 14,863
permits for Cambria residents to carry concealed handguns,
including 1,977 to women.
</P>
<P>
   Dauphin County, by contrast, with almost 100,000 more residents
than Cambria, gave out 6,000 permits for concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Residents can obtain a five-year permit to carry a handgun by
filling out a one-page application at their county sheriff's
office. The only way people can be denied a permit is if they have
been convicted of a felony or on drug charges, or if they have a
known alcohol problem or have been institutionalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no other hoops you have to go through,'' said Joe
Sudbay, spokesman for Handgun Control.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, concealed handgun permits are virtually
nonexistent, as that state only allows residents whose careers
require them to carry weapons. New Jersey has permitted just 4,300
residents to carry concealed handguns, with 95 percent of those
going to retired policemen or armored car guards.
</P>
<P>
   Sudbay said Pennsylvania should require some safety training for
people that carry weapons, as is done in Texas, where residents
must undergo between 10 and 15 hours of safety training before they
will be granted a license to carry a concealed handgun. That would
deter some people from getting the license, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Tom Ridge believes that the new instant background
check, which began July 1, ensures that felons and drug dealers do
not get handgun permits. And Handgun Control does credit Ridge with
adopting a strong background check, going even further than federal
guidelines in denying some gun licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty much a national leader,'' said Jerry Feazer,
Ridge's spokesman. ``If you should not have a gun in your hands,
you will not purchase one, at least not legally, in Pennsylvania.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kolar, the Cambria sheriff, said the issue isn't always
about keeping guns from criminals, especially in rural areas like
his where hunting and target practice are deep-rooted traditions.
He noted that there are an increasing number of women taking up
hunting, as well as men and children from families that haven't
been around guns their entire lives.
</P>
<P>
   Those with hunting licenses, which required safety training,
shouldn't have to go through safety classes, Kolar said. But the
others should, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some type of schooling should be available,'' he said. ``There
should be some type of guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   STATES WITH THE MOST RESIDENTS LICENSED TO CARRY CONCEALED GUNS:
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania: 575,000
</P>
<P>
   New York: 530,000
</P>
<P>
   Washington: 249,649
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts: 175,000
</P>
<P>
   Texas: 161,433
</P>
<P>
   Source: Handgun Control, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
