<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4798 &Cx1f; tad-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-BJT15-COX     08-14 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-BJT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release on the weekend of Saturday,
August 15, 1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-PLANES _ In a move to reverse the gradual aging of its
fleet, Delta will accelerate the retirement of its 131 Boeing 727
jets. The last of the three-engine, three-pilot workhorses will
leave by 2005, three years ahead of the previous schedule. They
will be replaced primarily by the 737-800, which is more efficient
and requires only two pilots. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   AIRFARES _ American Airlines is raising advance purchase fares 4
percent and Delta expected to follow suit. The move follows a
similar attempt last week that collapsed when Northwest didn't go
along. This time the increase exempts routes of direct competition
with Northwest. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GAPACIFIC-DEBT _ Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s debt levels are forcing
it to stop its share buyback program, which totalled $150 million
of stock in the first six months. The company also said it expects
to spend $60 million late this year and early next year trying to
fix its Year 2000 problems _ only $7 million of which has already
been spent. (Mitchell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CITRUS _ The first citrus forecast is released today. (Waresh,
Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   VOTE _ Final vote by Teamsters at Tropicana's plants in Fort
Pierce, Fla., and Bradenton, Fla. (Bhatt, Palm Beach Post). 12.
</P>
<P>
   IMAC _ With 150,000 advance orders and predictions that as many
and 400,000 will be sold by year-end, Apple Computer's iMac arrives
at stores Saturday amid great expecations. Computize, an Austin
Apple seller, wasn't sure late this week how many iMac's it would
get from Apple for the launch. So the business asked customers who
had ordered several iMacs to settle for a partial order for a few
days and let the store sell some to walk-in customers. Anticipation
of the one-piece computer and monitor, which has been billed as an
evolutionary step ahead of standard personal computers, has helped
push Apple's stock to its highest levels in years. (Mahoney, Austin
American-Statesman). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMAC-FIRST _ The first impressions of the iMac. How does it
feel, how does it respond? Does it work as a concept? As a
computing device? (Gallaga/Green, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TEST-DRIVE _ ATLANTA _ The German/American automaker BMW reaches
a milestone this month when the 100,000th of its ``brand within a
brand'' M-Series vehicles comes off the assembly line at its Greer,
S.C., plant. (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA _ When auto experts talk about
``alternative'' vehicles, they are usually referring to those
powered by natural gas or electricity. But you might also consider
a nontraditional vehicle as an alternative. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ ATLANTA _ Adhering to the manufacturer's
specification for fuel octane is not a condition limited to the
owners of ``high performance'' vehicles. It is just as important
for the rest of us to heed the octane requirements of the cars we
drive. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
