<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4828 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      08-14 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN SAYS RUBLE   WON'T BE DEVALUED; STOCKS REBOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Seeking to stave off fears of a financial collapse,
President Boris Yeltsin Friday said Moscow would not devalue its
embattled currency, as Russian stocks rebounded after a week-long
free-fall that had left them at two-year lows.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, who made several contradictory remarks, was firm on one
thing in his first public appearance in a month: His government
would continue to prop up the ruble, the stability of which is seen
as one of the few concrete economic achievements of six years of
painful reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no devaluation,'' Yeltsin told reporters in the
medieval city of Novgorod, where he visited while taking a break
from a fishing vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's promise appeared to bolster investor confidence in
Russian markets. The Russian Trading System index _ the Russian
stock market's main indicator _ closed up 13.67 percent to finish
at 115.00, and trading even had to be halted briefly because prices
were rising too sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Friday, the index had plunged 24 percent this week,
culminating in Thursday's 6.5 percent drop, which prompted one
television station to call the day ``Black Thursday.'' Yields on
short-term treasury bills also dropped but still closed at 161
percent, up from 85.31 a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agreed it was too early to dismiss fears that Russia
may be forced to default on debt payments or devalue the ruble _
moves the government, and Russia's Western allies, fear could have
serious social and political consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month after the International Monetary Fund and
other world lenders handed Russia a whopping $22.6 billion bail-out
package, some observers are now saying that the West will have to
pony up as much as $15 billion more to keep the Kremlin afloat.
</P>
<P>
   In a 40-minute phone call with the Russian leader, President
Clinton, who is heading to Moscow for a summit next month, Friday
urged Yeltsin to act quickly and decisively on the economy, Reuters
news service reported.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's greatest fear is the possibility that a ruble
collapse could set off a chain reaction of hyperinflation and
social protest that could sweep away the Yeltsin government and
replace it with extremists, a sobering possibility in a country
with thousands of nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been reeling for months from the effects of the Asian
crisis and the low prices for oil and gas, the country's most
lucrative hard currency exports. Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko
has promised tough measures to raise tax revenue and cut spending,
but he has been unable to win support in the opposition-dominated
parliament. Confidence in his ability to halt Russia's downward
spiral is waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IMF package ended up being double what anyone thought, and
that should have been overkill,'' said Marshall Goldman, economics
professor at Wellesley College and associate director of Harvard
University's Davis Center for Russian Studies. ``Now, it may very
well be that we have to come up with another loan.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, seeking to appear calm and in control, Friday gave a
vote of confidence to Kiriyenko, but gave the opposite impression
during impromptu remarks to reporters on other matters.
</P>
<P>
   First the president said there was no need to cut short his
vacation and return to Moscow. Then he abruptly announced that the
fishing was lousy and it was time to get back to work. Likewise,
Yeltsin at first dismissed the need to call an emergency session of
parliament. Then he signed a document asking the lower house, the
State Duma, to convene as soon as possible to debate Kiriyenko's
anti-crisis measures.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition groups that dominate the Duma said they would
agree to an emergency session as early as next week, but only if
the government explained what was going on in the economy first,
before the lower house reviews any laws.
</P>
<P>
   While the panic in Russian markets has yet to be felt among
ordinary citizens, most of whom keep what money they have outside
banks, there are ominous signs of crisis in the economy. Friday,
some foreign exchange booths shut down in central Moscow, blaming a
lack of hard currency, and some banks refused to allow depositors
to withdraw dollars from savings accounts. Many currency exchanges
remained open, but ruble dipped from 6.3 to the dollar Thursday to
between 6.75 to 7 to the dollar Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank on Wednesday placed some restrictions on the
ability of commercial banks to buy hard currency, and the banking
system is already suffering liquidity problems and a crisis of
confidence. Firms that import consumer goods have begun to complain
that foreign lenders have stopped accepting letters of credit from
Russian banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
