<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4829 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-14 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OFFENSIVE COORDINATOR KEEPS THE FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Paul Boudreau is respected by his offensive
linemen because he's direct and to the point. He told them in June
that if the Patriots had trouble running the ball, he would blame
them directly. He challanged them to adopt the attitude that paving
the way for the running game was their most important function.
</P>
<P>
   He was persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   Now Boudreau is trying to convince the naysayers that the new
approach is working. He urges skeptics to stop looking at the
dreadful exhibition statistics the running game has produced (2.8
yards per carry) through two games. He says that when and if the
Patriots decide who the main running back will be, there'll be a
big difference statistically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they're doing a pretty good job now ... we just don't
know who the runner is,'' said Boudreau. ``That's the big thing, in
my opinion. We've just got to know who the running back is. If it's
a committee _ Derrick Cullors, Sedrick Shaw, and the rook (Robert
Edwards) _ or if it's two guys ... whatever. We're trying to get
1,500 yards out of that spot. If we can, that's great. Last year we
had 1,160 yards out of Curtis (Martin) before he got hurt. He was
on pace for 1,500. He would have had a good year running the ball
had he not got hurt, and we wouldn't be having this discussion
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   When all is said and done, Edwards will be New England's
starting back. The staff is convinced of his ability. He will miss
Monday's game against the Cowboys in Mexico City because of a groin
problem, play a limited amount in Washington, then get turned loose
against Philadephia. At least that's the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stats in preseason games don't matter,'' said Boudreau. ``If
you win, that's the bottom line. You can keep track of all those
stats and they don't mean a thing. I see improvement in my guys. I
see our tight ends knocking people down. I see our back-side guards
and tackle chopping people _ working hard on the back side. I'm
really pleased with what they're doing. We don't see any wins for
it. In the third and fourth quarter, the guys in there aren't going
to be the (regular) guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the San Francisco game, we were backed up five
times inside the 15-yard line and made a couple of first downs in
tough running situations and we punched it out. Sedrick fumbled the
ball. If you can change field position and keep Steve Young off the
field, then that helps your situation. Right now there's just no
stat to prove what I'm saying.''
</P>
<P>
   That's for sure. As convincing as Boudreau sounds that his line
will meet the challenge he's issued, the facts offer no such
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Last week on fourth and 1, Harold Shaw was stuffed for a 2-yard
loss. The Vikings got great penetration in the middle of the line.
If ever the attitude of knocking people back has to exist, it's in
those situations. This time it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy about where we are,'' said coach Pete Carroll.
``We have not made the progress with moving the football the way we
would like with all of the guys we have on offense. I think you
will see in the next couple of weeks that we have made some
progress with our running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau is not advocating that the offensive coaches hurry and
decide on the starting running back, but soon the linemen need to
know who will be the primary back so they can adjust to a style.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to see what Robert can do,'' said Boudreau. ``He's
got two preseason games to show something. We could do what KC did,
and they used three guys. Derrick has shown some spurts like he did
last year. Derrick was a fine running back for us last year. He's
188 pounds, and so the question is, can he run the ball 27 times a
game? Probably not. But if we have a committee and he has 10
carries and he's our third-down guy, then that's a significant
start. He's the kind of guy that when he gets into the open field,
he can make a guy miss. That's why he's good on special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau said all the backs in camp suit the blocking style of
his line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system is the way it is,'' he said. ``We had to block a
little bit different with Curtis because we had to hang a little
bit more on the back side. These guys are in our style, and all
three of them can run within our style.''
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau said veterans Max Lane and Todd Rucci have had good
camps, while Dave Wohlabaugh has been solid. Bruce Armstrong's
stress fracture hasn't been a factor because the veteran All-Pro
has ``been wearing that cast and he doesn't feel he has it on. He
feels soreness in the mornings but then he doesn't notice it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau lauded Heath Irwin for the competition he has given
Rucci. He said the Class of '97 is also progressing. Ed Ellis, who
missed last week's game with strep throat, has been the most
impressive, while Scott Rehberg and Damon Denson (who recently
suffered an ankle injury) have stepped up their play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they have to play right away? No,'' said Boudreau. ``If we
have anything happen up front, I'm not going to worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   While being ordered to improve their run-blocking, the linemen
also have had to adapt to a new system which emphasizes the
three-step drop for the quarterback, as opposed to the five- and
seven-step drops of yesteryear. The blocking is much different,
according to Boudreau, because the guards and centers are
accustomed to dropping back more, and if they do that with a
three-step drop, they'll fall on Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the average fan, who can't break down film and watch
blocking schemes, can't see much progress with the run-blocking. To
hear Boudreau tell it, there's nothing to worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   But the masses need to see a lot more before they're convinced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
