<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STAKES-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT'S REPUTATION, LEGACY AT STAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For Sunday release, Aug. 16) 
 
By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton places his legacy and reputation
_ and perhaps his job itself _ at stake Monday when he tells a
grand jury about his relationship with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors from independent counsel Kenneth Starr's office will
ask the president if he had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky
and asked her to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   The president has publicly denied a sexual relationship with the
25-year-old Californian. She reportedly has told the grand jury a
different story, though she maintains Clinton did not pressure her
to lie.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, it must be an agonizing moment as he faces
questions that are humiliating for him, embarrassing for his wife
and daughter, and damaging to his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Congress could decide to pursue impeachment charges to remove
him from office, a move that would plunge the nation into a
spectacle that could last for months.
</P>
<P>
   And, even if he keeps his job, the president's moral authority
as the nation's leader could be severely undermined, experts
contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end game here is survival,'' said Terry Madonna, a
pollster with Millersville University in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Wittmann, director of congressional relations at the
conservative Heritage Foundation, said, ``Clearly what's most at
stake is his credibility, and credibility is the coin of the realm
in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst scenario for the president would be impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, Starr is expected to send a report to Congress
about his findings in the case. Public hearings with direct
accusations on live television could come at some point the future.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress repeatedly have said there is little
inclination to pursue impeachment unless the president commits
perjury before the grand jury, which will watch the interrogation
by closed-circuit television. Still, members could give a full
airing of Starr's findings just as the campaign season gets under
way.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment seems most unlikely because few GOP leaders want to
hand the presidency over to Vice President Al Gore, the Democrat to
beat in 2000, for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Constitution, a president can be impeached for ``high
crimes and misdemeanors,'' but it does not define those terms. If
the House votes for articles of impeachment, the Senate conducts a
trial on whether to remove the president from office.
</P>
<P>
   Should Starr accuse Clinton of perjury before the grand jury,
the House could be forced to pursue a formal impeachment hearing.
However, if the issue remains whether Clinton lied in a civil
deposition about his sex life, many members speculate there will be
little inclination to seek impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   No president has ever been removed from office by the
impeachment process. President Nixon resigned in 1974 as the House
prepared articles of impeachment. President Andrew Johnson was
impeached by the House in 1868, but the Senate fell one vote shy of
the two-thirds total necessary to remove him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what everybody knows now, I do not believe it is likely
that Congress would pursue impeachment,'' said Larry Gerston, a
political science professor at San Jose State University.
</P>
<P>
   Gerston cites Clinton's high standing with the public based on
the healthy economy, questions over the definition of an
impeachable offense and whether perjury would meet that definition;
the use and abuse of the independent counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the consequences remain serious even if Congress takes no
action.
</P>
<P>
   A damaged Democratic president would serve the political
purposes of Republicans now and when they try to reclaim the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is operating at half-speed. In a way,
Republicans have the president where they want him. He is largely
dysfunctional, particularly on domestic matters. They've got a
weakened president, which will allow them to do more than they
might have done otherwise while they keep him in office,'' Gerston
said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, an overwhelming majority of the public believes
Clinton lied when he denied a relationship with Lewinsky. However,
polls indicate that an overwhelming majority also believe Clinton
should not be impeached. And his job approval rating exceeds 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But presidential power also resides in the moral authority of
the person holding the office, the ability to rally public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``His moral capital has been diminished and that is critical to
any president's leverage with both the public and Capitol Hill,''
Wittmann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically what's at stake is trying to save any capacity to
be effective over the next two years. So that stake is very high,''
said Robert Holsworth, a political science professor at Virginia
Commonwealth University.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he is hoping is the testimony and the next few months
will enable him to begin with a fresh start. He is the king of
fresh starts, but whether he'll really get that is an open
question,'' Holsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton dubbed himself ``the comeback kid'' in 1992 when
he first sought the presidency and was declared politically dead
numerous times. He fended off allegations throughout the 1992
campaign that he dodged the draft for the Vietnam War and had an
affair with Gennifer Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   His resilience repeatedly has defied conventional wisdom. Still,
the current crisis may be more than his reputation can take, even
if he beats Starr in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be impossible for him to be associated
with a dignified presidency,'' said Earl Black, a political science
professor at Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   But Gerston said it's too early to say how Clinton's legacy will
develop. It could be, he suggested, that ``the whole issue of
Monica Lewinsky will be looked upon with a wince'' while history
reflects more brightly on Clinton's other accomplishments. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
