<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON FACTORY WORKERS PROTEST JOB CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDOVER, Mass. _ More than 500 &UR;  &LR; employees demonstrated outside a
Raytheon Co. defense manufacturing plant here Friday after learning
that 261 factory jobs would be cut from the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; About 100 of the cuts are expected to come from the Andover
plant, a union official said.
</P>
<P>
   The protest by members of Local 1505 of the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers came in the midst of bargaining
over a new labor agreement with Raytheon. The current &UR;  &LR; three-year
contract expires Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Predawn demonstrations also were held at Raytheon plants in
Quincy and Waltham Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Raytheon announced a merger with Hughes, it was quoted as
saying there would be no layoff of manufacturing jobs,'' said David
Whalen, an assistant business manager for Local 1505 in Andover.
``But here we are one year later, and more than 200 jobs are going
to be eliminated. This is a slap in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon spokeswoman Toni Simonetti said the decision to cut
factory jobs was ``strictly market related,'' and had nothing to do
with the company's $9.5 billion buyout last year of Hughes Aircraft
Co., the defense arm of Hughes Electronics Corp., a subsidiary of
General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reduction of 261 hourly jobs is due solely to a reduction
in the volume of work on certain defense programs such as the
Patriot Missile systems and the Hawk Missile systems,'' said
Simonetti.
</P>
<P>
   Simonetti declined to discuss contract negotiations. ``We do
have a (strike) contingency ... but we also feel that we are having
a productive dialogue with the union,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Whalen said talks began at the end of June and are expected to
continue through August. Key union issuesare job security and pay,
he said. ``In 1995, we agreed to some concessions, including a cut
in the pay &UR;  &LR; scale,'' said Whalen. ``But now we have people who were
making $15 (an hour), got laid off and then were recalled at $8.31
per hour. We now have a two-tier wage structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon, one of Massachusetts' biggest employers, has
facilities in 10 communities and 15,400 employees statewide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
