u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOP100-NOVELS-550&AMP;ADD     08-14 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOP100-NOVELS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100-BEST LIST ENCORE, WITH NEW RULES AND JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Faced with widespread criticism of the list it
released last month of the 100 best English-language novels
published in this century _ most piercingly in written comments by
two of the judges who helped compile it _ the Modern Library says
it will significantly overhaul the way it picks its choice of the
century's hundred best English-language nonfiction books later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   In separate articles published this week, historian Arthur
Schlesinger Jr. and novelist William Styron, who were both members
of the 10-judge panel that drew up the list, distanced themselves
from the final outcome as well as from the methods by which the
books were chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the opinion pages of The Wall Street Journal,
Schlesinger said most panel members were ``astonished by at least
the last two of the top five choices.'' These were Vladimir
Nabokov's ``Lolita'' and Aldous Huxley's ``Brave New World,'' which
followed James Joyce's ``Ulysses,'' F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``Great
Gatsby'' and another of Joyce's works, ``Portrait of the Artist as
a Young Man.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that while the panel had been asked to rate these
top five novels in order of merit because they had appeared on
nearly every judge's list, the members did not rank by number the
other books they nominated as being among the hundred best.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Modern Library editors ranked them according to the
number of times they appeared on individual judges' lists. When two
or more novels tied with the same number of votes, the editors,
rather than the judges, decided what order they should be placed
in, a fact first reported in The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Schlesinger also noted that Arthur Koestler's ``Darkness at
Noon,'' which occupied eighth place, had no business being on the
list at all since it was originally written in German.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he came down in favor of the Modern Library's
attempt to choose the 100 greatest novels in general terms, saying
``anything that provokes people to read novels and debate their
merits is a cultural victory.'' Writing in the current issue of The
New Yorker, Styron said he ``cheerfully'' assented to the view that
the Modern Library's final list was ``weird'' and that it displayed
a ``generally oppressive stodginess.''
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledged that the panel of judges who made the
selection was ``entirely white, predominately male and somewhat
doddering.'' Schlesinger had calculated their average age at 69.
</P>
<P>
   Modern Library officials said they would change the process in
producing the planned list of the century's 100 best nonfiction
books so that the selection panel would be more diverse and the
voting system more rigorous.
</P>
<P>
   Like Schlesinger, Styron said that many books placed high on the
list owed their positions not to merit, but to the fact that eight
or nine judges thought they should appear ``somewhere among the
anointed hundred.''
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion, a luncheon meeting of the panel with ``good wine
that allowed for lively disputation'' would have produced a more
satisfactory result, eliminating such ``toothless pretenders'' as
Booth Tarkington's ``Magnificent Ambersons'' and Max Beerbohm's
``Zuleika Dobson.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In recent interviews several other members of the judges' panel
expressed reservations about the final Modern Library list.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the selection system employed ``not particularly
scientific,'' Ian Jackman, the Modern Library's managing director,
said he would discard the current tie-breaking system, which had
been used, he said, because it was not practical to refer every
dead-heat back to the full panel of judges. Instead, the library
will use a ranking system based on ``weighted voting.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was also committed to adding new judges to the panel,
which is made up of members of the editorial board of Modern
Library, to lower the average age and make it more representative
of present-day society.
</P>
<P>
   British novelist A.S. Byatt is the only woman and non-American
so far on the panel, which has no members from racial or ethnic
minorities. Other members are Gore Vidal; Daniel Boorstin, a former
librarian of the Library of Congress; historian Shelby Foote;
Vartan Gregorian, president of Carnegie Corp.; Edmund Morris, a
historian; and John Richardson, the Picasso biographer.
</P>
</TEXT>
