<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Commentary: Clinton rappers rock
</P>
<P>
   By Rowland Nethaway
</P>
<P>
   c: 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``I have often thought that if there had been a
good rap group around in those days, I might have chosen a career
in music instead of politics,'' mused Richard Nixon in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was off for Nixon, but it might be dead on for Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Hillary as the ``Two Fer One Rappers.'' They would
rock. MTV. Top of the charts. Huge.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton already has Hollywood friends who give him scripts and
acting lessons so he can appear sincere on television.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon was ahead of Clinton on this score as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sincerity is the quality that comes through on television,''
he told the Washington Star in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon understood it. Clinton can do it.
</P>
<P>
   The above quotes come from a new book, The Experts Speak, which
is an expanded an updated edition of a 1984 book by the same name.
The authors are Christopher Cerf, a former contributing editor to
the National Lampoon and co-editor of The Politically Correct
Dictionary and Handbook and co-author Victor Navasky, publisher and
editorial director of The Nation.
</P>
<P>
   The book is a collection of quotes from experts _ pundits,
authorities, talking heads, etc. _ who willingly predict,
pontificate and speculate but turn out to be perfectly wrong. Some
of the quotes are instructive compared to current events. Others
</P>
<P>
   are simply entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1996 Henry Aldridge, a North Carolina state
representative, gave this explanation why there was no need for his
state to fund abortions for rape victims. ``People who are raped _
who are truly raped _ the juices don't flow, the body functions
don't work, and they don't get pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Other AIDS experts quoted in the book included movie-maker Spike
Lee and Montana Lt. Gov. Dennis Rehberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``AIDS is a government-engineered disease,'' Lee was quoted in
1992. ``The problem with AIDS is: you got it, you die. So why are
we spending money on this issue?'' said Rehberg in 1994 when
arguing for reduced state expenditures for hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   With tobacco lawsuits and settlements in the news, consider the
1962 quote from Sir Charles Ellis, senior scientist for British
American Tobacco Company. ``It is my conviction that nicotine is a
very remarkable, beneficent drug that both helps the body to resist
external stress and also can as a result show a pronounced
tranquilizing effect....''
</P>
<P>
   Guess which expert made the following quote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must expect the Soviet system to survive in its present
brutish form for a very long time. There will be Soviet labor camps
and Soviet torture chambers well into our great-grandchildren's
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Give up? It was U.S. Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., five years
before the Soviet collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The book contains quotes from politicians and political experts
who predicted Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton's 1992 presidential
candidacy over following reports that he committed adultery and
lied about dodging the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Clinton is) a dead stone loser,'' said Democratic pollster
Tubby Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   More quotes predict Clinton's political demise during a
second-term presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton will lose to any Republican nominee who doesn't
drool on the stage,'' said an Oct. 30, 1995 Wall Street Journal
editorial.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another Nixon-Clinton parallel universe quote: ``If the
press continues its zealous overkill on this affair, it is not
likely to destroy either President Nixon or the Nixon
Administration but it will gravely injure something more important
_ the faith of the people in . ... (the) freedom of the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Change the date and the name, and this quote from an April 25,
1973 editorial in the Burlington, Vt. Free Press could appear in a
newspaper today.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: RNeth(AT)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
