<HEADLINE>
AUTO INSURERS SEEK 15.5 PERCENT RATE INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As expected, the state's auto industry Friday formally
asked state regulators for a 15.5 percent rate increase for next
year, saying the steep hike is needed to make up for lost revenue
from four years of rate reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Johnston, spokesman for the Automobile Insurers Bureau of
Massachusetts, said the rate hike also is needed to cover the
rising cost of repairing cars as people buy more expensive
vehicles. He said the cost of the average repair in 1993 was
$1,283, and now the cost is $1,483.
</P>
<P>
   State insurance regulators last year approved an average 4
percent cut in rates, the fourth consecutive year Massachusetts
drivers have received cuts in auto insurance rates. Last August,
the auto industry had initially sought about a 7 percent hike,
Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said the industry has faced a revenue shortfall in the
last several years, which must be reversed. ``Clearly, a reasonable
rate increase is necessary to preserve a stable market in
Massachusetts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday's official filing with state regulators, some
members of the auto industry earlier this week had begun talking
about a proposed 15.5 percent rate hike. Acting Governor Paul
Cellucci and Attorney General Scott Harshbarger said Thursday they
are against such a sizeable increase.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance commissioner will set rates in December, after
hearing from the industry, Harshbarger, and the State Rating
Bureau, an agency in the Division of Insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
