<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AVENGERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE AVENGERS' IS A VALIANT TRY, BUT IN THE END IS PRETTY AWFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As everyone knows by now, the big-screen version of the
cult-favorite, '60s British TV series, ``The Avengers,'' has become
a pre-release media event for the worst possible reason. Its
studio, Warner Bros., has all but abandoned it.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the blockbuster-wannabe has secsured a place in the
movie record books for being the only film of its budget (more than
$50 million, before promotion costs) so far in the '90s to not have
a premiere, a junket, a press screening or opening-day star
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with a certain ghoulish fascination that critics and
audiences queued yesterday afternoon for a first look at this
pariah. And the question that every reviewer has to answer today
is: just how bad can this thing possibly be?
</P>
<P>
   Well, to put it in the perspective of the summer, let's say that
it's not as insipid as ``BASEketball,'' as trashy as ``Mafia!,'' as
thoroughly boring as ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' or as
ponderously overblown as ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers. Directed by Jeremiah Chechik. Written by Don
Macpherson. Cast: Ralph Fiennes, Uma Thurman, Sean Connery. Warner
Bros. Meridian 16, Guild 45th, Oak Tree, Bella Bottega, Crossroads,
Issaquah 9, Kirkland Parkplace, Woodinville 12, Everett 9, Grand
Cinemas Alderwood, Mountlake 9, Cinema 17, East Valley, Gateway
Center, Kent 6, Lewis and Clark, Valley Drive-in. 91 minutes. Rated
PG-13 for violence and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   It's also hard to get too mad at it, because in many respects,
it's a valiant try. Producer Jerry Weintraub has obviously resisted
the studio pressure to junk up the proceedings with today's
standards of bad-taste, and his film stays resolute to the series'
stiff-upper-lip, deadpan silliness.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still a dead movie from fade-in to fade-out. While
there's nothing glaringly or embarrassingly awful about it (except
for maybe the non-script), it simply doesn't engage us _ even for a
minute. Its efforts to make the TV series' unique spirit come alive
in a new and larger medium somehow dismally fail.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the problem, as always in a flop of this
magnitude, is in the casting. Ralph Fiennes, playing a considerably
younger version of the hero, Jonathan Steed, is pleasant but so
lackluster that he often seems to disappear. Uma Thurman as the
heroine, Mrs. Peel, is better, but her flat delivery and vulnerable
manner are all wrong for the character.
</P>
<P>
   The repartee that was so droll and witty and irresistible from
the mouths of the series' Patrick Macnee and Diana Rigg here seems
mannered and annoying. The stars also have little in the way of
chemistry _ so that when they fall into a passionate kiss
(something that would never happen in the series), you actually
find yourself wanting to look away.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Don Macpherson's script _ something about a
master villain (Sean Connery) trying to manipulate the world's
weather for profit _ is such a travesty of basic story-telling that
it's virtually impossible to follow. You can never quite figure out
any character's motivation in any particular scene.
</P>
<P>
   And Jeremiah Chechik (``Benny and Joon,'' ``Diabolique'') is
never director enough to make the film's style triumph over its
lack of substance _ which is exactly what the TV series did so
well. Its scripts were every bit as silly and gleefully
preposterous, but somehow it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Here, it seems to matter.
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, however, it may well be that ``The
Avengers'' belongs to its own unique time and place, and to its own
distinctive stars. It may also be that it belongs on the small
screen _ because blown way up and extended to 91 minutes, even in a
relatively faithful adaptation, it's become something grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers. Directed by Jeremiah Chechik. Written by Don
Macpherson. Cast: Ralph Fiennes, Uma Thurman, Sean Connery. Warner
Bros. 91 minutes. Rated PG-13 for violence and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
