<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-ECON-530&AMP;ADD     08-14 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-ECON-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG GOVERNMENT INTERVENES TO STRENGTHEN MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ After days of speculative attacks on Hong Kong's
currency, the government confirmed Friday that it had intervened to
shore up the stock and futures markets.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Tsang, the financial secretary of Hong Kong, said the
government took the rare step of dipping into its reserves to buy
shares and futures contracts because it thought currency traders
were improperly manipulating the territory's financial markets to
make ``speedy profits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not tolerate attempts by speculators to manipulate our
interest rates,'' a grim-faced Tsang said as he stood next to the
chairman of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority, Joseph Yam, at a news
conference here.
</P>
<P>
   The monetary authority waded into the market to buy Hong Kong
dollars late last week and earlier this week. But the government
refused to characterize those moves as an intervention, saying
instead that the government was merely raising local currency to
finance a temporary budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's action, which was announced after the stock market
closed, is far more aggressive than merely buying dollars. Rumors
of the intervention galvanized the market, which had been battered
by heavy losses all week. The Hang Seng index rebounded 564.27
points, or 8.5 percent, to 7,224.69 _ its ninth-biggest point gain
in history. The index had dropped about 16 percent since the end of
July.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the government's purchases, rumors surfaced
Friday that local companies with ties to the government were also
buying shares to further prop up the Hang Seng.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's action underscores that, after several weeks in
which the foundering Japanese yen commanded the attention of Asia's
markets, currency trading is turning into a blood sport elsewhere
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Using remarkably blunt language, Tsang accused traders of
employing ``a whole host of improper measures'' to undermine the
Hong Kong dollar. He said they had spread ``vicious rumors'' that
Hong Kong was going to break its exchange rate, which is linked to
the U.S. dollar; that China was about to devalue its currency, the
yuan; and that Hong Kong's banks were unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Tsang also opened the door to future intervention, though he
cautioned that it would only occur in ``exceptional
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the government's move rescued the Hang Seng from one of
its most dismal weeks in recent memory, several analysts said the
underlying reasons for Hong Kong's economic woes remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weak yen is clearly the fundamental driver, and it is
growing weaker by the day because of domestic developments,'' said
Jan Lee, the chief economist at the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking
Corp. here. ``The Japanese authorities lack the political will to
deliver the necessary changes.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Japanese yen lost a bit of ground, trading at
146.35 yen to the dollar on Friday, down from 145.16 yen on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Nikkei index turned in a similarly lackluster
performance, declining 258.09 points, or 1.7 percent, to 15,123.93.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts also said they were troubled by the government's
bellicose tone, which they said could erode the confidence of
investors in Hong Kong.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They noted that inflammatory remarks about currency traders by
Malaysia's prime minister, Mahatir Mohamed, had alarmed many
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is legitimate to wage war against speculators in a
calculated manner,'' said Miron Mushkat, a strategist at Indocam
Asia here. ``But Hong Kong is turning this into something of a
jihad against the speculators.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the issue of tough talk, some analysts said they feared
that Hong Kong might be unable to maintain its commitment to a
linked exchange rate when the Japanese yen is spiraling downward
and virtually all of its neighbors have already deeply devalued
their currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hong Kong's monetary regime, known as a currency board,
the Hong Kong dollar is pegged to the U.S. dollar at a ratio of 7.8
to 1. When traders sell the currency in large volumes, the board
can act to raise interbank interest rates, forcing down asset
prices and eventually making the Hong Kong dollar attractive to
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with such a system is that the government must be
prepared to tolerate painful spikes in interest rates, which can
strangle credit and hobble economic growth. Hong Kong is already
limping through its worst downturn since World War II, with an
unemployment rate of 4.5 percent and a 2.8 percent contraction in
its gross domestic product in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politicians are absolutely committed to the exchange rate,
but at what cost?'' Lee asked. ``At the cost of a very significant
deflation in Hong Kong _ far more than what I believe people are
willing to tolerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous efforts to defend the Hong Kong dollar have resulted in
sharp drops in property prices and on the stock exchange, which is
largely driven by real estate industry values. By last Wednesday,
after several days of intense selling of the Hong Kong dollar, the
Hang Seng index was trading at a five-year low.
</P>
<P>
   Tsang said Friday that the attacks on the Hong Kong dollar were
designed to force a chain reaction of soaring interest rates and
swooning stock prices. He said the same hedge funds that speculated
against the dollar accumulated short positions in the shares of
Hong Kong companies. When those stocks plunged, he said, the hedge
funds stood to profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is vulnerable to manipulation and has recently
showed signs of becoming one of the main reasons of speculators
attacking the Hong Kong dollar,'' Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
   By engineering a rally in share prices, the government hopes to
inflict heavy losses on the hedge funds _ a punishment it thinks
will dissuade them from speculating on the currency in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts said Hong Kong would remain vulnerable to
speculative attacks as long as its currency traded higher than
those of its neighbors. Moreover, the gap between Hong Kong and
other Asian countries seems likely to widen rather than narrow. The
Japanese yen continues to weaken, and despite China's
protestations, many analysts think it will eventually devalue the
yuan.
</P>
<P>
   A Hong Kong brokerage firm released a report on Thursday
predicting that China would devalue the currency at the end of the
year. The firm, Indosuez W.I. Carr Securities, said Beijing would
feel compelled to take such action in order to keep its economic
reform program on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were just a temporary crisis, you could just plug the
gap for a year or so and get back to the reform process later,''
said Michael Taylor, an economist at Indosuez W.I. Carr Securities.
``But it isn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
