<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-WINERIES-ART-2TA     08-14 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-WINERIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL WINERIES PROLIFERATE OUTSIDE CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic showing top wine-producing states is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALISADE, Colo. _ Parker and Mary Carlson have an unpretentious
attitude about making and marketing their wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the swirl, sniff and spit crowd,'' Carlson said.
``Our wines are just meant to be enjoyed. They're light and fruity,
easy drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Their Carlson Vineyards labels have playful names like Prairie
Dog Blush, Tyrannosaurus Red and Gewurzasaurus. And they are made
from Colorado grapes. Hundreds of acres of cabernet, merlot,
chardonnay and gewurzstraminer are thriving on the western slopes
of the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   It is a process being repeated in many states without long
winemaking traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The number of U.S. wineries doubled to 1,817 between 1980 and
1995, the last year for which data are available, according to the
American Vintners Association in Washington. More than half of the
new wineries are outside California. Except for Alaska, North
Dakota and Wyoming, every state in the nation has at least one
winery.
</P>
<P>
   The trade association said New York, Oregon, Washington and
Virginia had a combined total of 379 wineries, up from 138 in 1980.
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Missouri, Texas, Michigan, New Jersey, Indiana
and New Mexico each had 20 or more.
</P>
<P>
   But many of those wineries operate on a fine line between a
pastime and a small business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wine industry outside of California, Washington, Oregon
and New York tends to be a very small cottage industry, almost a
home industry, one step beyond a hobby,'' said Louis Perdue, who
publishes an Internet newsletter called Wine Investment News. ``The
problem is that they don't make a great deal of wine, and if you
don't make a great deal of wine, it's hard to make a great deal of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Vic Motto, a partner in Motto, Kryla &AMP; Fisher of St. Helena,
Calif., which provides consultants and accountants for the wine
industry, says vineyards and wineries are capital intensive. A
winery that grows its own fruit typically has assets of $4 to $5
for each dollar of annual sales, Motto said, compared with $1 or
less in assets per dollar of sales for a manufacturing company.
</P>
<P>
   But many small vintners are motivated primarily by a love of
wine and a desire to combine agriculture with an art that has
existed for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain romance to it,'' Motto said. ``You're
growing some fruit that you're going to convert into a product that
has a certain amount of mystique to it and charm.''
</P>
<P>
   The winery operations in most states are still dwarfed by
California's labels. Eric Sims, an economist with Motto, Kryla,
estimated that California wines accounted for 90 percent to 95
percent of the $16 billion in sales of U.S.-made wines in 1997.
Most of the rest came from New York and Washington, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Simon Siegl, president of the American Vintners Association,
said advances in scientific knowledge have helped spread commercial
vineyards into new regions. New tools and techniques include more
effective fungicide applications, better water management and
improved ways of dealing with severe cold weather, which is not a
problem in California's grape-growing regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In years past, the growers just didn't have the tools to win
out against nature,'' Siegl said. ``As more and more research
delivers better tools to the winemaker, it's more feasible for wine
to be produced in some of these regions.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's tiny emerging wine industry is an example of how
winemaking is proliferating throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At 4,700 to 6,400 feet above sea level, the Colorado vineyards
are among the highest in the world, but the area's radiant summer
days and cool nights are great for grapes, and improved vineyard
management techniques are helping to solve problems of long, cold
winters.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the state had two commercial wineries. Now there are
21, according to the Colorado Wine Industry Development Board. Five
new Colorado wineries received licenses in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson Vineyards, south of Palisade in the Grand Valley of the
Colorado River, is typical of the recent trends.
</P>
<P>
   The winery has three acres of its own vineyard and buys ``seven
acres' worth'' of grapes from other growers in the area, to make
about 15,000 gallons of wine a year. Carlson, 52, said he expected
to sell about $350,000 worth of wine this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Carlsons started their winery in 1988. ``We were home
winemakers for about 10 or 15 years before that, so it's just a
hobby that got out of control,'' Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first four years, Carlson also continued working at his
supervisory job at a Coors ceramics plant in nearby Grand Junction.
He has taken short winemaking courses at the University of
California at Davis, the American mecca of viniculture education,
and some of his wines _ including the 1995 Gewurzasaurus _ have won
medals in national competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Like other vintners interviewed in the area, Carlson was
reluctant to talk about profits. He said that the winery produces a
taxable income, ``but it's all going back into the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas and Susan Phillips have a cabinet full of medals in the
tasting room of their Plum Creek Winery beside U.S. 6 in Palisade.
The prize they are proudest of is a gold medal from the 1992 San
Francisco Fair for their 1990 Grand Mesa, a blend of merlot and
cabernet franc.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Phillips said people at the California competition, whose
knowledge of Colorado's fledgling wineries was sketchy at best,
were dumbfounded. ```Who are these guys?' _ that's what they were
saying about us,'' Mrs. Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillipses are both lawyers in Denver, three hours over the
Rockies from Palisade. But the couple spends more than 40 extended
weekends a year working at their winery and 55 acres of vineyards,
helped by a dozen full-time employees and as many seasonal workers.
</P>
<P>
   They opened the winery in 1984 and Phillips estimated that they
had invested ``considerably more than $2 million'' in the venture,
first breaking even after seven years.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he predicted, total sales of grapes and wine will be
$800,000 to $900,000, but he declined to discuss profits or losses
for the privately held company.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Wine Industry Development Board expects 1998 sales
of 79,000 gallons for all microvintners in the state which amounts
to less than 1 percent of the Colorado retail wine market,
according to John Lowey, the group's executive director. The
board's long-term goal is for Colorado wines to win 10 percent of
the state's 9-million-gallon market.
</P>
<P>
   Total sales of all wine in the United States increased from 449
million gallons in 1993 to 508 million gallons in 1996, according
to the American Vintners Association.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Siegl, the president of the association, said the improving
quality of wines made throughout the country had contributed to the
growth of wineries by giving consumers more confidence in what they
buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting better and better wine every time they turn
around,'' Siegl said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in western Colorado, viniculturists say, a dry
climate helps prevent vine disease; intense summer sunlight gives
grapes good color and flavor, and low nighttime temperatures
promote acid retention, which is regarded as a key to premium
winemaking. But potential problems in Colorado include severe
winter cold, which can damage vines, and late spring frosts, which
can abort the budding process.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado wine board, which is financed with a small share of
state taxes on wine, pays for a research station and experimental
vineyard operated near Palisade by Colorado State University.
Growers and winemakers say Richard Hamman Jr., a viniculturist who
operates the research station, has helped improve the area's grape
crops and wines.
</P>
<P>
   Hamman said that many local wines were still mediocre. But he
said the industry had the potential to expand in western Colorado,
with up to 3,500 acres suitable for vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not ever going to be a Napa in terms of size,'' he said.
``But the quality _ we can make just as good a grape here as they
can in California, for most varieties.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamman has experimented with different varieties of grapevines
to find those that adapt well to the Colorado climate, and many do.
But no variety resisted a cold wave in February 1989 that dropped
temperatures to 23 degrees below zero and damaged most vine tissue
above ground level. Colorado produced almost no grapes that year.
</P>
<P>
   In seminars for growers on how to reduce winter damage, he
teaches such techniques as reducing water to vines in the late
summer to hasten their winter acclimation process and delaying
pruning until late in the winter to leave more dormant buds in case
some are damaged by winter freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Many growers have installed electric wind machines, huge fans
that dissipate low layers of frosty air. And Hamman is also working
on an experimental spray of water, sugar and an acid taken from
ground seaweed that can postpone the time when buds pop out, a
precaution against late spring frosts.
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Padte Turley operate Colorado's oldest and largest
winery. The Turleys bought a fruit farm near Palisade in 1977 and
converted orchards to vineyards in 1985. They sold grapes to
Colorado Mountain vineyard, a pioneering Colorado winery that was
operating in the red. In 1989, they bought the winery from its
absentee owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I bought it is they weren't making any money, so
they couldn't buy my grapes any more,'' Turley said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the grape-crop busts in 1989 and 1991, the Turleys
managed to keep the winery alive by importing grapes from
California. It is now called Colorado Cellars Ltd. and its sales
have been growing at about 10 percent a year, reaching $630,000 in
1997. The winery makes about 25,000 gallons a year, although Turley
declined to discuss the company's earnings in detail.
</P>
<P>
   One problem Colorado wineries have struggled with is getting
Denver-based distributors interested in their wines. Turley, who
worked as a distributor before buying the winery, tackled the
problem by hiring a sales manager and buying a van to deliver his
wine throughout Colorado. He says Colorado Cellars wines are sold
at about 3,500 restaurants and liquor stores, more than half of the
licensed outlets in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're selling everything we make,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
