<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OWES U.S. THE UNVARNISHED VERSION ABOUT LEWINSKY  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16)  
 (THIS EDITORIAL WILL APPEAR IN SUNDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - President Clinton faces a daunting challenge Monday
before a federal grand jury, and the future of his embattled
administration _ not to mention his desperately sought historical
legacy _ hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after promising the American people ``more rather
than less, sooner rather than later'' about the Monica Lewinsky
affair, we hear he may try to square his testimony with the complex
web of evasions, diversions, delays and apparent lies that he and
his minions have spun in a frantic effort to postpone this day of
reckoning into a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advisers creating strategy based on definition of act,'' read
Friday's disturbing headline.
</P>
<P>
   We suggest he try something else _ the unadorned truth, without
calculated spin, memory lapses or grammatical subterfuge. It's
easier and despite its many risks on the heels of so much dizzying
rhetorical footwork, it's also safer.
</P>
<P>
   And when he's done, he should go one step further and tell the
whole unvarnished story to the overpromised American people.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, of course, he has no obligation to do the latter (or
even the former, if he's gutsy enough to assume the role of a
criminal and invoke the Fifth Amendment). But a president is more
than a citizen entitled to presumptions of privacy and certain
legal safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   He is a public servant who surrendered most of his privacy claim
two decades ago. He now owes the nation an explanation that will
restore a measure of credibility to the office he has immeasurably
cheapened and bring an end to this tawdry affair staining the
nation's honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only sex,'' his defenders argue. ``If he lied, it doesn't
matter because it's none of our business.'' But they are wrong. It
does matter. Presidential lies can't be neatly sorted. Official
credibility is not divisible.
</P>
<P>
   As Thomas Friedman recently noted in the ``New York Times,'' in
a world where Russia has 20,000 nuclear warheads and an
impoverished arms industry eager for business, where the Asian
economy is spiraling downward, where Kosovo and Albania are
``imploding,'' where Saddam Hussein blocks U.N. weapons inspectors
and Iran is testing a long-range missile, American credibility
matters deeply. And the president, for better or worse, owns the
lone world superpower's only singular voice.
</P>
<P>
   To this task, only the truth, the whole truth, will suffice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't inhale'' will not work, nor will the oft-employed
``not that I recall'' of his last testimony under oath in January.
Forget ``mistakes were made.'' And if he tries, as suggested by
Friday's news accounts, to explain that oral sex is not the
``sexual relations'' he so firmly denied, he will become a global
laughingstock and his presidency will effectively end, no matter
how Kenneth Starr's report later plays out in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Will Americans forgive him the truth? We don't know. If it turns
out he has been less than truthful, there will be a political price
to be paid _ possibly even impeachment, although Congress now seems
to have little stomach for it. But better he pay it than the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive? Maybe. But not forget. The only worse outcome from
Monday's testimony than more of this destructive dance of deception
would be that we learn nothing from it. Bill Clinton can help the
nation learn by first accepting his own culpability. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
