<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S MARKETS RALLY AS WESTERN POWERS DISCUSS RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's financial markets rallied Friday after the
Kremlin and the major Western powers indicated that they were
working on still further plans to end the nation's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But with banks still shaky and the memory of Thursday's panic
fresh in their minds, brokers and analysts said they were not so
much optimistic about a solution as relieved that Friday's markets
had not completed the collapse that began the day before.
</P>
<P>
   After losing almost 6.5 percent of their value Thursday, Russian
blue-chip stocks regained about 4 percent Friday. Nine-month
government bonds were yielding about 150 percent, well under the
200-percent-plus yields of Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin, breaking his summer vacation Friday to
inspect a meat-processing factory in the ancient city of Novgorod,
insisted there would be no devaluation of the ruble _ ``that's firm
and definite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That would signify that there was a disaster and that
everything was collapsing,'' he added. ``On the contrary,
everything is going as it should.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin said Yeltsin had a lengthy telephone conversation
with President Clinton on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   (In Washington, White House press secretary Mike McCurry said
Friday that Clinton and Yeltsin did not discuss whether a new aid
package from the West would be needed. ``This was not a phone call
about money. It was a phone call about doing the things necessary''
to stabilize the struggling economy, McCurry said. ``They discussed
some of the steps that will be necessary to, over the long term,
assure economic stability in Russia,'' he added.)
</P>
<P>
   The banking system, which became the focus of Thursday's panic
after it became clear that some major banks were unable to repay
major loans, remained solvent, if short of foreign currency. Moscow
banks were open Friday, although many refused to sell their
customers dollars. The city's hundreds of hole-in-the-wall currency
exchanges were selling dollars, sometimes at exorbitant rates, but
many had posted ``No dollars'' signs by day's end.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bank was trading currency at the rate of about 6.3
rubles per dollar. But at some currency exchanges around town, the
rate approached 7 rubles per dollar. ``It looks as though they
avoided a run on the banks, which was the nightmare we were staring
at this morning,'' said Tom Adshead, co-director of research for
Moscow's United Financial Group. ``The foreign-exchange market
dried up. But fortunately, nobody's clamoring for their money.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the moment, the critical question is whether the banks will
do as well next week. Thursday's crisis was rooted in months of
speculating by some banks in high-yield government bonds and
currency ``forwards'' _ contracts to buy or sell currencies at
specified future dates. The banks had bet that the ruble would
remain stable and that the bond prices would not collapse _ and
when their bets soured, they were unable to cover their losses.
</P>
<P>
   More currency contracts will fall due next week, and the ruble's
weak status means that some banks may have to absorb large trading
losses. As occurred this week, other banks that put up government
bonds as collateral for loans could be asked to produce more money
now that the bonds have lost much of their value, a practice known
as a margin call.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia's central bank has begun pumping money into some of
the most illiquid banks, and analysts said it was spending still
more money to keep the value of the ruble from deteriorating
further. That pleased investors, but it is uncertain how long the
Central Bank, which has but $17 billion in reserves, can continue
without outside help.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's leaders continued to reject calls to devalue the ruble,
a move that would reduce the nation's debt, but would also ignite
inflation, destroy investors' confidence and provoke a political
showdown with Communists and nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin made a point of noting that he had not even broken his
summer vacation to return to Moscow, but instead had directed Prime
Minister Sergei Kiriyenko to press ahead with an overhaul of tax
and budget policies that is seen as critical if the government is
to remain solvent.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin also summoned the Communist-controlled lower house of
Parliament into emergency session to address the fiscal crisis.
Because the Duma has refused to meet, Yeltsin has been forced to
issue a series of legally dubious decrees ordering the measures
Kiriyenko is undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, the Communists, apparently struck by the seriousness
of the collapse, grudgingly agreed to convene, still insisting that
they would have nothing to do with tax increases and other
controversial provisions of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said that finance ministers of the major
Western industrial powers were already talking about how they might
mount another loan package or other assistance to steer Russia away
from bankruptcy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
