<SLUG> BC-SERONO-PLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERONO TO CLOSE PLANT IN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Serono Laboratories, which less than three years ago trumpeted
a &UR;  &LR; $40 million expansion of its biomanufacturing facility in
Randolph, Mass., said Friday it will close the plant in November
and dismiss 100 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The United States subsidiary of The Aeres-Serono Group of
Geneva, Switzerland said production of the two drugs made &UR;  &LR; in
Randolph _ human growth hormone and Serostim, an AIDS medication _
will be shifted to newer and larger facilities in Switzerland and
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cessation of our activities in Randolph is the consequence
of production efficiencies achieved at our other recombinant human
growth hormone manufacturing plants,'' said Jean-Pierre Verhassel,
senior executive vice president, &UR;  &LR; manufacturing, of Aeres-Serono .
``As a result of this increased capacity, we can no longer justify
the production of growth hormone at the Randolph facility.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to shutter the firm's only American production
facility follows a series of legal challenges &UR;  &LR;  by Genentech Corp.
Human growth hormone _ one of the first biotechnology-developed
drugs approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration _ was
initially developed by Genentech Corp. When Aeres-Serono, which &UR;  &LR; 
developed a similar drug, sought to market the product in the U.S.,
Genentech successfully sued &UR;  &LR;  to block its U.S. distribution . As a
result, Serono could produce the drug in Randolph solely for
overseas sales.
</P>
<P>
   Serono's manufacturing shutdown &UR;  &LR;  follows a series of
 &UR;  &LR; decisions by smaller Massachusetts biotechnology companies &UR;  &LR; to
outsource drug production and focus on research.
</P>
<P>
   A Serono spokeswoman said closing the Randolph facility will not
affect the more than 300 employees at the company's U.S. commercial
operations headquartered in Norwell, Mass. or Aeres Advanced
Technology, a research facility also located in Randolph.
</P>
<P>
   Verhassel said the company will try to find jobs for the 100
dismissed manufacturing employees. Serono will continue to operate
its warehousing and distribution facility in Randolph, which
employs 15 people, a company spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1917EDT &QL; 
