<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-AVENGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AVENGERS' MISSES OUT ON APPEAL OF ORIGINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE AVENGERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Directed by: Jeremiah Chechik, screenplay by Don MacPherson,
based on the TV series.
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Ralph Fiennes, Uma Thurman, Sean Connery, Jim
Broadbent, Fiona Shaw, Eileen Atkins
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Avengers,'' shielded from advance viewing by the withering
eyes of critics, arrived on movie screens Friday with a muffled
thud, missing almost entirely the teasing deadpan byplay between
the veddy, veddy British agents John Steed and Emma Peel. In the
mid-to-late '60s, ``The Avengers'' was a conspicuous part of the
British invasion of American pop culture, trailing in the wake of
James Bond and the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's easy enough to spot the origins of the TV
``Avengers'' in the extravagant James Bond spoofs, it owed as much
to the throwaway surrealism of ``A Hard Day's Night.'' The
incongruity-filled capers calling upon the lethal sang-froid of
Steed and Mrs. Peel ranged from nominal to campy. The fun came from
watching their shared sense of unruffled style.
</P>
<P>
   At their best, they scarcely seemed to notice the criminal
activity erupting around them. They were too busy engaging in
pursuits such as sculpture or chess, or at least having the cool
cockiness to pretend to be. The best moment, one of the few that
seem alive in the new movie starring Ralph Fiennes and Uma Thurman
in the roles originated by Patrick MacNee and Diana Rigg, comes
when they're playing between-the-lines sexual chess during a game
of actual chess.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the movie largely seems a spent force. Or perhaps an
unspent force. Fiennes, impeccable in his bowler hat, tailored
suit, sword cane, and bulletproof waistcoat, has the cool murmur
down cold. Thurman looks sensationally slinky in a succession of
clingy outfits, but is too ill at ease to muster the nonchalance
that made Mrs. Peel so entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   That she should be at a loss is understandable, especially
whenever she's asked to fight an evil clone of herself. The film
rides a pretext rather than anything that might be thought of as a
real plot. It must have seemed a coup to cast Sean Connery as the
villain _ Bond gone bad and turned into the enemy. But Connery's
role as a mad Scottish meteorologist, bent on world domination by
seeding clouds selectively and thus controlling climate, lacks the
light-handed playfulness that made him the best of the Bonds, the
only one really.
</P>
<P>
   Although the role of over-the-top tartan-plaid heavy must have
appealed to his Scottish nationalism on some level, Connery, too,
comes across as overwrought and uncomfortable. Only Eileen Atkins,
playing a droll embodiment of grandmotherly muscle, escapes
unscathed as the film collapses under a weight of special effects,
much as the ``X-Files'' movie did. The problem with ``The
Avengers'' on the big screen isn't that it doesn't make sense, but
that it doesn't make the right kind of nonsense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0330 </DOCNO>
