<HEADER>
A4898 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-IMAC-BOS &LR;      08-14 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-IMAC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE ROLLS OUT IMAC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fourteen years ago, a woman with a sledgehammer introduced
television audiences to Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh computer.
Today, Apple hopes to achieve the same kind of impact as it
launches a daring new computer called iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say the iMac will enjoy strong sales, as
longtime Mac users trade up from older machines. But they are
skeptical the new model will attract significant numbers of people
using personal computers based on Microsoft Corp.'s Windows
operating systems and Intel Corp.'s Pentium processors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Apple is giving iMac a rousing sendoff. It will be the
biggest product launch in the Cupertino, Calif.-based company's
history, with $100 million of advertising planned. There'll be
prime-time TV ads, and billboards with slogans like ``Chic. Not
geek'' and ``I think, therefore iMac.''
</P>
<P>
   The most visible aspect of the campaign will be the iMac itself,
a translucent blue-white ovoid that looks as if it were designed in
a wind tunnel. The all-in-one unit carries a $1,299 price tag.
That's cheap for a Macintosh, especially one with a built-in
monitor and speakers, a CD-ROM drive, 32 megabytes of memory, a
four-gigabyte hard drive, and a 56-kilobits-per-second modem. There
is even a high-speed connection to Ethernet networks, so that the
iMac can be used in business offices.
</P>
<P>
   Macintosh fans have lusted after the iMac since a prototype was
unveiled in May. Apple said earlier this week that it had taken
150,000 advance orders for the computer, raising fears of
shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are building them as quickly as possible,'' said iMac
product manager Tom Boger. ``We expect to have tens of thousands of
them available by Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   But there will be shortages of add-on devices like printers and
disk drives. That's due to the iMac's unusual design. The computer
does not include the usual floppy disk drive. Nor does it have the
standard external device ports for plugging in printers and other
devices. Instead, all add-ons must be connected using a new
technology called Universal Serial Bus, or USB. Unfortunately, few
USB devices have reached the market. For instance, Imation Corp. is
taking orders for a USB external disk drive for $189, but units
will not be available until later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Some Mac fans say the lack of accessories will cause them to
delay their decision about buying an iMac. ``I have a scanner and a
Zip drive that as far as I know, I won't be able to connect to
it,'' said Michael Rankin of Weymouth, an electronic production
specialist for Houghton Mifflin Co. ``I'll keep checking the Web
for news, and if it still sounds good around Christmas time, I
might get one then.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the nation's biggest maker of personal computers, Apple has
seen its market share plummet in recent years. According to
preliminary figures from International Data Corp., the slide
continued in the second quarter of 1998. The figures put Apple's
share of worldwide desktop computer sales at 3.1 percent, down from
3.2 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Few industry-watchers think that the iMac will do much to
reverse this trend. ``You need more than this,'' said IDC's Roger
Kay. ``If they doubled their market share as a result of this,
they'd still be a minor player.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay thinks that a burst of iMac sales will drive up Apple's
market share, but only for the time it takes for owners of older
Macintoshes to upgrade their systems. Once the loyal customer base
has been satisfied, he predicted that iMac sales will fall off. But
Kay added that there are enough loyal Mac users to allow Apple a
healthy profit from that market alone.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's stock, which traded below 13 last December, closed
Friday at 40 1/2, up 1 1/16, on Nasdaq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
