<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOT-ITEMS-$ADV16-NYT &LR;      08-14 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-ITEMS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT ITEMS: LONDON EDITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 16) 
 (bl)  
 By VICKY WARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Modest in Silk
</P>
<P>
   Jemima Khan, daughter of the late financier Sir James Goldsmith,
shocked London society in 1995, when she forsook West End
nightclubs and a university career to marry Imran Khan, a former
captain of the Pakistani cricket team, and a Muslim. Followed by
the paparazzi, she toured poverty-stricken streets of Lahore in a
shalwar kameez, the Pakistani pajama-style pantsuit. Surprisingly,
the public deemed the look smashing.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ms. Khan is introducing a line of Western clothes inspired
by Pakistani dress: floor-length sequined cocktail dresses in heavy
woven fabrics; dyed silk brocade coat dresses, chiffon cardigan
wraps.
</P>
<P>
   Not all are as modest as Muslim law requires: Some dresses come
in shorter lengths and have halter necks. Ms. Khan said she wanted
``to design clothes that are sufficiently modest for me, but are
still feminine and smart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cross and A la Mode, the boutiques that carry Jemima Khan,
sold out in a week, and the racks remain empty. ``The dresses are
made by hand in Pakistan, and each takes around three months to
complete,'' explained Ms. Khan, whose dresses cost about $975.
Proceeds go to a hospital founded by her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Service
</P>
<P>
   Socialists with servants? These days, the 101 female members of
Parliament, known by the press as Blair's Babes, are as likely to
debate the abolition of the House of Lords as the rights and wrongs
of nanny-hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never used to have staff, but after my fourth baby I cracked
and employed an au pair and a cleaner,'' said Margaret Hodge, a
Labor member. ``Everyone lambasted me. You couldn't be a socialist
and have a maid. Now under New Labor, we're not so ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Shades of the pre-World War II era of the scullery maid,
housekeeper and butler, as in ``The Remains of the Day.'' According
to polls in the Spectator, British spending on domestic help has
doubled in the last decade. The boom is financed by the aspiring
middle class, working mothers who need help and young fogies who
fancy having a black-tie butler serve dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers to the upstairs-downstairs household should note that
butler etiquette must still be observed. Not to be confused with a
gentleman's gentleman, the butler faxes the office with a dinner
menu but does not polish your shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen's New English
</P>
<P>
   Natural Spice: Nickname for Geri Halliwell (Ginger Spice), now
seen walking about bereft of makeup following her split with the
pop band.
</P>
<P>
   Henmania: Hysteria for Britain's Wimbledon hope, Tim Henman.
</P>
<P>
   TTH: Trying too hard. For instance, turning up in a shiny new
Barbour jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Happies: High asset professionals. Replacing yuppies, they are
more likely to invest in property than in Porsches.
</P>
<P>
   Tuerschlusspanik: German for the ``Bridget Jones' Diary''
syndrome of being single in your late 30s. Literally,
door-shut-panic.
</P>
<P>
   Glamouflage: The flashy gear needed to get into spots like the
Met Bar and look as if you belong.
</P>
<P>
   The New Insensitivity: Lack of charm in everyday behavior, like
asking the butler to shine your shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The Bloke Look
</P>
<P>
   Suiting up in London used to be simple: Bankers went to Savile
Row, salesclerks to Marks &AMP; Spencer. But newly image-conscious
young professionals want zippy suits with designer labels, like
John Rocha's boldly colored, luxuriously lined, close-cut models
(coming to Saks Fifth Avenue in New York in the fall).
</P>
<P>
   Owners are so attached to the new suits that they won't take
them off for any occasion. After Gordon Brown, the chancellor of
the Exchequer, eschewed white tie at a Mansion House dinner to
deliver his annual speech about the economy, men started wearing
suits instead of more formal attire to all kinds of upscale social
functions.
</P>
<P>
   At London weddings, it is now more chic to exchange the
traditional heavy black tailcoat for a tonic suit, in two-tone
linen or silk, made by Jigsaw, due to open a branch in New York in
the fall (prices start at $480).
</P>
<P>
   Snobbish hostesses are dismayed by the new sartorial
egalitarianism, and the mishmash of attire at their wedding
receptions. ``There is a backlash,'' said Marcus Ross, fashion
assistant at British GQ magazine. ``There's been a marked increase
in wedding invitations stipulating morning dress.'' Fashion's
dictates still can't compete with those of the mother of the bride.
</P>
<P>
   Carry On, Notting Hill
</P>
<P>
   What Richard Curtis did for the holy state of matrimony in
directing ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' he is about to do for
London's trendiest neighborhood with his newest film, ``Notting
Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the comedy, starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant, won't
be released until next year, residents are already not amused. They
fear Curtis will satirize them all as louche 20-somethings, known
for their trust funds, drug-taking and love of rasta music.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Notting Hill is home not only to trustafarians,
but also to fashionable figures like Jade Jagger, daughter of Mick
Jagger; Helen Fielding, author of ``Bridget Jones' Diary,'' and
Nicholas Coleridge, of Conde Nast U.K.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent hot spots of Notting Hill, once a small artisan
community, include the American restaurant Dakota (Madonna has
already had two parties there); the Tabernacle, which imported
Allegra McEvedy from New York's Tribeca Grill to be the head chef,
and the Pharmacie, owned by Sir Terence Conran.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anxiety is that the popularity of the film will attract
crowds, who will drive out all that is bohemian and eclectic and
replace it with money and the banal,'' said Philip Delves
Broughton, a Notting Hill homeowner. Will he see it? ``Of course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
