<HEADER>
A4902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-JURY-$ADV     08-14 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-JURY-$ADV16 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN AN HISTORIC WHITE HOUSE SETTING, CLINTON WILL GIVE HIGH TECH
TESTIMONY
 &HT;    For release Sunday, August 16
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seated in the room where generals briefed Franklin
Roosevelt on the allied invasion of Normandy and surrounded by
ornate furnishings that date to the beginnings of the republic,
President Clinton will answer prosecutors' questions on Monday
about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be aided by three lawyers and White House video equipment
that will feed his sworn testimony via closed circuit television
into a closed and windowless room at the U.S. district courthouse
several blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   There, for the first time in American history, a federal grand
jury will receive live testimony from a sitting president, who
planned to spend much of Saturday and Sunday rehearsing for
Monday's session.
</P>
<P>
   At 1 p.m., Clinton is scheduled to walk into the so-called Map
Room, which Roosevelt used as a situation room for military updates
on World War II campaigns, on the first floor of the White House
residence.
</P>
<P>
   There Clinton will be grilled, probably for several hours, by
representatives from the office of independent counsel Kenneth
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Aides with Starr's office, the White House and lawyers familiar
with the arrangements all declined to say whether Starr would be
present for the testimony, or whether questions would be asked by
other prosecutors on his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Clinton's answers will be fed live to the 23-person
grand jury and videotaped for any jurors unable to view the
testimony as it unfolds. Jurors may submit questions to the
prosecutors, but they are under no obligation to put those
questions to Clinton. Jurors may not put questions directly to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, Starr has been investigating allegations that
Clinton had a White House affair with former intern Monica Lewinsky
and later urged her to lie about it under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent grand jury appearance, however, Lewinsky reportedly
contradicted Clinton's version of events, outlining a long-term
White House affair.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have said little about whether Clinton
intends to stick by his earlier denials or to amend his account.
Clinton's spokesman, Michael McCurry, told reporters Friday he
expected Clinton to respond fully and honestly to prosecutors'
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know why he wouldn't. He's under oath. The truth is
the truth. He's got to testify and it's a consequential thing when
you go before a grand jury,'' McCurry said. ''But we don't know
what is going to be asked. We obviously don't know what's going to
be answered.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said he didn't know whether Clinton plans to address the
nation after his Monday testimony and that he probably wouldn't
know until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to leave shortly after his testimony to
begin a two-week vacation on Martha's Vineyard, off the
Massachusetts coast.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will sit beneath a cut-glass chandelier made in England
before the Revolutionary War, surrounded by 8th-Century Chippendale
chairs, desks and tables arrayed across a century-old Oriental rug.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging above a sandstone mantle is a map showing military
positions across Europe as U.S.-led Allied forces closed in on Nazi
Germany on April 3, 1945 _ nine days before Roosevelt died, and
five weeks before Germany surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   Technicians are going to pains to ensure that the closed-circuit
signal remains closed to potential hackers who might try to
intercept testimony expected to shed light on Clinton's
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Aides with Starr's office, the White House and Clinton's legal
team refused to discuss those arrangements. Experts say the most
likely possibility is that the signal could be sent through
existing White House fiber optic lines and routed to the
courthouse. Alternatively, if the signal is to be broadcast, it
could be scrambled in an attempt to prevent a high-tech hijacking
of the potentially explosive testimony. Experts say fiber optic
transmissions are more secure than those broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be accompanied by no White House staff other than
White House Counsel Charles Ruff. Also present on Clinton's behalf
will be two of personal attorneys, David Kendall and Nicole
Seligman, both of the Washington law firm Williams &AMP; Connolly.
White House officials refused to say whether Clinton's lawyers can
advise him during the questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Normally witnesses appear before a grand jury alone. Even their
attorneys are required to wait outside of the grand jury room, as
part of efforts to ensure the secrecy of grand jury hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office subpoenaed Clinton last month to appear before
the grand jury. Clinton agreed to testify on camera from the White
House, on the condition that Starr withdraw his subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury does not determine a person's innocence or guilt,
but merely reviews testimony and evidence to determine whether a
prosecutor has a case with sufficient evidence to warrant a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
