<SLUG> BC-MA-FLEET-ATMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET FINANCIAL TO IMPOSE 75-CENT ATM SURCHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN AND BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fleet Financial Group Inc. said Friday it will impose a
75-cent surcharge for users of its automated teller machines who
are not customers of the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The surcharge, not unexpected, is lower than had been previously
projected.
</P>
<P>
   While battling consumer groups and lawmakers who wanted to ban
all surcharges, Fleet's officials have long talked about imposing
$1 ATM surcharge on non-customers. They cited the figure as the
amount they charge in other states where they operate and necessary
to cover costs.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleet spokeswoman Ellen Molle said the bank's new figure of
75 cents was a business decision based on the local economy, and
that $1 was never a set figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is based on what we thought the competitive marketplace
could bear,'' she said. ``We never said $1.''
</P>
<P>
   The surcharge plan, which has been filed with the state banking
commissioner, would take effect on Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The state's other large bank, BankBoston, could not be reached
late Friday about its decisions regarding surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's announcement comes as the 210-member Massachusetts
Bankers Association told the state attorney general's office Friday
that it was rescinding a plan it proposed last month, which set a
maximum $1 ATM surcharge for non-customers at the state's two
largest banks, Fleet and BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was designed in part to mollify concerns among smaller
banks that the fees would cause their depositors to switch to the
big banks. In addition to the cap on fees, Fleet and BankBoston
also agreed not to run advertising or promotions encouraging
customers of other banks to switch to one of the two big banks to
avoid surcharges. The two banks also agreed to work out agremeents
with the smaller banks to allow them to pay the surcharge fee
directly, rather than have their customers assessed it while taking
money out of a BankBoston or Fleet ATM.
</P>
<P>
   The plan came under attack by the attorney general's office,
which raised anti-trust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Forte, president of the trade group, said his group is
pulling back from the plan because it doesn't want to get into a
protracted legal battle with the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   After consulting with the association's attorneys, Forte said,
the association decided ``we have to pull that plan off the
table.'' He emphasized that the association always viewed the plan
as a a set of ``voluntary best practices guidelines'' and not a
rigid price-setting deal between two big banks.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston and Fleet own two-thirds of all ATM machines in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the announcement by Fleet, Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger reiterated his call for an ATM surcharge ban. He
described the charge as ``unfair to consumers and ``a threat to
community banks in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   He said ``it too soon to tell'' if the Massachusetts Bankers
Association's decision to pull back last month's plan satisfies his
anti-trust concerns. He said he has scheduled meetings with the
banks next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
