<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEST-FORK-DEVELOP-ART     08-14 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-FORK-DEVELOP-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTERS FACE DEVELOPERS ACROSS A GENTLE RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., N.C., S.C.)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAYTON, Ga._ The real white water, the ``Deliverance white
water,'' is all downstream. But upstream, on the West Fork of the
Chattooga River near the intersection of Georgia, South Carolina
and North Carolina, the gently flowing shallows provide an ideal
training ground for paddlers who are not quite ready to navigate
Class V rapids and 7-foot falls.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the West Fork has provided a serene and unfettered
journey through the Chattahoochee National Forest. On one recent
brilliant afternoon, canoeists saw a great blue heron lift off a
driftwood perch and flap its way around the bend like a forward
scout. Skittish darters zigzagged just beneath the surface,
streaking away from the approaching bow. The smell of polecat
lingered on the banks.
</P>
<P>
   But things have not been very idyllic here since Earl Lovell,
Scottie Fain and Chris Henson bought the only major tract along the
West Fork that is not part of the national forest. Last August, the
three developers spent about $1.5 million to obtain 230 acres on
both sides of the river and announced plans to subdivide it for
high-end housing.
</P>
<P>
   They did not stop with their plan to sell lots starting at
$200,000. Although the Chattooga is designated by Congress as one
of 154 national wild and scenic rivers, the developers declared
that the one-mile stretch of the West Fork flowing through their
land was private property and could not be traversed without
permission.
</P>
<P>
   In enforcing their blockade, the developers played off the
imagery of ``Deliverance,'' the 1972 movie filmed on the Chattooga
in which four canoeists encounter serious trouble from two mountain
men on the riverbank.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they hung a sign from a cable across the river
saying, ``Private Property _ Survivors Will Be Prosecuted.'' From
time to time, paddlers choosing to ignore the warning were
confronted by bands of men on the shore who strongly suggested that
they remove themselves from the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there are 10 big guys sitting there on the bank with
shovels, it can be a little intimidating,'' said Mark Lovell, who
is Earl Lovell's son. ``After all, this is the river where
`Deliverance' was filmed.'' One of the developers' lawyers, Jay
Bennett, noted with a chuckle that his clients once considered
hanging speakers from the trees so that trespassers could be
greeted with a recording of ``Dueling Banjos,'' the movie's twangy
theme song.
</P>
<P>
   Those accustomed to running the river are not amused. Buzz
Williams, a former river guide who now directs the Chattooga River
Watershed Coalition, said he had dissuaded a group of men from
carrying out a plan, hatched in a barroom, to send a flotilla of
armed paddlers down the West Fork. Perhaps even more menacing, a
group of trial lawyers volunteered to float through the property.
</P>
<P>
   Williams speculated that the developers may want to incite
public protest so that pressure will mount on the Forest Service to
buy the land at an exorbitant price. ``They're in it to make a huge
amount of money,'' he said of the developers. ``It's a form of
high-stakes leverage with a very important piece of property.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovell, a white-haired fireplug of a man whose voice rumbles
like a bulldozer, is not the least bit offended by Williams'
description. ``I strictly buy every piece of property to make a
profit,'' he said, explaining that the developers would gladly sell
for $4.6 million, a one-year turnaround of 207 percent. ``All
things being equal, I'd rather see the Forest Service get it, but I
ain't giving them no slack.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although Williams and Lovell share a certain mutual admiration,
as well as the common goal of persuading the Forest Service to buy
the land, the two antagonists live in different worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 48, is a hippie-ish outdoorsman with the sinewed
deltoids of an expert paddler. He drives a battered pickup and
lives with his wife in a non-electrified mud hut modeled after a
Mongolian yurt.
</P>
<P>
   Lovell, 64, lives in a stunning hilltop house on a 700-acre
spread in nearby Clarkesville that boasts a 360-degree view of the
surrounding Appalachians. He is regarded as a savvy businessman who
is known for coarse language. In an interview, he went out of his
way to volunteer that he uses a racial epithet when referring to
black people.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, most folks around here have never appreciated James
Dickey's characterization in ``Deliverance,'' which depicted the
locals as toothless, tourist-raping hillbillies. But the movie's
thrilling scenes of whitewater canoeing gave birth to a new
outfitting industry in northeast Georgia that brings about 75,000
rafters and paddlers to the Chattooga each year.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Justice Department used the commerce generated by
the outfitters as the foundation of a federal lawsuit that seeks to
declare the West Fork as a navigable waterway. Under the U.S.
Constitution, navigable rivers are public property. Case law has
established that a river's navigability depends on its capacity for
commercial transport, but a judge must decide whether whitewater
outfitting fits that definition.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Cassidy, general counsel for American Rivers, a national
conservation group, said that courts have applied different
definitions in different cases. But, he asserted, ``when Congress
designated these as wild and scenic rivers it intended that members
of the public would have a right to boat on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, the lawyer for the developers, countered that canoes
and kayaks are not customary vehicles for trade. ``But the main
point,'' he said, ``is that what the government wants to do, which
is to avoid development up there, they can only do by paying us the
fair value.''
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing in June, the Forest Service and the developers
agreed to try to negotiate a purchase price. While talks are
ongoing, the developers have removed the sign over the river and
stopped confronting paddlers as they cross the property.
</P>
<P>
   But if hostilities resume, Williams may press the Forest Service
to condemn part of the shoreline for a scenic easement, which would
insure access to the river. He acknowledged that doing so would be
unpopular here in Rabun County, where private property rights are
considered sacred because the government already owns 63 percent of
the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a hornet's nest,'' Williams said. ``But if they
push us to the wall, we'll play every card we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
