<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAOS ASIDE, IRVIN STILL KING OF CHARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ She was blond-haired and blue-eyed and
was pressed up against the chain-link fence, her head about level
with the knees of the adults around her, who were straining to get
Michael Irvin's autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the lunchroom at training camp the other day, Irvin had
strolled over to the fence to sign for the folks patiently waiting.
No way he could ignore the little blond-haired beauty as she twined
her 3-year-old fingers through the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are so cute,'' Irvin told her as he knelt to squeeze her
hand. ``Do you know how cute you are?''
</P>
<P>
   The little girl's cheeks dimpled as she flashed a heartbreaker's
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said simply.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin burst into laughter as he stood up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are so great,'' he said, ``because they're never afraid
of the truth. Why is it, when we get to be adults, we feel we have
to lie?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a rhetorical question and the dozen or so Cowboys fans,
happy to have the team's famed wide receiver so near, smiled and
shook their heads.
</P>
<P>
   But the question hung there in the early afternoon heat, begging
an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Why indeed?
</P>
<P>
   I was hanging around to ask Irvin _ again _ to sit down for an
interview. It was my fifth request since training camp began, the
second time that day.
</P>
<P>
   It still hasn't happened and probably won't, but you never know.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in camp I had endured two brushoffs and an official
stiffing from Irvin. That's how those in my business rate our
nonproductive interview attempts.
</P>
<P>
   It works like this: You approach a player as he's leaving the
practice field, or entering the cafeteria, and politely ask if he'd
mind giving you a few minutes after lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Most are amenable. Irvin, for obvious reasons, can be tough to
pin down.
</P>
<P>
   A brushoff is when they say they don't have time, maybe
tomorrow, that kind of thing. When the player acquiesces, you set a
time and when they don't show or offer up some other sudden excuse
why they can't stay for the interview, you've been officially
stiffed.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago Irvin agreed, finally, to sit down after
lunch and a national TV interview he had promised to do. I waited,
biding my time and thinking of what questions to ask. But when he'd
completed his TV deal, he blew by with a weak apology about an
appointment he had to keep.
</P>
<P>
   Something about a haircut, I think.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't hide my disgust well, hoping to make Michael feel as
guilty as possible.
</P>
<P>
   That guilt was what I was playing on when I made my fourth and
fifth runs at him the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, I like Michael Irvin. I can't help it. He makes me
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like some of the things he has done, but it's difficult
to spend any time around him and not be charmed. He's personable,
fun, direct and highly quotable, an asset not to be undervalued
when you're a reporter looking for a story. Plus, he truly enjoys
talking.
</P>
<P>
   He also can't seem to stay out of trouble, explaining his most
recent reticence about facing a notebook or tape recorder. Thus,
you won't be reading any Irvin quotes here.
</P>
<P>
   We spent a good bit of time just talking, Irvin being careful
not to reveal too much, me trying to tiptoe around taboo subjects
and still understand what's going on in his head.
</P>
<P>
   No juicy revelations about what happened in that dorm room with
Everett McIver. No finger-pointing. No alibis. No concocted
stories.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I can tell you:
</P>
<P>
   Somebody other than the Cowboys _ perhaps his probation officer
_ has instructed Irvin to keep quiet on the McIver incident until
all investigations have been completed.
</P>
<P>
   He is livid at reports he was involved in a payoff to McIver.
</P>
<P>
   He remains convinced that, at heart, he is a good, if imperfect,
human being, who very much believes that he can be a productive
player for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys keep saying nobody's going to jail, everything's
fine, the situation has been handled internally and it's no longer
an issue.
</P>
<P>
   I'd still like to hear the whole story, on the record, from
Michael's own lips someday.
</P>
<P>
   And even though we're all adults here, I won't even insist on a
polygraph machine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
