<SLUG> BC-FDA-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA CAN'T REGULATE TOBACCO, APPEALS COURT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cigarette makers won a major victory Friday, as a
federal appeals court blocked President Clinton's landmark effort
to regulate tobacco sales and marketing, particularly to children.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing a lower court finding, a three-judge panel in the US
Fourth Circuit of Appeals ruled 2-1 that the Food and Drug
Administration has no authority to regulate tobacco, as Clinton
ordered the agency to do in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, issued less than a month after a move to further
regulate cigarette makers died in the Senate, sets up a likely
Supreme Court showdown over Clinton's high-stakes effort to crack
down on the $50 billion tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling strengthens the hand of tobacco companies in their
negotiations to settle smoking-related lawsuits by about three
dozen states. The decision also is expected to renew the push for
congressional action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that Congress did not equip the FDA with tools
appropriate for the regulation of tobacco because it had no
intention that the (Food, Drug,and Cosmetics) Act apply to tobacco
products,'' the appeals court ruled in a majority opinion written
by US Circuit Judge H. Emory Widener Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration immediately vowed to challenge the
ruling, first by petitioning the full appeals court to reconsider
its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``is fully committed to the FDA's regulatory role and
its role in protecting our children,'' said White House spokesman
Michael McCurry. ``Reaffirming the Food and Drug Administration's
authority over tobacco products is necessary to help stop young
people from smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, if upheld, would strike down the FDA regulations
currently in effect, including a requirement that stores demand
proof of age for anyone under age 27 who attempts to buy
cigarettes. The legal age to buy cigarettes in all 50 states is 18.
</P>
<P>
   The other FDA regulations at issue are rules limiting
vending-machine sales and outdoor advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-tobacco advocates expressed outrage at the ruling, although
many said they expected a setback because the appeals court is
based in Richmond, Va., deep in tobacco country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is simply a way station on the road to the US Supreme
Court,'' said Richard Daynard, director of the Tobacco Products
Liability Project at Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   Still, William D. Novelli, president of the Campaign for
Tobacco-Free Kids, decried the decision as ``a victory for Big
Tobacco's lawyers over America's families and their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Widener, who was appointed to the bench by President Nixon, was
joined in the ruling by Senior US District Judge James H. Michael
Jr., an appointee of President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not dispute in this case that Congress has charged the
FDA with protecting the public health and that tobacco products
present serious health risks for the public,'' Widener wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Widener and Michael concluded that the FDA regulations on
tobacco exceeded the agency's authority.
</P>
<P>
   The lone dissenter was Senior US Circuit Judge Kenneth K. Hall,
an appointee of President Ford, whose opinion is expected to figure
prominently in a likely Supreme Court appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inasmuch as cigarettes and smokeless tobacco are responsible
for illness and death on a vast scale,'' Hall wrote, ``FDA
regulations aimed at curbing tobacco use by children cannot
possibly be contrary to the general intent of the (Food, Drug, and
Cosmetics Act) to protect the public health.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court reversed a decision last year by US District
Judge William Osteen in North Carolina, who upheld the FDA rules
under the agency's finding that nicotine should be regulated as a
drug and tobacco products as drug-delivery devices. Even that
decision, however, rejected government restrictions on tobacco
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's decision was welcomed by the nation's five largest
tobacco companies that appealed the lower court decision: Philip
Morris, R.J. Reynolds, Brown &AMP; Williamson, Lorillard and U.S.
Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The industry was joined in the appeal by convenience store
retailers and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased by the court's ruling that the FDA does not
have authority to regulate tobacco products, and that the agency's
1996 tobacco rule is invalid,'' the cigarette companies said in a
joint statement. ``The industry remains fully committed to taking
meaningful steps to reduce underage tobacco use.''
</P>
<P>
   Several leading anti-tobacco advocates in Congress criticized
the court's ruling. ``I believe the FDA has ample authority under
current law to regulate tobacco to protect the public health, and
I'm optimistic the Supreme Court will revisit it,'' said Senator
Edward M. Kennedy, Democrat of Massachusetts. ``The FDA's role is
especially important in protecting children from the cynical
advertising assaults of the tobacco industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, an Arizona Republican who led the
unsuccessful push for anti-tobacco legislation in the Senate, said,
``The appeals court's decision makes it even more imperative that
Congress pass legislation to address the problem of youth tobacco
use and addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys general in nearly 40 states had filed briefs with the
appeals court supporting the FDA regulations. Several expressed
disappointment at the decision, which gives the tobacco industry
fresh momentum as it fights numerous lawsuits from states trying to
recover billions of dollars in medical costs for smoking-related
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the Supreme Court imposes some common sense,'' said
Massachusetts Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, ``tough action by
Congress is our last hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling does not affect state and local laws
governing tobacco sales, use or marketing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
