<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFARES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This time, increase might stick as American boost is matched
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An on-again, off-again effort by big airlines to boost
certain advance purchase airfares may finally take hold, resulting
in a 4 percent increase for some travelers.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines initiated the increase, and on Friday
Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines, along with United, Continental and
US Airways, matched the move.
</P>
<P>
   The increase affects many, but not all, advance purchase prices.
For instance, from Atlanta a 14-day roundtrip fare to Washington's
Reagan National Airport rises to $380 from $365, while a 21-day
fare to Denver moves to $441 from $424.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines have tried to quietly boost such fares no fewer than
six times dating back to the spring, according to analyst Sam
Buttrick of PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Delta initiated a similar boost last week. But like the previous
hikes, it was rescinded when Northwest Airlines did not go along.
The apparent reason, Buttrick said, was that Northwest has been
plagued with service and labor woes, and did not want to risk
further alienating loyal customers.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines can't legally agree to raise fares as a group, but
typically don't stick with an increase unless rivals go along.
</P>
<P>
   This time, American exempted flights into Northwest hubs _
Minneapolis, Detroit and Memphis _ and Delta did likewise. The move
was seen as an offer to mitigate the effect on Northwest, but
unless Northwest matches the boost in other cities it could still
fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the increase won't affect sale fares or the lowest
advance purchase fares in markets where Delta competes with
discounters such as AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't affect walk-up fares or those requiring no
weekend stay, which are most often used by business fliers. Those
fares have risen more sharply over the past year than advance
purchase fares, which have been relatively stable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
