<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
 
PROBATION OFFICIALS TALK WITH COWBOYS' McIVER, IRVIN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MEDE NIX 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas County adult probation officials have talked with Cowboys
guard Everett McIver about a July 29 incident at training camp that
left him with a cut on his neck, said Ron Goethals, director of
Dallas County's community supervision and corrections department.
</P>
<P>
   The interview took place at Cowboys training camp in Wichita
Falls when, Goethals said yesterday, probation officials also
talked with Michael Irvin. A source with knowledge of the situation
said that Irvin was involved in the dormitory-room incident in
which McIver was cut with a scissors.
</P>
<P>
   Goethals said he would not comment about what was said by
McIver, or ``several'' other people probation officials spoke with.
</P>
<P>
   McIver was unavailable for comment. Cowboys owners Jerry Jones
said the investigation ``has not interrupted any player from
practice or interfered with anything we have done during training
camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Goethals had said probation officials would not
investigate the incident unless a complaint of criminal action was
filed. But the McIver interview came during the normal course of
business, which ``you can assume'' was to talk to Michael Irvin,
Goethals said.
</P>
<P>
   Goethals said officials from his office are in contact with
Irvin regularly according to the terms of his probation.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said that the interviews of McIver and others is not
a change in the stance of the probation department regarding the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   The interviews may not necessarily lead to a decision to file a
report with District Judge Manny Alvarez, who sentenced Irvin to
four years' probation in 1996 after Irving pleaded guilty to
possession of cocaine, Goethals said. Alvarez can revoke Irvin's
probation and sentence him to two to 20 years in prison if he finds
Irvin has violated his probation.
</P>
<P>
   Goethals maintains that the usual threshold to seek revocation
of probation would be the filing of a criminal complaint _ which
would indicate some evidence of a crime _ and not merely reports of
what might be considered a criminal incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a matter pending before the court, and we are
acting as the eyes and ears of the judge,'' Goethals said.
</P>
<P>
   The interviews with people about the incident is not in response
to publicity surrounding the incident or a change in the way the
probation department is handling the case, Goethals said.
</P>
<P>
   A probation officer would normally make arrangements to talk
with or visit a probationer who is going to be out of the county
for an extended period of time, like at a training camp in Wichita
Falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the normal scheme of things,'' he said. ``And in the
course of that arrangement, (probation officers) might talk to
other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Goethals said he did not know if probation officers actually
visited Irvin at the Cowboys' training camp last year when it was
in Austin or merely made arrangements to talk with Irvin by phone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
