<HEADLINE>
SEEDS AT COREL BEING BLOWN AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ The seeds have fallen by the wayside, blown
by an ill wind into the dry ditches, so now the question for the
Corel Boston Cup is this: Can flowers still bloom on the tennis
court without seeds?
</P>
<P>
   Fourth seed Silvia Farina departed Thursday, and Friday top seed
Amanda Coetzer and No. 2 Anke Huber were double-dutched, leaving
only No. 3 Lisa Raymond with a chance to sprout.
</P>
<P>
   Coetzer lost to Barbara Schett, 6-7 (7-3), 6-4, 6-2, while Huber
fell to Mariaan de Swardt, 6-3, 7-6 (7-5), in the quarterfinals at
Babson College. Raymond beat Corina Morariu, 7-6 (7-5), 6-2, and
will meet de Swardt in Saturday's first semifinal at noon.
</P>
<P>
   All fine and good, say Schett and de Swardt, the
seed-scrunchers, because they feel their time is coming. Especially
Schett, the 22-year-old Austrian from Innsbruck who time and again
has found herself with chances in the third set to knock off the
top women in the world ... only to fail. The 29th-ranked woman in
the world has the litany of missed chances learned by rote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against (Jana) Novotna, I was 5-4 and 40-love in the third
set, and then I had (Arantxa) Sanchez (Vicario), 5-2, in the third
set ... always against Top 10 players,'' said the 5-foot-10-inch
Schett. ``It was in Berlin this year, Novotna and Sanchez was in
Berlin, too ... always in Berlin. Then against (Monica) Seles, I
had six match points once ... two years ago in Madrid ... and I
lost that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday Schett led, 5-3, in the first set with her serve against
Coetzer, the eighth-ranked player in the world, only to let the
South African crawl back. At 6-5, Schett had the advantage over
Coetzer but once again let the South African off the hook, and
Coetzer drew level at 6-6 and won the tiebreaker by acing Schett
for the final point.
</P>
<P>
   Schett's memory bank now kicked into some very grim selective
recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been leading, 5-3, with my serve and I was thinking it
happens very often to me against Top 10 players,'' she said. ``So I
was thinking, `Come on. Not again. I do not want to lose again.'''
</P>
<P>
   The two women held serve through the first four games of the
second set. Then a marathon fifth game, lasting nearly 15 minutes,
tested the wills and bodies and psyche of Schett and Coetzer, who
was serving. Coetzer fell behind, 0-40, but battled back even and
five times wouldn't relent as Schett had the advantage. On her
sixth tango with fate, Coetzer couldn't bring the game back to
deuce as she double-faulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see that mentally, she was a little ... ah, broken ...
after that game,'' said Schett. ``Then she was serving really bad.
The problem was that I hadn't been aggressive enough with her
serves. I think her second serve is not so hard, and I could step
in and be aggressive, but that's what I didn't do (until that fifth
game). But then I was aggressive and I made the breaks ... or she
double-faulted.''
</P>
<P>
   Coetzer would win only three more games the rest of the match.
But with that memory bank in the grim mode, Schett could enjoy
little of it, even when she was up, 3-0, in the final set.
</P>
<P>
   First, said Schett, ``Amanda never gives up and always fights to
the last point. Amanda doesn't make any presents to her opponent.
You almost have to beat her twice, I would say.''
</P>
<P>
   When Coetzer broke her in the fourth game of the final set,
Schett felt that old Novotna-Seles-Sanchez Vicario scenario
creeping back into play, even though her groundstrokes were
blazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she broke me at 3-love, I was getting a little nervous
again,'' said Schett. ``That's because ... you know, I was leading
very often against those (top) players and I not win. And you know,
in the mind, you always think about that a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schett cruised home, and it was Coetzer who was left
mystified by the turn of events. The South African conceded she was
``sluggish'' and ``I never really ever felt comfortable'' and ``I
really struggled with my returns, Fridayand that was very
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   There comes a game every match that is as much a test of wills
as bodies, and Coetzer conceded that losing that fifth game of the
second set ``was definitely the crucial point.''
</P>
<P>
   What was surprising to fitness freak Coetzer ``was that I didn't
feel very energetic or motivated at that point, and I don't often
feel like that. It was very hard for me not to get through that
game _ I really had a lot of opportunities in it _ and it was the
turning point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
