<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retirement date moved up for Delta's oldest jets
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines will accelerate the retirement of its
oldest jets, prodded in part by more stringent requirements for
maintaining aging aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based airline said the move, which involves its
Boeing 727s, will help check a gradual rise in average fleet age
and improve customer service by boosting reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has 131 of the jets _ more than any single type in its
fleet _ and said it plans to retire them all by 2005, rather than
2008 as previously planned.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokeswoman Laura Gillig said one reason for the move is a
recent change in Federal Aviation Administration rules that results
in more frequent mandatory inspections for some 727s. She said
Delta and other airlines that fly the 727 face significantly higher
costs over the long run if they keep the jet in their fleets.
</P>
<P>
   The planes will be replaced primarily by a new version of the
737, another '60s-era workhorse now being produced in updated
models. The replacement should help Delta pare operating costs. The
727 has three engines and requires three pilots, while the 737 has
only two of each.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the new 737s arrives this fall, when the 727
retirements will begin. Gillig said deliveries of 737s will be
stepped up in coming years to match the accelerated retirement
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's 727s average 21.6 years in age, ranking them just ahead
of the next-oldest jet in the fleet, the L-1011 TriStar, at 19.4
years. The L-1011s are slated for replacement by an extended
version of the 767 widebody slated for initial delivery in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of Delta's 570-jet fleet has crept upward in
recent years, from 9.6 years in 1993 to 12.4 years currently _
about in the middle of the industry pack.
</P>
<P>
   Separately on Friday, Delta said it will begin new service
between Portland, Ore., and Fukuoka, Japan, on Oct. 29. But it has
delayed the start of new Portland-Osaka flights until June 1999.
The flights are the result of a new treaty allowing more carriers
to add flights between the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
