</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALABAMA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Profile on Alabama: Tide's DuBose confident in new aides
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ By his own admission, Mike DuBose made a ton
of mistakes in his first season as Alabama's head football coach.
And they all, he said, stemmed from one nearly fatal flaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed way too much,'' said DuBose, whose 4-7 record in
1997 was Alabama's worst since 1957, the year before Bear Bryant
took over.
</P>
<P>
   DuBose assumed that all his assistant coaches would be like him
when it came to the intensity and the work ethic they brought to
the job. He assumed that they believed in team goals first and
individual glory last. He assumed that they were all automatically
loyal to him as head coach. Not so.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was an assistant coach, I wanted to know more about my
position and my responsibility than anybody in the country. I
assumed the staff felt the same way,'' he said. ``That was a
mistake. Some people had different agendas.''
</P>
<P>
   DuBose won't discuss the specific problems that plagued his 1997
coaching staff, but those close to the program talk about an
incendiary mix of the old and the new. The old ones were holdovers
from the staff of Gene Stallings, who were wedded to the
traditional, conservative style of Alabama football. Can't blame
them _ Stallings won 70 games in seven years in Tuscaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   The new one were DuBose's own hires, brought in to help
implement his vision of what Alabama football should be in the next
century _ a sophisticated passing game to set up the running game,
after the manner of Tennessee and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the sparks to fly. After rolling up more
passing yards (253) than running yards (240) in a 42-17 win against
Houston, Alabama was held to just 238 total yards (97 rushing) in a
20-0 win over Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt, as it turned out, had the SEC's best defense. But
the holdovers from the Stallings era saw it as evidence that the
passing philosophy was doomed to failure and were very vocal about
it in the staff meetings.
</P>
<P>
   DuBose listened and eventually gave in to that point of view. It
was, he said, the most serious mistake he made as a first-year
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let it influence my decision-making process, and we reverted
back to the style of football we played in the past, and that's not
what I wanted to do,'' DuBose said. ``It was the wrong thing to do.
It was a mistake, but that's a mistake I'll never make again.''
</P>
<P>
   From then on, the Alabama offense was caught in a competitive
twilight zone. Opponents began to throw up eight-man defensive
fronts to stop the run, knowing that the Crimson Tide didn't have
enough confidence to pass their way out of it.
</P>
<P>
   In seven of Alabama's last 10 games, the Crimson Tide was held
to less than 300 yards of total offense. It lost five of those
games and with each loss, the tension on the staff grew. Even the
players were aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely saw the turmoil, and it had some effect on us,''
cornerback Fernando Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   The problems culminated in the final game with Auburn. With less
than a minute left, Alabama had the ball with a 17-15 lead. The
Crimson Tide faced a third and eight at its own 36-yard line.
DuBose walked down the sideline to make sure the punt team was
getting ready, assuming offensive coordinator Bruce Arians would
call a safe running play.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Arians called a screen pass to fullback Ed Scissum, who
fumbled after a jarring hit by Auburn's Martavious Houston. Auburn
recovered at the Alabama 33-yard line and with 15 seconds left,
Jaret Holmes kicked a 39-yard field goal to give the Tigers a
crushing 18-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, DuBose grappled for an explanation. Either he knew
about the call and gave his approval, or he didn't know about the
call in this most critical of situations. DuBose had assumed Arians
knew what he wanted at that point in the game, and it had cost him
dearly.
</P>
<P>
   The changes came swiftly. Arians was fired, and offensive-line
coach Neil Callaway was moved to offensive coordinator. Callaway is
Dubose's former teammate and roomate. They are friends who have
shared the same philosophy for more than 20 years. DuBose can
communicate better with Callaway and will trust his judgment with
the game on the line. ``Bruce (Arians) needed for me to be more
involved, and with Neil, he'll know what I want in those
situations,'' DuBose said. ``If he doesn't know it, I will tell him
at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Three other assistants _ Woody McCorvey, Danny Pearman, and
Curley Hallman _ went out the door with Arians. In their places,
DuBose hired four men he thinks will address the major weaknesses
in the program:
</P>
<P>
   _ Charlie Stubbs, who learned the passing game at BYU, became
quarterbacks coach. Last season as offensive coordinator at UNLV,
Stubbs took a freshman quarterback, Jon Denton, and led the WAC in
passing (2,586 yards). Denton also led the WAC in total offense
(287.9 ypg). It is hoped that Stubbs can work the same magic with
Tyler Watts, Alabama's highly touted freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbs, who also was assistant head coach at UNLV, was willing
to come to Alabama despite the fact that Callaway has the title of
coordinator and will call the plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much of an ego,'' Stubbs said. ``I just wanted to
work with and against the best.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DuBose lured Ronnie Cottrell away from Florida State by making
him assistant head coach. Since 1990, Cottrell had earned a
national reputation as the Seminoles' recruiting coordinator,
putting together one nationally ranked class after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings a work ethic to the recruiting process that didn't
exist here before,'' DuBose said.
</P>
<P>
   The move already has paid off, as Alabama's incoming class is
rated in the top five by every major recruiting service.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did at Florida State, we can do here,'' said Cottrell,
a native of Brewton, Ala., who played at Troy State. ``We just have
to broaden our horizons and work at it every single day.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Charlie Harbison, a former defensive backs coach at Clemson,
and Jackie Shipp, a former All-Big Eight defensive lineman from
Oklahoma, ``give us a spark we haven't had on that side of the
ball,'' DuBose said.
</P>
<P>
   So, all the pieces of the new organization are in place. DuBose
has surrounded himself with a group of men who share his vision and
can be counted on to remain loyal when the times get tough. And
yes, Alabama will have some tough times this season. Perhaps as
many as last season. But DuBose won't have to spend any time
looking over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good about this staff. There are not a lot of
egos,'' he said. ``They have goals and ambitions, but no hidden
agendas. And that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday: Tennessee
</P>
<P>
   Alabama fact box for Saturday
</P>
<P>
   _ Location: Tuscaloosa, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enrollment: 19,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Mike DuBose is 4-7 in one year at Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nickname: Crimson Tide.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stadium: Bryant-Denny (83,266, Tuscaloosa); Legion Field
(83,091, Birmingham).
</P>
<P>
   _ All-time record: 717-260-43.
</P>
<P>
   _ SEC Championships: 20 (1933, 1934, 1937, 1945, 1953, 1961,
1964, 1965, 1966, 1971, 1972, 1973, 1974, 1975, 1977, 1978, 1979,
1981, 1989, 1992)
</P>
<P>
   _ 1997 record: 4-7, 2-6 SEC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Schedule: Sept. 5 vs. BYU; Sept. 12 vs. Vanderbilt
(Birmingham); Sept. 26 at Arkansas; Oct. 3 vs. Florida; Oct. 10 vs.
Mississippi; Oct. 17 vs. East Carolina (Birmingham); Oct. 24 at
Tennessee; Oct. 31 vs. Southern Miss; Nov. 7 at LSU; Nov. 14 at
Mississippi State; Nov. 21 vs. Auburn (Birmingham).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
