<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR Notebook: Spencer taking time off after injuries
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Jimmy Spencer begins a two-week medical
absence today from the Winston Cup circuit because of recurring
headaches resulting from injuries suffered when he hit the wall two
weeks ago at Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still bothering me a little bit, but what helped me make
the decision was my family, my kids,'' Spencer said. ``My wife
didn't say anything either way, but my kids said, 'Daddy, maybe you
better heal up before you race again.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer is taking no chances, saying he's willing to sit out the
rest of the season if necessary, and his sponsor, Winston, has
assured him he has a ride next year even if he doesn't drive again
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, says Spencer, is in making decisions running lap
after lap. He found himself last week questioning simple decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation, I think your blood pressure goes us, the
heat in the car goes up, and I think everything starts to play on
your mind,'' Spencer said. ''' don't want to jeopardize any of my
competitors, and I sure don't want to jeopardize Travis (Carter)
and this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Laton improved
</P>
<P>
   Gary Laton has been upgraded from critical to fair condition
after his crash during Busch Grand National qualifying Thursday. He
was alert and orientated and was able to move his arms and legs and
talk to his family.
</P>
<P>
   Busch doings
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Grubb led second Busch qualifying with a speed of 176.289
mph. Buckshot Jones starts 35th on his qualifying effort of 174.474
mph. Provisionals went to Tim Fedewa, Ed Berrier, Shane Hall, Jeff
Grogh, Ashton Lewis, Blaise Alexander and Dave Rezendes.
</P>
<P>
   Purvis loses
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jeff Purvis should have kept his mouth shut after all.
NASCAR Commissioner Charles Stang upheld the fines and suspensions
imposed on Purvis, increasing the original fine from $5,000 to
$10,000, and upheld the four-race suspension and season-long
probation. The penalties were imposed against Purvis for an
altercation on pit road during the running of the Lycos 300 at
South Boston Speedway on July 25. His suspension began in
Indianapolis and will conclude in Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   Although Hendrick Motorsports drivers Jeff Gordon and Terry
Labonte have won the last three Winston Cup championships, neither
driver has won a Winston Cup race at Michigan. . . . The last five
Winston Cup champions have led in points after the 20th race of the
season. Jeff Gordon, winner of last week's Bud at the Glen, is the
'98 Winston Cup points leader after 20 races . . . . Rusty Wallace
celebrated his 42nd birthday Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
