<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURMA-STUDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT FROM N.H., FIVE OTHERS, RELEASED BY BURMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ Her brother is used to seeing her get
whatever she wants. Her mother is proud, but plans to ``have a talk
with her'' about the dangers of her global activism. Her father is
just amused that she is now ``a convicted seditionist.''
</P>
<P>
   Anjanette Hamilton was sentenced by a Burmese court to five
years hard labor Friday after handing out pro-democracy leaflets in
the Southeast Asian nation recently. But she and the five Americans
with her were deported instead, and are now en route to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old college student has long been driven to help the
less fortunate of the world, friends and family told the Globe. She
once raised $6,000 for an orphanage in India, where she spent a
year while in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't know her that well, she's really shy and quiet,
but she comes home and she's a real tiger,'' said her 18-year-old
brother, Matt. ``She gets whatever she wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, known as Angie, began her travel and humanitarian
activities with a high school exchange program in India. But her
goodheartedness goes back much further.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging in the Hamiltons' kitchen is a framed painting, in which
a wide-eyed child sits precariously on the edge of a hospital bed,
wrapped in a blanket emblazoned with the Red Cross symbol. Hamilton
painted the image as a school art project at the age of 12 or 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other kids just painted fruit bowls,'' said lifelong friend
Jessica Dominguez, 19, of York, Maine. ``She did people from other
cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, about to start her sophomore year at American
University in Washington, D.C., worked during school and all summer
to raise the money for her trip to Southeast Asia. She told her
family that she would be bringing medical supplies to refugee camps
in Thailand near the Burmese border.
</P>
<P>
   She did more than that, however. She and 17 companions from six
Asian and Western nations were detained for distributing leaflets
on the 10th anniversary of a national uprising against the Burmese
military regime, a movement that left 3,000 dead in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``She assured us that she had no intention of going to Burma,''
said her mother, Alison. ``Maybe it was an unplanned thing. Even if
it wasn't, she certainly wasn't going to tell us that.''
</P>
<P>
   Called a soft-spoken and intelligent young women, Hamilton had
never before worried her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few days, she's made up for all the years she
didn't give us any worry, which I will tell her when I see her,''
her mother said. ``We're not mad at her, but we'll have a lot of
talks after this incident.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton's Portsmouth home Friday buzzed with the excited
voices of friends celebrating Angie's imminent return. They spoke
in awe of her courage, humility, and commitment to international
relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   After a year spent in India, Hamilton organized students and ran
car washes, ultimately raising $6,000 for an Indian orphanage. Ever
modest, she did not even tell friends when she received a Rotary
Club honor for her efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really nonchalant, and even when she's in the paper you
don't hear about it from her,'' said friend Jordan Cocchiaro, 19,
of Portsmouth. ``This summer, she was just like, `Oh, by the way, I
bought a ticket to Thailand.'''
</P>
<P>
   According to her mother, Hamilton's belief in the power of the
individual was bolstered by her stay in Brazil last summer, where
she built latrines for families in a remote village.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just one little person, but she came home feeling she
really had made an impact,'' Alison Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   She also learned the flexibility necessary to live in the
developing world. A health enthusiast who jogs and previously kept
to a vegetarian diet, she began eating some meat in order not to
violate social customs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Brazil, her host father butchered a cow in the garage every
single week,'' her mother said. ``She learned to look out the
window and say, `There's the cow of the week.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's mother credits her daughter's global interests to
years of voracious reading. In elementary school, Hamilton had to
be pried away from her books and forced onto the playground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the books have opened up this whole world to her,''
her mother said. ``When you read about a far-off land, it comes
alive to you and you want to go see what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Though concerned about their daughter during the five-day
detention, Alison Hamilton, a sixth grade teacher, and husband
William Hamilton, a retired engineer, were comforted by word that
an embassy official had brought books to Angie in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said she was reading two books a day,'' the mother said.
``We knew that if she had books, she was at least happy.''
</P>
<P>
   At American, Hamilton is majoring in anthropology and
international development. It was there that she became involved
with a college group called the Free Burma Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Burma is widely considered to have one of the most repressive
regimes in the world under a military that has been in power since
1962. Most recently, Burma has been in the headlines because of the
government's standoff with pro-democracy leader and Nobel Peace
Prize winner Aung San Suu Kyi. Burma is refusing to allow her to
meet with other members of her party.
</P>
<P>
   While Portsmouth was celebrating Friday, the White House issued
a rebuke of Burma's treatment of the group of foreign activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``But while we're pleased that these American citizens will be
returning to the United States, this episode is a reminder that
there is an absence of protection of human rights in Burma and a
failure of the Burmese government to allow freedom of expression,''
said White House spokesman Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's friends expect her to return home as determined and
passionate as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably find her in another country in six months,''
said Dominguez. ``She has a passion for this, and she's such a
driven person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
