<SLUG> BC-MA-INMATES-DNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE BLOCKED FROM CATALOGUING IMATES' BLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KIEHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bucking a national trend allowing states to create DNA
databases of criminal offenders through blood samples, a
Massachusetts Superior Court judge ruled Friday that such a state
law is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Isaac Borenstein ruled that the purpose of the law _ to
identify possible suspects in crimes and deter repeat offenders _
did not outweigh the  &UR;  &LR; privacy citizens are guaranteed under the
Fourth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of the state's compelling interest, an unjustified
random bodily intrusion without any indication of individualized
suspicion is unreasonable and intolerable,'' Borenstein said in his
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The state said it would appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the decision reinforces is that police can't simply round
up all the usual suspects and require them to submit their DNA to a
databank,'' said the Committee for Public Counsel's Benjamin Keehn,
an attorney for the plaintiffs. ``If it's OK to grab prisoner's
DNA, then why isn't OK to grab the DNA of welfare recipients or
homeless people or any politcally vulnerable group? This really
does affect all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was brought by the American Civil Liberties Union of
Massachusetts and the Committee for Public Counsel on behalf of six
people in prison or on probation.
</P>
<P>
   While 47 other states have laws similar to the one in
Massachusetts, many of them have never been challenged or are
narrower in scope than the one Borenstein struck down, experts
said. Attorneys for the plaintiffs said they hope the ruling will
encourage challenges of the laws already in place in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts law, passed last September, required anyone
convicted of any of 33 crimes, or anyone in prison or on parole for
committing those crimes, to submit a blood sample that would be
used in a DNA database.
</P>
<P>
   The law went into effect in January and 1,200 samples were taken
before an injunction was issued against the collection. About
10,000 people would be affected by the law.
</P>
<P>
   The state argued that prisoners, through their criminal actions,
give up some of their rights, and the law was necessary as a public
safety measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people targeted don't have the same expectations of
privacy as law-abiding citizens have,'' said Assistant Attorney
General Gregory I. Massing. ``There is a tremendous chance that
(prisoners and parollees) will commit crimes in the future, and
this will help solve those crimes and deter them from committing
new crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The case turned on the Fourth Amendment, which prohibits
unreasonable searches and seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, there must be a strong suspicion that an
individual has committed a crime before subjecting that person to
submit a blood sample for DNA testing. But the state argued that
the intrusion of taking a blood sample was minimal and justified in
the interests of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein, however, ruled that to accept such an argument would
effectively turn the Fourth Amendment on its head.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was applauded by prisoners, parolees and their
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Dwight Harrison, who is on parole after serving 16 years for
an armed robbery and attempted murder in 1978, said the ruling
means he can finally try to live a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, 41, who lives in the Boston area, received a letter in
March informing him that he had to submit a blood sample for the
DNA database. Such a requirement, he said, represents an extension
of the sentence that he has already served.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel strongly that my time is done and I should be able to
be free and go on with my life,'' said Harrison, who was not a part
of the lawsuit, but did testify at a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Legal and genetic experts criticized the law as being too broad
in the crimes and people it covered and not specific enough in how
the DNA samples could be used.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed out that the law did not restrict the use of the
DNA samples to identification of crime suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The samples could be used for research or to create genetic
profiles of certain groups, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the law did not require the state to share DNA
information with the person it came from, said Paul Billings, who
is on the board of the Council for Responsible Genetics in
Cambridge, Mass.  &UR;  &LR; For example, it could mean the state would know
about &UR;  &LR; potential health problems, but not share that valuable
information with the person who gave the sample.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
