<SLUG> BC-MA-LIQUOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE 10-MILE LIQUOR SALE LAW RULED UNFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a ruling that could lead to Sunday liquor sales
across the state, a Superior Court judge ruled Friday that the law
allowing liquor stores in communities within 10 miles of the New
Hampshire border to open on Sundays is unfair to stores outside
that zone.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Margaret R. Hinkle ruled the state could not penalize an
Essex liquor store owner who opened his store on Sundays to
challenge the 10-mile law. His store was just outside the border
area. Hinkle said the Legislature's choice of a 10-mile cutoff was
arbitrary and therefore violated the due-process rights of
storeowners outside the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the lawsuit offered starkly different opinions
Friday on the impact of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing this decision does is make the rules that allow
stores in the 10-mile towns to open on Sundays applicable
statewide, as it should be,'' said Evan T. Lawson, the Boston
lawyer who represented package store owners fighting the law.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman for the state Alcoholic Beverages Control
Commission, which enforces state liquor laws, said the agency
interpreted the judge's ruling to mean all liquor stores in
Massachusetts must now close on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman, Kim Hinden, said the state would file a motion
next week asking the judge to clarify her ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she said all liquor stores in the state should
continue operating under the existing rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are within 10 miles and have a permit you should
sell,'' she said. ``If not, you shouldn't do it until we seek
clarification.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the ban on Sunday sales outside the 10-mile area is
lifted, store owners must also receive permission from local
licensing authorities before they can sell liquor on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts first allowed Sunday sales in border towns in 1990
in response to competition from state-owned stores in neighboring
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Chisholm, the owner of Chebacco Liquor Mart in Essex, said
the law discriminated against package store owners just outside the
10-mile area.
</P>
<P>
   For nine months in 1996 he opened his store on Sundays and
flouted the law. His plan, made in concert with other store owners
who called themselves the New Border Coalition, was to challenge
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the ABCC caught up with Chisholm and ordered a
30-day suspension for violating the Sunday law. Chisholm responded
with a lawsuit, calling the law unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm pointed to the neighboring town of Ipswich to make his
point that the law was fundamentally unfair. A small uninhabited
swath of beachland and marshes in Ipswich is within 10 miles of the
New Hampshire border, allowing liquor stores in that town to stay
open on Sunday even though the stores themselves are not within 10
miles of the border.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Chisholm said, his store is roughly the same distance
from New Hampshire as at least one of the Ipswich stores.
</P>
<P>
   Hinkle appeared sympathetic to that argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is...whether a store may sell on Sundays is only
tangentially related to its proximity to the border,'' she wrote in
her 16-page decision.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office, which represented the state in
the lawsuit, argued it was within the Legislature's authority to
create a border area where Sunday sales are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Lawson said the ruling would allow Chisholm to open this Sunday,
but he advised his client to await clarification from the judge
before selling liquor on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibiting Sunday liquor sales is based on the belief
that the day should be ``a uniform day of rest and relaxation,''
according to the ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
