<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMAC-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      08-14 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMAC-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
iMAC IS EASILY THE MOST STYLISH COMPUTER AROUND 
 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON_ Crack open the box that cradles a brand new iMac from
Apple Computer, set the one-piece system on a desk and sit back to
wait for the comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow! Is that one of those new Apples?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool. What is it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That thing looks like a demented bowling ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that packing material, or is that stuff what it's really
made of?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is that thing on the back? It looks like something you'd
see on a six-pack of beer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um ... can I have it?''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it, the translucent turquoise-and-white iMac
draws a reaction. But the big question is whether that reaction
will translate into sales when the highly anticipated _ and highly
hyped _ consumer Macintosh goes on sale starting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For Cupertino, Calif.-based Apple, the company that arguably
launched the personal computer revolution, the success of the iMac
is directly related to the survival of the company.
</P>
<P>
   For Apple, the iMac is the equivalent of the K-car, the boxy,
inexpensive automobile that Chrysler hoped would pull it back from
the financial abyss in the early 1980s. The K-car ultimately saved
Chrysler, and Apple is counting on the iMac to do the same for it.
</P>
<P>
   But while the K-car was an ugly, functional machine, the iMac is
easily the most stylish computer available. At the very least,
Apple will get high marks for its radical departure in PC design.
It puts to shame all those beige boxes now sitting on store
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac is aimed at consumers, a market Apple has not actively
courted in two years. It will sell initially for $1,299 _ slightly
more than low-priced consumer machines that use the competing
Microsoft Windows 98 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Apple says it has received 150,000 pre-orders. Depending on
who's doing the speculating, estimated sales for the iMac range
between 500,000 and 800,000.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half ago, Apple was bleeding red ink. Interim chief
executive Steven Jobs has turned that around, and the company has
become profitable again. Its shares have soared, going in the
opposite direction of the retreating stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Although Apple has had several quarters of profits, those have
largely come because costs have been slashed and competition has
evaporated. Under Jobs' direction, Apple forced several
manufacturers to stop making Macintosh clones. Now Apple has the
business all to itself _ but it's not much business. Some analysts
estimate Apple's market share has dropped to around 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Apple needs the iMac to be a hit. And a ``hit,'' in this case,
means it must sell to more than just the notoriously devoted Mac
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will clearly get the Mac-heads excited,'' said Tim Bajarin,
an analyst with the San Jose, Calif.-based Creative Strategies.
``While we believe the iMac will help Apple's fortunes in the short
term, it will buy them some time to deal with their problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for Apple to be around three to five years from now, they
must find a way to grow the company. That's why they are launching
a $100 million ad campaign _ the heart of it is to get the
attention of the new user.``
</P>
<P>
   Apple is entering a different consumer market from the one it
left in 1996. Analysts estimate that as many as 50 percent of all
home PCs sold now are under $1,000. There are complete systems
available _ monitor, CPU and printer _ for under $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's the least expensive Macintosh, it is far from
underpowered. It comes with a 233-megahertz PowerPC G3 chip, a
speedy processor that Apple claims is much faster then Intel
Corp.'s Pentium and Pentium II equivalents.
</P>
<P>
   It also has 32 megabytes of memory, a 4-gigabyte hard drive, a
56K modem and a built-in 15-inch color monitor.
</P>
<P>
   It's packed into a wedge-shaped, see-through case that looks
like a 1960s-era portable TV. Apple has paid close attention to
this look _ the mouse, the keyboard and even the power cable are
translucent.
</P>
<P>
   Apple brags about the speed of the PowerPC G3 chip _ its press
materials describe it as ``Pentium-toasting.'' But running it
side-by-side with a 300-megahertz Pentium II Toshiba Equium 100,
the iMac doesn't open applications, or switch between them, any
faster. Apple's claims are based on running programs that require
intense computations, not necessarily the way consumers use a
computer day to day.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the iMac's slick design gets in the way of its
usefulness. The computer's mouse, for example, is perfectly round
and smaller than most other mice. It looks cool, with the internal,
two-color ball that is visible through its clear plastic. But it's
too small to be comfortable, and the round shape makes it easy to
lose the mouse's orientation _ in other words, which way is ``up.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``i'' in iMac stands for Internet, and Apple is touting this
as a particularly easy way to get online. When an iMac owner starts
the computer for the first time, an Internet Setup Assistant walks
him or her through the process, then volunteers to make a dial-up
connection to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the fact that the iMac does not come with
a floppy disk, a staple on all other personal computers. Apple's
Jobs has said that floppies are on the way out, and the iMac is
here to help hurry their demise.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also been left out to cut costs. Floppy drives on a
Macintosh include a motor that ejects the floppy disk, and thus
they cost more to make than the drives found on Windows-based
systems, which have a mechanical ejection system.
</P>
<P>
   External disk drives _ ranging from traditional floppy drives
that hold 1.44 megabytes of data to those that hold over 100
megabytes _ will be available, but they will be pricey, costing
between $80 and $120.
</P>
<P>
   Although the iMac is expected to sell well, Apple's showdown
will come after initial wave of buyers has come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   That's when first-time buyers walk into a computer store and
spot the iMac on the shelf, next to Compaq Presarios, IBM Aptivas,
Hewlett-Packard Pavilions and Packard Bell Legend Supremes.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's worst nightmare will be if those new-to-computing
shoppers stop to admire the iMac _ oohing-and-ahing over its slick
design and clicking around its easy-to-use interface _ and then
take home a Windows machine.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Apple made have made a neat product that sold
well to the faithful, but it will have gained nothing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1955EDT &QL; 
