<SLUG> BC-MA-TICK-DEATHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FROM BAY STATE ISLANDS DIE OF TICK-BORNE DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State public health officials are using two recent
deaths from babesiosis, a tick-borne disease with malaria-like
symptoms, to remind people to use caution around ticks.
</P>
<P>
   The fatal infections were the first in Massachusetts caused by
the illness in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death is a very rare event with babesiosis,'' said Bela
Matyas, director of epidemiology for the state department of public
health. ``There's no evidence that the number of cases or their
virulence have increased.''
</P>
<P>
   A 67-year-old man from Martha's Vineyard died on Sunday and a
39-year-old from Nantucket died on Aug. 3 after they contracted the
illness last month.
</P>
<P>
   People at greatest risk for serious infections of babesiosis are
those who have had spleens removed, have compromised immune systems
from conditions like HIV, or are over the age of 50, said Dr. Peter
Krause of the Connecticut Children's Medical Center in Hartford,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Pachico was 67 and Phil Bresten, 39, had had a spleen
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Babesiosis has primarily been contained in southeastern
Connecticut, Block Island, Nantucket, Martha's Vineyard and eastern
Long Island, Krause said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that people who have been in areas where ticks abound
should watch for symptoms that last more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have either a persistent fever or become pretty ill
after a tick bite, you should be checked,'' said Krause who
published an article about the disease in a recent issue of the New
England Journal of Medicine. Symptoms also include chills, fatigue,
and headaches, sometimes followed by profuse sweating and muscle
pain.
</P>
<P>
   The illness is detected through blood tests, and treated with
quinine and the antibiotic clindamycin.
</P>
<P>
   A protozoan parasite in the tick causes the disease by invading
red blood cells. In rare cases, it has been transmitted through
blood transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 21 cases were reported in the state, Matyas said. In
1998, from May through Friday, 11 cases have been reported. Last
year 17 cases were reported May through August.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent infection, Matyas advised that people stick to paths
when walking through thick woods, wear long pants tucked into
socks, and check the body regularly for ticks since infection
occurs when ticks remain attached for 24 to 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lyme disease, which is also carried by ticks and produces
fever and fatigue, babesiosis is increasing with a growing deer
population, Krause said. He predicted that babesiosis diagnoses
would increase because of a greater awareness among doctors and
more laboratories carrying tests for it.
</P>
<P>
   Lyme disease, however, is more prevalent and poses a greater
public health threat, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
