<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4937 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AVENGER-REVIEW-LADN     08-14 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVENGER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AVENGERS' MAY DRIVE TV SERIES FANS TO REVENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 1 Star 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Since Warner Bros. does not want me to draw any
comparisons between their feature version of ``The Avengers'' and
the 1960s British television series (which was the official reason
the film wasn't screened for critics prior to its release Friday),
I will save all such observations until the end of this review.
</P>
<P>
   That out of the way, let me say that ``The Avengers'' is quite
horrible all on its own merits. It is dull, incomprehensible and
completely absent of wit and fun. As I was leaving the theater, a
couple who had paid for a later showing were demanding their money
back. And as far as I know, their dissatisfaction didn't come from
any nostalgic fondness for the original John Steed and Emma Peel.
They simply knew a turkey when they saw one.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is so amazingly bad on so many different levels,
primarily because its director, Jeremiah Chechik (``National
Lampoon's Christmas Vacation,'' ``Benny &AMP; Joon'') has absolutely no
business being behind a $60 million special-effects film rooted in
arch British humor.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a script that makes the ``Batman'' movies (more of
an inspiration here than the TV series) look like Tolstoy and lead
actors (a completely miscast Ralph Fiennes and Uma Thurman) who
have no on-screen chemistry. When they kiss, they're like a couple
of androids on Valium. Sure, we've heard of British reserve. But if
these characters were any more restrained, you'd begin to suspect
they had been lobotomized.
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes plays John Steed, the British agent in the bowler hat,
and Thurman is Emma Peel, the British agent in tight, form-fitting
designer garb. We mention the clothes so prominently because they
have more personality than anything else in the film. Steed and
Peel are battling Sean Connery's villain, a cipher intent on
controlling the weather for reasons he keeps to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Connery is barely a presence here, and when he shows up, he's
reduced to uttering claptrap like: ``You will buy your weather from
me, and by God, you'll pay for it!'' It's obvious Connery knows
he's in a stinker as his mind seems to be elsewhere whenever he's
on screen. Maybe he's counting his paycheck or thinking of new ways
to fire his agent.
</P>
<P>
   If you've seen the TV show, you know what a wasted opportunity
this ``Avengers'' is. But you can't get blood from a stone or wit
from filmmakers who confuse vacant blank stares with whimsy. Way
back when, series actors Patrick Macnee and Diana Rigg were a
triumph of irresistible style over substance as Steed and Peel.
Here, style and substance take a beating. And it's a bloody awful
one at that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 1956EDT &QL; 
