<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rover won't be easy to come by at this weekend's Reds game
 &HT;    By Jenn Hildreth
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ All it takes to get one of the 15,000 Rover
beanie babies at the Reds game against the Montreal Expos this
Sunday is a ticket and a wristband.
</P>
<P>
   And, to the chagrin of many adults, you have to be 14 years old
or younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids get the wristbands and kids get the beanie babies,'' said
Cal Levy, Reds marketing consultant. Adults are already complaining
about the age limit for the Reds first beanie baby promotion, but
Levy said the team has many other promotions which are also just
for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Rover, a red dog beanie baby retired on May 1, has an estimated
value of $15-$30, and it is expected to reach $40 by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Wristbands for the toys will be distributed starting at 9 a.m.
Sunday at gates 3 and 11 only, and all gates will open at 11:15 for
the 1:15 game.
</P>
<P>
   This season, beanie babies have proven successful in raising
attendance for many teams, including the Chicago Cubs, New York
Yankees, Detroit Tigers, and Texas Rangers. The Tigers game on Aug.
8 used ``Stripes'' (a tiger beanie baby) to more than double their
regular season attendance average.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said the Reds have not seen a significant jump in ticket
sales yet, but he said they are hoping for a last-minute surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good chance that you can wait and buy your ticket
that day (and still get a beanie baby),'' said Levy, pointing out
that the likelihood is not great that 15,000 kids 14 and under have
already bought tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Jenn Hildreth writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
