<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE, NEWS MEDIA FILE BRIEFS FOR ACCESS IN MICROSOFT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for the news media Friday accused Microsoft
of seeking to rewrite an act of Congress in the company's effort to
block public access to pre-trial testimony of company CEO Bill
Gates and others.
</P>
<P>
   The company first wanted to ``proceed with secret depositions in
contravention of the statute,'' and now is arguing that the law
allowing access to depositions ``does not mean what it plainly
says,'' the lawyers argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's effort to rewrite an Act of Congress is without
merit,'' said the lawyers, representing the New York Times Co., the
Seattle Times, ZDTV, ZDNet, Bloomberg News and Reuters America Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The media lawyers were supported Friday by lawyers for the
federal government and for 20 states and the District of Columbia
in three separate briefs urging a federal appellate panel to uphold
a lower court ruling allowing public access to the remaining 25
depositions in the Microsoft case.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is expected to reply on Monday, reiterating its desire
to keep the depositions closed, and the appeals panel could rule
shortly after that.
</P>
<P>
   The depositions are to be taken in cases filed by the federal
and state governments accusing Microsoft of violating the nation's
anti-trust laws to win a monopoly in the market for Internet
browsers. The company denies any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The news media have demanded access to the remaining
depositions, citing a little-known 1913 statute that guarantees
public access to the taking of evidence in civil anti-trust suits
brought by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Justice Department recommended to Congress last
year that the law be repealed. But Congress did not act on the
recommendation, and now the Justice Department says the law must be
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's reading of the Publicity in Taking Evidence Act
cannot withstand even casual scrutiny,'' the Justice Department
argued in its brief Friday. ``The language is absolutely clear and
unambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said it is now engaged in negotiations
with Microsoft to avoid the release of confidential information
during a public deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The wrangling over depositions has delayed preparations for the
case. Gates was scheduled to be deposed last Wednesday, but the
deposition was postponed while the debate over access is waged.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the delay, lawyers for the federal and state
governments and Microsoft on Thursday urged U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson to delay the trial by two weeks from its
scheduled start date of Sept. 8. The judge has not yet decided
whether to accept that proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
