<HEADER>
A4947 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLOON-FOSSETT-ART-5     08-14 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLOON-FOSSETT-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLOONIST NEAR HALF-WAY POINT IN ROUND-THE-WORLD FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guided by a team of meteorologists, balloonist Steve Fossett
threaded his way through an ``atmospheric minefield'' Friday and
approached the west coast of Australia, completing nearly half of
his attempted round-the-world flight.
</P>
<P>
   Fossett was expected to reach Australia late Saturday. The
54-year-old commodities broker and adventurer seemed certain to
break the ballooning distance record he set in 1997, when he flew
10,360.6 miles from St. Louis to Nonkhar, India.
</P>
<P>
   On this, his fourth attempt to circle the world nonstop, Fossett
is again flying solo in an unpressurized capsule.
</P>
<P>
   Although pitfalls lie ahead over Australia and the vast expanse
of the Pacific Ocean beyond, hopes for a successful completion of
the transglobal flight were rising.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his first full week of flight Friday, which began
in Mendoza, Argentina, Fossett still faced daunting problems as he
sought to be the first balloonist to circumnavigate the earth. But
by almost continuously changing altitude, his big Solo Spirit
balloon escaped a succession of wayward winds that could have
carried him southward toward Antarctica or northwestward over the
Indian Ocean. Either course would have doomed his flight.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rice, the leader of Fossett's meteorology team in his
mission control headquarters at Washington University in St. Louis,
particularly feared the northwestward winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have injected Steve into a high-pressure,
counterclockwise circulation pattern, going nowhere,'' Rice said.
``For a balloonist, that would be like getting stuck in a giant
parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to steer a balloon, except by climbing or
descending into winds headed in the right direction; globally, that
direction is generally from west to east. To exploit high-speed
winds that blow under the jet streams, Fossett has been flying as
high as possible, and in his unpressurized capsule he must breathe
oxygen almost continuously.
</P>
<P>
   The first big problem arose Wednesday when a southward wind
current cut across Fossett's track just east of the southern tip of
Africa. On Rice's advice, Fossett descended to 20,000 feet and
managed to squeak past the danger. But a still greater hazard came
Thursday at another crossroad in the sky. A strong wind began
nudging Fossett ever farther northward, toward the ``parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   As an emergency measure, Rice asked Fossett to climb to about
29,000 feet _ the height of Mount Everest. Even at that altitude,
the balloon was only 7,000 feet higher than the northward current
that had to be avoided. As tension mounted and the hours passed,
the team waited to see if the maneuver had worked. There was little
sleep for Fossett or his ground crew.
</P>
<P>
   But by early Friday, the crisis seemed to be past. Fossett was
told he would have to remain at 28,000 feet or higher to stay out
of trouble; meanwhile, however, the balloon had changed its course
due east toward Australia, as planned. The maneuver had succeeded.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fossett's team, with which he communicates by e-mail, using a
lap-top computer and the Satcom-C satellite, believes he now stands
a fair chance of completing the rest of the trip, although any
delays caused by failing winds could deplete his supply of propane
fuel and force him down in the vast South Pacific, far from any
shipping lane. He is consuming a lot of oxygen, and if his supply
runs short he will have to descend into much less favorable wind
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Without the technological progress of the last 20 years, Rice
said, it would not have been possible to get this far. Twenty years
ago last Tuesday, Rice was acting as the meteorologist for the
Double Eagle II as it completed the first balloon crossing of the
Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, you just plotted your course with a pair of
dividers and off you went,'' Rice said. ``But today we have Global
Positioning Satellite tracking, we have a great communications
satellite, and we have these wonderful atmospheric models from the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration that allow us to
calculate precisely where to look for the winds we need.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, scientists have tried to improve climate
forecasting with the help of powerful computers, using programs
that combine data from many different places. These programs, or
models, take into account fine details of air pressure,
temperature, moisture, wind speeds, altitudes and directions.
</P>
<P>
   A forecaster must gather as many data as possible from
satellites, aircraft and sensors on the ground and the sea to fill
in the blanks in a model, which then computes probable conditions
at any specific place and time. Such modeling, although still very
imperfect, is essential for weather forecasting and for tracking
storms, smoke from volcanoes, dust from desert storms, fallout from
nuclear explosions and balloon flights.
</P>
<P>
   If Fossett succeeds in circling the world, he will win the
Budweiswer Cup and a $1 million prize offered by Anheuser-Busch
Cos. Half of the prize will be donated to charity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
