<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDERMOTT-BOEHNER-SPI     08-14 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDERMOTT-BOEHNER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN APPEALS DISMISSAL OF LAWSUIT AGAINST COLLEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican Conference Chairman John Boehner
Friday appealed a judge's dismissal of his lawsuit against Rep. Jim
McDermott, saying that the ruling, if allowed to stand, would
undermine the security of electronic communications throughout the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Boehner, R-Ohio, said that, in deciding to appeal, he relied on
advice from three House Republicans with expertise in law
enforcement, each of whom suggested he attempt to revive his
lawsuit. In the lawsuit, Boehner accuses McDermott, a Seattle
Democrat, of violating electronic communications privacy laws by
allegedly leaking to newspapers a recording of a phone conversation
in which Boehner was a participant.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Hogan threw out Boehner's lawsuit
last month, saying that McDermott's alleged actions were protected
by the First Amendment to the Constitution. McDermott has declined
to say what role he played in leaking the conversation among House
GOP leaders, a report of which wound up on the front page of The
New York Times. The leaders were discussing how to react to House
Speaker Newt Gingrich's ethics woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The breakdown in civility and bipartisanship in Congress sunk
to new lows in January 1997, when it became clear that the ranking
minority member of the House Ethics Committee (McDermott) had
played a direct, unethical, and illegal role in a plot to topple
the duly-elected Speaker of the House,'' Boehner said in a letter
to his House GOP colleagues. ``The purpose of my civil suit against
Representative McDermott has been, and will continue to be, to send
a clear and unambiguous message to those who might one day follow
his example: no American should be permitted to violate the law in
pursuit of a political goal.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott's lawyer, Frank Cicero, said he was not surprised that
Boehner decided to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe Judge Hogan was correct, and properly applied the
law in his ruling,'' Cicero said. ``Because we believe he was
correct, we believe the decision will be upheld on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehner Friday released letters from three House Republicans,
including House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
Rep. Deborah Pryce, R-Ohio, a former state judge, and Rep. Michael
Oxley, R-Ohio, a former FBI special agent.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said that he had asked his staff lawyers to review Hogan's
decision, and that ``without exception, each person independently
concluded that the ruling is susceptible to being overturned on
appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned with the court's conclusion that the wiretap
statute does not prevent a criminal from stealing a conversation
and giving it to someone else, who is then free to disseminate the
information with impunity,'' Hyde wrote. ``This certainly was not
the intent of the Congress in enacting the statute.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott's alleged actions are also under investigation by the
Justice Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
