<HEADLINE>
GLOBE, REPORTER FACE FINES FOR REFUSING TO REVEAL SOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A Superior Court judge Friday imposed fines on The
Boston Globe and medical reporter Richard A. Knox for violating a
court order seeking the names of confidential sources used in
articles that are the basis of a libel suit.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lois Ayash is suing Knox and The Globe, alleging she was
unfairly blamed for the drug overdose that caused the death of
Globe health columnist Betsy Lehman. Lehman died in 1994 after
being given an overdose of chemotherapy. Several months later, Knox
wrote an article that stated that Ayash had countersigned the
flawed medication order. The Globe later published a correction,
acknowledging that it erred in identifying Ayash as signing the
drug order. The article also called Ayash the ``leader of a team''
of doctors at the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute who treated Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   Ayash's libel suit says Knox and the newspaper caused injury to
her reputation. In related claims against Dana-Farber and David
Livingston, a former physician-in-chief at Dana-Farber, Ayash
contends that she was singled out when others at the hospital
should have been held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Ayash's attorney, Joan A. Lukey, said getting the names of
confidential sources used in the Knox series is vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is basically hamstrung in her ability to prepare her case
against all of the defendants without the confidential sources
being identified,'' Lukey said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, Suffolk County Superior Court Judge Peter M.
Lauriat said The Globe's refusal to comply with a Feb. 23 discovery
order constitutes a contempt of court. Lauriat ordered that
starting Aug. 24, Knox must pay the court $100 per day until he
names the sources. Each week thereafter, the fine increases an
additional $100 a day. The Globe will be fined $1,000 a day the
first week. Each week thereafter, the fine is increased an
additional $1,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Al Larkin, Globe vice president and assistant to the publisher,
called the fines ``onerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin said The Globe will appeal the decision and ask that the
fines be stayed until the appeal is decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as the Globe respects Judge Lauriat's admonition that
`no man is above the law' we also know what other courts have said:
reporters should not be forced to disclose the identities of their
confidential sources. Period. The right to protect those sources is
a crucial aspect of newsgathering and a fundamental element of the
First Amendment,'' Larkin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
