<TEXT>
<P>
   RECORD NUMBER OF PEOPLE WERE ON PROBATION OR PAROLE LAST YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Embargoed for release Monday, August 17
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Texas papers out; a separate version moved for Texas
papers
</P>
<P>
   EDS: STATE BY STATE BREAKDOWN IN SECOND GRAPH
</P>
<P>
   By DANIELLE SHOOK
</P>
<P>
   C.. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A record number of people, more than 3.9 million
adults _ one in 35 _were on probation or parole in 1997, according
to Justice Department statistics released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; BEGIN STATE INSERTS &QR;
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, more than 45,400 adults were on probation and more
than 4,000 were on parole, an increase of more than 25 percent over
the previous year. A study based on the statistics stated that the
parole population increase may have resulted from a state law
mandating a period of parole supervision for all persons sentenced
to prison for crimes committed on or after July 1, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, more than 230,000 adults were on probation and more
than 8,400 were on parole.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, more than 148,400 adults were on probation and more
than 21,900 were on parole.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, more than 105,000 adults were on probation
and more than 8,100 were on parole.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, more than 118,700 adults were on probation and more
than 6,800 were on parole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; END STATE INSERTS &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Over half of those on probation or parole nationally had felony
convictions; more than one-fourth were convicted of a misdemeanor,
and; more than 10 percent were on probation for driving while
intoxicated or under the influence of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder, more than 685,000 adults, were on parole, a
conditional supervised release following a prison term. Nearly all
had felony convictions. Half of the parolees had received a
mandatory release because of a sentencing statute or laws requiring
early release for good behavior. The others had their parole
approved by a parole board.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nationwide, women account for 21 percent of all probationers
and 11 percent of the parolees.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blacks represent more than a third of probationers and almost
half of the parolees.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hispanics represent 16 percent of probationers and 21 percent
of the parolees.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1.6 million probationers and 400,000 parolees were
discharged from supervision last year. More than 60 percent of
those exiting probation, and more than 40 percent of those exiting
parole, successfully met the conditions of their supervision.
</P>
<P>
   During the same year, 18 percent of probationers and 41 percent
of parolees who were discharged from supervision were jailed
because of a rule violation or new offense.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder unsuccessfully exited probation or parole for
variety or reasons including death.
</P>
<P>
   EDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
