<SLUG> BC-BULGER-CONDO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SEIZES FUGITIVE GANGSTER'S CONDO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The FBI and federal prosecutors may not know where fugitive
Massachusetts gangster James ``Whitey'' Bulger is keeping himself
these days but they now can be sure he's not hiding out at his
condominium in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The $160,000 condo in Clearwater is now the official property of
the federal government, which took legal steps last spring to seize
it because they said Bulger bought the condo as part of a
money-laundering scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The forfeiture, which became final when Bulger didn't respond to
legal ads placed in newspapers in Clearwater and Boston or to
notices sent to his last known address in South Boston, was
approved by a federal judge late last month. On Thursday, sealed
court affidavits in the case were opened, according to the US
Attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger, the South Boston crime boss and longtime FBI informant,
fled before he, his criminal partner Stephen Flemmi, and various
Mafia associates were indicted on federal extortion and
racketeering charges in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, who was also an FBI informant, said in court papers that
he and Bulger were tipped off to the upcoming indictment so they
could flee.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government now owns Unit 216, Bayside Gardens II, at
the Sand Key Condominium in Clearwater. In the civil suit seeking
forfeiture of the property, federal prosecutors said the money used
to buy the condo in April 1993 came from a joint checking account
held by Bulger and his brother, John.
</P>
<P>
   But all the money in the account had been deposited by Bulger or
by others on his account, according to the US Attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   The money came from two sources, according to prosecutors:
Bulger's proceeds from a still-disputed winning Mass Millions
lottery ticket, as well as the $360,000 profit he made in December
1989 in a real-estate ``flip'' involving the same-day purchase and
sale of the South Boston Liquor Mart, reportedly his criminal
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger's sister, Jean Holland, is still fighting a court
decision in January 1996 which forfeited Bulger's $1.9 million
share of the winning lottery ticket to the government.
</P>
<P>
   And his brother, John, is appealing the dismissal in May of his
claim to nearly $200,000 seized in November 1996 from a
safe-deposit box and two bank accounts he held jointly with his
brother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
