<HEADER>
A4963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEST-BANK-WATER-ART-5     08-14 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-BANK-WATER-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER DIVIDES HAVES FROM HAVE-NOTS IN WEST BANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(js) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEBRON, West Bank _ In the unrelenting heat of what has been an
unforgiving summer, water should spell relief.
</P>
<P>
   But in this city of 200,000, most taps ran dry a month ago, just
as record temperatures took hold, soaring day after day to nearly
100 degrees. That would have spelled misery anywhere, but what has
made it worse on the West Bank is that Palestinians cannot help but
notice that they are the only ones so parched.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sign of a water shortage in the Jewish settlements
just outside Hebron. There and in Israel as a whole, residents
still water lawns and wash their cars. Yet most water for the
Palestinians still flows through Israeli pipes, and by the time it
gets to cities like Hebron these days, there is barely a trickle
left.
</P>
<P>
   It was only 18 months ago that the Palestinians celebrated an
agreement that brought Hebron under their control, making it the
last of seven West Bank cities to come under Palestinian self-rule.
This summer, with cisterns empty, showers a luxury and fresh
laundry a distant dream, many are learning basic lessons about the
limitations of an incomplete peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't clean; we don't wash our clothes; we don't use the
water for anything but drinking,'' said Jibrin Kaffrawi, a
32-year-old electrician, who had embarked with his wife and seven
children on a quest for water at almost any price. ``But still
there is not enough to go around, because it is all in the hands of
the Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel still controls nearly all the water resources in the West
Bank, including three enormous aquifers, just as it did during
years of direct rule when it occupied all of the territory. Simply
to dig a new well is prohibited unless a Palestinian can first
negotiate a host of political and technical restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which the Palestinians will acquire water rights
is supposed to be part of a final peace settlement. Until then,
access to most fresh water is governed by a 1995 agreement that
requires Israel to make available a fixed amount of water _
slightly over 1 billion cubic feet a year _ to meet the
Palestinians' ``immediate needs.''
</P>
<P>
   That arrangement leaves big gaps. It provides the average
Palestinian less than one-third as much water as the average
Israeli _ and less than half of what Palestinian experts say the
people need. And it does nothing to prevent those gaps from growing
wider in the heat of summer, as Israeli authorities juggle the flow
in order to meet their own customers' surging demands.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a heat wave that has made this the hottest summer in
more than three decades in the Middle East, and the effect is
stark.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a city in suffering,'' said Emad Azir, the water
commissioner in Hebron, the hardest hit of the Palestinian cities.
It has imposed a rationing system permitting households running
water no more than once every 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, Azir said, is that the amount of water Israel
supplies to Hebron has declined to its lowest level in memory _
about 176,500 cubic feet a day, less than half the supply during
the rainy months of winter.
</P>
<P>
   On the rare occasions when the supply is turned on, every spigot
is opened wide, in order to replenish every vessel within reach.
Other times, there is little option but to forage, either at a
nearby spring, where the water is of dubious quality, or by paying
an exorbitant price to a well-connected merchant able to arrange a
private delivery.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even those who are relatively well off say the shortage has
forced an uncomfortable change in their summertime habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your whole life style changes,'' said Hamza Aweiwi, 26, a shoe
salesman and newlywed who said that he and his wife had not had
running water since their wedding July 17. ``I've bought new tanks
for the roof, and paid a lot to fill them, but I can only dream of
the days when I used to take two showers.''
</P>
<P>
   As in most matters that divide Israelis and Palestinians, each
side blames the other.
</P>
<P>
   Meir Ben Meir, Israel's water commissioner, contended in an
interview that Israel is providing 15 percent more water to the
Palestinians than required under the 1995 accord. If Palestinians
need more water, Ben Meir said, the solution is not to take it away
from the Israelis, but for the Palestinians to exploit new sources,
such as desalinization.
</P>
<P>
   But Fadel Kawash, the Palestinian water commissioner for the
West Bank, accused Israel of failing to carry out promises to
increase some water allocations, and of dragging its feet on
Palestinian requests to dig exploratory wells, which he said were
more economical than desalinization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason for this water is the Israelis,'' Kawash said.
``A drop of water is the basis for living, and without it there can
be no development and no peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
