<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SCALP-SETTLEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL, 9, WINS $7.5 MILLION FOR AMUSEMENT RIDE INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In one of the nation's largest settlements for a case of its
kind, &UR;  &LR; a 9-year-old girl won an agreement Friday that will pay $7.5
million during her lifetime for scalp injuries suffered on a
children's amusement ride.
</P>
<P>
   The out-of-court settlement means that Danielle Foti, a
fifth-grader from East Bridgewater, Mass., ``will be well taken
care of for the rest of her life,'' said her mother, Karen Foti,
40. She described the family as thrilled by the agreement with
Bonkers 19, the now-defunct company that ran the indoor amusement
park, and Zamperla Inc., which purchased and distributed the
Mini-Himalaya ride that caused Danielle's injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping that some owners of these rides will look at the
size of the settlement and say, `Maybe these rides aren't as safe
as they should be, and maybe we should spend a few dollars to make
them safer,''' Foti said. ``We don't want anyone to go through the
hell we've been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jerry Ellis, president of the Building 19 company that
owned Bonkers 19, nor Paul White, the company's lawyer, could be
reached Friday.
</P>
<P>
   David Daly, a lawyer with the firm of Daly, Kehoe &AMP; Crosson,
which represented Zamperla Inc., did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 14, 1996, Danielle and a girlfriend, Valentina
Espinola, strapped themselves into the 14-car sled ride at the
little Bonkers 19 amusement park in Weymouth, Mass. They were
celebrating their 8th birthdays together.
</P>
<P>
   But while her mother looked on in horror, Danielle's long brown
hair caught in the motor behind her seat. ``It pulled her head
through the fiberglass seat and into the motor, which continued to
grind and tore her scalp off the right side of her head,'' said the
Fotis's lawyer, John Dalimonte, with the Boston firm of Karon &AMP;
Dalimonte.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until Espinola stood up in the moving car and
screamed for help that operators finally stopped the ride,
Dalimonte said. ``Danielle's friend was a brave little girl,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonkers 19 closed as a result of the bad publicity that followed
the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Now after four surgeries and twelve 12 saline injections to
expand what remains of her scalp, Danielle is doing as well as can
be expected, her mother said. She still is a straight-A student who
likes math, horses, swings, bike riding, and collecting Beanie
Babies.
</P>
<P>
   But ``she's not half as outgoing as she used to be. She's much
less trusting of machinery _ and life,'' Foti said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl is self-conscious about a scar, about 10 inches long
and 3 inches wide, that goes from the front to the back of the
right side of her head. And although therapy has helped to ease the
trauma, she still has nightmares and painful memories.
</P>
<P>
   In one recurring memory, Dalimonte said, ``she's playing or
doing something fun, something a child would think would be safe,
like talking to a clown, when all of a sudden the clown turns into
a wolf that attacks her.'' Foti said, ``And she asks a lot of
questions about death now that never came up before.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement means that the family, and especially Danielle,
will not have to relive the tragedy in court. It also means
Danielle will receive the $7.5 million tax-free, including $30,000
annually during her college years to cover tuition costs and $5,000
a year for medical expenses every year of her life.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dalimonte, resolution of similar cases yielded
$1.25 million and $950,000, respectively, for women in Illinois and
Maryland, both of whom sustained scalp injuries when their hair
caught in drill presses.
</P>
<P>
   About three months before the Foti accident, another
Massachusetts child, 4-year-old Karley Logan, was injured on the
same Mini-Himalaya ride when her foot got caught beneath one of the
sled-like cars. A settlement in that case is being negotiated.
</P>
</TEXT>
