s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$A     08-14 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16)  
 (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG OIL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A British Amoco &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest foreign takeover ever of an American company,
British Petroleum announced that it would buy Amoco (the name once
stood for American Oil Company) for $48.2 billion, eclipsing
Daimler-Benz's $40.5 billion deal for Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, subject to regulatory and shareholder approval,
would create the world's third-largest multinational oil company in
net income, after Exxon and Royal Dutch/Shell. The combination is
expected to create a formidable competitor.
</P>
<P>
   B.P. is known for its skill at finding oil in the North Sea and
elsewhere around the world, while Amoco's strength is in refining
its products into oil and chemicals and distributing them to
consumers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELL ATLANTIC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Score One for Workers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Proclaiming victory, 73,000 members of the Communications
Workers of America ended a two-day strike and returned to work at
Bell Atlantic. The company, which serves telephone customers from
Maine to Virginia, agreed to guarantee job security to its union
workers _ even in digital technologies only now being developed.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in labor relations called it a significant union
victory. Kate Bronfenbrenner, director of labor education research
at Cornell University, said workers in other industries were likely
to be inspired by Bell Atlantic's agreement to phase out a nonunion
customer service operation in Virginia. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE RUSSIAN BEAR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mauling the Market &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given the way markets are performing in Moscow, Lenin's views on
capitalism might look prescient. The main stock market index has
plunged nearly 50 percent in four weeks, and the market was
temporarily closed on Thursday as sellers swamped buyers; it ended
the day with a loss of 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on short-term Russian bonds exceeded 300 percent. George
Soros, the international financier, called for sweeping financial
changes and a devaluation of the ruble by 15 percent to 25 percent,
a move the government has insisted it will not make.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Belarus, where the local money is known as the
zaichik, or bunny, the government will no longer accept its own
currency as payment for exports. The bunny has lost half its value
in five months. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Global Tremors &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No man is an island, as John Donne observed, and neither is any
market. Stocks were battered on Wall Street and in Western Europe
as investors _ particularly big institutional traders _ worried
about the worldwide effects on corporate earnings of Asia's
financial crises, the Japanese yen's tumble to an eight-year low
and Russia's ravaged markets. The Dow Jones industrial average
closed at 8,425.00, down 173.02 for the week, and with
small-company stocks hit even harder, the NASDAQ index ended at
1,790.19, down 56.58 points. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   GEOCITIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Going Public, Keeping Private &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investors clamored to buy the stock of Geocities, which gives
its two million members their own pages on the World Wide Web to
display pictures of their offspring, their pets or whatever strikes
their fancy _ a business on which it has not proved it can make
money.
</P>
<P>
   It went public on Tuesday at $17, and the shares more than
doubled that day to close at $37.3125. But two days later, the
company ran afoul of the Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the government's first Internet-privacy enforcement action,
the commission said Geocities had lied when it told subscribers,
both adults and children, that it would not disclose personal
information it collected from them.
</P>
<P>
   Settling the matter without admitting wrongdoing, Geocities
posted a new privacy statement explaining how it uses the
information it collects. The stock ended the week at $37.35. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE ECONOMY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GM Strikes Take a Toll &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The productivity of American workers fell in the second quarter
at an annual rate of 0.2 percent after surging at a rate of 3.5
percent in the first three months of the year. The drop, the first
in three years, was attributed to the effects of Asia's economic
crisis and to UAW strikes that virtually shut down General Motors
plants for up to two months.
</P>
<P>
   Those strikes also depressed retail sales, which the Commerce
Department said fell 0.4 percent in July. Excluding automobiles,
sales rose for the sixth time in seven months. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Ravaged Cotton Crop &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texans and Oklahomans like to refer to their part of the world
as God's country. After a 100-degree summer and drought that has
cracked the red clay soil, a visitor could be forgiven for thinking
its patronage resides elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the cotton crop has been burned up, and livestock has
been liquidated. Texas officials estimate that the drought will
cost farmers and ranchers $1.8 billion and will drain $4.9 billion
from the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Howard, Oklahoma's agriculture commissioner, said, ``The
ag dollar goes around Main Street six, seven, eight times, but it's
not going around now, because it's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the Agriculture Department said, the cotton crop
will be down 24 percent from last year. If there is a silver lining
for the two states, it is that their economies are far more
diversified and industrial than they were during the Dust Bowl of
the 1930s. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HMOs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mismanaged Care? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators reported that health maintenance
organizations have billed the government for administrative costs
related to their private customers, bringing them more than $1
billion a year in overpayments from the Medicare trust fund. ... In
New York, the State Insurance Department asked Oxford Health Plans
to increase its reserves for its New York plan by $152 million to
insure that it could pay claims over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported a loss of $507.6 million for the second
quarter. ... United Healthcare's $5.5 billion acquisition of its
rival, Humana, collapsed after the value of United's stock fell
$2.9 billion earlier this month. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lower Prices for '99 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor, the No. 2 auto maker, announced that it would cut
prices across the board for the first time in more than 30 years.
The decrease, which will affect 1999 model cars and trucks,
averages 0.3 percent, or about $61, from comparably equipped 1998
models. But the prices of Ford's highest-volume cars, the Ford
Taurus and Mercury Sable, will fall by $1,000 to $1,800. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIVENT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brouhaha on Broadway &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Creativity is a big asset to a Broadway producer _ but creative
accounting is not. Livent Inc., the producer of ``Ragtime'' and
``Show Boat,'' said an internal investigation had found serious
accounting problems involving millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The company, now led by Michael Ovitz, the former Hollywood
power broker, said its financial results would almost certainly
have to be restated, and after an emergency board meeting in
Toronto, it suspended Garth H. Drabinsky, the impresario who built
the company and serves as chief creative director. Two executives
said he kept two sets of books to conceal extravagant spending. He
denied it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
