<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4970 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-HORSE-FARMS-2TA     08-14 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-HORSE-FARMS-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STABLES FIT FOR A KING: SPLENDOR IN THE BLUEGRASS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ky., Calif.)   (af)  
 By SASHA CAVENDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERSAILLES, Ky. _ In the Bluegrass, in the heart of central
Kentucky, some horses live better than most people, in barns that
look like castles or cathedrals, with spires and cupolas,
stained-glass windows and garden sculpture, chandeliers and
hand-forged gates.
</P>
<P>
   From their straw-banked stalls, the horses have views of some of
the finest real estate in the world: rolling emerald hills etched
with Kentucky's famous four-board fences _ white or black _
following the landscape like reels of satin ribbons winding uphill
and down dale.
</P>
<P>
   At one farm alone, the views include swan ponds, fishing lakes
and 800 rose bushes. These estates seem like countries, not country
farms.
</P>
<P>
   Horses are to Kentucky what cars are to Detroit, or corn to Iowa
_ a multibillion-dollar business. The horses themselves are
captains of industry; some are worth tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stallions are arguably the single most valuable property the
farm has,'' said Eric Shaffer, the architect for Gainsborough Farm
here, which was named for the original in England and is owned by
Sheik Maktoum al-Maktoum, the eldest of four royal brothers of the
United Arab Emirates. Thus, he said, ``you want to show off the
horse in the best light and best setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Breeding top sires to top mares is where the money is. Fabulous
sums are paid for unknown risks: A stud fee of $100,000 to $200,000
(prices rise and fall, as in the stock market) may get a mare a
single mating with a legendary sire but will not always guarantee a
live foal.
</P>
<P>
   Called the sport of kings, horse racing is also the maker and
breaker of fortunes. Its devotees say that the passion for
thoroughbreds transcends mere financial considerations; still, it
devours money _ $500,000 here, $10 million there.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, prices scraped the sky at Keeneland's July
Sales in Lexington, the premier annual auction of horseflesh that
commands the attention of horse owners around the world. Yearlings
sold for as much as $13 million in international bidding among
Arab, British, American and Japanese buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Prime land sold for $10,000 an acre. Sales parties matched the
prices, with elephant rides, hot-air balloons, and dinners cooked
by Wolfgang Puck.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the market _ and its colossal prices _ fell. Tax laws
changed, hammering the industry. The circus animals and calliope
music faded. Banks called in loans; farms flooded the market. ``It
bottomed out in '91,'' said Joe Riddell, a Bluegrass horse-farm
broker. ``The same land sold for just $4,000 an acre. Now, it's
going up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even as Asia's financial crisis has diminished the
presence of Japanese bidders, new wealth from high-technology
entrepreneurs and the growing international horse business have
kept the Bluegrass busy.
</P>
<P>
   The top bid for a colt last month was $4 million _ the first
time in seven years that it had surpassed $2 million. And prime
land is now commanding $6,000 or more an acre, Riddell said, ``with
no structures, no fence.'' Serious horse farms range from 600 to
3,000 acres, with 1,200 the average.
</P>
<P>
   To Riddell, a former farm manager himself, ``the grandeur is up
to someone's ego; how deep is your pocket?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A stall is a stall,'' he added. ``How much does a horse care?
He's not going to be running in it; he just stands in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the stunning design details serve functional purposes.
Cupolas, for example, were originally put on barns for ventilation
and light; they create a chimney effect, pulling up air. The
fresher the air, the fewer the bacteria and the healthier the
horses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are business considerations, too. Dan Rosenberg, manager
of the Three Chimneys Farm, home of Seattle Slew, the Triple Crown
winner in 1977, said beauty was worth the investment _ ``to attract
prospective clients.''
</P>
<P>
   The farm's stallion barns are ``designed to be safe and healthy
for the horses and efficient from a labor standpoint,'' he said,
``but also to be a sales tool.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Here's where we're going to put the horse' says something to
the owner,'' Rosenberg said. ``To prospective breeders, it's
atmosphere, image and aura you're trying to promote.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen E. Paulson would agree. He is the founder of Gulfstream
Aerospace and a leading breeder of thoroughbreds, among them Cigar,
the two-time Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent more than $150 million on horses. ``I look at it
like digging oil wells,'' he said from his office in Del Mar,
Calif. ``If you dig just a few, forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has three Brookside farms _ in California, in Florida and in
Versailles (pronounced ver-SALES). His 1,400-acre farm here is one
of the area's prettiest, with 20 three-spired barns, painted snow
white with hydrangea blue trim. The main house was built in 1790;
Paulson supervised its renovation.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't stint on the stables, either, selecting crystal
chandeliers for all the barns. With three cupolas in each barn,
that's 60 chandeliers. At night, they light up the landscape. Asked
if the farm's design reflected his taste, Paulson said wryly, ``I
had some influence.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An exception to the owner-as-designer rule is Gainsborough,
perhaps the most lavish Bluegrass farm. It is a product of a
collaboration between the farm manager, Allen Kershaw, and Shaffer,
a Lexington architect. ``My marching orders,'' Kershaw said of
Sheik Maktoum's instructions, ``were to create a first-class
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I decided on the octagonal shape, everything followed
from that,'' Shaffer said. Eight-sided cupolas show off
stained-glass windows with Gainsborough's jockey silks of royal
blue. Geometry is everywhere, from stall windows to fountains to
footpaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``At night, the barns almost glow,'' he said. ``With the lights
reflecting off the lake, the cupolas and windows are
transformed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kershaw, a former architecture student, said beauty was fine but
that function came first: Farms need healthy horses. ``You don't
turn the horses off like the fax machine when you go home; they're
a constant responsibility, 24 hours a day,'' he said. ``We make the
surroundings detail-oriented so the grooms and managers are into
it, and so injuries and sickness in the horses don't get missed.''
</P>
<P>
   As for costs, Kershaw said, ``the expensive part is what you
don't see _ the infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We use water from our own lake and wells, the roads,
electricity all hidden underground; security, fire safety,'' he
added. ``I have people I send to water school.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainsborough visitors seem to love it all: the waterfalls, the
sky-lit barns of sculpted wood, the no-expense-spared details.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful barns ripple across the Bluegrass hills. Gainesway's
magnificence evokes Tuscany, Hill 'N Dale's brick courtyard looks
like a grand English country estate, and the cavernous stone barns
at Ashford Stud are the work of 21 stonemasons. No wonder visitors
might want to swap places with the horses.
</P>
<P>
   Riddell recalled how expenses rose past $920,000 for a barn at
the Adena Springs farm. He told Frank Stronach, the owner, that of
the costs, ``$120,000 is for the horses, the rest is for you.'' The
cedar-and-stone barn had been Stronach's dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `That's fine. Let's build it,' '' Riddell said. So
they did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
