<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PGA NOTEBOOK: Andrade continues on-again, off-again play
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Barely in the Pacific Northwest for 24 hours
Thursday after securing a spot as the eighth alternate, Billy
Andrade birdied the first four holes at Sahalee Country Club and
registered a surprising 68, tying for second place.
</P>
<P>
   So much for happy hour.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the Atlanta resident returned to the spottier play that
has typified a frustrating season. He required 77 shots to tour
Sahalee in the second round and finished dangerously close to the
cut line.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as it catching up with me, I don't think it was that at
all,'' Andrade said. ''I think that's bull. I just didn't play that
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Putts that found the hole Thursday weren't cooperating Friday. A
four-footer for birdie that would have settled Andrade to 1-over
for the tournament missed at the 15th. An hour later, Andrade had
lost three shots to par with a double-bogey at the 16th and bogeyed
the unyielding, arguably unfair 475-yard 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm frustrated,'' said Andrade, who stands 108th on the money
list ($181,391) after finishing 31st ($665,602) last year. ''I'm
just having a tough year. It seems like when I need a birdie putt,
I don't make it. When I need to hit a good drive, I hit it in the
rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Keppler fails to make weekend
</P>
<P>
   Summit Chase pro Stephen Keppler, the Georgia PGA Section's lone
representative at Sahalee, settled for a 6-over-par 76 Friday and
failed to make weekend play at 149. Keppler allowed three
double-bogeys, consecutively on No.4 and No. 5, and then also on
the 18th, catching the lip of a bunker ''and moving the ball about
10 feet.'' The good news? Keppler need not rush to Brunswick for
Monday's start of the Georgia Open. ''I played about the same today
as yesterday (a 73),'' said the Suwanee resident. ''I just couldn't
avoid the doubles. . .Columbus' Larry Mize followed his 75 with a
71, but also missed the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Couples regrets poor preparation
</P>
<P>
   Seattle native Fred Couples, who improved to a 71 after
Thursday's 75, said he felt no extra pressure from the local
attention. ''It's only frustrating that I didn't practice a lot
harder before I got up here,'' said Couples. ''I don't want to make
it sound like I wanted to play poorly, but I relaxed the last
couple of months.'' . . . Stuart Appleby shot 10-over 150 with a 73
Friday, failing to make the cut in his first appearance since the
death of his wife Renay July 23. ''I'm not expecting great
things,'' Appleby said. ''Ninety percent of the game is mental, and
if you're not mentally fit, you're not going to play your quality
shots.''.. . .1995 champion Steve Elkington, having battled viral
meningitis and sinus surgery in recent months, is an unexpected
contender at 2-under 138 after a 69 Friday. ''I'm due for some good
luck and some good golf,'' he said. ''I feel great. I'm close to
100 percent.'' . . .After an opening 80, John Daly improved to a
72, but missed the cut for the fourth time in five years. Since
winning the 1991 PGA, Daly has finished 82nd, tied for 51st, tied
for 29th and missed four cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
