<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ busy they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, they say El Nino is the cause of everything these
days,'' Besheer said. ``I don't know if that's the case here, but
it's buggier. Plus, the economy's good and the Kansas City area's
growing, so there are just more jobs out there.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, in particular, the tight labor market and strong
economy combined to put a lot more people to work. The number of
employed youth nationally, for example, increased by 2.8 million
from April to July.
</P>
<P>
   Youth employment always rises in the summer, but this year the
number of unemployed youth rose far less than usual, indicating
more jobs were available and filled by those who wanted them.
</P>
<P>
   Stock market activity, for two summers in a row, also has
remained hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constant, overwhelming amount of things people have on
their plates has taken away the ability to notice it's summer,''
counselor Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doldrums, if any, seem to have moved to January and
February, not July and August. People are saying now that they're
so busy they can't stop to feel how they feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
