<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSH COMES TO SHOVE ON MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Some things don't make sense _ the revelation, for
instance, of a federal investigation showing that health
maintenance organizations benefit from Medicare overpayments
exceeding $1 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, according to federal investigators, is ``highly
inflated'' administrative costs.HMOs aren't paying their ``fair
share'' of these costs, and government should attempt to recover
the excess payments, according to the report from the inspector
general of the Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to stockholders of United Healthcare Corp. The company
bid to acquire rival Humana came a cropper after a collapse of
United Healthcare stock that gave shareholders a haircut of nearly
$3 billion. The plunge partly resulted from United's decision to
reduce company Medicare involvement due to losses.
</P>
<P>
   That came after United took an unexpected $900 million
second-quarter charge, which some analysts fear may be only the
first of more unpleasant surprises to come.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond United Healthcare's Medicare-related problems, The Wall
Street Journal also reported this week that some other Medicare
HMOs are making radical adjustments to cope with a continuing
financial squeeze. Soaring drug prices combined with Medicare
belt-tightening has resulted in management miscalculations that
will cause other HMOs to both reduce Medicare exposure and trim
benefits for remaining clients.
</P>
<P>
   One key problem, it appears, is prescription drugs. Traditional
Medicare doesn't cover this cost, and one of the primary
attractions of the Medicare HMO was coverage for prescriptions
either entirely or up to a generous threshold. About 15 percent of
all Medicare enrollees currently belong to HMOs, and Washington
plans initiatives to double that participation rate in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   This aggressive move to encourage HMO enrollment may be at odds
with Medicare's financial situation. As the program's finances
become more strained, the need to control costs will intensify.
Since HMOs are paid a capitation fee for each enrollee, rising
patient demands for benefits and costs of medical care will
inevitably collide with Medicare's relentless need to economize.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a solution is found to resolve conflicting economic
goals, Medicare's experiment with the HMO concept may fail. This
likely would be devastating to the long-term prospects for Medicare
because the HMO is the last, best hope to keep the program viable
for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   As corporations have found, managed care _ warts and all _ is
the only way to keep health-care coverage costs within reasonable
limits. Uncle Sam's access to taxpayer resources gives government
relatively more breathing room, but the public's capacity to pay
enough taxes to underwrite limitless access to care isn't infinite.
</P>
<P>
   As for government's claim that HMOs are using government as a
cash cow to ease administrative costs, there seems much room for
debate. The inspector general charged that many HMOs profit
excessively from Medicare. The reality would seem to suggest that
Medicare has become more a daunting bottom-line challenge than a
source of easy profits for the health-care providers and insurers
involved in the actual marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the truth lies in this issue, one thing is obvious.
Government has just as much incentive as the private sector to
watch its pennies, and all Medicare beneficiaries will bear the
consequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4980 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-ANALYSIS-650&AMP;ADD     08-14 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-ANALYSIS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DESPITE UPS AND DOWNS, ECONOMY NOT LIKELY TO UNRAVEL
ANYTIME SOON  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Russia facing financial turmoil, Asia sinking deeper into
recession the president fighting for his political life and the
stock market swooning, the blindingly bright economic picture of
the last couple of years suddenly looks murkier.
</P>
<P>
   What makes things a bit scary is that the economy has already
shifted into slower gear, and slowdowns _ which make it harder for
businesses and consumers to shrug off random blows _ have a way of
turning into recessions. ``Things can pile up,'' said June O'Neill,
director of the Congressional Budget Office. ``They can unravel as
quickly as they materialize.''
</P>
<P>
   But the economy is not likely to unravel anytime soon.
Forecasters are counting on low inflation, falling interest rates
and confident consumers to keep growth going in the year's second
half. They are taking last month's news about a slide in everything
from industrial production to retail sales _ all made worse by the
General Motors strike _ in stride.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a slowdown, they say, is just what the doctor ordered.
``The domestic economy is still very sound,'' said Mickey Levy,
chief economist at NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. ``I see it
moderating from a robust to a sustainable place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Chip consensus of 50 economic forecasters sees growth
just shy of a 2.4 percent annual rate for the second half of the
year and more of the same next year. That would not be as heady as
the average 4 percent growth rate of last year and earlier this
year. But it is considered fast enough to keep unemployment near
its 28-year low of 4.5 percent, without being so fast as to
intensify inflationary pressures or invite interest rate increases
by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single Blue Chip economist sees a recession beginning in
the second half. ``Asia has slowed the economy,'' said Bruce
Steinberg, chief economist at Merrill Lynch, ``but its only
intrinsic problem is a shortage of workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the risks to this essentially benign outlook are numerous
and real, economists admit. A disaster in one area or a combination
of mini- disasters could darken the economic picture. Apart from
bolts from the blue like a military confrontation with Iraq or
natural disasters, Asia's woes could worsen sharply, reducing U.S.
exports still further, deepening the downturn in manufacturing and
hammering corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The political crisis surrounding the presidency could paralyze
the economy, just as, in some analysts' eyes, Watergate may have
deepened and prolonged the severe recession of 1973-75.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a stock market rout could shake consumers' confidence
and wreak havoc on household balance sheets, causing spending to
collapse and inventories to pile up. In 1990, Saddam Hussein's
attack on Kuwait and surging oil prices frightened consumers badly
enough to tip the economy into recession.
</P>
<P>
   Like the special effects in the movie ``Armageddon,'' the nasty
hypothetical possibilities are so palpable that it is easy to
forget the economy's strengths. Momentum, for example. Sturdy
consumer and business spending will probably offset a further
deterioration in the trade deficit, a decline already built into
most forecasts for the second half. The side effects of the Asian
crisis _ the stronger dollar, lower interest rates and cheaper raw
materials _ are actually bolstering the purchasing power of
American consumers and businesses and lifting the profits of many
companies in finance, transportation, services and consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   Analogies between Monicagate and Watergate fail to take into
account the impact of Richard Nixon's economic policies and his bad
economic luck, as Larry Kudlow, the chief economist at Skandia,
points out. Long before Nixon resigned the presidency in August
1974, inflation was spiraling out of control, the dollar was
sliding and oil prices were soaring.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While a sudden, sharp stock market decline _ two or three times
the recent 10 percent drop _ would almost certainly affect
consumers, there is no reason to believe they would head for the
hills, especially since the Federal Reserve would surely push
interest rates down to cushion the blow and encourage spending.
</P>
<P>
   Though the fallout from the recently settled GM strike has made
it hard to see clearly, consumers and businesses are still spending
at a steady pace.
</P>
<P>
   Business investment, which surged at a 26 percent annual rate in
the year's first half, is bound to slow, but not necessarily to a
crawl. Total corporate profits have flattened in recent quarters as
companies in such fields as high technology, energy and machinery
have seen sharp declines. Still, many companies in the service
sector are still enjoying double-digit gains. Overall profit
margins remain close to historic highs. Productivity is up nearly 2
percent from a year ago, and wage costs, while drifting higher,
show no signs of taking off. Cash flow _ a measure of businesses'
ability to finance capital spending _ is strong. ``The fundamentals
for capital spending are still pretty good,'' said Richard Rippe,
chief economist at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a sudden collapse in demand, there is little reason to
expect that business will stop replenishing inventories. Stockpiles
look fairly lean relative to sales. Much of last winter's big
pileup, when inventory accumulation hit a record $91 billion, has
already been whittled away.
</P>
<P>
   As with business spending, consumer spending, which spurted at a
torrid 6 percent annual rate in the first half, is bound to
moderate. But the latest readings from the nation's malls show
that, sales of big-ticket items other than cars were up smartly in
June. Consumers are not stinting on services either; so many
consumers are traveling that airlines are once again raising fares,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   With consumer net worth $12 trillion higher than just four years
ago, courtesy of the stock market, and consumers more willing to
use their capital gains than ever before, consumers have been
spending virtually everything they make and saving almost nothing.
But newfound wealth has not been the main prop of spending; jobs
are still plentiful and incomes are rising much faster than
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   So far, consumers have not been spooked by the latest stock
market gyrations. Confidence, which is close to historic highs,
seems to depend more on such factors as inflation, interest rates
and, most of all, job growth, says Richard Curtin, director of the
surveys of consumers at the University of Michigan. To the extent
that consumers worry about the Asian crisis, he said, it is because
they fear that it will result in layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the doubling of stock prices in the last two years has
dwarfed the recent declines, leaving consumers with strong gains.
The Dow Jones industrial average is still up 6.5 percent for the
year. ``Consumers will impart a degree of stability to the economy
that wouldn't be there if they reacted like traders,'' Curtin said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, a lot of economists' confidence in the
economy reflects today's low inflation and zero budget deficits,
which leave policy makers considerable maneuvering room. ``In a
low-inflation environment, you have great flexibility for the
Federal Reserve to counter an excessively weak economy,'' points
out Rippe. During the economic slowdown in 1995, for example, the
Fed eased three times, and the economy rebounded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
