A4981 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-PRODUCTIVITY-2     08-14 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-PRODUCTIVITY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCTIVITY RISE SHOWS HAZY, CRAZY DAYS OF SUMMER ARE NO LONGER
LAZY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Summer doldrums have gone the way of home
milk deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   These days are supposed to be the dog days of summer, yet
business continues to run at a feverish pace.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, air conditioning combats the effects of seasonal heat
for most workers. Plus, there are too many channels and not enough
free time to get bored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like the summer frenzies now,'' said Connie Russell,
a clinical social worker and career development coach.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics and individual observations both indicate that the
``lazy, hazy, crazy days of summer'' aren't lazy anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Labor Department's productivity figures. In the
third quarter last year _ the period covering the summer months _
U.S. productivity gained markedly over the second, or spring,
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity measures hourly output by American workers. Last
summer, it grew at the fastest pace in five years. This summer's
figure won't be known until later this fall, but analysts expect
continued growth.
</P>
<P>
   Data show that the average number of weekly on-the-job hours by
U.S. production workers doesn't drop during the summer, either.
Last August, for example, the average work week was 35 hours; in
July last year it was 34.9 hours. No other months that year had a
higher average.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Czaplewski, vice president-human resources at Missouri Gas
Energy, looked shocked when asked whether the summer doldrums had
set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Czaplewski said. ``In some ways, our
activity increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the utility's phone centers aren't as busy handling
customer queries about their winter bills, other work, such as
training programs, fills summer days.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, workplaces frantically contend with employee
vacations. Summer, when kids are out of school, continues to be the
peak family vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are desperate for their vacations,'' said Robert Rosen,
a Kansas City counselor who works with people on life and career
issues. ``But they work harder before they leave to get ready to
go, and then there's tremendous anxiety when they come back and try
to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're draining their recharged batteries almost
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   And the workers who aren't on vacation work doubletime to fill
in for absent colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, absenteeism doesn't rise in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of National Affairs Inc. tracks monthly unscheduled
absence rates. The research organization's line graph shows annual
peaks (more absences) between November and April and annual valleys
(fewer absences) between May and October.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, fewer workers play hooky to go fishing or take a
``dog days'' break.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics in Kansas City, regional
economist Dave McDermott is waiting to take his vacation this fall,
largely because his wife is too busy to leave her work.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannie McDermott is a children's librarian at Olathe (Kan.)
Public Library, where out-of-school children flood the story hours
and book stacks. The library _ like camps, movie theaters and video
rental shops _ rocks during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different kinds of entertainment available
now, the summer is spent running kids around,'' noted Russell, the
clinical social worker and career counselor at Centerpoint
Counseling and Recovery in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work didn't stop just because school was out,'' said Cathy
Bien, a Leawood, Kan., mother of four. ``Then their leisure time
was filled with more and more things, so I'm also shuttling them
around to all these structured activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The days of cloud-watching from a hilltop have been replaced by
swim meets, baseball practices, Scout camp, dance recitals and
birthday parties.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of summer boredom also is cut short by an early
return to school. Several area school districts start back to class
on Aug. 20, which still is in the thick of summertime.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Jadlow, a workplace chaplain for three area car
dealerships and four assisted living centers, finds that summer
heat makes some difference in work pace _ but not necessarily
attitudes _ of people who don't work in air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the car dealerships, the pace slows down a bit back where
the mechanics are, especially toward the afternoon,'' she said.
Still, she said, ``they're real troupers'' about staying on task.
</P>
<P>
   And in the air-conditioned front offices, Jadlow doesn't see any
change in work pace or emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, when I go to the retirement homes, the residents
are sitting around with their sweaters on, complaining it's so cold
because of the air conditioning. They have to go sit outside on the
porch to get warm.''
</P>
<P>
   Indoor, climate-controlled work conditions combine with the
national, if not international, scope of business to make climate
immaterial at many workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace of work and of change is so fast these days, it
doesn't seem like things slow down anywhere,'' said Leigh Branham,
vice president at Right Management Consultants in Overland Park,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is prime time for corporate relocations, Branham added,
and all that inter-city and intra-company movement quickens the
pace.
</P>
<P>
   Seasonal work, such as construction, typically soars in the
summer. Of course, when it gets hot enough to sizzle roofing tar,
it's also too hot for workers to maintain an all-day, fast-working
pace.
</P>
<P>
   That's when extra water breaks or midday rest periods occur _
but that doesn't mean the amount of work lessens. Crews stay on the
job until the last tinge of sunlight or even work under lights at
night.
</P>
<P>
   And, as if busyness were contagious, even the bugs are more
active this summer. Jay Besheer, of Gunter Exterminating Co., said
the industry's talk nationally and locally is all about how busy
they are. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
