<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4994 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ISOLATION-720     08-14 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ISOLATION-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL CLINTON, ALL ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-DEFENSE, CLINTON-REACT, and CLINTON-NH-VOICES) 
(js) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``The president would like to speak to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of old friends, academics, legislators, political
analysts and governors have picked up the telephone in the last
five years and heard some version of those spine-straightening
words, as Bill Clinton ricocheted from one crisis to another, from
one freighted political choice to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to sleep and insatiable for information, he was punching
through his cocoon of White House aides for a reality check or a
street-level glimpse of the public, to insure that he assessed
every possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But the president is not leaning on White House operators _ or
operatives _ in preparing for the most portentous day of his
turbulent career, his aides say. Faced with questioning under oath
on Monday about his private life, with impeachment proceedings
tuning up in the wings, Clinton has almost no one he can turn to
for advice, say his friends and current and former advisers.
</P>
<P>
   No one besides a few lawyers has enough information about the
president's legal predicament to give him political counsel worth a
phone call. If others learned the facts, they could be compelled to
share them with the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The question, in the view of the president's allies, is whether
the enforced silence matters _ whether Clinton, his ultimate and
most trusted strategist, can make the right decisions in this
cliffhanger without examining every line of approach first. ``In so
many ways, this guy is being asked to act contrary to his own
instincts,'' one former White House official said.
</P>
<P>
   A profoundly private man, Clinton may acknowledge to 23 grand
jurors that he had an intimate relationship with Monica Lewinsky,
some of his closest advisers say. A cautious politician whose
reflex is to battle rather than give an inch, he is also weighing
an extraordinary gamble, describing his testimony in an address to
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   At a White House renowned for fierce response to any accusation,
damage control has, eerily, taken a holiday. The president's
advisers, uncertain of the truth, have not fanned out on television
to defend him. Some, unneeded now and anxious to project a
relaxation-as-usual image, have simply left town on long-planned
trips.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has vanished to Hawaii for two weeks.
Erskine Bowles, the White House chief of staff, is golfing in
Scotland; his deputy, John Podesta, who has run the political
damage control effort for seven months, only returned from vacation
on Friday. Lanny Breuer, a senior member of the White House
counsel's office, has gone fishing. Bruce Lindsey, the president's
closest aide, is recuperating from back surgery, and is rarely at
the office.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, canceled her
vacation in early August to stay at his side, and Chelsea Clinton,
on break from Stanford University, has stayed at the White House as
well. ``His bulwark of support, his wall of protection on this, has
been Hillary and Chelsea,'' said the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who has
met periodically with Clinton since the first thunderclap of
Lewinsky accusations in January.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he is careful about how detailed their
conversations become, for fear of Kenneth Starr, the independent
prosecutor. ``We talk, and when we talk we have prayer, but I have
carefully stayed away from the legal area in this, because Starr's
been so bizarre in his hauling people before his grand jury,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has seemed at times weary and muted recently. But if the
president feels isolated or pressured, he is not revealing it to
some close friends or to his senior aides. Riding in his limousine
in Los Angeles on Tuesday, Clinton indulged in a favorite pastime,
a game of hearts played during a running, bantering conversation.
After the president won a hand, one adviser, who had been been
asked by reporters whether Clinton was lonely, observed
sarcastically that his victory might improve his mood.
</P>
<P>
   The president glanced at him over his newly dealt hand. ``What
are you talking about?'' he asked, according to two of the players.
Another participant in the game replied, ``The press thinks you're
curled up by yourself depressed in the back of this limo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do they get that?'' Clinton asked, with a baffled grin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   To some of his own advisers, the president is a mystery now.
They wonder why he does not vent more anger. They wonder if he
misled the public and them as well. They wonder how he could have
risked his presidency on a relationship, whatever its nature, with
an intern. They mourn a lost year, and they wonder if he will get
his term back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, they wonder what he will do on Monday. ``Any staff
member who tells you they know what he's doing,'' one official
said, ``they're lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has acknowledged having caused pain in his marriage, and
he has acknowledged a preference for boxer shorts over briefs. Such
admissions helped give him a reputation as a compulsive sharer of
personal details, a needy baby boomer turning the nation into his
analyst. In fact, despite his legion of friends, Clinton confides
in almost no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think that his personal, private, innermost
part, I don't believe he shares that with anybody, except maybe
Hillary,'' said David Leopoulos, one of Clinton's closest friends
since childhood. ``I don't even try to approach that with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Leopoulos said that he was amazed to read during the 1992
presidential campaign that Clinton's stepfather had been a heavy
drinker who sometimes turned violent. His friend never told him.
``Never a hint,'' he said, chalking the secrecy up to titanic inner
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, on a visit to Little Rock, Clinton gathered with
friends dating back four decades. They played cards _ hearts, of
course _ and told stories until five in the morning; the president
described his trip to China and his hopes for democracy there. But
though his friends worried that he was going through a brutal time,
they did not discuss the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel terrible for him, but I don't think he feels terrible
for himself,'' Leopoulos said. ``He said the other night in our
card game, `I wish I could run again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's history of relying on himself to handle agonizing
matters might explain his seeming equanimity now. He has never
counted heavily on any Democratic wise man to guide him. He ran
challenging his party's orthodoxy, implicitly repudiating the
judgment of predecessors and congressional Democrats. While he has
what one former aide calls ``crushes'' on advisers, he usually
discards them eventually and moves on to new ones, in a constant
search.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton often leaves the impression that he agrees with whatever
argument he hears. In fact, his current and former aides say, he is
usually adopting it only to test it out. Once he feels he can argue
every side of a question, he decides, alone.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigation has created an odd zone of mincing
conversation around the president. He is surrounded by people who
have testified before the grand jury: the steward who brings his
fruit and diet ginger ale, the personal secretary who guards his
door. For some, the rush of reporters outside the federal
courthouse and the grilling by prosecutors was a searing
experience. Yet they do not discuss it with the man at the center
of it, White House staff members say.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, however, life proceeds as though Clinton had no
testimony planned, as though his private lawyer had not moved into
the White House. On Friday, Mrs. Clinton sprang an early birthday
party for her husband, who turns 52 on Wednesday. White House staff
gathered behind the Oval Office to sing and to share a cake
decorated with sugary portraits of a golf ball, an eagle, Buddy the
dog, and Socks the cat.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Clinton has been reassured by such warm receptions,
especially the embrace of crowds. As he works ropelines or moves
among guests at fund-raisers, strangers tell them they love him or
say nasty things about Starr. In his free-form remarks before
friendly crowds at fund-raisers, the president comes as close as he
ever does to giving a public glimpse of his private thinking, aides
say. He seems preoccupied now with energizing his second term.
</P>
<P>
   The president's aides were proud for a brief time to have
persuaded him to shorten his remarks in public to just ten minutes.
But in the last couple of weeks, Clinton has pushed his typical
time to more than twice that, as he urgently counsels against
apathy. He tells crowds to grab this historical period to improve
education, strengthen Social Security, and protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this is a golden moment for our country,'' the president
said at a fund-raiser here Friday, ``and the big question is what
to do with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
