<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Irvan No. 1 as Pontiacs occupy Pepsi front row
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Whatever it is that brings out the best in
Pontiacs qualifying at Michigan Speedway was at work again Friday.
Ernie Irvan won the pole and Bobby Labonte the outside pole.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third race that a Pontiac graced the inside row _
Johnny Benson in 1996, Ward Burton in '97 and now Irvan.
</P>
<P>
   It was Irvan's 21st career pole, second of the year, and came on
a speed of 183.416 miles per hour. Labonte was just a tick slower,
running 183.374 mph.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the Pontiac secret?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tape,'' said Irvan. ``That car likes to be taped up solid.
When Ryan (Pemberton, crew chief) told me that, I thought he crazy.
But what it does is create downforce on the front tires.''
</P>
<P>
   It also must be attracted to high speed tracks, considering that
Pontiac drivers John Andretti and Todd Bodine held down the front
row in the spring Primestar 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know whether what you run is good enough, especially
as fast as people are running here,'' Irvan said. ``We aren't
really trying for poles, but they are nice to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Pontiacs dominate the first row, Jeff Gordon's Chevrolet
was just a tick slower in 183.341 mph, and Dale Jarrett was fourth
in his Ford Taurus with a speed of 183.132.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we weren't pole material today, but I was hoping to go
a little faster than that,'' Gordon said of his lap. ``Going out
first you never know how this track is going to pick up. I knew
coming off turn four to take the green flag (starting the lap),
that the car felt really, really tight. Still, it was faster than
we ran in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can complain. This was an equal opportunity qualifier,
featuring three Pontiacs, four Chevys and three Fords in the top
10.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt wasn't in one of them. He never got off pit road,
victimized by a faulty oil pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't been running that great, but we tried some things
for qualifying and were going to give it our best shot,'' said
Earnhardt, who may try again today or take a provisional. ``As I
started off pit road, the oil light came on. It had locked the oil
pump and broke the belt. It's a freak deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt isn't the only one looking for help. Johnny Benson is
39th, Darrell Waltrip 40th, Dave Marcis 45th and Kevin LePage,
making his debut with Roush Racing, is 46th.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
