<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES DELIVERS BIG THANK YOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who announced
Thursday that the Cowboys would return to Wichita Falls for
training camp next year, didn't plan on announcing the Cowboys'
intentions for 1999 this early.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said he thought the city and Midwestern State
University had earned such an announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something they deserved,'' Jones said. ``This is an
expression of how pleased we are and how effective our training
camp has been here. The facilities are tremendous, and there's an
energy here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said his decision was influenced by the players, who raved
about their dormitory, the meeting rooms and a respect for privacy.
He didn't even consider another site.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman said the players are pleased
with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty excited to be coming back,'' Aikman said. ``The
people have been great. The facilities have been wonderful. From a
player's perspective, we couldn't ask for anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   Wichita Falls and Midwestern State couldn't ask for anything
more either, as both are expecting big returns from the presence of
the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The city projects that training camp will have an economic
impact of more than $4.2 million. It cost $450,000 of city and
private funds to put on the training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the money, however, Midwestern State President Louis
Rodriguez said the heightened national awareness of the school and
city can't be measured financially.
</P>
<P>
   Close to 90,000 fans, including many out-of-towners, have
attended practices in this city of 103,000. The Cowboys issued 550
media credentials during the past four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, noting that the camp was pulled off in only five
months of preparation time, said a year to prepare will make things
bigger and better. &QL; 
LETT COULD BE BACK EARLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though defensive tackle Leon Lett will miss the rest of the
preseason with a sprained medial collateral ligament in his left
knee, he could return to practice in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said Lett will probably begin light
running in 10 days. And while Lett won't play in any remaining
preseason games, Maurer said he will certainly see time on the
practice field before the Cowboys open against the Arizona
Cardinals on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Lett injured his knee when Saints quarterback Billy Joe Hobert
fell on him during Tuesday's scrimmage in Shreveport, La. &QL; 
BRIEFLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys guard Nate Newton didn't practice yesterday because of
knee swelling. The trainers, however, expect him to practice today
and play in Monday's game against the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Kavika Pittman, still hobbled by a sprained ankle,
is not expected to play against the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Chris Warren (groin) has a ``50-50'' chance of
playing against the Patriots, Maurer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
