<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: RAZZLE DAZZLE 'EM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK RICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The most short-lived comeback in the history of show
business ended this week when Michael Ovitz was brought to grief on
Broadway in a plot worthy of ``The Producers.'' The tale would
match Mel Brooks' in hilarity if only thousands of innocent
stockholders _ not unlike the little old ladies romanced by Zero
Mostel into investing in ``Springtime for Hitler'' _ weren't left
holding the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, you may recall, is the former superagent whom the press
anointed ``the most powerful man in Hollywood'' _ but who fell from
grace in 1996 when Michael Eisner canned him as president of Disney
after only 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this April, Ovitz was resurrected once more as a major
show-biz player by the media, after he spent $20 million of his
$100-million-plus Disney settlement to take control of Livent, the
Toronto-based theater-producing company that gave Broadway
``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   But a not-so-funny thing happened on the way to the Tony Awards
that ``Ragtime'' failed to win. Ovitz is now crying that he was
duped by another show-biz hype artist: Garth Drabinsky, the
co-founder of Livent and the producer of its shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Ovitz management at Livent alleges that Drabinsky engaged in
accounting ``irregularities'' to hide the severity of its losses.
Drabinsky, who denies the charges, has been locked out of his
office _ and trading in Livent stock has been halted as official
investigators move in.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any books were cooked or not, it's still amazing how
easily Ovitz and a credulous press were played for suckers,
especially given Drabinsky's history of having been pushed out of
the movie-theater chain Cineplex Odeon in 1989 for piling up debt.
</P>
<P>
   Any outsider with common sense and a pencil could figure out
that Livent was hemorrhaging money by simply adding up rough
figures on the back of an envelope. There is no way that
extravaganzas like ``Ragtime'' and ``Show Boat'' could have been
making profits, no matter how many seats they were selling (and
Variety reported plenty of empty seats on the road).
</P>
<P>
   The shows' overhead _ huge casts, grandiose sets and costumes,
unprecedented ad blitzes _ was simply too high. Weeks before Ovitz
bought into Livent, the off-Broadway revue ``Forbidden Broadway''
was featuring a ``Gagtime'' parody in which a little boy warned
investors, ``You won't make your money back!''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, who apparently believed his own inflated press, fell for
Drabinsky's, too. Though some journalists have been skeptical of
Livent from the start, more typical was a naive 1997 New Yorker
piece in which speculative, impressive-sounding box-office figures
($600 million for ``Show Boat'' by 2000) were tossed around as if
they insured profitability, and Drabinsky was portrayed as having
the potential to turn the gamble of Broadway producing into ``more
of a risk-free proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same day this year that Livent posted a $30 million loss,
an extensive Washington Post profile was on the stands saluting
Drabinsky's ``Midas touch.'' The media, not unlike the rest of
America, seem to go gaga when caught in the klieg lights of a
self-promoting P.T. Barnum who throws glitzy opening-night parties
and travels by private jet.
</P>
<P>
   When Drabinsky took his tumble this week, theater people
lamented the ``tragedy'' of it all _ the tragedy apparently being
that he won't be showering famously inflated salaries on Broadway
anymore. No one could seriously argue that his actual contributions
to the stage remotely matched those of his models Florenz Ziegfeld,
David Merrick and Cameron Mackintosh.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a real tragedy here, it's for the stockholders in
Livent. A source close to the situation says that the company is
now pinning its immediate hopes on ``Fosse,'' its new musical
stitched out of old Bob Fosse dance numbers, and on the Chicago
opening of ``Ragtime.'' But the last Broadway dance anthology like
``Fosse'' _ ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' _ lost millions, and
there's no reason to believe ``Ragtime'' will be any more
profitable in Chicago than it has been in its slack road
engagements thus far in Los Angeles, Washington and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday some mutual-fund companies holding Livent shares wrote
down the value of their investments by as much as 70 percent.
Ovitz, who's on a cruise in Europe, could not be reached for
comment. He's presumably contemplating his next comeback, as no
doubt is Drabinsky. Hold the front page.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
