<HEADER>
A5004 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-MEDIA-TEX     08-14 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-MEDIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY-FOX FRAY OVER RIGHTS TO NHL MAKES DOLLARS, SENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never throw anything away, my Aunt Jane the collector used to
say, someday it might be valuable.
</P>
<P>
   So here I sit with my six Phil Ortega baseball cards, a case of
Billy Beer and my Mod Squad lunch box. Worth about a buck-fifty
altogether, I figure, though you could fairly say any picture of
Peggy Lipton in her prime is just about priceless.
</P>
<P>
   That must be the way Big TV is looking at the NHL these days.
Not that long ago, say around the time hockey came to Dallas, TV
broadcast rights for a season-load of Whalers vs. Jets could be had
for the cost of a retired Beanie Baby.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. The Walt Disney Co., which ought to know something
about the value of programming, is offering to pay the NHL $600
million over five years to carry games on its ESPN, ESPN2 and ABC
networks.
</P>
<P>
   And Fox, which has been showing NHL games on weekends the past
several years with little ratings success, is considering matching
the ABC portion of that bid and keeping the glow in its comet-tail
puck.
</P>
<P>
   Now, $600 million isn't much compared to the NFL's $18 billion,
eight-year contract with the networks, but then a lot more people
are willing to watch Brett Favre throw than Pavel Bure skate.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the NHL played about as well in American living rooms
last year as the Blackhawks did in Chicago. Over the past four
years, viewership is down by a third, with young male watchers
abandoning in even larger numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, more people drank Billy Beer during the Carter
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, here are two media giants, Disney and Fox, battling for the
rights to bring you hockey in the next millennium. There is even
talk of a legal set-to, with the Fox folks saying NHL executives
didn't properly explain to them the details of the Disney bid in
time to meet yesterday's league-imposed deadline for a
counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   It's like fighting over the rights to sign Ortega out of
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, considering the state of pitching these days ...
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Disney-Fox squabble might make business sense.
Maybe not enough to justify a 260 percent increase in rights fees,
but sense all the same.
</P>
<P>
   Securing the rights to air NHL games on ESPN, ESPN2 and ABC
starting in 1999-2000 won't win Disney the TV equivalent of the
Stanley Cup. But, for a relatively paltry sum, Disney's networks,
especially the Deuce, would get even more of that oh-so desirable,
hard-to-come-by TV commodity _ live, quality sports programming.
</P>
<P>
   Live sports programming is about as valuable to a network
executive as goal-scorers are to a hockey club.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN already has NHL cable rights, in a shared package with Fox,
but under the new Disney-take-all proposal its cable networks would
get even more games. ESPN2 would go from 75 per season to more than
100, while ESPN would keep about two dozen contests on its
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   NHL ratings might be down, but, as anybody who's a regular
watcher of the Deuce knows, even a midseason Canucks-Kings game is
preferable to reruns of ``World's Strongest Cheerleaders'', or
``In-line Skating Bloopers''.
</P>
<P>
   Disney executives are also betting that the long-anticipated
hockey boom occurs sometime during the new contract. No one could
expect boffo viewership back in the days of the Original Six, or
even after the first or second rounds of expansion. There still
were too many teams in Canada then and not enough in the United
States, particularly in the South and the West.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that has all changed. With teams up and running or in
production in Nashville, Tenn.; Minneapolis; Atlanta; and Columbus,
Ohio, hockey truly is a national game. That should mean more
viewers, particularly young ones. If it all plays out, hockey may
someday be a ratings success story, a programming piece well worth
collecting.
</P>
<P>
   My Aunt Jane would be pleased.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
