<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET-NORTH-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY TO EXPAND IN TIMES SQUARE AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter has signed an agreement to
move into a new 1-million-square-foot office tower on Seventh
Avenue between 49th and 50th Streets, according to real estate
executives.
</P>
<P>
   If completed, the deal would represent the latest in a series of
expansion moves by the city's big investment houses, whose growth
has helped fuel New York City's economic resurgence in the last few
years. It also would add another piece to a building boom in the
Times Square area driven largely by media and financial companies.
</P>
<P>
   After many months of on-again, off-again negotiations, Morgan
Stanley signed a letter of intent Tuesday with Rockefeller Group
Development Corp. to build and occupy a proposed 33-story glass
tower on what is now a parking lot and a rare development site in
midtown Manhattan, according to the executives, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The site, known as Rockefeller Plaza West, was a victim of the
recession in the early 1990s and sat fallow for nine years. But
with rents soaring and little vacant space available in midtown,
the land has become very valuable, although at least two companies
in the last year have tried and failed to come to terms with the
owner, the Rockefeller Group, which is a subsidiary of Mitsubishi
Estate Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockefeller Group's plans for the Seventh Avenue tower are
now going through the city's land use review process. According to
documents filed with the Planning Commission, the 33-story
skyscraper would include an atrium at the corner of Seventh Avenue
and 49th Street with an entrance to the subway as well as the vast
underground concourse beneath Rockefeller Center to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's letter of intent gives the investment bank
exclusive rights to complete a deal at Rock West within a specified
time, one real estate executive said.
</P>
<P>
   If a final deal is struck this time, the new office tower would
be Morgan Stanley's third building in the area and its latest step
in creating a corporate campus at the northern end of Times Square.
The Rock West site is across the street from Morgan Stanley's
building at 750 Seventh Ave. And both buildings are only a block
north of the investment bank's 43-story headquarters at 1585
Broadway, between 47th and 48th Streets.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley, like many of the largest investment banks, moved
to midtown during the 1970s from lower Manhattan, the city's
traditional financial center. In 1995, the investment bank decamped
to a newly resurgent Times Square, suddenly rife with financial and
media and entertainment companies like Disney, Viacom, Bertelsmann
AG, Proskauer Rose and, soon, Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley and other major financial institutions are
expanding. According to the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, the
number of jobs in the securities industry in New York City hit a
record of 164,300 in June, surpassing the previous peak of 163,000
for the first time in 11 years. Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. are both scouring the metropolitan area for more office
space, while Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. is building a new headquarters on
Madison Avenue between 46th and 47th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley declined comment Friday, as did the company's
broker, Colliers ABR. Rockefeller Group Development president
Jonathan Green was no more forthcoming, nor was his broker, Cushman
&AMP; Wakefield. But word of the tentative deal, which was shrouded by
confidentiality agreements, spread quickly through the real estate
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This continues the trend of large financial companies
devouring whatever space is available in the city today,'' said
Howard Michaels, chairman of the Carlton Group, a real estate
advisory firm. ``As the Wall Street boom continues, the space
requirements for the investment banks grow ever larger.''
</P>
<P>
   In this year's first four months, financial service companies
accounted for nearly 11 percent of all commercial leasing in the
city, according to a recent report from the office of state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs is putting together its own corporate campus
downtown, where the investment bank recently leased 660,000 square
feet of space at 180 Maiden Lane and 520,000 square feet at 10
Hanover Square. The company, which is based nearby at 85 Broad St.
and One New York Plaza, is back in the market looking for more
space, according to real estate brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, which bought a 780,000-square-foot tower at 222
Broadway last year, is now hunting for a million more square feet
and will probably end up finding space in nearby Jersey City, N.J.,
brokers said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from real estate, Wall Street has fueled budget surpluses
for the city and the state and accounted for an astounding 56
percent of the increase in inflation-adjusted earnings in New York
City between 1992 and 1997, while representing only 5 percent of
the jobs. But financial analysts have warned of the danger that the
city's economy is so dependent on the fortunes of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``While good times on Wall Street pour unprecedented personal
and business tax revenue into the city and the state, the flow of
income from this single area poses some risks,'' McCall said
Thursday. ``A market downturn, or worse, a broader economic
recession, would result in job losses and the loss of a significant
source of funds for the city and the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a robust stock market and record profits among Wall
Street companies, the American and New York Stock Exchanges, the
commodity exchanges and the investment banks have demanded hundreds
of millions of dollars in tax breaks to remain in the city. Morgan
Stanley, which received a $100 million tax subsidy in the early
1990s, is expected to go back to the city for more if a deal is
struck at Rock West.
</P>
<P>
   The tower would be something of a victory for Mitsubishi Estate,
which lost a billion-dollar investment in the historic Rockefeller
Center complex during the recession.
</P>
<P>
   The site itself has served as a barometer of the New York real
estate market. Green began buying the parcels that make up the site
at the start of the last real estate boom in 1980. But by the time
he had demolished the existing buildings and obtained city approval
in 1990 for a 55-story, 1.3 million square foot limestone tower, a
recession had devastated the New York real estate market. In 1994,
the Rockefeller Group turned it into a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Rockefeller Group nearly struck a deal with
Morgan Stanley for the property, but it ultimately balked at the
suggestion of turning over the property to Morgan Stanley's
developer, Gerald Hines.
</P>
<P>
   According to one executive who knows of the deal, Morgan Stanley
returned to the negotiating table recently, agreeing to lease the
land for 99 years, pay the Rockefeller Group a development fee and
still use Hines to build the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
