<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5013 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.S.-680&AMP;ADD-NYT     08-14 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. URGED ARMS MONITOR TO AVOID CLASH WITH IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ariz.)  (lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and Britain urged Richard Butler,
the chairman of the U.N. arms-inspection team, not to have a
confrontation with Iraq by trying to hold a surprise inspection
after Baghdad suspended cooperation with the inspectors earlier
this month, senior U.S. and British officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials were responding to a Washington Post report on
Friday about private U.S. discussions with Butler and his decision
to drop plans for the inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Until Baghdad broke off cooperation with U.N. inspectors on Aug.
3, these officials said, they had supported Butler's plans to hold
surprise inspections at two sites that promised new information
about Iraq's chemical, biological and missile programs. Butler had
brought the necessary inspectors to Iraq when he arrived on Aug. 2,
intending to go ahead with the inspections.
</P>
<P>
   But on Aug. 3, once Iraq broke its February agreement with the
Security Council and the U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, to
cooperate fully with the inspectors, the officials said, they did
urge caution on Butler. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright sent
word to Butler that she wished to speak to him. After leaving
Baghdad, Butler traveled to Bahrain, where he could talk to her on
a secure line in the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that they were not eager to rush into a
``precipitate confrontation'' with Iraq that would focus on Butler
instead of Iraq's breach of its promise to the Security Council and
Annan. Nor did they want another military crisis with Iraq on
Baghdad's timetable, before Washington could prepare the political
and diplomatic ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``A confrontation on the ground in Iraq may prove a point, but
it doesn't get you closer to what you want to accomplish, which is
to help UNSCOM do what it needs to do,'' a senior Clinton
administration official said, referring to the U.N. Special
Commission on arms inspections. ``By keeping the focus on what Iraq
has done, which is to suspend inspections, rather than on what
Butler does, allows no country on the Security Council to contend,
as some have done over the last six months, that UNSCOM and Butler
have provoked Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, Albright denied reports that she
had been urging Butler, the chairman of the U.N. Special
Commission, for months to avoid confrontations with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had no change in our policy,'' said Albright. ``We
support UNSCOM in its inspections and fully support UNSCOM's right
to decide where, when and how it conducts its inspections.'' She
added: ``I do not tell Chairman Butler what to do. There should be
absolutely no doubt that the United States wants to see UNSCOM
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   She was responding to news reports, also broadcast on NBC
Nightly News on Thursday night, that Washington and London had
tried, over a period of months, to dissuade Butler from carrying
out surprise inspections in Iraq in order to avoid a new crisis
with Baghdad. The reports cited officials concerned that Washington
and London were undermining UNSCOM and arms control, a concern
expressed regularly by some UNSCOM officials who request anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Mike McCurry, emphasized that
although Butler takes advice from the Security Council, he makes
all operational decisions on whether to make an inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not our role,'' McCurry said. Asked whether U.S.
officials had suggested that certain inspections be delayed or
stopped, McCurry said: ``We consulted with them about the best way
to conduct their mission _ timing, outcomes, best way of achieving
their mission. But we don't order them not to conduct missions.''
</P>
<P>
   UNSCOM itself issued a press release saying that ``the
allegations are false.'' The statement denied that Butler ``has
been given or accepted external direction with respect to
operational activities'' of the commission and said he would ``find
it invidious were any attempt made to direct his operational
decisions or to micromanage the day-to-day work of the Special
Commission.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to the Post account, sometime in mid-July Butler met
with Peter Burleigh, the second-ranking U.S. delegate to the United
Nations. Burleigh read Butler a list of U.S. questions about the
planned raids. While Burleigh stressed that the decision was
Butler's, he left Butler, the Post said, ``with the plain
understanding that the United States did not support his plan.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official, after having read the guidance Burleigh
read to Butler, disputed the account, saying that the questions had
sought information about what Butler planned, and that Burleigh had
begun and ended the meeting with a statement of support for Butler
and his work.
</P>
<P>
   Butler intended to go ahead with the inspections, taking the
appropriate experts with him to Baghdad, said British, U.S. and
U.N. officials on Friday. It was only after Baghdad ``pulled the
plug'' on Butler on Aug. 3 that Washington and London suggested
that he avoid new inspections that Baghdad was going to block
anyway, and that he take up Iraq's breaking of its promises with
the Security Council first.
</P>
<P>
   Butler then made the tactical decision to pull out the
inspectors and informed Washington of that decision, the officials
insisted. One senior official said that Washington had expected
Iraq to pull the plug on Butler closer to October, when economic
sanctions are up for review. One reason, the official suggested,
might have been leaks to Baghdad about Butler's inspection plans.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., the chairman of the
House International Relations Committee, wrote Albright to ask for
a copy of Burleigh's talking points, ``as well as similar talking
points used by other administration officials,'' including herself,
in discussions with Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., wrote Clinton urging him to clarify
Iraq policy and reaffirm his commitment to eradicating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The officials insisted that UNSCOM had been making significant
progress in the last few months and had held as many as 10 surprise
inspections, which included one at Air Force headquarters that
produced a document leading to the discovery of Iraq's production
of VX nerve gas for missiles, which Iraq had denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been the most consistent and forceful proponent of
UNSCOM's right to conduct challenge inspections and to have full
access when and where it chooses,'' a senior U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that the burden is now on Annan and the
Security Council to get Iraq to keep its word and allow UNSCOM to
work freely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fault here clearly lies with Baghdad and not with
Butler,'' one official said. ``There's only one place to point the
finger. It strengthens our hand in the Security Council, it shows
the region that Washington is flexible and not eager to strike
militarily at Iraq, and it lays the foundation for military action
if necessary, while giving Saddam a chance to fold first in the
face of a truly united Security Council.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
