<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NASTYCAMPAIGN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush ad meant to be humorous, but MacKay isn't laughing
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Radio listeners began listening Friday
to what Jeb Bush is calling humorous while Buddy MacKay says it is
the beginning of the nasty campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-second ad accuses Lt. Gov. MacKay of being a lifelong
proponent of higher taxes. As an announcer lists a series of taxes
that MacKay has supported during his political career, other voices
express shock and dismay.
</P>
<P>
   One, an older women with a strong Southern accent says, ``I'm
getting steeeamed, Buddy.'' Others say ``Buddy'' in derisive tones.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign insists that the ad is factual and that the
humorous approach is intended to poke fun at MacKay's record, not
MacKay as a person. The MacKay campaign accepts neither
explanation. They accuse Bush of launching a negative attack on
MacKay and distorting his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been saying for months that everyone should run and
hide because we were going to be attacking them,'' said Robin
Rorapaugh, MacKay's campaign manager. ``Look who's attacking. This
is the death knell of the kinder, gentler Jeb Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spokesman, Cory Tilley, said MacKay, ``has asked voters
to judge him on his experience. That's what we're doing, in a
humorous way. We're looking at his experience, which has been to
try and raise every tax he's ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKay has promised that if elected governor, he will not raise
taxes during his first term. Rorapaugh says that MacKay has
supported tax increases during his political career but she adds
that an elected official cannot spend more 30 years in office
without at times seeing a need to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when it is the responsible thing to do,''
Rorapaugh said. ``This is just further evidence that Jeb Bush has a
total lack of understanding about what it means to be in public
life. He might check with members of his family who have been in
public life and broken promises to raise taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   She is referring to a pledge President Bush made during the 1988
campaign when he said, ``read my lips, no new taxes.'' Shortly into
his first term, Bush reneged on that promise. Jeb Bush, saying he
has learned from his father's mistake, says he wants to lower taxes
but has not made a promise not to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Jeb Bush is doing is distorting the facts and making
statements that are untrue and unfair,'' Rorapaugh said. ``This is
the kind of campaign voters have come to expect from Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley is a Palm Beach (Fla.) Post political editor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
