<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-DROWNEDVICTIM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Haitian woman who drowned could have been in U.S. legally
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Benette Dorsonne was running out of
hope, her family says. After waiting eight years for a visa to
leave Haiti and join her family in Delray Beach, the 26-year-old
woman sought a faster route.
</P>
<P>
   She traveled nearly 800 miles, but the last few yards cost her
her life.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsonne was one of two Haitians who drowned near Florida's
Jupiter Inlet Monday after a smuggler dumped a boatload of
immigrants on a sandbar and left them to swim the last 100 yards to
shore.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. State Department official calls the death ``almost a
Greek tragedy.'' He said Dorsonne could have been on her way to
American by now if she had answered a letter sent to her home in
Port-au-Prince last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never got a response,'' the official said Friday from the
U.S. Embassy in the Haitian capital. ``The missing piece is: where
was she in November?'' said the embassy staffer, who asked not to
be identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt the letter was ever sent,'' said Bruna Dorsonne, 24,
Benette's younger sister, who lives in Delray Beach. ``There is no
way she would miss something that important.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsonne's family said they saw Benette in Port-au-Prince last
month, at the same home where she had lived for several years and
at the same address where Benette's mother got her only visa
approval letter in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy official said Benette's file notes no contacts from
the family. Her father, Joseph Dorsonne, 56, said he and other
family members tried to contact the embassy on visits in past
years, but no one was ever available to talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsonne said he applied for Benette to come to the United
States on a family immigration visa in 1990. He also applied for
his wife, Jeann-Loretta, who emigrated on a visa in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsonne said the last he heard of Benette's application was in
October 1991 when he got a letter saying his petition was approved
_ but Benette would have to wait until her name came up in the
annual allotment of visas.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsonne's application did not qualify for first preference, a
category reserved for children of U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are a resident alien, you are at the lowest
priority,'' said Alfred Celcis, a Delray Beach paralegal who helped
Dorsonne fill out the visa petition for his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Time also worked against the Dorsonnes. Benette's 21st birthday,
in January 1993, dropped her another notch in the preference
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put her at the end of the line,'' said Dorsonne.
</P>
<P>
   He was more fortunate with getting a visa for his wife. Wives
and children under 21 fall into a larger allotment category.
</P>
<P>
   The number of immigrant visas allocated for adult children of
green card residents is 26,266 for 1998. Benette was competing with
applicants from all over the globe.
</P>
<P>
   A typical wait for applicants in that category is six years.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Benette had passed her eighth anniversary as an visa
applicant.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so frustrated because she had been waiting so long,''
said her brother, Vernel, 30, who immigrated to the United States
in 1983, three years after his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we went down there to see her, we could see that
frustration in her face,'' Vernel said. ``We didn't know if it
would be another 10, 20 or 30 years before she could come.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Haitians who sneak ashore during the dark of night
are part of the visa-weary, said Daniella Henry, coordinator of the
Haitian American Community Council in Delray Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been waiting eight or nine years and they don't want
to wait anymore,'' said Henry, who said Haiti's worsening economic
condition is driving this summer's increase in smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami immigration attorney, Cheryl Little, said complaints
against the U.S. Embassy's consular services in Haiti are common.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get anyone on the phone, you don't get your letters
answered and cases seem to get lost in the system,'' said Little,
who works with the Florida Immigration Advocacy Center.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Little wrote a report on the problem that she titled:
Haitian Children Awaiting Visas _ A Plea for Help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be time for another report,'' Little said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dorsonnes will bury their daughter in Delray Beach today,
following 10 a.m. services at the Our Lady of Perpetual Help
Haitian Catholic Church, 510 SW 8th Ave. in Delray Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Vernel Dorsonne said the family is now worrying about his
younger brother, Evens, 22, who applied for a visa to leave Haiti
along with Benette. They wonder if he will keep faith in the visa
allotment or follow Benette's path.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what's in his mind,'' said Vernel.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-14-98 2026E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
