<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILLER-SUICIDE-COX     08-14 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-SUICIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confessed killer jumps to his death from moving prison van
 &HT;    By Lillian Weis and Daniel Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ He had been calling all the shots for
the past two months as he confessed to killing five people in New
York and burying one of them outside Greenacres since 1985. But
when it came time to pay his penance, not even handcuffs, shackles
and a moving van could keep him from taking his own life as he
plunged about 65 feet to his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``My lessons here are learned- onto a better place now... I
Win,'' Gary Charles Evans, 43, of Troy, N.Y. wrote in a letter
delivered to his attorney Randolph F. Treece Friday afternon.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, a convicted antiques thief who has been arrested at least
23 times and has eight felony convictions, would have become the
third Death Row inmate since the state's 1995 death penalty law if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters pulled Evans' body from the Hudson River with a
boat where he was pronounced dead at the scene before noon Friday,
authorities said. He landed on the rocky edge of the Hudson River
in a foot of water, U.S. Marshals said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were traveling about 60 miles an hour when he apparently
threw both his feet through the window and shattered it,'' said
Troy Fire Chief Robert Essigan. ``Somehow he jumped out the window,
over the guardrail and into the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Essigan said Evans had his hands shackled behind him and his
feet chained when he was riding in the rear of a caged U.S.
Marshals van on what was supposed to be a 20-minute trip back from
a U.S. District Court in Albany. A second vehicle, also with two
deputy U.S. Marshals, followed the van driving Evans back to the
Rensselaer County Jail where he was being held without bail. Evans
had just been sentenced to two years for a federal parole violation
when the van crossed the Troy-Menands bridge about 11 a.m., and he
dove onto the roadway through the side window.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go off a bridge that high ..., the fall would have to kill
you,'' Essigan said. ``I got to him 10 minutes after he jumped and
he was already dead. He didn't drown.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both vehicles stopped and deputies chased Evans who hobbled to
the side of the road after heading towards one of the deputies
first before jumping off of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The first calls to firefighters were reports that a construction
worker had been hit by a car and knocked off the bridge. Passersby
saw Evans' orange coveralls and thought he was working on a road
crew. The two marshals escorting him called for help and watched
from the shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was really nothing they could do,'' Essigan said. ``This
guy was quite an escape artist. He was good, and I guess this was
his spectacular ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans told police he killed three of his childhood friends in
June and led them to their bodies including one in Palm Beach
County, Fla. Timothy Rysedorph, 39, of Saratoga Springs, had been
shot in the back of the head several times before Evans dismembered
his body with a chain saw in October, police said. Evans had been
charged with two counts of first-degree murder in Rysedorph's death
making him eligible for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   He was also charged with the shooting deaths of Damien Cuomo,
28, of Troy, on Dec. 27, 1989, and Michael Falco, 26, also of Troy,
in 1985. Palm Beach County sheriff's officials and New York State
Police unearthed Falco's skeletal remains in a wooded area on the
grounds of the Fountains Golf &AMP; Country Club on July 14th. Evans
told police he shot Falco in the back of the head 13 years ago, put
his body in the trunk of his friend's car and then drove him to
Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   ``He killed Michael when he was 26,'' said Elaine DiMauro,
Falco's former girlfriend and the mother of his two children _
Kelly, 18, and Justin, 16. ``He had a family and two children to
look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping he would go to jail,'' DiMauro said. ``Justice
still hasn't been served.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans had also confessed to the murders of two coin and jewelry
shop owners who he killed in Herkimer an Jefferson counties in 1989
and 1991. He had been traveling across the country before he was
arrested in St. Johnsbury, Vt. in May, police said. He was
extradited to New York after being charged with stealing antique
cufflinks worth $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the gates of hell are opening wide open for this
man,'' DiMauro, 37, of Sunrise said. ``The fires are burning pretty
crisp. I hope to God they sufficate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Weis and Daniel Moffett write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
