<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAREHOLDER-SUES-20TH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR SUES INSURER 20TH CENTURY OVER BUYOUT BY AIG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 &HT;    By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- An investor has sued 20th Century Industries,
saying it failed to protect shareholder interests as American
International Group Inc. took controlling interest of the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Investor Peter Salit claims in the suit filed in Los Angeles
Superior Court that officials of 20th Century, based in suburban
Woodland Hills, were fiduciarily irresponsible in failing to enact
a ``poison pill'' or other provision to ensure that New York-based
AIG would pay a premium for acquiring a controlling stake in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which seeks class-action status to represent other
20th Century shareholders, would require company officials to
protect non-AIG investor interests. It does not specify how that
should be done.
</P>
<P>
   Salit could not be reached for comment on the suit. Ric Hill,
20th Century spokesman, said Salit's action is at best misguided,
though he added that the company has not seen the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that businesses in California have to operate
in an environment where individuals, often for financial reasons,
are permitted to maintain a garden variety of lawsuits to try to
extract money from them,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   AIG in July took a controlling interest in 20th Century, 4{
years after bailing out the insurer when claims from the 1994
Northridge Earthquake devastated its balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   AIG has slowly bought shares in 20th Century since then, and
this month exercised several million warrants for stock, taking its
ownership above the 50 percent mark. AIG officials earlier this
week asked 20th Century to dissolve its board of directors so they
can appoint new ones.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
