<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-FDA-675&AMP;ADD-N     08-14 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-FDA-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT RULES THAT FDA CAN'T REGULATE CIGARETTES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal appeals court ruled on Friday that the Food and Drug
Administration does not have the authority to regulate cigarettes
or smokeless tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a setback to anti-smoking groups, state attorneys
general and members of Congress who saw federal regulation as the
most potent weapon to reform the cigarette industry and control how
it marketed cigarettes to teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2-1 decision on Friday, a three-judge panel of the 4th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va., overturned a
federal district judge's ruling of last year that upheld FDA
regulation of tobacco, a step that would allow government officials
to control cigarette nicotine levels.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the FDA declared that it had the authority to regulate
nicotine as a drug, and to regulate cigarettes as drug-delivery
devices. But the appeals panel ruled that the FDA needed explicit
authority from Congress to regulate tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   In a 58-page opinion, the panel's majority wrote that there is
``strong evidence that Congress has reserved for itself the
regulation of tobacco products rather than delegating that
regulation to the FDA.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Justice Department said on Friday that they
would appeal the ruling to the full appellate court. Some legal
experts said the question of tobacco regulation probably would end
up before the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's decision was the latest in a string of recent
courtroom victories for cigarette makers, and even some
anti-tobacco advocates and lawyers said legal momentum might have
swung toward the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reversal of three hard years of work by an awful lot
of people, and it didn't have to end up like this,'' said Richard
Scruggs, a lawyer from Pascagoula, Miss., who helped draft a
$368.5-billion settlement between cigarette makers and state
attorneys general that would have allowed FDA regulation. After the
settlement was taken up by Congress this year, it collapsed when
anti-tobacco advocates pressed for tougher sanctions against
cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, some lawyers and politicians who had helped draft
last year's deal said that Friday's decision suggested that
advocates may have miscalculated in pushing too hard in Congress
for harsher penalties against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Other anti-smoking advocates downplayed the decision, saying it
had been rendered by a court in the heart of tobacco country.
Others said that they would try to use the decision to pressure
Congress to enact legislation that would grant the FDA full
authority over tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This throws the ball back in Congress' court, and they have to
exercise their authority,'' said William Novelli, president of the
Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids, an advocacy group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, cigarette producers, who had challenged the
FDA's tobacco regulations, hailed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased by the court's ruling that the FDA does not
have the authority to regulate tobacco products and that the
agency's 1996 tobacco regulations are invalid,'' producers said in
a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   The producers added that they ``remained committed to taking
meaningful steps to reduce underage tobacco use.'' The companies
were in the case included the Philip Morris Cos., R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco, a unit of RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp., Brown &AMP; Williamson
Tobacco Corp., a subsidiary of BAT Industries and Lorillard
Tobacco, a subsidiary of the Loews Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will have no immediate impact on federal efforts to
regulate tobacco because it will be stayed pending appeal. But
should it withstand court challenges it could eliminate federal
money for programs intended to make it harder for young people to
buy cigarettes and would prevent any future efforts by FDA
officials to control nicotine levels in cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   More immediately, the decision could affect the new round of
settlement talks started recently between tobacco companies and
states that are suing producers to recover money spent treating
smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scruggs, the lawyer, said some state officials had been
demanding that producers drop their challenge to FDA authority in
exchange for legal peace. But now, he said, such demands were
likely to fall flat. ``The industry has the cards,'' he said.
``They stopped legislation. They stopped the FDA. They have the
momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Scruggs and Christine Gregoire, the Washington state attorney,
said they blamed some anti-smoking advocates for pushing cigarette
makers too far in the recent debate in Congress over last year's
accord. Under that plan, which was reached on June 20, 1997,
tobacco companies, in return for protection against some
smoking-related lawsuits, agreed, among other things, to submit to
some federal regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that history will reflect that June 20 was a golden
opportunity for major reform,'' Ms. Gregoire said.
</P>
<P>
   Some leading public health advocates like Dr. David Kessler, the
former commissioner of the FDA, had argued that the tobacco
regulations agreed to by industry negotiators last year were
inadequate. On Friday, Kessler, now the dean of the Yale University
Medical School, said he remained convinced that the courts would
eventually uphold the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that we learned from our investigation points to
the fact that nicotine is an addictive drug and nothing in this
opinion changes that,'' said Kessler. ``Nicotine fits the statutory
definition of a drug.''
</P>
<P>
   The stage for Friday's ruling was set when a federal judge in
North Carolina held last year that the FDA could regulate nicotine
as a drug and cigarettes as a drug-delivery devices, although he
denied the agency authority to control cigarette advertising.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge William L. Osteen Sr., in Greensboro, denied
the agency authority to control cigarette advertising.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, President Clinton hailed the ruling as a ``great
victory for the fight we have been waging for our children's
health.''
</P>
<P>
   While Osteen held that the FDA had the authority to regulate
tobacco because Congress had not clearly evidenced its intent to
withhold such power, the panel's majority said the question should
have been whether lawmakers had expressly delegated such powers to
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's decision was the latest legal victory chalked up by
cigarette producers. On Thursday, a Florida court raised doubts
about a landmark $1-million verdict against Brown &AMP; Williamson
Tobacco in a lawsuit brought by a smoker when it ruled that the
action should have been tried in the country where the smoker
lived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
