r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MGM-LOSING-INVESTORS-     08-14 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MGM-LOSING-INVESTORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MGM MONEY PROBLEMS DRIVING AWAY INVESTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hopes that the legendary Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer
studio will survive have dimmed in recent weeks, with investors
backing away from the struggling studio.
</P>
<P>
   MGM shares have lost nearly 25 percent of their value since July
29, when they traded at $20 a share, matching the price of November
1997's initial public offering. It closed Friday at $15.1875, down
$0.1875, at the lowest price since the IPO.
</P>
<P>
   The decline reflects a trio of concerns -- whether MGM can
compete effectively while spewing red ink, whether anyone will buy
the cash-starved studio, and the share dilution from a coming
rights offering to raise $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   The latest chapter in the long-running MGM drama unfolded with
the Aug. 5 disclosure that the studio had held buyout talks with
unidentified companies, believed to include Time Warner Inc., The
Walt Disney Co. and News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   News of a possible sale caused a slight run-up of the stock the
next day, but two other announcements -- a halt of new TV program
development and the disclosure that MGM had only $132 million left
of a $1.3 billion credit line issued in October 1997 -- dampened
any bullishness.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts have concluded that billionaire Kirk Kerkorian,
who controls 65 percent of MGM, may not necessarily sell MGM for a
third time but rather forge a partnership with a major TV power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the announcements as a signal that Kirk is
throwing in the towel,'' said Stewart Halpern, an analyst with ING
Barings Furman Selz. ``It's more in line with the strategy of a
joint venture giving MGM direct access to cable or enough clout to
get programs on to additional channels. That's consistent with what
MGM has been saying they would do all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Halpern, who retains a ``buy'' rating, said MGM's outlook will
improve in 2000 when it regains some of the TV rights to a large
portion of the MGM library from Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK15     08-14 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Jones has a flip side for almost everything
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Andruw Jones had just one single through the first
11 games of August.
</P>
<P>
   That's the downside. The upside: he hit three doubles, a triple
and four home runs, driven in eight runs and stole two bases. As
with everything else with Jones' 1998, there's another side. Add in
the fact that he's a leading candidate for a Gold Glove and the
same player that has burned Bobby Cox's biscuits several times this
season remains a central cog to his team.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good level,'' Jones assessed his season. ''Well, it's
not a good level. It's an alright level.''
</P>
<P>
   When play began Friday night, Jones was tied for the NL outfield
assists (14, with Pittsburgh's Jose Guillen). He was tied for the
NL triples lead (8, with Arizona's Karim Garcia) with eight. He led
the Braves in doubles (26) and stolen bases (15) and while his next
strikeout will he his 100th, his 214 total bases were third only to
Chipper Jones and Andres Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   ''He doesn't swing easy,'' said Cox, ''that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   What Jones continues to lack is consistency, his average
traveling from .250 to .270 and back down again all season. He is
far from the .231 hitter of 1997 but he has yet to show the .300
dependablity he did through 1,200 minor league at-bats. The start
of this seasn probably prevented that, after Jones suffered through
a dreadful .204 April that included a 2-for-40 start.
</P>
<P>
   Jones opened the Dodgers series at .259. Since April, he has hit
.274.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not good to slump any time but if you're going to slump,
it's better to slump early,'' Jones said. ''It's hard to have a
good season when you slump in the middle. My point is, if I need to
struggle, I hope it's early in the year and then come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bye-Bye Byrd
</P>
<P>
   Paul Byrd was claimed by the Philadelphia Phillies Friday, a
casualty of the Norm Charlton acquision, stamping a final grade on
the Greg McMichael trade of 21 months ago. Byrd, who had been 5-5
with a 3.69 ERA in 17 starts this year with Class AAA Richmond, had
been designated for assignment when the Braves purchased Charlton's
contract Tuesday and needed to open a spot on the 40-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd had just one Atlanta appearance this season (two runs given
up in two innings April 19 in Colorado) and finished his Braves
stint at 4-4 with a 5.56 ERA in 32 appearances. His future with the
club never recovered from the great 1997 bullpen purge, when he was
sent down July 12, 1997, in a group transaction that brought Kevin
Millwood, Mike Cather and Chad Fox to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Braves no have nothing to show for dealing away
McMichael, their primary set-up man from 1996 whom they sent to the
New York Mets for Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   No. 20
</P>
<P>
   In the last of a sequence of salutes for making the Hall of
Fame, Braves broadcaster Don Sutton's number 20 was retired by the
Los Angeles Dodgers in a ceremony before Friday night's game.
Though Sutton pitched for five major league clubs, 15 of his 23
seasons spent with the Dodgers. He joins Pee Wee Reese (1), Tommy
Lasorda (2), Duke Snider (4), Jim Gilliam (19), Walter Alston (24),
Sandy Koufax (32), Roy Campanella (39), Jackie Robinson (42) and
Don Drysdale (53) as the only Dodgers with retired numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Going to Cooperstown or winning 300 games, I could pre-plan,''
Sutton said. ''If I do this and that, I'll win 300 games. And if I
win 300 games, I'll probably go to the Hall of Fame. But this is
something I could ever plan for or think about or hope for. I don't
think a ball club can give a better pat-on-the-back than this. All
I ever wanted was someone to say, thanks for the effort. This far
exceeds that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thou shalt not surf
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko came home this weekend and all he could do was
watch. A TV crew had hoped to take Klesko out to the beach and film
him surfing some of the spots he surfed as a kid. But as stipulated
in the four-year contract he signed with the Braves last winter,
Klesko cannot surf during the season, due to the physical risks.
Klesko went out to Huntington Beach Friday anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ''I brought my surfboard. It was awfully tempting,'' he said.
''So I sat on the beach and moped. I watched a surf contest, ate a
bagel and read the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
