<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Singh leads the pack at PGA Championship
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Vijay Singh has another chance to be known as
something more than a driving range machine. Taking his practice
game to the course Friday, Singh equaled the Sahalee Country Club
course record of 66 established Thursday by Tiger Woods and grabbed
the early midway lead in the 80th PGA Championship at 4-under-par
136.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old from Fiji, who led the 1993 PGA at Inverness,
eventually finishing fourth and two strokes behind Paul Azinger,
pounded Sahalee on a day when tight pin placements often took
scores in the other direction. Erupting for a front-nine 30, Singh
assumed a one-stroke lead on a cluster of players that included
non-PGA Tour winner Scott Gump (69) and Scotland's Colin
Montgomerie, who bogeyed the difficult 18th for 3-under 67.
</P>
<P>
   First-round leader Tiger Woods shot a 2-over 72 to stand two
shots back at 138 along with 1995 champion Steve Elkington (69),
Andrew Magee (68) and Brad Faxon (68).
</P>
<P>
   Singh's nemesis is always the putter, which he currently is
handling with a left-hand-low approach, but Friday it treated him
kindly, allowing no three-putts. His longest birdie putt was from
20 feet on the 7th; his shortest from four feet on No. 1 and No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm putting well,'' Singh said. ``I have a good feel for the
greens. That's a good thing to have going into the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, desperate for a major, wasted his opportunity to
also equal the course record and tie Singh by bogeying the 475-yard
18th. Fresh off a putting lesson from Dave Pelz that corrected
serious alignment problems, Montgomerie built momentum on the back
nine by sinking a 25-footer for a birdie at the 14th and a
15-footer at the 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I'm not hitting the ball very well,'' said
Montgomerie, ``I'm still hitting it fairly straight. If I can putt
the same way on the weekend, I obviously have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Andrade, who started the day tied for second after an
opening 68 as the eighth alternate, slipped to a 77 and is at
5-over 145.
</P>
<P>
   Singh hit nine of 14 fairways, 14 of 18 greens and used 29
putts. After the flawless front nine, he made two bogeys on the
back nine. In the 1993 PGA, Singh registered a record 63 in the
second round, but then stalled over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure of a major is always different than a normal
tournament,'' Singh said, ``and I'm just going to go out there and
try to feel like (it's) a normal tournament as much as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Gump, who tied for 79th last year in his first PGA Championship,
got to 5-under, then bogeyed the 15th and 16th. Gump did not play
in the year's other majors, but does not sound unnerved by the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure to me is how well you're playing,'' said Gump. ``If
I'm playing well, not much is going to bother me. ... I lost my
(PGA Tour) card and had to get my card back on the Nike Tour.
That's pressure. Leading a tournament, that's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
