<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE TO GET J.C. ALL-AMERICAN HARRIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Junior college All-American Rico Harris is
expected to enroll at Cal State Northridge and play basketball for
the Matadors this season, a source said.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-9 forward from Temple City High School, Harris
initially signed with Arizona State in 1995 but was academically
ineligible as a freshman. In March 1996, he was arrested for
alleged involvement in a sexual assault case. No charges were
filed.
</P>
<P>
   Harris left ASU shortly thereafter and spent the past two
seasons at L.A. City College.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN coach Bobby Braswell declined to comment because Harris has
not signed a letter of intent and is a recruitable athlete until
the fall semester begins.
</P>
<P>
   Harris could not be reached for comment, but L.A. City coach
Mike Miller was surprised by the development.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first I've heard of it,'' Miller said. ``Nothing
against Northridge, but why would he go there? This is a kid that
Kentucky, Rhode Island and Connecticut were recruiting. He almost
went into the (NBA) draft. I had 17 NBA guys in here (last season)
looking at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any truth to it, it was done without my
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris orally committed to Rhode Island last summer but never
signed a letter of intent with Jim Harrick's Rams. He declared for
the '98 NBA Draft then withdrew _ allowing him to matriculate
anywhere with two years of eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Harris has completed the course work for his associates degree,
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rico's been a good citizen here,'' Miller added.
</P>
<P>
   Harris will be CSUN's best player _ indeed, the Big Sky's best
player _ the moment he steps on the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
