<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES RALLY WHILE STOCKS CONTINUE SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long-term Treasury rates fell to their lowest level
in 30 years Friday, but the stock market's increasingly painful
slide continued.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in yields and the decline in stocks could both be
traced to the economic crisis in Asia and the financial turmoil in
Russia, and the uncertainty they have fostered among U.S.
investors.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's slump, the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks
is now down more than 10 percent from its high, the Wall Street
definition of a correction. The Nasdaq composite index, which is
dominated by technology stocks, and the Russell index of 2,000
smaller-company stocks have already fallen more than 10 percent.
And the Dow Jones industrial average is just points away.
</P>
<P>
   But even the weak performance reflected in these indexes hides
the damage in the broader market and the pain that many investors
have been feeling. According to Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, the
stocks that trade on the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq
market are down an average of 35 percent from their 52-week highs.
Twenty-five percent of the stocks are down 50 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the troops instead of the generals, you are
in a bear market,'' said Thomas Galvin, chief investment officer at
Donaldson, Lufkin, and an analyst who expects the market to recover
in the fall. ``And the question is: How long will it persist?''
</P>
<P>
   While stocks are tumbling, the Treasury market is rallying, and
for some that is not a positive signal. For most of the last three
and half years, the bond market and the stock market have moved in
the same direction, responding to the positives of low inflation
and strong earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see stocks down and bonds up, the message is there is
a problem ahead for the economy,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief
investment officer at First Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have been hurt as the economic drag from Asia reduces the
corporate earnings that investors watch so closely. And each new
company that now warns of lower earnings, as Ciena Corp. did on
Friday, has a bigger impact.
</P>
<P>
   Asia is also slowing growth here and around the world. In
addition, the drop in demand for important commodities like oil and
copper is helping keep inflation low. Both of these trends _ and
the millions of investors who are looking for a haven for their
money _ are helping bonds and are likely to push long-term rates
even lower in the months ahead, several analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The predominant underlying fundamentals of a slowing world
economy and lower inflation are the real drivers that are going to
be here next month and the month after that,'' said Dan Lokoszka,
portfolio manager, global fixed income, at Wells Capital Management
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond finished at 5.54 percent,
down from 5.59 percent on Thursday and down from the previous low
of 5.58 percent on June 15. The price, which moves in the opposite
direction from the yield, rose 29/32, to 99 15/32.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 10-year note, which is a benchmark for
mortgages, fell to 5.39, from 5.44 on Thursday, but it is still
above its low of 5.35 percent on June 15. The interest rate on
30-year mortgages has been below 7 percent for eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward slower growth because of Asia, said Mickey
Levy, chief economist at Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities, should
keep Federal Reserve Board policy-makers on hold when they meet
next week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert DiClemente, chief U.S. economist at Salomon Smith Barney,
said he was working on scaling down his growth forecast for the
second half of the year. ``Big pockets of the world economy are
deteriorating around us,'' he said, adding that the yield on the
30-year bond could now move into a range of 5 percent to 5.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the stock market, the Dow fell 34.50 points, or 0.4 percent,
to 8,425, and is just 20 points away from a 10 percent correction.
The Dow had shot up almost 100 points at the opening, in part
because of a small rebound in the Russian markets and talks between
Russian officials and the United States and other countries about
more aid.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, officials in Hong Kong announced that they had
bought stocks to shore up the troubled market there. Rumors of the
announcement, which was made after the market closed, helped send
the Hang Seng index up 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dow lost its gains in the afternoon and would have been
down even more except that the stock of J.P. Morgan, which was once
again the subject of new takeover speculation, jumped 8.2 percent,
adding about 38 points to the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P index dropped 12.16 points, or 1.1 percent, to 1,062.75
and is now down 10.4 percent from its high of 1,186.75. The Nasdaq
index fell 12.35 points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,790.19 and is off
11.1 percent from its high. The Russell index fell 1.04 points, or
0.3 percent, to 402.79. It is down 18 percent from its high and is
off 7.8 percent for the year. The other major indexes are still up
for the year: the Dow, 6.5 percent; the S&AMP;P, 9.5 percent, and the
Nasdaq, 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the retail investor, who has kept
the bull market going in past downturns by buying on the dips, will
step in again and, if so, when.
</P>
<P>
   Abby Joseph Cohen, the co-chairwoman of the investment policy
committee at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., said investors are ``having a
hard time looking to September,'' when she thinks that the outlook
for earnings and the economy will be much better than it is now.
</P>
<P>
   Asia and the Clinton investigation are ``dominating our lives
right now,'' Galvin said. ``Speculation is rampant and the only
news is bad news.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
