<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-RANCH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS OFFERS BASKETBALL WORKSHOP AT HOOP RANCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where does Utah Jazz center Greg Ostertag go in the off-season
to learn the fine art of the sky hook?
</P>
<P>
   Where does former TCU sharpshooter Mike Jones go to turn himself
from an undrafted, too-slow-for-the-NBA shooter into a burgeoning
pro?
</P>
<P>
   They head out to the Basketball Ranch of Texas, where former
Mavericks guard Brad Davis helps pro players get better, teaches
would-be pros what they need to know to overcome the ``would-be''
and even works with youngsters wanting to make the high school
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very helpful to my game,'' said TCU point guard
Prince Fowler, who has been a ranch hand for the past month. ``I
know I'd rather do those individual workouts with them, because
they know what they're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Basketball Ranch of Texas is a joint venture by Davis and
business partner Herb Stephens, a longtime basketball-camp
instructor who was the girls coach at Paschal High School from 1981
to '86. And it's not really a ranch, but a one-on-one workshop
Davis and Stephens bring to their approximately 50 clients using
various sites throughout the Fort Worth-Dallas area. Their clients
include Ostertag; former TCU players Jones, James Penny and Dennis
Davis; SMU freshman Nigel Smith from Kennedale; and New Mexico
sophomore Greg Davis from Martin High School.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler, who has one season left with the Horned Frogs, has
already noticed some upgrades in his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned how to get low with the ball, shoot the floaters
over 7-footers and make good decisions with a simple pass,'' he
said. ``I'm also getting better in terms of working on my footwork,
pulling up for my shot, and reading the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The clients come mostly by word of mouth, Brad Davis said, and
pay $30 for every hour on instruction. He and Stephens teach
everything from the value of footwork, to the art of perfecting the
sky hook. That's what brought Ostertag to Davis and Stephens, as
well as wanting to improve his overall post play.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has been one of the program's greatest benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   After being shunned in the NBA draft in June because of his slow
footwork and inability to handle the basketball, Jones decided to
sign on with the Ranch. On Monday, he signed a one-year contract to
play basketball in Poland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've helped a lot with my footwork and increased the depth
of my shooting, so I think it's a good deal,'' Penny said. ``As for
Mike, I know they helped him a lot with his quickness, because
after going through the program he was a lot faster getting through
his moves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Basketball Ranch of Texas is the brainchild of Stephens, who
started the concept with 12 clients 2 1/2 years ago. Stephens was
finally able to convince Davis to join him earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Basketball Ranch of Texas is more of a philosophy, and the
philosophy is we're going to teach fundamentals,'' Stephens said.
``Brad and I are so much alike in regards to teaching the
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know every coach we've talked to say they spend so much time
on the team concept, and they don't have much time to work on the
individuals. Well, that's what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephens formerly ran a basketball camp in Kentucky, and he once
had center Brad Daugherty as one of his campers. Stephens said he
continued to work with Daugherty when he became an All-American at
North Carolina and during his rookie season with the Cleveland
Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad (Daugherty) told me back then that I needed to be doing
this for a living,'' Stephens said. ``He said he got more out of
working with me than he did with anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   So Stephens listened to Daugherty. Now, he hopes he'll get a
chance to work with another local center _ the Mavericks' Shawn
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big believer that you have to put weight on him,''
Stephens said. ``We think we can get him in here and we can get him
going, because what I particularly specialize in is big people and
the hook shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who played for the Mavericks from 1980 to '92, said the
Basketball Ranch concept fits his busy schedule. Each client goes
through a one-hour workout _ 30 minutes with Davis and 30 minutes
with Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every kid that comes in has a different need, and the first
time we have a kid for lessons we do evaluations for about the
first 15 minutes,'' Davis said. ``We talk to the kid, we talk to
his coach or his parents and see what they think he needs to work
on, and see what he thinks he needs to work on, and then we take it
from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every hour it changes. Every kid comes in with a different
need, so it's fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
