<SLUG> BC-CITRUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orange crop will be smaller, forcasters warn
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ This year's extended wet and dry spells
will mean a 10-percent decrease in Florida's upcoming orange crop,
according an influential consultant's forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The state's groves will produce 219.5 million 90-pound boxes of
oranges during the harvest season that starts in November,
Orlando-based Citrus Consulting International Inc. predicted in a
report to its grower clients Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That compares to this season's record 244 million boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news because there is a substantial amount of
inventory in the state of Florida right now,'' said Andy Taylor,
treasurer and controller for Caulkins Indiantown Citrus Co., which
grows primarily oranges on 16,000 acres in Martin County.
</P>
<P>
   A drop in orange output would end a two-year string of record
Florida harvests that has driven prices down and left storage tanks
full of surplus concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   As of Aug. 1, 175 million gallons of concentrated orange juice
were in storage, compared with 143 million gallons in storage at
this time last year, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The private forecast, historically the first reliable glimpse at
the coming crop, sent orange juice futures up 4 percent Friday.
Orange juice for September delivery closed Friday up more than 5
cents at $1.12 a pound on the New York Cotton Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Futures trader James Cordier said consumers can expect to see
that reflected in retail price hikes of up to 15 cents a gallon as
early as next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers are very quick to raise prices at the local level,''
said Cordier, a trader with Allendale Inc. in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture releases its first forecast
Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   While extreme weather in the first half of the year stressed
trees and caused them to drop more fruit than usual, a harvest or
219.5 million boxes still would represent Florida's third-largest
crop ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't anybody panic,'' Taylor said. ``There is still a lot of
juice to drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Waresh writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
