<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAY GIVE PUBLIC ADDRESS AFTER TESTIFYING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and his legal advisers wrestled
Friday with whether the president will speak publicly after he
describes his relationship with Monica Lewinsky to a federal grand
jury Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing that no decisions have been made, Clinton allies
said he is leaning toward acknowledging some sexual contact with
the former White House intern to the grand jury and arguing that he
technically did not lie in an earlier sworn statement denying
sexual relations with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an intense debate was underway among White House
officials and Clinton allies over whether he should give a brief,
public address once his unprecedented grand jury appearance was
over.
</P>
<P>
   One aide told The Associated Press there was a ``90 percent''
chance the president would speak publicly before flying to Martha's
Vineyard in Massachusetts on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the White House declined to discuss the president's
strategy considerations for his session with prosecutors, who are
investigating whether he had sex with Lewinsky, lied about it when
questioned under oath in the Paula Jones lawsuit, and urged others
to cover up the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are going to speculate going into this weekend
about events on Monday,'' said White House spokesman Mike McCurry.
``But we don't know what is going to be asked. We obviously don't
know what's going to be answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony Monday will be a central part of a report
independent counsel Kenneth Starr is preparing to send to Congress
outlining evidence of impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The president is to sit down with prosecutors at 1 p.m., EDT, in
the Map Room, a ground-floor room at the White House where
President Roosevelt kept track of developments during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Grand jurors will view the session by closed-circuit television
from the federal courthouse 12 blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Clinton will be two of his private attorneys, David
Kendall and Nicole Seligman, and White House counsel Charles F.C.
Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president would meet frequently with his legal
team through the weekend. ``I know that Mr. Kendall had been
somewhat concerned that he has not had the time (with Clinton) that
he had expected'' because the president has had to deal with the
Capitol shooting, the embassy bombings in Africa and the economic
crisis in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about reports that Clinton might acknowledge engaging in a
certain kind of sex with Lewinsky that would not contradict his
testimony in the Jones case, McCurry said he was uninformed. ``I
have no clue as to whether there is definitional jockeying going
on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear to me that the people who do know aren't
talking,'' McCurry said. ``They're not talking to us, they're not
talking to you, and so all of this is guesswork.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton adopts the sex-but-no-lie strategy and limits how
much he has to say about sex, he could avoid contradicting
Lewinsky's account of their affair. In her grand jury testimony two
weeks ago, she reportedly described a dozen White House sexual
encounters with the president. She also reportedly testified that
they discussed ways to hide their relationship but that Clinton
never suggested she lie under oath.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy would involve Clinton seeking semantic shelter
behind a definition of sexual relations used when he was questioned
in the sexual harassment lawsuit filed against him by Jones. A
federal judge limited the definition of sex to: ``Contact with the
genitalia, anus, groin, breast, inner thigh or buttock of any
person with an intent to arouse or gratify the sexual desire of any
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton allies have argued privately that the definition does
not include oral sex, an ambiguity that reportedly has been debated
during meetings of the president's legal team.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton critics Friday likened the proposed sex-but-no-lie
strategy to his admission earlier this decade that he once smoked
marijuana but did not inhale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strategy reinforces the impression that this fellow can
never be candid. It's a little too cute,'' said Bruce Fine, a
former associate deputy attorney general who has urged Congress to
convene impeachment hearings. ``If anything, this strategy could
make it worse for Clinton. It says this guy, even up to the 11th
hour, can't make a truthful contrition statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican with presidential
ambitions, said Clinton can't equivocate before the grand jury.
``His duty at his grand jury testimony on Monday is simple _ to
tell the truth,'' Ashcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president now testifies that he did have a sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky in the White House, it will mean
that he lied to the American public and that he lied on his oath in
court in the Paula Jones lawsuit,'' Ashcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   Former deputy White House counsel Lanny Davis, a longtime
Clinton ally, said the president ``will testify consistent with the
Paula Jones deposition, but I think he's likely to go somewhat
beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the president's position will be embraced by
the American public ``if he is perceived to be telling the truth,
whatever the truth is.''
</P>
<P>
   A new CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll found 56 percent of Americans
saying that if Clinton lied under oath as a witness in the Jones
case, that would be serious enough to consider removing him from
office. Only 31 percent said having a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky was serious enough to consider his removal.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 1,276 adults conducted from Monday through Wednesday
has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
