<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PERFORM-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A PERIOD OF LOSSES, SOME FUNDS FIND GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of what 3 money managers buy on the summer sell
off is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16)  
 (af)  
 By NOELLE KNOX   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From its peak on July 17 through last Tuesday, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index returned a negative 9.9 percent. Several
mutual funds, however, managed to return a tidy profit, testimony
to the proliferation of bear-market funds, which sell stocks and
index futures short to help returns in such times.
</P>
<P>
   Small surprise, then, that a 44-point spread separates the
best-performing fund from the worst.
</P>
<P>
   One curiosity is the presence of the Crabbe Huson Special fund
at the top of the losers' list. It dropped 21.6 percent over the
period, despite the fact that it had been widely pilloried for big
short positions in such high-flying stocks as Dell Computer and
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be ironic if they had gotten out of those
positions,'' said Laura Lallos, a senior analyst with Morningstar
Inc., the Chicago financial publisher. The fund's
small-capitalization holdings clearly would have hurt it over the
period because such stocks were punished brutally.
</P>
<P>
   A Crabbe Huson spokeswoman said the fund's managers, who also
run the lagging Crabbe Huson Small Cap fund, were unavailable for
comment last week.
</P>
<P>
   The no-load shares of the Safeco Small Company Stock fund
finished second from the bottom, losing 20.3 percent, disrupting
what would have been an otherwise strong year-to-date performance.
The Safeco fund, which is 18 months old, got clobbered on two
stocks in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Penederm, the fund's largest holding, is being acquired by Mylan
Laboratories Inc. and was hit by a government investigation into
allegations of price fixing by Mylan and other generic-drug makers.
Penederm shares fell from $23 on July 16 to $16.375 on Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   And Stage Stores, a clothing retailer based in Houston, posted
dismal second-quarter sales results on Aug. 6 and said that it
would have trouble meeting third-quarter estimates. The company,
which represented 3.2 percent of Safeco's holdings, fell to a low
of $9.875 that day; it had traded as high as $53.75 in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the names in the fund come back? I firmly believe so,''
said Greg Eisen, manager for Safeco Small Company Stock. ``When? I
don't know. I can only wait.''
</P>
<P>
   One new family of mutual funds found itself on both lists. The
Profunds Ultra Bear fund returned 22.9 percent between July 17 and
last Tuesday, while the Profunds Ultra Bull lost 19.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sapir, chief executive of Profunds, said the funds,
started last November, did exactly what they were supposed to do.
Profunds Ultra Bear, using options on stock index futures, is
intended to deliver a return that is equal to twice the negative
performance of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Profunds Ultra Bull is the mirror image of the Ultra Bear, using
derivatives as it seeks to double the S&AMP;P 500's positive returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
