<HEADLINE>
THREE NEW CASES OF `FLOCK WORKER'S LUNG` REPORTED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three new cases of a recently identified occupational lung
disease have been reported in Rhode Island and Massachusetts among
textile mill workers, bringing the total number of ``flock worker's
lung'' to 13 in the two states since its discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, the respiratory disorder has been diagnosed in three
men in their 20s and 30s by a University of Massachusetts Medical
Center physician and a Brown University researcher who discovered
the disease but was fired for insisting on his right to publicize
the finding.
</P>
<P>
   The two Rhode Island cases were diagnosed in May and July among
employees at the Pawtucket plant of Microfibres Inc., despite the
company's two-year effort to address scientists' and regulators'
concerns about a link between the ailment and making flocked fabric
for upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   The new cases ``must raise questions about the company's medical
surveillance and engineering interventions to date,'' said Dr.
David G. Kern, who was fired by Memorial Hospital of Rhode Island
last year. Kern remains at the hospital temporarily, and continues
to look for another job.
</P>
<P>
   John Woodhouse, spokesman for Microfibres, the world's largest
flocked fabric maker, said the firm has done everything recommended
by federal regulators and remains committed to solvingthe problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case of a company that is doing everything that we
can think of, and everything that anybody else seems to be able to
think of. Yet still, the nature and the cause of this condition
still eludes the best minds and the best experts,'' Woodhouse said.
Microfibres had initially hired Kern as an occupational health
consultant, but terminated his contract after he insisted on
publicizing his findings.
</P>
<P>
   Kern's battle to present his findings at a scientific meeting
last year drew support from occupational health specialists and
highlights increasing worries about research results being quashed
by industry and medical institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Other physicians welcomed Kern's willingness to face the
obstacles and cited benefits in their work.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Dr. Glenn Pransky of the University of
Massachusetts Medical Center diagnosed his latest patient with the
occupational lung disease. The center brought two others to the
attention of federal researchers earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pransky would not say where his patients live, or which textile
plants they work at, citing patient confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Pransky credited Kern for helping these patients get properly
diagnosed through the UMass occupational and environmental health
program. ``Had Dr. Kern not decided to come forth and publicize
this information, for all we know, these people might ... be
dead,'' said Pransky, who heads the program.
</P>
<P>
   The two latest Rhode Island cases are in addition to eight
others among Microfibres' employees that Kern identified and
reported to state and federal occupational health officials since
1996. Kern and colleagues report more details about those first
eight cases in today's Annals of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   While Kern has reported these two other cases to state, federal
and company officials, Woodhouse said only one has been confirmed
by a company specialist so far.
</P>
<P>
   Of the first eight workers diagnosed, Woodhouse said, six have
returned to work. Worldwide, the company has about 1,000 employees,
with about 175 of them at the Pawtucket plant. Woodhouse said
Microfibres has spent $1.5 million at the plant to investigate and
improve conditions as recommended by federal regulators, plus more
than another $3.5 million at its four other plants around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The work-related disease, first described as ``flock worker's
lung'' by federal health officials last year, results from
pulmonary inflammation that can lead to permanent scarring. Severe
coughing and difficulty in breathing are symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   The best treatment is for the worker to get out of the
manufacturing environment linked to the disease, researchers say,
although medications can also treat the symptoms. Researchers are
not sure what in the manufacturing process causes the disease.
Flocked fabric, a velvety material used in upholstery and toys, is
made from tiny nylon fibers applied to an adhesive-coated backing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
