<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-MUTINY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION SUBDUE MUTINY IN SHOOTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ The Revolution still have the worst record in Major
League Soccer. But they remain in playoff contention after holding
the Tampa Bay Mutiny to a 1-1 tie, then taking the post-match
shootout Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The point the Revolution earned gives them 20 points in 25
games, still 1 behind the Mutiny in the race for the final Eastern
Conference playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   And the Revolution's fortunes received a further boost with the
return of Jair, their most promising midfielder in the early part
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jair had been listed ``out for the season'' by MLS after
breaking his left ankle May 16. But he resumed training last month,
hoping to return to action by the Aug. 22 match against Los Angeles
at Foxboro Stadium. He entered the lineup a week early, replacing
Johnny Torres at the start of the second half and immediately
changing the dynamic of the Revolution offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution attack became less predictable. And though he
appeared to tire late in the second half, Jair was able to maintain
possession and put teammates in threatening positions.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Revolution took a first-half lead on an Ivan McKinley
goal, they seldom seemed capable of putting the game away. But they
were resourceful enough to remain in playoff contention, thanks to
some spectacular goalkeeping by Ian Feuer and McKinley's clinching
shootout goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution lost Oscar Pareja (hamstring) in the fifth minute
and failed to mount a cohesive attack in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's offense went through midfield and produced effective
buildups, especially through Mauricio Ramos and Paul Dougherty in
the middle and Frankie Hejduk on the right. But Feuer blocked
everything until the final minutes of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Feuer's first save stopped Steve Ralston from the goal area
after McKinley failed to clear a Hejduk cross in the ninth minute.
</P>
<P>
   A Hejduk run followed by a Roy Wegerle backheel set up Dougherty
to go in alone on Feuer five minutes later. Feuer made his most
spectacular stop on Alan Prampin, who flicked a Hejduk pass on the
edge of the goal area and drilled a scissors kick in the 34th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   The best Revolution attempts were speculative long-range drives
by defenders Edwin Gorter and Manny Motajo. David Nakhid replaced
Pareja, changing from his accustomed role as a defensive midfielder
to an attacking midfielder. The Revolution had difficulty adjusting
to the change but eventually threatened late in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Marcel Yonan whistled a foul instead of allowing play to
continue with Imad Baba in possession 40 yards from the goal. But
the Revolution capitalized as Gorter curled a free kick into the
middle of the penalty area. Raul Diaz Arce's header was punched out
by Thomas Ravelli, but McKinley followed for a 1-0 lead in the 38th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Ralston slid through the Revolution defense on
the edge of the penalty area, but Feuer pushed aside his low shot.
But in the 44th minute, Motajo flicked away a corner directly to
Wegerle, who quickly centered to Ralston, who headed in to tie the
score.
</P>
<P>
   Jair made his first appearance since May 16 at the start of the
second half and quickly changed the dynamics of the Revolution
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Jair brought some sensibility to midfield and displayed enough
strength and savvy to hold off defenders. He faked Dougherty to
open space, then split the defense with a 60-yard lead pass to Imad
Baba. Joe-Max Moore and Diaz Arce followed the play, and Diaz Arce
had a clear shot saved by Ravelli.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the half, Jair dribbled through two defenders in
the Revolution end, then set up Nakhid for a 25-yard drive which
was saved by Ravelli.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa had a clear chance to gain the lead, but substitute Paul
Young's rebound was high after Feuer halted Dougherty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
