BC-FINBUDGET-BC-FINBUDGET-FINBUDGETSF 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - FINBUDGET  Here are the finance stories the San Francisco Chronicle plans to
move for AMs and PMs of Saturday, August 15. For questions, please
call Georgie Dennison at 415-777-6055.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; HEALTH _  &LR; Larry Adelman, who operates a seven-person documentary
film company in San Francisco, was so upset by the latest statement
from the firm's health care provider that he had to sit down. The
provider had just notified him of a hefty 23 percent increase next
year. ``I was outraged,'' said Adelman. ``They couldn't give us any
explanation.'' Small companies like Adelman's aren't the only ones
grappling with climbing health insurance rates this year, but they
face steeper increases than larger firms. And they're left with the
tough choice of either cutting employee benefits or watching
monthly expenses soar. BY AMY DOAN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DIGITAL 15 &LR;  _ One of Germany's technology giants has dipped its toe
into the Silicon Valley venture pool by opening a $300 million fund
to invest in networking and telecommunications startups. Siemens AG
is a $70 billion industrial Frankenstein that grafts together 16
different divisions, including electric power generation,
chipmaking, computing and telephone equipment. Given its size and
complexity, Siemens isn't noted for speed, which is a liability in
the fast-moving telecom equipment business, where it competes with
U.S. firms like Lucent and Cisco Systems. That's why Siemens
executive Anthony Maher said the company chose Mustang Fund as the
name of its new venture arm, which will be headquartered in Santa
Clara. BY TOM ABATE
</P>
