<HEADER>
A5087 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-SFCHRON-HEALTH     08-14 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL FIRMS FEEL SQUEEZED BY ESCALATING MANAGED-CARE
PROVIDER  RATES 
 &HT;     BY AMY DOAN 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - HEALTH   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Larry Adelman, who operates a seven-person documentary film company
in San Francisco, was so upset by the latest statement from the
firm's health care provider that he had to sit down.
<P>
   The provider had just notified him of a hefty 23 percent
increase next year. ``I was outraged,'' said Adelman. ``They
couldn't give us any explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   Small companies like Adelman's aren't the only ones grappling
with climbing health insurance rates this year, but they face
steeper increases than larger firms. And they're left with the
tough choice of either cutting employee benefits or watching
monthly expenses soar.
</P>
<P>
   They also realize they have to pay the higher rates or risk
losing employees to firms that do offer such coverage.
</P>
<P>
   If Adelman's company, California Newsreel, sticks with its
current provider, the total monthly premium for the four employees
covered by the company plan will jump from $1,463 to $1,804 for
full coverage. California Newsreel pays 100 percent of the premiums
and Adelman says he won't shift the burden onto his employees.
</P>
<P>
   Many managed health care plans have kept premiums relatively
stable for the past few years, but they have been raising rates
recently to cover costs ranging from higher administrative expenses
to the price of trendy prescription drugs like Claritan and Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, companies are bracing for 6 percent
increases next year compared to 3 percent increases over the past
few years, according to a 1998 study by KPMG Peat Marwick.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is tougher for small businesses because they face
rates that are about 30 percent higher than what large companies
pay for equivalent plans, according to the National Federation of
Independent Businesses, a Washington, D.C., advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent federation survey, rising health costs is
the single biggest worry for business owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen increases before, but this is ridiculous. We're
running out of options,'' said Adelman, who has been running his
company since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   His health insurance provider, Anthem Health Care &AMP; Life
Insurance Co. in Piscataway, N.J., attributed the rise in
California Newsreel's rates to health care industry trends, but
acknowledged that small companies sometimes pay more than large
companies for identical coverage.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this disparity is that insurance agents receive
higher commissions for small company accounts than they do for
large company accounts, said Rich Phillips, a vice president and
actuary with Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual to see commissions of 8 to 10 percent for work
with smaller operations compared to 3 percent for large companies,
he said. The higher commissions reflect the fact small companies
bring in less revenues than larger firms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; John Bertko, a principal with Reden &AMP; Anders, an actuarial
analysis and health care consulting company in Berkeley, says
providers also charge small companies higher premiums because they
represent a statistically bigger risk.
</P>
<P>
   That's because many small or sole proprietor businesses,
especially those with younger employees, choose not to get any
health coverage. More than 30 percent of ``young companies'' don't
buy insurance, Bertko noted.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, small businesses that buy health insurance wind up
paying more because the pool of insured tilts toward older
employees who are more likely to have expensive illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the higher rates is that while large firms
have enough employees to insulate themselves from ``rate spikes,''
small companies can experience a jolt in rates when a single
employee has a high claim.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurers also say small companies are less predictable
due to the small number of employees covered and the fact that they
tend to have high job turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they're less easy to predict than a large company with
many employees, providers are going to err on the side of
conservativism because they need to protect themselves against
worst-case scenarios,'' said Anthem's Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, small-business owners say the situation is
unfair because they don't have the power to negotiate with
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When rates go up, it's small companies that get squeezed the
most because we have less clout,'' said Adelman.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Kaplan, owner of Ace Mailing, a 30-person company in San
Francisco, agrees. Kaplan, whose company uses Kaiser's medical
plan, said she just agreed to a 9 percent increase and has been
told to expect at least an 11 percent increase on top of that next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous concern _ I don't know if we can afford
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said that unlike large companies, which are ``courted''
by providers, her company has to ``sign whatever is put in front of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to the recent negotiations between Oakland-based
Kaiser and the California Public Employees Retirement System, one
of the biggest health-care purchasers in the country.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS in June agreed to a 10.75 percent increase in its Kaiser
premiums for next year compared to the 12 percent Kaiser had
initially asked for.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were able to throw their weight around in a way we just
can't,'' said Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   A Kaiser executive said that the 1.25 percent reduction did not
result from negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took another look at their senior population and found that
more of them could go into our Senior Advantage program, which
dropped the costs a bit,'' said Dean Kemp, who manages Kaiser's
plans with small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that we charge small companies higher rates because
they can't negotiate is just wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many small-business advocates maintain that the only way
they can get better rates is to pool together to increase their
purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
   A bill strongly backed &UR;  &LR; by House Republicans would allow small
businesses to join forces across the country to purchase health
care. Right now, businesses can pool together only within their
state.
</P>
<P>
   The Hastert Bill, named after Illinois Representative Dennis
Hastert, would let small businesses form ``Association Health
Plans,'' or ``health marts,'' as they're nicknamed. The bill, which
has cleared the House, is now awaiting a vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The plans might decrease rates for some businesses, because they
would effectively make the the risk pool _ the number of workers
that insurance companies base their expected expenses on _ bigger
and more predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Small companies could then spread the risk of illness and injury
across many workers and regions, just like large employers do.
</P>
<P>
   But detractors say it will simply force companies with low
health care expenditures to subsidize companies with higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   Others fear that a provision in the bill that eliminates the
need for state-by-state regulation will open the door for
underfunded, unreliable providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might help, but I'd be cautious about it, because it would
be hard for a few people in Washington to oversee all of these
companies, so you could have companies signing a bunch of
businesses onto their health plan and going belly-up,'' said
Borland.
</P>
<P>
   Another critic says the bill doesn't go far enough. ``What's
needed is a way for small companies to pool together with large
companies in their region _ then you'd get equitable rates,'' said
Wanda Jones, president of New Century Healthcare Institute in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
