<HEADER>
A5088 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MARKET-INVESTORS-2     08-14 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MARKET-INVESTORS-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE EAST SIDE, A MARKET BLOWOUT IS JUST A BREEZE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Ed: Please note subslug)  
 (af)  
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are many prisms through which to view the state
of the economy. Stock prices are the current fixation, of course.
But there are also consumer confidence figures, the long bond
perhaps. And then there is dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Sirio Maccioni, owner of Le Cirque 2000 on Manhattan's Upper
East Side, said he sold more filets of halibut, chocolate souffles
and creme brulees last week than he has in many, many months. At
neighboring Daniel, this summer has been the season of the $5,000
bottle of wine. Elaine's, the famous local watering hole, has been
selling filet mignon and martinis smartly every night.
</P>
<P>
   Correction? Up here, that could mean: ``Please recheck my bill.
You forgot to add my goat cheese tart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I have the impression when the market is bad people
just want to eat more,'' Maccioni said. ``In the last couple of
days, I have been really focusing on this issue, and I have to tell
you that I have seen more people drinking and eating than ever
before. Maybe they just want to be good sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, market experts would say, they've lost their minds. Gurus
and analysts aplenty contend that something has changed. That
reality is finally throwing its wet blanket onto a market long
fueled by euphoria. That with the Dow Jones industrial average down
9.8 percent from its peak just a month ago, the good times are
over.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Upper East Side _ where people think nothing of doing
their entire grocery shopping at the gourmet market on the corner,
where 28-year-old market mavens call nine-room apartments with
walk-in humidors their bachelor pads, where the goings-on along
Wall Street are watched with the same intense interest usually
reserved for one's loved ones _ sentiment remained strong last week
that the good times are now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still see all the signs of a bull market on the Upper East
Side,'' said Nicole Gresham Perry, a stockbroker who lives in the
East 80s with her husband, George Perry, a specialist in commercial
real estate deals. ``You still need a reservation to get in the
local hamburger joint, and the limos from Wall Street are lined up
outside it every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that people aren't watching the market's movements closely.
Some of the selling that has knocked stocks off their heights
emanated from this neighborhood, as profits were converted into
real estate holdings or, more often, plain green cash.
</P>
<P>
   But the much-talked-about wealth effect _ the translation of
money made on paper to money spent on stuff _ appears to be on an
almost giddy high, as if New York's aristocrats subconsciously
believe that spending in and of itself can help prevent a further,
and more serious, market correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as the market dived, the business here has been
phenomenal,'' said Christopher Dziadosz, manager of Eagles Antiques
on Madison Avenue at 83rd Street, as he leaned back into a wildly
expensive leather chair. It thrilled him, certainly, to sell dozens
of antique end tables and imported decorative pillows in the dead
of summer. But he acknowledged that he was also somewhat
frightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never see this kind of money coming in this time of year,''
Dziadosz said. ``I'm perplexed. If people are skittish, why are
they throwing hundreds of thousands of dollars at me?''
</P>
<P>
   Economists warn that the stalling of the bull market cannot help
but take a toll, eventually, on consumer spending. Indeed, with
more people than ever owning stocks, many experts say a big drop
would hurt the economy more now than in the past. And if so, New
York's economy _ in which Wall Street has become the biggest force
_ will feel the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants certainly recognize the connection. ``People have to
(italics)feel(end italics) rich,'' said Dziadosz, who recently sold
a $45,000 English table the day it arrived in his store _ about
three months and a day faster than he had expected. ``There is an
emotional tie. Sometimes a person isn't feeling great one day and
they decide not to redecorate their apartment, and then their
daughter marries a nice guy and suddenly they feel happy and come
in and buy, buy, buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember the 1920s, when everyone was partying before the
infamous fall? Or what about all those ill-timed real estate
purchases in early 1987? If people uptown are reflecting on the
past, it does not seem to scare them. In any event, stocks have not
yet fallen enough for average Americans, let alone the East Side's
upper crust, to be panicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nineteen eighty-seven was a real eye-opener to people,'' said
James Glassman, senior United States economist at Chase Manhattan
Bank. ``They learned that the market can have very sharp drops but
recover so dramatically that the average investor now views a
market drop as a buying opportunity. I think it will take a lot, a
very large correction, to really shake people up.''
</P>
<P>
   Of dozens of people working or living on the Upper East Side who
were interviewed last week, most said they were leaving their money
just where it was _ or even picking up some beaten-down stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am doing is staying put,'' said Diane Terman
Felenstein, a public relations executive who also runs a women's
investment club. ``I sold after the '87 crash. Then I wept. All
those companies came back. So now I am in for the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Leeds, who manages money at Buckingham Research Group
and lives on Fifth Avenue, shares his neighbors' views. ``This is
no time for panic,'' he said. ``Most people have gotten some cash
or bought some bonds, but I don't think anyone is running out of
the market. They are going to reinvest at a lower price.'' He is
giving similar advice to his clients.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Still others say they have no reason to worry about the market's
volatility. ``Business is wonderful,'' said Selda Chender, an
interior designer. As for stocks, Ms. Chender said she avoids all
equities. ``I lost too much money,'' she said. In 1987? ``No,
dear,'' she replied. ``In 1974.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Elliot, who owns women's and men's clothing stores bearing
his name on Madison Avenue, said he could judge what was happening
in the economy by which store had better sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman shops when she's happy, she shops when she's sad, she
shops when she's mad, she shops when she's glad,'' said Elliot,
holding court from a wooden chair in his women's store. ``When men
are sad, they drink themselves into a stupor. That is probably why
the men's business over the last week and a half dropped
dramatically and the women's business has been phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who have lived through decades of bull and bear
markets, a swift and sharp correction off a giant base can seem
almost inconsequential. ``You have to be practical and believe in
capitalism,'' said Arthur E. Crumlish, a salesman for a high-end
printing concern who lives off Park Avenue with his wife,
Gabrielle, a schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   Crumlish, 60, said he learned long ago not to liquidate stocks
in a panic, not to spend all his investment profits, and to believe
that a bear market is like an unwelcome guest who will ultimately
agree to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to try and hope you're in a situation where you're
assured of a basic existence,'' he said. ``I always wanted to be so
successful that you'd have to call me at the beach right now. But
the important thing is that we've raised the kids and sent them all
to college. I feel optimistic about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to call the beach to reach plenty of other East Siders
this time of year. ``People are definitely taking money out of the
market and are buying houses out here,'' said Andrea Ackerman,
managing partner of the Southampton office of Dunemere Associates
Real Estate, which serves a large Upper East Side clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ackerman said her record-breaking summer included sales in
East Hampton of a small cottage for $5 million and a luxury home
for $12.5 million _ neither of them on the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not the kind of negotiating on the asking price that
there used to be,'' she said. ``Chances are if someone comes down
10 percent, that is about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, the story is much the same. ``Over the last year,
a lot of people have taken money out of the market and bought their
dream house,'' said Barbara Corcoran, chairwoman of Corcoran Group,
the broker for 40 percent of the Upper East Side's luxury
apartments. ``Earlier, the market was our foe, because people were
making so much money they felt it would be too expensive to get
out,'' because they would miss out on further gains.
</P>
<P>
   Are people the slightest bit nervous? ``I am finding that our
clients are talking concerned but not acting concerned,'' Ms.
Corcoran said.
</P>
<P>
   What gives economists, retailers, manufacturers and other
participants in the American economy the jitters, of course, is the
prospect that the affluent may start to act on their concerns. And
at least some have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already reined in spending,'' said Ann Rapp, an art
dealer who was out shopping along Madison Avenue the other day.
``In the last few months, I've been cutting back on restaurants _
not that I can't still get a table at Mortimer's _ but I am cutting
back. On clothes too, definitely. You've got to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs of incipient inflation could send the stock market into a
steep plunge _ and the economy with it. Formal gauges of the cost
of living remain in check. But the Upper East Side has its own
measures, and, again, they involve food.
</P>
<P>
   Cemal Tezean, who has been selling fruit on the corner of Third
Avenue and 84th Street for three years, notes an annoying
connection between market drops and the price of cherries, grapes
and plums. ``Stock market down, fruit prices up!'' he declaimed.
``Last week, I get a box of grapes for $20; this week, same box
$28.'' Shoppers paid $1.25 a bunch, compared with $1 the previous
week. ``Customers complain,'' Tezean, 38, said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some people on the East Side who don't give the
financial markets the first thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear the bond guys crying,'' said Elaine Kaufman, owner of
Elaine's, the Second Avenue restaurant favored by novelists,
journalists and Woody Allen. ``The writers aren't affected by it;
they go on writing and just don't care. The small business owners
keep going. The computer geniuses don't care. These people are just
going on with their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
