<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-TELLABS-CIENA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A LITTLE ABRACADABRA, AND HOW THOSE NUMBERS FALL INTO PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16)  
 (af)  
 By KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing's more fun than watching a good magician. With a wave of
a wand and some sleight of hand, these conjurers create worlds in
which anything seems possible _ elephants vanish, ladies are sawed
in half and assistants levitate.
</P>
<P>
   But even David Copperfield could learn a trick or two from some
of the true masters of illusion: the financial wizards on Wall
Street and in corporate America. With a wave of a pen and some
sleight of hand, they can transform reality _ bad numbers vanish,
expenses are cut in half and earnings levitate. Shareholders rarely
notice these tricks _ which are perfectly legal _ until some of
their investment disappears.
</P>
<P>
   So today, let's part the curtain a bit, and reveal secrets
behind some of this financial hocus-pocus. One place to start is
the merger deal involving the Ciena Corp., which has attracted
praise for equipment that allows long-distance companies to
increase capacity significantly without new cables.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, Ciena has been rushing toward its merger with
Tellabs Inc., another company in the industry. For strategic
reasons, the deal makes sense: Tellabs needs Ciena's technology,
and Ciena needs Tellabs' customers.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder meetings to approve this deal are scheduled for
Friday, but last week Ciena tossed out some chilling news for
Tellabs stockholders: Its third-quarter earnings would be far below
analysts' expectations, in part because of a delay in a $25 million
order.
</P>
<P>
   How could this happen so suddenly? The simple answer is, it
didn't. Ciena's earnings have been deteriorating for months. And,
whether by accident or design, somebody has been keeping those
facts up their sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Like most tricks, this one can be fathomed by following one
simple rule: in this case, keep your eye on the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with what's known as the S-4 registration, which is
issued for use by shareholders in deciding whether to approve a
merger deal. In that document, there are signs that this deal was
being rushed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, take a look at page 18, where some of Ciena's
financial data are reported. The document reports numbers for the
six months that ended on April 30, as well as for the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As if they had disappeared, the second quarter's numbers are not
mentioned. Odd, since the document was filed with the Securities
and Exchange Commission well after Ciena reported its second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the numbers can't be figured out. By
subtracting the first quarter from the six-month total, a problem
comes up. The numbers indicate that Ciena reported a gross profit
of $36.8 million. But in the quarterly filing for that period,
Ciena reported almost $78.9 million in gross profit.
</P>
<P>
   Why the difference, particularly when it works to Ciena's
detriment? ``That's a typo,'' said Patrick H. Nettles, chief
executive of Ciena. ``That's a transcription error in preparing the
document.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough, and on Friday Ciena said it was correcting the
error in a new filing, shortly after it was pointed out to the
company. But the error raises a question, particularly about a
crucial deal document that Nettles says was reviewed by ``two audit
firms and a lot of lawyers.'' Was this deal of more than $7 billion
being rushed too fast, resulting in a $42 million typo?
</P>
<P>
   Sounds as if a closer look at the S-4 is in order. On the next
page, the document describes what the financial performance of a
combined Tellabs-Ciena would look like. The results seem just
dandy: Both companies earned 37 cents a share, and they are merging
in a one-for-one stock swap. A result, by this calculation, is that
shareholders would suffer no dilution in earnings per share and
would still enjoy their 37 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Careful, it's a trick. The secret, disclosed in a footnote, is
again that Ciena's second quarter disappeared. In combining the two
companies, which have different fiscal reporting periods, the
financial magicians used the quarter ended on April 3 for Tellabs,
and the quarter ended on Jan. 31 for Ciena.
</P>
<P>
   In those two 90-day periods, which had a bit less than 30 days
in common, both Ciena and Tellabs (italics)did(end italics) earn
their 37 cents.
</P>
<P>
   But compare Tellabs' quarter ending April 3 with Ciena's second
quarter, ending April 30 _ periods with more than 60 days in
common. Suddenly, the combined numbers don't look so good. Tellabs
still has its 37 cents, but Ciena's earnings per share drop to 29
cents, meaning that combining the companies would dilute earnings
for Tellabs holders.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who plow further into the S-4 will eventually find a
disclosure _ in the second-to-last sentence of a long paragraph on
a page of nothing but type _ that the proposed deal would indeed
dilute Tellabs earnings per share for 1998 and 1999. But why
weren't numbers used up front reflecting that?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ciena said that was a decision by Tellabs. A spokesman for
Tellabs said the earlier numbers were used on the advice of its
accountants. The spokesman added that the numbers provided a direct
comparison between the two companies' first fiscal quarters, even
though the dates were significantly different.
</P>
<P>
   By this point, it sounds as if it's time to take a close look at
Ciena's second quarter, a period of enormous struggle for the
company. Ciena's vulnerability has always been its small customer
base. In the first quarter it at least temporarily lost one of the
biggest, Worldcom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   By the second quarter, negotiations between Tellabs and Ciena
were under way, and on the day Ciena was announcing its earnings,
lawyers for Tellabs were distributing a draft of the merger
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A deal certainly would not have looked too tasty to Tellabs'
shareholders if Ciena's revenues were falling after the Worldcom
debacle _ and indeed they weren't. The company announced $142.7
million in second-quarter revenue, up from $134.3 million in the
first quarter. Even without Worldcom, the company was bringing in
more money. But earnings fell. (Remember the drop from 37 cents a
share to 29 cents?)
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the financial results should have raised questions about
the quality of those earnings. Accounts receivable _ revenue
counted in reported financials that did not yet translate into cash
in hand _ ballooned to their highest level ever, $132 million. That
translates into receivables being more than 80 days outstanding, up
from the usual range of about 30 to 50 days.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, such an expansion in accounts receivables is a
sign of trouble. Perhaps revenues are being recognized extremely
quickly, robbing the next quarter of profits; payment terms are
being loosened, increasing the risk of future losses, or a single
contract is making up a huge portion of earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Nettles indicated that the third possibility
was the answer. Ciena began shipping a new product in the second
quarter, he said, and one big buyer required a field test before
final acceptance. That test was completed near the end of the
quarter, he said, meaning that the revenue was recognized before
payment had been made.
</P>
<P>
   But that also means Ciena's other sales did worse in the second
quarter than the numbers indicated _ the impact, perhaps, of losing
Worldcom. If that had been mentioned in the S-4, it would have been
a clear sign that without another huge shipment of new equipment,
third-quarter revenue was likely to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies say they are still on course for a merger, but
the marketplace isn't so sure. Since the deal is a one-for-one
stock swap, the share prices for the two companies should be
tracking each other closely _ and indeed they had been.
</P>
<P>
   But _ oops! After Friday's announcement, the price of Ciena
dropped $17.0625, to $54.125, while Tellabs dropped $13.6875, to
$58.125, in NASDAQ trading. That $4 spread means the market is not
so sure the companies can get this deal done.
</P>
<P>
   So, what should investors do? Well, if they think the two
companies can still pull this rabbit out of their hat, they should
sell Tellabs and buy Ciena, locking in $4 of profit. Or, if they
think the deal will fall apart, they should probably just stay
away.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, one thing's for sure: It's going to be one
heck of a trick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
