<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT TO DISCLOSE FEW DETAILS, SOURCES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is prepared to tell a grand jury
Monday that he spent time alone with White House intern Monica S.
Lewinsky, and he is expected to discuss the nature of their
relationship while refusing to provide details to the independent
counsel, sources close to the president said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony may differ from sworn statements he made
Jan. 17 in the Paula Corbin Jones sexual harassment case and from
his finger-wagging public denial of a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   As anticipation built Friday about the president's grand jury
appearance, speculation was rampant around Washington that Clinton
was going to change his story and testify that he had had an
intimate relationship with Lewinsky. White House spokesman Michael
D. McCurry refused to confirm any of it. ``All this is guesswork,''
he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry did confirm that Clinton will testify at 1 p.m. Monday
in the historic White House Map Room, where Franklin Roosevelt
followed World War II.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony, expected to be completed in a day, will be
broadcast live to the grand jury at US District Courthouse about a
mile from the White House, via a one-way video feed. It will not be
made public.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said he was uncertain how long the testimony would last,
but he guessed it would be several hours. He said it was unclear if
Clinton would make any public statement about his testimony before
heading off to Martha's Vineyard late Monday night or early Tuesday
for a planned two-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the president's advisers, both within and outside the
White House, have urged Clinton to come forward and speak to the
American people before his testimony is leaked to the news media
and interpreted by his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of private lawyers and the first lady, who are
protected by legal privileges, are privy to the details of
Clinton's story and his decisions on what to say. His political
advisers have been trying to assess the consequences of the
unprecedented appearance on his presidency without full knowledge
of the facts.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them, nonetheless, have reportedly urged Clinton to
acknowledge some type of relationship with Lewinsky, even if it was
a sexual relationship. As that argument goes, Clinton would not
necessarily be contradicting his deposition in the Jones case
because the definition of sexual relations approved by US District
Judge Susan Webber Wright would be different from what may have
occurred between him and Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Lewinsky, 25, reportedly testified to numerous sexual
encounters with Clinton in the White House over an 18-month period.
She said she did not believe he encouraged her to lie under oath,
though they explored ways to keep the relationship a secret. She
has turned over a navy blue dress thought to contain genetic
material that may match Clinton's DNA. The dress has been sent to
an FBI lab for testing.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Clinton said he wants to avoid providing
details that may appeal to more purient interests, and that he
feels may not be relevant to the perjury and obstruction of justice
aspects of the probe.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, those sources said, his lawyers may object to
certain questions during the grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Under special arrangements made with independent counsel Kenneth
W. Starr's office, Clinton will be accompanied by his attorneys for
his testimony, unlike other witnesses who go before grand juries.
The president's two private lawyers, David E. Kendall and his
partner, Nicole K. Seligman, will be present.
</P>
<P>
   White House General Counsel Charles F. Ruff, who has sat in when
Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton previously have given testimony
to Starr, also will be there. The testimony will be videotaped by
the White House Communications Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Clinton would answer all the questions, McCurry said,
``I don't know why he wouldn't. He's under oath. The truth is the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to testify, and it's a consequential thing when you
go before a grand jury. But we don't know what is going to be
asked. We obviously don't know what's going to be answered,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry joked about the rampant speculation about what Clinton
will say to the grand jury. ``It's kind of like going into Super
Bowl weekend,'' he told reporters. ``You read every coach's or
ex-coach's idea of what the winn
</P>
</TEXT>
