<HEADLINE>
SINGH GRABS THE LEAD AT SAHALEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ They always seem to forget Vijay Singh when
they talk about the best players who have never won a major golf
championship. They shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   There he was in Friday's second round of the 80th PGA
Championship at Sahalee CC, grabbing the lead in the early hours of
a long sorting-out process. He checked in with a
course-record-tying 66 for a 4-under-par 136 total and and headed
to the practice range.
</P>
<P>
   This is Singh's trademark. Nobody spends more time at the range,
on the putting green, or striving to win. ``I like to practice,''
said Singh. ``There's always something you can work on. If it's not
the long game, it's the short game. Or the putting. You can never
practice enough putting. I just like to practice and I'm always
working on something out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh had left the practice range by the time Steve Stricker
seized the lead with a birdie on the 16th. But Stricker took a
double bogey on the 17th and Singh's score stood up by a shot over
Stricker (68), Colin Montgomerie (67), and Scott Gump (69). The
grouping at 138 included Rhode Island's Brad Faxon (68),
Australia's Steve Elkington (69), Andrew Magee (68), defender Davis
Love III (68), and first-round leader Tiger Woods (72), who had set
the course record Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Singh opened with birdies on the first (9-iron, 4 feet) and
second (two putts) and added birdies on the fourth (wedge, 12
feet), seventh (8-iron, 20 feet), and ninth (5-iron, 4 feet) to
make the turn in 30. The lid came off briefly on the 11th when he
bogeyed by taking two putts from 10 feet. After a birdie on the
13th when he hit an 8-iron tee shot to 8 feet, he bogeyed the 17th
out of a bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key was the start of my round,'' said the native
of Fiji. ``I kept my round going from there on, and that gave me
confidence. I hit a lot more greens today than I did Friday, and
obviously, I putted a lot better. You've got to putt well on greens
like this. It's getting hard and fast. If you're on the correct
side of the pin, you have a good chance of making birdies. That's
what I did today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gump quietly slipped into the top group and could have led
outright except for bogeys on the 15th and 16th. ``I had a chance
to space myself a little bit,'' said Gump. ``I haven't been in this
position too many times, so I'm having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He is noted as one of the most accurate drivers on the PGA Tour,
and Sahalee is a course that demands accuracy. ``That's mu strong
point,'' said Gump. ``I just stayed patient, hit fairways, hit the
greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie finished with a bogey on the 18th but is where he
wants to be entering the weekend. ``I think I've gotten the best
out the first two rounds that I could do,'' he said of a round that
included a birdie on the 16th, leaving him 4 under. ``Putting today
was good. I had a number of 20-footers that went in. Where the pins
were tricky, I just played conservatively and played percentage
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Faxon seemed on his way to a vintage round but found the left
rough on the 18th and had to play a safe shot out to the right side
of the fairway. He ended up missing a par putt from 15 feet. ``I
played very well today,'' said Faxon. ``It's a little like Pebble
Beach. You have to get off to a good start. I'm excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods encountered trouble on the second when his second shot on
the par-5, 507-yard hole went over the green and he ended up
lipping out on a misread putt for par. He bogeyed the fourth and
sixth before running off eight straight pars that preceded a bogey
on the 15th. He birdied the 16th to stay in the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those rounds where I didn't hit the ball
particularly well,'' said Woods. ``I didn't give myself a lot of
chances for birdies, but I hung in there and my short game was
great today. I made a lot of good saves. I'm pleased to shoot 72
the way I hit the ball all day. I'm only two back, and that's
perfect. That's where I really need to be. If they put a lot of
water on the course with the (predicted) cooler conditions, it will
play really soft. If they don't, it will be firm and very fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
