<SLUG> BC-CIENA-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO WOULD-BE PARTNERS SEE SHARES PLUNGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of two makers of telecommunications equipment, Ciena
Corp. and Tellabs Inc., partners in a pending $7.1 billion merger,
plunged Friday, after Ciena announced that its third-quarter
profits would be less than half what had been expected.
</P>
<P>
   Investors stampeded out of the stocks on speculation that
Tellabs' acquisition of Ciena, which had been approved by both
companies' boards, would be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq market, shares of Ciena fell $17.625, or 23.9
percent, to $54.125, while Tellabs shares dropped $13.6875, or 19
percent, to $58.125. The two stocks were the most actively traded
Friday on U.S. markets. When the deal, a one-for-one stock swap,
was announced in June, a mere 62.5 cents separated the value of the
two stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing with analysts, the chief executive of Tellabs,
Michael Birck, tried to put investors' fears to rest, stressing
repeatedly that both companies had reaffirmed their commitment to
the deal being completed. He also said that the acquisition would
still be for the long-term good of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had long considered Ciena's operations to be high risk,
but few expected the company to post such a setback. Ciena, which
makes equipment that can increase the capacity of long-distance
networks by a factor of 16 or more, warned that its third-quarter
profit would fall between 13 cents and 15 cents a share. According
to a survey by First Call Corp., an investment research company,
analysts had expected Ciena to earn 32 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Nettles, Ciena's chief executive, attributed his
company's troubles to a delay in a $25 million order and a major
discount that was given to a large customer in exchange for future
volume sales. After listing these problems, Nettles added, ``Our
business is sound; our market is sound.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ciena's unexpected shortfall in earnings has raised
suspicions that its operations are not as sound, and its
market-leading equipment is not as immune to competitors, as was
once believed. Lucent Technologies, North America's largest maker
of telecommunications equipment, would love to oust Ciena as the
lead maker of its product.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had other worries. Awarding a steep discount to one
customer suggested that Ciena's market lead for its equipment was
not very large. There were also doubts about whether Ciena would
land a large contract with AT&AMP;T, the United States' largest phone
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most upsetting thing about Ciena's announcement is the
deterioration of the company's gross margins,'' said Michael
Neiberg, an analyst with Ing Barings Furman Selz. ``They need to be
over 50, but we think in the third quarter they dropped to the mid-
to low 40s.''
</P>
<P>
   Ciena, though, should fare well from its acquisition by Tellabs.
Ciena, which has a small number of products and a limited
distribution system, would remedy both shortcomings with the deal.
Tellabs, which makes systems that allow circuits to communicate
without being soldered together, would immediately become the
market leader in wave division multiplexing equipment, Ciena's
product line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the merger to take place and to go through at the
original terms,'' said Steven Levy, managing director at Lehman
Brothers. ``With this deal, Ciena reduces the risk that some
customer can say: `Poof. Give me a discount or I won't buy anything
more from you.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
