<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-3FAMILY-ART-2T     08-14 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-3FAMILY-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG-HORIZON MANTRA, WITH A CHORUS OF `DIVERSIFY' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., N.Y., Pa., Fla., Minn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16.)  
 (af)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON and ROY FURCHGOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)In light of the market's recent declines, The New York
Times interviewed three families with differing investment
philosophies to see what, if any, adjustments they were making. The
Times also asked certified financial planners to review the
portfolios and, if needed, make recommendations. The results
suggest that investors have convinced themselves that sticking with
stocks is the conservative thing to do.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roger Pettett, a retailer in Phoenix who owns about 70 stocks,
doesn't panic anymore when the market's down. ``I'm not selling or
even thinking about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is a big change in attitude. Pettett, 58, said that until
about a year ago, he had been ``a real hair-trigger'' investor _
making as many as 100 trades annually, buying a stock, then bailing
at the first hint of trouble, only to watch it recover and then
some.
</P>
<P>
   He blames his behavior on his business: retail close-outs. His
chain of Back Alley stores sells surplus goods at bargain prices.
``I'm used to getting in and out and making a quick buck,'' he
said. ``I tried the same thing with stocks, and it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, as a long-term move, Pettett put half of his
mid-six-figure investment account into blue-chip companies with
dividend reinvestment plans. He split the money among 30 or so
stocks, including Compaq Computer and Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of his stock holdings are in about 40 growth stocks,
more than a dozen of them small Arizona companies. Over all, about
85 percent of his money is invested in stocks; the rest is in bank
certificates of deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Pettett, who is married and has four grown children, wonders why
he didn't adopt a buy-and-hold strategy sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are raised. The house is paid,'' he mused. ``I don't
have the pressure on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing Pettett's investments, Stephen Barnes, a fee-only
certified financial planner in Phoenix, didn't see a need to make
major changes. ``I get the feeling the portfolio you've built is
consistent with the risk you can withstand,'' he told Pettett. ``As
long as that's the case, you'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Barnes recommended some fine-tuning: cutting the number
of stocks; diversifying by moving into other asset classes, like
foreign stocks or real estate, and adding bonds for some stability.
</P>
<P>
   Pettett said he had already trimmed his stock holdings, though
``it does need more.'' He is interested in foreign stocks and says
his next move may be into a fund of Japanese stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Gilbertson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alan and Vicki Schechter of Dix Hills, N.Y., were vacationing in
Lake Louise, Alberta, when the Dow swooned 299 points on Aug. 4.
Hearing the news, Schechter, 51, chief financial officer at
Lutheran Medical Center in Brooklyn, called in to check his
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got aggravated,'' said Ms. Schechter, 49, a librarian at
Frank P. Long Intermediate School in Bellport, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just lasted for a second,'' her husband responded. ``The
scenery was too pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could have mellowed Schechter during the market meltdown
11 years ago. Though he preaches the gospel of buying on dips, his
reaction to the October 1987 crash was to sell _ a lot. ``I really
regretted doing it,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   So despite the latest downturn, which was much less severe, the
Schechters are not changing their investment mix, which they call
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Each has an employer-sponsored retirement plan, invested mainly
in Fidelity Investment funds like Fidelity Fund, Equity-Income II
and Growth and Income. They also have a brokerage account with
about nine stocks, including Microsoft, IBM and Pfizer; index
funds, and a tax-exempt money-market fund.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Schechter said he might use some of those cash reserves to buy
more shares of stocks he owns that are off their highs.
</P>
<P>
   With their two children finished with school, the couple's main
objective is financial independence. Given their aggressive saving
_ the two have contributed 10 percent of their annual salaries over
the last 30 years to their retirement plans _ and the market's
great run, Schechter thinks they are close to their goal,
regardless what the market does in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the Schechters' portfolio, George Toth, a certified
financial planner at Chestnut Investment Advisory in Erdenheim,
Pa., said the couple did a ``great job'' of accumulating assets
through disciplined investing. But he was concerned that they might
have too much money in large stocks and large-stock mutual funds,
both of which track the market and put them at more risk than they
might realize.
</P>
<P>
   For diversification, he suggested putting about 15 percent of
their retirement money in a convertible bond fund _ at least
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Toth also said the Schechters needed to figure out their
downside risk and set price targets for their stocks and funds _
and to get out if those targets were hit.
</P>
<P>
   Schechter dismissed the recommendation to diversify (``The
economy was built on these large, well-capitalized companies'') and
added that he didn't need to set price floors because he's a
long-term holder. ``Over a 5-to-10-year period, I think they're all
going to rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Gilbertson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frank Leon, 46, a regional sales manager in Coral Springs, Fla.,
for the software maker Visiontek, offers this market advice: don't
shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then in '87, there were guys who shot themselves, guys
who shot their stockbrokers; if they had just waited a few weeks,
it would have changed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Faith in long-term prospects has allowed Leon and his wife,
Darlene, 41, to endure the market's recent swings calmly. Such
equanimity is especially impressive because Leon accepted an
early-retirement package from Motorola last year and has since seen
the company's stock _ he owns about 3,500 shares or options _ fall
from a high of about $80 to about $50 today.
</P>
<P>
   Leon began investing in stocks in the early 1980s, putting money
into technology stocks and amassing a portfolio worth about
$180,000. He also contributed the maximum to his 401(k), which was
worth $316,000 when he left last September after 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Leon also has about $17,000 in an individual retirement
account from a marketing job at Mitel, a telecommunications
company, which she left about 14 years ago to raise their children,
Danielle, now 13, and Jenna, now 9. After Leon retired, the couple
put their combined assets in the hands of a certified professional
planner, Ernie G. McMullen of Noble International Investment in
Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``The portfolio was really nondiversified,'' McMullen said. But
the Leons had little debt, except for a $185,000 home mortgage.
Since they had prepaid about $60,000 for their children's college
tuition, the Leons' goal was to save for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen cut the concentration on technology. He also
reallocated several international funds Leon had bought, moving
into mostly long-term growth and international growth funds.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months McMullen has also built cash to nearly 20
percent of the portfolio, as a defensive measure.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the portfolio, Bob Klosterman, president of White Oaks
Wealth Advisors in Minneapolis, agreed with many of the fund picks,
but recommended further diversification and _ despite the market's
recent wobbling _ a reduction in cash.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested trimming Leon's Motorola holdings. But if Leon
cashes out before September, the proceeds will be taxed as income;
if he waits, it will be taxed at the lower capital-gains rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to weigh between 20 percent tax and 20
percent loss,'' Klosterman said.
</P>
<P>
   Unworried, Leon is standing pat. ``If you look at the pattern of
the market from 1900, it always goes up,'' he said. Plus, he
doesn't own a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Furchgott
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
