<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GRANDJURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRAND JURY: AN UNPLEASANT MEMORY FOR CLINTON AIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-DEFENSE, CLINTON-ISOLATION, CLINTON-NH-VOICES)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``I came to call it the `Darkness at Noon' suite,''
said Sidney Blumenthal, President Clinton's communications
coordinator, grimly recalling the bland yet fearsome grand jury
room where dozens of administration workers have been questioned by
federal prosecutors these past seven months, 12 blocks east of the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton believers who grandly imagined capping their careers
as public servants at the West Wing inner sanctum of power, their
unexpected detour to the grand jury of Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr, has provided a starker White House memento than they ever
bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an experience I wouldn't wish on my worst enemy,'' said
former White House chief of staff Leon Panetta, who was among the
many administration witnesses summoned. ``First, that gauntlet of
intimidation outside,'' he recalled, referring to the crowd of news
media encamped on the courthouse sidewalks since January. ``And
then going into what is a pretty cold place _ a building that's a
throwback to the days of J. Edgar Hoover _ and waiting alone in a
barren hallway to be called in for the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance before the Starr grand jury Monday will be
significantly different from the experience his underlings have
been enduring. For one thing, he will remain in the White House,
far from the media gauntlet, and he will testify by remote
television hookup, with the 23-member grand jury listening and
watching his testimony elsewhere in their own closed room. For
another, the president, far from testifying alone as is the grand
jury norm, will have a lawyer on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Officials will not discuss details of the secret session, but
the television signal of Clinton under oath is expected to involve
state-of-electronics encryption to foil possible snoops.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether the grand jurors will have free rein
to ask him questions or be limited at best to channeling them
through the prosecuting staff. In any case, witnesses describe the
grand jury as just the sort of cross-section audience that Clinton
favors as a speaker _ mostly African-American, tending toward 50
years of age and older, with more women than men, according to the
accounts of several witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The soundproof, if not quite leakproof, grand jury room on the
third floor of the E. Barrett Prettyman courthouse has come to loom
gothically over the White House as the jurors tracked Starr's
pursuit of the president. A wide assortment of anxious Clinton
aides, bodyguards and factotums have been summoned and ordered to
answer honestly under the standard court oath _ ``so help you
God.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury, which needs 16 members for a quorum, has sat as
a watchful, sometimes openly curious panel of anonymous city
residents quietly gauging the truth of what they hear.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, charged to operate in secrecy, was convened last
September to handle the waning phase of the dry, complex Whitewater
inquiry into the decade-old land and political dealings of Clinton
as governor of Arkansas. But the jurors were jolted onto a
sensational tangent in January when the sex-and-mendacity
allegations involving former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
were first directed at the president and assigned to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Those few witnesses who care to recall the grand jury experience
offer widely differing impressions about the long-running tattoo of
questions and answers. To track the proceedings, jury members have
taken personal notes that are locked away by federal marshals after
each session. Eventually the notes will be destroyed, with jurors
sworn to a permanent secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   A few witnesses cite frightening, bare-knuckled questioning by
the Starr assistants as jurors listened passively. Others recall
jurors bored to sleepiness by repetitious questions, a prosecutor's
technique that wary White House witnesses were alert to as a
possible perjury-trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time you're kind of nervous, but like everything
else it becomes routine,'' said former Clinton political strategist
George Stephanopoulos, sounding resigned to the multiple grand jury
visits _ three in his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I saw REM sleep from a few during my stint,'' one
witness said. Another recalled the scene as gray and bureaucratic.
Jurors would be marched out for coffee breaks as the lawyers
reloaded their questions for the difficult, tedious mission of
strafing for chinks in the presidential armor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surprising thing is the common impression of Ken Starr,''
said Blumenthal, who appeared three times. ``That impression _
Starr's obsessional pursuit, his bearing down on witnesses, getting
blood from the stone _ none of that ever happened. To my knowledge,
as we say in the grand jury, Starr's never there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But that has largely proved beside the point to the many Clinton
supporters subpoenaed under Starr's signature to face assistants
far more experienced than he is in the sharp-edged art of grand
jury inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Some witnesses found the jury members mute vassals of a
prosecutor who asked all the questions. ``It's the proverbial grand
jury ready to indict a ham sandwich,'' said one witness, speaking
anonymously and angrily. ``They're Starr's to shape, and they show
no sign they could be in control of this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses recall surprising moments of grand jury spunk.
Bob Weiner, a White House aide subpoenaed by Starr, described being
peppered by nonstop rephrasings of the same question even as he
sought to exercise his right to take a break and confer with his
attorney waiting, as allowed by law, outside the jury room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, some woman on the jury simply interrupted and said,
`We'll take a 10-minute recess now,''' said Weiner, rating the
moment a scrap of mercy in a thoroughly unpleasant experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``A horrendous situation, and you feel it in your gut,'' he
said. ``You feel very much beyond your pay grade, a pawn in a game
of Get-the-President.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Blumenthal, Weiner was one of the feisty few who later
emerged on the courthouse steps to criticize Starr's proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Starr hearings are the McCarthy hearings of our era,''
said Weiner, who followed up his appearance with a letter demanding
an apology from Starr. ``In retaliation, Starr slapped me with
another subpoena, this time for my private phone records,'' added
Weiner, delighted that the phone company declined to honor the
independent counsel's request that the subpoena be kept secret from
Wiener.
</P>
<P>
   For Panetta, his point of pride is that, unlike virtually all
the other witnesses who have been paying out a collective fortune
in legal fees, he resolved not to hire a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a lawyer,'' he said. ``I didn't want to pay someone $300
an hour for me to be recollecting what I already know.'' A good
thing, Panetta added, for he was indeed questioned for three hours,
but mainly about the White House floor plan, a mundane topic that
he said consumed 90 percent of the questioning. ``The other 10
percent was about whether I had ever seen the president with Monica
Lewinsky,'' Panetta said. ``I had not and basically said so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
