<SLUG> BC-BURIALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA REP. STUMP AGAIN PROTESTS NON-MILITARY ARLINGTON BURIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the second time this month, Rep. Bob Stump is
protesting the burial of non-military fallen Americans in the
nation's premiere veteran's cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Stump, chairman of the House Veterans
Affairs Committee, said, ``It's wrong'' to bury in Arlington
National Cemetery three employees of the American embassy who were
killed in the terrorist blast in Kenya on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are displacing three of our military people. We've got no
more ground there,'' Stump said.
</P>
<P>
   What space remains in crowded Arlington should be reserved for
select military heroes, Stump said, and he's working on a law that
would mandate just that.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Stump criticized the burial of Capitol Police
detective John Gibson in Arlington for the same reason (Gibson had
no military service), although he acknowledged that Gibson was a
true hero.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was killed inside the U.S. Capitol after a gunman forced
his way past security and began firing. Another Capitol Police
officer was killed and a tourist wounded. The second officer
killed, Jacob Chestnut, was qualified for burial in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   This week, President Clinton, at the request of the State
Department, granted waivers from the strict Arlington burial rules
for Julian Bartley, 55, the Kenyan embassy consul general;
Bartley's 20-year-old son, Jay, who had a summer job at the
embassy; and Prabhi Kavaler, 45, a native of India who worked for
the general services office in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Americans killed in the bombing attack were
killed on active duty in the military service and are therefore
qualified for an Arlington burial.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Stump won a unanimous House vote for his bill that
would end waivers of the cemetery's burial requirements and limit
interment rights to those killed on active duty, those who retired
from military service, and those who won either a Purple Heart or
Silver Star.
</P>
<P>
   Stump originally drafted the legislation to separate burial
waivers from politics after controversy over a Clinton
administration waiver that permitted the Arlington burial of the
late Ambassador Larry Lawrence, whose body was exhumed after it was
discovered that the major Democratic donor had lied about serving
in the Merchant Marine.
</P>
<P>
   Stump's bill is hung up in the Senate, where some in the upper
chamber are concerned it may prevent them from burial in Arlington.
Stump said he is working to satisfy Senate concerns by rewriting
the bill to again allow limited waivers. &QL; 
Adrianne Flynn can be reached at (202) 662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980814.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5120 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SMART-SPORT-UTES-     08-14 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-SPORT-UTES-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE IT WAS JUST A JIMMY; NOW IT'S `HOME, JAMES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 16)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Motors' marketing wizards have honed their Ginsu knives
to a razor's edge as they've sliced and diced the sport utility
market. Consider GM's lineup of compact utilities, all of them
variations on one basic platform:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chevrolet Blazer comes in five trim levels, with two doors
or four, with or without four-wheel drive. The Blazer starts at
$22,178 and runs to $32,000 _ a new Trailblazer model for 1999 will
be $35,000 _ and competes mostly with the Ford Explorer and Jeep
Grand Cherokee. It is aimed at buyers in their mid-30s to late 40s
with an average household income of $60,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Oldsmobile Bravada, which comes only as a four-door with
all-wheel drive for about $33,000, is supposed to offer an
``understated'' alternative to imported luxury models to people
from 40 to 50, with household incomes of about $85,000. Olds hopes
to steal sales from the Mercedes-Benz ML320, Infiniti QX4 and Lexus
RX 300.
</P>
<P>
   _ The GMC Jimmy is available in four trim levels, with two or
four doors, with or without four-wheel drive. Starting at $22,351
and climbing into the low $30,000s, the Jimmy competes most
directly with the Grand Cherokee and Explorer, as well as with the
Mercury Mountaineer, Toyota 4Runner, Nissan Pathfinder and Isuzu
Rodeo. Typical buyers are in their mid-40s with household incomes
of $68,000 a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Yet another model, the GMC Envoy, arrived this year. A
fancier, flashier version of the Jimmy, the Envoy is aimed at
buyers 34 to 49 with household incomes of more than $100,000 a year
who desire an ``expressive'' luxury sport utility, in contrast to
the toned-down Bravada. GMC sees the Envoy going against the Grand
Cherokee Limited and the Explorer Limited. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s and 80s, this slicing and dicing to create multiple
models from a single design was wryly known as ``badge
engineering'' _ the engineering consisted of sticking different
emblems on the fenders. Today, the buzzword is ``brand
management''; in either case, the results are different vehicles
that are much the same. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 GMC Envoy, along with the larger 1999 Yukon Denali, was
created in a bid to distinguish GMC as a premium alternative to
Chevrolet after decades in which trucks from the two divisions were
essentially the same. And though the Envoy is a Blazer/Jimmy
underneath, it is supposed to be the flagship of GM's compact sport
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   On the outside, the Envoy has a flashier appearance with
aluminum wheels, a single-color grille, a different bumper and
high-intensity-discharge headlamps. The high-tech headlamps emit a
distinctive blue-white light, and they require an automatic
load-leveling suspension to keep them properly aimed. In contrast
to the Jimmy, the Envoy comes only with four doors, and four-wheel
drive is standard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the Envoy is outfitted in two-tone, double-stitched
leather with the ``Envoy'' logo emblazoned on the headrests, and
Zebrano wood trim throughout the cabin. The Envoy's comfortable
seats are much fancier than those of the Jimmy, adjusting eight
ways, and they memorize two drivers' preferred settings.
</P>
<P>
   Standard features on the Envoy include a premium Bose AM/FM
stereo with cassette or CD player, electronic climate control, a
Homelink transmitter that opens garage doors and security gates,
remote keyless entry and a leather-wrapped steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, radio controls are being added to the steering wheel.
Standard safety equipment includes less forceful air bags,
anti-lock brakes and a theft-deterrent system. A sunroof is the
sole option.
</P>
<P>
   The platform, engine and automatic transmissions of the Envoy,
Jimmy, Blazer and Bravada are virtually identical. The platform was
redesigned for 1995 and its ride and handling were vastly improved.
But as has been the case with many recent GM redesigns, it did not
set new standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Envoy, like the other offsprings of the platform, is powered
by a 4.3-liter V6 engine, rated at 190 horsepower. In the Envoy,
the engine is paired with GM's four-speed electronic automatic
transmission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Envoy distinguishes itself from the Jimmy in its suspension.
Different shocks give the Envoy a smoother highway ride. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, in contrast to the Bravada, the Envoy has full off-road
capability. The Bravada is equipped with a full-time
all-wheel-drive system. The Envoy has a four-wheel-drive system
that can be turned on and off, and a low gear range for difficult
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1999 models go on sale in the fall, including the
Jimmy, they will include AutoTrac, a feature that allows the driver
to select between full-time all-wheel-drive or shift-on-the-fly
four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Envoy and Jimmy will also come with GM's tow/haul
feature; with the press of a button on the shift lever, it
automatically adjusts the transmission's shifting to suit a heavier
load.
</P>
<P>
   The Envoy is a perfectly fine luxury sport utility. Its ride is
comfortable, and it has virtually any amenity one could want. Its
price of $34,650 is on par with other well-trimmed compact sport
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nothing makes the Envoy stand out. It has considerably less
space than the Explorer. It lacks the off-roading tradition of the
Grand Cherokee. It is not as refined as the Infiniti QX4 or as
car-like as the Lexus RX 300. It scores lower on the prestige scale
than the Mercedes ML320. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Envoy has a lot of nice touches. But it costs $5,000 more
than the top-of-the-line Jimmy, and it is a new, unknown name going
against a lot of very tough, well-established competitors. With GMC
trying to make a luxury footprint, the Envoy is a step, but not a
big one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: A Blazer with all the bells and whistles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
