<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Aug. 16,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSICALS-REVIVALS (subslug) (New York) _ Audiences flocking to
the Martin Beck Theater for the current revival of ``The Sound of
Music'' could care less that many critics find the musical
irredeemably saccharine. With its famously tuneful score, this 1959
show, the last Rodgers and Hammerstein collaboration, is
comfortingly familiar. People watch dazed with happiness, bobbing
their heads, along with the Von Trapp children as they learn their
do, re, mi's, smiling with recognition as Maria lists her favorite
things. There is no glitz, no benumbing spectacle, no blaring
rock-ified orchestra, just good old-fashioned musical value and an
uplifting story. By Anthony Tommasini. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GABRIELE-MUNTER-ART (Undated) _ ``Gabriele Munter: The
Expressionist Years, 1903-1920,'' an exhibition of 70 paintings,
drawings and prints at the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts in Richmond
through Sept. 20. For students and knowledgeable admirers of
20th-century art, Munter (1877-1962) is little more than an elusive
presence in the annals of German Expressionism. For decades she has
been mentioned in these histories, when mentioned at all, as pupil
and companion of the Russian painter Wassily Kandinsky. By Roberta
Smith. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SERBAN-CYMBELINE-THEATER (Undated) _ Andrei Serban, 55, the
theater director who was born in Romania and is currently the head
of the graduate acting program at Columbia University,
``Cymbeline'' opens Sunday night as part of the New York
Shakespeare Festival's 43rd season. By Andrea Stevens. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   AYCKBOURN-THEATER (London) _ It is no secret that, after 53
plays, Alan Ayckbourn relishes a challenge. And in play No. 49,
``Communicating Doors,'' the task he has posed for himself is this:
how to mold a comic thriller _ or even a scary farce _ while at the
same time shuttling his characters back and forth in time with an
abandon many a filmmaker might envy. By Matt Wolf. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KRIS-KRISTOFFERSON-FILMS (Undated) _ If sentimentality is the
tendency to show more than one feels, Kris Kristofferson is the
opposite of sentimental: the man who feels so much that he cannot
help but show it. He is what he wrote about, a walking
contradiction _ a Rhodes scholar propelled though life less by
reason than by impulse; a Golden Gloves boxer blessed with a poet's
understanding of irredeemable loss and late-night yearnings. Rugged
yet capable of being wounded, solitary yet reachable, he veers
between two styles: supremely laid back and wound tighter than
most. By Elizaeth Kaye. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS4KIDS (Undated) _ Brief reviews of some films and their
suitability for children. This week: ``Ever After: A Cinderalla
Story''; ``Air Bud; ``Basketball.'' (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TROCKS-DANCE (New York) _ Es Ballets Trockadero de Monte Carlo,
a gay dance group that started in New York City in 1974, will
perform at the Joyce Theater for a week starting next Tuesday. By
Jennifer Dunning. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ZEMLINSKY-MUSIC (Undated) _ The centenary of Alexander von
Zemlinsky's birth, 1971, prompted the first flurry of his music
revivals. In the 1980s his operas were brought back to life, and
there were several important recordings. Now James Conlon is
pressing the case again, with five Zemlinsky albums recorded under
his baton for EMI Classics in Cologne, Germany, and more to come.
By Paul Griffiths. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BOTSTEIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ Who, in musical history, could have
guessed that a meddlesome figure like Leon Botstein would come
along? Not Mendelssohn, obviously. ``In everything I have written
down there is at least as much deleted as there is allowed to
stand,'' the composer told a friend around 1842. ``My `St. Paul'
originally had a third more numbers, which shall never see the
light of day.'' But Botstein, the American academic turned
conductor and festival director, has exposed those numbers to the
full glare of recordings. By James R. Oestreich. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YIDDISH-MUSIC (Undated) _ For more than a century, Yiddish music
has survived in America. The melodic vernacular of displaced Jews
from Eastern Europe, it is a music of secular wit and religious
fervor, the music of a people in a conflicted dance with
assimilation. By Barry Singer. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ADAM-COHEN-MUSIC (Undated) _ Adam Cohen, 26, the son of Leonard
Cohen, deserves points for jumping in over his head and infusing
some passion into a moribund folk-pop tradition. In the best songs
from his debut album ``Adam Cohen'' (Columbia) _ the nasty,
tormented ones _ this talented but still partly unformed songwriter
forces you to feel his anger, jealousy and frustration over various
erotic entanglements. By Stephen Holden. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEA-CEREMONY-ANTIQUES (Kyoto, Japan) _ Mrs. Mihoko Koyama, 88,
who for 40 years until 1991 had been collecting objects for the
Japanese tea cermony, are being exhibited in the Miho Museum in the
town of Shigaraki. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CALIFORNIA-GOLD (Undated) _ Panning for gold in
California. By Todd S. Purdum. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Traveling the internet: The Kuralt
approach and age discounts. By L.R. Shannon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EGYPT (Cairo, Egypt) _ A 10th-century church is rescued
in old Cairo. By Douglas Jehl. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ More ticks. Thanks, El Nino. By
Susan Gilbert. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Times Square visitors to get high-tech
help; Tours of Paris for the French-impaired; Thomas Wolfe's house
is damaged by fire; Getting a head start on a Van Gogh show.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Questions and answers on travel. This
week: Sacred Music Festivals; A South Pacific Tour; Side Trip to
Majorca. By Ray Cormier. (Moved).
</P>
</TEXT>
