<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA IS JUST ALL-AROUND GOOD GUY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Redsox-Comment)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He still gets a sincere laugh out of his prank in Omaha
four years ago. It was two hours before the Red Sox faced the Twins
Friday night at Fenway Park, and there was Nomar Garciaparra in the
Boston clubhouse, shaking his head and laughing at his offbeat
concept of comedy. Four years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to have fun,'' he said between giggles. ``I like to
fool around now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the panicked group standing outside a downtown Omaha hotel
didn't think it was funny when Garciaparra and a couple of his
Georgia Tech teammates ran around the tornadophobic city yelling,
``Tornado!'' But perhaps they'll appreciate this: Nothing ever gets
old for this man, humor included.
</P>
<P>
   You could search his compact disc player now and find a very
modern hip-hopper named DMX. He is considering reinserting a trendy
crew called Bones, Thugs 'N Harmony back into his CD rotation, too.
But don't be fooled by that. Garciaparra's true hip-hop loves are
groups such as Eric B. and Rakim, a duo that was most popular in
the 1980s. It's a genuine oldie by today's standards, but,
Garciaparra explained, ``that was real hip-hop.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past two summers, we have watched Garciaparra play as if
he were controlling his own likeness in an unreal, videogame world.
He was Rookie of the Year last season. This year he's a top five
candidate for MVP. Think of what you do when he comes to the plate.
Isn't he one of the rare players you expect to get a hit almost
every time up?
</P>
<P>
   But if you went to your neighbor this morning and said, ``I
think Nomar Garciaparra is a terrific player,'' you might be asked
if you are a permanent resident of another place like, say,
Neptune.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to overlook greatness sometimes. It would be foolish
to do that with Garciaparra. It is not normal for 175-pound
shortstops to be a few RBIs away from 100 in mid-August. It also
isn't normal for such a shortstop to tell you that the hitting
streaks and home runs and gaudy plays in the field don't matter _
and mean it.
</P>
<P>
   What we now see at Fenway is a 25-year-old athlete who was
raised in the tradition of Jim Thorpe: Play everything, be good at
everything, learn the value of humility. Maybe Dan Duquette wasn't
exaggerating in the spring after announcing Garciaparra's contract
extension. At the time, the Duke implied that his shortstop eats
all his vegetables, chews his food exactly 32 times before
swallowing, and flosses after every meal.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing we know, Garciaparra will be asking Bobby Grier if he
can have a shot at playing running back for the Patriots. Well,
let's just say it wouldn't surprise me.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's exclusive property of the Red Sox,'' Duquette said last
night. ``For the next seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   But you get the feeling the man could be a Sox, Patriot, or
member of the Revolution if he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in high school, I played football, soccer, and
baseball,'' Garciaparra said. ``In California, soccer season was
during basketball season, so I could play all three sports. I've
been playing baseball and soccer since I was 6.''
</P>
<P>
   We are talking about a man who was kicking 60-yard field goals
in practice. A guy who was good enough to score 17 goals on his
high school soccer team during his senior year. A kid who told
himself he needed to get a football or soccer scholarship to
college and then try to ``walk on somebody's baseball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra has frustrated many media types by refusing to talk
about his statistics. It seems as if he is being unnecessarily
difficult. But long before the Sox picked him 12th overall in the
1994 draft, Garciaparra's father, Ramon, sat him down and told him
how to approach baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played every position growing up,'' he said. ``My dad told
me that I was going to play everything. So I knew how valuable the
catcher was, the right fielder was, the pitcher was ... Stats were
never important to me because it didn't tell me how good I did that
day or how bad I did that day. Numbers aren't going to tell me
that; I'm going to know myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go 4 for 4 and get jammed four times and have a terrible
day at the plate. It just means I got lucky. It doesn't mean I had
a good day. That's how I was taught to look at the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The philosophy never got old for Garciaparra. He doesn't sneak
into the clubhouse and gaze at stat sheets when cameras aren't
around. In fact, cameras usually aren't around precisely because he
is not seen as a media entertainer. But there are some charismatic
athletes you love to talk to but don't necessarily want batting
cleanup following Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   You want that with Garciaparra. Doesn't it seem like 10 years
ago that you heard about a prospect named Garciaparra who was a
brilliant fielder but an average hitter? This Garciaparra and the
one who led off last year even seem like different players.
</P>
<P>
   If I had an MVP vote, Garciaparra would certainly be in the top
five. Alex Rodriguez and Ken Griffey would be there, too (although
I would penalize them for putting up great numbers on a bad team).
I would round out the list with a couple of Yankees (David Cone,
Derek Jeter).
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been many times this year when Nomar has played
like the best player in baseball,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   And that should never get too old to watch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Holley is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
