<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSSIAN MARKETS RALLY ON HOPES OF RECOVERY
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial markets rallied after the Kremlin and the
major Western powers indicated that they were working on plans to
end the nation's economic crisis. After losing almost 6.5 percent
of their value on Thursday, Russian blue-chip stocks regained about
4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But with banks still shaky and the memory of Thursday's panic
still fresh, brokers and analysts said they were not so much
optimistic about a solution as relieved that the free fall had
halted.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK, STILL BENIGN, FADES A BIT
</P>
<P>
   With Russia facing financial turmoil, Asia sinking deeper into
recession, President Clinton fighting for his political life and
the stock market swooning, the bright economic picture of the last
couple of years suddenly looks murkier. But the economy is not
likely to unravel anytime soon. Forecasters are counting on low
inflation, falling interest rates and confident consumers to keep
growth going in the year's second half.
</P>
<P>
   LOSS FOR TOBACCO REGULATORS
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court ruled that the Food and Drug
Administration does not have the authority to regulate cigarettes
or smokeless tobacco. The ruling is a setback to anti-smoking
groups, state attorneys general and members of Congress who had
used the threat of regulation to press the tobacco industry to
reimburse states for the health costs of smoking, and to limit
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   STRYKER TO BUY A UNIT OF PFIZER
</P>
<P>
   Stryker said that it had agreed to buy Pfizer's Howmedica
orthopedics unit for $1.9 billion, expanding its line of products
to repair injured joints and bones. Shares of Stryker fell 19
percent because the costs of the acquisition could slow the
company's growth.
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND APPROVES RESCUE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Thailand approved a new program to salvage its financial system,
which has been crippled by recession, years of poorly planned
real-estate development and a currency devaluation. Getting lenders
back on their feet is vital to pulling the economy out of its first
recession in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   McDONALD'S RESTATES RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's Corp. restated its second-quarter net income to
reverse a $125 million charge for a new food-production system,
saying it would spread the charge gradually. The company said it
had made the change after discussions with the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION FELL IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   Industrial production decreased 0.6 percent in July, the second
consecutive monthly decline, as manufacturers struggled to overcome
sluggish Asian demand and the General Motors strikes cut auto and
truck output by 20 percent. Inflation remained tame at the
wholesale level. In a second report, the Labor Department said
producer prices rose 0.2 percent in July after having fallen 0.1
percent in June.
</P>
<P>
   GM SAYS STRIKE COST $1.65 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   General Motors estimated the third-quarter production losses as
a result of work stoppages from labor strikes in Flint, Mich., cost
it $1.65 billion after taxes, the company said in a federal
securities filing. The total includes a loss of $1.3 billion for
GM's North American operations and another $350 million for GM's
Delphi Automotive Systems unit.
</P>
<P>
   RAIL EMPLOYEES SENT BACK TO WORK
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered 3,400 striking Conrail track-maintenance
employees to return to work just hours after they walked out over
Conrail's use of outside contractors to build tracks in Marysville,
Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
