<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-TWINS-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      08-14 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TWINS-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX CELEBRATE THIS BASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox and Twins resumed bashing the ball Friday
night, turning Updike's lyric little bandox in the Back Bay into
the big league version of a roadside batting cage.
</P>
<P>
   Drop a dollar's worth of quarters into the machine, cock bat,
swing for downtown.
</P>
<P>
   When the quarters finally ran out at Fenway Park, it was the Sox
who were left standing, their bats running red hot after a wild
13-12 triumph over Minnesota that was decided on Donnie Sadler's
two-run single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, who went 3 for 4 with three RBIs, broke an 11-11 tie
when he drove in Troy O'Leary and Jason Varitek to bring the Sox
their 71st win of the season. Their 70th the night before also had
been a slugfest _ 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   This one wasn't secure until John Valentin stabbed a bouncer to
third for the final out, enabling Tom Gordon to survive a
bases-loaded situation for his 34th save.
</P>
<P>
   A sellout crowd of 32,888 saw Sox starter Tim Wakefield fall
into a 6-0 deficit in the top of the third inning, a lead that was
erased in the bottom of the third when the Sox sent 10 batters to
the plate, eventually tying it on Mike Stanley's two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over, the Sox lost leads of 8-6 and 9-8. They
moved to an 11-9 lead in the bottom of the fifth when Damon Buford
launched a two-run triple, but the Twins tied it again, 11-11, in
the top of the seventh on a two-run double by Paul Molitor.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins began to light up Wakefield in the second when Todd
Walker hit a leadoff bomb on a 3-0 pitch and Ron Coomer followed
suit with a deep threat on a 2-0 offering. Twins, 2-0. Coomer's was
a mammoth shot, rattling off the Coke bottles halfway up the
left-field light stanchion.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota added four runs in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The rally began with Otis Nixon's leadoff single to center, the
best-hit pitch of the inning. After Paul Molitor rolled out, Matt
Lawton hit a roller to Mo Vaughn that was labeled out No. 2. But
Wakefield, covering first on the play, dropped Vaughn's soft toss,
leaving runners at first and third. The fun continued.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Cordova followed with an infield single, a roller hit too
deep in the hole for shortstop Nomar Garciaparra to cover and throw
in time. Nixon came across with the 3-0 lead, and runners were
parked at first and second. Next, Todd Walker lifted a lazy fly to
short left, an innocent shot that took one hop into the left-field
boxes for a ground-rule double, bringing across Lawton with the 4-0
lead. Coomer slapped a ball to Valentin at third, forcing a throw
to the plate to cut down Cordova. The ball was there in plenty of
time, but catcher Jason Varitek forgot to catch the ball. Twins,
5-0, and counting. The next hitter, David Ortiz, watched a 1-1
pitch squib through Varitek's glove for a passed ball, and in
trotted Walker with the 6-0 lead. Gruesome.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the inning saw the Sox fire up their bats, chasing
Twins starter Dan Serafini in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The first run came across when Sadler followed a Varitek double
with a sharp single to left. A Darren Lewis double to right put
runners at second and third, and a Valentin walk loaded the bases
for Vaughn. The Hit Dog launched a Wall double, bringing across
Sadler and Lewis and halving the Twins' lead to 6-3. Garciaparra
sliced another run off the lead with a sacrifice fly to center
before Stanley smoked a 3-1 pitch over the Wall to tie it, 6-6.
Goodbye, Serafini.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox kept up the offensive pressure in the fourth, taking
their first lead of the night. Sadler's one-out single and Ortiz's
boot of a Lewis roller to first left runners at first and third.
Valentin delivered a soaring, Wall-scraping triple for an 8-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch-by-pitch carnage continued in the next half-inning
when Wakefield was cashiered in a hail of hits, including a Coomer
single, an Ortiz single, and a Terry Steinbach homer into the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the fifth, the hits just kept on coming and the
Sox again moved out in front, 11-9. The rally began with a Stanley
walk. O'Leary lashed the ball past Ortiz and it screamed into foul
territory. The ball was in play, but a member of the Fenway grounds
crew, a young fellow stationed on a chair just beyond the tarpaulin
at the face of the box seats, gobbled it up like a true Gold
Glover. He then threw into the stands, thinking the ball had been
foul. Wrong. O'Leary was parked at second with a ground-rule double
(he likely wouldn't have had more), and Stanely moved to third.
Buford then sent a triple that bounced off the Sox bullpen and put
them ahead, 10-9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
