<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-NUKE-SCIENTIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIA ALMOST BUNGLED INTELLIGENCE COUP WITH IRAQI REFUGEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (with IRAQ-NUKE)  
 (bl)  
 By JUDITH MILLER and JAMES RISEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dr. Khidhir Abdul Abas Hamza, one of Iraq's top nuclear
scientists, defected in 1994, he expected the United States to
welcome him with open arms. But U.S. intelligence officials had no
idea who he was.
</P>
<P>
   Hamza's flight from Iraq, recounted by Iraqi opposition figures
and former and current U.S. officials, was potentially an
intelligence coup for the United States that almost turned into an
intelligence bonanza for the Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.S. intelligence officials and Iraqi dissident
leaders familiar with Hamza's case, he fled Baghdad in September
1994 by hiring a smuggler to get him to the Kurdish haven in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   There he sought out Ahmed Chalabi, a fellow graduate of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology who at the time was working
with the CIA as head of the Iraqi National Congress, a U.S.-backed
opposition group. After Chalabi put Hamza in touch with the CIA,
the scientist was astonished and furious to learn that the agency
was not interested in helping him defect to the United States,
Chalabi said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   A former U.S. intelligence official who was involved in the
CIA's initial negotiations with Hamza now acknowledges that the
agency erred in its initial handling of the Iraqi scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did strange things in this case,'' said Warren Marik, then
an official in the CIA's Iraq group. ``We acted too quickly on this
guy and brushed him off too quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Marik arranged for a CIA scientist and another official at the
agency's headquarters in Langley, Va., to talk by satellite
telephone with Hamza to determine whether he was credible.
</P>
<P>
   But the telephone negotiations quickly broke down. The CIA
officials wanted Hamza to provide sensitive information to them
immediately over the phone, while he insisted that he would only
talk after the agency had arranged for his defection to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dickered back and forth for 45 minutes, and the agency
dismissed him,'' Marik. ``But it's not supposed to be done by phone
like that. We were two days short of what it really takes to
determine a defector's value.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated and eager to find a safer haven, Hamza fled first to
Turkey. He then landed a job in another country with nuclear
ambitions, Libya. Teaching physics at Alzawiya University, Hamza
says, he was approached to work in Libya's fledgling nuclear
program, but refused.
</P>
<P>
   President Saddam Hussein finally caught up with him in 1995,
when the Iraqi secret police sent Hamza's eldest son to Tripoli,
urging him to return to his nuclear job in Baghdad. His son said
Iraqi agents had tried to kill him twice, underscoring the
consequences of refusing the invitation to return.
</P>
<P>
   His son had arrived just after The Sunday Times of London had
reported that Hamza was presumed to have been kidnapped and
assassinated by Iraqi agents in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   The tale was an elaborate fabrication. But Hamza said the
article and a third attempt on his son's life had prompted him to
leave Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Hamza fled to Tunisia and then to Hungary, intelligence
officials said. From there, he made contact with Chalabi and an
official with another Iraqi dissident group, the Iraqi National
Accord, which had connections to both U.S. and British
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he arranged to meet with the CIA's station chief at the
U.S. Embassy in Budapest, Hungary, and was soon on his way to
Washington, intelligence officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the officials said, the spy agency arranged to pluck
his family out of his home in downtown Baghdad. Another smuggler
brought his family into northern Iraq, where a CIA team met them.
They are now reunited with Hamza in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamza's life is still far from ordinary. He now works for a
Washington-based research center run by David Albright, a leading
U.S. expert on Iraq's nuclear program and will publish an article
Monday about his experiences in Iraq in the Bulletin of Atomic
Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   But he remains frustrated that his immigration status in the
United States has not been resolved and that he has yet to receive
a green card permitting him to travel and establish a permanent
legal residency in his newly adopted country. He is still
classified as a refugee, said Dawn Lurie, his immigration lawyer in
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
