<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DELMAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINER BYRNE HOPES TO TOUCH ON GOLDEN YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For his next trick, Pat Byrne plans to turn Touch
Gold into a Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Which sounds preposterous. Touch Gold began his 4-year-old
season in late June, has a single allowance-level victory and just
$42,000 in earnings to show for it, and will face his first major
competition of the year in the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del
Mar this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But Byrne is the England-born, Kentucky-based trainer whose
careful management kept Favorite Trick undefeated in eight starts
in 1997 and helped that colt become the first 2-year-old since
Secretariat to be named Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   So when he says Touch Gold's talent, combined with a well-mapped
if ambitious schedule, can produce an equally unlikely championship
in 1998, you have to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll keep him unbeaten for the year,'' Byrne said
of Touch Gold, who was 4 for 7 last year, when he won the Belmont
Stakes, and is 1 for 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
   With perfection as the goal, no horse has as much at stake in
the Pacific Classic as Touch Gold, who will be ridden by Pat Day
when he faces defending champion Gentlemen, Puerto Madero, Free
House and five others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Touch Gold is a magnificent animal, and I'll be
disappointed if he can't win,'' Byrne said.
</P>
<P>
   After this, the trainer said, he plans to send the son of Deputy
Minister to the Sept. 19 Woodward Stakes at Belmont Park in New
York and/or the Oct. 10 Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont, and the
Nov. 7 Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs in Kentucky. In the
unlikely event he keeps winning, capturing Grade I stakes on the
nation's three major thoroughbred circuits, and defeats Horse of
the Year front-runner Skip Away at least once, award voters would
have to be impressed.
</P>
<P>
   It would be an unusual route to the title for horse and trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Touch Gold was a Horse of the Year possibility for much of '97,
when he was trained in Southern California by David Hofmans. He ran
an impressive fourth in the Preakness after cracking a hoof at the
start, beat Silver Charm out of a Triple Crown in the Belmont
Stakes with the hoof patched, and won the Haskell Invitational at
Monmouth Park to look like the leading 3-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't the same in the Pegasus Handicap at the
Meadowlands and the Breeders' Cup Classic at Hollywood Park,
finishing last in both races, and he was put away for the winter to
let the foot heal.
</P>
<P>
   Then his owner, Frank Stronach, decided to consolidate his
stable, and sent Touch Gold and about 40 other horses to Byrne.
This was Byrne's reward for a breakthrough season in which he won
37 percent of his races, became the fourth trainer to saddle two
winners on a Breeders' Cup card, and was second to Bob Baffert in
controversial voting for the trainers' Eclipse Award.
</P>
<P>
   To sign a five-year contract as Stronach's private trainer,
Byrne, 42, gave up Favorite Trick, the Horse of the Year and
champion 2-year-old, and Countess Diana, the champion 2-year-old
filly.
</P>
<P>
   The deal seems to be paying off for Stronach and Byrne. They
have Touch Gold, recent Whitney Handicap winner Awesome Again and
the 4-year-old filly Relaxing Rhythm among the top 25 in Daily
Racing Form rankings.
</P>
<P>
   But Touch Gold was off the chart for half the year before
returning to action with a swift, nearly gate-to-wire mile victory
at Churchill Downs on June 28. To Byrne, the long absence shouldn't
disqualify his colt from Horse of the Year contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't stay in the stall because he was hiding from
anybody,'' Byrne said. ``He stayed in the stall because of a foot
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Classic won't be an easy first step in the
championship campaign. Touch Gold's single, one-turn mile might be
insufficient preparation for the 1\-mile race. He would be the
first out-of-state horse to win the eight-year-old event.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Mandella, who trains the favored entry of Gentlemen
and Puerto Madero, thinks Touch Gold is the one to fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call him a wild card. I'd call him a great
threat,'' Mandella said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne obviously agrees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
