<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIETNAM-EMBASSY-ART-N     08-14 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-EMBASSY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S FORMER SAIGON EMBASSY PASSES INTO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam _ The most talked-about construction
project in this city of soaring cranes and clattering jackhammers
is a building that has come down, not gone up. It is the old U.S.
Embassy, which until July stood in the heart of the former Saigon
as a brooding reminder of America's presence here during the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the State Department decided to demolish the embassy
to make way for a new consulate. A week ago, barely two months
after the building went under the wrecking ball, a Vietnamese
construction crew was carting out the last truckloads of rubble,
leaving a mossy wall topped with barbed wire and squat gun towers
as the only remnants of the once formidable compound.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials in Vietnam are eager to consign the old embassy
and all it represents to history. They talk excitedly about the
more modest consulate that is going up next to the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   The newly appointed consul general, Charles Ray, said he hoped
that the first U.S. diplomatic mission here in 23 years would
promote robust commercial ties with Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war is behind us physically, and we have to put it behind
us emotionally,'' said Ray, who served two tours as an Army officer
here before becoming a diplomat. ``We really need to close that
door and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the memories linger. And the demolition of the embassy
has stirred deeply ambivalent feelings among many Americans who
live here. While some said they were relieved to be rid of a daily
reminder of defeat, others said they regretted losing a piece of
history.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk about the new relationship between the United
States and Vietnam _ one based on joint ventures rather than jungle
warfare _ the war still casts a long shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have regrets,'' said Frederick Burke, a lawyer
with the Chicago-based firm of Baker &AMP; McKenzie who works in a
gleaming new office tower that overlooks the embassy grounds. ``It
was a landmark, perhaps an ignominious one, because it represented
our last step out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the United States finally gave up its long struggle in
Vietnam on April 30, 1975, when a military helicopter evacuated
Ambassador Graham Martin from the roof of the embassy, hours before
Communist troops captured Saigon. In the preceding days, Marine
guards fended off frantic crowds who were swarming the gates,
begging for a way out of the besieged capital.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the chaotic retreat, the embassy had come to
symbolize the turning tide in Vietnam. Built in 1967, it was
stormed and partly occupied by the Vietcong during the Tet
offensive in early 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, in a gesture that offended some Americans
here, the Vietnamese government erected a red-stone memorial to the
Communist heroes of that offensive on the sidewalk outside the main
gate.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the embassy became a minor tourist attraction
for Americans. Tour buses pulled up in front of the building so
passengers could gaze at the familiar honeycomb concrete walls and
rooftop helicopter pad. Although the Vietnamese had turned it into
offices for the state oil company, they allowed the building to
fall into disrepair, which lent it just the right aura of decay.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists were not the only people who were fascinated. After the
United States and Vietnam exchanged ambassadors last year and the
United States reclaimed the building, visiting U.S. lawmakers began
asking for tours.
</P>
<P>
   That bothered the new U.S. ambassador, Pete Peterson. A former
Navy pilot who was shot down by the North Vietnamese and spent more
than six years in Hanoi as a prisoner of war, Peterson has little
patience for trips down memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   He also worried that someone might be injured roaming the halls
or clambering out onto the helicopter pad. ``The building was a
dangerous, unsafe edifice that had no future use,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As if to confirm his fears, two Vietnamese construction workers
were killed in June during the demolition when they stepped onto
the roof of an elevator moments before its cables were severed. The
men plunged several floors to their deaths, adding to the litany of
misery associated with the building.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolism aside, Peterson said he also wanted to tear down the
embassy because he viewed the site as a potential source of cash.
The compound is in the middle of what is fast becoming the most
prestigious business district in Ho Chi Minh City. The State
Department is mulling plans to build an office tower next to the
consulate, which it could lease to private tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Such an arrangement would help the State Department, which faces
potentially huge costs to upgrade security at its installations
around the world in the wake of bombing attacks on the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has classified the Ho Chi Minh City consulate as a
temporary facility. That means it does not require heavy
fortification, which will keep the projected cost under $3 million.
After last week, though, such a shoestring approach might run into
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing the bunker-like embassy with a sleek tower rented out
to lawyers, bankers and accountants may be as good a symbol as any
of the new era in U.S.-Vietnamese relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fits in with both the American and Vietnamese spirit of
consumerism,'' said Peter Sheridan, a Vietnam veteran who is now a
business consultant here. ``I say put up a high-rise and make some
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments were echoed by several Vietnamese who strolled
past the compound on a recent morning. Though some had vivid
memories of the building from childhood, few expressed sadness
about its demolition, so long as the United States was committed to
investing in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's there to be upset about?'' asked Bui Nguyen, 27, a
teacher, who waited for a friend near the front gate. ``Everybody
can make mistakes. If it's in the past, why don't we forget about
it and build something new?''
</P>
<P>
   Ngoc Luong, 50, said: ``The relationship between the United
States and Vietnam is different now. We are doing trade, not
fighting a war.''
</P>
<P>
   Luong, who was trained as a stonemason, was loitering around the
site in the hope of getting hired as a laborer. ``I can demolish
things too,'' he said with a broad smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
