AUG. 16 -- INVEST-3FAMILY-1, 8-14 -- Frank and Darlene Leon of
Coral Springs, with their daughters, Danielle and Jenna, weathered
the recent stock-market gyrations calmly. They believe that holding
tight in the short term pays off in the long run. ``Back then in
'87, there were guys who shot themselves, guys who shot their
stockbrokers; if they had just waited a few weeks, it would have
changed,'' says Mr. Leon. (Susan Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- WASHINGTONS-SWORD-BOS, 8-14 --
Fran Beatty, senior landscape architect for the Boston's historic
parks, stands with George Washington statue at the Boston Public
Garden. Ever since Charlestown sculptor Thomas Ball completed the
bronze statue in 1869, Washington's sword has been ``liberated''
many times by pranksters and petty vandals. ``If it wasn't a public
monument and very valuable, it might be very funny,'' says Ms.
Beatty. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ART-MUMMYS-BOS, 8-14 -- Rita
Freed, the curator of the Museum of Fine Arts, looks over a
description in the gallery for the newly renovated Egyptian and
Ancient Near Eastern collections. In these new spaces the MFA has
signed on to the recent trend of galleries-as-stage-sets, with
approximation of the archways and ziggurat-shaped crenellations
from the Great Ishtar Gate in Babylon. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- COMFORTABLE-BAT-BOS,
8-14 -- Kenneth Lazarus, president of Active Control Experts Inc.,
holds the $290 bat Copperhead ACX bat. Lazarus' company has
designed a system, embedded in an aluminum bat, that turns the
bat's natural vibrations into energy - energy that is not felt by
the batter. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NORTH CONWAY, N.H. -- Aug. 14, 1998 --
CLIMBING-HANGOUT-BOS, 8-14 Approximately 400 vertical feet above
the treetops, Chuck Stevenson, lower right, climbs Ironhorse Ledge.
Joe Lentini, Stevenson's instructor and the director of Eastern
Mountain Sports Climbing Schools, keeps him tethered and secure.
``I find it challenging to stay calm,'' says Stevenson, the CBS-TV
producer of ``48 Hours.'' (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- FASHION-DO-RAGS-BOS, 8-14 --
In the bleachers on a local ball field, do-rags are the latest
craze in headwear. They always served a function, but the do-rag,
that cut-up piece of worn stocking that came from the deep recesses
of a forgotten sock drawer, has become a fashion statement on the
street corners of many neighborhoods. (David L Ryan/Boston Globe
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
