<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/14/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) DOVER, N.H. -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- CLINTON-NH-VOICES-3,
8-14 -- New Hampshire residents are voicing yet another chorus of
defiant indifference to allegations that Clinton may have had
sexual contact with Monica Lewinsky. I think it's terrible for our
nation and I truly think it's not doing us any good around the
world,'' says Inez DiMambro, right, a 68-year-old housewife and
mother. ``He's the president,'' says shopping companion Diane King.
``He should act more presidential.'' (Rick Friedman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) DOVER, N.H. -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- CLINTON-NH-VOICES-2,
8-14 -- Many New Hampshire residents are tired of hearing that
Clinton may have had sexual contact with Monica Lewinsky.
``Ultimately, I think it's a travesty that people don't have better
things to do with this country than to investigate whether the
president is sleeping with obviously more-than-willing partners,''
says construction laborer David Pierce, center. ``How about let's
talk about something really important - the New York Yankees!''
(Rick Friedman/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DOVER, N.H. -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- CLINTON-NH-VOICES-1,
8-14 -- Bob Carroll, an auctioneer working an antiques auction
being held at Elks hall here, feels as do many other New Hampshire
residents regarding reports that Clinton may say he had some sexual
contact with Monica Lewinsky: tired of it all. ``Leave the poor man
alone,'' he says. ``I think he should say he had this sexual
encounter and it's between he and his wife, not he and the world.''
(Rick Friedman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
INVEST-YERGIN-Q&AMP;A, 8-14 -- Dr. Daniel Yergin, chairman of Cambridge
Energy Research Associates and author of ``The Prize,'' a history
of the oil industry for which he won a Pulitzer Prize in 1992. ``I
think there is a kind of modesty, actually, about oil pricing
forecasts,'' he says. ``Until the mid-'80s, there was a belief you
could forecast the future, and now people really see prices more as
assumptions rather than as actual forecasts.'' (Ruby Washington/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
MARKET-OVERVIEW-2, 8-14 -- Selda Chender, an interior designer,
avoids stocks: ``I lost too much'' decades ago, she says. Gurus and
analysts aplenty contend that something has changed. That reality
is finally throwing its wet blanket onto a market long fueled by
euphoria. That with the Dow Jones industrial average down 9.8
percent from its peak just a month ago, the good times are over.
(Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
MARKET-OVERVIEW-1, 8-14 -- Christopher Dziadosz, manager of Eagles
Antiques on the Upper East Side. ``If people are skittish, why are
they throwing hundreds of thousands of dollars at me?'' he asks.
Amongst the well-to-do in Manhattan, sentiment remains strong that
the good times are now, despite the contention by gurus and
analysts aplenty that something has changed. (Thomas Dallal/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- CLINTON-ISOLATION, 8-14
-- President Clinton speaking at a Democratic fundraiser in
Washington on Friday. Faced with questioning under oath this coming
Monday about his private life, and with impeachment proceedings
tuning up in the wings, Clinton has almost no one he can turn to
for advice, say his friends and current and former advisers.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LINDENHURST, N.Y. -- Aug. 14, 1998 --
NY-CEMETERY-STRIKE, 8-14 -- Steven Sprung at Sprung Monuments in
Lindenhurst. The stones are stacking up because workers will not
cross picket lines. Replacement workers at cemeteries have buried
the dead and maintained the grounds since early April, when workers
went on strike at one cemetery and were locked out by owners at
seven others. But hardly a single monument has been erected since.
(Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) HEBRON, West Bank -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- WEST-BANK-WATER,
8-14 -- On the outskirts of Hebron a pool provides a meager source
of supplemental water for Palestinians coping with rationing. The
water supply, controlled by Israel, has been reduced despite an
unusually hot summer. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
SUNTAN-LOTIONS, 8-14 -- Used correctly, tanning lotions no longer
have the unhappy effects they used to. If you must have the
suntanned look, why not turn to the large array of self-tanning
creams, which allow the user to appear heedlessly self-indulgent,
without any actual damage? (David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
INVEST-METZ, 8-14 -- Michael Metz, a managing director of CIBC
Oppenheimer for equity research, has been calling stocks overpriced
for four years. ``I think the reality principle is coming back to
Wall Street,'' says Metz, 69. ``The reality is that Asia is not a
passing fancy.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
CHER-AUDITIONS-2, 8-14 -- Maggie Gallagher, a teacher, belting out
``If I Could Turn Back Time,'' Cher style, at her audition for
``And the Beat Goes On: The Sonny and Cher Story,'' a
made-for-television movie that will air on ABC in February. The
movie is based on Sonny Bono's autobiography and will depict the
couple's life together, from the moment they first met to the
period after their divorce. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
CHER-AUDITIONS-1, 8-14 -- At the auditions for the upcoming
television movie, ``And the Beat Goes On: The Sonny and Cher
Story,'' are, from left, Sharon Allitt, 34, of Beachwood, N.J.;
Maggie Gallagher, 29, of Manhattan, and Rhonda Roenfeldt, 23, of
Queens. In homage to the Cher of the '70s, all three women wore
midriff-baring tops, but in a distinct nod to the '90s, all three
exposed belly buttons were pierced. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
CAR-SMART-SPORT-UTES, 8-14 -- The GMC Envoy. A fancier, flashier
version of the Jimmy, the Envoy is aimed at buyers 34 to 49 with
household incomes of more than $100,000 a year who desire an
``expressive'' luxury sport utility. Its ride is comfortable, and
it has virtually any amenity one could want. Its price of $34,650
is on par with other well-trimmed compact sport utilities. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
ABOUT-CARS-GM-YUKON-2, 8-14 -- The Cadillac Escalade has softer
leather seats, some extra wood trim and a longer warranty, but it's
really just a dressed-up Yukon Denali. At $43,500, the Denali is
pricey - $8,000 more than the top-line Yukon SLT - and the Cadillac
version is expected to be nearly $47,000. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
ABOUT-CARS-GM-YUKON-1, 8-14 -- The GMC Yukon Denali is big, but
well-balanced. The introduction of the Yukon spearheads a movement
by GMC to establish itself as a luxury line distinct from
Chevrolet. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PHOENIX -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 16 --
INVEST-3FAMILY-2, 8-14 -- Roger Pettett, a Phoenix retailer,
believes that holding tight in the short term pays off in the long
run. ``I'm not selling or even thinking about it,'' says Pettitt,
58. In January, as a long-term move, Pettett put half of his
mid-six-figure investment account into blue-chip companies with
dividend reinvestment plans, splitting the money among 30 or so
stocks. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CORAL SPRINGS, Fla. -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 16 -- INVEST-3FAMILY-1, 8-14 -- Frank and Darlene Leon of
Coral Springs, with their daughters, Danielle and Jenna, weathered
the recent stock-market gyrations calmly. They believe that holding
tight in the short term pays off in the long run. ``Back then in
'87, there were guys who shot themselves, guys who shot their
stockbrokers; if they had just waited a few weeks, it would have
changed,'' says Mr. Leon. (Susan Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- WASHINGTONS-SWORD-BOS, 8-14 --
Fran Beatty, senior landscape architect for the Boston's historic
parks, stands with George Washington statue at the Boston Public
Garden. Ever since Charlestown sculptor Thomas Ball completed the
bronze statue in 1869, Washington's sword has been ``liberated''
many times by pranksters and petty vandals. ``If it wasn't a public
monument and very valuable, it might be very funny,'' says Ms.
Beatty. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- ART-MUMMYS-BOS, 8-14 -- Rita
Freed, the curator of the Museum of Fine Arts, looks over a
description in the gallery for the newly renovated Egyptian and
Ancient Near Eastern collections. In these new spaces the MFA has
signed on to the recent trend of galleries-as-stage-sets, with
approximation of the archways and ziggurat-shaped crenellations
from the Great Ishtar Gate in Babylon. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- COMFORTABLE-BAT-BOS,
8-14 -- Kenneth Lazarus, president of Active Control Experts Inc.,
holds the $290 bat Copperhead ACX bat. Lazarus' company has
designed a system, embedded in an aluminum bat, that turns the
bat's natural vibrations into energy - energy that is not felt by
the batter. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NORTH CONWAY, N.H. -- Aug. 14, 1998 --
CLIMBING-HANGOUT-BOS, 8-14 Approximately 400 vertical feet above
the treetops, Chuck Stevenson, lower right, climbs Ironhorse Ledge.
Joe Lentini, Stevenson's instructor and the director of Eastern
Mountain Sports Climbing Schools, keeps him tethered and secure.
``I find it challenging to stay calm,'' says Stevenson, the CBS-TV
producer of ``48 Hours.'' (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Aug. 14, 1998 -- FASHION-DO-RAGS-BOS, 8-14 --
In the bleachers on a local ball field, do-rags are the latest
craze in headwear. They always served a function, but the do-rag,
that cut-up piece of worn stocking that came from the deep recesses
of a forgotten sock drawer, has become a fashion statement on the
street corners of many neighborhoods. (David L Ryan/Boston Globe
Photo) *LITE
</P>
