<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACK FOX MOVES TO TIGHT END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC quarterback John Fox started nine games last
season. But perhaps sensing the mood of training camp, he has
decided to play tight end this season.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who threw for 1,940 yards and 12 touchdowns last season,
informed USC coach Paul Hackett on Thursday night that he wanted to
make the switch. The change was so sudden that Fox had still not
informed his family by Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett asked Fox to sleep on his decision, but the junior was
adamant that he wanted to make a permanent position change.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's decision was no doubt spurred by the diminishing role he
has played in training camp. After losing the No.1 job to sophomore
Mike Van Raaphorst last spring, Fox appeared to be falling further
down the depth chart with the emergence of true freshman Carson
Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been so frustrated for a long time,'' Fox said. ``It's a
decision I had to make. I'll never play quarterback again. It's not
my race anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was given a fair chance to compete for the starting
position, Fox said, ``I don't know if I should comment on that.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the small number of snaps he took in practice this
week?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't count that low,'' Fox said. ``Of course (it affected
my decision). Not being able to get out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he never pondered being anything other than the No.1
quarterback. As it became clear he would not win the job, he became
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the position I wanted to be in,'' Fox said. ``It
unsettled my soul that I was in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he and Fox spoke for about an hour Thursday night.
Hackett said he provided few answers for Fox because he has not
decided who the No.2 quarterback will be, although Palmer clearly
seems to be the leading candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to make a decision,'' Hackett said. ``I tried to
tell (the quarterbacks) I would make a decision. But I wasn't ready
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Fox) just did what he felt was best for the football team.
This was not a guy making a knee-jerk reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Fox leaves Van Raaphorst, Palmer, junior Quincy
Woods and freshman Jason Thomas at quarterback. The entire group
has two college starts among them, both by Van Raaphorst last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the NCAA in Kansas City and checked. We now have the
youngest and most inexperienced quarterback corps in the United
States,'' Hackett joked.
</P>
<P>
   The decision also removed an interesting dilemma for the
Trojans, if Van Raaphorst were injured in the season opener against
Purdue. Would they use a true freshman (Palmer) or be better served
by playing it safe and going with the veteran Fox?
</P>
<P>
   It might be a moot point, although Fox wavered slightly about
ever returning to quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't go back. That's not my position any more,'' Fox said.
He then paused, and added, ``If the team needed it, I would do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox didn't just surprise the coaches, he also surprised his
fellow quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``John made a pretty gutsy decision,'' Palmer said. ``I hope he
can help the team out. I feel good about the shot the coach has
given me.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst, who sat out Friday afternoon's practice after
suffering a groin pull, was caught off guard by Fox's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big person,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``I know he's been in
the spotlight, and the toughest thing for him was not the change
but talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox had an inconsistent sophomore year and was often bothered by
a nagging ankle injury. He lost the starting position to Van
Raaphorst in the eighth game but started the final two games after
Van Raaphorst suffered a season-ending ankle injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
