<HEADER>
A5208 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CLINTON-NH-VOICES-A     08-14 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-NH-VOICES-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE CLINTON OVERCAME AN EARLIER SCANDAL, VOTERS ARE STILL
INDIFFERENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add to graphic note; no other changes)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map
and graphic showing polling information is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, N.H. _ Beneath the glass gaze of a great stuffed elk
head, Bill Clinton delivered an extraordinary oration here in the
winter of 1992 that historians will probably end up calling his
``Last Dog'' speech.
</P>
<P>
   His primary campaign badly wounded by allegations that he had
cheated on his wife and questions about his draft record, Clinton
defied speculation that he would have to drop out and instead,
vowed that he would persevere until ``the last dog dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, New Hampshire residents rewarded his perseverance
with a second-place showing in their first-in-the-nation primary,
enough to keep his candidacy alive.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in that very same Elks hall, with Clinton facing the
most personally perilous moment of his presidency as he prepares to
testify before a grand jury Monday, New Hampshire residents voiced
yet another chorus of defiant indifference to allegations against
him _ and a wish that it would all, finally, go away.
</P>
<P>
   Pausing for emphasis, Bob Carroll, an auctioneer at an antiques
auction being held at the club, declared, ``Leave. The poor man.
Alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later about his expectations of the president, in view of
reports that Clinton may say he had some sexual contact with Monica
Lewinsky, Carroll said, ``I think he should speak to the people _ I
think he should say he had this sexual encounter and it's between
he and his wife, not he and the world.'' And that should be that,
Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments were often repeated among two dozen people
interviewed in the Elks bar, at the auction and around the
375-year-old community of Dover, and they appear to reflect broad
swaths of national public opinion as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a CBS News poll conducted between Tuesday and Thursday this
week among 1,579 adults, two-thirds of respondents said they
thought the charges against Clinton involved private matters that
did not affect his job as president. The poll, however, also found
rising sentiment in favor of an apology from the president if it
turns out that he lied under oath or instructed Ms. Lewinsky, the
former intern with whom he is accused of having an affair, to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Clinton should do if the charges against him are
true, 44 percent said he should apologize, up from 35 percent at
the end of July. Seventeen percent said he should resign, 13
percent called for impeachment proceedings, and 22 percent said the
matter should just be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   In general, 50 percent of respondents said they thought Clinton
should address the public after he testifies, against 41 percent
who thought he should not.
</P>
<P>
   In Dover, among Democrats and Republicans, Clinton fans and
foes, the broadest consensus seemed to concern an overwhelming
desire for this whole surreal episode in the history of the U.S.
presidency to end, the sooner the better. Some said they thought
Clinton should admit his affair with Ms. Lewinsky, if he had one;
others said he should stonewall; almost all said, in effect,
``Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain phrases came up repeatedly: ``Between him and his
wife,'' and ``laughing stock of the world,'' and ``Skeletons in the
closet'' (as in, everyone has a few, especially sexual ones).
</P>
<P>
   And one theme, no matter how open-ended the question asked,
seemed to predominate: resentment about the price of the
investigation, both in terms of money and its absorption of public
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's terrible for our nation and I truly think it's
not doing us any good around the world,'' said Inez DiMambro, a
68-year-old housewife and mother who was browsing among exquisite
dolls about to be auctioned off.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is a Republican,'' added Ms. DiMambro, who votes as
an independent, ``and he's concerned, too, because he doesn't think
this is of great value to our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, 68 percent of respondents in the CBS Poll sad that
whatever Clinton has done, the country would have been better off
without any investigation at all. A full half of Republicans
interviewed agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Such common antipathy for the process under way does not appear
to translate into agreement on whom to blame, however. Polls have
found that more people tend to blame the investigation or political
enemies for damaging the presidency than blame Clinton himself, but
there are still those like Ms. DiMambro's doll-shopping companion,
Diane King, who noted, ``He's the president. He should act more
presidential.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. King also expressed concern about the continuing effect the
White House scandal seems to be having on the country's moral
tenor, including the gutter-level discussions it prompts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I heard the words ``O.S.'' once, I think I heard it 95
times and I really don't think it's necessary,'' she said,
referring to oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Dover residents' responses also indicated just how pervasive
discussions of the scandal have become, from a high school student
who said her history class had compared Clinton's alleged
infidelities to those of Franklin D. Roosevelt, to Barrows' mention
of how the investigation is being used as an example in a criminal
justice class he has been taking in college.
</P>
<P>
   If the discussions of the investigation often float off into
salacious levity, it is partly because of a widespread belief that,
ultimately, the repercussions of all this will not be serious for
Clinton or for the presidency. There may be whispers about
impeachment proceedings on Capital Hill, but the prospect seems
incredible this far from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole thing is going to be dropped,'' said George
Younger, a retired court bailiff and chagrinned Republican. ``The
Republicans do not want to see him impeached, because if he is,
Gore will have two years to solidify the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their professed indignation at the attention paid the
scandal, Elks at the bar also found themselves discussing it for
the pure lurid fun of it.
</P>
<P>
   For all the humor, however, a sense of serious unease remained.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, said construction laborer David Pierce, ``I think
it's a travesty that people don't have better things to do with
this country than to investigate whether the president is sleeping
with obviously more-than-willing partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about let's talk about something really important _ the
New York Yankees!'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
