<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-14 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY AD CAMPAIGNS BY GOP HOPEFULS  
 DEMOCRATS GET A BREAK IN MARYLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   IDAHO CONGRESS RACE MAY BE 1996 REDUx  
 (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early Ad Campaigns By GOP Hopefuls
</P>
<P>
   Folks in Iowa and New Hampshire have long been accustomed to
presidential candidates, actual and potential, showing up to
campaign for the next election before the dust has settled from the
election just past.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the appearances are for making small talk and dinner
speeches, or maybe to endorse candidates in local elections. There
is little, if any, actual mention of the next presidential contest,
but everybody knows and understands the game that is being played,
even if game time is still the better part of four years off.
</P>
<P>
   Now White House wannabes are beginning to advance the starting
time of their television, radio and newspaper advertising
campaigns. Again, there is a bit of a game involved, since the
advertisements tend to push a bill or issue before Congress rather
than the presidential aspirant and since they are usually paid for
by the aspirant's political action committee.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, everybody knows and understands the game,
particularly the part about using PACs and other cover
organizations to promote ideas and issues that are really
ideological stalking horses for wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that the first advertisements started showing up
about a year before the first caucuses and primaries. For the 2000
election, however, the first advertisements showed up in 1997, a
good three years before the election, when magazine magnate Steve
Forbes ran some radio commercials in Iowa, New Hampshire, Arizona
and elsewhere that promoted a tax reform measure before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Tax reform was Forbes' major issue when he sought the Republican
nomination in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., began running radio and
newspaper advertisements in Iowa that call for tax cuts to help
working families.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements, which cost $26,500, were paid for by
American Values, the Ashcroft political action committee, and
closed with an invitation to Iowans to come out and meet the
senator as he tours the state. There is no mention in the
advertisements of Ashcroft's White House aspirations, but the
promotion of family values is a mainstay of the Ashcroft
presidential pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone on the family issue, tax reform or political
advertising, another Republican aspirant, former Tennessee Gov.
Lamar Alexander, will begin a $200,000 television advertising
campaign Monday, initially concentrating on places like Iowa and
New Hampshire but eventually ``going up,'' as campaign managers put
it, in more than a dozen other states. The ads are being paid for
by We the Parents, a PAC recently set up by Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Does any of this matter this early?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the next round of presidential preference polls from
Iowa will tell. For measuring purposes, in the last round of
polling Forbes ran a strong second with Republican voters, behind
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, while Alexander and Ashcroft hardly
registered any support at all.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats Get A Break in Maryland
</P>
<P>
   Almost two-thirds of the nation's governors are Republicans _ 32
out of 50 _ and Democratic hopes for reducing that heavy
preponderance in this year's elections have never been high.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts say the Republican tide that swept through so
many states in recent years is still running high, and they rate 7
of the 11 Democratic governorships up for grabs in the fall as
``vulnerable'' to a Republican takeover.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most vulnerable is in Maryland, where the current
Democratic incumbent, Parris Glendening, squeaked into office in
1994 with just a hair over 50 percent of the vote. And he has been
struggling ever since, dogged by disputes over gambling laws and
money for schools, stadiums and pensions.
</P>
<P>
   But the other day he got a break.
</P>
<P>
   His main challenger in the Sept. 15 primary, Eileen Rehrmann,
the chief executive officer of Harford County, northeast of
Baltimore, dropped out of the race, citing a lack of campaign
money.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of her retreat lies not in the threat she posed
to Governor Glendening's renomination, since she was well behind
him in the polls. Rather, her departure means that he will not have
to spend the next month fending off increasingly pointed,
party-dividing attacks by her and her two most politically powerful
supporters, Baltimore Mayor Kurt Schmoke and Prince George's County
Executive Wayne Curry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he will be able to focus his campaign energies on his
presumed Republican opponent in the fall, Ellen Sauerbrey, a former
state legislator who also was his general election opponent in
1994. Polls indicate a second Glendening-Sauerbrey contest _ she
espouses a conservative brand of Republicanism while he is a
moderate Democrat _ could be every bit as close as the first.
</P>
<P>
   This seems especially likely if Ms. Rehrmann, Schmoke and Curry
do not heed the governor's call for unity. Thus far they have have
been silent on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Schmoke and Curry, who are black, that silence
means that Glendening may not be able to count on piling up big
vote margins in heavily black and heavily Democratic Baltimore and
Prince George's County.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho Congress Race May Be 1996 Redux  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Going into the 1996 election, Democrats figured they had a good
shot at unseating Rep. Helen Chenoweth of Boise. They said she was
too conservative even for Idaho's heavily Republican and heavily
conservative 1st Congressional District, which stretches the length
of the western side of the state.
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong. But not by much.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a major money infusion from the League of
Conservation Voters and the AFL-CIO, Democratic candidate Dan
Williams, a former congressional aide, came within 6,500 votes of
beating Ms. Chenoweth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two years later, Democrats still think Ms. Chenoweth is
vulnerable. And they still believe that Williams can exploit that
vulnerability and help the Democrats regain control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials in Washington promise assistance. So does big
labor. And once again, the League of Conservation Voters has Ms.
Chenoweth on its list of candidates who pose what they believe is a
``dirty'' threat to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   As in 1996, the league has hired a full-time political worker to
assist Williams. The league has also pledged to contribute at least
$200,000 to the Williams campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But overtaking Ms. Chenoweth will probably be no easier this
time around than two years ago. She is pretty good at fund-raising
herself and can depend on assistance from the national Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she has lowered her hard-right profile a bit over the
last couple of years, thereby undercutting some of Williams' major
argument for turning her out of office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
