A5228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CANADA-INDIANS-N     08-14 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CANADA-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CANADA'S NOBLE GIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Utah)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 15:
</P>
<P>
   Canada's decision last week to give the Nisga'a Indians control
of their ancient tribal lands in British Columbia was an overdue
but honorable gesture, born partly of guilt for past injustices and
partly from a belief that tribal sovereignty will lead to economic
self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   But the government in Ottawa must make sure its trust is not
abused. In particular, it must hold the tribe to national laws,
especially those protecting the environment, even if that limits
what the Indians hope to do.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. experience with Indian sovereignty might be helpful to
the Canadians, who in fact have come rather late to the idea _ more
than two centuries behind the United States, which granted
self-government to 371 separate tribes between 1778 and 1871. The
treaties struck between Congress and the tribes gave the Indians
tribal homelands and freedom from state control. But they remained
subordinate to the will of Congress, becoming, in effect, nations
within a nation, levying their own taxes and enforcing their own
laws but always subject to a higher power.
</P>
<P>
   This is essentially the same arrangement that the Canadian
government has struck with the Nisga'a tribe. The tribe will be
encouraged to engage in forestry, mining, fishing and other
activities to sustain its independence. At the same time it will be
asked to obey national laws, including strict environmental
regulations _ a vital point since the land to which the Nisga'a
will be taking title, with its extensive pine forests and pristine
streams, is not only visually stunning but also ecologically
fragile.
</P>
<P>
   But this ``nation-within-a-nation'' architecture, however clean
it looks on paper, has not prevented conflicts in the United States
between tribes and local and state interests. Some of these
conflicts involve money _ whether, for example, non-Indians who run
businesses on reservations should pay taxes to the tribe or to the
state. Many disputes involve the environment.
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, for example, the Isleta Pueblo tribe forced the
city of Albuquerque to spend $300 million to clean up a nearby
river. A federal court ruled that the Indians were well within
their rights under the federal Clean Water Act. Conversely, the
Goshutes, a tribe in central Utah, decided last year to lease part
of their reservation as a storage ground for high-level civilian
nuclear waste. The Goshutes said they were simply invoking their
sovereign powers to make themselves self-sufficient. Their
neighbors, quite rightly, were horrified.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this dispute will have to be resolved by the
authorities in Washington, which is just where it ought to be
settled. As the senior partner in the treaties, the federal
government must juggle two obligations. One is to protect tribal
interests, the other to assert the national interest when tribes
overreach.
</P>
<P>
   So will it be in Canada, where neighbors of the Nisga'a in
British Columbia are already complaining that the deal gives the
tribe unfair advantages. Having made the gift of sovereignty,
Ottawa must now control its consequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
