A5230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CEMETERY-STRIKE-AR     08-14 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CEMETERY-STRIKE-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR DISPUTE HALTS JEWISH RITES AT CEMETERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A four-month labor dispute at eight Jewish cemeteries
in Queens, Brooklyn and Long Island has left hundreds of mourners
unable to dedicate gravestones of relatives and friends, as Jewish
custom dictates, because monument-company workers refuse to cross
the picket lines of cemetery workers.
</P>
<P>
   Replacement workers at cemeteries have buried the dead and
maintained the grounds since early April, when workers went on
strike at one cemetery and were locked out by owners at seven
others. But hardly a monument has been erected since then, and
mourners say they have been robbed of the chance to put at least a
ceremonial end to their grief.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish custom calls for burial within 24 hours, and for the
ceremonial unveiling of a graveside monument in a year, to close
the traditional period of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Lenore Edelman said her brother, Samuel, died so unexpectedly in
April 1997 that she was barely able to organize a funeral service
for him at Mount Hebron/Cedar Grove Cemetery in Flushing, Queens.
So she had hoped to schedule a more elaborate ceremony on the first
anniversary of his death. But the stone bearing her brother's name
has not budged from the factory where it was carved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad enough that the funeral was one-two-three, because
it was such a shock when he died,'' Ms. Edelman said. ``We hoped to
have an unveiling where we could let people know. I die every week
when I call the man at the monument company and find out we still
can't schedule it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds like Ms. Edelman have had to put their grief on hold
while labor negotiations continue. For now, the new graves bear
only temporary markers of metal or wood. Some graves in family
plots have no markers at all. And even if the monuments were
delivered, they could not be installed, since there is no one to
pour the concrete foundations.
</P>
<P>
   David Schenck, a vice president of sales at Sprung Monument Co.,
which has nine branch offices in the metropolitan region, said that
more than 500 monuments were piled up in his factory because of the
labor dispute. He said his workers, who are members of an
International Brotherhood of Teamsters local, have refused to cross
the picket line, but he added that he also feared that stones would
be vandalized if they were placed before a settlement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at Mount Lebanon Cemetery in Glendale, Queens _ one of
eight Jewish cemeteries in Queens and Brooklyn and on Long Island
that make up the Cemetery Employer Association of Greater New York
_ went on strike on April 7, when contract negotiations dissolved.
The next day, the owners of the seven other cemeteries locked out
their workers in sympathy with Mount Lebanon. More than 340
gravediggers and groundskeepers at the eight cemeteries had worked
without a contract since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers on reductions in pension and medical
benefits for the workers, who make between $18 and $20 an hour.
Both sides said this week that they had reached agreement on those
issues, but now were divided on how to deal with five workers who
were dismissed while on the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Goldberg, a business representative with Local 74 of the
Service Employees International Union, which represents the
cemetery workers, said that the owners had refused to allow the
dismissals to go to arbitration, and that the union would not
concede unless the dismissed workers were given some type of
appeal. ``We just want to get everybody back to work and start the
healing process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Hass, president of the cemetery association, said more
than 1,400 burials had been performed since early April, ``every
one of them on time, with dignity and decorum.'' He added that
after a two- or three-week period during which grounds went
untended, scores of replacement workers have kept the grass mowed
and the weeds in check.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's been very frustrating because we have continued to
service the Jewish community, and we maintained our original
position to try to keep costs down, and yet we're still
characterized as the villains,'' Hass said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Lelonek, a manager at Memorials by Riverside, a monument
company in Manhattan, said he fielded dozens of calls every week
from relatives desperate to get a monument dedicated and unveiled.
``It's really a shame, because a lot of people feel very unsettled
right now,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
