<HEADER>
A5232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-SALESMAN-NYT &LR;      08-14 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-SALESMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A SALESMAN WHO PAID ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Zara Grauer still remembers her first date with
Howard Bardach. He stepped aside to let her board a bus, then sat
beside her and suggested they share some coffee and conversation.
Walking home afterward, he asked her not to walk so fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you feel well?'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I want it to last longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sentimentality. It figured, since he fancied himself a
ladies' man. Such salesmanship, too, since he was just as likely to
approach strangers on the street and ask if they wanted to buy or
sell his roach-killing paint, hand warmers or special light bulbs
whose rays rivaled ``sunshine on a June day.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who got beyond the product pitch would learn that Bardach,
80, had once been a Yale man, a Navy man and the owner of a
packaging business. They were also told that he had moved to the
Hell's Kitchen neighborhood after one of his sons committed suicide
and his wife divorced him. Despite those setbacks, he reinvented
himself, convinced that riches still waited for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to this neighborhood to get away from it all,'' said
Sylvie Pappis, a friend. ``And he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Too much so. Starting about a year ago, he grew thin and quiet.
He stopped writing the wacky, hyperkinetic letters hawking his
products and solutions to the world's ills. He stopped being a
salesman. On July 27, he hanged himself. His death seemed as
impenetrable as the successes and sorrows of his very life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' said Roger Starr, a former city official who
worked on the Yale Literary Magazine with him and received his
bizarre letters over the years, ``there's sort of a gap between
being eccentric and being insane. I'm not sure what side of that
gap he fell on.''
</P>
<P>
   His letters and phone calls would make you think he was on the
wrong side. What kind of person would call a reporter at 4 a.m. and
urgently insist that he leave his ink-stained cocoon to embrace the
world of wealth by selling those special light bulbs?
</P>
<P>
   Then again, John Waldo Adams, his best friend, knew him as the
only person who ever threw him a birthday party in his 90 years on
this earth. The two met around 20 years ago when Bardach stopped
him on the street and tried to sell him a chemical with amazing
gunk-removal powers. When he discovered that Adams was a poet, he
volunteered to type his writings, offering free editorial advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted me to get more fun and laughter into my poems,''
Adams said. ``I was writing about the condition of the world, the
economy, the psychological, the sociological. Sometimes he said it
was too serious.''
</P>
<P>
   He often stopped by Ms. Pappis' hat shop on West 54th Street,
sometimes with lady friends as possible customers. ``He had a good
eye for colors,'' she said. ``He was always attentive. He wasn't
like a lot of men who pass by the store and don't notice. He paid
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   She suspected something was amiss last year, when he would walk
past the store with only a nod. Some of his friends said he had
cancer, though he would never talk about what was going on. He
always had lunch at a nearby senior center, but the people there
knew even less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was a tortured soul,'' said Sharon Beard, who works
at the center. ``But he carried himself without a scintilla of
self-pity. He was a classy man.''
</P>
<P>
   While his friends in Hell's Kitchen wondered what was wrong, Ms.
Grauer explained simply that he had had an epiphany about a year
ago when she fell ill. He took care of her, she said, and grew
caring and calmer. But she suspected that he was disappointed by
his fizzled business plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it must have been difficult when the Yale magazine
would arrive and he saw this one was a CEO and that one had a home
in Montauk, and he hadn't accomplished,'' she said. ``That's what
got to him.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't matter to the dreamers and buddies who met him
during his last years. They recalled a man whose hard life never
diminished the fast talk. To them, he was Howie Bardach, salesman
and friend. They only wish he had let them in a little closer a
little longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was essentially a salesman,'' Ms. Grauer said. ``It was
like `Death of a Salesman,' when the wife said, `Attention must be
paid.' I always thought of that because I did pay attention. The
first time we sat on the couch, I put a pillow behind him. I don't
think anybody had ever done that for him before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
