<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-RHODEN-COLUMN-wor     08-14 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RHODEN-COLUMN-words&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SIDESHOW MAKES TYSON MAIN EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to Mike Tyson to rewrite a script. An armada of news
media was prepared to descend on Trenton, N.J., Friday morning for
Tyson's latest moment of truth: the day he would find out whether
his privilege to box would be restored by the New Jersey State
Athletic Control Board.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a year, the shame would be over. Tyson hasn't
fought since June 1997 after Nevada officials revoked his license
and fined him $3 million for biting the ears of Evander Holyfield
during a heavyweight championship bout in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, the day before the decision on his boxing
license in New Jersey would be rendered, Tyson's camp withdrew the
application and almost immediately applied for a license in Nevada.
It was another bizarre turn in the life of an athlete who has
become a living American soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 Tyson, 20, became the youngest heavyweight champion in
history. In 1992 he was convicted of rape. He served three years in
an Indiana prison and was released in March 1995. The fight with
Holyfield was his opportunity to fulfill a legacy, a claim to
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in his career, Tyson stood ready to be ranked among
the most terrifying, if not the greatest, fighters of all time. Now
Tyson is a pathology moving from venue to venue.
</P>
<P>
   This latest attempt at a shortcut is a microcosm of Tyson's
dance pattern _ two steps up, one step back. He should have applied
for his license in Nevada in the first place. But someone in his
camp felt the Nevada State Athletic Commission would refuse to
grant the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   So, Plan B, which was not Tyson's idea, another adviser said,
was hatched. They would apply in New Jersey. That move angered
Nevada regulators, who saw it as a way to circumvent a recently
passed federal boxing law, the Professional Boxing Safety Act of
1997. It requires all states to honor suspensions in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Luther Mack, a member of the Nevada board, called Tyson's move
to New Jersey ``a slap in our face.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum, the president of Top Rank, who has been involved in
boxing promotions for nearly 30 years, said: ``My supposition was
that they had every assurance in the world that they were going to
get a license in New Jersey. They miscalculated because they didn't
realize the political storm that would ensue.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's sidestep drew a scathing rebuke from New Jersey
political figures and from Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who has been
calling for reforms in boxing and who was a co-sponsor of the
Professional Boxing Safety Act.
</P>
<P>
   But even with all the high-powered opposition, the end run
around Nevada nearly worked. During his hearing before the New
Jersey commission 20 days ago, Tyson was the model of civility as
several character witnesses spoke before the panel for more than
three and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
   But then he snapped. The corporate-political arena conditions
cause most of us to hide our anger, resentment, fear and loathing
behind a mask. Tyson doesn't wear that mask well. This, in fact, is
part of his appeal. He is who and what he is. Not far beneath the
surface lies the rage of the puncher, the brawler who loses his
temper whether the goal is near or not.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is no Pollyanna. Everyone knows it, and now the New Jersey
State Athletic Control Board knows it. Following a 45-minute
questioning by Michael Haas, an assistant attorney general, Tyson
became angry, and in remarks to the panel he uttered an expletive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is control,'' Arum said. ``You or I, if we're before
a commission, we shut our mouths because we want to get them to
give us a license. We act like normal people, not because we're
moralistic; we hold it in, because we have control.''
</P>
<P>
   But the issue, at Tyson's hearing and with Tyson in general, is
how much punishment is enough. Is a yearlong suspension from
boxing, a $3 million fine and an estimated $50 million in lost
earnings enough?
</P>
<P>
   Enough, already. Pitchers throw at batters, hockey players
slash, football players intentionally try to maim. Tyson snapped
one night and bit.
</P>
<P>
   This is the nature of his appeal. These mercurial changes _ the
sudden rewriting of scripts, unpredictable behavior _ count more
than his victories or losses. His life is the attraction. Arum said
Tyson is boxing's version of ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything he does is in a glass bowl,'' Arum said, ``and
people are fascinated. He can have seven fights in a row and lose
every single fight, and still do a good pay-per-view because people
are fascinated by the Tyson story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
