<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHASE IS ON AS MONTGOMERIE AND SINGH SOAR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ With so many contenders, and so many
possibilities, the stage has been set for a memorable weekend at
the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Some of golf's biggest names emerged from the woods of Sahalee
Country Club on Friday, putting themselves in the thick of a
wide-open hunt for the year's final major championship. Either
Vijay Singh or Colin Montgomerie could put the icing on their solid
careers by winning that elusive first major championship. Tiger
Woods and Steve Elkington remained in position to add another major
to their collection. Davis Love III, the defending champion, lurked
near the lead with a chance to become the first person to win
back-to-back PGA titles since Denny Shute in 1937. And while Love
and Mark O'Meara were among those who were near the lead,
dark-horse contenders like Steve Stricker, Scott Gump and Andrew
Magee are in position to pull an upset victory.
</P>
<P>
   Forming the prelude to a pressure-packed weekend, Singh shot a
four-under-par 66 Friday to take the clubhouse lead at four under
par (136) with several contenders still on the course during the
second-round. Tying the course-record 66 that Woods set on
Thursday, Singh was one stroke ahead of Montgomerie, who shot a 67
Friday, and Gump, who shot a 69. Stricker was still on the course
at three under through 17 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there was an impressive logjam at two under that
included Woods, Elkington, Magee and Brad Faxon _ all in position
to make a weekend move. And O'Meara, trying to become the first man
since Ben Hogan to win three majors in the same year, was at one
under par after Friday's 70.
</P>
<P>
   So while Singh liked where he stood, he knew that next 36 holes
would be perhaps the most demanding of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to have a different mind-set, but the pressure is
going to make you do that,'' he said. ``I've played a lot of
weekends going into the lead, or close to the lead, but this is
something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it was sure to be exciting. The race to glory on Sunday
became even more wide open when players like Singh, Stricker and
Montgomerie made moves, and Woods did not. Starting the day with a
two-stroke lead at four under par, Woods struggled to a
two-over-par 72 Friday, and he was happy to score that well.
</P>
<P>
   Woods never found a consistent rhythm all day, feeling
uncomfortable with his swing and leaving himself few opportunities
for birdies. A subpar round would have allowed Woods to keep his
lead. But he was pleased that he prevented an average round from
becoming a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased to shoot 72 with the way I hit the ball,''
Woods said after a round that included three bogeys and just one
birdie. ``I'm only two back. That's perfect, that's where you need
to be. I'm very pleased with the way I scored, but not happy with
the way I hit the ball. I didn't have a feel for my swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh had a feel for his swing, playing to his strengths _
length and accuracy with his tee shots and irons. Tight courses
like Sahalee suit Singh's game, and he showed that early Friday,
making birdies on three of the first four holes to build early
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to hit a lot of fairways here,'' said Singh, a
35-year-old native of Fiji, who has won five times on the PGA Tour,
with four top-10 finishes this year. ``I'm putting well. I have a
good feel for the greens. I think the key was the start of my
round. That gave me confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh made a four-foot putt for birdie on No. 1, a 40-foot putt
for birdie on No. 2, a 12-foot putt for birdie on No. 4, a 20-foot
putt for birdie on No. 5, and a 4-foot putt for birdie on the par-3
No. 9, after hitting a beautiful 5-iron shot off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Singh was in sole possession of the lead at five
under par, but he made his first bogey on the par-5 No. 11 when he
got into trouble after a bad tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   Singh followed with a birdie on No. 13, but he bogeyed the par-3
No. 17, when he hit his tee shot into a bunker, then failed to get
up and down for par. While Singh badly wants to win a first major,
so does Montgomerie, one of the world's top players, who has grown
tired of answering questions about not winning major championships.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the last 10 winners of the PGA have ben first-time major
winners. Montgomerie would love to continue that trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about my score and my position,'' said
Montgomerie, a 35-year-old native of Scotland, who has been the
leading money-winner on the European Tour for the last five years.
``I haven't come over here to finish second. If I can putt anything
like I have the past two days, I have an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gump, a 32-year-old who lives outside of Orlando,
Fla., may have been the least known of the contenders, but he was
thrilled to be in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm playing well, the pressure won't bother me,'' said
Gump. ``If I'm playing poorly, I'm frustrated. Having a putt to
make or miss the cut is not much fun. But playing well is
enjoyable. And to be in this position is fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
