<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTS ARE NOT LISTED IN WILL OF WOMAN WHO DISAPPEARED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The will of an Upper East Side millionaire who has
been missing for more than six weeks does not list the lead
suspects in her disappearance as beneficiaries, officials involved
in the case said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers for the suspects, Sante Kimes and her son,
Kenneth, hailed the will as evidence that the Kimeses, who are
being held in New York on credit card fraud charges, were not
involved in the disappearance of Irene Silverman, 82.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have said that they suspect that the Kimeses were
planning to defraud Mrs. Silverman out of her East 65th Street
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The will clearly shows that the Kimeses had absolutely no
motive to cause the demise of Mrs. Silverman,'' said Mel Sachs, Ms.
Kimes' lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clearly shown by the fact that the will would not in any
way benefit the Kimeses,'' Sachs added.
</P>
<P>
   John Sare, the lawyer handling Mrs. Silverman's will, said he
would not comment on whom the will lists as beneficiaries. But he
said his law firm had begun the lengthy process of having Mrs.
Silverman legally considered a missing person. A person must be
missing for at least three years, according to state law, before he
or she is declared legally dead and the will can be executed, Sare
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person has to be missing for three years without being
heard of,'' he said. ``Only when there is a declaration of death
would it be possible'' to execute the will.
</P>
<P>
   Sare said a copy of Mrs. Silverman's will was filed in
Surrogate's Court in Manhattan on July 13. The following day, he
said, Judge Renee Roth named the Bank of New York to oversee the
maintenance of Mrs. Silverman's town house and other property.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Justice Jeffrey Atlas of state Supreme Court
in Manhattan denied a request for bail for the Kimeses on the
credit card fraud charges. Sachs and Jose Muniz, Kimes' lawyer,
were appealing a decision by Judge Herbert Adlerberg last week to
deny the mother and son bail. Prosecutors charged the Kimeses with
using a Florida man's MasterCard to buy drinks and dinner at the
Pierre Hotel, as well as items from a Chanel boutique.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Kimeses said they would appeal Atlas' ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
