<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SMASH YET ANOTHER BARRIER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last decade or so, a woman's serving as a bishop has
become less remarkable among some Protestant denominations, as the
office has been opened to female clerics in the United Methodist
Church, the Episcopal Church and the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America.
</P>
<P>
   But that hardly means there are not still firsts. One occurred
earlier this week when the Rev. Kay Ward, a seminary professor,
became the first woman to be elected bishop by Moravians, members
of a Protestant tradition with autonomous church provinces around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   What also made the election, in the Northern Province of the
Moravian Church in America, a distinctive event is the unusual way
Moravians choose bishops: Elections take place without caucuses,
campaigns for office or even candidates.
</P>
<P>
   When the province's synod, its top policy-making body, meets
every four years, blank ballots are handed out to several hundred
delegates, and everyone writes down the name of someone he or she
thinks would make a good bishop. After the first ballot, the names
of those who got votes are announced, and the balloting continues
until someone gets a two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably representative of a mind-set in our denomination
that if somebody wants the job, that's probably the wrong person
for the job,'' said Hermann Weinlick, editor of The Moravian, a
church magazine in Bethlehem, Pa. The process, he said, is ``kind
of juxtaposed against'' secular society, in which ambition for
office is often rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ward, director of continuing education at Moravian
Theological Seminary in Bethlehem, said modestly that her election
as bishop was ``a small part'' of a larger story about women's
attaining leadership roles in her church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty amazed,'' said Ms. Ward, who is also a professor
of pastoral theology. ``There are no words for this, and I'm a big
talker.''
</P>
<P>
   Moravians call themselves the first Protestants, tracing their
roots back to before the Reformation, to Jan Hus, a Czech reformer
who proclaimed Scripture to be an authority superior to church
tradition and hierarchy. He was eventually condemned as a heretic
and burned at the stake in 1415.
</P>
<P>
   A half-century later, his followers formed the Unity of the
Brotherhood (considered by Moravians a forerunner of the present
church) and began ordaining ministers. Over the years, Moravians
have become known for their music and hymns, their widespread
missionary work and a focus on ecumenism.
</P>
<P>
   Lately they have been growing outside Europe and North America.
Of the more than 730,000 Moravians in 19 provinces worldwide, about
40 percent live in Tanzania. ``It's the fastest-growing area of the
church,'' Weinlick said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the church's North American presence is small, with
29,000 members in the Northern Province, scattered among 13 states
and two Canadian provinces. (There is also a Southern Province,
with about 20,000 members, based in Winston-Salem, N.C.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ward, 56, holds a doctorate from the Claremont School of
Theology in California, is married to a Moravian pastor and has
four adult children. She will be consecrated as a bishop on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Her role will be that of spiritual leader, without the
administrative duties that also occupy bishops in other churches. A
Moravian bishop serves as a pastor to the church's pastors.
</P>
<P>
   Bishops also ordain deacons and consecrate presbyters, the
Moravians' two, essentially identical orders of ministry. And, Ms.
Ward said, they ``really are charged with praying for the church
and for individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the process by which bishops are elected, Weinlick said
it was intended to produce someone from the church's mainstream, a
person known as a good listener and speaker, who can relate to
different people.
</P>
<P>
   At the six-day synod that ended on Tuesday in Bethlehem, Ms.
Ward won on the third ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the quickness with which they reached the
decision,'' Weinlick said, ``we felt it was a consensus and what
we'd say is God's will.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he thought the time for this had come, given that
the province began ordaining women to the clergy in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   In her acceptance speech, Ms. Ward asked for delegates' prayers
and said, ``We never know what will happen when we respond to God's
call.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said the path to her election began long ago, when
church leaders opened the way for women to become pastors and
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never know what will happen when men, clearly led by God's
inclusive spirit, choose to break open tightly bound fists full of
power and authority,'' she said in the speech. ``And so I
understand that what is happening here today takes place in a much
wider context, a much longer journey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
