<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLEBY DOES HIS BEST AMID TRYING CONDITIONS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ An emotionally trying tournament for Stuart
Appleby ended Friday when he missed the cut with a 36-hole total of
150, 10 over par. Appleby was competing for the first time since
the death of his wife, Renay, who was killed last month after being
struck by a car. Understandably, Appleby found it hard to
concentrate. But he took an important step by returning to
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was easier than yesterday,'' said Appleby, a 27-year-old
Australian. ``I'm looking at this process as not an instant thing.
The most frustrating thing is that I'm out here playing, and I'm
not 100 percent prepared. But under the circumstances, there is no
other option.''
</P>
<P>
   Appleby received warm applause from the gallery on every hole,
and he finished strongly, making birdies on the final two holes.
With this tournament behind him, Appleby hopes to play better in
next week's Sprint International, followed by the NEC World Series
of Golf in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to look at the next two events as stepping stones,''
said Appleby. ``This tournament is like a warmup for what's coming.
I have to deal with a lot of issues, and one of them is golf.
Hopefully, it will get a little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Local Favorite Has It Rough
</P>
<P>
   It was another frustrating day for Fred Couples, a crowd
favorite who grew up in nearby Seattle. Couples shot a 71 Friday,
after shooting a 74 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only frustrating that I didn't practice a lot harder
before I got up here,'' Couples said. ``If you play very little,
you are not going to play well, and that's a proven fact. The
hardest thing for me was the way I played. I don't think there was
any more pressure. It seemed like yesterday, every time I was in
the rough, I was a couple of feet in the rough. Today was a little
better, but I missed a lot of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his difficulties, Couples was still thrilled to see a
major played in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sahalee is a great course,'' said Couples. ``Seattle has put
on a great show. I am always proud of Seattle. Coming back was a
real treat.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost Likes His Chances
</P>
<P>
   David Frost's best career finish in a major is a tie for fifth
at the 1995 Masters, and he has never finished higher than 10th at
a PGA Championship. Yet, after shooting a 69 Friday to move to one
under par for the tournament, Frost liked his chances this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely a course I can win on,'' he said. ``It is the
type of course where nobody has an advantage. The long hitters
don't have an advantage over the shorter guys. I think it's
anybody's game.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost, who is 38, has 10 career victories on the PGA Tour, but
it will be interesting to see how he responds to being in weekend
contention at a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with a lot of patience the past two days,'' he said.
``There weren't too many birdies out there for me, but a lot of
pars. It's funny how it works. The more you play for a par, the
more a birdie jumps in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
