<HEADLINE>
TYSON MOVES ON; NEW JERSEY LEFT WITH LACK OF CLOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Hazzard, the New Jersey boxing commissioner, said Friday
that he would have preferred Mike Tyson to proceed with his
application for a New Jersey boxing license rather than withdraw
and apply for one in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he would let the process go forward,'' Hazzard said.
``I would have liked for there to have been some closure to the
matter, especially after having given him the opportunity to be
heard before the commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson withdrew his New Jersey application on Thursday, one day
before the state Athletic Control Board was to render a decision. A
site and date has not been set for Tyson's Nevada application
request. But a hearing will take place sometime in September in Las
Vegas before the five members of Nevada's state Athletic
Commission. Three members of the commission must vote in favor of
Tyson for him to receive his license.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada commission revoked Tyson's license on July 9, 1997,
after Tyson bit the ears of Evander Holyfield during a heavyweight
championship bout in Las Vegas on June 28, 1997. The commission
ruled that Tyson would have to wait at least a year before seeking
another license.
</P>
<P>
   Hazzard said he did not think Tyson's decision to withdraw his
application in New Jersey would have an adverse effect on the
process in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that Nevada will deal with the issues on their
merit and will give Mike Tyson a fair hearing, which is what he got
here,'' Hazzard said. ``We didn't view his applying here as an end
run around the law. When your livelihood is at stake, you make a
decision to go where you feel you will be best served.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazzard said Tyson did not hurt himself with his outburst near
the close of the hearing, in which he uttered an expletive in
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He testified for two hours,'' Hazzard said. ``I don't think
this board would have taken those final three minutes and make that
the deciding factor. This board would have taken all of the factors
into consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who was the co-author of the
Professional Boxing Safety Act of 1997, issued a statement Friday
commending Tyson for returning to Nevada to seek reinstatement of
his license. Earlier this week the senator had rebuked Tyson for
trying to circumvent a part of the Boxing Safety Act, which calls
for states to recognize suspensions in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Because Nevada had revoked Tyson's license and not suspended it,
Tyson and his attorneys were using a loophole to get around the
law. The senator's criticism was part of the reason Tyson withdrew
his application in New Jersey, according to Jeff Wald, a Hollywood
entertainment executive who is acting as one of Tyson's advisers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
