<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-MARINA-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MARINA THRIVES WHERE WAREHOUSES CAST SHADOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Along a narrow creek that divides a sooty Bronx
industrial park from the whooshing traffic on the Hutchinson River
Parkway, where the setting sun casts shadows of warehouses and
tractor-trailers, exists a seagoing community like no other.
</P>
<P>
   There is Francois Guillet, the weather-beaten owner of this
unlikely marina, who speaks English laden with the diction of the
French Alps and dreams of retiring here. And Daniel Torrez, a
former Greenwich Village shopkeeper who has built an art studio
inside a ramshackle houseboat and arranges orchids on the foredeck.
And ``Uncle Bob,'' a disabled jail guard who eases his pain with
beer and companionship on the deck of his motorboat, the Golden
Girl.
</P>
<P>
   What unites them all is a love of the water, and a willingness
to see past their immediate surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Where some might be put off by the speeding cars on the parkway
_ the nearest lane of traffic cannot be more than 250 feet from the
dock _ Torrez says he tunes out the noise. ``Sometimes, at night,
there's hardly anyone on the highway, and you can hear the birds,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the parkway's proximity has its advantages. Directly
opposite the marina is a rest stop, with a gas station and a
McDonald's. So boaters in need of a refill, or hungry for a
hamburger and fries, simply have to paddle a rowboat a few yards
across Westchester Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx, the only borough of New York City that is part of the
mainland United States, actually has a wealth of marinas and
boaters. In addition to the dozen or so boatyards on City Island,
there are several on Eastchester Bay near Throgs Neck, and one
hidden away on the Hudson in Riverdale.
</P>
<P>
   Guillet's 30-slip marina on Westchester Creek, Metro Marine, was
built in 1957 by the late Jerry Conroy, a retired tugboat captain,
said Guillet, who bought it from him 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the time, the location south of Westchester Square was
an odd choice. The path of Westchester Creek was shifted slightly
in the 1930s to make way for the parkway. It might have been filled
in and paved over then, but for a fuel company that needed to
continue receiving oil shipments by barge. So the Army Corps of
Engineers dug a new path for the creek along Commerce Avenue,
Guillet said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, oil barges still inch up the waterway once a month or so,
twice a week in winter. But over time, despite the growth of an
industrial park alongside it, the creek has become more of a refuge
than a commercial artery, a sort of maritime version of the
community gardens, or casitas, that have sprouted on vacant lots in
many neighborhoods in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the marina has drawn police officers, schoolteachers
and other working people unable or unwilling to pay the rent at
more fashionable boatyards. Some are new boaters, like the criminal
lawyer who received his boat, the Bandolero, as payment from a
client, though a few have been coming here for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Aviles, a self-employed insurance broker in the
Morrisania section of the South Bronx, comes here after work a few
days a week to go fishing for the plentiful bluefish and striped
bass to be had in Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I come at 2 or 3 in the afternoon, depending on the
tides,'' he said. ``There's nothing better.''
</P>
<P>
   Others seem rarely to leave the dock _ like Uncle Bob (he keeps
his surname secret), a guard at a prison for the criminally insane
on Wards Island who was disabled in a fight with an inmate in 1996.
These days, his hands fall asleep if he is out at sea for more than
half an hour, he said. But he and a group of buddies show up nearly
every day to relax, grill chicken or steaks, and drink beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anxieties is the boiling pot,'' he said. ``If you don't
release the tensions, the pot explodes. You can relieve a lot of
stress over here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Torrez, 51, who owned a flower shop in Greenwich Village for
many years but moved to the Bronx last year while recovering from
meningitis, discovered the marina a few months ago while riding his
bicycle through the industrial park. He spotted it behind a
chain-link fence, and swooned.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I used to pass by here, I used to think it was slums,''
he said. ``I never thought I'd be living here.''
</P>
<P>
   Life at this marina, like any other, has its own rhythms. Things
are quiet most days, except for the occasional groan of a rusty
crane, circa 1945, that Guillet uses to hoist boats in and out of
the water. Around 4 or 5, the yard begins to fill with the
after-work crowd. On Saturdays and Sundays, the dock is overrun
with children and families and the air is filled with the smells of
barbecuing.
</P>
<P>
   The boaters are an eclectic bunch, but they get along, said
Torrez, the artist and orchid lover. ``We're all a puzzle, and it
fits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guillet, 56, says he loves his ``poor man's boat club,''
although he sometimes sounds as if he wishes his life had taken a
different turn a long time ago. Born near the French ski resort of
Albertville, he learned to sail as a boy in the mountain lakes
there. Following his brother to New York in 1963 to work as a
contractor, he bought his first boatyard, the Sunrise Marina on
Eastchester Bay, in 1968. His wife, Gail, was the marina's
secretary. They were married in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago, boating was good,'' he said. ``It was
easier to borrow money from the bank for a boat than a car. I had a
waiting list. I had to refuse customers.''
</P>
<P>
   So Guillet bought the marina on Westchester Creek as a low-rent
option for his overflow business. But the recession of the late
1980s and early 1990s dropped the bottom out of the boating
business, he said. Today, he supplements his scant profits from the
two boatyards with his earnings as a barge captain, providing a
floating crane that is used in bridge inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he says, he will sell the Sunrise Marina. He and his wife
are making a home of an old three-story building that overlooks the
marina on Westchester Creek. Although his wife, who was raised in
the Bronx, says she has been begging to leave the borough for
years, Guillet says they will retire here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he says, his face lighting up through sweat and
filth and a full gray beard. ``I don't see a building in front of
me here. I'm not blocked in. I'm never crowded, like those people
who live in those apartment buildings, on top of each other, in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to buy this,'' he added. ``There's not that much
income. It's a way of life _ like a fisherman, or a farmer. Every
boat is like a cow, you know? You pull the boats like cows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
