<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MALLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES MALLEY, 86, WHO INVESTIGATED KENNEDY SLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Kan., Mo., Texas)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Roland Malley, a retired FBI division chief who played a
central role in the investigation of President John F. Kennedy's
assassination, died on Aug. 7 at his home in Alexandria, Va. He was
86.
</P>
<P>
   Malley, a 34-year veteran of the FBI, also served as president
of the Society of Former Special Agents of the FBI and as chairman
of its charitable arm, the Former Agents of the FBI Foundation. He
retired from the agency in 1971 as head of its general
investigative division with the rank of inspector.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Kansas City, Kan., he graduated from the University
of Missouri at Kansas City School of Law and joined the bureau in
1937. He worked in Missouri, New York and Texas, where he was in
charge of the Houston office.
</P>
<P>
   He was called to Washington in 1952 and assigned to the general
investigative division. When Kennedy was killed in November 1963,
Malley helped direct the FBI investigation.
</P>
<P>
   After President Lyndon B. Johnson ordered creation of the panel
popularly known as the Warren Commission for its chairman, Chief
Justice Earl Warren, Malley became the bureau's liaison to the
panel. It heard from 552 witnesses and pored over reports from 10
federal agencies involved in the investigation. The panel's report
in September 1964 pronounced Lee Harvey Oswald the lone killer.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations of a whitewash persisted, however, and in 1978
Malley was called to testify before a Select House Committee on
Assassinations, which wanted to know how federal agencies handled
themselves in the inquiry. He was asked then about the possibility
of a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know it was on everybody's mind,'' Malley told the panel.
``Was somebody else involved? That existed from the minute it
happened.'' He then told of the FBI's efforts to track down
possible Cuban or crime-syndicate connections, but said that no
credible evidence was found.
</P>
<P>
   Malley's survivors include his wife, Pat; a daughter, Patricia
Tighe, also of Alexandria, and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
