<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR OF THE NIGHT, ACT 89. THIS TIME IT'S PETTITTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The premise of competing with the rest of the
American League is lost. The Yankees challenge themselves now, each
other. Andy Pettitte tries to match Orlando Hernandez. Paul O'Neill
wars within. They all seem to be trying to play each game to
perfection.
</P>
<P>
   And the Yankees are coming as close to that regular-season
archetype as any team in this century, closer than any team since
World War II. With Pettitte pitching into the eighth inning,
Mariano Rivera coming on for another save and Chuck Knoblauch
hitting another home run Friday night, the Yankees beat the Texas
Rangers, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   More than two weeks remain in August and the Yankees are on the
verge of 90 victories: They have 89, and just 29 defeats, having
won nine consecutive games. Should they win half of their remaining
44 games, they would match the most victories in AL history, 111 by
the 1954 Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball teams are not supposed to win like this. Some
basketball teams have, like Magic Johnson's Los Angeles Lakers and
Michael Jordan's Chicago Bulls. Football teams win like this, like
the University of Nebraska and Don Shula's Miami Dolphins. But
baseball is a team sport controlled by individuals, particularly
the pitcher; with an effective pitcher, the worst team can beat the
best team. Each day, a bad team can play well and beat a good team.
</P>
<P>
   But every day, the Yankees play great baseball; they benefit
from routine pitching excellence. Hernandez struck out 13 Rangers
and allowed two hits in eight and one-third innings on Thursday,
and afterward Manager Joe Torre addressed questions about whether
Hernandez would be part of the pitching rotation in the playoffs _
the inherent effect of that being that Pettitte might be shifted to
the bullpen. A nice friendly competition, Torre called it.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, now 14-6, is as proud and as driven as any of the
Yankees, however, and he pitched with as much determination and
intensity Friday night as he has all year, his sinking fastball
generating one ground ball out after another, 11 in the first seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to be in trouble in the seventh, after walking Juan
Gonzalez to lead off the inning, with the Yankees ahead by just
3-1. Will Clark then hit a blooper to short center field. Derek
Jeter raced out from shortstop and Bernie Williams raced in from
center, the ball dropping to a space between them; Jeter reached
up, gloved the ball _ and dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams, seeing Gonzalez halfway between first and second,
picked up the ball and threw to second, where first baseman Tino
Martinez was stationed, for a forceout. Martinez was exactly where
he was supposed to be. That is why they win.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez followed with a single to right and Clark stopped
at second. But Pettitte rammed cut fastball after cut fastball on
the hands of Todd Zeile, who popped up, and then struck out Mike
Simms, ending the inning.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Then the Yankees finished off Aaron Sele with a two-out rally in
the bottom of the seventh. Chad Curtis singled, and for no obvious
reason, the 46,547 fans at Yankee Stadium began chanting, ``Let's
Go Yankees, Let's Go Yankees,'' loud enough to overwhelm the music
from the public address system.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi singled, and the crowd noise intensified. Knoblauch,
who had hit his 16th home run in the fifth inning, dumped a single
into short center field. Curtis scored, Girardi aggressively took
third, and when the throw from Roberto Kelly went there, Knoblauch
took second _ just as he is supposed to. That is why they win.
</P>
<P>
   The noise got louder when Jeter slammed a single to right field.
Both Girardi and Knoblauch raced home, and the premise of
competition was over, for Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Among the regulars, Girardi probably is the Yankees' poorest
offensive player. He does not hit home runs, does not hit for a
high average, does not steal bases.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre loves it when Girardi bats with a runner on first,
because of his ability to put the ball in play. Scott Brosius
opened the third inning Friday night with a walk on four pitches,
Girardi strolling to the plate behind him. On Wednesday, Girardi
had broken open a game against Minnesota with a two-run double on a
hit-and-run play.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Torre did not wait: on the very first pitch to
Girardi, he ordered a hit-and-run. Brosius broke from first base as
Sele delivered homeward, and Girardi laced a line drive over the
head of second baseman Mark McLemore, the ball splitting the
outfielders as Brosius ran until he crossed home.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did not get any more runs in that inning, but they
added one in the fourth, when Williams homered. Knoblauch bashed
his home run with two out in the fifth, and Rivera induced a
game-ending double play from McLemore, the Yankees' third double
play of the game. That is also why they win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
