<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LUBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT M. LUBY, 88, FOUNDER OF REGIONAL CAFETERIA CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Texas)  (js) 
 By ROBERT McG. THOMAS Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert M. Luby, a restaurateur who had such a down-home devotion
to quality and such an accommodating string of unemployed relatives
that he helped turn a small Texas cafeteria business into a
$500-million chain with more than 200 restaurants in 11 states,
died on Thursday at a hospital near his summer home in Colorado
Springs. He was 88 and had retired as president of Luby's
Cafeterias Inc. in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Luby grew up on cafeteria food would be something of
an understatement. Within a year after he was born in Mansfield,
Mo., in 1910, his father, Harry, an Illinois-born entrepreneur who
operated a men's clothing store in Springfield, had made a fateful
business trip to Chicago and returned fired by the possibilities of
a strange new food establishment he had encountered there.
</P>
<P>
   Copying the Chicago operation from its name to its menu he
daringly opened the New England Dairy Lunch in Springfield and
promptly discovered that people there had been hankering for
bargain-priced boiled vegetable dinners served buffet style from a
12-foot counter.
</P>
<P>
   A family operation from the beginning (Luby's mother, Julia,
planned meals and helped cook even with a toddler underfoot), the
original short-counter cafeteria was so successful that a second
one was opened in Springfield in 1912 and Luby's father embarked on
a novel path of incremental improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that patrons would resent changes, even those that
improved operations, the elder Luby began the practice of selling
one cafeteria, usually retaining a minority interest, while opening
a new, improved version in a different town. The result was the
creation of what was not so much a chain as a dotted line of a
dozen cafeterias stretching from Missouri through Oklahoma, Texas
and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the family and the family business reached San
Antonio in 1927, Harry Luby had done well enough to retire at 39,
leaving his teen-age son with a near obsession for the business he
had grown up in.
</P>
<P>
   During his high school years Luby did every facet of cafeteria
work from serving food to washing dishes and while studying
business administration at the University of Texas in Austin he
took a couple of years off to open and operate a cafeteria in
Corpus Christi, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After his graduation in 1934, Luby indulged in a short burst of
wanderlust, opening a cafeteria in San Francisco. The city's
Depression-era maritime union problems helped doom the business but
not before it had brought Luby two important assets, an especially
satisfied customer named Georgina Wenglein, who became his wife,
and her brother, George, who was persuaded to return to Texas with
Luby and join him in the cafeteria business.
</P>
<P>
   By 1940 Luby had opened several cafeterias in Texas, but after
the outbreak of World War II he sold out and joined the Army Air
Corps, spending his years as an intelligence officer stationed in
California and dreaming of creating a chain of cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   Teaming up with a cousin, Charles Johnston, he founded the
modern Luby's chain in San Antonio in 1947 and began an expansion
using Wenglein and other relatives as trusted managers.
</P>
<P>
   When he ran out of relatives, Luby, recruited investor-managers
whose 40 percent share of the profits assured that they would be as
concerned about quality and efficiency as Luby was.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were several long-established cafeteria chains in
the South, where an appetite for a hearty, home-style meal that
doesn't cost an arm and a leg is not considered as declasse as it
is elsewhere, Luby's insistence on quality and attention to detail
helped assure a steady expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Initially operated as Cafeterias Inc., the company sold stock to
the public in 1973, changed its name to Luby's Cafeterias Inc. in
1981 and gained a listing on the New York Stock Exchange in 1982,
the year Luby stepped down as chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, as the company he founded continued to flourish and
expand (its 231 cafeterias specializing in regional favorites from
grits to tamales stretch from Arizona to Florida) Luby, who became
a multimillionaire providing low-cost food that even now averages
just above $5 a meal, devoted himself to civic work, travel,
hunting and fishing, golf _ and gourmet cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Luby, twice a widower, is survived by his wife, Kathleen; a
daughter from his first marriage, Martha Lahana of Littleton,
Colo.; a stepdaughter, Elizabeth Rogers of San Antonio; and two
stepgrandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-14-98 2347EDT &QL; 
