<HEADER>
A5273 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS     08-14 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Monty doesn't lack 
confidence, conceit
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
REDMOND, Wash. _ We hate Monty, don't we? We hate him so much, he
had to play the last 40 holes of the U.S. Open in the company of
San Francisco's finest.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to, say, British soccer fans, golf fans are
well-behaved. Still, the Olympic galleries, having been egged on by
a talk-radio jackal, abused Colin Montgomerie so mercilessly that
they had to call in the gendarmes to keep an eye on him.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of the Statue of Liberty notwithstanding, Montgomerie
has not been roundly welcomed on these shores. He's hardly of the
huddled-masses class, having missed few meals in his lifetime.
Colin is widely perceived to be a pompous uh, colon, and his tongue
can be frightfully acerbic.
</P>
<P>
   He's the full Monty all right _ full of Monty. He talks a better
game than he generally delivers, which is saying something because
he is a superb golfer, having been the European money leader for a
record five years running.
</P>
<P>
   And although he doesn't always play his best when it counts the
most, he has been a leading American nemesis in the past two Ryder
Cup defeats, of which he says: ``Because I got the most points, I
tend to be seen as the reason why America lost. Well, I'm sorry
they lost. But it hasn't been my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   It's those kinds of statements, albeit inarguably honest ones,
that get Monty in trouble. But the gallery swarms here haven't been
as hostile as the Bay Area's. Monty insists there have been no
unpleasantries to disrupt his ball-striking, so once again he has
played himself into contention for a major golf title, something he
never has won.
</P>
<P>
   He'll begin the final 36 holes of the PGA Championship one shot
back, trailing only Vijay Singh, the one player who might be less
liked than he is. On a day when two huge crowd favorites, tragic
figure Stuart Appleby and the tortured John Daly, were regrettably
culled from the competitive mix, there sat the ruddy-cheeked
Scotsman, eyeing the catbird seat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a bogey on 18, he had fashioned a 67, one final errant
putt shy of the course record Tiger Woods established Thursday. And
for the second afternoon in a row, he could say, ``I got the best I
could get out of my round.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, being Monty, he had to find something about which to
grumble. It's generally accepted among his peers that Monty is the
finest whine ever produced by Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got Steve Elkington's picture up there, I see,'' he
said, frowning at the poster fluttering above him in the interview
room.
</P>
<P>
   The media tent is full of these large photos, each honoring the
many champions in the PGA's 80-year history. And Elk's hangs among
them because Monty's doesn't. The Houston-based Aussie beat the
Scot in a sudden-death playoff at Riviera in 1995, one of the
nearest of Monty's near misses.
</P>
<P>
   The only major Montgomerie hasn't contended in is his ``own,''
the British Open, where he routinely humiliates himself in front of
thousands of mortified countrymen. But his majors record is
otherwise fairly impressive, save for that conspicuous dearth of
first-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain why he stays so frequently in the hunt, he
replies without a trace of blush: ``Because, well, I'm quite good.
That's why I'm here, you know. I am obviously quite talented and
good at my job.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a slightly _ slightly _ more self-deprecating Monty
who paid us a visit Friday. He complained, at one time or another,
about all facets of his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't hit the ball well for about six months now,'' he
said, admitting he's in the midst of ``more of a struggle than I've
ever had before'' as he attempts to correct a tendency to badly
pull his tee shots and misread his putts.
</P>
<P>
   He's playing it so safe at Sahalee that his driver hasn't left
his locker. He packs a 5-wood instead. As for his improved touch on
the greens, he credits the efforts of short-game guru Dave Pelz for
coaxing more confidence out of him. At Royal Birkdale, he whacked
70 putts Thursday and Friday, ``at least 10 too many'' and enough
to leave him on the south side of the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Monty scored well Friday because, for the most part, he putted
brilliantly, sinking ``a number of'' 20-footers. But when asked if
that was indicative of his skill or his luck, he waited for the
laughter to stop before answering: ``It's never luck. I have a lot
of skill. I have a lot of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough to win this PGA?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about my score and my position,'' Monty said.
``It's a course I knew in practice would suit me, although I'm not
striking the ball well. I'm still hitting it fairly straight, which
you must do around here. If I can putt the same way on the weekend,
I obviously have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Monty never does, for all his bombast, is flat-out
predict victory for himself. He hasn't crossed the line between
unpopular and insufferable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
